<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-RADAR-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 U.S. OVES AHEAD ON RADAR FOR WIND SHEAR AT N.Y. AIRPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Twenty-four years after a crash near Kennedy
Airport in New York alerted the world to the danger of wind shear,
New York City is finally expected to get a new radar to spot the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Every other major airport in the nation already has the
wind-shear detection system, but the Federal Aviation
Administration had been thwarted in its efforts to install it in
the New York area because of opposition from Long Island residents
and former Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who championed a system
built by a Long Island company that used a different technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with D'Amato out of office, the FAA is moving again to
install the system locally, this time in Brooklyn rather than Long
Island. But the Interior Department does not like the FAA's new
proposed location, a 1.8-acre site it owns within Floyd Bennett
Field, because the field is part of the Gateway National Recreation
Area.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department says that building the radar, which
would detect wind shear at both Kennedy and La Guardia airports,
would be an illegal use of the park. But the FAA, in a decision
dated Monday, said that the 110-foot-square portion of the site
that it would use for the radar had no recreational value because
it was entirely surrounded by a heliport leased to the New York
Police Department for the next 25 years, and was already closed to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   The $6 million radar is a 37-foot ball on top of an 82-foot
tower, which a National Park Service spokesman said might frighten
people and prevent them from visiting the park.
</P>
<P>
   Among 47 such radars that are being erected around the country
in response to the crash at Kennedy, all but six are in full
operation, and New York's will be either last or second to last,
depending on the progress of construction near Midway Airport in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The radar ``sees'' air by sensing movements in dust or water
vapor. It looks for a phenomenon called ``microburst,'' in which
the wind blows straight down and then fans out horizontally, like
water being poured from a pitcher onto a tabletop. An aircraft
approaching a microburst would first encounter headwinds, then a
downdraft, and then tailwinds.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence can lead pilots to drop too low and hit short of
the runway, which is what happened on June 24, 1975, when Eastern
Air Lines Flight 66, a Boeing 727 inbound from New Orleans, burst
into flames and virtually disintegrated as it hit light stanchions
on approach. Much of the debris was strewn over Rockaway Boulevard.
One hundred and twelve people on board died.
</P>
<P>
   A wind-shear crash near New Orleans in July 1982 killed eight
people in their homes as well as all 145 people on the plane. The
most recent major wind-shear crash was of a USAir flight near
Charlotte, N.C., in July 1994, which killed 37.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials say privately that the system is needed urgently
in New York, but that they do not want to get in a public argument
with the Interior Department. If they cannot agree, the Justice
Department would decide. The FAA hopes to construct the system this
year and put it into operation by the middle of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The new system, called terminal Doppler weather radar, emits
electromagnetic energy like all radars. Because of that, no one
seems eager to have the radar as a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Park Service, Manny Strumpf, said:
``I'm not going to get into a shouting match with the FAA. We don't
know whether or not there is a safety issue here.'' But the
question, he said, is ``whether or not it appears ominous to
visitors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
