A0349 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CAMINITI-H     03-31 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CAMINITI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Ken Caminiti spent Monday night in a hospital
near the Astros' spring headquarters and might be headed for some
time on the disabled list.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After finally getting over a tough bout with the flu, Caminiti
developed an acute sinus infection that landed him at Osceola
Regional Hospital. He was released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The infection was treated intravenously with antibiotics. The
possibility that the Astros might put Caminiti on the disabled list
to start the season has more to do with his lack of playing time
than anticipation of his infection lingering.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old third baseman has been out of the lineup for a
week and has played in 12 of the Astros' 25 Grapefruit League
games. Caminiti has just 28 at-bats this spring. Manager Larry
Dierker and general manager Gerry Hunsicker are concerned that
might not be enough action to get Caminiti ready to start the
season on time.
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros decide to disable Caminiti, it can be retroactive
to the last exhibition game he played. He would have to miss at
least six days, meaning he could be activated April 10 when the
Astros play the Brewers at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're looking at something that appears to be a
long-term problem,'' Hunsicker said of Caminiti's infection. ``But
I think we're running out of time to get him ready. Starting him on
the disabled list is a distinct possibility. We're going to
evaluate the situation and probably make a decision by Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Craig Biggio, who has been rooming with Caminiti
this spring, has doubts about how the gutty third baseman would
respond to starting the season on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that would go over real well with Cammy,''
Biggio said. ``Good luck on that one. This thing has been kind of
up-and-down. He was pretty bad the first night, and then he felt
better the next day. But the third day he was right back to where
he was. He was in a lot of pain. He's been sucking down
painkillers. You could just see how miserable he was (when he went
to the hospital).''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Caminiti starts the season on the disabled list, Bill
Spiers would be the opening-day third baseman, and Russ Johnson
would start the season in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hunsicker told Johnson on Tuesday he would be heading
back to Class AAA New Orleans whenever Caminiti returns. That
didn't go over too well with Johnson, who earlier in the day lost
out to Alex Diaz for the final spot on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping I'd make it this time, but it didn't work out.
Same thing, different year,'' said a frustrated Johnson, who
already has spent two seasons at New Orleans. ``I don't know what
to think. I guess they don't think I'm good enough to play for the
Houston Astros.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a first-round draft pick in 1994, believes he has
accomplished all he can at Class AAA, and earlier this spring he
suggested that Hunsicker trade him if the Astros couldn't find a
spot for him on the major-league roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel out of place here,'' he said. ``But I'll keep
playing as hard as I can. I may not be good enough for them, but
I'm going to be the best I can be, and I know that's good enough to
play in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, it's the same thing. They send me down, and it's
like they take the heart right out of me. I'm bitter right now, but
I'll continue to do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker understands Johnson's frustration, but he has no
intention of giving Johnson away for the sake of making a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a frustrating time for Russ,'' Hunsicker said.
``He has a family to support, and he's looking for some stability.
Unfortunately, it's not going to happen for him right at this
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it appears Caminiti's situation might give Johnson
an opportunity to be on the big-league roster, if only for a few
days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
