</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSANNAH-OPERA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: TAKING A LOOK INTO THE SOUL OF `SUSANNAH'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Fla., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not often that composers live long enough to see
their operas enter the repertory and to hear successive generations
of singers perform them. Strauss, who died in 1949 at 84, was one
of the few. Consider this: He coached the soprano Marie Wittich,
who created the daunting role of Salome in 1905, and conducted the
great Ljuba Welitsch in it nearly 40 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Puccini, who lived to be only 65, had similarly rich
experiences. The year of his death, 1924, Lucrezia Bori, in her
prime, was acclaimed at the Metropolitan Opera as Mimi, a role
introduced by Cesira Ferrani in Turin 28 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But few composers in the second half of this century have been
as fortunate. Carlisle Floyd is a notable exception. In 1955 Floyd,
then a 28-year-old junior faculty member at Florida State
University, supervised the premiere of his opera ``Susannah''
there. The next year it was produced by the New York City Opera
under the baton of Erich Leinsdorf. It garnered for Floyd, who
writes his own librettos, the New York Music Critics' Circle Award
and an invitation to present the work at the Brussels World's Fair
in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure ``Susannah,'' adapted from the biblical story of
Susanna and the Elders and relocated to an isolated mountain region
of Tennessee in an unspecified present, has joined the repertory.
There have been more than 800 performances around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night it finally receives its Metropolitan Opera
premiere, with Renee Fleming in the title role. And seated in the
audience with the composer will be Phyllis Curtin, the soprano who
created the role 44 years ago, who performed it at City Opera the
next year and in some 30 other productions through the late '60s
and who remains, as Ms. Fleming put it recently, ``the benchmark''
for all who follow.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a rare gathering of creator and colleagues. And two
days ago, after the final dress rehearsal at the Met, in another
meeting of historic resonance, Floyd sat down with the two
cherished Susannahs to reflect on it all.
</P>
<P>
   These two important sopranos are separated by nearly three
generations. Ms. Curtin, 77, is living in retirement in Great
Barrington, Mass., though she continues to teach in summer at the
nearby Tanglewood Music Center. Ms. Fleming, recently turned 40, is
at the peak of her vocal artistry and popularity. It was surely her
interest in this role, which she first sang in 1993 with the Lyric
Opera of Chicago, that enticed the Met to present it.
</P>
<P>
   (This production by Robert Falls is jointly sponsored by the
Lyric Opera and the Houston Grand Opera. James Conlon conducts.)
</P>
<P>
   For all the success and popularity of ``Susannah,'' some critics
and connoisseurs have deemed it a regional work by a regional
composer. Floyd uses an operatic style that has been called verismo
with a small v, meaning not exactly an extension of the school of
Puccini and his contemporaries, but a realistic, contemporary
American equivalent. The harmonic language of ``Susannah,'' though
sometimes touched by anguished dissonance, is unabashedly tonal;
the melodic content is beguilingly lyrical and strewn with tunes
that evoke Appalachian folk music. At 90 minutes, it tells its
story concisely and directly.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Curtin, the directness is emotional and musical as well
as dramatic. ``I don't think there is anything mysteriously
psychological in this whole piece,'' she said. The depictions of
the rural characters, the fundamentalist preacher who comes to
town, the evocations of the square dance and the frenzied revival
meeting: it is all ``right there,'' she said, ``completely honest
and deeply moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Curtin is confounded by those who dismiss the opera as
``Southern and folksy,'' thinking it incompatible with grand opera.
``Americans go along with the provincial Italian locale of
`Cavalleria Rusticana,''' she said, ``and they take delight in `Der
Rosenkavalier,''' which is steeped in the protocols of 18th-century
Viennese aristocratic life.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
