<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUSANNAH-OPERA-ART-2N     03-31 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSANNAH-OPERA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: aristocratic life.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Southerners like Floyd, born in Latta, S.C., the son of an
itinerant minister, and Ms. Curtin, from Clarksburg, W.Va., the
opera's judgmental, fundamentalist characters, wary of the outside
world, fearful of differences, are familiar. ``These are the folks
I went to school with and caught the itch from,'' he said. ``I came
to really care for them.'' Ms. Curtin recalled that a family
friend, who worked for the welfare bureau, went into the hollows to
try to talk parents into vaccinating their children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fleming, who was born in Pennsylvania and grew up near
Rochester, may lack a geographical tie to the region of the opera,
but not a musical one. ``When I was 12, I played on the piano and
sang Susannah's lullaby, `The Trees on the Mountains,' all the
time,'' she said. ``I wanted to perform it in a student recital.
But my mother said I was a little young to be singing about the
`man who made me love him, then left me alone,' and my heart that
`wants warmin' and my baby who wants a name.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat like the biblical Susanna, the operatic character is a
hearty, naturally sensual young woman, going on 19, who is
surprisingly centered considering the trauma of her childhood: An
orphan, she has been brought up by her older brother, Sam Polk, a
trapper with a weakness for drink (Jerry Hadley in this
production). One day, some church elders see Susannah bathing naked
in a creek by her home. Outraged, they report to the town's new
minister, Olin Blitch (Samuel Ramey).
</P>
<P>
   The town turns against her, and Little Bat, a smitten adolescent
who hangs around her house, is bullied into saying that Susannah
has allowed him to ``love her up.'' The lie serves to confirm
general suspicions about her. ``That pretty a face must hide some
evil,'' the sniping Mrs. McLean says.
</P>
<P>
   Olin Blitch visits Susannah one night while her brother is away,
intending to pressure her to repent. Instead his loneliness bursts
forth, and he entices the broken young woman into a sexual
encounter. Realizing it is her first, the guilty minister tries to
turn town opinion without revealing his own sin. It is too late.
Sam kills Blitch and escapes to the mountains, leaving Susannah
shaking with bitter laughter and completely ostracized. What will
she do? ``Live on that farm for the rest of her life and feed her
chickens,'' Ms. Curtin is convinced.
</P>
<P>
   The most intense discussions among the composer, Ms. Fleming and
Ms. Curtin involved the question of why Susannah does not resist
Blitch's seduction. And is it even a seduction at all?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fleming thinks Susannah is initially enchanted by Blitch
when he arrives at the square dance. ``It's like Elvis Presley has
walked in,'' she said, ``and he chooses her as a dance partner.
She's flattered.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Curtin believes that Susannah was never consciously
attracted to the preacher, and is soon crushed anyway by his craven
hypocrisy. After days of being ignored yet gossiped about, Susannah
seeks comfort from her brother, saying simply, ``I cain't wait till
pretty things looks pretty agin.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' Floyd said, ``this line is the definition of
depression. It's like she is waiting for a curtain to be lifted on
her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fleming recalled: ``The first time I sang the role, I had
trouble understanding why Susannah gives in to the minister. She
sings, `I'm so tired, I just can't fight no more.' What does she
mean? It didn't make sense. I was younger then. Now I'm older,
wiser, and have suffered more knocks. I get it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fleming points particularly to the speech in which Susannah
tries to tell the minister that the talk of something improper
between her and Little Bat is a vicious lie. ``I never spent sich a
week as this,'' Susannah says, deeply pained and finally angry. But
the minister answers, ``That's the sin in your heart, that weight
you speak of.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Susannah realizes that everything is hopeless, Ms.
Fleming said. ``What's the point? She is just utterly exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd believes that seduction is the wrong term for what
happens. There are two people, both defeated, he explained: she by
the false accusations; he by his hidden desire and the effort of
being so righteous all the time. ``They are drawn together out of
human and momentary weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' Ms. Fleming said, lighting up. ``That's a wonderful way
to put it. That's why  &UR; you &LR;  wrote the opera.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators have suggested that the way the townspeople
browbeat Little Bat into accusing Susannah is a metaphor for
McCarthy-era witch hunts.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd said the parallel was not conscious. ``I'm too practical a
man of theater; it just struck me as right,'' he said. ``But I did
write the work during the McCarthy years, and I lived through the
terrors. At Florida State an accusation was tantamount to guilt. We
faculty had to sign a pledge of loyalty or lose our jobs. It
affected me and informed me emotionally. And there it is in the
opera. But I can't say I put it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd left Florida State in 1976 for the University of Houston,
where he remained until his retirement. This has been a banner year
for him: in the fall the New York City Opera presented a gritty,
well-received production of his 1970 opera, ``Of Mice and Men,''
probably his second-most-performed work and most musically
adventurous score. His 12th operatic work, ``Cold Sassy Tree,'''
based on a novel by Olive Ann Burns, is scheduled for a premiere by
the Houston Grand Opera in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Susannah'' remains his milestone. ``The soprano Patricia
Racette told me that she is in opera today because as a girl she
was moved by a performance of `Susannah,''' he said. ``Comments
like that are the balm of my old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there is no video document of Ms. Curtin's Susannah, VAI
Audio recently released on compact disk a 1962 performance of the
opera from New Orleans with Ms. Curtin and two of her favorite
colleagues, Norman Treigle as Blitch and Richard Cassilly as Sam.
Ms. Fleming listened to every recording of Ms. Curtin in the role
that she could find. ``It means a lot to me that Phyllis Curtin
will be in the audience,'' Ms. Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   The heritage continues, as it should, Floyd said: ``The young
soprano Emily Pulley, who is covering Susannah for these
performances at the Met, told me that she is studying Renee.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
