<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDLORD-FUNDRAISER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPER AND DEMOCRATIC PARTY CONTRIBUTOR MISUSED FUNDS, AUDIT
FINDS
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass.)  (nk) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A real estate developer who has raised hundreds of
thousands of dollars for President Clinton and the Democratic Party
has been accused by federal officials of misappropriating $1.4
million from a troubled housing complex in the South Bronx even as
the tenements fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development, which holds the mortgages for the Jose DeDiego Beekman
Houses, is moving to seize the complex of 38 buildings and 1,238
apartments in the Mott Haven section of the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 25 years, the complex has been owned by Gerald
Schuster, general partner of the Continental Wingate Company, a
real estate company in Needham, Mass., that has rehabilitated
dilapidated buildings in New York and Massachusetts with federal
subsidies, tax breaks and low-interest loans.
</P>
<P>
   According to an audit by the Inspector General's Office at HUD,
Schuster and his companies siphoned $1.4 million in funds from the
complex to pay company employees and to repay loans to his own
companies. Some of the funds were also diverted to other
investments.
</P>
<P>
   The findings of the audit were referred to the U.S. Attorney's
Office, which notified Schuster in a March 25 letter that it was
considering civil action in connection with the allegations. The
U.S. Attorney has not filed a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, HUD officials, who had taken control of the
Beekman Houses more than two years ago, also told the tenants that
the agency ``would formalize ownership of the properties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The department has taken these actions in the best interests
of the tenants and taxpayers,'' said Peter Ragone, a spokesman for
HUD. ``HUD is committed to insuring that all New Yorkers in
federally supported housing have access to a decent, clean and safe
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Eisner, a spokesman for Schuster and Continental Wingate,
said that the allegations of misappropriation of funds were
``without merit.'' He said the company had not even seen the audit
of Beekman Houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the best of our knowledge and ability,'' Eisner said, ``we
are in full and complete compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuster and his wife, Elaine, have contributed to, and raised
enormous sums for, the Democrats in Massachusetts and nationally.
Last year, Clinton attended a $5,000-a-plate fund-raising dinner at
the home of the Schusters in Boston.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Starting in the early 1970s, Continental Wingate and its limited
partners renovated the 38 buildings that Beekman Houses comprises
with federally subsidized mortgages and later rent subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   But in December 1996, Continental defaulted on six of the eight
mortgages for Beekman Houses. HUD then paid off $27.4 million in
loans and took control of the complex. Since then, HUD has spent
more than $15 million replacing windows and stoves, rehabilitating
500 kitchens and 450 bathrooms and making the buildings more
secure.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Allen, president of Tenants United for Better Living, said
that conditions had improved at the buildings recently. ``HUD has
been a treat,'' she said. ``We didn't know we were entitled to all
the services we're now getting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Allen and another resident of the complex said the
problems at Beekman Houses were more complex than simply a bad
management company.
</P>
<P>
   Their neighborhood was plagued by drug gangs in the 1980s and
suffered from the federal government's declining support for
housing for poor people. One woman blamed HUD's negligence for
allowing conditions to deteriorate.
</P>
</TEXT>
