<HEADER>
A0361 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-31 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The trophy case no doubt was already being
dusted.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke Blue Devils might have been practicing acceptance
speeches. The comparisons to past teams with similarly overwhelming
greatness were streaming in.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell's San Francisco. Lew Alcindor's UCLA. Bill Walton's
UCLA. Bobby Knight's 1976 Indiana. Christian Laettner's Duke.
</P>
<P>
   With every Blue Devils victory in the march through March _ by
20, 30 points _ two words consistently echoed across the college
basketball landscape.
</P>
<P>
   With every burly spin by Elton Brand or sweet swish by Trajan
Langdon, the words draped themselves around the Devils like the
freshly clipped basketball nets they were supposed to wear as
victory necklaces Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Best ever?
</P>
<P>
   The Devils wore the words well. They never wavered. They looked
unbeatable. They were 37-1. They won 32 straight. They were the
first Atlantic Coast Conference team to sweep to a 16-0 league
record.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow it was the Blue Devils who were dusted on a
Connecticut Monday night that was as cool and refreshing as the
gulf breezes outside Tropicana Field and the jolly smile on Khalid
El-Amin's face.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there was a shocking Duke loss and a fascination with
finding a reason why the Devils finally cracked.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils were so good _ the best ever, many thought _
that the 77-74 loss to Connecticut had to be self-inflicted. Didn't
it? It had to be one of the greatest upsets ever. Didn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons to other great teams that failed at the brink of
glory were made. Images of Villanova shocking Georgetown in 1985
and North Carolina State dropping Houston in 1983 were flashed
across television screens.
</P>
<P>
   The critical traveling call on Langdon with 5.4 seconds
remaining was likened to past blunders such as Michigan forward
Chris Webber's timeout that wasn't in 1993 and the bungled pass of
Georgetown's Freddie Brown to North Carolina's James Worthy in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski's decision to give the ball to
Langdon in the final seconds was questioned like other fateful
moments _ Houston's Akeem Olajuwon drifting to the top of the lane
as Lorenzo Charles sneaked behind for the winning bucket in 1983,
or Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim failing to call time out after
Indiana's Keith Smart hit the go-ahead shot in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not a blunder. This was not a questionable decision
or the fates finally laughing back.
</P>
<P>
   And if this was a shocker, the shock is that we did not see it
coming.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of UConn's national championship win Monday, we
can realize now that we saw exactly what the basketball world
expected to see. We saw a showcase for one of the best college
basketball teams ever.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Jim Calhoun's Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people were saying so many great things about Duke, I
understood because I was saying a lot of the same things,'' Calhoun
said. ``They are truly a great basketball team. But I knew we were
a great team, too. I'm not shocked at what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, nothing about Duke's loss should be considered
self-inflicted, because nothing about Connecticut's amazing effort
in Monday's win was different from what it had showed all year.
</P>
<P>
   While the basketball world marveled at the talent and depth of
the Blue Devils, Calhoun was fielding a team that had maybe the
best pure scorer, toughest point guard and best defender in the
NCAA Tournament _ Richard Hamilton, El-Amin and Ricky Moore.
</P>
<P>
   While depth was considered Duke's strength, Connecticut got more
minutes (43-24), more points (17-8) and more rebounds (8-1) from
more players off its bench (4-3) Monday night, as the Huskies had
done all year.
</P>
<P>
   While Duke was rolling to a 37-1 record going into Monday
night's championship, Connecticut was 33-2 before Monday, with one
of the losses coming when Hamilton and center Jake Voskuhl were out
with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding plays in the championship game will be replayed for
years and perhaps even called Duke blunders. There was the
traveling call on Langdon and his crash to the ground later in the
desperate final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But they were not blunders or mistakes at all. They were plays
that showed just how great Jim Calhoun's Connecticut was in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The travel didn't just happen; Moore made it happen by wrapping
himself around Langdon with arms and legs flailing and the great
Duke guard cracking. El-Amin coolly hit back-to-back free throws.
Then Moore again harassed Langdon until the buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. Positively. Absolutely. I want Trajan Langdon to
take the last shot,'' Krzyzewski later explained about the final
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Of course he did. And he should have. Langdon was one of the
best players on a truly great team _ truly great.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Calhoun's Connecticut was better. And maybe we even
should call it one of the best ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
