<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUNK-DRIVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS CRACKDOWN ON DRUNKEN DRIVERS CUTS ACCIDENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the first month that the New York Police
Department began seizing the cars of drunken drivers, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said Tuesday that the program had been a successful
deterrent, leading to drops in arrests for driving while
intoxicated and in related automobile accidents.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the mayor said, the police have impounded cars
in less than half of the cases in which they arrested drivers on
charges of being intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Between the start of the program, on Feb. 22, and last Thursday,
342 people were arrested on charges of driving while intoxicated,
but the police seized only 164 vehicles, or about 48 percent of
those involved in arrests, according to Police Department
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 178 vehicles that were not seized under the program after
drunken driving arrests, 149 belonged to individuals other than the
accused driver, 12 were leased cars, six were rental cars and 11
were marked as evidence of other crimes, such as car theft.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers suggest that the police will confiscate far fewer
than the 5,000 cars that some officials had predicted would be
seized this year. Between March 25 and Tuesday, 47 more people were
arrested on charges of driving while intoxicated and 17 cars were
seized, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday morning at a police auto pound in
Brooklyn, Giuliani said that overall arrests for drunken driving
had declined more than 25 percent compared with the same period
last year. Drunken driving arrests had dropped 7 percent in 1998
when compared with 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also said the number of accidents caused by drunken
driving had declined to 110 from 179 in the same one-month period
last year, or about 38.5 percent. ``The results have been really
very, very impressive,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also offered new statistics to support the toughest
aspect of the program, that even cars belonging to first-time
offenders are seized. He said first-time offenders had caused 80 to
90 percent of drunken driving fatalities in the United States last
year. And he said first-time offenders had caused the only two
drunken driving fatalities in the city this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective is to take a 3,000-pound weapon out of the hands
of what is in fact a violent criminal, somebody who drives drunk,''
said Police Commissioner Howard Safir, who attended the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, which has filed a lawsuit on behalf of a group
whose cars were among the first seized under the new program, said
Giuliani had overstepped his authority by starting the policy
without seeking a change in forfeiture laws from the state
Legislature. .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
