<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0365 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIGILANTE-AZR &LR;      03-31 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIGILANTE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX POLICE HONOR ONE MAN WHO USED WEAPON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One man is called a hero after he blasts 14 rounds into a car of
three Mexican nationals suspected of killing a Phoenix policeman.
</P>
<P>
   The police union gives him a $500 reward and a certificate for a
replacement gun at an emotional ceremony Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another man opens fire, along with police, on a suspect in the
shooting death of a girl in a north Phoenix apartment complex on
Peoria Avenue three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Police never even released his name.
</P>
<P>
   So what are the rules for good Samaritans when police officers
are in distress?
</P>
<P>
   It's actually quite simple, says Sgt. Mike Torres, a Phoenix
police spokesman. The citizen's actions must be legal and police
must need the help.
</P>
<P>
   Rory Vertigan, who was transported to and from Tuesday's
ceremony by a police escort, acted legally in firing on the car
with the men who are accused of killing Officer Marc Atkinson.
</P>
<P>
   One of the suspects aimed his weapon at Vertigan. Vertigan's
help also was important to police because Atkinson was alone in his
police cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Vertigan's help, police were able to quickly nab
Felipe Petrona Cabanas, his cousin Oberline Cabanas Salgado and
Oscar Martinez Garcia. Each was indicted on counts of first-degree
murder, aggravated assault and drug charges by a Maricopa County
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The man on Peoria Avenue also felt in danger and had legal
justification to fire on Samuel Rotondo. Rotondo was indicted for
first-degree murder in the shooting death of 11-year-old Rebecca
Ray last December. But the civilian shooter's actions weren't
needed since there were many police officers in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Police also didn't know if the man was friend or foe, and his
gunfire presented problems because it came in a heavily populated
area, Torres said.
</P>
<P>
   But in some cases, the help is not potentially dangerous for
innocent bystanders and saves an officer's life.
</P>
<P>
   Like the case of Officer Lyn Butcher, who had her pistol
wrestled from her by a man she had stopped at a DUI checkpoint
March 22. He fired three or four rounds at her but was distracted
by a man who charged at him after seeing Butcher in distress.
</P>
<P>
   That man turned out to be 24-year-old Francisco Diaz Sedilla,
who also was honored with Vertigan and presented with a $1,000
reward. Butcher later sobbed as she was embraced by Diaz and said,
``Without him I would be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, a gardener who moved to Phoenix four years ago from the
Mexican state of Jalisco, said the rules of engagement for taking
on a bad guy who could have killed a police officer were easy for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw a woman on the ground and a big man over her firing
shots,'' Diaz said. ``I don't care who the woman is, in that type
of situation I will help her.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, who was unarmed, charged 34-year-old Parviz Amin Zavosh of
Scottsdale, who fired two shots in Diaz's direction, narrowly
missing his leg, Diaz said. Zavosh then fled in his vehicle and was
killed by police later at his home in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on the two officers prompted city officials to
commit two patrol officers to each vehicle citywide during the most
dangerous times, from 3 p.m. to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Skip Rimsza said 77 more police officers will be hired at
an anticipated cost to the city of $3.5 million annually. Rimsza
said that the city would be applying for a matching grant to the
federal Department of Justice and that ``we could really struggle``
if state funding is cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``But every city in this state should go to two-officer cars,''
Rimsza said.
</P>
<P>
   That's a given, said police officers from around the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   As for citizens getting involved to help officers, they say
common sense is of utmost importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, the last two in Phoenix have turned out well, but I
don't recommend anyone taking the law into their own hands,'' said
Sgt. Dave Moyers of Maricopa County Sheriff's Office. ``The most
important thing for citizens is to be another set of eyes and ears
for license numbers, description of the suspects and what direction
they went.''
</P>
<P>
   Officer Andy Vidaure, a state DPS spokesman, noted that a state
statute requires citizens to help officers if the police ask them
for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult call, though, for a citizen to say if
they should jump in or not,'' Vidaure said. ``Especially if
handguns are involved because that can get real ugly real fast. If
a citizen feels up to a situation physically and wants to lend a
hand, they need to be sure and announce that they are there to help
the officer.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Shaffer can be reached at (602) 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
