<HEADLINE>
GOING STRONG AT 85 
A CARDINAL'S VOW 
BOOK STARS ON TV 
 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with NADINE BROZAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How big would the round table at the Algonquin Hotel
have to be to hold the crowd at Budd Schulberg's birthday party?
</P>
<P>
   The obvious answer is, bigger than it is. After all, Schulberg
collaborated with F. Scott Fitzgerald in his 20s, wrote the script
for ``On the Waterfront'' in his 30s, managed prizefighters in his
40s _ and celebrated his 85th birthday on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Why the Algonquin?
</P>
<P>
   ``I went there with Dorothy Parker, not early when she was part
of the round table, but later,'' Schulberg said. ``I went there
with Bill Faulkner.'' And, improbable as it sounds, considering the
Algonquin's elegant reputation, he put up a heavyweight, Archie
McBride, there before a 1955 bout at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The guest list for the party was ``a cross-section of people
I've known over the years,'' Schulberg said. They included
Christopher Plummer, who appeared in the 1958 film ``Wind Across
the Everglades,'' which Schulberg wrote and produced; Jason Robards
Jr., who won a Tony Award for his role in Schulberg's play ``The
Disenchanted''; Patricia Kennedy Lawford (``I worked for her
brother, Bobby Kennedy,'' he said); Phyllis Cerf Wagner, whose
first husband, Bennett Cerf, published Schulberg's first book,
``What Makes Sammy Run?'', and Elia Kazan, who directed ``On the
Waterfront.'' Also on hand were Schulberg's wife, Betsy, and their
children, Benn and Jessica.
</P>
<P>
   The birthday cake had two Oscarlike statues on top, and
Schulberg invited Kazan to join him in blowing out the candles.
Kazan, whose 90th birthday is six months away, received an honorary
Academy Award last week that reignited the controversy about his
having named names in the 1950s, when the House Un-American
Activities Committee was investigating Communist influences in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that in all the brouhaha of these last weeks, there was
so much emphasis on that political situation that people lost sight
of the work he'd done,'' Schulberg said. ``His pictures, 15 or 16
of them, are artistically four stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulberg also said that he had promised to ``stay in shape to
punch Rod Steiger in the nose for his comments about Kazan.''
(Before the Oscars, Steiger made the rounds of talk shows,
denouncing the decision to give Kazan the Oscar.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I said it jokingly,'' Schulberg said. ``It was a positive sort
of an evening.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cardinal's Vow &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal John O'Connor looked out at the television cameras and
reporters during a special Mass at St. Patrick's Cathedral on
Tuesday night and made a not-so-solemn vow:
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise I will never, never again write a letter saying this
will be my final anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few months the cardinal has been dropping hints
that he would step down imminently, and when he invited all the
priests in the archdiocese to Tuesday night's ceremony (the Chrism
Mass, which celebrates the priesthood), he wrote them that it might
be the last one he would perform as cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal submitted his resignation to the pope on his 75th
birthday in 1995, as required by church law, but it was not acted
upon.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he will turn 80, at which point he will lose his
vote in Vatican councils.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you expect me to announce my retirement and my
successor, all I can do is give you the phone number of His
Holiness,'' O'Connor said Tuesday night _ and went on with his
sermon.
</P>
<P>
   Book Stars on TV &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To the amazement of everyone at the QVC television shopping
network, where ``book'' is a verb used to describe the act of
cajoling big-name guests into agreeing to go on the air, one of the
hot sellers during the program ``Live on Fifth Avenue'' on Sunday
was not a lava lamp or a cubic zirconium necklace, but a book.
Something with pages that could be read.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Public Library Desk Reference, to be specific. Some
850 copies were sold in 2 minutes 54 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul LeClerc, president of the library, noted that the Desk
Reference has long been the biggest seller at the library's gift
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was he surprised that the library's $799 chairs _
made-to-order reproductions of those in the main reading room _
drew hundreds of calls to QVC. ``One person who recently came here
for a visit obviously shared my passion for the chairs and promptly
ordered 12 for his dining room,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
