<HEADER>
A0373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-RESPECTFUL-POLIC     03-31 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RESPECTFUL-POLICING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RESPECTFUL LAW ENFORCEMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, March 31:
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Amadou Diallo was killed in a hail of 41 police
bullets almost two months ago, the unarmed West African's death has
become a racial benchmark in New York City. The shooting has
provoked the arrests of more than 1,200 demonstrators at
police &UR;  &LR; headquarters. It has forced changes in police policies,
including an overhaul of the Street Crimes Unit, where the four
policemen worked, and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has made his first
efforts to meet with black leaders and even hear out some of his
most vocal critics.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, as this divisive case moves into the legal system,
with second-degree murder indictments of the policemen expected
Wednesday, a troubling debate about the Diallo legacy is spreading
into the public dialogue. Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard
Safir are talking about a slight uptick in shootings and murders in
New York City, and Safir has questioned whether ``this whole
atmosphere'' after the Diallo shooting might be affecting the
ability of the police to do their job.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor is also sending a message that protesters and the
media coverage of the Diallo affair could be dangerously
distracting the police, sapping their confidence. One unfortunate
implication is that only the old way worked and that tampering with
past police practices could mean a return to the destructively high
rates of crime and fear in the city. Do it our way, this message
suggests, or suffer.
</P>
<P>
   A number of experts have argued that vigorous policing does not
need to ignite community anger or limit civil rights, that security
does not require bullies or necessitate verbal and physical abuse.
A recent report from the Vera Institute of Justice in New York City
makes that point expertly with a study of two police precincts in
the South Bronx where crime is down but so are civilian complaints
about verbal or physical abuse by police.
</P>
<P>
   The institute found that the success of these precincts in
dealing with their communities depended heavily on the attitude of
the commanding officers. In these two areas, the precinct
commanders not only followed department policies for ``respectful
policing,'' they also went beyond the requirements with more
training and careful managing of personnel. For example, when there
were civilian complaints, these two commanding officers took them
seriously, often talking about the problems directly with the
officers involved. Younger officers charged with complaints or even
``displaying attitude problems'' were paired with officers
experienced in policing without antagonizing the public.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which deserves more study at 1 Police Plaza,
concludes that these successful precincts prove that ``large
reductions in crime can be achieved while practicing respectful
policing.'' The city should not be forced to choose more crime or
more civilian complaints. We deserve neither.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
