<HEADER>
A0375 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KC-MAYOR-KAN &LR;      03-31 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-MAYOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNES WINS IN LANDSLIDE FOR KC MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kay Waldo Barnes celebrated her 61st birthday
Tuesday by winning election as Kansas City's first woman mayor.
</P>
<P>
   She defeated two-term Councilman George Blackwood by a decisive
59 percent to 41 percent in a race that gave voters a choice
between maintaining the city's current direction, or trying to
improve basic services while controlling spending.
</P>
<P>
   The vote with, 100 percent of precincts reporting, was 45,146
for Barnes and 31,319 for Blackwood.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who will be inaugurated April 10, campaigned as both an
experienced politician and an outsider with fresh ideas and a
creative approach to the city's problems. She spent more than a
year laying the groundwork for an aggressive, well-financed and
well-organized campaign, and she led in the polls since December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited about the election results and deeply
appreciative of the opportunity to serve as mayor of Kansas City,''
Barnes said Tuesday night. ``I take the responsibility very
seriously and will do everything I can to be the kind of mayor of
whom the city will be very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood said simply:``I gave it my best shot. Everybody worked
real hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' victory will go down in the history books because of her
gender. That fact appeared not to be lost on women voters, who
backed Barnes by better than a 2-to-1 ratio in a mid-March poll
conducted by The Kansas City Star. The poll had Barnes and
Blackwood attracting about the same amount of support from men.
</P>
<P>
   Although Blackwood trailed Barnes in the polls, in the two weeks
before the primary his campaign became more focused as he salvaged
a second-place finish among six candidates.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed the course and, as the weeks passed, his campaign
gained momentum, especially as he emphasized how he would carry
forward the agenda of Mayor Emanuel Cleaver.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver, who never publicly endorsed Blackwood but who supported
his candidacy, declined to comment Tuesday night on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   In the four weeks since the primary, Barnes and Blackwood had
endured intense campaign schedules, participating in dozens of
debates, fund-raisers and small group meetings.
</P>
<P>
   They clashed over many issues, particularly the mayor's role in
the Kansas City School District, the city's approach to
neighborhoods, and strategies for cutting the city budget.
</P>
<P>
   They traded potshots over their television commercials. But in
person they were always cordial to each other, and they each shared
strong connections to the city's power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has spent 30 years building a management consulting and
public-speaking business. She also was a pioneer in Kansas City's
women's movement, serving as one of two women on the 13-member
Jackson County Legislature from 1974 to 1978 and as one of two
women on the nine-member Kansas City Council from 1979 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   She lost her re-election bid in 1983 and got out of politics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she was appointed to the city's Tax Increment Financing
Commission, which reviews tax breaks for major developers. She was
chairwoman of the commission until 1998, and people impressed with
her leadership style encouraged her to run for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes quietly began exploring the idea more than a year ago and
began campaigning in earnest more than six months ago. She had more
than 1,600 campaign contributors and picked up most of the major
endorsements. She even enlisted the help of her famous cousin,
retired CBS news anchor Walter Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   In her campaign, Barnes said her priorities included ending the
perception of corruption at City Hall, improving basic neighborhood
services and controlling spending to rein in the city's $881
million budget.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood, 59, ran his campaign as though he were the incumbent,
describing the positive aspects of Kansas City and stoically
sitting through Barnes' criticisms during debates and forums.
</P>
<P>
   But Blackwood did engage Barnes through his campaign
commercials, making light of her record as a council member and
attacking her for participating in closed-door meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood's general election campaign concentrated on such
issues as economic development and public safety. His platform
recommended forming a committee to study whether to change the
Kansas City Board of Education from an elected body to one
appointed by the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes heavily criticized him for interfering with the school
district rather than supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood got off to a rough start in the general election race
when he appeared at a campaign event with alcohol on his breath and
accepted a ride to his next stop from a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   But he rebounded quickly.
</P>
<P>
   His latest campaign finance disclosures showed that he had
raised almost as much money as Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Barnes apparently offered the right combination
of qualities. She was a fresh face with a hands-on background at
City Hall. Her enthusiasm on the campaign trail didn't hurt,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``People saw her as new but experienced,'' political consultant
Jim Bergfalk said. ``I don't believe anybody who was new and
inexperienced could have won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
