<SLUG> BC-EDIT-UCONN-CHAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE HUNGRIER HUSKIES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, March 31:
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the University of Connecticut's basketball players did
not read the script for a Final Four tournament that everyone in
St. Petersburg, Fla., was calling the Duke Invitational.
Unfortunately for Duke, its players had memorized the script and
come to believe in their own inevitability. So had Duke's semifinal
opponent, Michigan State. On Saturday, the Spartans played
aggressive defense but seemed rattled on offense and intimidated by
Duke's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the UConn Huskies brought a different attitude to
Tropicana Field. Theirs was a team intent on proving that an old
baseball saying _ a hungry player will beat you _ applies to
basketball, as well. Too much has been made of the stumbles of
Duke's star, Trajan Langdon, in the last seconds of the game. The
Huskies won because they had already delivered over 39 minutes of
obsessive team defense, a well-balanced offense and a streak of
clutch shooting by Richard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   UConn came away with its first NCAA championship, and Duke,
surprisingly, nailed down an odd distinction, too. The Blue Devils
have now lost six championship finals, more than any other team.
That's a deceptive statistic, of course. It means that year after
year, Duke is in the race for No. 1, and the Blue Devils won
consecutive championships in 1991 and 1992. They play the game very
well down in Durham. But this year the team from Storrs
demonstrated that even a storied opponent is vulnerable to hubris
and the superior effort of a team with equal talent and even
greater hunger. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 0032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-VA-MENTAL-PATIEN     03-31 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-VA-MENTAL-PATIENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WHEN MENTAL PATIENTS ARE AT RISK
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, March 31:
</P>
<P>
   When federal officials in Washington shut down all animal and
human experimentation at the nation's largest Veterans Affairs
medical center last week in Los Angeles, it was a welcome sign that
government agencies may no longer be willing to tolerate the
potential abuse of mental patients by scientists in the name of
drug research. The joint action by several different agencies
halted 500 different experiments at VA hospitals and clinics in Los
Angeles _ in the very city where the suicide of a patient at the
beginning of the decade helped to trigger concerns about drug
research.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Lamadrid killed himself in 1991 by jumping off the roof
of a building at the University of California at Los Angeles. He
was a former student there, one of dozens of schizophrenic patients
under study to see what the effect would be if their medications
were withdrawn. That procedure and another, in which patients are
given drugs specifically intended to make their symptoms worse so
that doctors can study them as they occur, are two of the most
controversial forms of drug research. Patient advocates charge that
both have been used at the West Los Angeles Veterans Affairs
Medical Center, which is one of the largest research institutions
in the United States, with a sorry record for the casual way it
monitors mental patients under study.
</P>
<P>
   The federal clampdown was based not on any specific abuses of
patients but on the medical center's failure to provide adequate
safeguards for patients involved in human experiments and the
required monitoring and reporting. Dr. Kenneth Kizer, under
secretary for health at the Department of Veterans Affairs, and Dr.
John Feussner, its chief research and development officer, deserve
credit for calling a halt until the defects are corrected. The
Department of Health and Human Services simultaneously cut off
federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   In states like New York and in the federal arena, where a
commission appointed by President Clinton has just finished
drafting its recommendations, efforts are under way to improve the
system for monitoring human research. The lesson just provided by
the Department of Veterans Affairs should guide them all. In
research on a population as fragile as the mentally ill, it cannot
be assumed that patients are being treated well. When they are not,
or one cannot be sure they are not, the process should be shut
down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 0035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-GOLLIN-NYT &LR;      03-31 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GOLLIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A. GOLLIN, PUBLIC OPINION RESEARCHER, DEAD AT 68
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Albert Gollin, a sociologist and public opinion
researcher who earned an international reputation for his studies
of newspaper advertising and readership trends, died March 24 at
his home in Manhattan. He was 68.
</P>
<P>
   His death came after a long battle with multiple systems
degeneration, also called Shy-Drager syndrome, related to
Parkinson's disease, said his wife, Ann.
</P>
<P>
   Gollin was given the Distinguished Career Award for the Practice
of Sociology from the American Sociological Association in 1994
and, in 1998, the Distinguished Achievement Award by the American
Association for Public Opinion Research; he was president of the
organization in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Gollin was born in Chicago on Dec. 8, 1930. He received a B.A.
in psychology at Queens College in 1952 and a Ph.D. in sociology
from Columbia University in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   His research career began in 1958 as a study director at
Columbia University's Bureau of Applied Social Research. He later
spent 14 years at the Bureau of Social Science Research in
Washington. There, he conducted research on the sociological
characteristics of Peace Corps volunteers, as well as those who
participated in the 1963 March on Washington and the 1968 Poor
People's Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always had an interest in civil rights,'' said his first
wife, Gillian Lindt, a professor of religion and dean of faculty
emerita at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Gollin joined the Newspaper Advertising Bureau, a trade
association in New York City that was then part of the American
Newspaper Publishers Association, as an associate research
director.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Gollin retired from the Newspaper Association of
America, which was created by the merger of the American Newspaper
Publishers Association and several other trade groups in 1992. At
the time of his retirement, he was vice president and research
director.
</P>
<P>
   He was also a senior resident fellow at the Freedom Forum Media
Studies Center at Columbia University during the 1995-96 academic
year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Gollin is survived by a son, Mark of
Seattle, and a daughter, Karin of Manila, a grandchild, three
stepchildren and four step-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
