<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NETS EXTEND LEASE ON BASEMENT APARTMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ It is happening slowly, like the drip of syrup
from a maple tree. But after what the Nets have been through, that
is reason enough to get excited.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying the athleticism, the depth and the energy that
everyone had expected of them when this shortened season began some
two months ago, the Nets played inspired basketball Tuesday night
for the second straight game and for one of the few times this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, they came up empty in the victory column _
tightening their grip on the Eastern Conference basement _ losing
to the Orlando Magic, 100-98, when Horace Grant sank a 16-foot
baseline jumper with 16 seconds left. But the team that has shocked
and disappointed New Jersey with its dismal, inconsistent play
seems to be improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the season goes until Aug. 15, we might get there,'' Coach
Don Casey said. ``You see the improvement, but they need a little
reward for it. It's not just about closing the gap. They need a `W'
for their efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who played well in losing to the Cleveland Cavaliers
last Saturday, came within inches of winning Tuesday night when
shots by Stephon Marbury and Chris Carr bounced off the rim in the
final moments. Inbounding the ball after Grant's jumper, the Nets
went to Marbury, hoping that he could create against Darrell
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   With 13 seconds left, a dribbling Marbury faced the Magic's
cat-quick guard and sized up his options at the top of the key.
Making his move with about eight ticks left on the clock, Marbury
drove to his left and got off a contested layup that was just a bit
too strong off the backboard. A scramble ensued, and Carr grabbed
the ball two feet in front of the 3-point line on the left wing.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking victory, he took a dribble, stepped behind the 3-point
line and launched his shot. It was close, but it was off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two seconds left in the game,'' Carr said,
defending his decision to go for 3 points ``You've got to take a
shot at the win. We had already made an attempt to tie and failed,
so I thought I'd go for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a bit disturbed by Carr's move, Casey did not dwell on it
_ ``In the kid's mind, the three wins the game, so at least he's
thinking in the right direction,'' he said _ because the good the
Nets (5-24) did far outweighed Carr's questionable judgment.
</P>
<P>
   In coming up just short of winning at the Orlando Arena, the
Nets threatened to do what few teams have.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic, which, at 22-9, has the best record in the Eastern
Conference, is 16-2 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there were the Nets, without their injured star Keith Van
Horn, who missed his second straight game with a sprained right
ankle, moving the ball crisply and shooting a torrid 60.5 percent
to take a 56-49 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who cooled off significantly in the second half,
shooting a mere 30.2 percent, put the Magic on the brink of defeat
with outstanding balance, teamwork and defense. They fought off
many challenges to keep their lead at 81-79 heading into the fourth
period.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles led five Nets in double figures with 18 points and
4 of the club's season-high-tying 16 steals. Marbury scored 7 of
his 17 points in the final 3 minutes 22 seconds, on two driving
layups, including one that gave the Nets a 98-96 lead with one
minute remaining, and a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   And the banged-up Jayson Williams turned in another fine effort,
contributing with 16 points and 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Anderson, who hit a 19 footer to answer Marbury's go-ahead
basket four seconds later and tie it at 98, led Orlando with 28
points, 9 of which came in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly ageless Dominique Wilkins followed with 17 points
in 13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, having finally seen a spark from his new team, summed
it up for the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a confidence booster for us,'' he said.
``We played hard, we played smart. We did everything we were
supposed to do. We played great defense. They just won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
