<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-GAS-LINES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. DRIVERS SORE AS GAS PRICES SOAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Motorists waited in long lines at discount gas
stations and others called off holiday trips as gas prices have
risen by an average of 15 cents a gallon across Southern California
in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Experts blame the increase on refinery problems in Northern
California and a vow by oil-producing countries to reduce their
output of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the average price for a gallon of regular self-serve
unleaded was $1.33 in Los Angeles, up from $1.19 two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But prices are changing day to day.
</P>
<P>
   Arco, which normally has among the lowest prices at some
locations, was selling a gallon of regular for $1.38, up from $1.30
a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gas prices are nuts,'' said Linda Mader who languished in
line for 15 minutes at a Costco service station in suburban Van
Nuys where a gallon sold for just $1.31. The prices are so high
Mader said she has called off a trip to Palm Springs for Easter.
</P>
<P>
   The hike also took a toll on civility as some customers fumed,
glared and prodded their fellow customers to hurry up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I come into work it's why, why, why?'' said
station attendant Jeshua Aguilar, 19. ``Why are the prices so high?
Why are you ripping us off? And I tell them it's like this
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The future of gas prices is less clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have analysts saying all sorts of things, that it will go
as high as $2 a gallon or it will go down,'' said Jeff Spring,
spokesman for the Automobile Club of Southern California. ``There
will be a point where people will pay greater attention to how they
drive to save on gasoline.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the California Energy Commission, a state agency
that monitors energy supplies, the price should begin to fall by
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should not be concerned about getting gasoline,'' said
Claudia Chandler, an assistant executive director of the
commission. ``(Prices) are already leveling off and probably by
next week you'll start to see it drop. By the end of April, we'll
probably be back to our seasonal normal levels'' of about $1.12 per
gallon for regular.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of oil-producing countries to cut production by about
2 million barrels a day has not had that much impact on California,
which gets most of its oil from Alaska, Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's 13 gasoline refineries are now back to 96 percent of
their normal production and supplemental shipments began arriving
this past weekend, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be soon enough for Jeffrey Nelson, who stopped Tuesday
at a Chevron station in Warner Center where regular was fetching
$1.48 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do short trips like I used to _ where it was more
economical for me to drive rather than fly _ because the gas prices
have risen so much,'' said Nelson, a 42-year-old New Yorker in town
to work with some recording artists he manages.
</P>
<P>
   When he left New Jersey three weeks ago, a gallon of regular was
89 cents, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by the Automobile Club of Southern
California, some stations are pushing $1.50 for a gallon of regular
and in the San Francisco Bay Area the average price of a gallon of
regular is $1.61, following three refinery problems there including
a fire at a Chevron facility last week.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than simply fill up the tank, Randi Riddle of suburban
Woodland Hills said she now takes whatever amount of gas $20 will
buy her.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are angry but what are you going to do?'' said Riddle,
a preschool assistant director. ``I quit smoking when they raised
the price of cigarettes. Now what, am I going to have to quit
driving?''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said she is concerned by reports that some motorists
are topping off their tanks almost on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're afraid that they're not going to find the same price
for gas tomorrow as they did today,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
