<HEADER>
A0390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT     03-31 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FINAL WORD BELONGS TO SPREWELL AND EWING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one but the brazen Latrell Sprewell would have had
the nerve. Out of foolishness or faith, Sprewell grabbed a Reggie
Miller miss and sprinted wildly down the floor, leaving his
teammates behind.
</P>
<P>
   It was basket or bust with 1 minute 20 seconds left in the game.
With two defenders in front of him, Sprewell darted to the left of
a backpedaling Miller and swooped in for a driving layup to finish
off an electrifying moment seldom before seen from a man in a
Knicks uniform. Cheering his every stride along his reckless path,
the crowd at Madison Square Garden fell head over heals for
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   And when the crazy end was over, so did Patrick Ewing. He
embraced Sprewell as the teammate who took the burden off his
hulking shoulders in an uplifting 94-93 victory on Tuesday night
over the loathed Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a poised victory against a team that mattered, in an
ending that didn't leave Ewing as the tragic figure again. Ewing,
who scored a season-high 37 points and was involved in a first-half
confrontation with Jalen Rose that nearly developed into a melee,
was buoyed by Sprewell's 18 points. Sprewell's flashy drive for a
layup was part of a 6-0 run the Knicks needed to surge past the
Pacers and douse Miller, who scored 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had a chance to win it with 7.9 seconds left. But his
shot bounded off the rim. Rik Smits grabbed the rebound in front of
Ewing, who had missed a jumper just seconds early as he fell to the
ground. Smits passed to Travis Best, whose 19-foot jumper bounded
off the rim. Again, the Knicks botched the rebound and gave the
rookie Al Harrington a chance to win it at the buzzer. But his tip
fell off the rim and the 19-year-old from Paterson, N.J., lay in
disbelief on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost so many close ones like this,'' said Sprewell,
whose layup closed the Knicks within 1 point before he hit two free
throws to give the Knicks the lead with 1:01 left. ``To be a part
of this is a lot more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from their mindless retaliations in Saturday's
loss to the Lakers, the Knicks kept their heads under duress in the
second quarter. Instead of getting sucked into the chaos, Ewing
held back from pummeling the lanky Rose with 2:57 left in an
intense first half.
</P>
<P>
   After going down hard in Ewing's shadow for a rebound, Rose,
sprawled on the floor, lifted his right foot to trip Ewing as he
stepped over him. Ewing popped up, scowled and rushed toward Rose,
who had his fists up, as if saying, ``Bring it on.''
</P>
<P>
   With Rose backing into the right corner of the court with Ewing
in front of him, referee Dick Bavetta got between the two and
received a broken nose for his effort.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Rose threw a punch at Ewing that did not land.
Ewing shoved, but apparently did not throw a punch at Rose or at
Dale Davis, who entered the scene. Davis and Ewing began shoving as
Coach Jeff Van Gundy wedged his diminutive figure in between the
two big men.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently learning their lesson from previous fight experiences
with Miami, none of the Knicks were seen leaving the bench. Once
the situation was defused by the officials, Rose, who had been
defending Sprewell, was ejected from the game for a punching foul.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in two games that the Knicks were
involved in an on-court scuffle. Against the Lakers, the Knicks
lost their heads and ended up with Chris Dudley and Kurt Thomas
tossed from the game.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Rod Thorn, the league's vice president of
operations, fined Thomas $5,000 for tossing Dennis Rodman on his
head in Saturday's game and Dudley $2,500 for throwing a ball and
hitting Shaquille O'Neal. For his part, shoving Dudley, O'Neal was
fined $3,500, which indicated the league felt the shove was more
aggressive than Dudley's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night, Ewing held back and played on. He led the
Knicks to 19 first-half points and helped provide his team with a
54-51 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, already down an injured Antonio Davis, had to figure
out how to overcome the weariness they were feeling in playing
their third game in three nights and how to manage undermanned.
</P>
<P>
   They handled it well to begin the third quarter. Using Smits to
spring outside of the slow-moving Dudley, who started next to Ewing
for the second game in a row, the Pacers went ahead 63-58 in the
opening four minutes of the third quarter. A couple of jumpers by a
very lively Ewing and the Knicks regained the lead by 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   A brief back-and-forth ended with Sprewell head-faking his way
into the lane for a 15-foot runner at the shot-clock buzzer with
2.9 seconds left in the third quarter. His play gave the Knicks a
74-73 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
