r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BASKETBALL-COLUMN     03-31 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BASKETBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNT ON DUKE IN 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As we turn to next season, a morsel to consider:
Connecticut's victory over Duke on Monday not only capped '99, it
may have sealed 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut star and Final Four MVP Richard Hamilton probably
will bolt for the NBA _ his value will never be higher, just ask
Miles Simon _ while Duke's defeat may cause center Elton Brand to
return for his junior year. (He wants a title.) In addition, the
loss likely convinced point guard William Avery to stay in school.
</P>
<P>
   If Brand and Avery return, you can hand Duke the trophy Oct. 15.
Here's a preliminary look at next season's contenders.
</P>
<P>
   SWEET 16: Auburn: The Tigers were no one-hit wonder. Although
they lose the element of surprise, Chris Porter, Scott Pohlman and
Doc Robinson will keep them in the Top-25 all season.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse: The inconsistencies of '99 will evaporate as the
starting five returns. Jason Hart, Etan Thomas and Ryan Blackwell
will help the Orangemen compete for the Big East title.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga: Like Auburn, the Bulldogs return most of their top
players _ only point guard Quentin Hall and center Jeremy Eaton
depart _ but they'll be a targeted team. The key is coveted coach
Dan Monson: If he returns, the Bulldogs will, too.
</P>
<P>
   Temple: If forward Lamont Barnes bolts for the NBA, Temple joins
the pack. But if Barnes returns, the Owls become a Final Four
contender with Pepe Sanchez, Mark Karcher, Kevin Lyde and coach
John Chaney's zone defense.
</P>
<P>
   Texas: Center Chris Mihm and power forward Gabe Muoneke give the
Longhorns a superb frontcourt. Replacing scorer Kris Clack won't be
easy.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's: Assuming forward Ron Artest heads for the NBA, the
Red Storm will have a solid frontcourt and brilliant backcourt
(Erick Barkley and Bootsy Thornton). If Artest returns, put St.
John's in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Florida: The Gators lose one-eyed wonder Eddie Shannon, but Mike
Miller, Brent Wright and Ted Dupay return with highly touted
recruit Matt Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State: Even if Mateen Cleaves returns, the Spartans
will have trouble duplicating their Final Four run. Morris
Peterson, Andre Hutson, A.J. Granger and Duke transfer Mike
Chappell will find, as Stanford did this year, that it's tougher
the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   ELITE EIGHT: Kentucky: Not even the Wildcats can lose a senior
class of Heshimu Evans, Scott Padgett and Wayne Turner and not feel
it. But by March, coach Tubby Smith will have Kentucky rolling
behind Tayshaun Prince, Desmond Allison, Jules Camara, Michael
Bradley and Jamaal Magloire (if he doesn't turn pro). The
recruiting class, as always, is excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona: The Wildcats lose All-America point guard Jason Terry
but replace him with heralded recruit Jason Gardner. They lose
all-conference center A.J. Bramlett but replace him with Wake
Forest transfer Loren Woods. Add sophomores-to-be Richard
Jefferson, Ruben Douglas and Michael Wright, and it's time for a
serious tournament run.
</P>
<P>
   Utah: The Utes lose point guard Andre Miller but return everyone
else of consequence, including starters Alex Jensen and Hanno
Mottola, top reserve Tony Harvey and the nation's best coach, Rick
Majerus.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State: The backcourt (Scoonie Penn and Michael Redd) is
good enough to get the Buckeyes through the draining expectations
that follow Final Four seasons. Coach Jim O'Brien's system is
superb, and center Ken Johnson may become the nation's top shot
blocker.
</P>
<P>
   FINAL FOUR:
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina: The Tar Heels return eight of their top nine,
including Ed Cota, Jason Capel and Max Owens on the perimeter. Kris
Lang and center Brendan Haywood, a future Lottery Pick, form a
gifted front line. Add top recruit Jason Parker, and UNC appears
poised for its second Final Four under coach Bill Guthridge.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois: A surprise pick, for sure, but the Illini have a
superb coach (Lon Kruger), a young team _ point guard Cory Bradford
is the vortex _ and a massive influx of talent. They'll be next
year's version of Ohio State _ a worst-to-Final Four turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas: Yes, they're back. After a subpar year, the Jayhawks
have most of their best players back and welcome top recruit Andrew
Gooden. He'll join Jeff Boschee, Eric Chenowith, Lester Earl and
Kenny Gregory to form an experienced and athletic core.
</P>
<P>
   Duke: If Avery and Brand return, watch out. The Blue Devils lose
Trajan Langdon, but Chris Carrawell, Shane Battier and Corey
Maggette return with experience and purpose. Add the nation's top
recruiting class _ Jason Williams, Mike Dunleavy, Casey Sanders and
perhaps Carlos Boozer _ and Duke will have 10 McDonald's
All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: The ridiculous report of the week comes from
ESPN.com, which said there was speculation at the Final Four that
UCLA coach Steve Lavin's job was in jeopardy. Despite the
first-round loss to Detroit, Bruins officials are happy with
Lavin's performance, his recruiting, the way he represents the
program and the fact he's not Jim Harrick.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins the Pacific-10 every couple of years, makes a few
Final Fours and stays out of trouble, Lavin will coach UCLA as long
as he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Harrick: Jim Sr. is a finalist for the Georgia job _
he'd be a good fit in the SEC _ while Jim Jr. wants the Pepperdine
gig. The Waves could do better, much better.
</P>
<P>
   Top recruit Carlos Boozer, whose finalists are UCLA, Duke and
St. John's, could announce his decision this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: UCLA will play Cal State Northridge on Dec. 5 at
Pauley Pavilion. Get your tickets now _ or get them 10 minutes
before tipoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
