<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS TAKE STING OUT OF HORNETS
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-CELTICS-HORNETS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By PETER MAY 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Team pictures Wednesday night. Everyone smile,
please.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino almost had to summon the airbrush artists after a
near collapse in the final five minutes Tuesday night. But he was
here-to-there smiles later after the Celtics woke up when it
counted and left town with a rewarding, albeit
tougher-than-it-shoulda-been 109-99 victory over the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   The victory is the second in three games and perhaps could
signal an end to the Era of Negativity that engulfed the team last
week. Kenny Anderson was terrific, Paul Pierce rolled back the
clock all the way to February, and Antoine Walker played another
strong all-around game. It was a dramatic 180 from the Celtics'
last visit here three weeks ago, when they were humiliated by an
undermanned and injured Charlotte team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans must have thought back then, `What is that CBA team
doing in this building?' '' said Anderson, who was 9 of 13 from the
field and had 22 points, including a team-resuscitating trey with
94 seconds to play. ``We're a different team. We've grown. I think
for that game, when we were here, we were like 18 years old. A high
school team playing against men. This was more like 25. We've
grown. We're making strides.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to argue otherwise, especially if team video
ace Frank Vogel sneaks into the tape vault and erases the final
five minutes. Until their late skid, the Celtics played almost
flawless basketball. They put on an offensive clinic, as evidenced
by the shot distribution: all five starters had no fewer than 10 or
more than 13. That's unselfish basketball. They harassed the
Hornets with their press, getting 22 points off 14 turnovers. They
shot 58.6 percent, a season high, and delivered the kind of game
Pitino hoped to see sooner and much more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way we wanted to play,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   The victory also snapped Charlotte's eight-game home winning
streak and was Boston's second straight on the road, where only
recently the Celtics had been sheep in sheep's clothing. The
new-look Hornets, with Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell, also had won
six of seven and even were talking about making the playoffs after
a 1-8 start. But the team the Celtics saw Tuesday night, even
though it shot 58 percent, played a lot more like the team from
earlier that prompted the Churchillian Derrick Coleman to note
``there goes the season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When they came here the first time, they were playing well and
we were down and we just outworked them,'' said Charlotte guard
David Wesley, one of five ineffective Hornets starters. ``The
reverse happened this time. They outworked us. They outplayed us.
We came out flat and didn't get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Boston big guys were Pierce, who had a shot-from-guns
first quarter (12) and finished with 19. He was going to the
basket, drawing fouls, looking like the Rookie of the Month that he
once was not so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to get my explosiveness back,'' said Pierce, who
was 7 of 12 from the field. ``I'm just mad it took me so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker (15 points, 6 rebounds, 5 assists, 4 stitches courtesy of
a Brad Miller elbow) was into serious shot avoidance; he took only
one in the first quarter, a trey, and drained it. Vitaly Potapenko
had 14 points, including two big hoops in the fourth right before
the Hornets made their run. Tony Battie had 12 off the bench as the
Celtics had seven players in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   But all the good things _ and there were a lot of them _ nearly
got blown away when the Hornets' reserves went to work. A Walker
layup gave Boston a 98-84 lead with 5:43 left and also brought
about vapor lock. Five unsuccessful possessions resulted in 10
straight Charlotte points. It was 98-94 with 2:08 left and Pitino
was not a happy camper.
</P>
<P>
   Battie made a free throw to make it 99-94 and then Miller, fast
developing cult status after games of 24 and 25 points this past
week, was called for traveling. Anderson, who was 2 of 17 from
international waters entering the game, then stepped up and hit The
Big One, which got the lead back to 8.
</P>
<P>
   The locker room was a much happier place than it was three weeks
ago. Those smiles you see Wednesday night will be real, at least
for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
