<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS ZING THE BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-KINGS-BRUINS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with lesser competition, faced with a prime chance to move
a giant step toward clinching a playoff spot, the Bruins Tuesday
night played every bit like an eighth-place team in search of an
identity, a reason to win, some meaning in a long season that is
drawing to a close.
</P>
<P>
   What they got, in the end, was a rude awakening: A 2-1 loss to
the lowly LA Kings, delivered with 66 seconds left in overtime from
the stick of Oli Jokinen.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost playoff time and the Bruins have caught a rut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, we need points,'' lamented losing goalie
Byron Dafoe, his own undefeated streak snapped at six games (3-0-3)
in the latest fault at the Vault. ``If that's not incentive enough,
I don't know what is _ end of story.''
</P>
<P>
   The tale of late has been the Bruins' inability to lay waste to
those who are there for the trashing. Saturday night, they held a
2-0 lead over the Maple Leafs and saw that dissolve into a 2-2 tie.
Thursday night, with the beat-me, kick-me, whip-me Blackhawks in
town, they grunted and groaned along for a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound like any way to tune up for the postseason?
</P>
<P>
   The loss prevented the Bruins from opening up a 7-point lead
over the Panthers and Rangers for the eighth _ and final _ playoff
spot in the Eastern Conference. In their last three games, they've
booted away 4 points, the gemstones that might have pulled them
into a seventh-place tie with the sagging Sabres (81 points).
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said team captain Ray Bourque, who was on the ice when
Jokinen backhanded in the OT killer, ``could come back to haunt
us.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, when there was help to be had at the trading
deadline, the Bruins decided not to add to their lineup. They were
gaining on the competition (i.e. Rangers and Panthers), some of
their kids were contributing, the front office liked the pulse it
thought it felt. Suddenly, the beat of momentum isn't there,
especially when the competition ranks, like the Kings, among the
lower echelon. And there is no help beyond what is right here,
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like our games against Toronto or Chicago,'' said
coach Pat Burns, whose postgame news conference was among his
briefest of the season. ``We could have eliminated two teams with a
win. We just didn't shoot tonight. I say it in practice all the
time _ shoot! shoot! shoot! We want to make a pretty play.''
</P>
<P>
   Overhandling the puck was only part of the issue vs. the Kings.
For the most part, the clubs engaged in 60 minutes of shinny,
skating freely up and down the ice with few, if any, aggressive
encounters along the boards or in the corners. It was a classic
no-hitter, and the Fleet boo-birds (some of them Celtic holdovers?)
began to get testy and more vocal by early in the second when it
was clear neither side would do battle. Had they been skating
waiters, porting glasses full of water, not a drop would have been
spilled.
</P>
<P>
   If one side could be rated better than the other, the Kings
would get the edge. Unimpeded, they were able to force the puck
deeper into the Boston end, part of the reason they held a 20-15
shot lead after 40 minutes. Maybe they didn't bury their chances,
but at least they were getting them, and they were getting them
without much resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Byron wasn't on top of his game,'' bemoaned Burns, ``this
would have been really ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's only goal came off the stick of Sergei Samsonov,
negating a 1-0 LA lead at 12:09 of the third. Parked in the right
circle, he wristed home his 21st of the season after linemate
Dmitri Khristich fed him a soft backhander as Khristich approached
the goal line. The goal ended a 10-game scoring drought for
Samsonov, last season's rookie of the year who has slumped as a
sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings took the 1-0 lead earlier in the third, at 5:40, when
captain Rob Blake crossed the blue line and nailed a long slapper
off right wing. Backing up on the play, defenseman Don Sweeney saw
the shot deflect first off his stick and then break in off Dafoe's
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The LA winner came with the Bruins scrambling in their end,
Jokinen sweeping in his shot with help from Craig Johnson. Red
light on. Up with the boos. Fade to silence as the disgruntled
crowd headed for Causeway Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were the better team out there, and we're playing
for more than they are,'' said Dafoe. ``Everyone seems to know the
Boston Bruins have trouble getting up for teams that are lower in
the league, and then we play unbelievable against the best teams in
the league.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be good news in the playoffs _ provided they get
there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
