<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ TO BOSSES: DON'T FENCE ME IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Juan Gonzalez returns to Texas tomorrow,
seemingly a baseball superstar who now has it all.
</P>
<P>
   But on second thought...
</P>
<P>
   Should the American League MVP do more in 1999? And will
Gonzalez be asking for more from Rangers management? More than just
the additional financial riches that will soon flow his way?
</P>
<P>
   When the Rangers' chartered jet from Florida smokes tire rubber
on the D/FW runway tomorrow night, Gonzalez will not be burdened
with most of the extra baggage from years past.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, for the most part, is the reputation of a brooding, sullen
man-child. Acceptance by the Rangers' fandom was slow, but Juan has
finally won them over, and not just with offensive might. Over the
years, he showed he cared about playing right field, and about
hustling ``almost'' all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching Juan when he first got here \Rin 1991\S and watching
him over the last couple of years, I'd say he's 90 to 95 percent
arrived as the complete ballplayer,'' said first baseman Rafael
Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no reason why it shouldn't be 100 percent. To me,
it is not acceptable for a superstar like him to loaf on an
occasional play in right field. To not hustle after a ball. Or to
not run hard to first base.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, returning to the Rangers after five seasons in
Baltimore, has appointed himself this spring the designated ``Juan
cop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be on his butt every time I see that temporary
lack of hustle,'' Palmeiro said. ``Juan is the best. I want him to
always give his best.''
</P>
<P>
   This is good. Juan listens to Rafael, even if Juan doesn't
necessarily like what he hears.
</P>
<P>
   But then comes a separate question. Will the Rangers' hierarchy
be listening to Gonzalez, even if team president Tom Schieffer
doesn't like what he's going to hear?
</P>
<P>
   A new long-term contract for Gonzalez within the next year, if
not sooner, is a given. The money will be stacked higher than a
Gonzalez moonshot to the bleachers. At age 29, Gonzalez still
hasn't reached his prime baseball years, is now in better physical
condition than ever, and has won MVP awards two of the past three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Forget, however, the money. That's Tom Hicks' worry.
</P>
<P>
   Much more interesting will be another of Gonzalez's contract
``requests.'' It is too early to call it a ``demand,'' but
eventually this may become one.
</P>
<P>
   To re-up with the Rangers, Juan wants architectural relief at
The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, move in the left-field fences, and therefore remove that
miniature ``Death Valley'' for right-handed power hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lose home run balls out there every season; balls that are
over the fence almost anywhere else are caught in Arlington,''
Gonzalez said yesterday. ``When I lose homers, I think we lose. The
team loses.''
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested to Juan that the dimensions might cost him 10
homers a season. ``No,'' he answered. ``Fifteen, maybe 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever ... the amount is significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told my agent \RJim Bronner\S that when we start
talking seriously about a new contract, I want the left-field
fences to be a big part of the negotiations,'' Gonzalez said.
``This is a major concern for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer, standing on the press-box roof here yesterday, smiled
broadly when told of Gonzalez's ``request.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan is a guy who has always been fair with us, and we've
always been fair with him,'' noted Schieffer, choosing his words
carefully. ``But having said that, we also aren't going to move in
the fences.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, this might become interesting.
</P>
<P>
   When The Ballpark was in the planning stages eight years ago,
Gonzalez was a budding home-run monster. But with a 390-foot power
alley to left field, and almost 370 to straightaway left field, the
park was not built with Juan's future in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, more than ever, pitching is a problem throughout
baseball,'' Schieffer said. ``With more right-handed power hitters,
we made left field the deep part. With less left-handed power, we
put the porch in right field. And since we built the park, the
pitching ranks have thinned even more. As it has turned out, I feel
the dimensions are perfect for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, one of the reasons Mo Vaughn became a prized
free-agent signee in Anaheim was because the Angels agreed to pull
in the fences. Gonzalez certainly noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will listen to Juan, but I also don't see this eventually
being a deal-breaker on Juan's part,'' Schieffer added.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not. But while money is a given factor in the
negotiations, a possible tug of war over the ballpark blueprint is
an extra and entertaining dimension.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 0110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
