<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0402 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-TIMBERWOLVES-MAVE     03-31 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TIMBERWOLVES-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMBERWOLVES ROUT FADING MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The pressure apparently got the best of Mavericks
coach Don Nelson last night.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was ejected in the second quarter of a 98-78 loss to the
Minnesota Timberwolves for vehemently protesting the lack of a call
on a play that knocked Mavericks guard Erick Strickland out of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   On the play, Strickland released an 18-foot jumper from the
right wing that missed, but he was knocked to the floor by
Minnesota's Tom Hammonds. Nelson quickly hopped from the bench and
used vulgar language to referee Tommy Nunez, who slapped Nelson
with a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   When Nelson followed Nunez onto the court and continued with
more spicy language, Nunez tagged him with another technical and
Nelson collected his first ejection of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Strickland was helped off the court and did not return to the
game after a diagnosis of back spasms. Assistant coach Donnie
Nelson coached the Mavericks for the balance of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson refused comment after the game, but Donnie Nelson
said his father's blowup was a way of ``protecting'' Strickland and
a sense of frustration from this disastrous season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any one of \Rthe three referees\S saw it,''
Donnie Nelson said. ``I don't think they don't make a call like
that on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that the official that was right next to the call
\RNunez\S was looking into the paint. Probably what happened was
none of them saw the call. ... he \RDon Nelson\S was standing up
and protecting his player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks (10-22) have lost three games in a row and eight
of their past 10. Tomorrow night, they are host to the worst team
in the NBA _ the Los Angeles Clippers _ in what has suddenly become
a game that could define this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an explanation,'' said guard Steve Nash, who had
three points and 10 assists. ``We've hit the wall, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Strickland will be re-evaluated today, but said the incident was
somewhat scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he tried to avoid me, but ended up hitting me in the
lower part of my body, and he also took my legs,'' he said.
``That's what scared me more than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were playing their fourth game in five days, and
Minnesota ran the weary-looking visitors ragged. The Timberwolves
built a 28-point lead early in the fourth period (88-60) on
back-to-back baskets by Kevin Garnett as the Mavericks played
nonchalant after the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With eight players scoring, the Mavericks distributed the ball
nicely and actually had a 24-22 lead. But the Timberwolves scored
the first 10 points of the second quarter as the Mavericks went
more than four minutes with scoring. Dean Garrett had six points in
the run, which was capped by a hammer-dunk by Hammonds.
</P>
<P>
   With Strickland out, and John ``Hot Rod'' Williams (stomach flu)
and Robert Pack (hamstring) back in Dallas nursing ailments, the
Mavericks were down to nine healthy bodies in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves were also hurting, playing without starters Joe
Smith (ribs) and Anthony Peeler (calf) and reserves Malik Sealy
(ankle) and James Robinson (back).
</P>
<P>
   Gary Trent led the Mavericks with 16 points and 11 rebounds, and
Shawn Bradley had 13 points. But after losing by 20 or more points
for the second time in the past three games, the Mavericks are
clearly a team at the crossroads.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
