<HEADLINE>
L.A. COPS AMONG PLAYERS INVOLVED IN BRAWL GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A coed softball game erupted into a bench-clearing
brawl, with the adult players swinging punches and baseball bats at
one another, and one man drawing a gun, authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived to break up the fights Monday, they were
surprised to find that at least three of the combatants were
off-duty LAPD officers.
</P>
<P>
   One off-duty officer drew his gun in self-defense after more
than one person attacked him with baseball bats, said Detective Ed
Heissel, in charge of the Crimes Against Persons unit at the Los
Angeles Police Department's Devonshire station.
</P>
<P>
   The brawl at the Petit Avenue park in suburban Granada Hills was
under investigation, and no arrests have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Soboroff, president of the Los Angeles Parks Commission,
called the conduct outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets you angry. You work very hard to offer this kind of
recreation for people,'' he said. ``There is no place in the league
for this kind of behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Los Angeles police officers were treated at Northridge
Hospital Medical Center for minor injuries, Heissel said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the fighting erupted after a referee's call
sparked an argument, and an off-duty police officer told the mother
of an opposing player to shut up.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next depends on whom you talk to: members of the
Quakes or the Aztecs team, which won the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Aztecs is made up of civilian players from a park league.
The Quakes include civilians and at least four Los Angeles police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Heissel and an Aztecs player said the disagreement began after a
referee changed his call from ``safe'' to ``out'' in the last
inning _ giving the win to the Aztecs.
</P>
<P>
   Aztecs player Pauline Castillo said, ``One gentleman from the
Quakes got in (the umpire's) face and started cussing at him.''
</P>
<P>
   A mother in the stands watching her son play for the Aztecs
yelled ``Kick him out of the game!'' Castillo said. The Quakes
player confronting the umpire then yelled back to the mother,
telling her to ``shut up,'' witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The son of the mother got upset and the whole fight started.
He said, Don't be talking about my mom like that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one-on-one to begin with and then all the guys started
going in,'' Castillo said, adding that at one point three Quakes
were fighting with four Aztecs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the off-duty officers' account, about 14 Aztecs
rushed toward the off-duty officers playing on the Quakes team,
Heissel said. ``There were a lot of people on the winning team
involved in assaulting the officers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the off-duty officers called 911 on his cell phone,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The fist-fighting and kicking stopped for a few minutes, and
then started again in the parking lot as the off-duty officers
left, Heissel said.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo said that at one point a Quakes team member held an
Aztecs team member's arms down while another Quakes member ``kneed
him in the stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   An LAPD officer retrieved a gun from his vehicle and pointed it
at the crowd and then at a female Aztecs player, Castillo said. He
held the gun within inches of the female's forehead, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Freeze! LAPD,' with his gun pointed to the people,''
Castillo said, adding that he never showed a police badge.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD Commander David Kalish said the case will be thoroughly
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being investigated as a criminal matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Singer, a park recreation supervisor for the Mid-Valley
District, said ``brouhahas happen'' at parks with yelling, pushing
and shoving.'' But he was upset to learn that it had escalated to a
gun being drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're adults. But in a way, they're like children. When kids
get into a fight, adults break it up. When adults get into fights,
who in the heck breaks it up?'' Singer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
