<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLEY FINDS A MISSION IN MOTHER'S ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Glenn Foley always was looking for charities
to donate time and money to. Six months ago, one found him.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Foley, the mother of the Seahawks' newest quarterback, was
rushed to the hospital on Oct. 5. It was thought she was having a
stroke. Tests instead showed she was going into kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of charity work before,'' Foley said Tuesday
during a break in the Seahawks' four-day quarterbacks camp. ``All
of a sudden, this one hit us right in our face with my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention weighing heavily on the hearts and minds of
Foley, his wife, Jen, and their close-knit families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was very physically and emotionally draining,'' Jen
said. ``It was scary.''
</P>
<P>
   This story has a happy but hectic ending.
</P>
<P>
   Sue had been diagnosed with polycystic kidney disease in 1970,
just after Glenn was born. PKD causes cysts to grow on the kidney,
which enlarges the organ and hinders its filtering ability. It is
the most common of the life-threatening genetic diseases and, at
this time, does not have a cure.
</P>
<P>
   Sue had one kidney partially removed in 1970, and last October
the other started to fail. She needed a transplant to live and had
only weeks to find a match.
</P>
<P>
   Each of her four sons volunteered, including Glenn, which would
have meant the end of his football career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Mom, what's the difference? I don't care if I play
football again,''' Sue told the Hartford Courant at the time. ``I
told him, I told all of them: No way. ... I never gave it a second
thought. I mean, this is not the same thing as asking somebody for
a ride to the mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sue got the needed kidney from her husband, Ed, who
like Glenn played quarterback at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to and following the Nov. 5 double
surgery where doctors removed a football-sizekidney from his mother
and replaced it with a healthy organ from his father, Foley would
fly from New York to Boston after practicing with the Jets to be
with his parents. Then he would fly back in time to be at practice
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crazy. Glenn had a lot of stuff on his shoulders,'' Jen
said. ``His mom's disease progressed so quickly, no one was
expecting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn and Jen already had started the Glenn Foley Wings
Foundation earlier in the year. A 3-handicap golfer, Foley had won
money in celebrity tournaments, only to give it to a designated
charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of donating to this charity and that charity, we
decided to start our own charity,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother's battle with PKD gave the new organization its
cause. Cliff Foley, Glenn's older brother, also has the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this happened,'' Jen said, ``it was very clear this is
what we were meant to educate people on.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Foley's entire family is involved in Wings. But it is Jen
who has it soaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the one who really has taken this thing and is running
with it,'' Glenn said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is with the Seahawks, who obtained him two weeks ago
in a trade with the Jets, the Wings Foundation has become
bicoastal.
</P>
<P>
   While Glenn was busy with practice Tuesday, Jen was setting up
her new office in Bellevue. The other office is in Moorestown, N.J.
The goal is to raise at least $200,000 for a PKD Foundation
educational grant, and to raise awareness of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be great. The awareness of PKD is about to
blossom,'' Glenn said. ``Now we can go coast-to-coast with it and
hopefully raise a lot of money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
