<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0408 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      03-31 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINCHCLIFFE MAKES GOOD USE OF HARD-EARNED CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Brett Hinchliffe admires Jim Abbott in the way
any other major leaguer would.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's amazing,'' the Mariners right-hander said. ``I watched
him the other day, that was the first time I'd seen him live. You
can't bunt on him. He's incredible. Then he bats, and he got a
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, people have asked Hinchliffe if he looked up to
Abbott for a different reason. Abbott, a veteran left-hander with
the Milwaukee Brewers, was born without a right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe, a rookie who has pitched his way onto the Mariners'
roster this spring, was born with a webbed left hand. The
hereditary condition is known as syncactylism. He was spared
another symptom, the loss of a muscle in the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe, who worked four innings in the Mariners' 9-5 victory
over the Arizona Diamondbacks Tuesday, was born with five fingers
on his left hand. But, recognizing the webbed condition, doctors
amputated his middle finger and inserted that bone in his thumb.
Hinchliffe has two bones in the thumb, allowing him to grip things
and giving him better mobility. His second and third fingers are
stubby, but both have joints and one has full mobility, and his
pinkie is normal.
</P>
<P>
   The scars from the operation are obvious, and Hinchliffe's left
wrist and hand are significantly smaller than his right. He has
thought about asking his glove manufacturer for a specially
designed model, but the one he has is fine. He has to tighten the
strap around his wrist, and occasionally a hard line drive will
knock the glove loose. But appearances aside, Hinchliffe's hand
functions normally.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger, things were said,'' Hinchliffe said. ``But
for the most part I wasn't really teased that much at all, at least
not that I can remember. It wasn't too bad when I was growing up,
because I could do everything and play all the sports. Guys
respected me.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those sports caused Hinchliffe trouble last spring. He
sprained his ankle playing basketball, leading to the first of four
setbacks that made him something of a mystery man to manager Lou
Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   The ankle injury, a detached retina, food poisoning and an
uncle's funeral back home in Michigan kept Hinchliffe out of action
during the exhibition season. He went 10-8 with a 4.00 earned run
average for Class AAA Tacoma, but a late-season bone spur kept him
from getting a September call-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the caravan this winter, and people asked, `Who are
some of the young pitchers coming up?''' said outfielder Charles
Gipson, Hinchliffe's best friend on the team. ``I told everyone,
`Brett Hinchliffe,' and they're all like, `Who's that?' But I've
seen him throughout the minor leagues _ he's got good stuff, lots
of pitches, works hard. It was a matter of just getting the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   That chance came this spring, and Piniella said Hinchliffe has
pitched ``as well as anyone we've had in camp.'' Including two
innings in a charity game, Hinchliffe has allowed three earned runs
in 17 innings for a 1.59 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   He has shown the M's a major league fastball, slider, curveball
and changeup, the last of which he can use to get left-handers out.
The 24-year-old also has shown major league confidence, displaying
an uncommon ease around Piniella and pitching coach Stan Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a throw day the other day, and Stan and I talked to him
the whole time,'' Piniella said. ``He was very relaxed, threw the
ball to both sides of the plate, worked on his breaking ball. You
can't do that with too many young kids. They're more intense and
focused on what they're doing. With Hinchliffe, he was intense and
focused, but also relaxed enough to talk to us and give us feedback
while he threw.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe said he benefited from being in camp last year,
absorbing the atmosphere and learning how major leaguers acted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I came into camp and I was all relaxed and ready to
go,'' he said. ``Last year I might have been nervous, but for some
reason, this year I'm just not. I don't know, it's just a different
feeling. I feel like I belong. I feel like I'm part of the team,
and that's why I'm so relaxed and so calm out there. It's a good
feeling to actually keep a smile on your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's easier to smile when you've never allowed a
major league run. In fact, Hinchliffe has avoided trouble almost
all spring, which is why catcher Tom Lampkin reminded him to keep
it together after allowing a pair of solo homers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to get everybody out all game,'' Lampkin
said. ``You have to rebound and pull yourself out of it. He seems
to me to have the type of personality that will enable him to do
that, but we'll have to see when the season starts. Because he's
going to be tested this year, there's no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Minor league pitching coordinator Bryan Price said Hinchliffe
always has had confidence. But it's taken him seven minor league
seasons to get a shot in Seattle because, at 6-foot-5 and only 190
pounds, Hinchliffe was raw when he entered the system and needed to
mature physically. Now, his physical tools allow him to approach
the game the way he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give the hitters too much respect,'' Hinchliffe said.
``A lot of young guys give hitters too much respect, and they're
afraid to throw their fastballs. But the hardest pitch to hit is a
well-located fastball, either inside or outside. I like to
establish that early.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe was slated to be the Mariners' fifth starter until
reliever Mark Leiter went down with a shoulder injury. Piniella
said Hinchliffe could fill Leiter's relief role for the first few
days of the year, then make a start April 14, the first day Seattle
needs a fifth starter. Or, he could stay in relief and Ken Cloude
could start.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Hinchliffe isn't counting on anything. Asked what
number he'll choose if he can drop No. 68 _ the highest still in
camp _ he laughs and says he won't think about it until he's flying
into Sea-Tac.
</P>
<P>
   But the last survivor in his row of lockers in the M's spring
training clubhouse doesn't think he's a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Said Gipson, ``He's just showing Lou what he already knew
himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
