<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTGAME ERUPTION PUNCTUATES LATEST SONIC SLEEPWALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Sonics center Olden Polynice has seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   The bench. The mediocre play. The team's barely above-average
record.
</P>
<P>
   And after the Sonics took a 95-87 pounding from the San Antonio
Spurs at the Alamodome Tuesday night, Polynice gave his duffle bag
a beating. Polynice, the team's energizer on the court, displayed
different emotions while slamming several personal belongings into
his luggage.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics lost for the second time in three games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little ticked off right now. (Expletive) 15 and 14?''
Polynice said, referring to the Sonics' record. ``I'm mad because
we're losing. I didn't come here to lose. I had other options.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps none of those included sitting on the bench for long
stretches, which is what Polynice, Billy Owens and Hersey Hawkins
did Tuesday. Frustrated by another slow start, Sonics coach Paul
Westphal made good on his word to shake up the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   So rookies Vladimir Stepania and Jelani McCoy were inserted with
Dale Ellis when the starting unit missed 10 of its first 12 shots.
The Sonics fell behind 27-14 after the first quarter, and fought
from behind the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics never led.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, the bad start tonight killed us,'' Westphal said.
`` ... It's a frustrating thing to have happen to you. Fatigue may
have played a part but you can't make excuses. You have to make
shots in order to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The team outrebounded a much bigger Spurs team, 47-41, but shot
just 38 percent from the field. Westphal used McCoy for 16 minutes
and Stepania for 23, partly because the pair of 6-foot-10 rookies
gives the team size up front. A bigger reason, though, for the
apparent youth movement is McCoy and Stepania seem to sometimes
play with more hustle and energy than the starters put together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we had to do,'' said McCoy, who had eight points,
five rebounds and four blocks. ``We outrebounded them. We hustled.
The shots just didn't go down. But we're going to keep playing
hard. That's all we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   It would appear the Sonics will continue to dig out of their
funk with younger players getting quality minutes. Westphal said as
much, and his rotation is starting to show that.
</P>
<P>
   Owens never re-entered the game after playing seven minutes in
the first quarter. Hawkins played 31 minutes, and Polynice saw just
23 minutes, which included just four in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to win games. I didn't come here for transition,''
Polynice, who finished with 10 points and nine rebounds. ``If
that's what's happening, it's news to me. Coaches make decisions
and we have to abide by them. But I came here because I thought
this team had a chance to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are trudging through this 50-game season just trying
to make the playoffs. Tuesday's game was their third in three
nights. It also was disappointing after the Sonics beat Dallas
rather easily Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   However, against the Spurs, the Sonics' shots mostly fell short.
They even missed 13 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had nothing to do with three games in three nights,'' said
Ellis, who scored 14 points in 27 minutes. ``If we don't play a
game, then we're practicing for two hours. What difference does it
make?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer must be effort.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 68-60 late in the third, the Sonics made their last run
with young legs on the floor. During one sequence, McCoy blocked
Tim Duncan's shot, rebounded a miss on the other end and scored on
a dunk that got the Sonics within 68-65.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the Sonics threatened, San Antonio responded behind
Duncan, who finished with a game-high 26 points and nine rebounds.
Duncan's dunk with 1:45 left in the game put the Spurs ahead 90-79,
and killed any chance of a Sonic rally.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics found the basket in the first quarter. They just
couldn't put a tennis ball through it. Owens and Gary Payton both
missed their first three shots.
</P>
<P>
   Payton struggled. He missed his first five shots before
finishing with 15 points on 5-of-13 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unfortunate after we played so well (Monday),'' forward
Detlef Schrempf said. ``They took us out of what we wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   These Sonics have been out of it all season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
