<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-ROCKETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS LOSE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Clippers entered March like lambs
and are coming out like lamb chops.
</P>
<P>
   Working the grill Tuesday were the Houston Rockets, who served
up the Clippers' 26th loss in 29 games, 104-95, in front of 9,188
at the Sports Arena. While the Clippers were digesting their 10th
loss in the past 11 games, the hungry Rockets (22-9) polished off
their eighth consecutive victory and 12th in the last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we could pay tribute to the Clippers' usual-and-abbreviated
bursts of pluck, but the only spin doctor who could adequately
treat this lingering epidemic is named Kevorkian.
</P>
<P>
   One rare Clippers constant is the relentless effort of undrafted
rookie forward Tyrone Nesby. Matched against Houston's Scottie
Pippen _ who happens to be the defensive standard for NBA small
forwards _ Nesby hopped around for a career-high 24 points and five
steals.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets _ whose Hall of Fame frontcourt is marking time
in style before being retired to the Hall of Fame _ are expected to
win game like these.
</P>
<P>
   In their corner was 15-year veteran Hakeem Olajuwon, who had
nine of those 17 against Clippers rookie Michael Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were required to withstand the Clippers'
interpretation of the transition game _ going from bad (Monday in
Denver) to worse. But _ before this one could get coyote ugly _
Nesby decided it was time for a few demonstrations of Clippers
chutzpah. He converted two interceptions into breakaway dunks, the
first a spectacular, double-dump reverse that was a 10 in anybody's
book.
</P>
<P>
   Nesby spruced up the resume even more by jamming Olowokandi's
missed jump hook to tie the score at 19 with 2:09 left in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Darrick Martin found rookie Cuttino Mobley's defense
to his liking and scored 12 of the Clippers' 22 first-quarter
points. The Rockets managed 23.
</P>
<P>
   The second quarter was a showcase for Othella Harrington,
Houston's low-post sub who worked Lorenzen Wright for 11 points as
the Rockets outscored the Clippers, 30-17, taking a 14-point
advantage into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, whose recent history suggests their motto should
not be ``May the fourth be with you,'' decided against rolling over
and playing dead.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Hudson, who was liberated from the CBA one week ago,
drilled a 3-pointer at 9:30 of round four to pull the Clippers to
within seven. Maurice Taylor followed with a bucket, but the
Rockets exhaled into a working _ and winning _ margin behind a pair
of heart-stabbing 3s by guard Brent Price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
