<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ In the darkness, the little
villages in the rolling hills and river valleys around the Kosovo
city of Dakovica emptied out, rushing _ literally, for their lives
_ to beat the 5 a.m. deadline set by Serbian forces. Even as some
60,000 ethnic Albanians streamed into this border town, mostly from
around a main highway to the northeast, Serb forces were
methodically going from village to village in an entirely different
area to the northwest, the Has District, telling the villagers they
must leave or they would be killed in the morning. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Frustrated by the war propaganda
that passes for news here, a small but significant minority of
Serbs spend long hours every day watching satellite television,
exchanging e-mail and surfing the Internet. But few find the
Western version wholly convincing. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BRITAIN (London) _ How Britain, with harsh, emotional
language about war crimes, is leading the campaign to win the
public's hearts and minds against Milosevic. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GENOCIDE (Washington) _ With the legal justifications for
the bombing ranging from flimsy to justifiably inventive, the U.S.
action in Kosovo may be effecting profound changes in the evolving
field of international law. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (Washington) _ Since the bombing of Yugoslavia
began, American officials have threatened to prosecute perpetrators
of violence in Kosovo, but for that threat to be credible, changes
must be made in the war crimes tribunal that would try them,
American officials and human rights advocates say. By Raymond
Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Blace, Macedonia) _ The flow of refugees from
Kosovo is overwhelming neighboring countries, leading to long
delays at the borders and, in some cases, refugees are being
ordered to turn back. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BASEBALL (Monterrey, Mexico) _ Major League Baseball's
first season opener to be played outside the United States or
Canada is scheduled for Monterrey on April 4. The game has caused
so much excitement that tickets sold out in three hours when they
went on sale here last month. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   GORILLA-WARFARE (Bwindi Impenetrable Forest, Uganda) _ A band of
16 mountain gorillas _ among the last 620 alive in the wild _
seemed healthy. But their future is far from guaranteed since the
war in the Great Lakes region of East Africa spread to their
neighborhood here in early March and took its latest victims: a
game warden and eight foreign tourists, including two Americans. By
Ian Fisher.
</P>
