<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NAME, IT'S TIME FOR RAMS TO RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italic) Today's episode of The Sporting Muse, which once again
casts a suspicious eye at the NFL: (end italic)
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL does indeed return to Los Angeles, there's some
business that needs to be considered by the league and any group of
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Cleveland reacted when Art Modell took the Browns to
Baltimore, a grass roots movement is needed to reacquire the name
``Rams'' from the infidels who took the team to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   This is a win-win proposition. L.A. would get back a name that
had deep meaning when the franchise played in the Coliseum, before
it shuffled off to sleepy Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams played for NFL titles with fellas named Van Brocklin,
Waterfield, Fears and Hirsch. The Rams were coached by George
Allen. The Rams produced more modern-day heroes like Merlin Olsen,
Deacon Jones, Roman Gabriel, Dick Bass. The Ram helmet logo once
had as much meaning in L.A. as the script Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis owners would make beaucoup dollars through new
merchandising for a name that the city would feel is its own, as
opposed to one it got second-hand. ...
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's expansion committee is scheduled to make its visit to
tour the Coliseum and Carson in late April. It wants to have a site
recommendation to return to the membership at a meeting in May.
</P>
<P>
   It will likely be then that the league will want an ownership
group to take form. A league source said the committee fully
expects prospective owners beyond the current suspects to step up.
...
</P>
<P>
   The NFL keeps saying that any expansion to 32 teams would be its
last for quite some time. Forgive my skepticism, but the league
would be very short-sighted financially if it stuck to that policy.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise fee in Los Angeles is expected to be around $650
million, and $500 million if Houston gets a team on the rebound.
Add those two numbers together and you have a billion reasons for
the league to go from 32 to 34 teams as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Two more teams at a modest $1 billion combined would produce a
one-time bonus of $30 million-plus for each current team. That
would far outweigh any loss in TV revenue through sharing with more
partners.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL were to time things correctly, it could have two more
teams ready to go just as it can exercise an option in the current
TV deal. Assuming that TV rights fees will continue to climb faster
than a missile, the league could get a boost to make up for
expanding to 34. ...
</P>
<P>
   Some critics are calling UConn's win over Duke Monday for the
NCAA title a huge upset. But it doesn't come close to N.C. State or
Villanova, who were real underdog winners. The Huskies were ranked
No. 1 for two months and came into the tourney a No. 1 seed. The
``upset'' notion stems from the heavy consensus on Duke, which led
oddsmakers to make Duke a double-digit favorite just to even out
the flow of bets.
</P>
<P>
   UConn deserved to win. Not only did Jim Calhoun discover a way
to frustrate Duke offensively, but his players played it to
perfection. And for once, the best game of the tourney turned out
to be its last. ...
</P>
<P>
   Billy Packer's all-time NCAA Tournament, running as part of an
ad in Sports Illustrated, produced a title game between the 1968
UCLA team and 1976 Indiana. Packer gave the Bruins the nod by two.
That had to take at least a year off his life. ...
</P>
<P>
   Matt Doherty is the new Notre Dame coach. And to think the
former Kansas assistant could have had the Long Beach State job
just a few years ago. He must be miserable about this shift of
fate. ...
</P>
<P>
   I am shocked, shocked I tell you, to learn that Jim Harrick is
pursuing the head coaching job at Georgia, just as I will be
shocked when he pursues the Clippers' job once Chris Ford is freed
from bondage. ...
</P>
<P>
   Interim Lakers coach Kurt Rambis inherited one major problem
from Del Harris too many players and not enough minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are one of the league's deeper teams, but 12-man
rotations are impossible in the NBA. To his credit, Rambis has met
the problem head on by saying there's no solution. ``I can't play
12 guys,'' he said Sunday. ``At best, I can have a nine-man
rotation, and there are nights when I'll use just eight.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more confounding habits of Del Harris was a
keep-everyone-happy substitution pattern that didn't work very
well. Travis Knight, who started 23 games this season, now shares
the end of the bench with Sean Rooks and J.R. Reid, who was having
a nice season with Charlotte (11.9 points, 6.3 rebounds) before
coming west with Glen Rice. ...
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to Tommy Lasorda? Once upon a spring, Dodger
fans would receive gushing daily reports on Dodger Blue. But with a
new general manager and manager in charge, Lasorda has been muzzled
for the first time in perhaps his life.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that his brief impact as GM last year won't be
felt. According to spring reports, Wilton Guerrero (traded to
Montreal for Carlos Perez), united with his brother Vladimir on the
Expos, is having a great spring. And Paul Konerko, now with the
White Sox, also has performed well. The White Sox plan to bat
Konerko as DH fourth behind Frank Thomas, meaning Konerko will have
high RBI potential.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado also signed Brian Bohanon to a $9 million contract
after a fine half-season in the Dodgers' rotation. This one will
likely blow up in the Rockies' face. Bohanon is a junkball pitcher,
and the altitude in Denver is notorious for flattening breaking
pitches. ...
</P>
<P>
   It's great that the Arrowhead Pond earned the rights to host
this year's Frozen Four, the NCAA hockey championships. But
considering three of the four finalists hail from New England
Maine, New Hampshire and Boston College it seems a long way to go
just to learn that the Pond has the worst ice in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   The one name in the tourney everyone will know is Maine's Steve
Kariya, the younger brother of the Ducks' Paul. To show you what
kind of season it's been for the Kings, Dave Taylor's alma mater,
Clarkson University, was eliminated in its regional. ...
</P>
<P>
   There is no truth to reports that Raiders owner Al Davis, after
seeing the crowd at the Cuba-Orioles game Sunday, opened
negotiations with Mr. Castro about a new stadium. How does one say
private seat license in Spanish? ...
</P>
<P>
   I hope Fidel knows that all those major league scouts and
personnel people who attended the Orioles' game as ambassadors
wanted to bring home more than a box of cigars. ...
</P>
<P>
   Mark your calendars: Los Angeles is bidding for the 2012 Olympic
Games. The group seeking the games, which includes 1984 Olympic
organizers Peter Uebberoth and John Argue, has officially launched
its campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC will make a decision in 2005. That gives the L.A. group
ample time to line up college scholarships for children of IOC
member, jobs for family members and large quantities of their
favorite alcoholic beverage. ...
</P>
<P>
   I just want to know what Elia Kazan has to say about Major
League Baseball playing a game in Cuba. Has he called his contacts
in the state department and read them the Orioles' lineup?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
