<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS LOSE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _As if twisting weather prophecy, the Los Angeles
Clippers decided to enter March like lambs and come out like lamb
chops.
</P>
<P>
   Working the grill Tuesday were the Houston Rockets, who served
up the Clippers' 26th loss in 29 games, 104-95, in front of 9,188
at the Sports Arena. While the Clippers were digesting their 9th
loss in the last 11 games, the hungry Rockets (22-9) polished off
their eighth consecutive victory and 12th in the last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   One Clipper who may prevent the team from hiring Kevorkian as
spin doctor is undrafted rookie forward Tyrone Nesby.
</P>
<P>
   Matched against Houston's Scottie Pippen - the gold-medal
standard for defense among NBA small forwards -- Nesby hopped
around for a career-high 24 points and five steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pippen is cool,'' Nesby said, who added shoe time to showtime.
``He said he like my game and told me to keep workin' hard. I asked
him if I could wear his shoes. He said he'd send some down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of talent in (Maurice) Taylor and Nesby,''
Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich, being gracious in victory, said.
``The Clippers are a dangerous team.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, and according to a recent survey, most NBA accidents occur
in the home.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting Rockets -- whose frontcourt (Pippen, Hakeem
Olajuwon and Charles Barkley) is marking time in style before being
retired to the Hall of Fame -- are expected to leave huge
footprints in games like these.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's big three combined for just 37 points, but rookie
guard Michael Dickerson went airborne for 19, while Brent Price
(19) and Othella Harrington (17) combined for 36 off the bench.
Price hit two from downtown to sabotage the Clippers' latest
fourth-quarter conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Taylor had 21 points for the Clippers, but extended his
rebounding slump by recording a lonely one.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps exacting a measure of revenge for the NFL's recent
expansion announcement, the mature Rockets blasted off to a 17-9
lead, fueled by their experience edge in the Great Nigerian
Showdown.
</P>
<P>
   In their corner was 15-year veteran Olajuwon, who had nine of
those first 17 against Clippers rookie Michael Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very mobile,'' Olowokandi said of Olajuwon, his low-post
role model. ``He's sort of like the Michael Jordan of the big
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this one could get coyote ugly -- Nesby decided it was
time for a few demonstrations of Clipper chutzpah. He converted two
interceptions into breakaway dunks, the first a spectacular,
double-dump reverse number that even the Russian judge would reward
with a ``10.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to do a 360,'' Nesby said, ``but I decided to keep
it simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-huh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just tryin' to get our guys pumped up.''
</P>
<P>
   He spruced up the resume a bit more by jamming Olowokandi's
missed jump hook to tie the score at 19 with 2:09 left in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers trailed by 14 at intermission, went down by 22 in
the third period, then rallied to enter round four down by only 11.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's 15-foot runner pulled them to within five at 84-79 with
9:06 to play, but Price countered with two heart-stabbing
3-pointers to restore order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
