<SLUG> BC-TAHOE-QUAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEW QUAKE FEARS IN TAHOE REGION  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The discovery of unmapped seismic faults in the
Lake Tahoe region has increased concerns that major earthquakes
could strike at any time over a wide area between Reno and the
lake's west shore.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have used a variety of techniques to locate the
faults, including tough treks through the rugged terrain of the
area's mountains, sophisticated satellite measurements of ground
deformation, and deep-water soundings that turned up evidence
showing that Tahoe's lakebed has been scarred by past quakes that
created huge underwater landslides and canyons.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, researchers at the University of Nevada in Reno
have warned that as small villages and once-isolated resort
communities expand into large urban centers, the potential damage
from future quakes demands more careful regional planning and
tougher building codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been excited and somewhat shocked to see how many active
faults we've found that haven't been mapped before,'' said Mary M.
Lahren, an earthquake researcher at the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``These could cause major damage to dwellings and business and
could disrupt transportation, communications, and gas and power
lines,'' said Richard Schweickert, chairman of the department of
geological sciences. ``Seismic activity could have serious impacts
on lake clarity and could also affect the nearby Reno-Carson City
metropolitan area.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the newest sonar technology for underwater soundings, a
team headed by James V. Gardner at the U.S. Geological Survey in
Menlo Park surveyed the lakebed last summer and found vivid
evidence that earthquake faults on both sides of Tahoe cleave the
lakebottom itself and have most probably been active in the past
10,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most significant of those newly mapped features,
Lahren said, is a long and complex fault zone in Earth's crust that
runs from Truckee through Dollar Point on the northwest shore of
the lake and continues beneath the lake to Sugar Pine Point and
beyond. The scientists are calling it the West Tahoe Fault.
</P>
<P>
   Another active fault zone extends from the southwestern suburbs
of Reno through Mount Rose and Incline Village and into the deepest
parts of the lake, Lahren said. It is now called the North Tahoe
Fault.
</P>
<P>
   A report prepared by Schweickert, Lahren and seismologist
Kenneth Smith concludes that the newly mapped faults are longer
than researchers have previously thought. Because the length of a
fault is directly related to the power of an earthquake, this means
``that the question of possible earthquake magnitudes needs to be
re-examined,'' they say.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the possibilities are real for large
earthquakes, with magnitudes of 7 or more, the researchers believe.
</P>
<P>
   Only last October, a magnitude 4.9 quake hit just north of
Incline Village. The same area was struck with a magnitude 6.5
temblor in 1966 and a magnitude 6 event in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the potentially damaging faults lies deep beneath
the ground, where a large part of Earth's crust is being
continuously deformed over a vast area stretching across 500 miles
of mountain and desert, from the Colorado Plateau in eastern Utah
to the eastern flanks of the Sierra. The region is known as the
Basin and Range Province, and it's moving.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Geological Survey, geophysicist Wayne Thatcher
recently created an array of 63 ground stations across the entire
province to measure ground motion by taking signals from the
high-precision satellites of America's Global Positioning System.
</P>
<P>
   In a report published in the journal Science earlier this month,
Thatcher and his colleagues found that for 125 miles or so, the
crust in the western part of the Basin and Range abutting the
Sierra is being steadily squeezed at a rate of 21/2 miles a year
northwestward against the more stable crustal block of the Sierra.
That's an inexorable crunch easily powerful enough to fracture the
deep crusts into seismic faults.
</P>
<P>
   In Reno, Schweickert, Lahren and Smith recently briefed
officials of the Tahoe Regional Planning Agency on the implications
of the research. The faults that run beneath Lake Tahoe, they said,
must be considered active because Gardner's new map of the lakebed
clearly shows that the fault traces cut through young sediments on
the bottom, and that large earthquakes in the relatively recent
past have apparently triggered huge landslides into the lake.
</P>
<P>
   There is strong evidence, Schweickert said, that quakes have
ruptured the ground throughout the Reno-Tahoe region repeatedly
during the past, and that they could happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' Schweickert said in an interview, ``is that we
have no way to tell how frequently large quakes have occurred on
each fault in the past, so we can't estimate their recurrence rate
in an effort to see the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reno group now hopes to take a stab at that kind of loose
prediction by taking core samples of the sediments and landslides
on the Tahoe lakebed. Organic matter in the samples would allow
them to use techniques based on radioactive carbon to determine the
dates when past quakes have struck _ and thereby to peer into the
future.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Schweickert said, ``we have to let people know
there's a significant earthquake hazard in the region, but we can't
tell them when the next one will come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
