<SLUG> BC-SISTERS-PROTEST-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: CATHOLIC WEEKLY SPURRED PROTEST OF `SISTERS' PARTY  &HT;     By DON LATTIN  
 and ELAINE HERSCHER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ For years, the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence
have celebrated their anniversary on Easter Sunday. Some years,
they even got permits for their outrageous parties from the city of
San Francisco.
<P>
   So why are the Sisters and the Roman Catholic Archdiocese
suddenly at each other's throats _ and both accusing the other of
intolerance and bigotry?
</P>
<P>
   What has changed in the Bay Area media equation is that the
archdiocese now has its own newspaper, a tabloid sent each week to
110,000 Catholic households in San Francisco, Marin and San Mateo
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic San Francisco gave the church hierarchy a way to rally
the faithful _ with more circulation than some local dailies.
</P>
<P>
   When the Board of Supervisors granted the Sisters a permit to
close a block of Castro Street on Easter Sunday, the newspaper ran
a stinging column titled ``Bending Over Backward to Ridicule the
Faith,'' written by Wade Hughan, vice chairman of the conservative
Catholics for Truth and Justice. It gave readers the phone numbers
of Mayor Willie Brown and four members of the Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call Reverend Amos Brown (who is both a Baptist preacher and a
city supervisor) and ask him if men dressed in habits with
crucifixes around their necks ridiculing our church is an
appropriate way for San Francisco to officially celebrate Easter,''
Hughan suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Enough Catholics called to inspire the mayor and two supervisors
to suggest that the city and the Sisters choose a date other than
Easter. On Monday night, the board refused, with Supervisors Brown
and Alicia Becerril dissenting.
</P>
<P>
   With San Francisco Archbishop William Levada serving as the
paper's publisher and spokesman Maurice Healy as associate
publisher, the archdiocese was able to bypass the Bay Area media,
including newspapers some church leaders see as having an
ambivalent _ or even hostile _ attitude toward the Roman Catholic
Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a growing feeling over the years that while
almost any expression is allowed in San Francisco, religious
expressions are suppressed,'' Healy said. ``Now there is a way to
relieve that tension.''
</P>
<P>
   The current dustup over the Sisters was a flash point _ and the
newspaper a convenient way to channel the Catholic hierarchy's
frustration with the gayest city in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a rupture culturally and spiritually, it's because
there's a chasm between the Catholic Church and the gay
community,'' said the Rev. Jim Mitulski, co-pastor of the mostly
gay Metropolitan Community Church in the Castro neighborhood. ``The
controversy over the Sisters has been an unfortunate way to talk
about much more important issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay people who have faced ostracism from the Catholic Church
have their own suspicions about the church's motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why all of a sudden the archbishop would freak out over this,
I don't know,'' said gay community activist Tommi Avicolli Mecca.
``Why this issue? Why a street closure in the Castro, of all
places, where outrageous things happen all the time? It's not
downtown. It's not in front of his church.''
</P>
<P>
   Healy replied, ``What's driving this is, Catholics have been
watching the Sisters engage in these activities for years on TV and
have been offended and haven't been able to express our feelings in
any way.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, San Francisco Catholics have simmered as their
influence declined in City Hall, while the political power of the
gay and lesbian community continued to grow. More than a quarter of
the Board of Supervisors are lesbian or gay. Its president, Tom
Ammiano, one of the most powerful people in City Hall, is among
them.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishops used to be invited to give the benediction at City
Hall events. Now they issue press releases complaining about the
mayor presiding over mass weddings of gay and lesbian voters
gathered under that same rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our new mayor's penchant for flamboyance has now turned out to
have a far more subversive purpose,'' Levada wrote in his March 19
column in Catholic San Francisco. ``It is linked to a relatively
new, broad-based campaign to change the legal definition of
marriage to include same-sex unions. ... The good order of society
itself requires us to draw a line to protect the institution of
marriage and the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Mecca is one of many gay activists who suggest that the church's
position on the Sisters is an opening salvo in its support of the
Knight Initiative, the measure on the state's spring 2000 ballot
that would make it impossible for same-sex couples in California
ever to legally marry.
</P>
<P>
   Mitulski said that with all the brouhaha, it has been easy to
forget that some of the most devout Catholics are gay. Half of his
500 congregants count themselves as Catholic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're Christians and we're gay and we're happy to celebrate
Easter, and then we're going down to the (Sisters') party,''
Mitulski said.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that both the Archdiocese of San Francisco and the
Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence will come out as winners when this
round of March Madness comes to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Church opposition to their Easter party has given the Sisters
priceless national publicity, guaranteeing a huge turnout for their
Castro Street extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   But the church has also let it be known that there is more than
one powerful voting bloc _ that the Catholic faithful, along with
the Castro's devotees, can make themselves heard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
