 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 426 - March 31, 1999   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 426 -- March 31, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. A FARE TO REMEMBER A person climbs into the back of a dimly
lit taxi. The only eye contact is through the rear-view mirror.
Negotiating a turn, the driver asks a question, prompting the
passenger to start talking. The client senses a need to respond and
within minutes is sharing his innermost thoughts. Only after the
taxi ride is over does the passenger learn that his catharsis has
been videotaped for ``Taxicab Confessions.'' The series documents
real and earnest hidden-camera interviews during late-night drives.
The producers-directors attest that ``everything'' has transpired
in their cabs - laughs, tears, drugs, violence and sex. It's the
passengers' candidness about their real lives that mesmerizes
viewers. By Maryam Heinen. From The Hollywood Reporter. 1,000 words
+ photo. 2. PETER, PAUL AND MARY HELP KEEP FOLK ALIVE The members
of legendary folk group Peter, Paul and Mary may all be over 60,
but they are still keeping the spirit of the '60s alive with music
and political activism. Their new retrospective album, ``Songs of
Conscience and Concern,'' resists the temptation to include hits
like ``If I Had A Hammer'' and ``Where Have All The Flowers Gone.''
Instead, the collection features less known harmonic gems, songs
chosen from the trio's 20 previous albums, to reflect the social
and political issues of today. By Tamara Conniff. BPI. 900 words +
photo. 3. NICKELODEON : THE CHANNEL THAT CHANGED KIDS TV Two
decades ago, certain truths about children's television were held
to be self-evident. Namely, that boys wouldn't watch TV shows whose
main characters were girls; that shows based on toys would be a
commercial success; and that a cable channel devoted to children
was not likely to become a major player in the TV industry. Then
Nickelodeon was born on April 1, 1979. As the network prepares to
celebrate its 20th birthday, it is the top-rated cable network in
the U.S., a distinction it has claimed for four years in a row. By
Don Aucoin. From The Boston Globe. 1,600 words + photo. 4.
CONFUSION REIGNS A damaging battle is about to break out in the
consumer electronics industry on a scale not seen since the VHS and
Betamax standards for VCRs fought it out in the early 1980s. Rival
alliances plan to launch two incompatible music formats. Both will
come with draconian anti-copying measures that may discourage
potential purchasers. By Barry Fox. New Scientist. 300 words. (N/A
Brazil, Australia, New Zealand.) 5. KELSEY GRAMMER'S SHRINK RAP
These are the very best of times for ``Frasier.'' The TV show has
thrived and gained even higher ratings. And few people are more
surprised than Kelsey Grammer, Frasier Crane himself. Interview by
Andrew Ryan. From TV Guide Canada. 1,300 words + photo. 6. DERMOT
MULRONEY WANTS HIS NAME BACK Dermot Mulroney's biggest hit was ``My
Best Friend's Wedding'' (1997.) ``I think that movie is the
ultimate comedy,'' he says, ``because you had characters played by
Julia Roberts and Cameron Diaz fighting over me ...'' The film's
success led to some new opportunties for Mulroney. Interview by
Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
GWEN VERDON STILL HEARS THE MUSIC Gwen Verdon has been successful
on stage, in films and on television and has an armful of awards.
Along the way, she taught Marilyn Monroe how to walk, served as
muse to great director/choreographer Bob Fosse and was in a string
of Broadway hits. It's rare for musical performers to find work
after they pass the song-and-dance age, but this 74-year-old isn't
finished yet. By Michael J. Bandler. 1,300 words + photo
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
GWYNETH PALTROW WOULD LIKE HER LIFE BACK AT 25, Gwyneth Paltrow
virtually stole the Oscor show. She has been described as the ``new
Grace Kelly'' and ``the Meryl Streep of the '90s.'' Paltrow, who
has worked non-stop for the past three years in England, Italy and
Canada, says she has been trying ``to get my life back.'' By Ivor
Davis. 1,300 words + photos. (N/A Great Britain and Australia.) 9.
PETE POSTLETHWAITE TAKES THE LEAD You've probably seen Pete
Postlethwaite's craggy face somewhere for the English actor has
played an impressive array of supporting roles in an eclectic range
of films, including Spielberg's ``The Lost World'' and the hit
drama ``In the Name of the Father,'' for which he received a best
supporting actor Oscar nomination. Now the 52-year-old character
actor is breaking new ground with his first romantic leading-man
role in ``Among Giants.'' By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,200 words +
photo. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81 I
am interested in story no. ______ from summary 426
</P>
