<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIAN-ASYLUM01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Albanian exchange student, 18, seeking asylum in U.S.
 &HT;    By Cathy Mong
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Genti Sulaj is 18 and hopes next week to be
working two jobs and saving some money.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to establish credit and buy things with the money he
earns.
</P>
<P>
   It's the American way.
</P>
<P>
   But Sulaj is from Albania, and what he wants most is to help pay
for his family's escape from the turmoil and strife that surrounds
them.
</P>
<P>
   The young man, who has made his home the past several months
with Miamisburg (Ohio) residents Charles and Frances Holloway, is
seeking political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   As refugees flee NATO bombings of Kosovo, Sulaj is consumed with
gratefulness, concern _ and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels bad I'm here and my family's there,'' Sulaj said.
``It bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents and sister live in Tirana, the capital of Albania,
but are safe for now. Sulaj received a brief phone call from them
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sulaj doesn't allow his fears to stop him. He is awaiting a
hearing on his request for asylum, has his work papers in order and
should receive his Social Security number any day.
</P>
<P>
   With that, he can begin working at Lowe's and the Olive Garden
restaurant. He has bought a 9-year-old car and plans to pay it off
in three or four months.
</P>
<P>
   Sulaj has been in the country since spending the last half of
his senior year in high school as a foreign exchange student in
Idaho. Instead of returning to Albania, he got off his plane May 22
in Cincinnati and boarded a bus to Dayton. Once in Dayton, he asked
around and found local shelters that took him in.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Holloway was introduced to Sulaj at The Other Place
daytime shelter after she inquired about finding someone to help
her with some hourly work.
</P>
<P>
   She said Sulaj, who speaks four languages and whose plight
touched her heart, opened her eyes to international war and strife.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening over there, I could bounce it off if it
weren't for Genti,'' she said. ``But I've talked to his mother.
I've talked to his sister, and I think they have more love in their
hearts than a lot of American families who seem to have
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's phone call relieved Sulaj for the time being, but he
also worries about other people he has met in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   One friend's family remains in Pristina, Kosovo, in the heart of
the bombing, and he has not heard from his parents. ``He is very,
very upset,'' Sulaj said. ``He is very, very worried. He is going
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sulaj said many young people he knew in Albania fled months ago
into Greece and Macedonia. ``This thing has been going on a long
time. It didn't start with the bombings,'' he said. ``Nobody stood
up against what was going on. Now the world is finally standing up,
and it's good. Somebody has to rise up.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Holloway tries to help Sulaj focus on becoming
independent and turning his dreams into reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were driving down the highway the other day and he got
really sad,'' Holloway said. ``I asked him, 'Genti, what's the
matter?' He said, 'I'm having the time of my life in America and my
family is in the situation they're in. It seems so unfair.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Genti, you're still their rock. You're still
their hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Mong writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
