<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aim '10-20-Life' law accurately
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _Prevention. Stopping crime before it
happens. Instructing all with criminal intentions that gun violence
in Florida will bring certain, dire consequences.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, and asserting only altruistic motives, the
Legislature last Wednesday passed ``10-20-Life,'' a bill requiring
minimum-mandatory sentences for gun crimes. The Senate vote was
39-0; in the House, it was 106-11. Gov. Bush, who campaigned on a
promise to crack down on gun-toting criminals, said, ``Our
neighborhoods and cities will be safer with this legislation,'' and
he will sign it into law.
</P>
<P>
   This legislation will increase minimum-mandatory sentences for
both violent crimes and drug trafficking. Beginning July 1, those
who commit such felonies while in possession of a gun are supposed
to receive a 10-year minimum sentence. If the felon fires the gun,
the mandatory sentence is 20 years. If anyone is injured, the
mandatory sentence is 25 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   During debate, the House members who voted against the measure
expressed concern that prosecutors probably would apply it most
often to minorities, especially young black men. Perhaps to counter
such argument and direct prosecutorial discretion, the final bill
legally defines ``possession'' of a gun as ``carrying it on the
person, or having it within immediate physical reach with ready
access with the intent to use the firearm during the commission of
the offense, if proven beyond a reasonable doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Also perhaps to cancel perceptions of intended bias, the bill
includes a monitoring feature. After July 1, 2000, state attorneys
must report to the governor and the Legislature how every case in
which a gun was fired was resolved, identifying defendants by age,
gender, race and ethnicity. Note: No such monitoring is required of
cases in which a gun was possessed but not fired. Otherwise, the
law on its face seems to have acknowledged possibilities for
prosecutorial abuse and included provisions to influence fairness.
</P>
<P>
   To educate the public, the bill allots up to $500,000 for the
Department of Corrections to publicize it. Given the current
availability of guns, I hope a public education campaign will
extend beyond the next fiscal year and focus significantly on
children as young as elementary-school age. Thoroughly informing
youths, especially poor, minority kids living in drug-infested
neighborhoods, is critical. Mired in circumstances where gun
violence is common, too many of these youngsters are conditioned to
believe that having a gun and using it is a personal choice without
serious legal penalties. Hence, every responsible adult has an
obligation to cite cases that will disabuse them of that notion as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   For example, under the law an 18-year-old man caught in his
apartment ``trafficking'' in cocaine and in possession of a gun
could get 15 years for the cocaine and 10 years for the gun _ a
potential total of 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the consequence of this law to a minor who commits a
felony with a gun and, based on prosecutorial discretion, is tried
as an adult. Consider also that for indictment purposes, gun
possession when a gun is ``within immediate physical reach ... with
the intent to use'' is a subjective call by officials, many of whom
view all blacks and Hispanics as likely criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Those who argue that such concern about possible negative
consequences of ``10-20-Life'' is unwarranted should look to
California, where this law is in effect. Blacks and Hispanics have
received 88percent of all the 10-year sentences for possession.
They received 100 percent of the 20-year sentences. Even if we can
swallow the lopsided stats in the first category, does anyone
really believe only black and Hispanic criminals were guilty of
felonies where a gun was fired?
</P>
<P>
   As this 10-20-Life becomes Florida law, let's hope its positive
intent of crime prevention prevails. More important, let's hope
that these inflexible rules are applied as intended _ without
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
