<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Drama played out at the drive-in
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Christine Baines
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   The couple is hotting up, as my father calls it. My sister and I
slurp faster on our malteds. We're kneeling on the back seat of our
Nash Rambler. Our view of the couple in the car behind is more
interesting than Yvonne De Carlo risking all for her man on the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   We are habitues of the drive-in, my sister and I, and excellent
judges of technique. We recognize the long-arm-stretch that ends
with a grab at a breast and observe the slow sinking of the now
intertwined couple until they disappear completely.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't long before we've also sunk from view, into the nest of
blankets and pillows we've brought from home, our teddy bears
tucked beside us, there in the dark cave of our car.
</P>
<P>
   I wake as swelling music signals the big scene when Yvonne De
Carlo rescues her pirate boyfriend. My mother and father have
melded into a single lump in the front seat. He begins nibbling at
her neck. She laughs. I sigh and fall back into sleep. My parents
kiss and hold hands more than anyone's.
</P>
<P>
   When we get home father will carry me into the house and tuck me
into bed. I pretend to sleep through this part but I think he
knows. ``Look,'' he says, ``here is a pirate lady. Let's take her
in and put her to bed. Maybe she'll stay forever if we spoil her
rotten.'' I giggle but try to make it sound like a snore.
</P>
<P>
   The carved ship on my bed's headboard becomes the pirate vessel
from the film but I see it through the window of a Nash Rambler.
Yvonne De Carlo is giggling as a pirate nibbles her neck.
</P>
<P>
   It's years later, 1963, and I'm in a drive-in again. We're
parked in the back row, in our slot, our friends ranged along each
side. We are here every week _ the Saturday night sexual tease. The
object of this game is to get the maximum titillation without
becoming bad girls. We've learned how to do this by watching
Annette Funicello keep Frankie Avalon interested but out of her
panties.
</P>
<P>
   Bad girls wear too much lipstick, eye shadow, high heel shoes,
clothes made of synthetic fabrics. Their handbags are plastic. Boys
talk about them. They mysteriously drop out of school.
</P>
<P>
   We wear dungarees and penny loafers and carry leather handbags.
Our lipstick is a thin layer of Tangee natural. We put Vaseline on
our eyelids instead of eye shadow. Sometimes one of us mysteriously
drops out of school. We don't like to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   On the screen the bad girls are writhing around in bikinis while
Annette sits sedately on the beach in a one-piece. At the end of
the movie Annette always has the best guys and the bikini girls
come to bad ends.
</P>
<P>
   A kiss is OK after a couple of dates, we reckon, and maybe some
above-the-waist petting if you're going steady. We spend hours
defining these limits and rules. Like, is a fraternity pin closer
to being engaged than a class ring and therefore license to go a
bit further? We'd all have made excellent 14th-century
ecclesiastics debating the fine points of morality.
</P>
<P>
   Picture it _ rows of steamy-windowed cars filled with desperate,
sweating, frustrated couples. In our own particular car the windows
have got steamier as spring has progressed. We started off with
above-the-neck petting, progressed to above the waist and are
weekly adding more body bits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me not fall into temptation,'' alternates with a more
realistic, ``Let me not get pregnant,'' my mantras.
</P>
<P>
   It's years later, the 1990s, and I'm gazing at the drive-in. The
screen has folded over itself, one of the side posts loose from the
ground. A few speaker posts still stand crookedly amid the weeds.
The refreshment stand looks like someone is using it for storage.
The ticket booth has disappeared in the widening highway.
</P>
<P>
   As I look over the ruin I can see again bugs caught in the
flickering light. I catch a whiff of the mixed smell of cooling
engines and popcorn and cheap perfume; our brave laughter flung
into the dark as we shaped our dreams inspired by the stories on
the dazzling screen.
</P>
<P>
   I stare at the screen, looking for some hint of our stories'
endings.
</P>
<P>
   Did the protagonists get a happy finish with rising music and
smiles and pretty sunsets, or was it to be one of those dark modern
dramas with only loss and confusion at the end?
</P>
<P>
   How did it all turn out?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Christine Baines lives in Oracle, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
