<HEADER>
A0614 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN01-COX     03-31 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shut up and eat, already!
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A new law makes it a misdemeanor in Brooklyn,
Ohio to use a cellular phone while driving unless you have both
hands on the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   I'd take that one step further by banning cell phones in
restaurants, or by creating cell phoning and no cell phoning
sections in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I have a cell phone. I'll admit it at the risk of ruining
my redneck reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But if there's one thing that yanks my chain, it's these
inconsiderate nincompoops who talk on their cell phones while they
do lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Folks, when we go out to eat, we don't want to be interrupted by
you calling home to see if mamma needs another Roma tomato from the
store. Tell the waitress if you want biscuits or cornbread and then
shut up and eat.
</P>
<P>
   There are emergency occasions when it would be acceptable to use
your cell phone in a public place. Like, say, if you were being
hacked to death. But calling your broker doesn't qualify.
</P>
<P>
   William Roberts of Austin has come up with a fun way to thumb
his nose at rude cell phoners. The retired chemist/engineer is so
fed up with jerks who yap on their cell phones in restaurants that
he's thinking about having business card-size notes printed up that
say:
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time you dine
</P>
<P>
   Get a burger and fries
</P>
<P>
   TO GO
</P>
<P>
   And eat in a $%&AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Telephone BOOTH.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he'd hand the cards out to these chuckleheads who talk on
their cell phones in restaurants. Good for him. If Superman could
change clothes in a phone booth, why couldn't a mannerless cell
phoner dine in one?
</P>
<P>
   Roberts got the brainstorm for the card after a couple of recent
cell phone encounters. The first occurred at a place called
Texspresso.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and his lady friend, Linda Wheeler, sat down for coffee
when they couldn't help but hear the man in a coat and tie sitting
at the next table over. This guy was conducting business in a loud
voice on his cell phone, like this was his office.
</P>
<P>
   As Roberts and Wheeler began chatting, the guy on the cell phone
got ticked off. See, Roberts' and Wheeler's conversation was making
it hard for him to hear on his cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started looking over at us as if to say, 'Why don't you
shut up. I'm having a business conversation here,' `` Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the guy with the cell phone got up and walked 15-20
feet away, now yelling into his cell phone, with his finger in his
ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's an idiot,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   On to round two: About a week ago, Roberts and Wheeler were
having dinner at the Hill Country Pasta House. A woman and two
teenagers were at the next table. Roberts says the three spent
dinner making and fielding calls and passing the cell phone around
the table ``so everyone could blather.''
</P>
<P>
   This began with the cell phone ringing. Roberts said the male
teenager, probably 18, answered the phone, talked a while, then
handed the phone to the female teenager, probably 16, who talked a
while, then handed it to the woman, who talked a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``That went on the whole meal,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to shove that cell phone where it won't ring no more.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-Mail: jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
