<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lent separates strong from weak
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When I was a kid, the Lenten season was an annual
test of character _ one I habitually flunked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you giving up for Lent?'' was a hot question among my
classmates at Ascension Grade School in the '60s. It was what
passed as a big-picture issue, one that compelled us to dissect the
larger questions: Should you give up Swizzle sticks or Pez? The
Time Tunnel or It's About Time? (The former was a 1967 drama about
time travel through history; the latter a 1967 sitcom about time
travel to the Stone Age.)
</P>
<P>
   This was a no-brainer, as far as I was concerned. ``I really
like The Time Tunnel ,'' I said, ``so I'm giving up It's About
Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Barb looked at me as if I were some unholy hybrid of Bathsheba
and Mary Magdalene.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should give up something that's hard to give up,'' she
said severely, posing as St. Barbara just as if I hadn't caught her
cheating off my test paper the week before.
</P>
<P>
   My first foray into Lenten sacrifice had been dropping Mighty
Mouse from my Saturday morning cartoon lineup, but Satan proved too
strong. I sat at the top of the stairs and watched, as if God
wouldn't notice my cheating if I were far enough removed. The same
thing happened two years later, when I struggled in vain against
temptation while my siblings watched The Beatles cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   Lent taught us the lesson of God's infinite forgiveness. There
may be no mercy for those who whispered during Mass or forgot their
chapel veil, but there was grace for us sinners who broke our
Lenten vows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up my before-bed snack,'' recalled Jim, ``but then I
started on an antibiotic for my bronchitis that says I can't take
it on an empty stomach, and I had to fudge a little (with fudge
ripple ice cream, it turns out).''
</P>
<P>
   Picking what to give up was an art in itself; you had to hit on
something that hurt, but not too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up swearing but I never swore,'' said Kate. ``Well, I
couldn't give up chocolate . And Bewitched? Are you kidding?''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Catholic church in those pre-Vatican II years, Lent
was full of loopholes. Only the extravagantly pious gave up whole
categories, like candy or TV. Most chose specific subcategories:
Reese's peanut butter cups, for instance, but not Smarties; bubble
gum, but not chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of the Lenten sacrifice is already assuming a quaint
air, like the Latin Mass. The trend now is to regard Lent as a time
of community service and volunteerism. The emphasis is not on
giving up, but on giving.
</P>
<P>
   That's all very well for adults, for whom life sometimes seems
like one long Lenten season. Give up candy? Rarely touch the stuff.
Give up potato chips? Cut down on cholesterol years ago, doctor's
orders. Give up TV? Who has time for it?
</P>
<P>
   Our kids are a different story. Schooled in the gospel of
instant gratification, bombarded with messages to
consume-consume-consume, they could stand to give up a little.
Won't that Easter-basket chocolate taste heavenly after 40 days of
deprivation? Won't that TV show seem more enthralling? They need to
learn they can live without one or two of those many things they're
so sure they can't live without.
</P>
<P>
   The best message in this Lenten season came, ironically enough,
during that orgy of opulence, the Oscars. As Roberto Benigni
accepted his best actor statuette, he thanked his parents for ``the
greatest gift _ poverty.'' His bountiful spirit conveyed his
meaning far better than his faltering English: It is in giving up,
and doing without, that we truly learn to give.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
