<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Being humbled before riding pros makes one ponder life
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Either a preacher or a pool shark lectured me once
on the benefits of a humbling experience.
</P>
<P>
   If those benefits exist, I'm first in line.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in my life, I know what it feels like to be
the slowest person in class. I have a new appreciation for people
who fall behind and can't catch up.
</P>
<P>
   I now know what the hand-wringing softies are talking about when
they warn that failure injures a student's self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   My Kevlar-reinforced leather glove had the VFR 800's throttle
pinned open on Texas World Speedway's grandstand straightaway. A
peek at my vibrating speedometer was proof that the few
modifications and special racing fuel had been worth it.
</P>
<P>
   A 157 mph, I felt like I was flying.
</P>
<P>
   Man, oh man, was I wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The next moment one of the instructors screamed past me like I
was on a riding lawnmower. The instructor, who may have been the
one who recently won a Daytona motorcycle race, casually turned
around in his seat and gave me the signal to follow him.
</P>
<P>
   He dipped down off the banking into turn one with his left knee
hanging out and his bike leaned over at an angle I would have
admired except my orders were to follow and learn. Yeah.
</P>
<P>
   I stayed with him through turn one but began to fall behind in
turn two. Coming out of the turn three, I could see the
instructor's right leg jut out as he flicked his bike into turn
four.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the instructor evidently gave up on me. Like one
of those ``Star Trek'' scenes, he disappeared in a warp-drive blur.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I came out of turn 12 and back onto the grandstand
straightaway, the instructor had probably helped four other
sportbike students, eaten lunch and finished a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the instructors are professionals. What about the other
students?
</P>
<P>
   When you are leaned over in a curve thinking that you are about
to violate all known laws of physics and discover the meaning of
life after the fact, it's really an ego buster to have a string of
your fellow students swing around you as though you are road kill.
</P>
<P>
   The only time I came close to keeping up with my classmates was
when it started to drizzle. I kept going as hard as I could and
everyone else slowed down. Stupidity occasionally has its rewards.
</P>
<P>
   When the track dried out, I again was toast.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than building confidence in my riding skills, I could
feel my confidence slipping away lap by lap.
</P>
<P>
   Without mirrors to tell who's behind you or brake lights to tell
if someone in front is slowing down, riders are instructed to raise
their left arms when slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   I felt I should ride the entire course with my left arm raised.
Perhaps I could duct-tape a mannequin's raised left arm to my
riding suit and save the energy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, that afternoon I raised my left arm coming into turn 12
and took the hot-lane pit exit. I parked next to my truck and sat
there contemplating my ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   My buddy soon rode up, killed his engine, flipped up his
faceshield and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   We have ridden thousands of miles on motorcycles but neither of
us had ever been on a sportbike race track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm loading my bike,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good idea,'' I said. ``If I take any more laps I may stop
riding motorcycles altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Sportbike school dropouts. Will our self-esteem ever recover?
</P>
<P>
   The next day I told another buddy who has been a champion
motorcycle racer how bummed out I became when other riders blew
around me.
</P>
<P>
   He said I should get over it and get better.
</P>
<P>
   Man, this merit system can be tough.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
