<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good Stuff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One good show
</P>
<P>
   It may be a bit late in the Lenten season, but the Discovery
Channel's Great Chefs will be fixing fish all day on Good Friday.
Fourteen back-to-back episodes will focus on decidedly upscale
preparations that may be worth looking at rather than cooking.
Witness swordfish with crabmeat-sesame crust and mirin cilantro
sauce. Soft shell crawfish are a delicacy favored by these chefs.
Crab napoleon and smoked salmon tartare sound comparatively simple.
Go surfing from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Study: brown bread tied to good health
</P>
<P>
   Mom was right _ brown bread is good for you.
</P>
<P>
   A study of more than 30,000 Iowa women, aged 55 to 69, showed
that those who reported eating more whole grains _ including
whole-wheat bread, brown rice, oatmeal and other unprocessed food _
were less likely to die in any given year. Although white bread is
fortified with some vitamins, it is no substitute for brown bread
nutritionally, the researchers said. ``Whole grains contain a wide
variety of nutrients and other constituents that are lost in
refining and that may be beneficial for health,'' they wrote in the
American Journal of Public Health .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
