<HEADER>
A0619 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE     03-31 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported on the Dew Line and North Warning
System. Can you tell me anything about a warning system called Pave
Paws, built in the 1970s to detect ICBMs from the U.S.S.R.?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're happy to, but it appears not to involve detection of
intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs), according to the
Dictionary of the Modern United States Military. Pave Paws _ whose
formal name is the Precision Acquisition of Vehicle Entry,
Phased-Array Warning System _ is an early-warning radar system
designed to detect sea-launched ballistic missiles (SLBMs). The
military dictionary says its radars have a range of 3,450 miles and
are capable of counting re-entry vehicles as well as predicting
where they would impact.
</P>
<P>
   Since it can take 10 minutes or less for a SLBM to hit the
United States, depending on the point of launch, Pave Paws radars
are tied in to NORAD (North American Air Defense Command), the U.S.
Strategic Command and the National Military Command Center to
enable a quick military response if needed. The dictionary lists
these locations for Pave Paws radars: Robins Air Force Base in
Georgia (since installation, it has been mothballed); Otis Air
National Guard Base in Massachusetts; Goodfellow Air Force Base in
Texas; and Beale Air Force Base in California.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was the lone member of Congress who did not vote to
support the U.S. effort in Yugoslavia?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rep. Barbara Lee (D-Calif.) was the only dissenter on the
resolution to to express House support for U.S. troops engaged in
military operations against Yugoslavia. Her office explained that
the freshman congresswoman is ``deeply concerned about the safety
of our troops,'' but her vote was in objection to the language in
House Resolution 130.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of its wording, today's resolution extended far beyond
expressing support for our troops,'' Lee said in her statement,
dated March 24. ``The first clause of today's resolution asks the
Congress to abdicate its responsibility for declarations of war
and, instead, embrace the notion that the president can authorize
the commitment of U.S. troops to war without congressional
approval. This is a notion which the Congress must reject for
constitutional reasons: It is completely impermissible for the
president to commit troops to war, a right given only to the
Congress by the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate action a day before the start of hostilities, 41
senators voted against a resolution supporting NATO air strikes
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On current episodes of ``This Old House,'' Norm Abram is
walking around with his right arm in a sling. What happened?
</P>
<P>
   A: A publicist at WGBH-TV in Boston, the station that produces
the program, said Abram tore his rotator cuff in a water-skiing
accident. No further details were provided.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are the 30 companies chosen that make up the Dow Jones
industrial average?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dow Jones &AMP; Co. explains that the editors of The Wall Street
Journal select the components. They take a broad view of what
industrial means, too: In essence, it's almost any company that
isn't in the transportation business or isn't a utility, because
there also are Dow Jones averages for those kinds of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing a new company for the DJIA, the editors are said to
look among substantial industrial companies with a history of
successful growth and wide interest among investors.
</P>
<P>
   The components aren't changed often. It isn't a ``hot stock''
index, after all, and the newspaper's editors believe that
stability of composition enhances the trust that many people have
in the averages. The most frequent reasons for changing a stock are
that something is happening to one of the components, such as being
acquired, or that another company may become more representative as
a market barometer, or that a different sector of the economy
should be represented. Whenever one stock is changed, the others
are reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Dow Jones industrial average stocks were
changed was in March 1997, when Woolworth, Westinghouse Electric,
Texaco and Bethlehem Steel were deleted, and Hewlett-Packard,
Johnson &AMP; Johnson, Traveler's Group and Wal-Mart were added. The
last changes before that came in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   If you have Internet access, check this site for information:
www.dowjones.com/
</P>
<P>
   Q: A short item in the newspaper reported that Cesar Chavez was
inducted into the U.S. Labor Department's Hall of Fame as its 22nd
member. Who are the others?
</P>
<P>
   A: These are the Labor Hall of Fame honorees, in addition to
Chavez: Mary Anderson, Cyrus S. Ching, John R. Commons, Eugene
Debs, David Dubinsky, Arthur Goldberg, Samuel Gompers, William
Green, Sidney Hillman, Mother Jones, Henry J. Kaiser, John L.
Lewis, George Meany, James P. Mitchell, David A. Morse, Philip
Murray, Frances Perkins, A. Philip Randolph, Walter Reuther, George
W. Taylor and Robert F. Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame posthumously recognizes Americans deemed to
have improved quality of life for U.S. workers by pushing for wage
increases, safer working conditions and more job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know Q&AMP;A has printed this information in the past, and I
saved it, but now I can't find it. How do I get a presidential
greeeting sent to my grandmother, who will be 80 soon? She's a big
fan of President Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   A: We haven't printed it lately, so we're glad to oblige for you
and many other readers who have asked us to repeat it. In addition
to birthday greetings for Americans 80 or older, anniversary
greetings are sent to couples celebrating 50 or more years of
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Requests must be put in writing and sent by mail to White House,
Attn: Greetings Office, Room 39, Washington, DC 20502; or faxed to
202-395-1232.
</P>
<P>
   You should request a card at least six weeks prior to the
occasion. For recorded information, call 202-456-2724.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I contact the national headquarters of the Republican
Party in Washington? I want to express my support of the party's
new stance on the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write: Republican National Committee, 310 First St. S.E.,
Washington, DC 20003. Or send an e-mail communication to the RNC at
this address: info(at)rnc.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you discuss the meaning and origin of the business terms
bull market, bear market and blue chip? I hear them often, but
without any explanation.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Bull market'' refers to a prolonged rise in the prices of
stocks, bonds or commodities. Bull markets usually last a few
months and are characterized by high trading volume. Various
theories are advanced about how the expression started, but the
Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase Origins says the most likely
one is that ``bull'' refers to a bull's habit of tossing its head
upward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear market'' is a prolonged period of falling prices. A bear
market in stocks usually is brought on by the anticipation of
declining economic activity, and a bear market in bonds is caused
by rising interest rates. The most plausible origin, according to
the Morris Dictionary, is that ``bear'' comes from the old axiom
about ``selling the skin before you've caught the bear.'' A trader
who operates in this fashion once was known in England as a
``bearskin jobber.'' An alternate explanation involves an attacking
bear's habit of thrusting its paws upward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue chip'' refers to the common stock of a nationally known
company that has a long record of profit growth and dividend
payment and a reputation for quality management, products and
services. Think IBM, GE and Du Pont, for example. Blue chip stocks
typically are relatively high priced and low yielding. The
expression was borrowed from gambling: The most valuable counters
in poker are the blue chips.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you settle something about my favorite country singer,
Clint Black? A co-worker said he's from New Jersey, but I could
swear he's a native Texan, like I am. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: Brace yourself. Black was born Feb. 4, 1962, in Long Branch,
N.J., according to The Comprehensive Country Music Encyclopedia.
But he grew up in Houston, the youngest of four brothers. And it
was in Houston where he started playing the harmonica at 13, and
shortly thereafter used songbooks to teach himself to play the
guitar. You know the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some time ago, there was a move to convert the United States
to the metric system. Whatever became of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: It went into hibernation _ encouraged, but not put on the
front burner, and never officially canceled, either. The federal
Metric Conversion Act of the mid-1970s was supposed to make metric
the accepted system in the United States. Even well before that _
the Metric Act of 1866 _ the metric system was given the official
OK by the federal government. But it has never caught on, even
though Americans deal with 2-liter Coca-Cola bottles and liter wine
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Since the conversion to metric in this country was never
mandated, and no deadline was set for voluntary compliance, most
people have stuck with the tried-and-true. It's confusing, that's
for sure. Consider a breakfast oatmeal container with this on its
label: ``42 oz.; 2 lbs. 10 oz.; 1.19 kg.'' The cereal's nutritional
values are calculated in grams, but cooking instructions use
standard American-style measure. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   (END TAKE 2 OF 2 FILES)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
