<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ My first foray into Lenten
sacrifice had been dropping Mighty Mouse from my Saturday morning
cartoon lineup, but Satan proved too strong. I sat at the top of
the stairs and watched, as if God wouldn't notice my cheating if I
were far enough removed. The same thing happened two years later,
when I struggled in vain against temptation while my siblings
watched The Beatles cartoon. Lent taught us the lesson of God's
infinite forgiveness. There may be no mercy for those who whispered
during Mass or forgot their chapel veil, but there was grace for us
sinners who broke our Lenten vows. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ My Kevlar-reinforced leather
glove had the VFR 800's throttle pinned open on Texas World
Speedway's grandstand straightaway. A peek at my vibrating
speedometer was proof that the few modifications and special racing
fuel had been worth it. A 157 mph, I felt like I was flying. Man,
oh man, was I wrong. This is a story of being humbled. (Nethaway,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A new law makes
it a misdemeanor in Brooklyn, Ohio to use a cellular phone while
driving unless you have both hands on the wheel. I'd take that one
step further by banning cell phones in restaurants, or by creating
cell phoning and no cell phoning sections in restaurants. (Kelso,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _Prevention. Stopping
crime before it happens. Instructing all with criminal intentions
that gun violence in Florida will bring certain, dire consequences.
To that end, and asserting only altruistic motives, the Legislature
last Wednesday passed ``10-20-Life,'' a bill requiring
minimum-mandatory sentences for gun crimes. The Senate vote was
39-0; in the House, it was 106-11. Gov. Bush, who campaigned on a
promise to crack down on gun-toting criminals, said, ``Our
neighborhoods and cities will be safer with this legislation,'' and
he will sign it into law. (Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
