   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-FOOD 0326 _ This week marks the last chance for a couple
years to do what seems to have been written in the stars: Have a
Once in a Blue Moon dinner party. On Wednesday, the moon will rise
full for the second time in the month, a celestial event that
occurs, as they say _ for obscure reasons _ only once in a blue
moon. So conjure up the heavenly possibilities for a dinner menu
that focuses on blue food. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) Art includes
3-column color illustration.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BLUE DRINKS _ Go all out for a Once in a Blue Moon party with
matching drinks. There are plenty out there. (Heller, Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES _ Full Moon Pepper Soup, Steak with Blue Cheese Sauce,
Peas Extraordinaire.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSPICE _ Only a few decades ago, a well-stocked pantry meant
having a good supply of flour, sugar, lard, some rice, beans and
maybe some canned tomatoes and other canned goods. Today, there is
an unprecedented variety of foods that have a long shelf life.
There is nothing necessarily second rate about a meal put together
primarily from the pantry shelf. (Parham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD NOTES _ With the population explosion at the cheese counter
these days, a guide that fits into a pocketbook could come in
handy. ``The Cheese Companion'' is filled with tempting color
photographs and evocative descriptions of about 50 varieties.
(Staff, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOOD page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN _ A weekly beer column by the Michael
Skube of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. This week: The largest
draft-beer emporium in the nation, . (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-TRENDS _ As we approach the Millennium, many of the hot
food trends in grocery stores are built on fresh foods,
convenience, technology, indulgence, and take-home. (Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EASTER-SCONES _ Specialty of the house. Bacon cheddar scones,
perfect for an easter brunch. (Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-GOODSTUFF _ Food shorts. (Dayton Daily News). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   CONDUCTOR-MCGEGAN _ Short interview/concert advance based on
conversation with Nicholas McGegan, ASO guest conductor this
weekend. He is a baroque specialist. He conducts Philharmonia
Baroque Orchestra, the best of its kind in country, possibly world,
in San Francisco. He's in his mid-40s. (Green, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BLUENOTE-RECORDS _ Blue Note records, the prestigious mainstream
jazz label for which nearly every important innovator in the music
has recorded, marks its 60th anniversary by dispatching several of
its hottest young artists on a nationwide tour. Dubbed the ``New
Directions'' tour, it arrives April 1 in Atlanta at an unlikely
venue _ the East Atlanta rock 'n' roll bar, the Echo Lounge _
underwritten by Camel cigarettes and co-promoted with Esquire
magazine. The talent, which includes saxophonist Greg Osby (an
oldster at a mere 37), is top-notch, and is packaged in a
fashionable manner that emphasizes a certain kind of hip, black
male image. We'll chat with two of the players _ Osby and
vibraphonist Stefon Harris _ Blue Note's prez, Bruce Lundvall, and
industry observers to look at not only the music (crisp, acoustic
jazz with an analytic awareness of tradition) but what the music
represents, and where these ``new directions'' are actually
leading. Also: try to get a word out of Camel about its sponsorship
amid these anti-tobacco times, and puzzle over the ironies of that.
(Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-FOOLS _ All on video for April Fool's Day: a fest of fools
and jokesters in high-grade films. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-RUGRATS _ ``The Rugrats Movie.'' (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-MINIS _ Mini reviews of: ``Everest,'' ``Home Fries,''
``The Farm: Life Inside Angola Prison.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT _ Focus on Steve Martin, who stars in ``The Out
of Towners'' at movie theaters starting Friday. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-NEXT _ Coming next week: ``Meet Joe Black,'' ``Beloved,''
``American History X,'' ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries.''
Coming May 25 -- ``Saving Private Ryan.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
