<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
   SF Wednesday, March 31, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-REDISTRICTING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Faced with the prospect of
losing one congressional seat _ and quite possibly two _ because of
a declining population, New York officials have begun a year-long
effort to ensure a thorough count in the 2000 census. By JOHN
CAHER.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GASOLINE (San Francisco) _ According to a survey released
Tuesday by the Automobile Association of America, the average price
of a gallon of regular, unleaded gas at a self-service pump in San
Francisco shot up to $1.61 this week. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN and
KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEN-PHEN (Houston) _ A three-judge panel in Harris County,
Texas, on Monday became the first court in the nation to disallow
evidence that the ``phen'' part of the ``fen-phen'' diet drug
combination has helped cause heart defects. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   BIRD-TRAIL (Galveston, Texas) _ A colony of 500 white pelicans
forms a flotilla, bobbing gently on the waves that lap the shore of
the Bolivar mud flats, a thin strip of land on Texas' Gulf coast.
Up to 10,000 birds, representing 50 species-0congregate on this
tranquil 500-acre Galveston Bay marsh. By CINDY HORSWELLL.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-THINGS (Undated) _ Things were already not going so
well for ``10 Things I Hate About You'' when Joan Armatrading faded
in on the film's soundtrack. Her ``The Weakness in Me'' is the song
that's supposed to reveal just how much Patrick (Heath Ledger) is
falling in love with Kat (Julia Stiles), but it only reveals how
hopelessly off-base ``10 Things'' is. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-VEGETABLES (Houston) _ Spring vegetables are as delicious
to look at as they are to eat. While choosing your bounty for
Sunday dinner, pick some extra baby artichokes, asparagus, yellow
wax beans, radishes, sprouts and parsley for a fresh centerpiece.
For your feast, our timely recipes will help you bring out the best
flavor from those tender vegetables. By ANN CRISWELL.
</P>
<P>
   With: SPRING-RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The first thing you notice about Gina
Gallo and her brother, Matt, is that these are nice folks. Cynics
would point out that as grandchildren of the late Julio Gallo, they
can afford to be. It was Julio Gallo who, along with his brother,
Ernest, built the world's largest winery operation. By MICHAEL
LONSFORD.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-UCONN (St. Petersburg, Fla.) _ Clearly, there are some sad,
misguided souls out there who stupifyingly underestimated the
Connecticut Huskies. Cancel the coronation of the Duke Blue Devils
as a team for the ages. At Tropicana Field, the Huskies gave the
bluebloods of college basketball a serious case of the blues. By
STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ There has been a lot of talk
about how President Clinton doesn't have an ``exit strategy'' or an
``end game.'' I guess that's something like ``closure,'' but long
ago military thinkers used the word ``victory.'' That word has
fallen out of use. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ One lawmaker in New York state
wants the public to pay for philosophers to provide help to
Medicaid patients. If we clear the way for Medicaid payment to
philosophers, can personal trainers be far behind? Will Medicaid
pay for gym memberships? How about art lessons, so depressed
Medicaid recipients can unleash their creative energies? By DAN
LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
