<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMPANIES INTRODUCE A NEW MATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thousands of companies, online and off, are blossoming because
of the Internet's fertile new soil for conducting commerce and
serving customers. But the blush may be rapidly fading from the
rose for many Internet-only businesses built on the increasingly
dubious strategy that whatever millions of dollars they lose today,
they will later ``make it up in volume.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``volume'' argument, which has become a mantra in the
Internet economy, comes in a couple of common varieties.
</P>
<P>
   A ``content'' company like the women's Web site iVillage, for
example, was able to raise $292 million in its first day on the
stock market last week, giving the company a market valuation of
$2.22 billion _ an astonishing figure, considering its widely
publicized financial problems and its underwhelming popularity
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Internet content companies, it did this by selling
investors on the notion that it would eventually generate high
enough traffic to the site that advertisers wanting to pitch goods
and services to the gold-mine women's market would someday support
iVillage's cost of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the volume concept for Internet retailers relies on a
two-step strategy: Their rock-bottom prices, often below cost, will
attract customers and revenue. Then, once they accumulate enough
volume in traffic and transactions to be considered competitors,
profit will eventually come from advertisers as well as from
various undisclosed financial arrangements with distributors and
vendors.
</P>
<P>
   The volume model has always had its detractors, most of whom
have been painted as hopelessly parochial neo-Luddite party
poopers, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing number of industry watchers and executives have
begun to question how a volume-driven Internet can survive, let
alone grow, when its native businesses can bring themselves to
utter the ``P'' word only in the negative. ``No profit for the
foreseeable future'' is now a boilerplate disclaimer in the
prospectus of an Internet company preparing an initial stock
offering.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially bewildering when most Web-based retailers seem
unconcerned that the Internet, with its ability to provide quick
and easy price and feature comparisons for products, is the perfect
profit-margin-killing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Using the inscrutable mathematics with which many Internet
retailers conduct business, closing the sale is the important
thing, even if rock-bottom pricing means that they lose money.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it is a common practice for Internet-only companies
that sell computers and consumer electronics to have two price
lists _ one for customers who shop through price-comparison
services and another, significantly higher, set of prices for
customers who arrive from other precincts on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   And these retailers often do not make good on the lower prices
they promise. An increasingly common tale is the one told by
Michael Tchao, a technology consultant who thought he bought an IBM
Think Pad computer _ twice _ by using one of the leading
price-comparison sites.
</P>
<P>
   On two occasions, the lowest-price retailers, as determined by
the comparison site, confirmed his order, then reneged, stating
that the computers were no longer available. To no avail, Tchao
reminded both that they were still advertising the computer exactly
as he had ordered it.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company will ship Tchao a computer at the price
advertised. Yet both are now in possession of every bit of personal
information, including his credit card number, that would be
required to make Tchao look like an actual customer in their
databases. This is valuable information for Internet businesses
that would have their companies valued on popularity rather than on
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   The story nicely illustrates an idea articulated by Mark
Anderson, a technology consultant and publisher of the Strategic
News Service newsletter (www.tapsns.com), in a recent issue devoted
to the shaky strategy of volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of making it up on volume when you are losing on
every product line is a tried-and-true recipe for something other
than success,'' Anderson wrote. And most Internet companies, he
added, do not and apparently cannot erect the traditional barriers
to competition _ like trade secrets, proprietary technology and
extreme start-up costs _ that would someday allow them to corral
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, the harder one looks, from weird stock valuations to
venture funding mania to basic business models,'' he wrote, ``the
more one begins to feel that from a financial perspective, there is
no `there' there.''
</P>
<P>
   But the acceptance of these wacky concepts is driven by the fact
that to date there is only one consistent method of making money on
the Internet _ the initial stock offering in which companies and
their investors sell the public on the possibility of future
growth, achieving valuations that are hundreds, sometimes thousands
of times any earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Then they sell the overpriced stock to day traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is, unfortunately, the business that is making the most
sense so far,'' said Anderson, who calls the Internet stock game a
scam, and adding, ``Siphoning funds from losers' gas tanks is an
old game, but one which has never been played for such high stakes
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The disconnect between this game and existing business practices
is stunning even to executives who are moving into the Internet
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who sell things know it is generally a good idea to
sell them for more than you pay for them,'' said Barry Diller,
chairman of the television and shopping concern USA Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet mogul-in-waiting, Diller is fighting to acquire the
search-engine company Lycos Inc., for a price that some investors
do not find very attractive in this era of sky-high valuations of
www.anything.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The margin of error is zero when speculation drives up stocks
to disconcerting levels,'' Diller said. ``Which reality do you pay
attention to? Stock? Or building a real business?''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Anderson said, ``If the point is not simply to
bilk a bunch of losers, is there real, profitable business to be
done?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-28-99 1819EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
