<HEADLINE>
BOB DOLE'S PROBLEM  
 EDITORS: THIS IS A CORRECTED VERSION OF THE STORY TRANSMITTED
YESTERDAY _ THE THIRD PARAGRAPH HAS BEEN REVISED. PLEASE DO NOT
PUBLISH THE EARLIER VERSION.
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this ``separate buy'' article it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.) 
 For release: Tues., March 30, or thereafter  
 By GERALDINE A. FERRARO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Bob Dole needs a job.
 &HT;    The last few months haven't been pleasant ones, as parents and
grandparents have watched their children learn far more than any of
them needed to know about sex and our political leaders.
 &HT;    I had thought, or at least hoped, that this phase was over once
the impeachment hearings ended and wannabe-Speaker Bob Livingston
(R.-La.) dried his eyes and packed his bags for home. House
Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R.-Ill.) had fessed up about an
adulterous affair and Right-to-Lifer Rep. Bob Barr (R.-Ga.) had
been outed for having paid for an abortion.
 &HT;    But no, along came Bob Dole, of all people, looking straight at
me and my grandson in my living room and talking about erectile
dysfunction.
 &HT;    I have no doubt that this has been a problem for some men since
the time our ancestors lived in caves. But, considering the
extremely short life span of cavemen, I presume that it wasn't a
matter of major concern to the community at large.
 &HT;    Nowadays, however, to judge by Bob's television commercial for
Pfizer Pharmaceuticals and its much-hyped product Viagra, this
problem is not only a matter for concern to the individual
affected, but also an important issue for the rest of us.
 &HT;    As I understand it from Bob's comments, erectile dysfunction _
or, as he more casually refers to it once he's warmed to his topic,
``E.D.'' _ can be caused by many serious illnesses, as well as
depression and other emotional problems. These tragic conditions
call for a doctor's help, not pharmaceutical treatment of one of
their symptoms.
 &HT;    Bob also fails to mention that age frequently plays a part in
this condition. If it didn't, why would all of us marvel at Tony
Randall fathering two babies in his late 70s, and why would Larry
King bother to announce, when his wife became pregnant, that he
hadn't used Viagra?
 &HT;    And what about the end of the commercial? Bob begins the ad by
saying ``Courage _ something shared by countless Americans. Those
who risk their lives, those who've battled serious illness.'' He
picks up this theme at the end by urging us to ``get educated''
about E.D., and telling us that, ``It make take a little courage,
but I've always found that everything worthwhile does.''
 &HT;    Is he referring to his impressive war record and his courage
under fire? Is he _ or are the scriptwriters for the commercial _
subtly equating courage in battle and the courage it takes to get
information about impotence?
 &HT;    I would hope not. Because to do so would be to mock the tears my
aunt shed in 1942 when she found out that her 19-year-old son had
gone down with his ship in the Pacific. It would be to cheapen the
struggle my cousin Frank had when he returned home, leaving a leg
and his future on the fields at Normandy.
 &HT;    It would even be to cheapen the horrific injuries which cost a
young Bob Dole the use of one arm and years spent in rehabilitative
therapy.
 &HT;    And the former senator isn't the only one likely to be affected
by the ad. After all, his wife is now mounting her own candidacy
for the Republican presidential nomination in the election of 2000.
 &HT;    Elizabeth Dole should speak to her husband about this Viagra
business. She needs the support of the religious right to win the
Republican nomination, and her husband's public discussion of
private matters could be problematic in those circles.
 &HT;    There are also gender issues involved here, obviously. Can you
imagine if Tipper Gore or any other wife of a presidential
candidate were to do a commercial for birth-control pills or some
feminine-hygiene product? I guarantee you that the old double
standard would be at work, and people wouldn't be laughing.
 &HT;    Bob Dole has had his turn _ now it's Elizabeth's, and she'll
find it a lot easier if her husband isn't on television talking
about their sex life. If his Washington law firm isn't keeping him
busy enough, maybe she can recommend him to the Red Cross personnel
office.
 &HT;    At the very least, she should ask him to push Pfizer to air its
ads at night, instead of during the morning news programs. After
all, it seems to me that more people are thinking about this
problem when children are already in bed, rather than over the
family breakfast.
 &HT;    As for me, I'm just glad my grandson is only 4 years old and
didn't ask me what the two words meant!
 &HT;    (Geraldine A. Ferraro, a former congresswoman and the Democratic
nominee for vice president in 1984, is a Manhattan-based
attorney.) 
 c.1999 Geraldine A. Ferraro 
