 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Web twinkles with astrologers' readings 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone knows the best use of the Web isn't research, nor is it
finding out if it's going to rain tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The most important use of the Web is getting your horoscope.
Otherwise, why would there be so many different horoscope sites on
the Web? The good thing about that sort of astrological richness is
you are almost sure to find just what you want to hear from one
site or another.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start our journey through the stars with a site for the
astrologer Sidney Omarr.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, you'll find sites for Omarr scattered across the Web,
but one of the best places to find him is on The Washington Post
site at www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/columns/horoscope.htm.
This is a very straightforward site. No added features, no fancy
stuff like compatibility matching or horoscopes for the entire
year. Just the identical predictions you'll find in the morning
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   If it's fancy and elaborate you want, then check out Jonathan
Cainer's site at www.bubble.com/WEBSTARS/. Cainer is a British
astrologer, and his predictions appear in the United Kingdom's
Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just his European nature, but Cainer seems more
entertaining and bolder in his predictions than most astrologers.
And his site does offer _ besides the standard daily horoscope _
extras such as year-ahead forecasts, weekly forecasts and a way to
check your horoscope for the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Astrology Net at serv2.astrology.net/ is more elaborate. There
are special romance and compatibility forecasts, general
information about astrology, live chats, a gift store (there are
plenty of commercial offers on this site), lists of famous people
who share your sign, monthly forecasts and the standard daily
forecasts (you can even specify whether you'd like the short
version or a longer one). The astrologer in residence here is Kelli
Fox, well known in astrology circles.
</P>
<P>
   If you're really into astrology, the sites mentioned might not
suit you. After all, you probably want something more precise.
While there are sites on the Web that offer that service, many of
them charge, so you may want to compute your own horoscope using
your place of birth and the time of day you were born.
</P>
<P>
   The next site called Astrodienst at
www.astro.ch/homepage/indexe.ht is primarily a pay site, but it
does have a nifty feature. You'll be able to find the latitude and
longitude (along with time zone information) for almost any city
you can name.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, even if you think flipping a coin is about as accurate
as astrology and a lot less weird, you still may want to bookmark
this site.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of school assignments and other grown-up chores require
time zone or geographical information.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
