 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
AlphaSmart's a `cool,' lightweight word processor 
By Jennifer Hill  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever carried around a laptop computer knows even
the lightest machine becomes a heavyweight over time.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with some concern that I began searching for portable
options for my son to use for writing at home and school.
</P>
<P>
   Although he seems comfortable carrying most of his current
valuable earthly possessions and a revolving library of six to
seven books in a load that probably weighs a little less than a
baby hippo, I was reluctant to add to his daily backpack load.
</P>
<P>
   While cruising Web sites about technology and learning, I kept
coming across references to the AlphaSmart keyboard. So I surfed on
over to the company's site at www.alphasmart
</P>
<P>
   .com/, where I discovered you can obtain a loaner keyboard for
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The loaner came about four days after filling out the forms,
just in time for a trial run working with the initial outline of my
son's science fair project. And, for good measure, there also was a
poetry assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it? How does it work?'' greeted its emergence from the
box. Both boys, who were immediately intrigued, deftly and easily
handled the footlong keyboard. It really is amazingly light.
</P>
<P>
   Its trim size is due to the fact it is a word processor, not a
laptop computer. But what it does, it does well.
</P>
<P>
   The AlphaSmart has eight files. File 1, which automatically
opens when the unit is turned on, will hold 16 pages of
single-spaced text. (The screen is four lines long.) Files 2-5 are
eight pages long, 6 and 7 are six pages, and 8 is four pages. The
total storage capacity is 64 pages of single-spaced copy, or
128,000 characters.
</P>
<P>
   With this arrangement, more than one family member can use the
AlphaSmart by working in different files, or one person can work on
several entries, or organize one long one.
</P>
<P>
   The shape and size of the keyboard make it easy to type on, but
I do wish it had a handle. I had visions of it flying out of the
crook of my son's sweatshirt-covered arm when bumped in the normal
jostling of life at school.
</P>
<P>
   And while a company spokesman assured me it could survive knocks
to the floor from a table or desk, she did draw the line for times
when the AlphaSmart meets concrete. And I wonder what effect the
ubiquitous woodchip dust at my children's school might have. (I
know for a fact this dust has the ability to creep inside tied
shoes, rendering once-white socks a permanent shade of greige.)
</P>
<P>
   Transferring a file from the AlphaSmart to your Mac or PC (it's
compatible with both) is simple. My 12-year-old was able to do it
unassisted the third time he used the machine.
</P>
<P>
   To transfer a file, you start your word processing software on
your desktop and open up a new file. Then you unplug the keyboard
cable from the keyboard and plug it in to the AlphaSmart. Press
``send'' on the AlphaSmart keyboard, and the file begins to
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the words appear on the screen of old Mac is what the
magic of technology is all about. As his Japanese-style poem about
Clyde, his frog, flowed onto the screen, my son uttered a soft but
sincere ``Cool.''
</P>
<P>
   That softly uttered exclamation also signaled to my mom antenna
that if he had one, he would likely use it, even at school, because
it was, after all, cool.
</P>
<P>
   Three AAA batteries provide about 120 hours of use.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing about the AlphaSmart may be its price. At
$229-$249, it makes portability affordable for many would-be users.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
