 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Get your mouse and er, mop, it's time for spring-cleaning 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have no business writing a column about spring cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   If you had to pass a test to use a mop or a broom, they wouldn't
give me a license. I have Evelyn to thank for my generally clean
house. She shows up with mysterious cleaning apparatuses and keeps
things halfway decent.
</P>
<P>
   There is one kind of spring cleaning that I understand. Your
computer is just as likely to accumulate dirt and grime as your
house. But the gunk in your computer can do more than embarrass you
in front of friends. It can actually ruin that expensive box of
chips.
</P>
<P>
   So today, in honor of spring, we'll do some cleaning that could
save you money and will surely make your computer last longer.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with your mouse. It's easy to clean, and that may
give you the confidence to tackle some of the other chores. We'll
start our mouse surgery by turning the patient upside down. You'll
see a retaining ring of plastic around what looks like a rubber
ball. Remove the ring by following the instructions printed on the
plastic (usually that means turning the ring to the left, but it
varies from mouse to mouse). Now remove the small ball and wash it
with a mild soap solution, rinse it and dry it. Then look inside
the mouse. You'll see that the ball rests on small rollers _
usually three of them. Take a cotton swab, moisten it with rubbing
alcohol and clean the rollers. Let everything dry and reassemble
the mouse. If it is more than a few months old, you'll notice it
works much better now.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you are filled with confidence, let's do something some
of you have never tried before: Open the case to your computer.
It's really not all that bad. Since the way you open up the case
varies from computer to computer, you'll need the manual. Truth is,
even without the manual, you can probably figure out how to open it
just by looking. Make sure you unplug that sucker before you do
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have the case off, look at the exhaust vent for the
small fan. Dust can clog the screen that protects the fan. If that
happens and air flow is restricted, the inside of your computer can
get as hot as an oven. The chips can easily fail if you leave them
half-baked. So cleaning the exhaust grille can save you money and
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the top is open, also take a look at the circuit board
itself. Is it covered with dust? If so, then you may have a short
circuit just waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal. The circuit board has tiny connections (called
traces) that run along the surface. The distance between these
traces is so small that even a particle of dust can bridge them.
</P>
<P>
   So what? Here's what. Some dust particles are actually pretty
good conductors of electricity. So the dust can bridge two traces
and cause a short circuit. Your computer will let you know about
that with an impressive smoke signal, and that kind of smoking is
definitely bad for its health.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to clean a dirty circuit board is to use a small
vacuum that's held well above any components so you don't bump into
them and ruin them. Another way _ not nearly as good _ is to use
one of those cans of compressed air that are sold in computer and
camera stores to blow the dust away. Evelyn could tell you why
that's not the best way _ you are just moving the dust from one
area to another.
</P>
<P>
   One last thing. I know some of you won't feel comfortable
opening up the case to your computer. That's fine. I don't feel
comfortable with a mop, so I hired an expert. You can do the same
thing and take your computer in to have the innards cleaned by an
expert.
</P>
<P>
   But, honest, this is easy. It ain't brain surgery. At worst,
it's mouse surgery.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com. Bill appreciates hearing from you but
cannot respond to all e-mail. Personal home page:
http://www.mindspring.com/(tilde)bhusted/bills.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-29-99 1040EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
