<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-ONLINE-CHARITIES-     03-31 3167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONLINE-CHARITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE MOST OF THE WEB, IT'S BUYER BEWARE WHEN GIVING TO ONLINE
CHARITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Americans become increasingly comfortable shopping online,
it's a pitch many succumb to: Buy an Elmo toy or a Stephen King
novel through our Web sites, and part of the purchase price will go
to the charity of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already like to shop online,'' said Sissy Brunk, who
patronizes one of the half-dozen sites making this pitch. ``It
makes you feel good that while you are shopping, a little bit goes
to a worthy cause.'' By stopping at www.igive.com, she is convinced
she is helping a children's charity she admires.
</P>
<P>
   Like credit cards that promise to give a sliver of whatever
amount is charged to a favorite cause, these Web sites appeal to
Americans' charitable side. They claim to have raised hundreds of
thousands of dollars for groups ranging from the Humane Society to
Hands on San Francisco, a volunteer group.
</P>
<P>
   But once you buy Elmo online, what happens to the few dollars
you thought was speeding its way to a good cause? While many
charities are getting checks directly from these sites, it is
impossible to know in every case. It may not end up in the
charity's hands as fast as you imagined _ if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Amounts may fall below some trigger point the retailer or Web
site has set before it will send a check. Money may not be credited
to the charity because of computer glitches. Or shoppers may fail
to follow somewhat burdensome instructions. IGive even carries a
disclaimer, deep in the electronic fine print, that it may be
impossible to guarantee that the charity gets the money.
</P>
<P>
   The last few weeks illustrate some pitfalls:
</P>
<P>
   _ IGive prides itself on letting shoppers name any cause they
fancy, and since the site was born in November 1997, they've
identified more than 4,300 of them. But in interviews, the site's
founder said not even half met the $10 threshold required by IGive
that a charity needs to raise through shoppers' purchases before
the site will cut a check. And IGive has not verified half of those
that qualify. The upshot: fewer than a quarter have been paid or
can expect a check soon. IGive, which said that it has written
checks for $200,000 of the $300,000 earmarked for charity, said
that it will do its best to make sure every charity gets its money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another site, www.charityweb.com, divides any money that has
been pledged to 20 causes that ostensibly have ``peace, life and
love'' in common unless shoppers e-mail other instructions. Those
20 include a Stanford University day-care center, where the site's
founders, a 1996 Stanford MBA and his wife, send one of their
children. The day-care center is one of only two causes that have
received money, only a couple of hundred dollars, so far. The
founder, Kurt Hansen, said that he included the center because he
is on its board but that the site is largely composed of causes he
has no connection with.
</P>
<P>
   _ One site that was full of promise only weeks ago,
www.charitymall.com, has temporarily shut down. Another,
www.socialgoods.com, has been absorbed by a rival,
www.4charity.com. These disruptions raise questions as to what will
happen to money already pledged.
</P>
<P>
   Some charities choose not to participate and object to how their
names are sometimes being used. American Red Cross, for instance,
agreed last year to conduct pilot programs with three new Web sites
that seemed to have financial backing and reputable managers:
Shop2Give.com, 4charity.com and Toysrweb.com. Recently, it bowed
out of the pilot program after it failed to generate the desired
financial results.
</P>
<P>
   And until contacted by a reporter, the Red Cross was unaware
that it was also listed on two other sites, igive.com and
MyCause.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``It dilutes the brand, and it can be very confusing,'' said
Bill Blaul, a Red Cross spokesman. He said the group will probably
ask the Web sites to desist, a request that might not be honored
given the experience of at least one charity that tried to wriggle
off the lists.
</P>
<P>
   To the entrepreneurs behind the Web sites, these hiccups are
just growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   These sites, serving as a middleman between the retailer and the
charity, promise a stream of revenue to charities. Typically, the
money the sites say will go to charity comes from commissions they
earn from online retailers like Amazon.com and J. Crew in exchange
for referring customers.
</P>
<P>
   Most Web sites keep part of the commission, but those that send
it all to charity can still make money by selling advertising and
product placement, finding corporate sponsors or hawking
information about shoppers' habits to market researchers. Many
sites promise not to reveal personal information without
permission, though it is too early to know whether they keep their
word.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet holds huge potential for charities. Nonprofits can
use it to reach donors as never before, e-mailing them about
initiatives, creating forums where donors can meet, and inviting
donations at a fraction of the cost of mass mailings.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross, for example, lets visitors to its site
learn about relief efforts and make online donations. It was also
one of the first to post most of its tax return on the Web _ all
but top executives' salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of these shopping sites say they, too, are helping
reinvent charity. ``We have become part of the fabric of a large
number of nonprofits,'' said Robert Grosshandler, who founded IGive
in Evanston, Ill., after selling his software company. IGive, 18
months old, appears to be the oldest site, and perhaps the largest,
claiming 43,000 registered shoppers doing what it calls
``Technogiving.''
</P>
<P>
   The sites' popularity is growing as charities tell donors to
check them out, as shoppers tell other shoppers about them and as
people surf the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a great medium for this kind of giving,'' said
Fiona Swerdlow, an analyst for Jupiter Communications, a research
firm in New York. ``It should be something that appeals to a lot of
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention charities. ``This kind of thing helps a lot,''
said Lenna Silberman Scott, a spokeswoman for Families of Spinal
Muscular Atrophy in Libertyville, Ill., which said the $600 it has
received out of the $1,300 it has been promised from IGive will
help fund research and provide wheelchairs and other medical
equipment to families in need.
</P>
<P>
   The shop-for-a-cause sites are quick to promote this lofty role.
But the half-dozen or so that have opened in recent months are all
very much for-profit businesses, although two that send all of the
commissions to charity say they are seeking nonprofit status. Some
were created by successful entrepreneurs, some by freshly minted
business school graduates. They tend to be mom-and-pop operations
with little venture capital or corporate backing. And as private
businesses, they divulge almost nothing about how well they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are significant differences,'' said William P. Massey,
president of the National Charities Information Bureau, a watchdog
in New York that says shoppers can easily stumble unless they
understand how each site works.
</P>
<P>
   It's far from clear what rules, if any, apply. The Web sites,
technically affiliates of the retailers, which play no significant
role in their charitable activities, do not consider themselves
traditional fundraisers or solicitors, governed by state laws. Only
a few have registered with state regulators. And none appear to be
posting bonds or creating other backstops to insure that money
pledged doesn't get diverted.
</P>
<P>
   Two already appear to be having difficulty. One,
www.charitymall.com, has temporarily gone dark. Run by two brothers
from New York, both electricians, the site hopes to convert itself
to nonprofit status to make itself more attractive to sponsors.
This was the one site whose retailers had agreed to pay charities
directly, so the money raised so far isn't at risk, one brother
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another, www.socialgoods.com, created by two 1998 Harvard MBA's,
had considered closing down at the end of the month but has been
absorbed by www.4charity.com., a rival started by a 1998 Stanford
MBA. Socialgoods.com's founder, William Morrison, said causes will
get any money they were promised.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of such sites represents ``the beginning of the
problem,'' said Michael DeLucia, director of charitable trusts for
New Hampshire and president of the National Association of State
Charity Officials. ``It is a perfect opportunity for a classic
telemarketing charity scam.''
</P>
<P>
   So what are consumers to do? With hundreds of thousands of
charities _ many with similar-sounding names _ pleading for help
the old-fashioned way in mass mailings and cold calls, giving money
away is already tougher than it should be. Confusion over how
electronic transactions work, how much actually goes to charity,
and who, if anyone, might claim a tax deduction, is not helping.
Even the simplest question _ which site delivers the most to
charity _ is not obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Buying an item from most sites yields only half as much for a
worthy cause as purchasing the same item through 4Charity.com,
which funnels all money it receives from retailers to the
charities. 4Charity, which is seeking nonprofit status, can do this
because it relies heavily on volunteers and plans to pay its bills
by selling information about collective shopping habits to
companies, according to Scott Dunlap, its founder. But consumers
would be hard-pressed to figure this out without hours of research.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, sites like Shop2Give.com and MyCause.com, which
offer shoppers hundreds of thousands of charities to choose from,
raise some of the thorniest issues.
</P>
<P>
   Information may be dated or wrong, since the Web site can't
reach out to every charity. The sheer number of choices also makes
it harder for any one charity to meet a site's minimum threshold.
And consumers may have trouble picking and choosing, given what's
presented. Interested in finding a worthy cancer cause? IGive
provides 35 choices, ranging from three chapters of the American
Cancer Society in Texas, to Cancer Care of Ridgewood, N.J., to
Cancer Caring Center in Pittsburgh, to the Cancer Curing Society in
Bonita, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Thus some consumer advocates say Web sites with fewer choices
might have more appeal. 4charity.com goes to great lengths to
enlist the support of the 25 charities it highlights, while
Greatergood has signed contracts with all 14 of its charities. So
while consumers may not get as much latitude, there is some
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 4,000 causes to keep tabs on, Grosshandler of
IGive said he counts on shoppers to inspect his work. The site
provides each shopper with a detailed accounting of how much the
causes selected by that shopper have ``earned.'' The shopper is
then free to contact the charity to make sure a check was sent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have a million auditors,'' said Grosshandler. But
whether charities can or want to handle inquiries concerning
trivial sums is another matter. ``The site is abrogating its
responsibility,'' in expecting consumers to question the charities,
said Blaul of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites also leave the impression that the process is as
quick as a mouse click. Greatergood.com, for instance, asserts,
``At least 5 percent of whatever you spend will go to the
not-for-profit you choose, automatically. It's that easy!''
</P>
<P>
   If only it were. Most retailers make the sites generate a
certain amount in referral commissions. J. Crew, for example,
typically requires a site to earn $250 in commissions before it
writes a check. Thus, a site entitled to a 5 percent commission
would have to generate $5,000 in sales _ perhaps 150 polo shirts _
before it could expect payment.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. Because the sites often set their own minimums,
starting at $10, any one charity has to inspire shoppers to buy the
equivalent of six or seven polo shirts _ or even a dozen _ before
it sees a dime.
</P>
<P>
   Hands on San Francisco, for example, has been told it is
entitled to more than $100 through 4Charity but must be patient;
the site makes payments only four times a year. The group is also
waiting for a check from IGive, a delay chalked up to a clerical
error.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking individual donations is not always easy. During the
holidays, one retailer, Cyberian Outpost, had computer problems and
for several weeks lost information about which commissions were
owed. While the retailer said it paid the sites what it estimated
it owed them, sites like Shop2Give and 4Charity had no way of
knowing how much they owed various causes unless shoppers contacted
them to reconstruct their purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites also require shoppers to take multiple steps to
ensure that their cause gets credit. IGive requires an electronic
proof of purchase via e-mail, but 10 percent of members never send
it. ``We consider that 10 percent a failure,'' said Grosshandler,
adding that the unaccounted funds still go to charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will use our best efforts to make sure that your worthy
cause gets the appropriate credit,'' the site's fine print warns,
``but in some instances the information provided to us by the
merchant may make that impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Other sites dance around facts consumers might want to know,
particularly those that might remind shoppers that the sites have
mercenary motives and might dip into any money they receive from
retailers to pay their own bills.
</P>
<P>
   MyCause.com leaves visitors with the impression that it is
``sustained by an additional commission paid by our affiliate
retailers,'' implying that its fees are not coming at the
charities' expense.
</P>
<P>
   Shop2Give, for its part, implied that retailers call all the
shots. The site allows the retailer ``to decide the amount to be
donated,'' it told shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Some big merchants like J. Crew say they did weigh in, but in at
least one case involving a major retailer, Shop2Give had more
influence than that. ``We would have no voice in what an affiliate
partner does with the revenue stream,'' said Ben Boyd, a spokesman
for Barnesandnoble.com, one retailer on Shop2Give's site. The site
is ``mischaracterizing our commission as a pledged donation.''
</P>
<P>
   After being made aware of the conflicting accounts, Shop2Give
said it was changing its language. ``Shop2Give then determines how
much of this total commission will go to a nonprofit
organization,'' the site now tells shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can also be forgiven for thinking they are eligible
for a tax deduction. They're not. Yet, only two sites, MyCause and
Shop2Give, make that clear. And Shop2Give even tells shoppers not
to lose hope _ it is ``actively working on finding a solution that
can accommodate tax benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to see how. Whatever money goes to charity is the
result of the site diverting some, or all, of what it gets from the
retailer. Most telling: Even the Web sites typically consider the
money they remit to charity a marketing expense, not a charitable
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest fear of state regulators and charity watchdogs is
that many sites are accountable to no one. Only a few, Greatergood,
Shop2Give and 4Charity, say they have registered under state law to
do cause-related marketing. Other sites like IGive and MyCause say
they do not fall under existing rules.
</P>
<P>
   State laws also come into play when sites raise money without
the charities' cooperation. When the American Camping Association,
for example, found itself on MyCause.com, it requested information
about the site's activities, to no avail. Though the group has not
asked to have its name removed, ``we feel very removed from it,''
said Bob Shultz, the director of development.
</P>
<P>
   Another educational charity, which requested anonymity, has
sought to remove itself from IGive, only to be told it has no say
in the matter. IGive members decide which causes to include.
</P>
<P>
   Use of a charity's name without its approval may violate laws in
many states. In Pennsylvania, no one can solicit on behalf of a
charity without its consent, said Karl Emerson, director of the
Pennsylvania bureau of charitable organizations.
</P>
<P>
   For every bona fide charity that ends up participating over its
objections, regulators also worry that imposters could seek out
listings and bombard shoppers with e-mail, imploring them to make
them the beneficiary. ``There is the distinct possibility that a
questionable charity will appear on one or more of these sites,''
said Massey of the National Charities Information Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   While Greatergood.com requires charities to be on the list the
Internal Revenue Service keeps of nonprofits that qualify for
tax-deductible gifts, it is one of the more stringent. Other sites
say they make case-by-case determinations, while IGive merely
requires causes to affirm they are nonprofits and engage in good
works, one reason it lists many lesser-known causes.
</P>
<P>
   Some like the Broken Nose Fund in Portland, Me., have neither
applied to the IRS for permission to accept tax-deductible
donations nor registered with charity regulators in their home
states. ``I am not registered because I am trying to make money for
myself, because I need surgery,'' said Ashley Lenartson, who is
looking to raise $15,000 to fix his own nose for the third time.
While he believes his is a legitimate cause, the only way consumers
could conceivably learn more about it would be to write to an
address he supplies IGive and wait.
</P>
<P>
   IGive's Grosshandler acknowledges that some groups on its site
are not bona fide charities and says the site's job is not to play
Big Brother. He suggested that it's possible that someone may have
registered a cause close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's their favorite worthy cause, it's great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the dilemma. If these Web sites survive, they will
come to resemble electronic shopping malls with as much to show for
themselves as the credit card companies that pioneered the
help-a-favorite-cause pitch. Nearly 6 percent of the $596 billion
in Visa and MasterCard volume last year went to cards that diverted
a fraction of purchases to worthy causes, according to the Nilson
Report, an industry newsletter in Oxnard, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But there are key differences. Credit card issuers are often
well-established companies that have earned consumers' trust. They
enter contracts with every charity they represent. And while
Internet companies often fall between regulatory cracks, banking
has always been well monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these shop-for-a-cause sites become a permanent part of
the scene depends a lot on what kind of results they deliver for
charities and consumers. What worries Dunlap, the founder of
4charity, is that some sites _ ones that mislead consumers or
alienate charities _ ``will ruin it for the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-30-99 1927EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
