<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0754 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP04-COX     03-31 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boiled custard recalls sweet memories
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Myra Hager of Lilburn (Ga.) is among readers who
remember, and sometimes make, boiled custard. She sent her
grandmother's recipe, which she said is at least 60 years old, in
response to a recent request from Nina Whitfield of Roswell (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Many in Hager's family say it wouldn't be Christmas without
boiled custard. Her grandmother used it as a base for lots of
desserts, including her father's favorite _ stirred into banana
pudding _ but always reserved a separate bowl full of plain custard
just for Myra. Our tester says it's great with fresh strawberries,
too.
</P>
<P>
   We hope it's the kind Whitfield wanted.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Boiled Custard
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 3 1/2 cups, 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon almond or vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   In a heavy pan over medium heat, bring milk to warm temperature
without boiling. In a bowl, mix the sugar and cornstarch. Add eggs
to sugar mixture and beat well. Pour the hot milk over the sugar
mixture slowly and mix well. Return full mixture to heat and cook
on medium-low until it thickens, stirring constantly. Do not
overcook. Bring to 170 to 180 degrees or until mixture coats the
spoon you are stirring with.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat, stir in extract and strain through wire
strainer if desired. Pour into a pitcher or bowl to cool and cover
with plastic wrap pushed onto surface of custard, to prevent a skin
from forming.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 178 calories, 7 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 30), 25 grams carbohydrates, 132 milligrams
cholesterol, 81 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Susan W. Vaughn of Conyers (Ga.) is looking for a recipe for
Hot Water Corn Bread. After reading about it in a cookbook that
extolled the bread's unique texture, caused by the hot water, she
was disappointed to find that the book didn't contain the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Linda Juckett (e-mail) is looking for a tossed salad recipe
that includes broken, uncooked ramen noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
