</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-FOOLS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No jest: Films offer cavalcade of fools for April 1
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's April Fools' Day. Feel like fooling around with some
jesters, clowns and just plain fools? Here are some prime examples
of film foolishness on video, though not necessarily ha-ha foolish.
And please note the absence of Jim Carrey, Jerry Lewis and Roberto
Benigni; we figured you already knew the usual fools.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Court Jester'' (1956).
</P>
<P>
   Danny Kaye's genial spoof of the Robin Hood legend and Hollywood
swashbucklers was one of his biggest hits. The agile Kaye _ he
proved as good at sword fights as he was with tongue twisters _
plays a cowardly carnival entertainer who gets mixed up in royal
intrigue when he's forced to masquerade as a world-famous court
jester. The ace supporting cast includes Angela Lansbury and Basil
Rathbone. Remember: The chalice with the palace has the brew that
is true.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World'' (1963).
</P>
<P>
   It's a dumb, dumb, dumb, dumb movie. And every bit as bloated as
its title (especially if you see the original 3 hour and 12 minute
version). But what it does offer is as fine a collection of
midcentury or so comics as you're ever likely to see gathered
together for one film.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Durante kicks the bucket (literally) in the opening scene,
but not before dropping a clue about some buried loot. So the hunt
is on, conducted with high spirits _ no matter how low the material
goes _ by the likes of Milton Berle, Jonathan Winters, Sid Caesar,
Edie Adams, Buddy Hackett, Mickey Rooney, Phil Silvers, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The icing on the madness? There are also cameos by every
still-ambulatory joker then in the biz _ Jack Benny, Don Knotts,
Buster Keaton, Jim Backus, the Three Stooges and at least a dozen
others.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The April Fools'' (1969).
</P>
<P>
   Myrna Loy and Charles Boyer are free spirits with a long and
happy marriage. Their example inspires a mild-mannered stockbroker
(Jack Lemmon) and a married woman (Catherine Deneuve) to chuck
their mundane lives and, um, do their own thing (well, it was the
late '60s).
</P>
<P>
   Deneuve, in her first American role, is lovely to look at (also
scared to death, remembers Loy in her autobiography), and Lemmon
does his dithering Everyman bit both touchingly and well. The
picture as a whole may not gel as well as its individual parts
suggest, but there's a splendid bit with Harvey Korman.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fools' Parade'' (1971).
</P>
<P>
   This quirky, virtually unknown film offers Jimmy Stewart in his
last appearance as a bona-fide leading man. After this, it was TV
and Lassie movies.
</P>
<P>
   An adaptation of an idiosyncratic novel by Davis Grubb (``Night
of the Hunter''), the picture takes place in rural West Virginia in
1935. Stewart, Strother Martin and Kurt Russell are ex-cons who
plan to open a general store with the money Stewart has saved from
his prison pay. But a crooked warden (George Kennedy) has other
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   If you were one of the 12 people who saw the movie, what you
probably remember most is Stewart's glass eye, which he uses to
bamboozle gullible thugs. The eye itself was something of a
problem. It was a prosthesis _ a kind of contact lens contraption _
that was extremely irritating to Stewart's own eye. He could only
wear it for 20 minutes at a time, which made for a stop-and-go
production schedule.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ship of Fools'' (1965).
</P>
<P>
   Critics called it ``Grand Hotel'' at sea when it came out.
Today, it would probably be characterized as ``Titanic'' minus the
iceberg with a dash of ``Schindler's List.''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Stanley Kramer, the movie takes place on an ocean
liner en route to Bremerhaven, Germany, from Vera Cruz, Mexico, in
1933. On board is a rich microcosm of humanity _ Vivien Leigh as a
fading divorcee; Lee Marvin as a boorish Texan; Oskar Werner as the
sensitive ship's doctor who's in love with Simone Signoret; Jose
Ferrer as a German businessman and enthusiastic Hitler supporter;
and Michael Dunn as the film's one-man Greek chorus.
</P>
<P>
   The off-screen dramas were as rich as the on-screen ones. Leigh
was dying; this would be her last film. Werner refused to be
photographed from the right. Meanwhile, Marvin was falling for a
bit player named Michelle Triola who, a few years later, would add
``palimony'' to our vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
