<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Everest'' (unrated) _ What was breathtaking on the
five-story IMAX screen (and earned an ``A'' grade) is still
impressive. David Breashears' documentary was filmed at the same
time as the 1996 storm that killed eight mountain climbers,
memorialized by Jon Krakauer's best-selling book ``Into Thin Air.''
But on the small screen, it bears the same relation to the IMAX
experience as a museum postcard does to the actual painting it
reproduces. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Home Fries'' (PG-13) _ Deep-fried hokum about an unwed
mom-to-be (Drew Barrymore) and the stepsons (Luke Wilson and Jake
Busey) of her late boyfriend. One wants to kill her; the other
wants to kiss her. A mix of Hollywood blandness and small-town
condescension, the movie can't decide if it's a romance or a farce.
But Catherine O'Hara chews the scenery _ in a good way _ as the
boys' vengeful mom. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   THE VIDEO COLLECTOR
</P>
<P>
   Notable videos on sale
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brit TV: ``Upstairs Downstairs: The Second Season,'' a
seven-tape box set, $149.95; single tapes $24.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kids: ``Catdog Together Forever,'' ``Catdog vs. the
Greasers,'' $12.95 each. ``Mama Do You Love Me?,'' VHS ($12.98) and
DVD ($24.98).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vintage: ``Portrait of Jennie,'' ``Intermezzo,'' ``The
Farmer's Daughter,'' ``Made for Each Other,'' $14.98 each
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Widescreen: ``The Black Hole Collector's Edition,'' the first
time in widescreen, VHS ($14.98) and DVD ($29.98).
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
