<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Rugrats' comfortingly familiar familial territory
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Rugrats Movie'' (G)
</P>
<P>
   The animated ``Rugrats'' hit the big screen with a big issue:
making way for a new baby. That's what Tommy Pickles has to do when
his folks come home from the hospital with Dylan ``Dil'' Pickles.
</P>
<P>
   On top of dealing with the constant crying, Tommy can't help
noticing all the attention his parents are giving to this needy
newcomer. His pals Phil and Lil and Chuckie aren't crazy about the
new kid, either. So when they all get lost in the woods, Tommy
fears that he has to choose between playing with his friends and
tending his nuisance baby bro.
</P>
<P>
   The movie version of the TV hit show is amiable, if frenetic,
aimed at kids who need to be stimulated every few seconds. Grade:
B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
