<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S REIGN OF ERROR IN YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The last few days I've felt sick, angry and
powerless. And I don't mean about rising gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Our president ordered the bombing of a small country run by a
man with a record of genocide, and yet never expected that the
genocide would be escalated enormously.
</P>
<P>
   I predicted it. Anyone could have predicted it by flipping
through the news clips on Slobodan Milosevic, Serbia, Sarajevo and
Kosovo. President Clinton, one of the smartest politicians in the
world, failed to predict it.
</P>
<P>
   How do we explain this? Clinton even promised Milosevic that he
would not send in ground forces. He didn't even have troops and
tanks in reserve in case the air war didn't go as planned _ which
it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a lot of talk about how Clinton doesn't have an
``exit strategy'' or an ``end game.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess that's something like ``closure,'' but long ago military
thinkers used the word ``victory.'' That word has fallen out of
use.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a chess analogy in this horror, it's that Milosevic
has been playing chess while Clinton has been playing his old game
of _ what? Strip poker? Or maybe Go Fish.
</P>
<P>
   End game? Clinton is fishing for a second move.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has Clinton boxed between two choices: the complete
``ethnic cleansing'' of Kosovo, or American casualties on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   As we know, taking casualties is politically unacceptable in
modern American war.
</P>
<P>
   We like our wars risk-free to Americans, easy and quick enough
to fit between stories like the rising price of gas and the Dow
hitting 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Just as I was starting to rant about those liberals (yes, mostly
liberals) who call for more bombing to stop the genocide, yet want
the war to be quick and free of American casualties, I got a call
from somebody who knows a thing or two about war and its effects.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Sullivan, a San Francisco native and former aide to Rep.
Tom Lantos, is the executive director of the National Gulf War
Resource Center in Washington, D.C. This veteran of the First
Armored Division in the Gulf War addressed the notions that the
Gulf War was a low-casualty, high-tech battle and that it was
quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say it was quick, because it's still going on,''
Sullivan said. ``You can't say it was so high-tech because the
Patriot missiles didn't work and the cruise missiles were as likely
to hit a civilian target as a military one. You can't say it was
low-casualty because thousands of Iraqis died, and still are dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole mythology of the clean, simple war is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it lives on in such bloodless Pentagon language as the use
of the phrase ``degrading enemy forces'' when talking about trying
to find targets in the fog and blow them up.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon and White House talk about ``punishing'' Milosevic,
while the air attacks make him a hero to his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I go past the Iwo Jima memorial,'' Sullivan said.
``You've got to go over and plant your flag in the other guy's back
yard to win a war. The U.S. had a comprehensive plan to defeat
Japan in World War II. There is no plan here.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans think there's no war, either. It's just another
president dropping bombs on another strange little country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that gets me are the talking heads on TV talking
about the `fireworks,' and going `Ooh' and `Aah,''' Sullivan said.
``Every time those `fireworks' go off, people are being blown to
heaven. When are they going to get some real people on TV?''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the original questions. Why did Clinton think bombs and
missiles would cow Milosevic into accepting an unfavorable treaty
and being nice to ethnic Albanians?
</P>
<P>
   And why did Clinton give away any advantage by promising his
adversary he wouldn't use ground forces?
</P>
<P>
   The easy answer is that Clinton avoided military experience.
</P>
<P>
   But plenty of generals and admirals have done dumb things, too.
</P>
<P>
   I believe the problem is that Clinton has been playing the game
he knows best, besides legal and sexual semantics. He's been
playing symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   Given a choice between symbols and substance, Clinton has always
chosen symbols, from his ``conversation on race'' to his
cruise-missile attacks on Sudanese penicillin plants.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton loves to send messages via laser-guided bomb and cruise
missile, a weapon that isn't very powerful, but looks good on TV
and doesn't result in lost pilots.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Milosevic stepped up the action in his much more
deadly non-game of genocide, or ethnic cleansing if you prefer that
awful term.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is playing for keeps. Clinton apparently was playing
to the polls, as usual.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it doesn't matter if the genocide would have
taken place without the bombing. It has increased because of
Milosevic's deadly serious chess playing, and we have no effective
way to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone remember how long it took to load the tanks of Paul
Sullivan's First Armored Division on ships and get them to the
Gulf?
</P>
<P>
   It's too late to get them anywhere near Kosovo now, and we're
stuck with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's America going to do to take care of these refugees?''
Sullivan said. ``We're responsible for them now. That's a tough
burden.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
