<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-THINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TAMING OF THE SHREW' MEETS ADOLESCENT ANGST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Things were already not going so well for ``10 Things I Hate
About You'' when Joan Armatrading faded in on the film's
soundtrack. Her ``The Weakness in Me'' is the song that's supposed
to reveal just how much Patrick (Heath Ledger) is falling in love
with Kat (Julia Stiles), but it only reveals how hopelessly
off-base ``10 Things'' is.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Armatrading? She writes ballads every mix-taper should be
proud to own, but the soundtrack to an upbeat teen movie? It's like
name-dropping to a bunch of people who wouldn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this update of Shakespeare's ``Taming of the Shrew''
is the type of movie that would just as soon have a middling rock
outfit like Letters to Cleo go amateur night all over the song
anyway _ so better to have the original.
</P>
<P>
   As handled by Gil Junger, the man responsible for the TV
syndication staples ``Golden Girls'' and ``It's a Living,'' ``10
Things'' is like something made by your incorrigible uncle, the one
who let you borrow his Malibu before you got your license, the one
who swore he'd keep your first sex and drug encounters ``our little
secret.''
</P>
<P>
   The hep uncle with the girlfriends about your age who thinks
he's cooler than your parents because he can ask you ``what the
dilly yo?'' Ugh. It's dispiriting to see a gaggle of up-and-comers
held in movie detention by forces more avuncular than awesome. Oh
``10 Things,'' how I loathe thee, let me count the ways.
</P>
<P>
   It's a movie repeatedly done in by its soundtrack. Just because
a film is based on a play from the 16th century doesn't mean the
music that drives it ought to come from that era too. What suburban
party goes through the trouble of bum-rushing some rich kid's
house, throwing up a couple turntables complete with DJ, then
spinning a creaky Thompson Twins number as if no one would notice?
</P>
<P>
   None of the characters notices much of anything going on beneath
the surface at Padua High. When Cameron (Joseph Gordon-Levitt)
decrees himself in love with the virginal Bianca (Larisa Oleynik),
he refuses to believe she's as shallow as she sounds. Never mind
that she's hashing over the difference between liking and loving
Skechers and Prada bags with her friend Chastity (Gabrielle Union)
as if memories of ``Clueless'' had all but dried up. Besides, names
do lie: Chastity is the biggest skeezer at Padua High.
</P>
<P>
   Bianca is smitten with the school hottie Joey (Andrew Keegan), a
socks and briefs model who appears to be wearing more make-up than
every girl running to the bathroom mirror for a touch-up between
classes. She'd like to go on a date with Joey, but her father
forbids it unless Kat, her hard-boiled, hot-blooded and willfully
manless older sister can scare up a beau. That sends Cameron and
Joey on individual scrambles to Patrick, Padua's resident bad boy,
to woo his even more callous half.
</P>
<P>
   This despair could all have been avoided if someone had the
basic social sagacity to realize a few things about the players in
this staged play. ``There's this boy ...'' Bianca tells her dad,
``who's a flaming imbecile,'' interrupts Kat.
</P>
<P>
   No, he's just flaming, but everyone's so focused on being
grateful that the Sylvia Plath-loving Kat owns a pair of black
undies and is ``not a kd lang fan'' that Joey's playing the
specious straight falls through the cracks of what could have been
a hilariously observant, modern movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``10 Things'' hides behind Shakespeare, kissing up to the Bard
when its makers and participants really owe their jobs and this
entire teen resurgence as we now know it to John Hughes. Updates
like this one and ``She's All That'' use literature to disqualify
the fact that they wish they had Hughes' breezy, infectious
neurosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``10 Things'' could have been wild, raucous fun, still quotable
in 10 years, but terms like ``up-chuck'' and ``panties in a twist''
are so 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stiles and Ledger are the big deals here. Together they seem to
be in another movie in which people don't suffer rubber emotions
but ones that stick. Stiles is especially captivating with her
husky voice and tomboy overtones. You're convinced she'll go to
Sarah Lawrence and have the lesbian tryst her friends and family
fear.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's afraid of her, turning Kat into a Solid Gold dancer
in the time it takes to drop one Notorious B.I.G. song at that
house party _ which is why it's the Spam of processed teen movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
