<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0819 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      03-31 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JEAN FORTUNES; JUMPER FATES; MS. MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SALLY JACOBS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a world fraught with uncertainty, a world in which stealth
bombers are shot down and the Good Samaritan's suicide line is
busy, there is a single unwavering constant. It is a comfortable
pair of blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   There are those among us, those of a certain, ah, disposition,
who know that the best pair of jeans are Levi's straight legs with
a button-down fly and the company's little leather square stitched
high on the butt. They do not need to be washed for months. They
are always there for you, molded to your body, even when your loved
ones are not.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was that this reporter leapt to Nina Munk's cover
story in the April Fortune on ``How Levi's Trashed a Great American
Brand.'' I confess: I never read Fortune. I consider stories about
corporate America as kin to month-old pork chops discovered in the
back of the fridge. But I read every word of this story.
</P>
<P>
   It is not, of course, so much a story about jeans as it is about
Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. CEO Robert Haas, one of those rare titans of
industry who actually care about people as much as profits. Levi's,
certainly, has suffered as the world has been flooded by ever new
brands of jeans _ its US market share of men 16 and older has been
halved in recent years. But the decline of this American classic is
also the result of Haas's utopian vision, according to Fortune, and
his determination to show that a company driven by social values
could do just as well as one driven by profits, and perhaps even
better.
</P>
<P>
   Haas, who sprang from the Peace Corps and Harvard Business
School to become the fifth-generation family member to run the
company in 1984, believes in corporate responsibility. Really! He
pulled out of China to protest human rights abuses. He created task
forces to make the company more aspirational. He distributed AIDS
leaflets outside the company cafeteria. There were lots of meetings
about finding meaning in the workplace. But somehow, Haas forgot to
keep an eye on what folks were wearing out there. And when managers
became distracted with a retailer-friendly program in the mid
1990s, the blue jean king kind of imploded. Fortune estimates that
over the past three years, the company's market value has shrunk
from $14 billion to $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune takes a tsk-tsk attitude about all this, sniffing
unhappily that madman Haas is virtually unfettered at the wheel
until 2011. The story nods at corporate efforts to reclaim its lost
market share, only to draw up in horror at Haas's promise to reward
every Levi's employee in the world with a bonus worth a year's
salary if the cash flow rises to a certain level in the next two
years. What! What next?! Free jeans for the homeless? So if it is
hard for readers to solider into the business press, it is nice to
discover that someone, somewhere, is doing it differently.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I remember the day Dano died. I did not know him, never even
heard of him in fact. But as I drove home from work one day last
November I listened enthralled to the radio account of how he had
plunged 1,100 feet into the dark of a Yosemite valley tethered to a
single rope. He was working on his sport.
</P>
<P>
   In the April issue of Outside magazine, Craig Vetter takes a
look at why, sort of. Dan Osman (his full name) was a rock rat, one
of those ropy-haired, iron-muscled men who spend their days
crawling up the craggy cliffs and sometimes jumping off them. Dano
was very good at it. In fact, he had created a whole system of
ropes and anchor lines that spread the weight of impact of his fall
and enabled him to jump from heights no one had ever tried before.
He called this new sport ``free-falling.'' And, lately, adventure
and sport companies had been shooting spots of the 35-year-old for
their ads.
</P>
<P>
   For Dano, not suprisingly, the ante got raised ever higher, as
did the height of the rocks he jumped off of. Although the story
promises in its headline to go deep, to look at whether his jumps
were ``as profound as he imagined, or just stunts taken to foolish
extremes,'' it largely does not. Mostly, it ogles the phenomenon
and a youngish man's tragic death. But it is a gripping story
nonetheless, a glimpse of wandering soul's brief collision with
identity. It is a story about doing it differently. It is a story
that Robert Haas might wish to read.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of things that are different, here's something that's
not. Ms. magazine is back on the stands after an absence of several
months while it was being sold to a group of women investors called
Liberty Media for Women. Although the bimonthly was supposed to
have been retooled to appeal to younger women, it looks less like a
new magazine and a lot like all the other women's magazines. That's
progress for you.
</P>
<P>
   The April/May issue includes a story on a woman's experience
with plastic surgery. (Mostly good.) One on adultry. (Mostly bad.)
A couple of pieces about a woman's run for the presidency. (Time
will tell.) And a host of updates on such boilerplate subjects as
abortion clinic violence, sexual harassment in public schools, and
the like. There are two stronger pieces, one on the political
implications of women becoming more religious, the other a woman's
memoir of her parents' divorce.
</P>
<P>
   In an introductory letter, founding editor of the original
magazine and current shareholder Gloria Steinem exults that Ms. is
at last women-owned and independent. ``I can't wait to see what
happens now,'' she concludes. Neither can we.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
