<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVERS REAP BENEFITS AS INSURER TAKES A HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1995, six years after the Berlin Wall fell, Commerce Group
Inc. introduced price competition to the Soviet-style auto
insurance market in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Things have never been the same since. The Webster-based insurer
initially offered discounts from the state-set rates to Commerce
subscribers who were also members of the American Automobile
Association. Rival insurers countered with discounts of their own,
including breaks for safe drivers. The state added to the mix by
cutting rates more than 20 percent over a four-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a golden age for Massachusetts drivers. The
same cannot be said for Commerce. True, the company is much bigger.
Its share of the Massachusetts auto market has climbed from 16
percent at the end of 1995 to 22 percent. But most other numbers
have been going in the wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   Profits, which peaked at $122 million in 1994, were just $96
million last year. The company's loss ratio _ the percentage of
each dollar of premiums that is paid out in claims _ has been
steadily rising. Investors have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, Commerce's stock price has
dropped from 35 to 25, a decline of 28 percent. Over the past three
years, the stock has climbed just 20 percent at a time when the
stock market in general has roughly doubled.
</P>
<P>
   What's the problem? A big piece of it, ironically, is the price
competition Commerce brought to the market. Credit Suisse First
Boston just shaved its 1999 and 2000 earnings estimates for
Commerce, blaming ``increased competitive pressures in personal
auto insurance in Massachusetts.'' Credit Suisse expects earnings
to fall this year and recover somewhat next year. Dowling &AMP;
Partners, a Hartford research firm, projects declining earnings
both this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   Because the company will report earnings in several weeks,
Commerce executives declined to talk about earnings or the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street thought the price competition might ease up a bit
this year. So did Commerce. In January, the company said it would
offer drivers with safe records a 5 percent discount this year,
down from 15 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month later, however, Commerce reversed course and
said the safe-driver discounts would be 8 percent. Commerce acted
after other insurers, including Liberty Mutual, set their discounts
at 8 percent. ``It's competition and we want to make sure our rates
are adequate to protect our market share,'' said Commerce spokesman
Anthony J. Battista, explaining the company's change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently once the genie of competition has been let loose,
it's tough to get it back in the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   But competition is not Commerce's only problem. The company does
the vast majority of its business in Massachusetts. As Credit
Suisse put it, ``Massachusetts has historically been an extremely
difficult operating environment for many personal auto insurers.''
The state has lots of traffic, bad drivers, and high medical costs.
It is also the only state that still sets auto insurance rates, a
task the rest of the country leaves to the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the industry asked for a 15.5 percent hike in rates.
Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt granted an increase of just
0.7 percent. Commerce called the rate hike inadequate. An executive
from another company, who spoke on the promise he would not be
identified, was less charitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision was insane,'' said the executive. ``The insurance
market here is highly politicized.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry has appealed the rate decision. The Supreme
Judicial Court is expected to hear the case this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce has been trying to solve its Massachusetts problem by
expanding its business in other states. Last year Commerce acquired
the Automobile Club Insurance Co., a firm that writes insurance
policies through AAA agents in 23 states. The deal increased
out-of-state business to 15 percent of the company's total.
Commerce's long-term goal is 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But life outside of Massachusetts is no picnic either.
``Nationally, competition is getting tougher,'' said Jeffrey
Thompson, an analyst with Advest in Hartford. ``Everyone is
fighting for market share.''
</P>
<P>
   With the growing popularity of insurance sales over the
Internet, the barriers to entry have practically disappeared, say
analysts. In such a world, where the product offered is essentially
a commodity, price wars could become a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts still like Commerce's prospects. They say the
stock has been beaten up too much, that the company is well run,
and that the Automobile Club deal will help over time. They may be
right. In the meantime, however, life is better for those of us who
buy auto insurance than it is for those who sell it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
