<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'VE HUFFED AND PUFFED _ WHAT DO WE DO NOW? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tomahawks are sizzling. The Stealths are bombing. Oh yes, we
lost one of our $45 million planes, but the American pilot ejected
safely. It was like a heroic movie: He was rescued just as a ring
of Yugoslavian soldiers was closing in on him.
</P>
<P>
   A telling cultural moment of how we view the NATO airstrikes
against Yugoslavia is on the front page of one of the nation's
leading newspapers. For ``an interactive look at Kosovo,''
including ``daily images of war,'' click on www.usatoday.com.
Somehow I just cannot picture such cavalier, capitalistic
computerspeak to plug photos of bleached bones at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Just as surreal was Tuesday's front page of The Christian
Science Monitor. It featured a story on a bill in Arkansas to ban
minors from violent video games in public arcades. One teenager was
quoted as saying: ``I have friends who spend their allowance in the
machines until it is all gone. Most of my class likes the
blood-and-guts or combat types best.'' The bill's author,
Lieutenant Governor Win Rockefeller, said, ``Video games basically
numb our youth'' to violence.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all of our intellectual claims that real war is a
serious business, it has become Nintendo. As long as it appears
that we are not spilling blood or guts, $45 million planes are
disposable toys. On Friday, a prominent Wall Street investor, Thom
Brown, said it ``would be very negative for the market'' if NATO
sent in ground troops. No ground troops, no real war, no worry. How
else do you explain that despite the grave comparisons of Slobodan
Milosevic to Hitler and the Khmer Rouge, the Dow finished Monday
above 10,000 for the first time ever?
</P>
<P>
   To borrow from Neil Postman, we have amused ourselves to defeat.
Here we are flying B-2 Stealths all the way from Missouri for
outrageously inefficient bombing runs merely on the philosophy of
``use it or lose it.'' The United States has spent $50 billion to
build planes to evade radar, yet because of the mountains and
clouds in this part of Europe, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon
said on Monday, ``we obviously have concerns'' about the Stealth's
``vulnerability.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they tell us they are bringing in yet more bombers, B-1Bs,
B-52s, Warthogs. We have huffed, puffed, and bombed Slobodan's
house down. We say we have crippled his ground radar. We say we are
decimating his tanks. Yet this is taking on all the appearances of
federal agents using battering ram tanks to demolish a ghetto
apartments only to find no drugs or dealers.
</P>
<P>
   For while we play with our toys, Milosevic is doing exactly what
he wants. Coveting Kosovo as sacred Serb grounds, he had already
driven out 500,000 of the 1.8 million ethnic Albanians, who had
made up 90 percent of the province's population. During the NATO
bombing, the stream of Albanians out of Kosovo has grown to an
average of 20,000 a day. Observers said Kosovo could be truly
``ethnic cleansed'' in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had planned to supply 4,000 troops to a
28,000-soldier NAT0 peacekeeping force, assuming that Milosevic
would crumble under air power. But to defeat Milosevic's 40,000-man
army, an army that knows how to hole up in the mountains, military
experts say NATO would need between 100,000 and 200,000 ground
troops and at least six months to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   But if Kosovo has no ethnic Albanians left to defend, the bombs
no longer have a point. It took five months to amass the nearly
550,000 troops for the Gulf War. But even though we liberated
Kuwait and secured our oil supply until the next crisis, Saddam
Hussein still stands.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said it would take about a month to amass enough ground
troops to seriously threaten Milosevic on the ground. It makes you
question what was the point of the bombing in the first place. On
Monday, in the face of the obvious, NATO's military commander,
General Wesley Clark, said, ``We never thought we could stop
this,'' referring to the ethnic cleansing. ``You can't conduct
police actions from the air in any country.''
</P>
<P>
   This means that up in those secretive war rooms, the brass knew
all along that air power alone would not deter Milosevic. But they
also knew, as Bacon said, ``there was no support within NATO for a
massive ground operation.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the world in a terrible quandary. We employed the
weapons of the Nintendo age to call a despot's bluff. We thought
nothing of it because the weapons are so distant from point of
launch to point of death. The ``images of war'' are so antiseptic
we are tempted to rule out other, less violent options. Or, in the
case of Kosovo, where genocide is quite real, we draw back from
using the only force that a despot will listen to _ the force to
destroy his army.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, there seems no real hope of stopping the exodus
unless the Russians, of all people, come to the rescue. Despite our
billions of dollars of air power, Milosevic is on his way to being
a fait accompli winner.
</P>
<P>
   He will be happy to allow a cease-fire with an ethnically
cleansed Kosovo. He will be happy to come to the bargaining table,
knowing that he forced the United States and NATO to be mere
bystanders to another trail of tears. But there will be relatively
few tears shed in the United States. The Dow went over 10,000
points.
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
