<SLUG> BC-WOM-NCAA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWERS FLOCKED TO WOMEN'S FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Duke beat Tennessee in the East Regional, it sent a shock
wave felt by anyone even remotely involved in college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Great, said some, it will be good to see new teams vying for the
national title. There will be more parity.
</P>
<P>
   Oh no, moaned others, who will pay any attention to women's
basketball now (without Tennessee)?
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, many people paid attention. The championship
game between Purdue and Duke Sunday night produced a 4.3 rating for
ESPN, meaning it was seen in 3.2 million homes. It was the second
biggest audience for an ESPN college basketball game, men's or
women's. (The biggest was the Arkansas-Princeton men's game in
1990, seen by 3.4 million homes.)
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee looked like a lock to reach the final based on its
31-3 record and the fact it was the three-time defending champion.
The team seemed destined to live up to its national presence: A
book by coach Pat Summitt, a cover story on her in Sports
Illustrated, and the star appeal of senior forward Chamique
Holdsclaw, the three-time AP Player of the Year who as recently as
two weeks ago was on the cover of TV Guide.
</P>
<P>
   Even nonchalant fans marveled at Holdsclaw's heroics and quickly
learned to pronounce her first name: Cha-MEEK-kwa. She was an
All-America for each of her four years at Tennessee and last month
won an ESPY as Female Athlete of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 43,281 people who filled out tournament brackets on
espn.com, 25,806 predicted Tennessee would win the championship.
Purdue was picked by 6,932, and 292 predicted Duke.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder, then, that last week's Tennessee-Duke game earned a
2.1 rating, the highest on ESPN for any non-Final Four game.
</P>
<P>
   But when Duke advanced, ESPN knew it had to change gears. No
problem, said Len DeLuca, senior vice-president of programming
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed the double Duke story was one people would
adopt,'' he said, as the Blue Devils men's and women's basketball
teams advanced to their Final Fours. ``We go for good stories, and
here it was served up to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The stellar rating of the championship game, he said, shows the
depth the sport has developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the growth of the Title IX generation,'' DeLuca
said. ``So the audience interest is no longer novel.''
</P>
<P>
   The other story lines ESPN had were that both Duke and Purdue
had defeated Tennessee, and that the teams shared players who had
played together at Purdue for a year. Nicole Erickson and Michele
VanGorp transferred to Duke from Purdue after their coach was
fired; Ukari Figgs and Stephanie White-McCarty stayed. Both pairs
of players also were roommates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a soap opera to me.'' said White-McCarty.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Meyers, ESPN analyst for women's basketball, admitted before
the Final Four that the network would have a challenge without Tenn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
