<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FUTURA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN BEHIND `THE SIMPSONS' LOOKS AHEAD WITH `FUTURAMA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America loves sitcoms, from ``I Love Lucy'' to ``The Many Loves
of Dobie Gillis'' to ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' not to mention
``Joanie Loves Chachi.'' We've loved them for the way they edge our
lives into satire and farce and sheer harmlessness. We've loved
them enough to inspire a glut of some 45 half-hour comedies on TV
schedules every week, not including the episodes in endless
syndication. We've loved them enough to wear them out, and to leave
our TV landscape littered with deadwood like ``Veronica's Closet.''
And so now, 50 years after early sitcoms like ``The Goldbergs,''
it's not surprising to find TV script writers, and TV viewers,
reaching beyond conventional, live-action sitcoms into the creative
possibilities of adult animation. With a roster of prime-time
cartoons like ``King of the Hill,'' ``The PJs,'' ``Family Guy,''
``Dilbert,'' ``South Park,'' and no less than seven forthcoming
series (including an adaptation of Kevin Smith's movie ``Clerks''),
we are on the verge of a full-fledged nighttime toon boom.
</P>
<P>
   It was Matt Groening who made the animation alternative hot 10
years ago with ``The Simpsons,'' which takes the nuclear family and
the nuclear world to new levels of dark hysteria. Now Groening is
joining the wave that he started with another witty series called
``Futurama,'' which premiered Sunday night. It's not quite the
revelation that ``The Simpsons'' was, but ``Futurama'' contains
enough inventiveness and heart to make it a worthy follow-up. Like
``The Simpsons,'' ``Futurama'' has a cast of unique characters who
are as lovable and fallible as they are pop-eyed and chinless. And
more than ``The Simpsons,'' ``Futurama'' goes places only animation
can go, with a colorful and comic vision of the year 3000 that
would tax even a Jim Cameron-size budget and a Fellini-size
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Futurama'' setup has a clueless pizza delivery boy named
Fry caught in a cryogenics chamber for a thousand years, and waking
to a new universe. It's the perfect territory for the cynical
Groening, and he overstuffs his futurescapes with pop allusions and
jokes that upend our own 1999 world. Some are quickie gags, like a
billboard for ``The Implant Hut,'' a J.F.K. Jr. Airport, and a line
adapted from the movie ``Pulp Fiction,'' with a cop saying, ``I'm
gonna get 24th century on his ass.'' And some are sharper-edged,
like the 25-cent ``Suicide Booth,'' Fate Assignment Officers who
insert permanent chips that determine people's careers, and the
ruins of New York City buried underneath a high-tech urban
construct.
</P>
<P>
   In the premiere, Fry befriends a heavy-drinking,
robot-porn-loving robot named Bender and a tough, sensible one-eyed
alien named Leela. He also connects with his only living relative,
a great-great-great-etc. nephew named Professor Hubert Farnsworth.
Future episodes will have the gang planet-hopping in service of the
professor's intergalactic delivery company. As you might expect
from the man behind ``The Simpsons,'' ``Futurama'' will also pick
up lots of unusual supporting characters as it develops, including
Dr. Zoidberg, a lobsterlike alien anatomy expert. We can also
expect to see a few familiar faces if the show returns to the head
museum introduced in the premiere. There, the classic heads of
celebrities like Leonard Nimoy, Dennis Rodman, Richard Nixon, and
Matt Groening himself live in jars of water, where they are fed
like fish. Now there's a scene you probably won't find on most
live-action sitcoms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
