<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 NCAA VIEWERS DON'T KNOW WHAT THEY MISSED
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Before we start dissin' CBS for broadcasting the lowest-rated
NCAA championship game in the last 21 years, consider the
following:
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces are dropping bombs in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Professional wrestling owns Monday night cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Neilsen Media has an absurd way of measuring viewers of sports
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Quality has little to do with commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   None of these facts are particularly revelatory but help explain
why Monday night's game between Duke and the University of
Connecticut received a 17.2 rating and 27 share in the national
overnight measurement of the 44 largest media markets. Last year's
game between Kentucky and Utah was just three percent higher, but
neither game came close to the 24.1 rating earned by the 1979
Michigan State-Indiana State game.
</P>
<P>
   Bird and Magic was a powerful draw, but the Duke-UConn game was
much better, going down to the last few possessions. Not even Billy
Packer's constant carping on the players' fatigue could undermine
the sheer energy the teams generated in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The game was up and down the entire 40 minutes, and in Boston,
the last 15 minutes attracted an additional 66,000 viewers, the
highest rating period of the game. The overall number in Boston was
a 13.2 and 23 share, making Channel 4 the ratings winner over Peter
Jennings's ``The Century'' on Channel 5 (9.5 and 16 share) and a
Julia Roberts movie, ``Something to Talk About,'' on Channel 7 (7.6
and 12 share).
</P>
<P>
   But no one guaranteed a thrilling final, and oddsmakers had No.
1 Duke a 9-point favorite. So why were the numbers so low?
</P>
<P>
   Blame the supposed Duke juggernaut and the overall lackluster
tournament. Of the 63 games, only one went into overtime, only 14
were decided by 5 points or fewer, and 17 were blowouts of 20
points or more.
</P>
<P>
   We have come to expect buzzer-beaters in the NCAAs. Last year,
20 games were within a 5-point spread, five were settled in
overtime, and only 11 were decided by 20 points or more.
</P>
<P>
   The semifinals were another story. Saturday's doubleheader is
supposed to build interest among casual fans for Monday night's
championship game. It didn't this year, largely because of the
lunatic du jour, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Male viewers turned to cable news channels in record numbers to
watch the bombings. MSNBC, CNBC, Headline News, CNN, and Fox News
attracted record numbers, mostly men. Between 5 p.m. and 11 p.m. on
Saturday, male viewers between the ages of 18-49 increased by a
total of 233 percent. The number for men between ages 25 to 54, the
most prized demographic for advertisers, skyrocketed by a
staggering 300 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While the cable universe is smaller than networks, the impact on
the NCAA was noticeable. The Monday night championship game went up
against pro wrestling on USA and TNT. In case anyone is keeping
score, pro wrestling usually provides the top five weekly cable
programs, and eight of the top 12. Each program attracts about 4
million households, mostly young men.
</P>
<P>
   Cable or network, those numbers are significant, especially
considering the Neilsen methodology. Its fact gathering, for
example, doesn't include out-of-home viewers, which doesn't make an
ounce of sense, largely because people tend to watch big-time
sporting events in groups.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Neilsen had installed a meter in the mobbed gyms at Duke
and UConn _ which it didn't _ the total number would have been two
households. Never mind that at least 10,000 people jammed in to
watch their schools. Ask yourself the following questions: When was
the last time you watched a Super Bowl alone? When was the last
time you watched ``Baywatch'' with a group of friends?
</P>
<P>
   CBS's Jim Nantz said he was disappointed by the numbers, but
still considered it a classic game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so special,'' Nantz said. ``No one ran away with it.
You got the feeling all night that it would go down to the wire. I
wished more people could have seen it. It was something to behold.
It was surreal. There were kids crying for joy and sadness, kids
holding hands, praying. There were genuine feelings, raw emotions
that you just don't see every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nantz is correct. With the exception of Hartford (49.7 rating
and 66 share) and Raleigh (36.2 rating and 49 share), a lot of
people just didn't see it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
