<HEADLINE>
MORE JOURNALISTS IN SURVEY AGREE WITH PRESS CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JUKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have met the enemy and it is us.
</P>
<P>
   That's the crucial finding in a new survey of 552 journalists
and news executives conducted by The Pew Research Center For the
People &AMP; the Press. A decade ago, for example, only about one-third
of news media professionals cited a lack of credibility with the
public as a major cause of declining news audiences. In the Pew
study released Tuesday, that number rose significantly, to about 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the big story is that journalists are beginning to
acknowledge the criticism of the press,'' said Pew Research Center
director Andrew Kohut, who finds ``the convergence of the public's
views of journalism and the journalists' views of journalism'' the
most striking aspect of the survey.
</P>
<P>
   This tough internal critique comes at a time of technological,
financial, and professional turmoil in the news industry. New
technologies _ such as the Internet and cable _ are ascendant,
while newspaper and network television news audiences steadily
erode. Sensational and salacious stories like the O. J. trial and
Lewinsky scandal seem to dominate the information landscape. And an
ever-louder drumbeat of professional media criticism and public
anger resonates in the ears of many journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalists are a lot more self-critical of the profession
than they used to be. They are critical of themselves in the same
way the public is critical of them,'' added Tom Rosenstiel,
vice-chairman of the Committee of Concerned Journalists, which
helped fund the study and design the questions.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 70 percent of the print, radio, TV, and Internet
journalists polled by Pew cite the blurring of lines between
reporting and commentary as a valid criticism of their business.
Nearly three-quarters of the newsroom staffers complain that news
outlets are too preoccupied with entertainment. (In that same vein,
solid majorities of those quizzed reject the notion that Geraldo
Rivera, Matt Drudge, and Larry King are fellow journalists.) And
nearly 60 percent of the respondents said national news
organizations gave too much play to the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large majority of news professionals sense a degradation of
the culture of news _ from one that was steeped in verification and
a steadfast respect for the facts toward one that favors argument,
opinion-mongering, haste, and infotainment,'' declared a Committee
of Concerned Journalists analysis of the data.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone greeted the Pew findings as gospel. Chicago Tribune
editor Howard Tyner, admittedly ``not a big fan of Pew,''
acknowledged that ``crediblity is clearly an issue and the public's
perception of the media is colored, at least in part, by
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But he worries about the media's tendency toward
self-flagellation and cautioned that ``I don't think (public
criticism) is grounds for us to be beating our chests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be listening to the public,'' said USA Today
editor David Mazzarella, who nevertheless is more bullish on the
media's performance. ``As for my own personal assessment of the
press, I think it's quite credible,'' he added. ``It just seems
that there's been this crescendo over time, particularly in the
past year, of breastbeating on the part of the presss.''
</P>
<P>
   One source of journalists' discomfort illuminated in the Pew
study is the growing fear about the impact of the bottom line on
the quality of journalism. Roughly 40 percent of the sample views
business and financial pressure as the most important problem
facing the news industry. In the past four years, the percentage of
those who say bottom- line demands have harmed news coverage has
risen from 37 percent to 53 percent among national TV and radio
personnel and from 24 percent to 46 percent among local electronic
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a large majority of newsroom staffers think the
buyouts of news organizations by diversified corporations and the
purchase of local newspapers by large chains are bad for
journalism, a sentiment not as widely shared by their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew survey also points up some areas of substantial
disconnect between the media and the public. Nearly 90 percent of
the media professionals polled believe press criticism of political
leaders prevents the pols from stepping out of line. Less than 60
percent of the public agrees.
</P>
<P>
   People in the news business say the primary cause of shrinking
news audiences is Americans who are overloaded with information.
But only 28 percent of the public cites that issue as a factor in
how they consume news. At the same time, only about one-third of
those at the national news media and less than half those at local
news outlets believe they ought to pay a great deal of attention to
the public's interests when deciding what to cover.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the survey does reveal a media culture that seems far
more inclined to acknowledge public attitudes and particularly,
criticism. The larger question, in many minds, is whether this
becomes a catalyst for serious reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more than navel gazing,'' said Kohut. ``This is
coming after Lewinsky. I think the press is in a place where it
sees itself under fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey means ``that journalists are going to be accepting of
change,'' added Rosenstiel. ``The question is which change are they
going to be accepting.''
</P>
<P>
   One interested observer is Jan Schaffer, executive director of
the Pew Center for Civic Journalism, which oversees a major media
reform movement. The journalists' self-criticism doesn't surprise
her, but ``to have it formally ratified in authoritative studies
adds more heft to the fire,'' she acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   But Schaffer is less certain that this dissatisfaction will
translate into meaningful change. ``I still think there is a great
(tendency) in the profession to not do what we say,'' she noted.
``And I don't know why that is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
