<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-GEOGHEGAN-ART     03-31 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-GEOGHEGAN-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS GEOGHEGAN: ON THE SIDE OF LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The hardest part of being Thomas Geoghegan
may be having to endure the things people say about you.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough being a labor lawyer in an era when management's
not only owner but king. It's that much worse having to squeeze
time from your practice to write two critically acclaimed works of
nonfiction, ``Which Side Are You On?'' (1991) and ``The Secret
Lives of Citizens,'' published last month. But what's hardest of
all _ or at least for someone as relentlessly modest as Geoghegan _
is all the praise you keep getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom is in a special class,'' declares a fellow Chicagoan,
author Studs Terkel, who's a client of Geoghegan's firm. ``He's an
American that you dream Americans should be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my idea of a self-made man,'' adds Harvard political
scientist Samuel H. Beer, who taught Geoghegan as an undergraduate.
``More than any man I know, he's made himself who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kinsley, the editor of the on-line magazine Slate and a
friend of Geoghegan's since college, says, ``He's extremely nice,
extremely decent, extremely devoted to causes outside himself, and
extremely talented.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware of how Pollyannaish his words sound, Kinsley hastens to
add a qualifier. ``I can say all the obvious things, and they're
all true, but what I'm not capturing is the weirdness of the
combination.'' ``Weirdness'' may be an understatement, actually.
</P>
<P>
   Law school attracts few people with so intensely literary a
sensibility. Kinsley likens Geoghegan (pronounced GAY-gun) to a
novelist, Beer calls him a poet, and next month his first play _ a
romantic comedy, no less, that one Geoghegan friend describes as
``When Harry Met Sally at the Union Hall'' _ opens in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Few Harvard Law School graduates have blue-collar clients. Few
people on the left are practicing Catholics, and even fewer
demonstrate such a penchant for irony.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Ed Sadlowski, who has known Geoghegan since 1976, when
he worked in Sadlowski's campaign for the presidency of the United
Steelworkers, comes closest to suggesting how sweeping an arc his
friend traverses. ``He'll be reading Plato one night, then go to a
ballgame with me the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs fans do need to be philosophical (their team has gone even
longer without winning a World Series than the Red Sox have), but
Platonism is not part of the labor-lawyer stereotype: a beefy guy
with a big voice who chews on a stogie while being driven around in
velour-upholstered comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's true Geoghegan enjoys the occasional cigar, but any
resemblance ends there. He has a lanky runner's frame and a long,
bony face that manages somehow to look both youthful and old
(Geoghegan's 50, but when the light hits him right he could pass
for a Rogaine-ready 35). He doesn't have a lawyer's face _ it's too
open. Neither is it a scholar's face _ it's too sly. Call it a
monsignor's face, one that's equal parts experienced and innocent,
precise and dreamy, of this world and beyond it.
</P>
<P>
   It's an appropriate face, actually, for someone with so divided
a personality. The phrase ``Capra hero'' tends to crop up when
people talk about Geoghegan. And, yes, he's a clean-cut,
still-somewhat-boyish idealist fighting the good fight out in the
heartland. But rather than being the title character in ``Mr. Smith
Goes to Chicago,'' he might more accurately be said to star in
``It's a Wonderful Life (If You Call This Living).'' Geoghegan
isn't Jefferson Smith. He's George Bailey, a man trapped by his own
goodness _ and made immeasurably more interesting by the resultant
tension between his capacity for doing the right thing and his
not-inconsiderable urge to indulge himself just as much as the rest
of us do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This internal struggle helps drive ``Which Side Are You On?,''
which is fitting, insofar as that book is as much memoir as
polemic. The new book is far more polemic, or even meditation, than
memoir, so Geoghegan dwells far less on this in-house debate
between duty and indulgence. That doesn't mean it's gone away,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the idea of being a lawyer,'' he says, but the emphasis
lies on ``idea.'' ``Part of me is tired of doing it. At the moment,
the practice is good. We've got some really interesting cases in
the office. But would I like to chuck it and go to Europe for a
year? Yeah. Does it seem pretty silly to me that I'm doing this
when I don't have a wife and kids and I don't have anybody to put
through college yet I'm still grinding it out? Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-doubt may have its drawbacks from the sufferer's point of
view, but there are few better antidotes to stridency or
self-righteousness. Certainly, Geoghegan exhibits neither failing.
Hard as he can be on Republicans and union busting and the
latter-day failings of US society generally, he is far harder _ not
to mention far funnier _ on himself.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls, for example, the time he was an intern at The New
Republic (this would have been shortly after the Watergate
break-in) and an editor suggested he might want to follow up on the
burglary, even at the expense of more policy-oriented topics.
Geoghegan describes his aghast response. ``You really . . . you
really think, this break-in . . . is more important than revenue
sharing?'' It takes a certain kind of individual, by no means
common, to have said such a thing in 1972. It takes an even rarer
one to tell the story on himself 27 years later.
</P>
<P>
   A constant awareness of the absurd carbonates Geoghegan's
writing. In the new book especially, he portrays political activism
as a kind of sweet, sad comedy, one that's no less serious an
enterprise for being faintly ridiculous. To be sure, the comedy is
often quite dark. ``The Secret Lives of Citizens'' is as explicitly
a lament as it is implicitly an exhortation. The book celebrates a
golden age that grows ever more distant (the New Deal). It mourns a
hero who died too young (Chicago's African-American mayor, Harold
Washington). It decries afflictions so manifold they run the gamut
from the US Senate to resident-only parking (as Geoghegan
demonstrates, each is inherently antidemocratic and inimical to the
civic ideal).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
