<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0844 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE01-COX     03-31 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spring into cleaning with kitchen touch-up
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, Martha Stewart can knock off that spring cleaning list in
no time flat. She has about 87,000 people at her beck and call and,
by golly, they darn well better do what she says.
</P>
<P>
   But for the average person, even with an extra hand or two
pitching in, all that rug beating and house hosing can be a bit
daunting.
</P>
<P>
   A good way to get the most out of a precious springtime energy
surge is to direct it at one project where it will do the most
good. But what to choose when so much around a winter-weary house
needs rejuvenation?
</P>
<P>
   Just take a good look under your kitchen sink and you will have
the answer. Alarmed? Don't be.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has dozens of professional kitchen organizers and
experts to take you step by painless step through a process that
will continue to reap benefits throughout the year and well into
the next. You may even enjoy yourself knowing you can do your
household no better favor than get that kitchen straightened out
and humming.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Cheever, a kitchen expert who is a consultant for the
National Kitchen and Bath Association, begins on
www.csz.com/hih/hrr/jul96/orgkitch.html by suggesting that Saturday
afternoon is usually the ideal time for undertaking kitchen
reorganization projects. Then she gets down to business by telling
you to remove everything from the kitchen cabinets and sort it into
three categories, according to where the items are used.
</P>
<P>
   She goes through each category and each item, and by the time
you are done you will probably know more about how your kitchen
works than you did before.
</P>
<P>
   But before you decide to go with that site, check out www
</P>
<P>
   .123sortit.com/RO/, which is called ``Sort It'' and click under
``kitchen.'' Here the experts take an even more supervisory,
step-by-step approach. Do this, do that, then do this. They even
schedule a couple of coffee breaks saying, ``See you in 10
minutes.'' When you finish a task, you get praise, virtual pats on
the back and, all in all, have a pretty good time.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites to help you get it done:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An excellent article on spring cleaning in general plus a good
list of spring cleaning chores is at pages.prodigy.com
</P>
<P>
   /getolife/spring.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You may want to check out and bookmark ``Organized Home,'' a
monthly webzine at organizedhome.com/ that is chock-full of good
tips on home organizing in general. This month has a pretty good
spring cleaning list of things to do around the house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pick up some tips from professional organizers at
</P>
<P>
   www.organized-living.com/aboutpo.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't miss home.fuse.net/grandmashouse/orgkitc.htm, a personal
essay that makes you think you're talking to your next door
neighbor on the subject of kitchen organizing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Grand Plan'' for cleaning your house is at
shell.surfsouth.com/(tilde)sdove/theplan.html.
</P>
<P>
   When you're done, a great way to celebrate the season and your
brand spanking clean and organized kitchen is to prepare a recipe
from www.macronews.com/siddish.html. The author of an essay urges
us to eat in harmony with the seasons.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Barley Soup With Mushrooms and Leeks
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 cups
</P>
<P>
   Soaking time: 1 hour to overnight Preparation time: 15 minutes
Cooking time: 50-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Karen Claffey at www.macronews.com/siddish.html says this soup
from her cookbook ``Fast &AMP; Fun Food'' brings renewed creativity and
``enhances our condition to flow with the energy of spring.''
</P>
<P>
   1cup pearl barley, sorted and washed
</P>
<P>
   8cups water, divided
</P>
<P>
   8ounces mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2medium leeks, white and green parts, divided and sliced
</P>
<P>
   2green onions, white and green parts, divided and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon dried oregano or 3 tablespoons chopped fresh
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon sea salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2to 3 tablespoons barley miso (at health food stores), to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup minced fresh dill or Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   In a 3-quart soup pot, soak barley in 2 cups water at least 1
hour and up to overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Over medium-high heat, add 6 cups water to the pot and bring to
a boil. Reduce heat to low and simmer for 30 minutes or until
barley is tender. Add mushrooms, white part of the leeks and green
onions, dried oregano (if using; if using fresh, add it later) and
sea salt. Return to a boil and simmer for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add leek greens and simmer for 1 or 2 minutes, until bright
green and tender. Remove 1/2 cup broth from the pot and put in a
small bowl. Add miso and dissolve any lumps. Pour the miso broth
into the pot and simmer 3 to 4 minutes. Adjust seasonings to taste.
Add fresh oregano (if using), green parts of green onions and dill.
Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 119 calories, 4 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 5), 26 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 346
milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
