<HEADER>
A0845 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-LAMB-ART-BOS &LR;      03-31 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-LAMB-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTER LAMB MAKES A TASTY DAY-AFTER TOPPING FOR LINGUINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Includes recipes)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Spring is entwined with religious and cultural icons, all
symbols of new life. Eggs and tulips play a part in this rebirth,
and so does lamb.
</P>
<P>
   In Christian iconography, lamb had a religious significance on
the table, but the meat had a practical aspect as well. Newborn
lambs were available at the end of the long Lenten fast. That they
became the centerpiece of the Easter table was, if nothing else,
logical.
</P>
<P>
   Today, families aren't sustained by their own land, and spring
lambs are hardly available. Yet the tradition persists. We eat lamb
(and very good lamb at that) raised in Colorado and Texas. Though
it may be labeled ``spring,'' it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to hang the label on everything _ even if it's eight
months old,'' says John Dewar of John Dewar &AMP; Co., a wholesale and
retail butcher. Genuine spring lamb, he says, is a month or two
old, and the whole lamb can weigh less than 20 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   So the leg of lamb on the Easter table is probably not genuine
spring and certainly didn't graze outside your farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that today's legs of lamb are bigger than those of
genuine spring lambs (American lamb legs weigh from 7 to 10 pounds)
means leftover roast lamb. Cold lamb sandwiches with French
mustard, diced lamb under a bed of mashed potatoes in a mock
shepherd's pie, or lamb tossed with pasta. Paul Sussman, chef of
Daddy-O's restaurant in Cambridge, Mass., adds Swiss chard to the
linguine, along with lentils and the diced lamb. The idea came from
an old James Beard book in which Beard combined lentils in a soup
with Swiss chard and lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   The rainbow chard he gets now has stems that are yellow, orange,
and red, and unless they're quite tough, he chops them along with
the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Sussman's roast lamb sits overnight in a Mediterranean marinade,
made from lemon juice, olive oil, white wine, garlic, and marjoram.
``The leg is pretty tender to begin with,'' he says. ``I have my
doubts whether marinating tenderizes the meat.''
</P>
<P>
   He does it for the flavor. ``The flavors penetrate. When it
roasts up, particularly with the olive oil in the marinade, you get
a crisper crust.''
</P>
<P>
   Sussman can't serve the leg whole in his restaurant, but he does
use the same marinade for pieces of lamb served shish kebab style.
</P>
<P>
   The leg isn't harmed by the second cooking, because he pulls it
from the oven when it's medium-rare. That way, he says, if the
potatoes and the rest of the dinner aren't quite ready, the lamb
can sit on the stove and wait for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long, though. Lenten rules might not be as strict as
they once were, so guests aren't as desperate for a succulent
roast. Still, the smell of the leg of lamb is incredibly inviting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
PAUL SUSSMAN'S MARINATED ROAST LEG OF LAMB WITH NEW POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   For the lamb:
</P>
<P>
   1 7- to 10-pound leg of lamb
</P>
<P>
   1 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest and juice of 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 cloves garlic, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped fresh marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the potatoes:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds new potatoes (about 1 1/2 to 2 inches in diameter)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Trim the lamb of excess fat. In a roasting pan that will hold
the lamb snugly, combine the oil, wine, lemon zest and juice,
onion, garlic, and marjoram. Add the lamb and turn it over in the
liquid to moisten the surface of the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate for at least 6 hours and
as long as overnight, turning the lamb several times.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the lamb from the refrigerator 2 hours before cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven at 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the lamb from the marinade, and sprinkle it with salt and
pepper. Set the lamb on a rack inside a roasting pan and transfer
it to the oven. Roast the lamb, basting it with the marinade, for 1
1/4 hours or until a meat thermometer inserted into the thickest
part of the lamb registers 135 degrees, for medium-rare lamb (let
the leg cook 10 minutes longer for pink meat).
</P>
<P>
   When the lamb has been cooking for 15 minutes, roast the
potatoes. Without peeling them, cut them into eighths. In a bowl,
toss them with oil, salt, and pepper. Spread them on a rimmed
baking sheet, skin side down. Roast them for 1 hour or until they
are crisp on the outside and tender inside.
</P>
<P>
   Carve the lamb into slices and arrange it on a platter with the
roasted potatoes. Serve at once with hearty greens tossed with
walnuts and black-currant vinaigrette (below). Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEARTY GREENS WITH WALNUTS
</P>
<P>
   AND BLACK-CURRANT VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons black-currant vinegar (or substitute balsamic)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons walnut oil or light olive oil
</P>
<P>
   8 cups mixed greens (watercress, frisee, Belgian endive,
radicchio, and romaine lettuce)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup walnut halves, toasted until golden
</P>
<P>
   1 cup homemade croutons
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, mix together the vinegar, salt, and pepper. Slowly
whisk in the oil, a little at a time.
</P>
<P>
   In a salad bowl, combine the greens. Scatter the walnuts and
croutons on top. Drizzle the greens with half the dressing and toss
well. Add enough additional dressing to coat the greens lightly.
Add more salt and pepper to taste, and serve at once. Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAMB WITH LENTILS, SWISS CHARD, AND LEMON OVER LINGUINE
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup French lentils
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch rainbow or red Swiss chard, rinsed thoroughly and
coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Juice of a lemon
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 cups leftover lean lamb, cut into 3/4-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound linguine
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Add the lentils and cook
them for 25 minutes or until they are tender. Drain them into a
colander.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse the pan and refill it with water. Sprinkle it with salt
and bring it to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, heat a large skillet. Add the oil and cook the onion
over low heat for 10 minutes. Turn up the heat and add the Swiss
chard, garlic, salt, black pepper, and cayenne pepper. Cook for 1
minute, stirring constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Add the lentils and lemon juice and simmer 5 minutes. Taste for
seasoning and add more salt, if you like. Sprinkle the lamb over
the top, turn off the heat, and cover the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the linguine in the boiling water for 6 minutes or until it
is tender but still has some bite. Drain it and divide it among 4
dinner plates. With a fork, make a well in the center of each
serving of pasta. Stir the lamb into the lentils and greens and
ladle the sauce onto each plate. Serve at once. Serves 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
