<HEADER>
A0847 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TEN-THINGS-BOS &LR;      03-31 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TEN-THINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN `TAMING' OFFERS AT LEAST 10 THINGS TO LIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
10 THINGS I HATE ABOUT YOU 
Directed by: Gil Junger 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``10 Things I Hate About You,'' Shakespeare meets the
teensploitation movie. But hold the groans. This rejiggering of
``The Taming of the Shrew'' for the high school set is a bright,
charming, refreshing surprise. Smartly written, lofted into orbit
by a heads-up ensemble performance, it's bursting with new talent
on both sides of the camera. The memories of high school sexual and
other politics are recent enough to the scriptwriting team of Karen
McCullah Lutz and Kirsten Smith for the duo to have nailed them
perfectly, while infusing the situation with believable romance and
even the odd tidbit of Shakespeare. It's a great mix and will
surely make ``10 Things'' the Easter holiday date movie of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most remarkable of all is that they have found ways to
get around the fact that Petruchio's grinding down of the spirited
Kat, with all the weight of a patriarchal society behind him, is
such a minefield as to be virtually unplayable. Julia Stiles's Kat
is no shrew. Her declaration of independence is invigorating and
sounds more Shavian than Shakespearean. It's just that her
hard-line feminism makes her a little tough to take. The film's
Petruchio doesn't muscle her into submission, but wins her with
sensitivity and imaginative wooing. The script genuflects to
Shakespeare in its choice of the male lead's name, Patrick Verona.
And, perhaps, you won't be surprised to hear that the Seattle-area
high school they attend is called Padua.
</P>
<P>
   Heath Ledger's romantic lead is a guy who's a little older than
the other students, a little cooler, with a mysterious past and a
sullen outlaw appeal. The script wisely never has him attempt to
overpower Kat in any way. Ledger's Verona suggests Patrick Swayze
with an Aussie accent, although he rises to a Gene Kelly moment in
his most charming scene. He woos Kat in public by dancing up and
down the concrete risers in a football stadium, beaming smiles at
her while dodging security. Stiles's Kat, meanwhile, has the
wittiest lines in the witty script, leaving no doubt of her
rapierlike intelligence, nor of the fact that her ferocious
exterior is also a defense for a softer Kat beneath _ just as
Patrick's cool-guy moves mask his gentler side.
</P>
<P>
   The teen romance stuff doesn't go anywhere surprising; rather,
it's the fullness and deftness with which it travels that makes for
such a satisfying hour and a half. The characters are better drawn
than in most films, teen or so-called adult. Larisa Oleynik's
Bianca, forbidden to begin dating until Kat does, not only sets the
plot mechanics in motion, but emerges more appealingly than in most
conventional Shakespearean productions, which settle for painting
Bianca as a bit of a twit. Joseph Gordon-Levitt, who suggests a
young Timothy Hutton, brings charm and savvy to the role of the guy
who falls for Bianca and pushes along the Let's-get-Kat-a-date
project. David Krumholtz, as his comic sidekick, is another big
plus, and so is Susan May Pratt, as the cute girl he has his eye on
and chases, with an assist by Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is advanced in that it refuses to make a fool or dummy
of the only parent in the film, Larry Miller's single father of Kat
and Bianca. He has his comic moments, but on the whole is drawn
with a tenderness and humanity that Shakespeare never gave his
equivalent in the play. What this film shares with Shakespeare is a
drive toward reconciliation; this is a film that likes its
characters. It's humane as well as clever. This is probably the
time to praise director Gil Junger, making his film debut after a
career in TV. When as many of the performances work as well as they
do here, he must have had something to do with it. ``10 Things I
Hate About You'' is a serendipitous convergence of romance and wit.
Even the high school, a huge red brick faux chateau high on a
hilltop overlooking Puget Sound, takes on a star aura. I loved ``10
Things I Hate About You.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
