<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0849 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKMAN-COLUMN-COX     03-31 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKMAN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's the American way: Our involvement in Kosovo has to do with
who we think we are
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The explanation for U.S. involvement in Kosovo _ and for its
apparent failure to date _ does not really lie in lofty talk of
strategy, diplomacy or geopolitics. It lies in the creation myths
that help bind a nation together.
</P>
<P>
   The American creation myth revolves around our war against King
George, around Valley Forge and the Declaration of Independence. It
is an inspirational tale of democracy in triumph over tyranny, of
the United States as an international beacon of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian creation myth is ancient by comparison, dating to
1389. That year, the Christian Serb army was routed at a place
called Kosovo by an Islamic army, and the loss condemned the Serbs
to centuries of humiliating foreign occupation. Through those dark
centuries, the Serbs celebrated their own stubbornness and capacity
for suffering by retelling the tale of Kosovo in song and poetry,
nurturing their sense of aggrieved nationhood through story.
</P>
<P>
   This, then, is the clash between those two national myths,
American and Serb, one optimistic and humane, the other dark and
defensive. And the medium that brought them into conflict has been
a storyteller of a different sort: television.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the Serbs have used terror and brutality in a
campaign to wipe ethnic Albanians, most of them Muslim, from
Kosovo. Scenes of Serb atrocities, broadcast on American
television, have had a predictable effect on U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
   We Americans like to think of ourselves as a humane and giving
people, too decent to stand by and let a bully brutalize a
powerless victim. In addition, U.S. military technology deludes us
into thinking that the dirty work of war can be done from a
sanitary, impersonal distance, with cruise missiles fired from
hundreds of miles away and bombs dropped at night from invisible
planes thousands of feet high.
</P>
<P>
   That illusion creates a startling dichotomy. Last weekend, TV
news was dominated by reports that a single American plane had been
downed. Hundreds of personnel and billions of dollars' worth of
equipment were mobilized to rescue the pilot, and broadcasters
pondered what impact the event might have on U.S. policy,
particularly if the pilot had died or was captured.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast with Serbia was stark. Each night, Serb parents
huddle in bomb shelters wondering whether they and their children
would survive the night's bombing. And each morning, they emerge
more supportive of the war than ever.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, we may have air power, but the Serbs have
commitment. And commitment might well prove more powerful. In fact,
with thousands of Albanians fleeing Kosovo each hour, our tepid
attempt to validate our national myth may turn out to be a disaster
even for those in whose defense we have acted.
</P>
<P>
   This is a bad situation, and it has become all too familiar. We
are captives of a new dynamic: Our humanitarian instincts are
easily provoked by a worldwide communication system that operates
as both a nagging conscience and an international 911 line. And our
status as the world's only superpower makes it temptingly easy to
act, flying off like an international Superman to right injustice
and protect the weak.
</P>
<P>
   That combination has driven us to action in Somalia, Haiti,
Bosnia and other hot spots. The only way to avoid future such
entanglements would be to ignore all pleas for U.S. intervention,
even in cases involving mass killings. But that option isn't open
to us, not if we're the nation we believe ourselves to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, critics of our policy toward Kosovo may be correct:
It may not work. It's a hard fact of life that sometimes you do the
right thing, and you fail anyway. If so _ if the Serbs choose to
absorb the NATO bombing as part of the price they have to pay for
taking Kosovo _ do we take the next step and commit ground troops?
</P>
<P>
   That decision will be debated in high-flown terms of strategy,
its impact on our relations with Russia, and other concerns. While
important, those issues will not decide the matter. Instead, the
decision will probably be driven by another central aspect of our
national character:
</P>
<P>
   We don't like to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bookman is associate editorial page editor of The Atlanta
Constitution. e-mail: jbookman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
