<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0850 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-GEILS-BOS &LR;      03-31 0277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GEILS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOLF ON THE PROWL: J. GEILS BAND REUNITES FOR TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We want to create a celebration of what we accomplished. I
feel excited that we can go out and do it again,'' Peter Wolf said
Tuesday, discussing the J. Geils Band reunion tour that is finally
on after years of maybes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this progresses further than the tour, hopefully it can
lead to more great Geils music,'' said Wolf, referring to the
tour's confirmed kickoff at the Tweeter Center for the Performing
Arts June 23 and 24. (Tickets go on sale Saturday at noon through
Ticketmaster.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little surreal, but exciting. I'm as anxious as the
next person to see how it all pans out,'' said Geils keyboardist
Seth Justman, noting that it's been 16 years since the group last
performed. ``They said it couldn't be done,'' he said of the
reunion, which is being pulled together with help from John Baruck,
REO Speedwagon's manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why now? I'd answer it by saying why not now?'' Wolf said of
the reconnection with Justman, guitarist J. Geils, harpist Magic
Dick, and bassist Danny Klein. (Drummer Stephen Jo Bladd has
declined to tour.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been wanting this for a long time. I still get
e-mails about what the Geils band meant to people,'' said Wolf, who
said the group will dig out such radio classics as ``Freeze
Frame,'' ``Centerfold,'' ``Love Stinks,'' and ``Detroit
Breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The group plans to keep its top ticket price at $39.50, a
bargain for today's rock reunions. ``We tried hard to keep the
ticket prices down,'' said Wolf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0855 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEOGHEGAN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-A     03-31 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEOGHEGAN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 CAMBRIDGE, Mass.: ... civic ideal).  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still, there is laughter in the book, and not a little of it,
for Geoghegan recognizes the silliness intrinsic to so much of what
citizenship entails (attend planning board meetings? gather
signatures? vote?). More important, he has written a book that,
superficial appearances to the contrary, is profoundly affirming _
an affirmation of the greatness of so much of this country's past
in this century, an affirmation of that past's relevance to its
possible greatness in the next _ and few mundane acts are as
inherently affirming as laughter. ``Pursuing the Promise of
American Life'' is the subtitle of ``The Secret Lives of
Citizens.'' Its author, a great admirer of the Czech novelist Milan
Kundera, could just as easily have paraphrased a Kundera title and
used ``The Book of Laughter and Remembering.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Geoghegan grew up in inauspicious surroundings for a celebrant
of the New Deal. Not only is Cincinnati the home of Robert Taft,
cosponsor of the labor movement's greatest bane, the Taft-Hartley
Act, it's the largest US city Franklin Roosevelt never carried.
``It was like being a French Huguenot to be a Democrat in
Cincinnati,'' Geoghegan says. ``It was a foretaste of the America
to come, and I didn't like it. So I went east.''
</P>
<P>
   He means Harvard, which he remembers as an immersion in
17th-century English history and literature (``I almost became a
Calvinist,'' he says, perhaps not altogether facetiously). What he
calls ``my claim to fame'' as an undergraduate was serving as
deputy to future New York Times op-ed columnist Frank Rich when
Rich ran The Harvard Crimson editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only did one truly bad thing,'' Geoghegan confesses. ``One
week when I was in charge, an invitation came to a cocktail party
because they were going to shoot a movie called `Love Story' here
in Cambridge. I was thinking, `Oh, that's a good thing for Frank to
go to,' when a voice inside me said, `Don't put it in Frank's box.'
So I got drunk with Ali MacGraw and Ryan O'Neal. It was a very
strange evening.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1971, Geoghagen had his New Republic stint.
Then came law school, with time aside for another tour at The New
Republic. He worked for the United Mine Workers in Washington,
D.C., and then the Sadlowski campaign in Chicago. He served in the
Department of Energy in the Carter administration. During those
days of malaise and moral equivalents of war, DOE was the grim
ground zero of Carterism (if such a thing there was), and after two
years of it Geoghegan was ready to get away as far and fast as he
could. New York? Boston? The West Coast? ``I thought, `If you're
going to be an American, you've got to do it all the way,' '' so he
returned to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   He joined a law firm headed by Leon Despres, a reform alderman
and local legend who today, at 91, is, as Geoghegan happily
declares, ``not even semi-retired, thank God'' (``Secret Lives'' is
dedicated to Despres). There's one other lawyer besides the two of
them, and ``nobody screens the calls,'' Geoghegan sighs, ``because
that's part of the office's policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simultaneously do this big-case stuff and also have this .
. . friends-and-neighbors sort of practice. You can do one or the
other, but trying to do both is maddening, and I have been trying
to do both over the years. So there's a lot of people who call up
for small legal problems. Then other people who are calling up,
`I'd like to bring a $25 million class action.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's one case Geoghegan pursued that people still talk about
_ with characteristic self-deprecation, he notes that it did put
the back of his head, if not his face, on Page 1 of the Chicago
Tribune _ an epic, seven-year battle to get 2,500 former
steelworkers the pension benefits they lost when International
Harvester pulled an extremely slick deal to divest itself of
Wisconsin Steel, where the men worked. In the end, Geoghegan got
his clients a $14.8 million settlement. He still regrets having
gotten them so little. Others marvel that he got them anything at
all. ``People wanted to abandon it,'' Sadlowski says, ``but Tom was
like a tenacious dog.''
</P>
<P>
   That tenacity points to what may be the weirdest element in the
Geoghegan combination: how such a true believer has never lost
himself in the abstractions of ideology, never given up his faith
in doing _ or at least trying. ``I'm emphatic about how important
it is to try,'' he says. ``That is the overwheming message of the
new book . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just enough to try in the romantic sense _ you know,
just noble tries. I'm half German, on my mother's side, and half
Irish, on my father's side. I think there is an element of the
German romantic that says how important it is to try, but there is
an element of the Irish politician that also says how important it
is to win. The noble gesture isn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a case with a lawyer once. We were in it halfway
through, and he said to me, `You know, when we started this I
thought you had in mind just taking a principled stand on
something. But I'm beginning to realize, to my horror, you're
trying to win this!' It was the nicest thing anybody ever said to
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
