<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR INTENSIFIES, BUT TARGETS ARE SMALLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As tales of violence in Kosovo increase each day,
so, too, do promises by NATO officials to ``intensify military
efforts.'' But with few hard statistics or details of each day's
attacks, military analysts are left to wonder: Is NATO keeping its
word?
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence it is. In addition to some 400 NATO warplanes
positioned to attack Yugoslavia since last Wednesday, the United
States this week announced it was sending over a new batch of
fighters, including five Air Force B-1 bombers and five EA-6B Navy
aircraft, known as Prowlers, which are radar-jamming planes
designed to confuse enemy antiaircraft systems.
</P>
<P>
   Ten refueling tankers are also on their way, Pentagon officials
said. Airstrikes, which at first took place only during the night,
are now being delivered around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   And the aircraft carrier USS Theodore Roosevelt, which left its
dock on the East Coast on Friday, is expected to arrive in the
Mediterranean Sea in a matter of days. Although the Roosevelt is
scheduled to continue on to the Persian Gulf for a six-month
rotation, several outside analysts and officials said the carrier,
equipped with some 75 warplanes, would probably make a stop in the
Adriatic Sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are clear indications that things are being stepped
up,'' said retired Colonel Joseph J. Collins, a senior fellow in
political military studies at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies in Washington. ``It's also clear, obviously,
that although we've done a lot,'' Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic ``has not yet reached his threshold. So stepping up our
activities clearly makes some sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The most convincing evidence may be the NATO target maps
themselves, according to defense analyst John Pike of the
Federation of American Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of the airstrikes, the maps showed NATO
warplanes mostly hitting previously known targets: airfields,
production plants, and manufacturing centers. The maps also
indicated sites where ethnic cleansing was taking place, mostly in
southern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, however, the previous ethnic-cleansing sites had
become NATO target sites _ a clear sign that allied forces were
zeroing on Serbian ground troops, Pike said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are clearly intensifying their efforts in several
respects,'' Pike said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also suspicions that NATO's military actions might
not be escalating as quickly as its rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said they believed the overriding fear of a US
pilot getting shot down is still driving the strategic planning,
citing as evidence the fact that the A-10 ground-attack planes have
not yet been used.
</P>
<P>
   The A-10, referred to as ``the Warthog'' and the ``flying
bathtub'' for its sturdiness and slow speed, has in recent days
been described as one of NATO's best assets in fighting small
groups of Serbian troops who are reportedly carrying out appalling
attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. Heavily armored, the A-10 is
equipped with both a low-altitude cannon and air-to-ground
missiles, and it flies low enough to target specific clusters of
troops.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also highly susceptible to being spotted by enemy
radar, analysts and officials said. And although Pentagon officials
have largely blamed the weather for not using the A-10, others
expressed concern that the pace is not picking up quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are intensifying, but not as quickly as I would
have advocated,'' said Senator John McCain, Republican of Arizona.
``But they are faced with a significant problem. And that is, you
cannot risk the loss of one American pilot. They are faced with the
problem of making sure they don't lose pilots or aircraft, and at
the same time, making sure that they inflict the maximum damage.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a member of the Senate Armed Services Committee, placed
some of the blame on NATO allies other than the United States,
saying he had been informed that US plans to attack a building that
housed the Yugoslav defense ministry had been vetoed by other NATO
nations.
</P>
<P>
   But another member of the Armed Services Committee, Senator Jack
Reed, Democrat of Rhode Island, was less critical of NATO for
executing what he called a ``very methodical plan,'' though he
acknowleged that it had only ``been disclosed in general terms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that they want to be careful about this,'' said
Reed. ``They are very concerned about the safety of the pilots
flying these missions. They don't want to rush into it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
