<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-CAMPAIGNS-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFECTIVENESS OF AIR WARS QUESTIONED ANEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Seven days into NATO's bombing campaign over
Yugoslavia, a question nearly as old as this century crops up once
again: Can you win a war, impose order, do much of anything, with
air power alone?
</P>
<P>
   If history provides clues, the answer seems to be: No, not
really _ unless you use atomic weapons (as at the end of World War
II) or unless the bombing is coordinated with soldiers fighting on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   NATO launched its present campaign with the idea of forcing
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to stop his aggression
against the Albanians in Kosovo, and shocking him back to the peace
table.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Robert Pape, professor of national-security studies at
Dartmouth College and author of the book ``Bombing to Win: Air
Power and Coercion in War,'' said in a telephone interview Tuesday,
``Bombing has never won a war or changed a state's behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Pape examined every air campaign in history _ from German
Zeppelin raids in 1914 to the US airstrikes over Iraq in 1991, with
World War II, Vietnam, and other conflicts in between _ and
concluded, ``Air power alone has never produced decisive effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Posen, a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology's security studies program, agreed: ``Officials use
bombing to try to affect the adversary's will or to punish him, but
most of these strategies don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the most successful air campaign of recent times, the
1991 US air war against Iraq, had its limits. The setting was ideal
for bombing. The Iraqis had buried their tanks in shallow shelters
in the sand, turning their entire army into a fixed target. The
desert landscape was flat and defenseless.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after a month of fierce bombing, a vast army of ground
troops was needed to push Saddam Hussein's warriors out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The brief air campaign against Iraq last December, designed to
punish Saddam Hussein for keeping United Nations inspectors away
from suspected weapons sites, seems to have had little effect
beyond hardening his resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam is the classic case of an air war that officials thought
at first would be easy, but quickly turned sour.
</P>
<P>
   President John F. Kennedy's chief military adviser, General
Maxwell Taylor, confidently wrote in a memo of November 1961,
``Nothing is more calculated to sober the enemy . . . than the
knowledge that the United States has prepared itself soundly to
deal with aggresssion in Southeast Asia at any level.''
</P>
<P>
   When the bombing started in full force in 1964, President Lyndon
B. Johnson's national security adviser, McGeorge Bundy, wrote in a
memo, ``The theory of this plan is that we should strike to hurt
but not to destroy, and strike for the purpose of changing the
North Vietnamese decision on intervention in the south,'' a theory
strikingly similar to President Clinton's current thinking behind
the Kosovo campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, the CIA reported, ``If anything, the strikes to
date have hardened'' North Vietnam's attitude, but then urged, ``We
must hit them harder, more frequently, and inflict greater
damage.''
</P>
<P>
   The advice was followed _ but, it seemed, 10 years and 59,000
American fatalities later, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, according to Pierre M. Sprey, a military
historian and former Pentagon official, ``Bombing has lengthened a
conflict. It causes the people being bombed to hate you _ a lot _
no matter what you claim your intentions are.''
</P>
<P>
   In Vietnam, during the ``pauses'' in the B-52 bombing campaigns,
the North Vietnamese had trouble getting people to repair roads and
bridges. However, once the bombing started again, volunteers
rallied.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, during World War II, before the Germans bombed London
and Coventry, British officials were worried about production rates
in local factories. The bombing galvanized the population, boosted
morale, and production soared.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies after the war showed the same thing had happened
in Germany. The Allies' intense bombing of Berlin and other cities
strengthened civilian support and industrial production for the
Nazi war machine.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, too, General Curtis LeMay's fire-bombing raids, which
destroyed whole towns, did little to dampen loyalty to the emperor
or determination to fight on. It took two atomic bombs, with their
unimaginable power, to do that, and nobody is talking about using
nuclear weapons against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the longtime US envoy on Yugoslav crises, has
argued that the NATO airstrikes in September 1995 directly
compelled the Serbs to sign the Dayton Accord, which fostered peace
in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   However, Pape said these airstrikes were preceded by a joint
Croatian and Muslim ground offensive that drove a half-million
Serbs out of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air power was just the icing on the cake,'' Pape said. The
strikes prevented the Serbs from providing reinforcements. As a
result, had the Muslim and Croat troops kept advancing, the
retreating Serbs could not have stopped them.
</P>
<P>
   Pape argues that, in general, airstrikes have decisive effects
only when combined in this way with ground troops. ``Pressure from
ground forces acts like an anvil,'' Pape said, ``forcing the
opponents to concentrate. Once they're concentrated, they're easier
to find, and easier to kill in large numbers, from the air.''
</P>
<P>
   In the struggle for Kosovo, NATO commanders have at their
disposal the A-10 attack plane, whose lethal 30-mm antiarmor
munitions destroyed more tanks than any other type of plane in the
1991 war against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   However, as long as Milosevic's troops can remain dispersed or
hidden, each A-10 sortie, no matter how well-executed, will have
very limited effects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1327EST &QL; 
