<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECOND COMING OF `STAR WARS'  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you noticed how the frenzy attending the release of the new
``Star Wars'' movie resembles Parousiamania? Yes, I thought you
had.
</P>
<P>
   Parousiamania, according to the Oxford English Dictionary, is
the ``excitement or frenzy aroused by the thought of the Parousia''
_ a New Testament Greek word referring to the ``arrival,'' or
Second Coming of Jesus Christ. Believing Christians live in
anticipation of this moment, the time of the Last Judgment and the
establishment of the Kingdom of Heaven on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Bible isn't clear on the timing of the Second Coming. As a
result, believers occasionally experience manic fits of
anticipation, especially in the months and years preceding a
millennium. How very odd that George Lucas has chosen the last
Easter Week of the millennium to dial up the promotional hype for
his new ``Star Wars'' episode, ``The Phantom Menace.'' Coincidence?
Or something more . . .
</P>
<P>
   In one respect, this analogy falls flat. Two thousand American
movie theaters have fixed the date for the arrival of ``The Phantom
Menace'' _ Wednesday, May 19. But in other ways, it holds up quite
well. Earlier this week, for instance, Lucas &AMP; Co. announced that
they wouldn't sell any advance tickets to avoid setting off a
bidding mania among crazed fans. So the loons who run the web site
http://starwars.
</P>
<P>
   countingdown.com started lining up Tuesday at Mann's Chinese in
Hollywood to buy ``Menace'' tickets!
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we have:
</P>
<P>
   --Gradual revelation: The unveiling of the two ``Star Wars''
trailers, one in November and one earlier this month, have
attracted more attention than most movies released during the same
period. The offical web site, http://starwars.com registered 3.5
million video downloads of the trailer during five days this month,
probably an Internet record.
</P>
<P>
   --Approved houses of worship: In a lengthy pronunciamento, 20th
Century Fox bossman Tom Sherak has declared that only certain,
specially qualified theaters will be allowed to show Lucas's
precious work: ``The film will play all digital formats, Dolby
Digital, DTS, and SDDS. If a theater is in a market that has
digital theaters but does not have digital sound, it will not play
in that theater.''
</P>
<P>
   --Speaking through the prophets: The New York Times dispatched
once-respected journalist Orville Schell to the Lucaslair, whence
he returned with the news that Lucas really, really loves his
children. In hot pursuit, CBS's Leslie Stahl gave Lucas 30 minutes
of prime airtime to reiterate his startling declaration of
unconditional love for his children.
</P>
<P>
   --Relics for sale: ``All four new `Star Wars' glass Christmas
ornaments are rendered with the old world craftmanship that has
made the Christopher Radko name world famous with collectors.
Crafted exactly as ornaments were a century ago, each unique piece
is individually mouth blown, silvered and hand painted, and
requires an entire week to create. Get ready to decorate your `Star
Wars' Christmas tree.'' Available for pre-order from the web site
at $20 each.
</P>
<P>
   --Canon Formation: Since 1994, Lucas's spokeswoman, Lynne Hale,
has been filming the making of ``The Phantom Menace.'' Working with
three recent graduates of Stanford University's film school, she
has shot more than 600 hours of must-see video, which can be
sampled at the web site.
</P>
<P>
   If you've read this far, you might find the ``Star Wars'' /
Parousia analogy stretched, or even offensive. Let me refer you to
the bible of ``Star Wars'' studies, Entertainment Weekly. EW
reports that in 1977, with the popularity of the ``Star Wars''
story rivaling that of you-know-who, director Francis Ford Coppola
``seriously proposed that Lucas start a religion, using the murkily
defined tenets of `the Force' as a central holy text.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was Francis's thing,'' Lucas told EW. ``I remember him
saying, `You know, you've got a certain amount of power in
politics. But religion! With religion, you really have power.' I
told him, `Forget it. I don't have any interest in power.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Are you reading this in the morning? Only 48 days and about 3
hours until the first showing!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
