<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORENSICS-ABUSE-BOS &LR;      03-31 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORENSICS-ABUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES SOFTEN TONE IN CHILD INTERVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERVILLE, Mass. _ A woman sits at a child-sized table in a
sparse room facing a young girl. They color, and talk casually
about dolls, starting kindergarten, and a favorite swing that goes
high enough to touch the trees.
</P>
<P>
   It could be preschool, except for what happens next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know why you came to talk to me?'' asks Stephanie
Brant, looking down as they both color.
</P>
<P>
   ``About Daddy,'' the 5-year-old answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did something happen with Daddy?'' Brant asks evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Brant's voice is as gentle as a summer breeze. It betrays
nothing except, perhaps, mild curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the point.
</P>
<P>
   Brant is a forensic child interviewer for the Middlesex District
Attorney's Child Unit, and she is engaging in one of the most
ethically _ and legally _ challenging conversations in modern life.
</P>
<P>
   She is talking to a little girl about her relationship with her
father, who is suspected of abusing her. She is trying to obtain an
accurate rendering of the facts, without coaching or encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Hovering behind every word is the ghost of the Fells Acres case,
the child sex-abuse prosecution generated by this very DA's office,
which has spawned a decade of appeals and allegations that the
procedures used to interview the child witnesses were flawed, that
the interviewers planted false scenarios of abuse in the minds of
children.
</P>
<P>
   While defending the overall fairness of the Fells Acres case,
Middlesex prosecutors acknowledged last year, for the first time,
that the techniques used to interview children from the Malden day
care center run by the Amirault family were improperly suggestive.
</P>
<P>
   Now the new DA, Martha Coakley, who once headed the Child Unit,
is implementing procedures to correct any bias. Last week, she
invited observers, including Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift, to see
a videotape of Brant using the techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (unit) opened in July 1989 somewhat in response to Fells
Acres,'' Coakley said. ``There was a need to respond to concerns
about how we interviewed. Obviously, the interviewing was not
perfect and we have learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The new methods, developed by child abuse specialists and
prosecutors, eschew many of the tactics widely used in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say those older approaches, which sometimes leave the
children in tears, don't work. In one instance cited even by
prosecutors as overly manipulative, interviewers used peer pressure
to extract information: One child from Fells Acres was told by an
interviewer that her playmate had already said she had been
molested.
</P>
<P>
   Now, interviewers no longer ask ``why'' questions, or react to
anything the child says, or make the child feel he or she is in
trouble or not being helpful. They no longer ask leading questions.
</P>
<P>
   And except for clarifying the many terms children use to
describe their body parts, interviewers now rarely use anatomically
correct dolls. Recent research has found that the dolls can lead
children to act out encounters that might be misunderstood by
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Brant is one of four full-time forensic child interviewers at
the Middlesex DA's Child Unit. They handle 800 cases a year, 200 of
which are prosecuted, a typical rate nationwide. Similar units work
with children at almost every district attorney's office in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Brant explains that she pays attention to every detail, no
matter how embarrassing or disturbing, and does not necessarily
assume a child is telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally, kids are upset and crying, but part of being
objective is maintaining a neutral stance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike in earlier cases, Brant's interviews are videotaped
through a one-way mirror, a move that allows defense lawyers and
others to scrutinize cases for fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a record now of what you are doing. We don't just
rely now on handwritten notes that described an interview as
`friendly,' '' said Maggie Bruck, a psychology professor at Johns
Hopkins University, who was a defense witness at a recent Fells
Acres appeal hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some defense lawyers remain skeptical that the revisions
have scrubbed all suggestiveness from the interviews. And they
object to the idea that interviewers such as Brant should be
full-time employees of the prosecution team, paid to help build
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not saying that everyone working with (district
attorneys) is trying to obscure the truth,'' said James Sultan, who
represents Cheryl Amirault Lefave, one of the three Fells Acres
defendants. ``But there is the tendency on the part of someone
working with the DA to have a pro-prosecution bias.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brant and other interviewers insist that they seek only the
truth, to be neutral, objective and unemotional as they elicit
facts from children whose trust and power have been stripped from
them.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual abuse is the most common crime against children, and the
toughest to uncover, they said. That 90 percent of accused sex
abusers are the child's father, stepfather, uncle, mother's
boyfriend, or other man close to the family makes the interviewer's
role even more pivotal: Interviewers must often dip and dive around
a confused child's efforts to protect someone he or she loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In cases where the perpetrator is a stranger, it is easier for
the child to talk about it _ there is no guilt of responsibility
associated with it,'' Brant said. ``When it is someone loved by the
child, trusted . . . you can see the child's need to protect a
parent or someone they know.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the lack of medical and other evidence in about 75
percent of the cases, say specialists, which gives them a
frustrating he-said-she-said quality that is often impossible to
prove either way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is too much emphasis on the interview itself, and that
is in part because law enforcement does not do a good enough job of
gathering collateral evidence to support or refute a child's
allegations,'' said Brian Holmgren, senior attorney for the
National Center for Prosecution of Child Abuse in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewers are left to sift through conversations, getting
children, some as young as 2, to reveal painful thoughts and
memories.
</P>
<P>
   When, during her videotaped interview, Brant asks the little
girl what happened with Daddy, the girl responds slowly, elliptical
at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah. But I think I forget,'' the little girl says, still
looking down at her picture. ``I just have to think about it. Maybe
if I am drawing, I can talk to you about Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, what tumbles out with disconcerting calm over two meetings
with Brant is a tale of Daddy making the then-4- year-old perform
oral sex on him and threatening to kill Mommy if their secret ever
emerges. Now, she says, she has moved and can't see her Daddy
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easier not to believe this is happening,'' said Brant,
who is expecting her first child next fall. ``This doesn't just
happen to other people's kids. It is prevalent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
