A0864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-CROSSING-BOS &LR;      03-31 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-CROSSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT TEXAS SCHOOL, BORDER BARRIERS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ Herman Aguirre's day begins badly whenever he
dresses like an American college student _ in jeans and backward
baseball cap, a day's growth of beard on his chiseled chin.
</P>
<P>
   As he crosses the toll bridge over the Rio Grande that links his
hometown of Juarez, Mexico, and his destination, El Paso, customs
officials pull him out of line, pepper him with questions, and look
through his backpack for contraband.
</P>
<P>
   They find only advanced computing textbooks, a snack, and other
telltale signs that Aguirre, the officials' prejudgment
notwithstanding, is just what he appears to be: an American college
student, even if not an American.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Aguirre is part of an unusual daily migration in
which several thousand Mexican citizens cross the border not for
low-paying jobs but to attend Texas public universities. Making it
even more unusual is the fact that Texas law allows all but the
richest among them to pay the same tuition as Texas residents _
more than $2,500 less per semester than nonresident rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's less than one-third as much money as it would be if they
charged me like an out-of-state student. I could never afford
that,'' said Aguirre, a computer information systems major who
expects to graduate in May 2000 from the University of Texas at El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Several Texas universities participate, but nowhere is the
program more popular than at UTEP, mainly because the sister cities
of Juarez, with 1.3 million people, and El Paso, with 700,000,
constitute what may be the world's largest cross-border community.
</P>
<P>
   The program took effect in 1988, at a time of declining
enrollment. Since then, the number of Mexican students has climbed
steadily. Mexicans now make up nearly 10 percent of UTEP's 14,600
students, the largest concentration of Mexican students of any US
college, school officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate beneficiaries are Mexican students such as
Aguirre and his girlfriend, Gabriela Carrera, a marketing
management major who joins him every morning on the 90-minute trek
from their homes to the school, which is close enough to the border
to be visible from the toll bridge.
</P>
<P>
   It is a journey of long walks, interrupted by several bus rides
and the unavoidable check of their student visas. Along the way on
the Juarez side, they pass graffiti-splashed buildings, old women
and young girls selling candy from makeshift stands, and a
seemingly endless stream of taverns. Once over the border in El
Paso, they move through well-swept streets and a well-tended
business district before reaching the UTEP campus.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond helping individual students, the program underscores the
growing interdependence not just of Juarez and El Paso, but of
communities all along the 2,100-mile dividing line between the
United States and its second-biggest trading partner. In the 5 1/2
years since passage of the North American Free Trade Agreement,
Juarez has boomed while El Paso, losing jobs to factories over the
border, has wilted.
</P>
<P>
   But both have learned how much they depend on each other, and
about the values that these neighbors share, despite divisions of
wealth and culture _ not to mention barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing NAFTA does is to emphasize the importance of
post-secondary education. It also emphasizes the importance of
bilingual communication skills. Those two factors make a university
education from the United States more attractive,'' said Tom
Fullerton, an assistant professor of economics at UTEP who has
studied the border economy.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the program's success _ and its strong support from
Republican Governor George W. Bush and a sometimes xenophobic Texas
Legislature _ cuts dramatically against the common, and not
unfounded, image of the border as a zone of endless skirmishes
between agents and illegals. Further, it flies in the face of ugly
caricatures of undereducated Mexicans crossing the border in
pursuit of welfare benefits, drug deals, or other undesirable
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing how the border can serve as a barrier to
communication,'' said UTEP president Diane Natalicio. ``Having
Mexican students on campus creates a little dissonance for people
at first. But then it helps lay a foundation for better
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguirre puts it more bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Americans think we are lazy people, dirty people. They
should see what we do to go to school, how hard we work,'' he said.
His day begins before dawn and he doesn't return home until after
10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment is open to Mexican students who are at least somewhat
proficient in English and who score at least 920 out of 1600 on the
SAT. To qualify for Texas resident tuition _ $1,057 per semester,
as opposed to $3,613 for out-of-state residents _ they must also
demonstrate financial need, which is not difficult for many Mexican
students.
</P>
<P>
   A semester at a university in Juarez can cost as little as $60,
students and UTEP officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The in-state tuition often poses a burden for Mexican students,
many of whom work on-campus jobs or clean homes in El Paso, earning
$5 or $6 an hour instead of the $3 a day in the factories and shops
just across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Once at UTEP, Mexican students are more likely to remain in
school than their US classmates. Retention rates for Mexican
students is 81 percent after freshman year, compared with nearly 65
percent for the student body as a whole. Since the program began,
roughly 1,000 Mexican students have graduated, more than 200 with
postgraduate degrees, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There are few if any public detractors of the program, despite
the fact that _ on paper at least _ UTEP forgoes about $3 million
per semester in the process.
</P>
<P>
   But any money lost is outweighed by the opportunity gained, said
Christina Bernal, a third-generation Mexican-American who oversees
the program, formally known as PASE. The name is both the Spanish
word for pass and an acronym for a Spanish phrase that translates
as Financial Assistance Program for Mexican Citizens. Most Mexican
students could never pay the higher tuition, she said, and would
not attend UTEP.
</P>
<P>
   Dissent is also muted by the fact that it is difficult to find
anyone at the school who pays the out-of-state rates. Only 1
percent of students do so. In addition to the 10 percent of
students who are Mexicans paying in-state tuition, 85 percent of
students are from the El Paso area.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bernal said she occasionally hears grousing. ``There are
some racist people in this state, and they don't like to think they
are paying the way for Mexican students,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On campus, however, Mexican students say they experience no
discrimination. That is unsurprising considering that two-thirds of
the student body is of Hispanic descent. Last fall a Mexican
student, Aaron Acosta, was named homecoming king.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the Mexican students, choosing majors that are
expected to lead to jobs, eschew liberal arts for programs in
computers, engineering, or business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the kids in my neighborhood, 80 to 90 percent, are
gang members,'' said Abdiel Quezada, 19, a computer science major
from Juarez. ``I hope to stay in the United States and get a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Most said they associate mainly with other Mexicans, but Lilian
Lopez, a math science major who has become a campus orientation
leader, has made friends from Michigan, Minnesota, and as far away
as Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to meet people,'' she said. ``They speak English, and I
want to learn better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
