<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASE AMONG OLD PEACENIKS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO &UR;  &LR; _ A B-52 bomber sits on the living room floor, and
no one wants to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   The ghost of Vietnam made a brief visit to the Democratic State
Convention in California, interrupting Tipper Gore, who substituted
for her husband. At first she uttered appropriate notes of
self-mockery. ``Speaking of the 2000 election, Al sends his
regards,'' she deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   When she became serious, so did the delegates. ``They are
standing for us,'' she said, praising the US forces involved in
NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia. ``It's never an easy decision to send
our troops into danger.'' A lonely voice shouted, ``Bring them
home!'' the only note of foreign policy dissent at the party
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, California activists defined themselves as antiwar
Democrats. They entered politics to follow Eugene McCarthy, Robert
Kennedy, and George McGovern _ all ``doves'' in the war in Vietnam,
the longest war in US history. In the 1960s, these delegates were
picketing party meetings, chanting ``Stop the Bombing! Stop the
War!'' Today they're on the inside, maybe feeling uncomfortable,
but not saying so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never believed I'd have to go back and vote on airstrikes,''
said Senator Barbara Boxer, celebrating with delegates her
successful reelection. ``But human rights belong to everyone in the
world,'' she added, and ought not to be denied ``because of
ethnicity, religion, or background.''
</P>
<P>
   Some delegates said they hadn't followed the war in Yugoslavia
but were willing to give the benefit of the doubt to a Democratic
president, Bill Clinton, a courtesy they did not extend to Lyndon
Johnson in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are always ready to duel about ideology, but at the
Sacramento Convention Center the guerrilla theater was tame and
theoretical. Delegates listened to Gray Davis, the first Democratic
governor in 16 years, who campaigned as a Vietnam veteran backing
``a strong national defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeating a campaign theme, Davis said, ``I pledged that I would
govern not from the right or the left but from the center,''
pausing for applause. Five delegates applauded. The 2,695 others
reacted as though an honorary Oscar were being awarded to Elia
Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Mayor Willie L. Brown Jr., substituting for
President Clinton as a luncheon speaker, addressed the delegates
and, through them, Davis, whom he had supported for governor early.
``You are running the risk of losing the enthusiasm of your base
and ultimately the loyalty of your base,'' Brown said. ``You must
do justice to your base.''
</P>
<P>
   On the sidewalk outside, the scene was surreal. Some 200
protesters mingled uncomfortably. Most were pro-Serb rather than
antiwar, waving Yugoslavian flags adorned with imperial crests. A
handful of aging hippies from the 1960s joined them, looking like
extras in the ABC comedy ``Dharma and Greg.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, not every old lefty repressed long-ago instincts. The
state Senate's president, John L. Burton, who protested the war in
Vietnam as a member of Congress, was the only party leader whose
letter of welcome injected ideology in the convention brochure with
ungrammatical fervor: ``We're on the road to 2000. And we're going
to make sure that road don't veer to the right.''
</P>
<P>
   After giving a two-minute luncheon speech, Burton stared at the
demonstrators, saying, ``They don't look too dangerous.'' He mused
about conventions past ``in '64, '66, '68 and right on through, all
about Vietnam.'' Calling Clinton's policy ``a pretty slippery
slope,'' he wondered ``whether genocide in Africa is different
because it doesn't involve white people'' and added: ``It's very
tough to support dropping bombs on people.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton left the convention early to drive home to San Francisco
to catch a documentary movie on Lenny Bruce, the late comic who
would have had some choice, unsympathetic, comments about the
silent discomfort of Democrats today.
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
