A0870 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-REDISTRICTING-HNS &LR;      03-31 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REDISTRICTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK MOUNTS CENSUS EFFORT TO RETAIN HOUSE SEATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Faced with the prospect of losing one
congressional seat _ and quite possibly two _ because of a
declining population, New York officials launched a yearlong effort
to ensure a thorough count in the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some people, the census is going to be considered another
piece of junk mail,'' Lt. Gov. Mary O. Donohue said Tuesday at the
organizing meeting of the Complete Count Committee, which includes
government and private sector representatives. ``It is perhaps one
of the most important documents that anyone will be asked to fill
out next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Next March, federal authorities will mail census forms to every
household in the nation, but officials here and across the country
are concerned that indifference in certain areas _ like New York _
could result in a significant undercounting. After the last census
in 1990, New York lost three seats in the U.S. House of
Representatives, and has acknowledged the loss of at least one more
after the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   The state now has 31 representatives in the House, while
California has 52 and Texas 30.
</P>
<P>
   The census count is required once every decade under the U.S.
Constitution and is used to determine how many representatives a
state has in Congress and how much aid it receives from the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do a good job in 2000, we are going to be stuck
with the numbers for another 10 years,'' said Tony Farthing,
director of the New York City Regional Census Center. ``We did not
get the message out clearly in 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   The Complete Count Committee is eager to ensure that New York
doesn't lose any more clout than necessary. The key, officials
said, is spreading the word and getting people to fill out census
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur G. Dukakis, director of the Boston Regional Census
Center, which services all of upstate New York, said the U.S.
Census Bureau will for the first time mount an aggressive
television campaign (the theme is: ``This is your future. Don't
leave it blank'').
</P>
<P>
   After the census is completed, a task force appointed by the
leaders of the state Assembly and Senate will come up with a
proposal for redrawing political boundary lines, so that each
member of the House of Representatives, as well as each state
Assembly and Senate member, represents approximately the same
number of people. Eventually, both houses of the Legislature and
the governor must approve the plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1335EST &QL; 
