u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-INTERNET-BOS &LR;      03-31 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET BECOMES THIS WAR'S JOURNAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the Web page of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the latest report
is marked ``Urgent, urgent, urgent'' with a headline posted in bold
red letters: ``Terror and massacre ... the humanitarian catastrophe
has happened.'' The site, at http://www.kosavapress.com, goes on to
list the names of people killed by Serbian forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the official Web site of the Serbian government
(http://serbia-info.com) offers an entirely different version of
events: One story accuses the ``NATO machine'' of attacking
villagers in Kosovo ``under veil of dark.'' Other pro-government
sites urge people to wear bull's eye targets on their clothing as a
symbol of protest against ``NATO aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, sites hosted by various human rights groups,
including New York-based Human Rights Watch and the London-based
Institute for War and Peace, are posting up-to-the-minute bulletins
on violence reported by affiliates in the field. And on bulletin
boards and in chat rooms, people are launching ``flame'' wars of
their own, vilifying President Clinton or Serb President Slobodan
Milosevic, depending on their political persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   In the first international conflict monitored and reported on
the Internet, there are as many versions of events as there are
people willing to post them. ``The role of information technology
in reporting military conflicts has long historic roots,'' said
John Pavlik, director of Columbia University's New Media Center.
``What's different today is that anybody can publish information _
governments, military authorities, journalists, or citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   World War II was reported over radio, while the Vietnam War was
beamed into American homes via television. Fax machines were the
primary source of communication used by students during the
uprising in Tiananmen Square. And now the Internet is the medium of
communication.
</P>
<P>
   But the new technology, however democratic, represents a
double-edged sword. ``There is a fantastic opportunity for folks to
distribute a picture of the world as they see it,'' said Andrew
Shapiro, director of the Aspen Institute's Internet Policy Project.
``But you don't have the truth filters that you have in traditional
media. You don't have editors and libel lawyers and layers and
layers and layers of intermediaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet human rights workers report that the Internet has been an
invaluable tool throughout the conflict in the Balkans. The
Institute for War and Peace has been monitoring the conflict in
Serbia since 1991, and after Western media members were expelled
from the area last week, its network of local journalists filed
regularly on its Web site, http://www.iwpr.net.
</P>
<P>
   ``When their mobile phones or e-mails are working, they are
filing reports two or three times a day,'' said Tanya Hassan, the
London group's director of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Sophisticated technology also enabled Radio B92, an independent
station in Belgrade, to broadcast via Internet after its air
transmitter was banned. Its site, at http://www.b92.net, also
features streaming video, including man-on-the-street interviews.
</P>
<P>
   But specialists warn that the new media is limited. ``We
shouldn't fall into the mythic sense that the Internet is
inherently democratizing,'' Shapiro said. ``We shouldn't say, `They
have the Internet, so why can't they overthrow this guy?' It
doesn't have the tools to determine the outcome of a military
conflict. I fear that Internet boosters tend to place too much
stock in the ability of the Internet to be a liberating force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1336EST &QL; 
