<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE     03-31 1902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS01-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that the general public in Havana wasn't allowed
to attend the game March 28 between the Cuban national team and the
Baltimore Orioles. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Only invited guests were allowed into the historic game at
Havana's Estadio Latinoamericano, and even they had to thread their
way through a heavy security cordon that included dozens of
plain-clothed police officers.
</P>
<P>
   As reported in the media, the government decided to keep tight
control over who could attend, distributing tickets to Communist
Party faithful through schools, youth organizations and unions.
Some tickets were parceled out to workers and civil servants as
rewards for meeting production quotas and other state goals.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fans who attended, electrician Leonardo Marquez, said
he was given his tickets as a reward for being productive. ``The
people here were all invited,'' Marquez told a New YorkTimes
reporter. ``It's for the protection of the foreigners here. We were
told to behave ourselves.'' Another fan, Roman Garcia, who didn't
get a ticket, denounced the government's decision, saying: ``I
always go to the stadium, even when there are only 50 to 100 people
in the stands. But I can't go because I don't have an invitation. I
feel tricked and disgusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a question that will be of interest to a lot of young
people. Is the rock singer who goes by the name of Marilyn Manson
the same person who played Paul on ``The Wonder Years'' about a
decade ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: That rumor goes around from time to time, but shock-rocker
Manson (real name: Brian Warner) says it isn't true. He also denies
other frequently recurring rumors, including the one saying he was
a child actor on ``Mr. Belvedere,'' and another claiming that he
died of a drug overdose in Phoenix. The part of Paul Pfeiffer on
``Wonder'' was played by Josh Saviano, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Delta Air Lines changed its policies about boarding
priorities for passengers traveling with children? We used to be
able to board at the same time as first-class passengers, but on a
recent trip from Phoenix to Atlanta we were told that isn't the
policy now, and those of us with children were to board only when
our row was called. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: Delta spokesman John Kennedy said the policy indeed has
changed. It's part of a procedure Delta has instituted to expedite
the boarding process ``in order to ensure on-time performance.''
All passengers _ and that includes children _ board from the rear
of the aircraft by row number when the gate agent makes the
announcement. The exception is people holding first-class tickets
and other priority passengers, who can board earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is fat-free cream cheese possible, when most if not all
of the fat in milk is in the cream?
</P>
<P>
   A: Check the ingredients list on the packaging of these products
and you'll see words like nonfat milk, whey protein, cultured skim
milk solids, skim milk, xanthan gum, carrageenan (a gum) and so on,
said Judy A. Harrison of the department of foods and nutrition at
the University of Georgia. This is your clue as to how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   Nonfat milk is used instead of whole milk or cream in the
production process of such products as fat-free cream cheese and
fat-free half and half. Milk proteins and gums, many of which are
plant-derived, are added to the nonfat milk to give the resulting
product texture or body similar to the original food product,
Harrison added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can an Internet user get a list of e-mail addresses of
U.S. senators and U.S. representatives?
</P>
<P>
   A: Of the 540 members of the 106th Congress (including five
non-voting delegates), the latest information shows that 386 had
e-mail addresses and 488 could be contacted via WWW home pages.
There are a number of online sources of information for reaching
them, and some list more traditional ground mail contact
information, too. Among the sources:
</P>
<P>
   www.visi.com/juan/congress
</P>
<P>
   www.vote-smart.org/congresstrack/contact
</P>
<P>
   www.capweb.net
</P>
<P>
   www.congress.org/ Q: I was extremely moved and hurt by the
pictures on TV of people in Kosovo forced out of their homes and
into the mountains. The announcer said monetary contributions to
help them would be best, but he didn't say where they could be
sent. Do you know?
</P>
<P>
   A: Several relief organizations are accepting donations. Among
them:
</P>
<P>
   American Red Cross: If sending a check, make it out to American
Red Cross International Response Fund (and indicate on the check
``Yugoslavia, including Kosovo'') and mail to American Red Cross
International Response Fund, P.O. Box 37243, Washington, DC 20013.
For credit-card donations, call 1-800-HELP-NOW (1-800-435-7669) and
again indicate ``Yugoslavia, including Kosovo.'' Internet users can
make online donations by visiting www.redcross.org and choosing
International Response Fund as the option for donating.
</P>
<P>
   CARE: Make your check payable to CARE, write ``Kosovo'' on it,
and mail to: CARE, Attn.: Donor Services, 151 Ellis St., Atlanta,
GA 30303. Online donations can be made at www.care.org and
credit-card contributions can be made by calling 1-800-521-CARE
(1-800-521-2273).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the diplomat who claimed immunity after
a traffic accident in Washington a year or two ago in which a young
woman died? He had been drinking and was speeding, as I recall.
</P>
<P>
   A: The case involved Gueorgui Makharadze, second-ranking member
at the embassy of the Republic of Georgia in Washington. The
accident, which killed Joviane Waltrick, 16, and injured four other
people, occurred in January 1997 when Makharadze's leased 1997 Ford
Taurus slammed into a line of cars waiting at a traffic light in
northwest Washington. Authorities said Makharadze was speeding
after a dinner during which he drank too much wine.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary step, the Republic of Georgia waived
Makharadze's diplomatic immunity so he could face criminal charges.
He pleaded guilty to involuntary manslaughter and aggravated
assault and was sentenced in December 1997 to seven to 21 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrick's family agreed last October to settle a lawsuit
against the Republic of Georgia and other defendants for ``well in
excess'' of $250,000 (the exact amount was not disclosed).
Waltrick's mother, Viviane Wagner, said she planned to use the
money to start a nonprofit foundation to educate the public about
drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   After the settlement was reached, Tedo Japaridze, Georgia's
ambassador to the United States, wrote to Wagner expressing sadness
for what happened, and adding that he realized ``no compensation is
possible'' for the loss of her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My family will be going on a skiing vacation north of
Vancouver, B.C., in December, driving into Canada from Seatte.
What are the entry requirements for U.S. citizens?
</P>
<P>
   A: No visa is required by Americans to visit Canada. Proof of
identity and citizenship (such as birth certificate or passport or
naturalization papers) is required, however, and passports or birth
certificates are preferred. Those bringing children must provide
the children's identification (i.e. birth certificate) and a letter
of permission from a parent or guardian if the child is traveling
with someone who does not have legal custody. It is recommended
that anyone traveling to Canada check with the nearest embassy or
consulate for more details. For online information, check this
site: www.canadatourism.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article about a flare-up in the former Soviet Union
mentioned two ethnic groups, the Ingush and the Ossetians. I'm not
faimilar with them. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Ingushetia is a republic in southwestern Russia. The majority
of the population is Ingush, one of the many Muslim mountain
peoples in the Caucasus. Their history has long been related to the
Chechen mountain peoples, who also are Muslim and whose language is
closely related to Ingush. But after the 1991 breakup of the Soviet
Union, the Ingush and the Chechen dissolved the union that had been
imposed on them after the 1920s, and formed two separate republics,
Ingushetia and Chechnya. Encyclopedia Britannica describes the
Ingush society as one based on clan and tribal relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Ossetians live in a region in Caucasia divided between the
North Ossetian Autonomous Republic of the Russian Federation and
the South Ossetian Autonomous Federation of the Georgian Republic.
Ethnically they're of mixed Iranian-Japhetic (Caucasian) origin,
Britannica reports. Their language belongs to the Iranian group of
the Indo-European family of languages.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that 30 companies are used to calculate the Dow
Jones industrial average, and they are changed from time to time.
What were the 30 companies making up the original Dow Jones
industrial average?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually there were only 12 companies when Charles Henry Dow
published his first industrial stock average on May 26, 1896. Those
1896 components: American Cotton Oil; American Sugar; American
Tobacco; Chicago Gas; Distilling &AMP; Cattle Feeding; General
Electric; Laclede Gas; National Lead; North American (utility);
Tennessee Coal &AMP; Iron; U.S. Leather, preferred; and U.S. Rubber.
</P>
<P>
   The number rose to 20 in 1916. The 30-stock average made its
debut in 1928 and the number has remained constant ever since, even
though the companies within the index occasionally have been
changed.
</P>
<P>
   The first average computed from the 1896 list, by the way, was
40.94.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently read that more than $4 million has been collected
in President Clinton's defense fund, and more is expected. Is he
required to pay taxes on this money?
</P>
<P>
   A: No one we could reach at IRS would comment on the record. All
we were told is that the subject of legal defense funds is not
addressed in the tax code, and ``it would be inappropriate to
discuss the tax situation of any individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I cracked an egg for a recipe, it had two yolks. What
causes this, and is it rare? The recipe turned out fine, by the
way.
</P>
<P>
   A: A hen normally ovulates one yolk a day, but occasionally two
yolks may be released and, on very rare occasions, there may be
three, said Michael P. Lacy, poultry scientist at the University of
Georgia Extension Service. So a two-yolk egg can't be considered a
rare occurrence, even though it's not usual. Lacy explained that it
happens when two yolks are ovulated at the same time, or close to
the same time, and are picked up simultaneously by the hen's
oviduct. (Think human pregnancies that result in fraternal twins,
whose development process begins when the mother's ovaries release
two eggs at about the same time).
</P>
<P>
   Lacy said double-yolked eggs are more common in young hens
because their oviducts are highly active, and meat-type chickens
are more prone to laying them than egg-laying strains. Also, some
strains of chickens produce higher incidences of double-yolk eggs
than others, he added.
</P>
<P>
   (END TAKE 1)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
