<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0923 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCON-HNS &LR;      03-31 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN FINALLY GETS SOME RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Clearly, there are some sad, misguided
souls out there who stupifyingly underestimated the University of
Connecticut Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Cancel the coronation of the Duke Blue Devils as a team for the
ages. Monday night at Tropicana Field, the Huskies gave the
bluebloods of college basketball a serious case of the blues.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies had too much bite, too much bark, too much game for
the top-ranked Blue Devils in the championship game of the NCAA
Tournament. A 77-74 victory over a team that came in with a 32-game
winning streak can't help but qualify as an upset, but there was
nothing flukish or freakish about the way the Huskies won their
first national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Even those in the crowd of 41,340 who had nosebleed seats could
see that the Huskies and Blue Devils collaborated on a championship
game worth seeing again and again. There were 14 ties and eight
lead changes before Richard Hamilton and Khalid El-Amin shot UConn
into the lead for good. The Blue Devils had two chances in the
final 15 seconds to save the game and a season of mythic
proportions, and they got the ball in the right hands.
</P>
<P>
   Duke senior guard Trajan Langdon is as pure of shooter as there
is in the country. He scored 25 points his final college game,
hitting the target on 5-of-10 of the 3-bombs he dropped on the
Huskies. Guard Ricky Moore is as tenacious a defender as UConn
coach Jim Calhoun has ever had on his side.
</P>
<P>
   Moore refused to let Langdon get even a glimpse at the basket
either time, triggering a raucous UConn celebration punctuated by a
moment of comic relief. One security guard mistook El-Amin as a
regular civilian and tried to escort the pleasingly plump point
guard off the court.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke section may have been stunned to silence, but not the
Huskies. Duke may have had the 37-1 record and the pedigree, but
neither Calhoun nor his players were taking bows for pulling off an
upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not shocked,'' Calhoun said. ``We truly believed we
could beat them. As of this moment, we're the best team in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun has been a head coach for 27 seasons. On his 13th trip
to the NCAAs, he removed himself from the running in the Best Coach
Never To Make the Final Four competition. The Blue Devils had
dashed his dreams of getting to the Final Four in 1990 on a
buzzer-beater by Christian Laettner. Consider the Blue Devils
repaid in full.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no better coach than I was three weeks ago, and I'm no
worse a coach than I was three weeks ago,'' Calhoun said. ``All I
can do is be true to my kids and do the best I can. If you hear a
loud yell tonight, it will be me.''
</P>
<P>
   All weekend, Calhoun went out of his way to give the Devils
their due. He took special care the day before the game to deliver
an ode to Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the coach for our generation,'' Calhoun said.
``He has identified such things as what a program is _ class,
competitiveness, preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, some coach certainly had the Huskies prepared for
everything Krzyzewski tried. The Huskies slowed down the Duke
offense by putting pressure on point guard William Avery, forcing
Langdon to bring up the ball. UConn defenders smartly double-teamed
Duke All-America center Elton Brand (15 points, 13 rebounds) into
confusion. On offense, the Huskies took advantage of their
quickness by spreading the floor and setting up pick-and-roll
opportunities. When the Duke big men slid over to help, Hamilton,
Moore and El-Amin diced and sliced the Duke defense.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure, Krzyzewski conceded afterward, eventually did in
Duke. Not the pressure of being a favorite, or having a chance to
secure a niche as a team for the ages. The pressure of trying to
stay with the Huskies every step for 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept constant game pressure on us,'' Krzyzewski said.
``It's a different form of pressure. We'd get it down to one point
or tied, and they'd make a big play. You have to give them credit
for making big plays in the second half. Because we made big plays.
It was a possession-for-possession game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies played like a team that was possessed. It was as if
they were carrying the banner for the likes of Tate George, Donyell
Marshall, Ray Allen _ the players who put UConn on the college
basketball map. When Calhoun took over the UConn program in 1986,
the talk around the state wasn't about reaching the Final Four. It
was about whether or not the Huskies belonged in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the Big East first and UConn second when I came,''
Calhoun said. ``What we tried to tell kids is, `Would you like to
play against Reggie Williams, Alonzo Mourning? Would you like to
play in the Carrier Dome _ not in Syracuse, but would you like to
play in the Big East?'''
</P>
<P>
   Those days, Calhoun and his staff would call a player and ask
what leagues they liked best. Player after player would talk about
the Big East. Player after player would express admiration for
Georgetown coach John Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you talked to John Thompson?'' the UConn coaches would
ask. ``No? Good.''
</P>
<P>
   Times change. Expectations soar. A Duke or a UCLA would trip up
the Huskies short of the Final Four. Calhoun began to chafe at
being criticized for, as he put it, ``mere excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA Tournament is a cruel, cruel thing,'' Calhoun said.
``It's a wonderful thing. I've watched it through the eyes of kids.
The elation is absolutely incredible. I've watched through the
eyes, without knowing it, of Gonzaga, Weber State.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in turn, when it ends, it doesn't just slowly end. The
curtain gets drawn down, and the band marches on and you look up
and it's like a parade that has just passed through and you're kind
of left to clean up. Emotionally, that's how you feel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's how the losing teams feel. The Huskies finally won the
last one, the big one. They were resilient, getting 13 first-half
points from Moore, who came in averaging 6.6 per game. They were
resourceful, getting by on a night when El-Amin committed six
turnovers and played only 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Moore kept the Huskies afloat early. Hamilton (27 points, seven
rebounds) steadied the ship during the middle and end. His
3-pointer down the stretch gave the Huskies a 73-68 cushion. Still,
the Blue Devils weren't ready to go away. El-Amin, who had hit a
floater over Shane Battier and Elton Brand with barely a minute
remaining, missed a jumper with the score 75-74 lead. The Blue
Devils retrieved the rebound and took a last gasp at the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 seconds remaining. The ball was in the hands of
Langdon. No way was Krzyzewski going to call a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Coach K telling Trajan to get the ball,'' Moore said.
``I felt like if he got it, he wasn't going to do anything with it.
It was crunch time. It was him against me.''
</P>
<P>
   From the left wing, Langdon tried to shake Moore with a spin
move to the middle. No way. Langdon wound up stumbling and
traveling. After two insurance free throws by El-Amin with barely
five ticks left on the clock, Langdon got one last chance. Just
past midcourt, he tripped. He fell. The mighty Blue Devils had
fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't describe it,'' Hamilton said. ``I still don't
understand the things that we did and accomplished. Maybe it will
sink in a week or two from now. We were just happy to put a smile
on Coach's face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
