<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRD-TRAIL-HNS &LR;      03-31 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRD-TRAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MAP PINPOINTS TEXAS COASTAL BIRDING TRAIL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CINDY HORSWELL 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ A colony of 500 white pelicans forms a
flotilla, bobbing gently on the waves that lap the shore of the
Bolivar mud flats, a thin strip of land on Texas' Gulf coast.
</P>
<P>
   When hungry, some move into a line and herd their prey by
beating the water with their 8-foot wings. The birds then use their
pouches, which can hold up to 12 quarts of water, to scoop up the
corralled fish.
</P>
<P>
   Great blue herons stand motionless nearby on tall, stiltlike
legs, watching. Timid spoonbills with their rosy-pink plumage wade
into the salty water away from the crowd. Piping plovers _ small,
brownish birds listed as a threatened species _ skitter across the
sand.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 10,000 birds, representing 50 species, congregate on this
tranquil 500-acre Galveston Bay marsh. It's the Houston Audubon
Society's Shorebird Sanctuary, annually attracting visitors from 17
countries and every state.
</P>
<P>
   It also is one of the 125 sites listed on a new map showing
where to ``bird watch'' in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   The map, which covers the upper coast from Texas Point National
Wildlife Refuge near Beaumont, to the San Bernard National Wildlife
Refuge near Brazoria, is part of the Great Texas Birding Trail
being developed along the state's 500-mile coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Though some might think nature would be lost amid Houston's
petrochemical complexes and smoke stacks, the opposite is true,
said David Dauphin of Baytown, president of the Texas
Ornithological Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 450 different bird species have been found on the
upper coast. Only two of the 50 states can claim that statewide.
One is Texas, which has recorded the most of any state, or 600
species, and the other is California,'' said Dauphin, co-host of an
educational TV series, ``On the Birding Trail.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a birding trail was conceived in 1995 when the U.S.
Department of Transportation gave Texas a $2.5 million grant to
develop its natural resources, said Madge Lindsay with Texas Parks
&AMP; Wildlife Department. The first of three maps for the trail, which
will run the length of the Texas coast, was released in 1997 and
covered only the state's central section.
</P>
<P>
   The second map _ for the upper coast _ should be available from
Houston-area chambers of commerce, tourist bureaus and the Texas
Department of Transportation in April, Lindsay said. The third map,
covering the lower coast, is expected to be finished by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   While the Houston-area birding trail snakes along the coast, it
also includes 15 loops that meander deeper into the countryside to
spotlight unique scenery or special hideaways, said consultant Ted
Eubanks of Austin, who has visited each site and helped design the
map.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have arranged the sites so that there's never more than an
hour's drive between each one. That should make it easy for
travelers to see quite a few sites in one day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown-and-white signs that picture a tern winging past the sun
are posted at each location on the trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sites aren't only designed for the avid birders, but for
anybody who enjoys the outdoors and wants an excuse to enjoy
wildlife. There are 70 million people like that,'' Eubanks said.
</P>
<P>
   He encourages those following the trail to contact area chambers
of commerce to learn of historical sites or other points of
interest to visit while following the trail.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks particularly enjoyed visiting the 19 sites on the ``Big
Thicket Loop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about seeing the Big Thicket, but not many people
know how to do it. It's more extensive than the natural preserve,''
he said. ``This loop goes from the Louisiana border, north along
the Sabine River to Toledo Bend and then wanders through the piney
woods.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the birds, Eubanks also was impressed by wild
azalea thickets, long-leaf pines, cypress swamps and private
hideaways not usually seen by the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the really remarkable sites in Newton County is owned
by a large timber company who maintains it as a wilderness park.
It's a canyon with rocky cliffs filled with wild azaleas. It's
other-worldly,'' he said. ``Another place is Boykin Springs north
of Jasper. It's a natural spring that creeps from a swampy lake.
It's part of a national forest that has sphagnum moss and
carnivorous pitcher plants that eat insects.''
</P>
<P>
   The map gives directions to the 125 sites, notes the best
seasons for viewing and lists special birds that might be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the birding destinations, one that might be the most
surprising is the loop centered on downtown Houston, Eubanks said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that John Audubon, the naturalist famed for painting
North American birds, made a trip to Houston soon after the city
was founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Audubon wasn't that impressed with the `mud hole,' he
reported seeing more ivory-billed woodpeckers here than he ever did
the rest of his life. He also wrote in his diary about the wonders
of wildlife along Buffalo Bayou,'' Eubanks said.
</P>
<P>
   Birding is still possible in Houston's urban setting, Eubanks
insists.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, birds can become so disoriented amid the
skyscrapers during spring migrations that they cluster in pocket
parks around the city, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Buffalo Bayou Loop'' is designed for visitors who want to
stay within walking distance or a short drive of downtown Houston
and the Texas Medical Center, about five miles from downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks and other experts agree that the single most spectacular
birding destinations on the upper coast are the High Island
sanctuaries on the ``Bolivar Loop'' during spring migration.
Beginning in mid-March, thousands of rainbow-colored songbirds
vacate their winter homes in Mexico and Central and South America
to travel to their summer homes in the northern U.S. states and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``These birds must have traveled 850 miles across the Gulf of
Mexico. Then they start looking for a resting place. They end up
funneling through High Island because it sits atop a salt dome, a
tiny pimple of ground with a forest of live oak trees. That's
because 40 miles in either direction is nothing but a flat,
treeless marsh,'' Eubanks said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes these birds have flown through storms and stiff winds
and are so exhausted when they arrive that they may literally fall
out of the sky and land wherever they can.
</P>
<P>
   For the thousands of tourists who descend on High Island during
migration, bleachers have been installed at the end of boardwalks
for observing the birds, especially during the peak of the season,
April 19-23, Dauphin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need to start birding is a field guide for bird
identification and some binoculars. It's easy and can be done in
conjunction with other outdoor activities,'' Eubanks said.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Burkett, the Houston Audubon Society's sanctuary manager,
said the birding trail also should lead to an appreciation for the
area's natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing habitat all the time with the destruction of the
rain forests in the tropics. We've seen some bird populations drop
by 50 percent in the last 20 years,'' Burkett said. ``That's why
it's so important to protect what we've got and acquire more
strategic sanctuaries, like the mud flats at Port Bolivar.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
