<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, April 1:
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-SERVICE (Undated) _ From the specialists who locate
objects of sentimental value to the ones who locate other
specialists, there are now alluring experts for every household
quest. With men and women spending more hours at work than they did
a decade ago, the do-it-yourself movement, both as an approach to
home decoration and as an outlook on life, has gone into decline,
giving way to the wide-ranging ``hire-it-out'' trend. Its credo is
simple: to save time, just delegate others to pick up the dry
cleaning, pamper the pets, coddle the offspring. By Jenny Lynn
Bader.
</P>
<P>
   KITSCH (Undated) _ Kitsch has history, too _ and bad taste has
its fashions just like good. Inspiration struck someone the day the
velvet car dice were born, just a surely as it did Duchamp or
Daumier. An artist had first to imagine and paint those cardsharp
dogs before they could become a figure of fun in beer ads. By Phil
Patton.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERWATER-RESTAURANT (Eilat, Israel) _ The Red Sea Star
Restaurant began with an underwater vision and ended up a vision
underwater: a whimsical restaurant deep in the Gulf of Eilat, where
diners devour fish platters under the scrutiny of fish peering in
at them through portholes. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MAYA-LIN (Clinton, Tenn.) _ For eighteen years Maya Lin's
reputation has been etched in stone. ``Every time there was a
bombing or a plane crash, I would get a fax,'' the designer of the
Vietnam Veterans Memorial said. Eventually, Ms. Lin made a
conscious decision to avoid being typecast ``as a person whose work
concerns death and destruction.'' But proving that her
architectural reach extends beyond black granite monuments has
taken time. ``I need a body of work to come out for people to
realize how serious I am about this discipline,'' Ms. Lin, 39,
said. By Fred Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
