<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, April 1,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ Developments in the NATO strikes
against Kosovo. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SLOBODAN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ To some of the people who came in
contact with him in 1995, Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic
deserved some credit for coming to Dayton and negotiating the
Dayton Peace Accord that ended the war in Bosnia. But the Serb
attack on the ethnic Albanian population in Kosovo has caused
opinions about Milosevic to undergo an abrupt change. ``I sure have
changed my mind,'' said Dieter Krug, who hosted Milosevic and the
rest of the negotiators at a dinner in 1995 at his restaurant,
l'Auberge, in Kettering. ``His actions speak for themselves,'' said
Krug. ``This shooting and killing of innocent women and children is
very bad.'' (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-TRAVELS _ WASHINGTON _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton returns
Thursday from her 19th solo trip abroad during her husband's
presidency, a look at how the first lady's travels are financed.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FUNDS _ Gov. George W. Bush, who still insists he is
only thinking about running for president, shows he is fiscally fit
to run. Bush is expected to announce he has raised about $4 billion
in the scant few weeks since he started asking for cash. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-INTERNET _ With the pressure to raise campaign
contributions at an all time high, candidates around the country
are turning to the internet as a new marketplace in which to raise
money. Presidential candidate Bill Bradley has asked the Federal
Election Commission to make credit card contributions solicited
over the internet eligible for matching funds. Experts see a huge
potential for candidates to raise money electronically,
supplementing more traditional techniques such as direct mail.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ The state of settlement talks may
become clearer at a previously scheduled status hearing for the
Microsoft antitrust case. (Glass., Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ NATO's 50th anniversary summit this
month will be held in a federal complex that authorities is highly
vulnerable to terrorists. At a Wednesday briefing, authorities are
expected to face questions about keeping delegates safe while NATO
is at war. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS _ Census Day is a mere year away, and the Clinton
administration still will not say how much its plan for the 2000
census will cost. Meanwhile, another wave of lawsuits awaits this
most controversial undertaking, which both Republicans and
Democrats fear the other side is trying to manipulate for political
reasons. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-REPORT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Three months before
federal engineers ask Congress to approve a $7.8 billion Everglades
restoration plan, Congress' investigating arm has prepared a draft
report castigating existing Everglades efforts as confused and
disorganized _ and maybe worse. From what we've been able to glean,
the General Accounting Office slams the National Park Service, the
Army Corps and other agencies for being unable to resolve
longstanding disputes that have idled expensive new pumps and
allowed the Cape Sable sparrow crisis to drag on. The GAO also
examined the $200 million that the corps and Interior Department
have spent since 1996 buying Talisman and other buffer sites in
Palm Beach County's sugar region and the east edge of the
Everglades. The agency began its study last fall at the command of
U.S. House appropriations leaders who were irked by the Florida
legislature's proposal to make the corps give more money to owners
of condemned land; Lawton Chiles vetoed the proposal last year, but
now Gov. Jeb Bush and his new water managers support it. Sen. Bob
Graham has warned that the GAO study will be scathing, and that it
could be a sign of further souring in the federal-state Everglades
``marriage.'' (King, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TERRORISM _ BOONE, N.C. _ Coverage of a speech by the nation's
domestic terrorism czar, Neil Gallagher, assistant director of the
FBI's National Security Division at Western Carolina University. He
is expected to talk a little about the hunt for Eric Rudolph.
(Harmon, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHWESTERN-UNIV-PRES _ In the 18 years since Dr. Roy Shilling
took the helm of Southwestern University, the school has increased
the size of its permanent endowment tenfold, tripled the number of
student applications and been named among the best regional liberal
arts colleges in the nation. Shilling announced Friday he will be
stepping down from the presidency effective June 2000. (LeBlanc,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
