<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-RECIPES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
(Eds.: See also: SPRING-VEGETABLES 
 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRIED BABY ARTICHOKES
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The recipe is from ``The Artichoke Cookbook'' by Patricia Rain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 quart oil
</P>
<P>
   10 small or baby artichokes
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup each: all-purpose flour and baking mix (recipe developed
with Bisquick)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil to 350 degrees for deep frying in a wok, heavy saucepan
or deep fryer. Clean and trim tough leaves from artichokes,
removing chokes if necessary. Cut in halves or quarters, depending
upon size. Set aside. Prepare batter: Beat egg and milk. Continue
beating; add salt, garlic salt, flour, baking mix and baking
powder. Stir in onion and parsley. Add prepared artichoke pieces to
batter. If batter seems too thin, add a little flour.
</P>
<P>
   Deep fry in hot oil, turning artichoke pieces until they are
browned, about 3 minutes. Remove cooked artichokes from the pan and
return the oil to 350 degrees before adding additional artichokes.
Drain on paper towels. Sprinkle with salt if desired. Makes 10
servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARTICHOKE AND MUSHROOM SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Houston Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
2 whole fresh artichokes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   Dash of white wine
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 fresh mushrooms, cleaned and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon prepared Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Snip 1/2 inch off tops of artichokes; trim outer leaves. Cover
in water; add lemon juice, garlic and wine. Cover pan; boil 20 to
30 minutes or until a petal near the center pulls out easily.
Remove from pan and turn upside down to drain.
</P>
<P>
   Or microwave: Rinse artichokes well in cool water. Pull off
lowest petals and trim stem even with bottom of choke. Cut 1/2 inch
off the top. Place upside down with a small amount of water (do not
use lemon juice, garlic and wine as in conventional method) in
microwave-safe casserole. Cover with lid or vented plastic wrap.
Microwave on high 7 minutes. Remove from dish; let drain.
</P>
<P>
   Remove heart of 1 artichoke, chop and combine with mushrooms.
Reserve remaining artichoke.
</P>
<P>
   For a marinade, combine sherry vinegar, salt, pepper, oil and
mustard (also include lemon juice, garlic and wine if you
microwaved the artichokes). Marinate artichoke mushroom-mixture 6
to 8 hours or overnight. Remove thistly part from remaining
artichoke and fill with mushroom mixture. Garnish plate with
julienne of red tip lettuce. Makes 1 serving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED ASPARAGUS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``Vegetables'' by James Peterson (William Morrow, $35).
Peterson writes that roasting is a great technique for cooking
asparagus, especially if it is watery or bland. It does cause some
loss of color, however.
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds medium asparagus
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Trim and peel asparagus, toss it in
olive oil and arrange in a baking dish just large enough to hold it
in a single layer. Sprinkle with salt and pepper. Roast 15 minutes.
Gently toss or push asparagus around with a spoon every 5 minutes
to help it cook evenly. Serve immediately or when cool. Makes 4
first-course or side-dish servings.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Asparagus
</P>
<P>
   From ``Vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to boil or steam asparagus before grilling. If stalks
are thicker than a pencil, peel them. Toss asparagus with a little
extra-virgin olive oil and fresh chopped herbs such as thyme or
marjoram. Grill only long enough to heat through and brown
slightly, 7 to 12 minutes. Two pounds asparagus will provide 4
generous side-dish servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASPARAGUS QUICHE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Great for a spring lunch or Easter brunch. From ``Good
Housekeeping Best Recipes 1999'' (William Morrow, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons solid all-vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons plus 4 cups cold water, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 pound asparagus, trimmed and cut into 3/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon coarsely ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces Gruyere or Swiss cheese, coarsely shredded (1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   Stir flour and 1/4 teaspoon salt with a fork in a medium bowl.
With pastry blender or 2 knives used scissor-fashion, cut in
margarine with shortening until mixture resembles coarse crumbs.
Sprinkle 4 tablespoons water over flour mixture, 1 tablespoon at a
time, mixing lightly with fork after each addition, until dough is
just moist enough to hold together. Shape dough into a disc; wrap
with plastic wrap and refrigerate 30 minutes or until firm enough
to roll.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in 2-quart saucepan, heat remaining 4 cups water to
boiling over high heat. Add asparagus and cook 6 to 8 minutes until
tender (or cook in microwave). Drain and rinse with cold running
water. Drain and set aside. Preheat oven to 425 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   On lightly floured surface, with floured rolling pin, roll dough
into a round 11/2 inches larger than diameter than inverted 9-inch
pie plate. Gently ease dough into pie plate; trim edge, leaving a
1-inch overhang. Fold overhang under; bring up over pie plate rim.
Pinch dough to form decorative edge. With fork, prick dough at
1-inch intervals.
</P>
<P>
   Line pie crust with foil; fill with pie weights or dried beans.
Bake pie crust 15 minutes; remove foil with weights. Bake crust 10
minutes longer, or until crust is golden. (If crust puffs up during
baking, gently press it to pie plate with back of spoon.) Reduce
heat to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in medium bowl, with wire whisk or fork, mix eggs,
half-and-half, pepper, nutmeg and remaining 1/2 teaspoon salt until
well-blended. Sprinkle asparagus and cheese into crust. Pour
half-and-half mixture over asparagus and cheese. Place sheet of
foil underneath pie plate; crimp foil edges to form a rim to catch
any drips during baking. Bake quiche 40 to 45 minutes, until knife
inserted in center comes out clean. Place on wire rack to cool;
serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 main-dish servings, each: 325 calories, 12 grams
protein, 19 grams carbohydrate, 22 grams fat, 141 milligrams
cholesterol, 380 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BROCCOLINI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The following broccolini recipes were developed for Mann Packing
Co. by Peggy Fallon, a California cookbook author and cooking
teacher. For more recipes and information, access Mann's Web site
(www.broccoli.com).
</P>
<P>
   Broccolini is also known as Asparation, as it's called by Sanbon
Inc., its other grower.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ASIAN BROCCOLINI
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
From The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons each: oyster sauce and chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon teriyaki sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon each: sugar and Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound (2 bunches) broccolini
</P>
<P>
   Combine oyster sauce, broth, teriyaki sauce, sugar and sesame
oil in a small saucepan. Bring to a boil and cook, stirring
occasionally, until sauce thickens. Remove from heat and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bring 3 to 4 quarts water to a boil in a large pot. Add
broccolini; cook 3 minutes or until just tender. Drain immediately
in a colander and shake off excess water. Transfer to a platter and
drizzle with the warm soy dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings, each: 33 calories, 3 grams protein, 6 grams
carbohydrates, 1 gram fat, 2 milligrams cholesterol, 323 milligrams
sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BROCCOLINI WITH HONEY-MUSTARD DIPPING SAUCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey mustard
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces (1 bunch) broccolini
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces thinly sliced prosciutto or ham
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine sour cream and honey mustard until well
blended. Cook broccolini in boiling salted water 30 seconds. Rinse
with cold water to stop the cooking; pat dry with paper towels. Cut
prosciutto slices lengthwise into 1-inch strips. Tightly wrap 1 or
2 prosciutto strips diagonally around each broccolini stalk,
leaving about 1 inch of stalk showing at the bottom. Arrange on a
platter with the sour cream dipping sauce. Serve chilled or at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings, each: 69 calories, 4 grams protein, 3 grams
carbohydrates, 5 grams fat, 15 milligrams cholesterol, 222
milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIXED GREENS BROCCOSPROUTS SALAD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 cups mixed baby salad greens or baby spinach, washed and
patted dry
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup seedless red grapes, halved
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pecan pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces broccosprouts or salad-style sprout blends (recipe
developed with Fresh Alternatives)
</P>
<P>
   Raspberry vinaigrette (homemade or bottled)
</P>
<P>
   Place salad greens on large plate. Arrange grapes, pecans and
sprouts over greens. Dress lightly with vinaigrette. Makes 2 to 4
servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GREEN GOURMET GARLIC DIP &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 green gourmet garlic plants
</P>
<P>
   8 stems cilantro with leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream (can use low fat)
</P>
<P>
   Discard roots of garlic plants; finely chop plants, including
cloves. Blend cilantro with garlic to a paste, adding water and
salt. Mix well with sour cream. Refrigerate covered until chilled.
Use as a dip or dressing with chips, crackers or salads.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Substitute mayonnaise for sour cream and serve on
sandwiches or hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN GOURMET GARLIC CHUTNEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch green gourmet garlic, chopped (discard roots)
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cumin seeds (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 teaspoon fresh lemon or lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Jalapeno pepper to taste (optional)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons olive or vegetable oil (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Combine garlic, cilantro, cumin, juice, jalapeno and oil in
blender or food processor; process to a paste. Add water if needed.
Chill in covered jar in refrigerator, or freeze in freezer jar. Let
thaw before using. Add to beef, pork or chicken.
</P>
