<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLOS BUILD ON FAMILY LEGACY: A PERFECT WINE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The first thing you notice about Gina Gallo and her
brother Matt is that these are nice folks.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics would point out that as grandchildren of the late Julio
Gallo, they can afford to be. It was Julio Gallo who, along with
his brother Ernest, built the world's largest winery operation.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who's been interviewing winemakers for nigh on 20
years, I think I can spot a phony, and frankly my (long) list would
have some well-known names on it. But not these Gallo names.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, as the younger generation, they're in the forefront of
transforming Gallo from a jug-wine-only operation _ a wine
refinery, if you will _ into producers of very fine (some even
world-class) wines. Which is taking time (they're young),
dedication (it's obvious) and money (don't even ask).
</P>
<P>
   The results have been impressive. Gallo has successfully
launched such premium brands as Rancho Zabaco, Indigo Hills and
Anapamu, as well as the Gallo Sonoma single-vineyard wines that
stand up to California's finest. In the process, ``We retooled from
a bulk-wine facility to a fine-wine facility,'' Matt Gallo said.
</P>
<P>
   The two Gallo siblings were in Houston recently on a tour
celebrating Gallo's having been named Winery of the Year by Bon
Appetit magazine. The focus of this visit was on a line of wines
called Gallo of Sonoma, a set of several varietals that are
line-priced at $10 retail.
</P>
<P>
   Gina and Matt Gallo stressed that these wines are premium grapes
from top-notch growing areas and vineyards, made in the same way as
their more expensive wine: fermented in French oak barrels, for
example. But they want to keep the prices affordable. ``We want to
bring wine back to the lifestyle, make it just part of the grocery
bill,'' Gina Gallo said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what we tasted from Gallo of Sonoma:
</P>
<P>
   1997 Gallo of Sonoma Chardonnay _ (4 stars) _ fairly soft, but
with a little zing that comes from Russian River Valley grapes, a
primo spot in Sonoma for chardonnay (and pinot noir).
</P>
<P>
   1997 Zinfandel _ (3-1/2 stars) _ pretty good fruit from Dry
Creek Valley (the mother lode area for zin) and smooth; could use a
little more intensity, though.
</P>
<P>
   1995 Cabernet Sauvignon _ (4 stars) _ nice wine, with good fruit
and no harsh aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   1996 Merlot _ (3-1/2 stars) _ good flavor and structure, but,
like the zin, it needs a little more bounce to the ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: The merlot and zinfandel are reasonably priced for
what's in the bottle, while the cabernet and chardonnay rate as
bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of younger generations, that's who's in charge of a
Sonoma County winery called Seghesio.
</P>
<P>
   Nice folks, nice wines. You may have read about them in this
space before.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Cathy Seghesio was in town last week, and we tasted her
family's wines. One of them blew me away. She simply smiled and
said, ``I thought you'd like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a red wine made from the barbera grape. Barbera is an
Italian varietal that for decades was a workhouse blending grape in
California. Some wineries, though, used to make stellar wines from
it. Anybody remember the 1968 Louis Martini Special Selection
Barbera?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Seghesio is an old Sonoma County winery, dating to the
turn of the century. But the label on this new barbera indicated
the grapes came from Mendocino County to the north. Mendocino is
not exactly a hotbed of barbera. What gives, I asked Seghesio, who
does national marketing for the winery?
</P>
<P>
   It seems her husband, Pete Seghesio Jr., the winery's general
manager, wanted to buy some barbera. Problem was, he couldn't
locate any of sufficient quality.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Seghesio continued the story. ``So Pete took out an ad in
the Santa Rosa Press Democrat (the local Sonoma County newspaper)
that said, `Looking for barbera.' Everybody laughed at him, but he
thought he'd give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one day, this man up in Mendocino called and said he'd
been selling his barbera to (a very large winery) that was using
the grapes to blend into their red table wines. He thought his
grapes were better than that, and would Pete like to buy them?
</P>
<P>
   ``So Pete went up, brought back a barrel of barbera. Except that
the man had only put in half a barrel of juice and filled the rest
of the barrel with oak chips. Even so, we could see just how good
those grapes were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we buy all his barbera.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a great story, I said. How much barbera can you make?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe 300-400 cases,'' she said. ``We sell most of it in
California. The rest goes to our best markets, which of course
includes Texas. You'll get'' _ she paused and lowered her eyes _
``14 cases.''
</P>
<P>
   That drop in the bucket for a state the size of Texas? I took
one more sip, and Kyle Britt of Prestige Wine Cellars here, who
distributes Seghesio, said, ``Well, there goes the allocation for
your ZIP code ...''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the 1997 Seghesio Barbera _ (5 stars) _ is
loaded to the gunwales with blackberry and blueberry fruit, with a
hint of raspberry. The vanilla from the oak barrels is in four-part
harmony, noticeable but not intrusive. The wine has good structure
but is not harshly tannic. And it has better balance than the
Flying Wallendas. In short, perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news, of course, is that (a) it won't be on shelves here
for another couple of weeks, (b) there won't be enough to fill an
eyedropper, and (c) it's pricey at $24.
</P>
<P>
   And worth every cent.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, we also tasted a few other Seghesio wines,
including:
</P>
<P>
   1998 Pinot Grigio _ (4 stars) _ a very nice rendition of a
crisp, flavorful, Italian-varietal white wine. About $14.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Zinfandel (Sonoma County) _ (4-1/2 to 5 stars) _ a rich but
well-balanced, slightly peppery version of California's ``native''
grape. For $10-$11, you won't find a zin to beat this one.
</P>
<P>
   1997 ``Home Ranch'' Zinfandel _ (4-1/2 stars) _ is the best
version of this wine I've had, with gutsy fruit and some sharp
angles, but all in all, a right tasty bottle of zin. ``Bigger''
than the Sonoma County Zin, and a little rougher, but would go
better with grilled meats, for example. About $29.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Keyhole Ranch Pinot Noir _ (3-1/2 stars) _ a pretty big
version of what's usually a delicate grape, this wine was a bit
standoffish to me. The aromatics, so important in pinot noir, were
muted, and the flavor a bit shy, too. Maybe it needs more bottle
age. About $19.
</P>
<P>
   1997 Sangiovese _ (3-1/2 to 4 stars) _ had that nice dusty,
dried-rose-petal nuance, although the fruit could've been a tad
brighter. This is one of the more authentically Italian-tasting
sangioveses from California. About $19.
</P>
<P>
   As we were leaving Collina's on Richmond, I noticed there was
one more sip left of the barbera, and not wanting it to go to
waste, I helped myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oops, there's goes another ZIP code's allocation,'' Britt
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WINE RATING: 5 stars, outstanding; 4 stars, fine; 3 stars, good; 2
stars, fair; 1 star, poor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
