A1021 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIFTGIVING01-COX     03-31 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTGIVING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The season for giving
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Spring may signal the end of cold weather, but it
certainly doesn't mean the end of showers. Between weddings,
graduations, anniversaries and the occasional birth, it's not
unusual to receive a flood of invitations and announcements this
time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Face it: Each time you open one of those thick, elegant
envelopes, it means you'll probably be buying a gift. And spending
half a day meandering through malls, seeking out that special gift
is a luxury few can afford. But, gift giving needn't be the
time-consuming chore it once was. Thanks to some sophisticated,
computerized gift registries, purchasing the perfect present now
can take less time than deciding which video you're going to watch
on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Federated Alliance, the corporation that owns several
department store chains nationwide, including Macy's and Rich's. It
boasts 250 stores, and all are connected to the Federated Gift
Alliance. Through this system, you can actually do your shopping
while stuck in the morning commute, if you have access to a cell
phone and a credit card. For instance, if your cousin is getting
married in California and is registered at Macy's, you can dial up
the nearest store, check out what's on your cousin's list, select
an item and request that it be wrapped and shipped _ all without
having to make the trek to the mall, much less break a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, brides continue to top the list of those
signing up for registries.
</P>
<P>
   And, what's on their wish lists?
</P>
<P>
   Traditional household items are still popular, but with a more
casual twist, said Peggy Kocher, Rich's corporate gift registry
manager. ``We now see brides mixing and matching patterns in china
and silverware as well as textiles. Also, some of the makers of
silverware are giving their traditional patterns a new look by
using a matte finish, and that's very popular right now with
brides,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, brides can have their mothers' patterns that have
been tailored to a more contemporary lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   At Bed, Bath &AMP; Beyond, brides and grooms can register for items
to fill every nook and cranny of their home. The gamut runs from
bedding to cookware and even rose-tinted light bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not everyone's in the market for china or crystal these
days,'' says Phyllis Lovelace, Hastings Nature &AMP; Garden Center
manager. She recently implemented a gift registry at the
110-year-old business on Peachtree Road.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true for older couples or those in a second
marriage, who might already have the basics. Couples moving into a
new home, in fact, might prefer gifts such as garden tools, bedding
plants, gardening books, trees _ even sod.
</P>
<P>
   At Home Depot, registrants can choose from a vast array of
possibilities, from patio furniture and home-decorating accessories
to faucets and, yes, even the kitchen sink.
</P>
<P>
   Something for everyone
</P>
<P>
   While brides make up the bulk of their registry business,
according to several retailers, expectant parents are increasingly
using this service. So it makes sense that baby gift registries are
becoming easier to find.
</P>
<P>
   Linking their gift registries with all store locations, chains
like Babies ``R'' Us, Toys ``R'' Us and Burlington's Baby Depot
offer convenience for shoppers who live out of the recipient's
area, as well as to mothers-to-be who can list preferences from
cribs to strollers and bottles to booties.
</P>
<P>
   Graduates, too, have climbed onto the registry bandwagon as have
those celebrating anniversaries and birthdays. There's even a trend
toward singles signing up for a year-round registry as a means of
collecting items they want on different gift-giving occasions.
</P>
<P>
   To fill that niche, Borders Books &AMP; Music on Peachtree Road
began a gift registry about a year ago. Here, grads who are media
buffs can sign up to receive their favorite tunes, films or books,
while some couples might prefer to compile a library or finish that
jazz CD collection.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ron Hancock, corporate services representative, the
store is testing this service before offering it at other Borders
locations.
</P>
<P>
   Have scanner, will shop
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't surprise anyone that registering for gifts is
pretty high-tech these days, especially at the large nationwide
chains.
</P>
<P>
   Target stores are hugely popular for their bridal and baby
shower registries and it's commonplace to see a bride or
mother-to-be armed with a hand-held scanner zipping through the
aisles, zapping everything from saucepans and crib sheets to tents
and everyday china.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kevin Schmitt, manager of the Target store at North
Point in Alpharetta (GA.), most people take about 30 to 40 minutes
to scan the items they want, then the information gets placed in a
computer linked to all Targets. Those shopping for gifts can go to
a free-standing kiosk at any Target location and get a printout of
the list.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us also uses the scanning system. You might think
that an overzealous youngster would use that scanner like a machine
gun, blasting everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not so,'' says Cathy Holden, department head for the juvenile
products and gift registry at the North Point store. ``From my own
experience, I would say that there are occasions where kids get
excited, but the parents are there to control them. Also kids are
pretty specific about what they want,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Morrow writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1457EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
