<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1023 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTERS-SHOPPING01-CO     03-31 1932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTERS-SHOPPING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf mecca has cultural, artistic assets, too
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA
</P>
<P>
   There's more to Augusta than golf.
</P>
<P>
   Although thousands of people will flock to the east Georgia city
from Monday through April 11 for the Masters Tournament, other
attractions await those who are in between rounds or who just don't
want to watch a dimpled little white ball fly through the air.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most interesting _ blending history, culture and
shopping _ are historic Riverwalk, on the banks of the Savannah
River, and Artists' Row on Broad Street. Here you can buy
everything from a blue willow porcelain teapot ($20) at the
Augusta-Richmond County Museum to a bag of Grits Pie Mix ($7) at
Spiffy Miffy's on Broad Street. Both areas are part of the effort
to revitalize the riverfront and downtown with shops, eateries and
galleries that attract visitors and locals alike.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta has long been associated with water. In 1736, Gen. James
Oglethorpe founded the city as a Colonial trading post along the
banks of the Savannah River. The river became the city's commercial
lifeline, carrying cotton, tobacco and other agricultural products
to the seaport of Savannah. However, the river that built Augusta
almost destroyed it. Periodic floods ravaged the city until the
city fathers built dams to regulate the river's flow. In 1913, the
city constructed a 56-foot levee to alleviate flooding in the
downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, Augusta's waterfront had became a blighted
area. During the mid-'80s, community leaders recognized its
potential as a tourist center and began breaking ground for the
development called Riverwalk. By the late '80s, the Shoppes of Port
Royal was opened. The riverfront mall included such upscale stores
as Colette's and Gucci. According to Jeannie Buttrum of the Georgia
Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism, ``the shopping area was
ahead of its time and proved to be commercially unsuccessful.'' It
closed in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But Riverwalk thrived as a cultural corridor. Today, after an
investment of $16 million, landscaped brick paths, seasonal flowers
and historical markers make it a place to enjoy concerts and
festivals or simply watch the water flow by.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The river) is calm, tranquil and has become a centerpiece of
the community,'' said Rebecca B. Rogers, director of communications
with the Augusta Metropolitan Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes referred to as Augusta's front porch, Riverwalk runs
from Fifth to 10th streets. Although a few souvenir shops dot the
area _ the Dock, Magnolia's on the River _ the riverfront is
essentially home to several museums with interesting gift shops.
</P>
<P>
   Begin your shopping foray at the Historic Cotton Exchange
Welcome Center &AMP; Museum (32 Eighth St.). In 1886, members of the
Augusta Cotton Exchange built this red brick structure that was
used by brokers until 1964. Tour the museum, pick up information
about activities in town and take home a souvenir of a miniature
bale of cotton ($2) or a burlap bag filled with cotton seeds ($4).
Also at the Welcome Center, you can order shirts and sweaters, caps
and visors from the Augusta National Golf Club. Pick up the
merchandise at the club gate or have it mailed to you.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite with kids of all ages is Fort Discovery/The National
Science Center (1 Seventh St.), which offers more than 250
interactive exhibits. Here you can walk on the moon, get videotaped
being chased by a dinosaur or fly a simulated jet. On a more
down-to-earth note, Jonathan Brandt, 8, from Columbia, S.C., was
exploring the science gift store on a recent Saturday morning. He
loved the policeman-shaped puppets ($18.95) and pronounced the
glow-in-the-dark yo-yo ($3.50) ``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   For a different type of experience, visit the Morris Museum of
Art (1 10th St.). Housed in the Riverfront Center, it contains a
permanent collection that surveys 200 years of painting in the
South. In its gift shop, visitors will find a treasure-trove of
goodies designed or made by Southern artists, such as a salt-glazed
pottery vase ($75) designed by Ben Owen III of Seagrove, N.C., or a
hand-blown glass ornament ($14.95) by Loretta Eby of Watkinsville.
</P>
<P>
   After doing Riverwalk, stroll two blocks south to Broad Street,
the main business street of Augusta. Its sunken, median parking was
designed by noted architect I.M. Pei in 1975 as part of a
redevelopment program.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of Broad Street's current renovation project is
Artists' Row, located in the 1000 block. Here, 14 visual artists
have revitalized the street by working and living in their studios,
many of which are warehouses more than 100 years old. A wide
variety of mediums is represented: paintings in watercolor, acrylic
and oil; porcelain painting; basket-making and pottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just celebrated our fifth anniversary,'' said artist
Will Fahnoe. ``Artists' Row was started by the city as a way to
recoup business for downtown. In the late '70s and '80s, businesses
fled to the malls. Many of these buildings were left empty.
Ceilings collapsed. We had to rewire. It was awful. I spent three
months just doing demolition. But the city has been wonderful,
paying rents in the first year. And exteriors have been renovated
as part of the Facade Grant Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't buy a building today,'' he said. ``The artists have
turned the street into gold.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the original artists, photographer Tom Barrett, remembers
that five years ago he had 35 black-and-white pictures in his
gallery Studio Fotografica. Today, he represents four photographers
and has more than 170 photographs. ``We have a way to go,'' says
Barrett. ``But restaurants are coming in and studios are offering
classes. Broad is bringing locals and tourists downtown again.''
</P>
<P>
   What's really attracting attention is First Friday. From 5-9
p.m. on the first Friday of each month, galleries and studios open
their doors and provide food and music. Each month, 800 to 1,000
locals and tourists take advantage of this laid-back way to view
new exhibitions and buy art.
</P>
<P>
   Browsing through the galleries, Gina and Mohammed Omari of
Augusta summed up what they liked best. ``Everything is so
diverse,'' she said, ``and all the art is done by local artisans.
That's what makes Artists' Row so special.''
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take 1-20 east to Riverwatch Parkway (Exit 66).
At the stoplight, turn left onto Riverwatch Parkway and proceed
downtown. Turn left on 10th Street, then right on Reynolds Street
to the Historic Cotton Exchange Welcome Center at 32 Eighth St.
Riverwalk is right here, and Broad Street is one street south.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Vary by store and gallery, but they generally are open
Tuesdays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Free parking in the lot adjacent to welcome center.
Free parking on Broad Street; also, a free parking deck at Ninth
and Ellis streets, one block off Broad Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Public restrooms at Eighth Street and Riverwalk and
Ninth Street and Riverwalk
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accessibility: Riverwalk is wheelchair-accessible; most stores
on Broad Street are wheelchair-accessible; studios and galleries on
second floors require climbing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-800-726-0243 for the Augusta Metropolitan
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boll Weevil Cafe &AMP; Sweetery. This casual restaurant, in a
150-year-old cotton warehouse on Riverwalk, features soups, salads,
sandwiches on home-baked bread, crepes, hand-tossed pizza and
veggies. Soups and salads range from $2.75 to $7.95, entrees from
$6.95 to $8.95. Hours: 11 a.m.-10 p.m. Mondays-Thursdays; 11
a.m.-11 p.m. Fridays-Saturdays. 10 Ninth St. 706-722-7772.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nacho Mama's. Order shrimp tacos, spinach-and-cheese
quesadillas, nachos and bean burritos off the blackboard menu.
Prices range from $1.50 for a black bean-and-rice taco to $6.95 for
a shrimp-and-cheese quesadilla. Lunch: 11:30 a.m.-2:30 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays; dinner: 6-10 p.m. Sundays-Saturdays. 976 Broad
St. 706-724-0501.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Luigi's. Entrees include spaghetti, lasagna and chicken
parmigiana. In the mood for Greek? Try baked Greek chicken with
olive oil, lemon and herbs. The steaks are also high on the
must-try list. Luigi's is a favorite stop of professional golfers
during the Masters. Entrees range from $7 to $15. Hours: 5-11 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays; 11:30 a.m.-2 p.m. Fridays. 590 Broad St.
706-722-4056.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Radisson Riverfront. Located on Riverwalk, each of the 234
rooms has a view of the Savannah River. Rooms start at $89, suites
at $150. 2 10th St. 1-800-333-3333.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Azalea Inn. This Victorian bed-and-breakfast has 21 guest
suites, some with fireplaces and Jacuzzis. Rates range from $79 to
$150. Smoke-free environment. 312-334 Greene St. 706-724-3454.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rosemary Hall. A short drive over the Savannah River to
Riverwalk, this bed-and-breakfast has eight smoke-free rooms
ranging from $75 to $195. 804 Carolina Ave., North Augusta, SC.
1-800-531-5578.
</P>
<P>
   Shop talk
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling of shops we found at Riverwalk and on/around
Broad Street.
</P>
<P>
   Antiques/collectibles
</P>
<P>
   Antiques World Mall, 1124-30 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   Broad Street Antique Mall, 1224 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Antique Mall, 1243 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   JD's Antiques, 516 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   Logan &AMP; Co. Antiques, 1255 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   The Market Place Antiques, 1208 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   Merry's Trash &AMP; Treasures, 1236 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Ghingold Antiques, Collectibles &AMP; Curios, 1230-1232 Broad
St.
</P>
<P>
   Riverwalk Antique Depot, 505 Reynolds St.
</P>
<P>
   State Furniture, 1204 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   Art galleries/studios
</P>
<P>
   Artistic Perceptions, 551 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta Art Exchange Gallery, 1028 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
