<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1036 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-READINESS-TE     03-31 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-READINESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULD AMERICA FIGHT A WAR? CONGRESS, PENTAGON QUESTION MILITARY'S
DEPTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's military readiness has sharply eroded and
its armed forces are spread dangerously thin because of such
international operations as NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia,
many lawmakers and Pentagon planners say.
</P>
<P>
   ``What valuable dollars will be taken away from military
readiness accounts to pay for this?'' asked Sen. Jim Bunning of
Kentucky, one of several Republican senators who have complained
about the latest military operation in the troubled Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, added, ``Just where is the
money going to come from? Is it going to come from other defense
accounts, so other places in the world where we have troops are put
at risk?''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether the Clinton administration has spent
adequately to maintain the Pentagon's war-fighting capability as
the U.S. military is used increasingly as a world police force.
Since President Clinton took office Jan. 20, 1993, the U.S.
military has been pressed into action about 60 times in such places
as Iraq, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Rwanda, Somalia and Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   The constant wear and tear on weapons, the expenditure of
ammunition and ordnance and the human stress resulting from long
separations of soldiers from their families is all part of the
equation. Weapons have to be maintained and replaced, bullets and
bombs have to be replenished, and military personnel must have
enough down time to keep the armed forces at peak efficiency,
lawmakers and top officers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you right now that we are in the same situation we
were in the late 1970s with the hollow force,'' said Sen. James
Inhofe, R-Okla., chairman of the Senate Armed Services subcommittee
on readiness. ``We can't afford to dilute our military strength any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Gen. Richard Hawley, who directs the Air Combat
Command, said, ``Funding has simply not kept pace with the demands
on our force. Mission capable rates have slowly declined since
1990.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the Cold War, defense spending has declined
dramatically, dropping from $358 billion in 1990 to a projected
$267 billion in fiscal 2000. During the Cold War, spending on the
Pentagon averaged about $320 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that funding issues should not keep the United States
from carrying out its international obligations as the world's sole
surviving superpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remember that we are a European power,'' said Sen.
Joseph Biden, D-Del. ``For 54 years, we have kept as many as
365,000 troops in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   But even some staunch supporters of President Clinton caution
that America's military might needs some shoring up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stability of the entire planet depends on the readiness
and availability of the U.S. armed forces,'' said Sen. Bob Kerrey,
D-Neb. ``We should not fritter them away in peacekeeping missions
in countries which do not rise to the level of vital American
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad are things at the Pentagon?
</P>
<P>
   _ The Air Force says that, as of Feb. 1, it had a shortage of
855 pilots, and that number is expected to grow to nearly 2,000 by
Jan. 1. Pilots cite frequent operations as a top reason for
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 25 percent of the Air Force's F-15 fighter planes need
repair at any given time and only 54 percent of its B-1B bomber
fleet is usable, prompting both planes to be called ``hangar
queens.'' ``We have one-third of our aircraft broken at all
times,'' said Maj. Monty Diehl, a maintenance officer at Langley
Air Force Base, Va.
</P>
<P>
   _ The grounding of Air Force planes because of a shortage of
parts has jumped more than 50 percent since 1990, and stripping
planes for parts, called ``cannibalization,'' has jumped 78 percent
in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Navy's Atlantic Fleet says it is short 7,600 sailors.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Marines' amphibious assault vehicles are, on average, 28
years old. Marine trucks and artillery vehicles are 17 years old,
on average. The CH-46, the Marine helicopter to be replaced by Bell
Helicopter's V-22 Osprey, is, on average, 31 years old. ``Some of
our airframes are older than their pilots,'' said Lt. Gen. Peter
Pace, commander of the Marine's Atlantic forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, since Operation Desert Storm, has cut eight divisions
and 630,000 troops. But it is facing deployments, Army officials
say, at rates that are four times what they were during the Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
   Recruitment and retention has become such a troubling issue for
the Pentagon that some lawmakers have begun talking about
reinstating the draft. Rep. Stephen Buyer, R-Ind., told a House
panel last year that too many people are escaping their civic duty.
``There are benefits to a draft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days before the airstrikes in Yugoslavia began,
Pentagon chiefs were telling a House Armed Services subcommittee
that America's war machine is showing its age.
</P>
<P>
   And despite Clinton's plans to boost Pentagon spending by $112
billion over the next five years, Hawley of the Air Force and other
top commanders say the figure is $50 billion too low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fixing readiness is not unlike trying to turn the Titanic _ it
takes a long time for even large rudder inputs to have a noticeable
effect,'' Hawley said. ``The funding increases are not sufficient
to fix all our problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Harold W. Gehman Jr. said the drop in troop numbers,
coupled with the increase in operations, is spreading America's
forces too thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we have downsized our military forces while using them
more frequently, maintaining our readiness is more difficult than
during the Cold War,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The readiness debate needs to go on until we find a way to
appropriately fund the right mix of operations and training,
modernization and quality of life, spare parts and engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   Pace, the Marine commander, said the corps has jumped through
hoops to maintain its status as the nation's ``911 force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have identified and exploited all available efficiencies,''
he said. ``We implemented improved business practices by reducing
inventories, saved on spares and parts by buying used items and
even manufacturing our own.''
</P>
<P>
   But some in Washington say they believe that the Pentagon must
share in the blame for its problems and that it has done little to
cut costs on big-dollar procurement programs.
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, for example, has been a regular
critic of Pentagon procurement programs, accusing several,
including Lockheed Martin's F-22 program and Boeing's FA-18E/F, of
being over budget and off schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, recently noted that
the Army bought thousands of trucks that were delivered behind
schedule and $100 million over budget. Moreover, the trucks' cabs
began rusting before the vehicles left the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO criticized the Army for selecting Stewart &AMP; Stevenson
Services Inc., a Houston-based company, for the work in 1991. It
noted that the company had no experience in building trucks or
combat vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Liesl Heeter, a defense budget analyst with the Center for
Strategic and Budgetary Assessments in Washington, said Pentagon
readiness, by many measures, has declined. But she added that the
Defense Department ``has pretty high standards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. always has a very big advantage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
