<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GASOLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPLY PROBLEMS PUMP UP GAS PRICES IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN  
 and KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gasoline prices in California rose sharply in
March to per-gallon averages of $1.31 in Los Angeles and $1.61 in
San Francisco, increases that were spurred by two recent refinery
fires and rising worldwide oil costs.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, gas prices have jumped 31 cents per gallon since March
11 in Northern California, and 14 cents per gallon in Southern
California, according to the California State Automobile
Association, an affiliate of the American Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   Although prices at the pump remain remarkably low in much of the
country, a plan by the world's leading oil producing nations to
tighten supplies is expected to drive up the price of fuel even
before the peak summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the average price for regular self-serve unleaded
gasoline is $1.08 per gallon, an AAA spokesman said Wednesday. The
cost in Hawaii is $1.54 and in California as a whole, $1.48.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Supervisor Michael Yaki said he would ask the
Federal Trade Commission to investigate gas pricing, adding that
the San Francisco Bay area had always been the ``cash cow'' for oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refuse to take any of their explanations anymore,'' Yaki
said. ``What's pretty clear is that any excuse will do to afford
the oil companies an excuse to gouge the people of the Bay area.
We've had refinery fires and explosions in the past and oil tankers
running aground and we've never had a price spike like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The price spike in Northern California is attributed in part to
two recent refinery fires _ one at a Tosco Refining Co. plant, the
other at a Chevron refinery. Problems at the plants in Northern
California mean companies must to turn to out-of-state suppliers
for gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These shipments are only scheduled to come through by
mid-April,'' said Susanne Garfield, a spokeswoman for the
California Energy Commission. ``That's good news. Having more of
the product on the market will ease fear and speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Until that supply arrives, the laws of supply and demand will
drive up the cost around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors also are contributing to the higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil jumped almost $3 a barrel when members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed last month to
cut production and reduce the world's oil glut.
</P>
<P>
   Industry specialists said gas prices are generally higher in
Northern California because there are fewer gas stations due in
part to high land costs.
</P>
<P>
   And gasoline prices are typically higher in California because
of strict federal pollution regulations that require use of
cleaner-burning fuels.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Mike Ross eased his Mitsubishi Galant into a
Texaco gas station Tuesday, took a look at the prices _ $1.67 to
$1.87 a gallon, depending on the grade _ and whipped out his cell
phone to complain about the prices to a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Then he reluctantly pumped a few dollars of gas. ``Let me put it
this way _ this is all I've got,'' he said, holding a crumpled $5
bill and a couple of dollar bills. ``And I'm not going to buy any
more than I have to at $1.67 a gallon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
