<HEADER>
A1058 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNTERTENORS-2TAKES-     03-31 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTERTENORS-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MALE ALTO TENOR FIELD IS GETTING CROWDED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Matthew Gurewitsch's most recent articles on theater have appeared
in The Atlantic Monthly and The Wall Street Journal.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once upon a time, there was a countertenor who had
his niche to himself. ``The most remarkable countertenor of the
20th century,'' Sir Michael Tippett called Alfred Deller. The quote
blazes off the recent reissue of the Deller Consort's John Dowland
anthology ``Awake Sweet Love,'' on Vanguard, which dates back to
1966.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. The morning mail brings an advance copy of ``Heroes,''
Andreas Scholl's new London CD, in stores next month, accompanied
by a fancy brochure citing Opera magazine to the effect that Scholl
is ``undoubtedly the best-equipped countertenor of the day, perhaps
any day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyrichord quotes Fanfare magazine to tout Russell Oberlin, whose
anthologies of medieval music, taped in the late 1950s, are
enjoying an enduring CD renaissance: ``He was the century's finest
countertenor. ... We have no countertenors who sing like this
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The field is getting crowded. Time to strike the male alto from
the rare-species list.
</P>
<P>
   To appreciate how well established this once marginal vocal
category has become, consider the case of David Daniels, who makes
his Metropolitan Opera debut on Saturday evening in a revival of
Handel's ``Giulio Cesare,'' with an encore scheduled for April 27
in the form of a recital at Alice Tully Hall.
</P>
<P>
   It was with the premiere of this Met production in 1988 that
Jeffrey Gall and Daniel Dash struck for their brothers the blow
that in 1955 Marian Anderson struck for blacks, opening the doors
of the nation's premiere opera house to a class of artists formerly
excluded. As in the case of Anderson, who was invited too late to
be heard in her glory, there was something disappointing and token
about the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   In the groundbreaking Peter Sellars production of the opera,
Gall had already played the title role as the Nixonesque kingpin of
the free world, a performance that brought him international
acclaim. At the Met, his role was that of Cleopatra's brother
Tolomeo, her effete rival for the Egyptian throne. He looked like a
minor satrap from ``Star Wars Meets Cleopatra'' and had little to
sing. As Nireno, the royal siblings' double-dealing confidant, Dash
had even less.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels has the title role on his agenda for next winter at the
Florida Grand Opera, but his Met role is that of Sesto, who stalks
through the opera seeking revenge for his father, the murdered
Pompey. No, it is not Caesar, but a role with which, in the Sellars
production, Lorraine Hunt scored a triumph. The Met's previous
Sesto was Hilda Harris, another mezzo-soprano. The current Tolomeo
is the well-established Brian Asawa, in 1991 the first countertenor
to win the Metropolitan Opera Auditions; the fast-rising Daniel
Taylor plays Nireno.
</P>
<P>
   On his debut CD, a Handel disk for Virgin, Daniels sings
Caesar's smoothly menacing duet with horn, ``Va tacito,'' and
Sesto's ``L'angue offeso,'' heaving with shame and
self-recrimination. The recent Handel revival has taught us how
wide an emotional spectrum Handel's characters encompass.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels rejoices in the possibilities, from the quivering,
outraged coloratura of Tamerlano's ``A dispetto'' (a souvenir of
his thrilling portrayal at Glimmerglass Opera in Cooperstown, N.Y.)
to the heartbroken, introspective legato of Ariodante's ``Scherza
infida.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opera house, Daniels sticks to the repertory in which
countertenors are no longer a novelty: notably, Baroque roles
originally sung as trouser parts or by castratos. This spring, in
Rome, he takes on Oberon, in Britten's ``Midsummer Night's Dream,''
the first great role for a modern countertenor (written for
Deller).
</P>
<P>
   As a recitalist, however, he pushes the envelope into
``standard'' repertory, written when the countertenor as a species
did not exist. Some are startled to hear him perform the Brahms
Songs With Viola (Op. 91), one of which is sung in the person of
the Virgin Mary. That Brahms, Beethoven, Schubert and other
composers whose music Daniels likes probably never heard grown men
singing in the range of a mezzo-soprano does not frighten him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I can bring as much variety of color and drama to the
recital repertoire as to opera,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Bejun Mehta is another countertenor whose career is growing
fast. The story has made the rounds how it was a profile of Daniels
in The New Yorker that opened Mehta's eyes to his calling. Like
Daniels, he was a former boy soprano; indeed, one of renown, with a
Delos CD to his credit that made a fan of Leonard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Like Daniels, he never set out to be a countertenor. But their
attempts to remake themselves in conventional categories (tenor for
Daniels, baritone for Mehta) only made them miserable. One day
Daniels shyly confided in his teacher that he had ``another
voice,'' and suddenly he was on his way.
</P>
<P>
   As Mehta, 30, tells it, he read this, put down the magazine,
stood up from his chair and started making sound. The downtown
debut that ensued almost immediately in Handel's ``Esther'' with
Millennial Arts Productions was as stunning for its fluency,
articulation and power as for its emotional abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Next came Handel's ``Partenope'' at the New York City Opera last
fall, several concerts here and abroad in which Mehta spelled an
indisposed Daniels, and a recital for Marilyn Horne's ``On Wings of
Song'' series at the Kosciuszko Foundation. Like Daniels, Mehta was
not shy about venturing into the standard repertory, from Brahms to
Barber and Britten. His performances justified every choice.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the recital, Mehta remarked that until recently,
he had never liked countertenors very much: ``Something about the
singing struck you as artificial: strained, not otherworldly. We're
on an arc of legitimization. When countertenors first came along,
they got jobs if they had the notes, and the notes didn't even have
to be pretty. Then people started demanding style, range, dynamic
control, emotional depth: all the things they demanded of `normal'
singers for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already know what the next phase will be. Young kids are
coming to me, asking me to teach them, kids who never thought about
being anything else. A lot that informs my singing comes from my
experience as a baritone. For the next generation, being a
countertenor is not this exotic thing. One of my great goals is to
cement the countertenor as just a voice.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, who is all of 33, marvels that music schools have
countertenors now: ``That was unheard of when I was a student.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite vanishing from sight for about two centuries, the
countertenor has a history stretching back at least to the Middle
Ages. Henry Purcell, the pre-eminent composer of 17th-century
Britain, wrote for countertenors and was a countertenor himself.
But the beast we know on the brink of the millennium, like the
early-music movement, is a creation of this century.
</P>
<P>
   An unsystematic survey of the recorded history from Deller
forward tends to confirm Mehta's analysis. Deller himself was an
artist of taste and expressivity, though perhaps too smitten with
melancholy. Long lines flow like dark ribbons of honey, though the
ends often fray like thread.
</P>
<P>
   He is at his most captivating in Britten's own recording of ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream'' on the London label, entering the action
shrill with monarchic fury at Elizabeth Harwood's equally unbridled
Tytania. But against the rainbow display of emotion Asawa puts on
in Sir Colin Davis's recording of the opera for Philips, Deller's
reserve in subsequent scenes comes off bloodless indeed.
</P>
<P>
   For some listeners, Oberlin remains the touchstone, but from a
newcomer's vantage point, his art seems a hard taste to acquire. In
Bernstein's weird ``Messiah,'' cut and pasted into a pattern
nothing like Handel's own, Oberlin may be the weirdest feature,
mouthing his music phoneme by fastidious phoneme on an equally
fastidious and immaculate stream of pear-shaped tone.
</P>
<P>
   Breakthroughs of the countertenor have been occurring with some
regularity. A Purcell recital by Andrew Dalton released on Etcetera
in 1984 stands out in memory for its intimacy and unaffected
dignity. Aficionados will know the names of James Bowman, Michael
Chance, Jochen Kowalski, Derek Lee Ragin and many more, past and
present.
</P>
<P>
   To a greater or lesser extent, they are cult figures all; of
each it has been said at one time or another that in him the ideal
of the castrato _ range, flexibility and brilliance of the female,
muscularity of the male _ has at last been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Pure speculation, of course. Meanwhile, plenty of mezzo-sopranos
are outgunning, on sheer decibels, any countertenor who has yet
appeared, which may be why a big house like the Met still thinks it
best to cast a Jennifer Larmore as Handel's Julius Caesar.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at about the same time as Gall, Drew Minter struck one
critic as the Tebaldi to his colleague's Callas. As an illustration
of what Daniels calls Minter's ``style and class and artistry,''
his vivid Handel CD ``Arias for Senesino,'' recorded on Harmonia
Mundi France in 1986, serves perfectly. ``Love Letters From
Italy,'' a Lyrichord release from 1996, catches Minter as the
collaborator of the early-music group Artek in sophisticated yet
thrillingly immediate accounts of works by Monteverdi, Gagliano and
Sigismondo d'India.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond reclaiming the music of the castratos for male singers,
some countertenors are casting an eye on roles originally conceived
for women. Still, the most famous cluster of trouser roles _
adolescents like Mozart's Cherubino, in ``Le Nozze di Figaro,'' and
Richard Strauss's Octavian, in ``Der Rosenkavalier,'' as well as
his Composer, in ``Ariadne auf Naxos'' _ may remain the province of
mezzo-sopranos, at least for a time.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, at any rate, has no designs on them. ``Octavian is too
high, and the orchestration is too big,'' he says. ``And the role
just doesn't interest me. If other countertenors want to sing it
and they can do it, more power to them. Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   One good reason, at least as far as Cherubino and Octavian are
concerned, is that an androgynous note is integral to the perfume
of these parts. Baba the Turk, in Stravinsky's ``Rake's Progress,''
subsumes a likely homosexual subtext intended by the librettists
W.H. Auden and Chester Kallman into the image of a bearded female,
a part Asawa has played with gusto and satin vocalism on film under
the baton of Esa-Pekka Salonen.
</P>
<P>
   If the countertenor is not yet ``just a voice,'' we have reached
the point where any given countertenor pretty much has the freedom
to be as great, as vain, as inventive or as bizarre an artist as
anyone else. Jeffrey Dooley and a Baroque ensemble have recorded a
Stephen Foster CD, ``Dear Friends and Gentle Hearts,'' due for
release on Lyrichord.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tour de force,'' says a label executive, but you must have
had to be there. A novelty I look forward to is ``Epitaph,'' on
Opus 111, featuring Sverrir Godjonsson in a womb-to-tomb cycle of
Icelandic folk songs.
</P>
<P>
   After ``The Dark is My Delight,'' a decorous debut album of
16th-century lute songs for RCA, Asawa has returned on the same
label with ``Vocalise,'' swamping his svelte sound in rich, gooey
arrangements of Rachmaninoff, Faure, Medtner and Villa-Lobos.
</P>
<P>
   The hype surrounding Scholl's forthcoming ``Heroes'' may not do
him much of a favor. For one thing, the album competes with his own
Handel CD ``Ombra Mai Fu,'' out this month on Harmonia Mundi
France, the specialized label from which the London star machine
recruited him to an exclusive contract.
</P>
<P>
   For another, Scholl's notion of the heroic has room for long
spells of self-doubt, which in his case translates to a penchant
for scooped, limp phrasing. Scrupulous musicianship and cultivated
sound notwithstanding, the program is more dutiful than exciting.
</P>
<P>
   A livelier side of his personality came through in a Harmonia
Mundi album with Pascal Bertin and Dominique Visse. Scholl crooned
Carmen's Habanera, Bertin had at ``My Way,'' and Visse hiccuped
through Offenbach's drunk act for ``La Perichole.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, the Three Countertenors warbled ``O Sole Mio,''
``Maria'' and ``Una furtiva lagrima.'' The CD was recently
withdrawn in deference to legal eagles asserting the franchise of
The Three Tenors. If countertenors in any numbers now pose a threat
to the troika of Carreras, Domingo and Pavarotti, they have come
farther than anyone can have imagined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1538EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
