<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEGEROV-MUSIC-$ADV0     03-31 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEGEROV-MUSIC-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAXIM VENGEROV, A GIFTED RUSSIAN VIOLINIST, RISE CONTINUES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Lawrence B. Johnson is the music critic of The Detroit News.  
 By LAWRENCE B. JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The young Siberian Maxim Vengerov continues to stake out his
ground among the most gifted and engaging violinists of, let's say,
the last 25 years. Let's say that, because ``half-century'' or,
indeed, ``modern times'' has an inescapable ring of hyperbole. Yet
Vengerov's magnificent new recording of Brahms's Violin Concerto,
with Daniel Barenboim and the Chicago Symphony (Teldec
0630-17144-2; CD), immediately brings to mind classic performances
available on compact disk.
</P>
<P>
   Vengerov, now 24, offers uncommonly personal Brahms, and it
resonates with that rare blend of intellectual depth, technical
finesse and lyric beauty that one associates with Jascha Heifetz's
patrician recording with Fritz Reiner and the Chicago Symphony,
from 1957 (on RCA), or Isaac Stern's stormy reading with Eugene
Ormandy and the Philadelphia Orchestra, from 1959 (on Sony).
</P>
<P>
   Lesser strengths would scarcely support the leisurely tempos
that invest Vengerov's performance with its transcendent
spirituality. Moreover, from the first measures of the broadly
paced opening movement, the easy rapport between violinist and
conductor is manifest and unflagging. Barenboim accomplishes the
critical double task of limning the concerto's symphonic structure
yet setting off the violin to optimum advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Vengerov conspicuously command the spotlight. The
single feature of this enterprise that most belies his years is his
essentially undemonstrative musical bearing. He can muster power
aplently, but the real magnetism lies in his restraint and his
subtle inflection, and in the profundity of ideas thus illuminated.
</P>
<P>
   Vengerov provides his own cadenza in the opening movement. Ever
since Brahms's day, most violinists have played the cadenza written
by Joseph Joachim, the most celebrated virtuoso of the time and the
composer's friend and technical consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Heifetz, a notable exception, substituted his own concise,
brilliant cadenza. By comparison, Vengerov's is a veritable
rhapsody, a lengthy ``improvisation'' rich with adroit spins on
Brahms's thematic ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The songful Andante, always arresting in competent hands, here
becomes a reflection of unexpected intimacy. In a way I've never
quite experienced before, Vengerov connects this movement with its
famously prayerful counterpart in the First Piano Concerto.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the finale, with all its propulsive energy, Vengerov
remains the elegant craftsman. Here he hews closer to the cool
precision of Heifetz than to the withering intensity of Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Vengerov veritably revels in the Chicago Symphony's luxurious
virtuosity and enjoys an equally felicitious partnership with
Barenboim as the pianist in Brahms's D minor Violin Sonata, which
fills out the disk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
