<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNDERWATER-RESTAURANT     03-31 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERWATER-RESTAURANT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE FISH WATCH YOU EAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel _ The Red Sea Star Restaurant began with an
underwater vision and ended up a vision underwater: a whimsical
restaurant deep in the Gulf of Eilat, where diners devour fish
platters under the scrutiny of fish peering in at them through
portholes.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala Serfaty, the restaurant's designer, was four months
pregnant and snorkeling in the Red Sea off Egypt when the concept
came to her. If the reef were soft, she thought, and you could
float weightlessly inside it, it would be just like a womb. Humans
would love it, she said to herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it sounds totally weird now, but I knew then that I
wanted to create an underwater environment,'' Ms. Serfaty, who
works in Tel Aviv, said recently. ``I wanted to create an interior
space that would merge with the sea, where the light and color and
language of shapes would play together in a kind of Ping-Pong.''
</P>
<P>
   From this lofty vision came the down-to-earth, or rather,
submerged, reality: a new tourist attraction in Eilat, a
southeastern city that, esthetically, is a sort of Israeli Las
Vegas _ without the gambling. The restaurant is still working out
the kinks peculiar to an underwater dining establishment, such as
how to keep food hot as it travels into the sea from a rooftop
kitchen. But the offshore decor is already attracting attention
from design aficionados in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Looking like a winged creature, the canopied entrance to the
restaurant sits at the end of a long pier jutting into the Gulf of
Eilat. Diners descend in an elevator to a depth of 20 feet beneath
the sea. The elevator doors open into a kind of reverse aquarium.
Outside the 62 portholes, school after school of exotic fish glide
by, dipping in and out of the coral gardens that wrap around the
restaurant. Overhead, the sea washes over the skylights, making it
abundantly _ and dizzyingly _ clear that one is submerged.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Serfaty said she sought to insure a feeling of equilibrium
underwater by designing wavy window frames and tables that reflect
the rippling water outside. Still, some visitors complain at first
of seasickness and need a period of acclimatization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just hold off on the food for a bit, if you don't mind
terribly,'' a German visitor, Uwe Stein, told the waitress as she
handed him a menu.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the furniture and lighting, inspired by sea creatures,
play off the surroundings. The amoeba-shaped tables are
coral-colored; their smooth, reddish surface is fashioned from
sand, painted with dye and coated with epoxy glue. In the bar, the
stools look like velvet sea urchins (the spineless variety) atop
seaweed legs of painted metal. Hanging from the ceiling are
crinkled silk starfish and pleated silk sea anemones that serve as
lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know a lot about interior decoration,'' said Rafael
Alterac, a retiree wearing a Greek fisherman's cap, who had parked
his boat at a nearby marina. ``But I like the beautiful feeling it
creates. It's like scuba diving without getting wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Serfaty perched atop a velvet stool, cooing at the fish.
``Shalom, shalom, sweetie,'' she said. It was just before lunch,
and the man she called the ``gardener'' was prettying up the
``grounds.'' He was, disconcertingly, floating outside the window,
wearing a mask and snorkel and brushing sediment from the corals
with gloved hands.
</P>
<P>
   The project began, fittingly, with another diver's dream. Ami
Ben Zvi, who owns a diving school in Eilat, collaborated with an
architect, Sefi Kiryati, and a marine engineer, Moshe Drimmer, to
form the structure. Made of metal, it was filled with water and
sunk on a concrete base into the sea floor. It went down in three
pieces, which were welded underwater and secured by spikes.
</P>
<P>
   The sea life there had died long before, killed by sewage and
overdevelopment. Doron Kairi, a marine-life expert, was hired to
reconstruct a reef under the supervision of the Israeli Nature
Reserve. Four years ago, he began transplanting fragments of living
coral from dying beds in the bay. Soon he was tending a coral
nursery, and bit by bit, he began landscaping with sponges, sea
stars and sea cucumbers. Once the habitat was recreated, the fish
followed _ butterfly fish, triggerfish, parrotfish, bluefish and
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old guys come here and see that the fish have returned, and
they feel like they're going back in time,'' said Roni Leni, the
project manager.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years after her snorkeling epiphany, Ms. Serfaty
heard about the sinking of the structure on the radio. A painter
and sculptor by training, she was already designing and
manufacturing aquatically inspired furniture and lighting at her
Tel Aviv workshop, home to Aqua Creations, the company she runs
with her husband, Albi. Ms. Serfaty put her fantasies on paper, bid
on the project and won the contract.
</P>
<P>
   When she saw the structure, it was forbidding: a cold, metallic
shell that she eventually covered with plaster and paint. To create
the warm space she had in her head, she knew she had to compensate
for the blue light pouring through the windows. She did so by
suffusing the room with yellows and reds. She used lighting and the
reflective surfaces of her shiny tables and mirrored floor, on
which a layer of transparent epoxy over sand makes a stylized
seabed.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is campy but soothing. As Ms. Serfaty had hoped, the
internal and external environments do play off each other. The fish
are reflected in the table surfaces, and images of the fake sea
creatures inside bounce on the reefs outside.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant's menu offers a mixed fare, but Ms. Serfaty was
disappointed that fish were on the menu at all. The chef, Oskar
Linden, said people were always asking him how he felt about
cooking creatures from the deep in such an environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I fry the fish, I try not to look in his eyes,'' he said,
a porpoise earring dangling from his ear lobe.
</P>
<P>
   When a whole grilled fish, head still attached, was set before
one diner, Noa Berger, an entire school of angelfish seemed to be
watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't feel quite right,'' Mrs. Berger said, taking a
timid bite and glancing up anxiously at her audience, who _ perhaps
she imagined it _ were clucking with their gills in judgment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
