<HEADER>
A1068 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-SONGS-HERITAGE-2T     03-31 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-SONGS-HERITAGE-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SONG BOOK'S FUTURE: STARING AT BLANK PAGES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Barry Singer's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
the composer Vernon Duke.  
 By BARRY SINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The noble parade of dead songwriters in Lincoln
Center's American Songbook series has begun, starting with Harold
Arlen in February and Richard Rodgers in March and continuing in
the fall with Jimmy Van Heusen and Jerome Kern. The mission is
nothing less than the preservation of our popular song heritage.
But is preservation enough?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the music of that melodious roster of songwriting
legends from the 1920s to the 1950s, like Cole Porter, George
Gershwin, Irving Berlin and their peers, will remain with us for
the foreseeable future. Long-term, though, their songs, written for
a mass market that no longer exists, employing standards of craft
and sophistication that no longer apply, seem destined for
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   And yet one cannot but hope. The establishment of the American
Songbook series at Lincoln Center is undeniably a hopeful
development: a sanctuary where the converted can gather regularly
and be preached to. Yet this is an audience nearly as old as the
songs it venerates.
</P>
<P>
   For the American popular song to be truly reborn, as opposed to
merely being endlessly resurrected, new composers must be found who
can reimagine and expand the cannon for younger listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Musical theater has in the last few years produced a handful
(all of them, sadly, neglected by Broadway): Michael John LaChiusa,
Ricky Ian Gordon, Jeanine Tesori and Adam Guettel (a grandson of
Richard Rodgers, who actually sang his grandfather's and Lorentz
Hart's song ``Glad to be Unhappy'' at Lincoln Center in March).
</P>
<P>
   All four possess the requisite talent and, more important, have
served the apprenticeship necessary to absorb the subtleties of
craft that songwriting of this caliber demands. Each has
reconfigured the American popular song form in distinctive and
highly original ways. The question remains, though, whether their
often rarefied concoctions will ever gain wide commercial
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   A more unexpected cause for optimism is a crop of young pop and
rock singer-songwriters that includes Rufus Wainwright, Elliott
Smith, Beth Orton and Duncan Sheik. In their work as songwriters
(their voices as singers aside), one discovers memorable snatches
of melody, lyric dexterity and even occasional wit, elements that
form the bedrock of the American popular standard.
</P>
<P>
   Though none of them now appears to give the American popular
song tradition more than a passing thought, maybe they should be
encouraged to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Wainwright, 25, offers the most promise. His recent debut album
is an often irresistible jumble of eclectic, psychedelic carnival
music, songs that are melodically seductive and occasionally even
constructed with sophistication. His lyrics, moreover, are shot
through with clever conceits that he nimbly runs with, in the
tradition of _ dare one even suggest it _ Porter and Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 29, is a knottier, more problematic composer but one who,
in an odd way, evinces even greater potential. Strip the Beatles
harmonies from his infectious pop tunes and ``Rubber Soul''
leftovers may be all that remain. Yet, Smith's adroit musical
craftsmanship and intuitive harmonic flair suggest that there might
actually be a classic traditional songwriter in the making here,
one with an original voice that combines romantic harmonies with
wrenching dissonance in an engaging way.
</P>
<P>
   Both Smith and Wainwright, like the more conventionally folkish
Sheik and the more raucously subversive Ms. Orton, are descendants
of Joni Mitchell, Bob Dylan and Lennon and McCartney rather than
Gershwin or Berlin. But what if these newcomers were invited inside
a towering yet increasingly distant tradition? What if they, and
we, were permitted to hear their songs reinterpreted by masters of
the American popular song?
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center's American Songbook series would seem best suited
for this mentoring role precisely because it is still inventing
itself and therefore unconstrained by longstanding programming
prejudices. In contrast, the 92d Street Y's invaluable ``Lyrics and
Lyricists'' series, which started out celebrating only living
lyricists, appears too engrossed in the history of this music to
even bother looking toward its future (though the series's new
director, Barry Levitt, has suggested this posture may change).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Symphony Space, for the last decade, has presented wonderful
daylong retrospectives devoted to single songwriters _ most
recently Frank Loesser. But there is also little room here for any
forward thinking amid the boundless traditionalism.
</P>
<P>
   At Lincoln Center, however, the potential is intriguing,
assuming, of course, that those in charge can be persuaded to
hazard something new. Why not put living and dead songwriters
together on the same program? Randy Newman, say, might be invited
to perform both his own music and that of Kurt Weil _ two
generations of astringent musical wits intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps Paul Simon performing his songs along with those of
Johnny Mercer _ an exploration of two All-American hit makers and
their extravagant depths.
</P>
<P>
   Among rock-and-roll's elders, Tom Waits and Lou Reed merit
consideration. Their music is directly descended from American
popular standards, reveling in the darkness that underlies the
sunny assumptions of much of that music. Joni Mitchell's seemingly
sweeter musical universe is no less obliquely linked to this
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The songs of all three bring to mind the sardonic brilliance of
that rough-hewn sophisticate Hoagy Carmichael. Any matchup
involving the four of them would certainly offer some fascinating
juxtapositions.
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't it be lovely to hear Burt Bacharach's blend of Tin
Pan Alley standards, Brill Building pop and vintage
rhythm-and-blues sung by the majestic jazz singer Carol Sloane or
even the classic pop song diva Barbara Cook? Songs from that nifty
batch recently written and recorded by Bacharach with Elvis
Costello would be worth exploring. It would also be illuminating to
hear Costello's own, supremely literate, surprisingly melodic songs
sung by real singers.
</P>
<P>
   Any attempt to reinvigorate the American popular song must also
address the performance conventions of the music. Debonair
posturing has lead to a decidedly nostalgic lifelessness. The point
about Fred Astaire was not that he sang as perfectly as he danced;
he was, in fact, no great singer at all, formally. What made him
the favorite of Gershwin, Porter and Berlin was that he sang just
as effortlessly as he danced, imputing a thrilling illusion of
spontaneity to their music, as if he were making it up on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, Lincoln Center's Arlen and Rogers evenings were a
fascinating contrast in spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   What ultimately separated the two was polish, or rather the
unexpected value that an absence of polish added to the Arlen
event.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a matter of intent. The 25-piece American Songbook
orchestra clearly lacked cohesive musical direction during its
Arlen outing (a raggedness largely tidied up by the time the
Rodgers concert was presented a month later). The Arlen bill even
endured a late scratch due to illness: the marvelously refined
Maureen McGovern was replaced at the last minute by the marvelously
unrefined Debbie Gravitte.
</P>
<P>
   The rawness that engulfed the Arlen proceedings proved anything
but a liability, however. No one would suggest that the American
Songbook series aspire to imperfection. But in the case of the
Arlen program, imperfection produced some terrifically raucous
music.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of the evening was embodied when the usually
circumspect Audra McDonald, who is black, growled, ``Damn, I'm the
whitest woman out here tonight.'' The audience roared, as it never
quite did at the meticulously performed Rodgers program a few weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   Living composers, fully alive performances by singers unafraid
to inhabit these songs without holding back _ that is what the
American popular song cries out for, not merely to survive but to
flourish. And if a more expansive definition of the popular
standard emerges as a result, well, that would be all right too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1546EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1071 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DANCER-DNA-GAME-N     03-31 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DANCER-DNA-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVOLUTION, WITH A BEAT YOU CAN DANCE TO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As William Gibson, the seminal cyberpunk novelist, observed,
``The street finds its own uses for things.'' Billboards and
back-alley nightclubs routinely grab bits and pieces of high
technology or high culture and bend them into strange, vibrant new
shapes.
</P>
<P>
   The latest candidate for metamorphosis is Richard Dawkins, an
Oxford professor whose books about evolutionary theory (``The Blind
Watchmaker'' and ``The Selfish Gene'') have been fueling ivory
tower research and highbrow cocktail party conversation for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The street has found its own uses for these ideas. To wit:
Dancer DNA, a CD-ROM that harnesses the mathematics of evolution to
produce new species of rave graphics. In this instance, the conduit
from Oxford laboratories to London clubs is a small British
software company, Notting Hill Publishing, which teamed up with
Dawkins to produce a CD-ROM about the evolution of life.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that CD-ROM was a small program that allowed
three-dimensional shapes to breed and mutate on a computer screen.
``The aim was to show how fast evolution could work,'' said Notting
Hill's creative director, Ben Whittam Smith. ``Because one of the
points was that evolution doesn't need tens of thousands of years.
It can happen just like that, right in front of your eyes, and with
software we could show that, using a genetic description language
that makes it very obvious what genes are and how they change as
you evolve these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we put it up on our Web site because it was quite a small
application _ we couldn't put the rest of the disk up, so we put
that up. And it had a massive number of downloads, comments,
e-mails and so on. So we realized we had something quite powerful.
But it didn't do anything, apart from being didactic. So we
realized we had to do something with it, and the idea almost came
out of nowhere: using music to control the evolution of these
shapes. And we realized we had Dancer DNA 1.0 in our heads.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, after much tweaking and tuning, is a program that
allows you to generate exotic digital images, select the most
fantastically beautiful ones, then mutate and breed them into an
array of spiny, globular, metallic creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Line the images up, and the program creates an animated
sequence, with each creature morphing into the next, all set to
music. (Slip an audio CD into the CD-ROM drive but be advised: the
creatures seem to prefer drum and bass.)
</P>
<P>
   Dancer DNA creates a gene space _ the universe of all possible
creatures that could evolve from the specimens you've selected _
and music guides the video sequence through that range of options.
Differences in rhythm and volume produce different frames of
animation. Music is the environment in which these creatures live.
It influences the way their genes are expressed.
</P>
<P>
   Spawned by the Dawkins project, Dancer DNA quickly established
an online foothold of its own. On Notting Hill's Web site, the
overwhelming consensus was that this software belonged in a
nightclub. So the programming squad took it to a rave, and people
in baggy pants loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the software was far too slow,'' Whittam Smith said. ``If
you're dancing, your perception of time becomes strangely accurate,
and if the software's out of sync, you notice it. So we completely
reworked the product to make it much, much faster so that we could
license the software to veejays' for live events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, all the video work is done by people who just
love graphics, get paid a pittance by clubs to turn up with a van,
do an eight-hour show, then go home with a pat on the back and not
even a free beer. They get paid so poorly that we cannot generate
any sort of meaningful revenue from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized the people with money are the brands. And we
realized the software could be used to advertise things. So we
completely rewrote the genetics language again so that it took a
slightly less organic view of how shapes are created and more of a
formal mathematical view, so it was easy to generate things that
humans make, perhaps with sharp edges _ like bottles. So it became
an advertising medium _ we are effectively paid by the brands to do
the shows, not by the clubs. At the moment we're doing a nine-month
tour with Bourjois Cosmetics, which is a part of Chanel. We've
worked with Sony Playstation, Holsten beer.''
</P>
<P>
   It's almost as if the evolutionary principles driving the
graphics were driving the product itself. Every time the program
hit some kind of economic roadblock, Notting Hill's programmers
rewrote its code. Via mutation and selection, the program evolved
its way into a youth culture fueled by advertising _ a fertile
niche where the software could proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Dawkins, a programmer is just computer code's way
of making more computer code. Hats off. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dancer DNA; Notting Hill Publishing; Windows 95 and 98; it can
be downloaded from www.dancerdna.com for 15 pounds (about $24). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
