<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1073 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-THEATER-3TAK     03-31 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-THEATER-3TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COUNTRY OF LESSER GIANTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Matthew Gurewitsch's most recent articles on theater have appeared
in The Atlantic Monthly and The Wall Street Journal.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture a Mount Rushmore in honor of the monumental characters
of American drama. What faces do you see there, carved in stone?
Willy Loman, Blanche DuBois, Theodore (Hickey) Hickman and Mary
Cavan Tyrone. But has our country yet produced drama worthy to set
beside the Greek tragedians, Shakespeare, Calderon, Schiller,
Ibsen, Chekhov? I think not.
</P>
<P>
   Willy, the washed-up salesman. Blanche, the desperate mantrap.
Hickey, the ``iceman,'' whose wife's perpetual forgiveness is his
ball and chain. Convent-bred Mary Tyrone in her morphine fog,
mourning her shattered faith and a buried child through her long
day's journey.
</P>
<P>
   Losers, every one.
</P>
<P>
   Losers, what's more, far past the point of no return when the
curtain rises. We never bear witness to the stages by which they
make their fate their own. Their stories unfold backward, through
endless hearsay. Whatever is wrong, don't blame them! It's not
their fault. From curtain up to curtain down, they point the
finger, make excuses, bellyache and lie.
</P>
<P>
   The only question is how long they can keep running on empty.
Long before victimhood became the glamorous political stance here
in the home of the brave, it was the ambitious playwright's idee
fixe.
</P>
<P>
   Larry, our Virgil in ``The Iceman Cometh,'' calls the inferno of
Harry Hope's saloon and rooming house the No Chance Saloon, the
Bedrock Bar, the End of the Line Cafe. Blanche takes a streetcar
named Desire, transfers to one called Cemeteries and gets off at
Elysian Fields _ a destination one actress articulated, with
purposeful ambiguity, as ``Illusion Fields.'' Next stop: the mental
ward.
</P>
<P>
   Our masterpieces of serious drama are dramas of failure.
</P>
<P>
   American plays that seek to analyze and reflect on what we might
grandly call the Human Condition or the Way We Live Now (or the Way
We Live Here) are a curiously recent phenomenon, more recent, in
fact, than similarly minded movies. D.W. Griffith made ``Birth of a
Nation'' in 1915, ``Intolerance'' in 1916. Not until after World
War I did American plays of comparable stature appear. The first
were the young Eugene O'Neill's ``Beyond the Horizon'' and ``The
Emperor Jones,'' mounted by the Provincetown Players in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, countless seriously intended plays have come and
gone. Sophie Treadwell and Maxwell Anderson, Clifford Odets and
William Inge stepped up to the plate. Pending unforeseen and
unlikely developments, their memory lives more in history books
than in drama courses, let alone on the living stage, where their
rare revivals give off a whiff of mothballs.
</P>
<P>
   History's judgment on American dramatists who are active and
esteemed today _among them Edward Albee, Margaret Edson, Horton
Foote, John Guare, Tony Kushner, David Mamet, Terrence McNally, Sam
Shepard, Nicky Silver, August Wilson _ may be kinder; it is too
soon to say.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that Shepard's ``Buried Child'' will endure. With a
gun at my head, I would also place bets on Albee's ``Who's Afraid
of Virginia Woolf?,'' Ms. Edson's ``Wit,'' Guare's ``Six Degrees of
Separation,'' Mamet's ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' Wilson's ``Ma
Rainey's Black Bottom'' and McNally's ``Master Class,'' which in
international productions has seemed a much richer, more enigmatic
script than most New York critics have supposed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a canon of older plays has formed. ``Death of a
Salesman'' qualifies as a classic, though the claim of Arthur
Miller's other scripts is shaky. The legacy of Tennessee Williams
includes several items that refuse to die (``The Glass Menagerie,''
``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof''), several
that refuse to live (``Summer and Smoke,'' ``Sweet Bird of
Youth''), and several that are available to the enterprising
resurrectionist (``Orpheus Descending,'' ``The Night of the
Iguana,'' ``Not About Nightingales'').
</P>
<P>
   No one denies that there is something tremendous about O'Neill,
even if it is measured by the clock (only three hours and change
for ``Long Day's Journey Into Night,'' four plus for ``The Iceman
Cometh,'' five for ``Strange Interlude,'' six for ``Mourning
Becomes Electra'').
</P>
<P>
   Thornton Wilder presents a special case. Our life resembles
``Our Town'' less and less, but his generous vision is still
appealing, as anachronistically American as apple pie. ``The Skin
of Our Teeth,'' Wilder's Joycean projection of human history onto
the paradigm of a ``typical'' mid-century American family, has its
champions, too. Come to think of it, George Antrobus, the play's
Father Knows Best, might merit a place on Mount Rushmore also,
except that he would seem so out of place. (He's not a loser.)
</P>
<P>
   Partly, no doubt, for chauvinistic reasons, we pretend that our
greatest plays measure up to the world's greatest. Directors,
critics and the public from London to Tokyo, from Paris to Sydney,
indulge us in this fantasy, treating our classics in a respectful,
often worshipful spirit of continuing exploration.
</P>
<P>
   The key word here is ``continuing.''
</P>
<P>
   However we choose to define a classic, a sine qua non is that
the material lend itself to reinterpretation in the light of
changing circumstances. On this test, our canonical masterpieces
fail. Unlike Oedipus, Hamlet or Hedda Gabler, the towering roles in
American drama belong to characters about whom it is impossible to
develop a genuinely fresh point of view. The deficiency extends,
unsurprisingly enough, to the plays in which they appear.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Our great American masters wrote plays the way a Stendhal or a
George Eliot wrote prose fiction. They spelled out a character's
appearance, age, physical tics, personal aura and psychology, not
to mention the setting, in overwhelming and often unrealizable
detail, down to the length of their noses and the titles of the
books on their shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The insights squirreled away in stage directions can be
remarkable. Meet Happy, Willy's younger son: ``Sexuality is like a
visible color on him, or a scent that many women have discovered.
He, like his brother, is lost, but in a different way, for he has
never allowed himself to turn his face toward defeat and is thus
more confused and hard-skinned, although seemingly more content.''
</P>
<P>
   Observations of such specificity _ also abundant in O'Neill and
Williams _ make absorbing reading, but what business does a
playwright have making such a show of omniscience? A novelist, by
convention, can do so, being free to speak to the audience
directly.
</P>
<P>
   A playwright, however, is at the mercy of intermediaries.
Clytemnestra or Uncle Vanya not only allow the actor to exercise
independent creativity, they also demand it. Whereas Willy,
Blanche, Hickey and Mary Tyrone take their marching orders and
execute a maneuver. Everything is diagrammed right there on the
page.
</P>
<P>
   As, for instance, in the final sequence of ``Long Day's Journey
Into Night,'' stage-managed with all the know-how of the mad scene
of ``Lucia di Lammermoor.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood is set by the sound of rheumatic fingers playing a
Chopin prelude on an offstage piano. The music breaks off and in
comes Mary, trailing her wedding dress, the talisman of a life
sacrificed to romantic illusion. ``I knew she heard my prayer and
would always love me and see no harm ever came to me so long as I
never lost my faith in her,'' Mary says, as her reminiscences draw
to a close, recalling her girlish devotion to ``the Blessed
Virgin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was in the winter of senior year,'' she says, as her
reminisces draw to a close. ``Then in the spring something happened
to me. Yes, I remember. I fell in love with James Tyrone and was so
happy for a time.'' These words are music on which Donizetti
himself could not improve. Delivered with minimal competence, they
cannot fail of their effect, but the effect is identical every
time.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of ``Death of a Salesman'' is similarly invariant.
Brian Dennehy transferred to Broadway this season from the Goodman
Theater, Chicago, accompanied by the sort of hoopla that greeted
the Electra of Zoe Wanamaker or the Hamlet, several seasons ago, of
Ralph Fiennes, performances that redefined the roles and thus the
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway's last Willy Loman was Dustin Hoffman, a bantam.
Dennehy is a bruiser. The different body image strikes a different
note of pathos, but it has no bearing on who Willy is. His meaning
is contained in the name Loman, his fate summed up in the immortal
line about riding on a smile and a shoeshine. The character knocks
at the gate of metaphor, but the gate stays shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody dast blame this man,'' says a cranky neighbor at
Willy's graveside, and who dast disagree? He has his failings, to
be sure: a little adultery, a little vanity, a lot of denial. He
puts up a brave front. He regrets his lost chances. Mostly, though,
he functions as Exhibit A in the playwright's harangue against
capitalist exploitation of the workingman. Instead of moral
inquiry, there is moralizing: ``Attention must be paid!'' When
characters in Ibsen moralize, as the awakened Nora does in the last
act of ``A Doll's House,'' they are not broadcasting the Author's
Message but voicing hard-won convictions of their own. From the
clash of opposing convictions, the drama takes fire.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Spacey's Hickey in ``The Iceman Cometh'' is generating, if
anything, an even louder buzz of anticipation than Dennehy's Willy
Loman did, and no wonder. The production, opening on Thursday at
the Brooks Atkinson Theater on Broadway, is based on the Almeida
Theater version mounted in London, where it won Olivier, Evening
Standard and London Critics' Circle awards for Spacey and for
Howard Davies, the director.
</P>
<P>
   Hickey (another salesman) is the party animal who all of a
sudden starts calling all his cronies on their ``pipe dreams,''
those not-so-little, not-so-white lies by means of which they hold
up their heads. (Samples: I'm not a whore, I'm just a tart. I wish
I were dead. I'll get my job back. White people treat me as a white
man. I love the proletariat. I loved my wife. I love my mother.)
</P>
<P>
   Everyone at Harry Hope's has a button, everyone else knows what
it is, and nobody ever pushes one, for fear of reprisals. In walks
Hickey, full of his new gospel, hawking truth serum, and all hell
breaks loose. ``I wrote the book,'' he keeps saying, setting people
straight much against their wills. Surprise! The truth sets no one
free. Hickey's pipe dream is the most lethal of all. (Hickey _ what
a name. Love bites.)
</P>
<P>
   Few actors at large have more aces up their sleeves than Spacey,
a master at keeping the spectator off balance. Who can doubt that
he will rivet the attention? But if he torpedoes my theory (and I
hope he does), he will be the first to achieve a significant
re-evaluation of one of American drama's iconic characters, defined
once and for all time, even for those too young to have seen him,
by Jason Robards in Jose Quintero's Circle in the Square revival of
1956.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The hope of anyone performing that service for Blanche DuBois
grows increasingly remote. For audiences under 65, who missed
Jessica Tandy, the role's reputedly incandescent originator, the
point of reference is the movie with Vivien Leigh. Is there
anything in the role she failed to show?
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of recent seasons _ separate Broadway revivals
mounted around Blythe (``Illusion Fields'') Danner and Jessica
Lange; Andre Previn and Philip Littell's new operatic
``Streetcar,'' starring the lustrous soprano Renee Fleming; Michael
Wilson's perceptive revival this season at Hartford Stage with
Annalee Jefferies _ says no. (The Hartford production returns in
July.)
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Lincoln Center Theater's recent revival of Lillian
Hellman's subclassic ``Little Foxes'' revealed in Regina Giddens
facets that few can have suspected were there. On film, Bette Davis
gave what looked like the definitive account of an iron-willed
gorgon, icily calling every shot in her nefarious property-grabbing
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   On the stage of the Vivian Beaumont, Stockard Channing portrayed
a desperate woman bluffing her way to Pyrrhic victory with a very
weak hand, transforming a star vehicle into something much more
fascinating: a play.
</P>
<P>
   As for Blanche, you can play much of her part for laughs
nowadays. (As history teaches, tragedy repeats itself as farce.)
What you cannot do is conceive of the part in any but the precise
masochistic terms Williams prescribes, as a vulnerable, poetic soul
shipwrecked on the cruelty of an uncomprehending world.
</P>
<P>
   Her name, like Willy Loman's, is emblematic. Blanche the
lily-white, Blanche the blameless, Blanche the more sinned against
than sinning. Never mind that she drove her husband to suicide,
never mind her questionable morals; Blanche is the victim here.
</P>
<P>
   ``What poetry!,'' Stanley sneers, after one of her lesser
tirades, representing all the brutes who ever failed to appreciate
her. ``We've had this date with each other from the beginning!,''
he announces later, on the brink of rape. To put it gently, the act
seems wildly out of character. Stanley needs sex the way a baby
needs the breast. A husband more attached to his wife's apron
strings you will not find. A rapist? In Blanche's dreams, but
Williams needed (italics)someone(end italics) to smash her.
</P>
<P>
   Previn reports that every soprano he meets these days wants to
sing Blanche in his new opera. ``It's an irresistibly
(italics)big(end italics) part,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Here may be the key to the lasting appeal of our American
classics. Focus on failure, reduce action to recrimination as they
may, they offer juicy opportunities for acting _ acting in the
sense of vicarious living under the gaze of those wonderful people
out there in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Actors' egos must be served, of course. No narcissism, no
performance. But on the ladder of dramatic greatness, the
satisfaction of such needs is only the first step.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
