<HEADLINE>
EXAMINING HITCHCOCK AT 100: AN INTERACTIVE MUSEUM EXHIBIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 By SHELLY FREIERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene on the screen is intimately familiar: a blond woman
smokes a cigarette, oblivious to the ravens gathering on a set of
monkey bars in the schoolyard behind her. By the time she finally
notices a bird landing next to dozens of others, the suspense is
almost too much to bear. So you click on the Pause icon and go back
in five-second intervals, trying to figure out how the scene was
made.
</P>
<P>
   While it would be impossible to interrupt a film in a theater
and clumsy to skip from shot to shot using a VCR, manipulating film
clips is central to Multimedia Hitchcock, a new computer program
that will be part of the Museum of Modern Art's centennial
exhibition on the filmmaker starting on April 16.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will be able to use a computer kiosk to learn about all
of Alfred Hitchcock's 53 films through a wealth of video, text,
audio and still images.
</P>
<P>
   In a section called Classic Sequences, for example, users can
watch a scene from one of 11 films, manipulate it frame by frame
and hear Hitchcock's own comments (or read an interview
transcript).
</P>
<P>
   When you click on the audio button during the playground
sequence from ``The Birds,'' you hear Hitchcock say he thinks that
the traditional technique of building suspense through
cross-cutting is ``worn out.'' He goes on to explain, ``That's why
when the girl was waiting outside, smoking, I stayed with her for
50 feet of film.''
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia Hitchcock has a biography of the director; reviews
and commentary by critics; video clips representing 27 films;
descriptions and credits for each film; the cameos Hitchcock made
in most of his movies; biographies of collaborators like David O.
Selznick, Ingrid Bergman, Gregory Peck and James Stewart; clips
from the television series ``Alfred Hitchcock Presents,'' and a
section examining his influence on directors from Truffaut to
Scorsese.
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia Hitchcock was developed by Robert E. Kapsis, a
professor of sociology and film studies at Queens College of the
City University of New York, as a tool for film students. He grew
up seeing the director's films. ``The thing about Hitchcock was his
psychological mastery of the audience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapsis said his original aim had been to build a scholarly
database of primary source material. For film students, Multimedia
Hitchcock offers a way to study the director by seeing and reading
original material. For the public, it offers a new look at
Hitchcock films through his writings and words.
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia Hitchcock will be on display at the Museum of Modern
Art through 1999. Unfortunately for fans, there are no plans to
produce the program commercially.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Veneziale, Sarah Kozinn and Lauren Popkin spent 30
minutes examining Multimedia Hitchcock when it was on display
recently at the American Museum of the Moving Image in Queens. ``It
was neat to hear Hitchcock's voice,'' said Veneziale, a big fan.
``It was like having a conversation with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kozinn enjoyed exploring the ``Psycho'' shower scene shot by
shot and the flexibility of the program's user interface.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are in control of everything,'' she said. ``It's like
creating your own documentary.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kozinn, who was born three years after Hitchcock made his
last film, ``Family Plot,'' in 1976, and has seen only three of the
director's works, is on her way to becoming a serious fan. ``I'd
never associate Hitchcock with today's horror films,'' she said.
``He's sort of his own genre.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
