<HEADER>
A1078 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-READING-ROOM-ANTIQUES     03-31 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-READING-ROOM-ANTIQUES-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING A FAMILIAR HAUNT AGAIN, BUT IN A NEW LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4)  
 (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The gloomy winter and the bright spring have provided
the proof. The glorious fullness of light that the architects John
M. Carrere and Thomas Hastings envisioned 90 years ago for the New
York Public Library's main reading room has returned the Beaux Arts
space to its former splendor.
</P>
<P>
   The room _ the length of a football field, the height of a
cathedral nave _ was darkened during the blackout days of World War
II when the arched tops of its 15 soaring windows were painted
over. It grew dimmer over the decades as the paint-scarred windows
were further blighted by grime that eventually obliterated the view
of the sun and sky from inside the room.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, entire tiers of bulbs in the chandeliers
short-circuited and lighting fixtures on the book stands and
reference shelves burned out, never to be repaired or replaced.
Later, as the number of microfilm machines and garish yellow chairs
multiplied, the room became dowdy.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue was realized under Paul LeClerc, the president of the
library, through the largesse of Sandra Priest Rose, a library
trustee, and her husband, Frederick Phineas Rose, a real estate
developer, who gave $15 million to restore the space.
</P>
<P>
   The room, newly named after their four children, is now called
the Deborah, Jonathan F.P., Samuel Priest and Adam Raphael Rose
Main Reading Room.
</P>
<P>
   Today, even on the darkest days, the room is filled with light.
The windows gleam with exquisite clarity, each pane replaced with
energy-efficient glass that prevents ultra-violet damage to the
books and the painted or stained-wood surfaces throughout the room.
</P>
<P>
   Refurbished or new lighting fixtures have made the titles on the
spines of books easy to read again. Fixtures have been installed
inconspicuously on tops of the bookcases on the room's perimeter to
illuminate the murals of sunny skies on the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Architecture is all about light,'' said the architect Lewis
Davis, who masterminded the restoration, paraphrasing his mentor,
Louis Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   Light even influenced the choice of new finishes on the American
white oak furniture throughout the room. The sun had bleached some
surfaces in the north and south sections, so they were refinished
in a far paler tone than their original nut brown. The
Renaissance-style tables, too, are this light color. They had been
darker, but restaining would have marred their ebony inlay.
</P>
<P>
   Once the microfilm machines and the yellow chairs were removed,
the tables were returned to the room, updated with wiring for
computers. Back, too, came the saddle-seat chairs along with the
baluster-shaped lamps with bronze bases and brass shades.
</P>
<P>
   The chairs, too, were refinished and appear more graceful in
their lighter incarnation. From the tops of their rounded backs to
the tips of their cabriole legs, the chairs borrow the best from
the imperial past with their scrolled Grecian arms and vase-shaped
Chinese back splat, a must for Ming emperors.
</P>
<P>
   These and other distinctive elements were brought together in
the 1840s in a hybrid chair form that Carrere &AMP; Hastings adapted
for the library.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the more than 600 chairs in the restored room are
reproductions, which were made by the Sam Moore Company of Bedford,
Va. After decades of requests from visitors, the library will sell
such reproductions in its shop at $799 each.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, 60 reproductions of the lamps were made to go along
with the 100 originals that survived. The new lamps were produced
by the Excalibur Bronze Sculpture Foundry of Brooklyn. The foundry
also rewired, cleaned and restored the original lamps, stripping
off the greenish white paint finish on the shades from the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   To maximize the amount of light given off by the lamps _ old and
new _ Excalibur painted the insides of the brass shades white.
Masters at decorative metalwork, the foundry restored damaged parts
or recreated missing ones, like rosettes, on the 18 chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   The reproductions cost more than $1,000 each, a price that
seemed too high for them to be sold in the library shop. A version,
produced in China for Visual Comfort of Houston, sells in the shop
for $268. It is more than three inches taller than the original,
with a narrower, taller shade, two bulbs instead of three and pull
chains to turn it on.
</P>
<P>
   Excalibur also made the lion-shaped bronze fixtures for the
entryway to the main reading room, as well as the cone-shaped
white-glass hanging lamps in the book delivery and retrieval area.
These hanging lights replaced those with green-glass shades,
artifacts sorely missed by many people who studied in this room
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry W. Henderson, who fields questions at the information
desks in the room and has worked at the library for 39 years, said
visitors still asked, ``What ever happened to those emerald green
lamps?'' He said he didn't miss them one bit: ``They were part of
the darkness that's gone now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1553EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
