<HEADER>
A1079 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COUPONS-ART-NYT &LR;      03-31 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COUPONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE GROCERY COUPONS FOR CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shoppers weren't the problem. Three years ago, the marketing
company Supermarkets Online decided to test the idea of offering
grocery coupons over the Internet. The company created a Web site
offering coupons that consumers could print out and redeem at their
favorite supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers liked it immediately,'' said David Rochon, president
and chief executive of Supermarkets Online, ``even though they had
to print out the coupons, even though they had to cut them out
afterward so they looked like normal coupons, even though we only
had a half-dozen or so offers a week on the service. They let us
know right away that they wanted even more coupons.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was with the manufacturers. ``Our version was not
acceptable to the manufacturers who offer coupons, because of all
the potential of fraud, the worry that nothing would prevent people
from counterfeiting unlimited amounts of coupons,'' Rochon
remembered. ``We realized then that if manufacturers weren't
willing, there wouldn't be an online service.''
</P>
<P>
   That was just the first of the many hurdles purveyors of online
coupons have faced. Clearly, there was a market. American shoppers
are predisposed to using coupons to save money _ four out of five
shoppers used coupons in 1997, redeeming more than $3 billion worth
of the offers, according to industry studies.
</P>
<P>
   To compete with traditional coupons, E-coupon companies have
struggled to come up with a secure, well-targeted way to turn those
coupon consumers from clippers to clickers.
</P>
<P>
   For its coupons, Supermarkets Online created a new system that
calls for consumers to print out a shopping list of discounted
products. Emblazoned with a special bar code, the shopping list can
be scanned at checkout at 9,300 participating stores nationwide to
total a shopper's savings and then issue a credit, in the form of
``Web bucks,'' that can be redeemed to pay for subsequent
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we officially launched the site in January 1998,
we had the solution in place, and that was the breakthrough,''
Rochon said. Since then, the number of offers on the site
(www.valupage.com) has increased to about 50 a week; the number of
coupon shoppers visiting the site has also gone up significantly,
from 20,000 a month in January of 1998 to more than three million
last month.
</P>
<P>
   For shoppers, online coupons offer a major advantage:
customization. Instead of picking through a random selection of
coupons that arrives in the mail or tucked into the daily
newspaper, shoppers can fill out online questionnaires specifying
their interests, zip codes and shopping habits and then receive
e-mail with relevant offers on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics differ slightly from site to site. For instance,
at some sites, consumers can print out paper coupons, redeemable at
brick-and-mortar stores. In other cases, the coupons can be
redeemed electronically at online stores. And, as is the case with
Valupage.com, a shopper who redeems the site's offers earns ``Web
bucks'' that can be used like cash.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the variety of online coupons _ offering
discounts that range from 50 cents off a package of Huggies diaper
wipes to $500 off a General Motors vehicle _ has proliferated with
the introduction of numerous online sites. Rather than relying on
determined shoppers to hunt down their coupon Web sites, many
companies have struck deals that will distribute their coupons on
popular portal sites and online services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the first step in the evolution of online
coupons, because there's an enormous opportunity here,'' said James
McQuivey, a senior analyst in online retail strategies at Forrester
Research. ``In the next two to three years, companies will figure
out how to get coupons more and more easily to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this month, for example, America Online's customers
will find Supermarkets Online's grocery offers distributed on an
AOL food channel. The online offers from Emaginet.com, which
specializes in so-called E-centives that can be redeemed on line,
appear on the online site of the newspaper USA Today, in the
Marketplace section.
</P>
<P>
   Val-Pak Coupons Online, which specializes in offering shoppers
coupons for such local products and services as pizza and dry
cleaning, struck a deal last month to team up with Yahoo to
distribute its coupons to the 50 million users on the popular
portal site. Val-Pak will eventually be able to send customized
coupons to Yahoo's registered users to offer them products
available in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a good fit, because the portal sites know exactly where
their users are registered,'' said Todd Leiser, vice president of
Internet technology at Cox Target Media, which owns Val-Pak.
</P>
<P>
   Another online coupon company, Coolsavings.com, last month
announced a daal with General Growth Properties, the nation's
second-largest regional mall company, to offer online coupons that
can be redeemed at local malls around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, online coupon companies envision a time in the
not-too-distant future where they will be able to deliver a
customized package of offers and information based on a shopper's
past habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't even need to know your name, just where you live
geographically and what you like to buy,'' Rochon said. ``It will
go beyond mere coupons. If you buy a lot of Oreos, maybe you'll get
a coupon for a new kind of cookie that tastes similar. If you buy a
lot of Miracle Whip, maybe you'll get a recipe, through e-mail,
that tells you how to use Miracle Whip as an ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could expand far beyond grocery savings. Maybe you'll get a
package of coupons in your e-mail for savings at your favorite
hardware store, gas station, even the shoe repair.''
</P>
<P>
   Until that day, however, finding online coupons remains a
hit-and-miss proposition. Surfing the Web looking for the perfect
coupon is enormously time-consuming. A more useful approach for the
shopper: limit the hunt to a trusted site or two, then get a
regular update on that week's offers in just a few minutes' time.
Better yet, find a site that sends e-mail updates directly to you.
</P>
<P>
   Because this is a relatively new industry, it pays to call ahead
to the retailer to confirm that the coupons will be honored. And as
with all coupons, check the expiration date before you print them
out: many online coupons are good only for a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early in the life cycle of online coupons,'' said Ken
Cassar, an analyst at Jupiter Communications. ``Going to the next
level, where they are really convenient and easy to use, might be a
bit of a stretch. But it's going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
