<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS ANSWERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How can I get a program to start automatically when I turn on
my computer?
</P>
<P>
   A. There is something rather satisfying about booting up your
computer, going to make some coffee and returning to your desk to
find your word-processing and e-mail programs open and ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a programs to do that is fairly easy, whether you're
using Windows 95 or 98 or Macintosh. You simply need to put a
shortcut or alias file of the program into the start-up folder.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a PC with Windows 95 or 98, use Windows Explorer to
find on your hard drive the folder for the program you want to open
when you boot. Open the folder, and then find and right-click on
the program's executable file (the one that ends in .exe) to create
a shortcut.
</P>
<P>
   Then type Control X to cut, go to the Start button, right-click
on that to get the pop-up menu and pick Open. Double-click on the
Programs folder inside the window to open it, then find the
Start-up folder in there and open it. Type Control V to paste the
shortcut into the Start-up folder.
</P>
<P>
   On a Mac, find the program file you want to use. Click on it
once and type Command M to make an alias file. Drag the alias file
to your desktop. Open the System folder on your hard drive and find
the folder called Startup Items. Drag the program's alias from the
desktop and into the Startup Items folder.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
