<HEADER>
A1085 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ST.-FRANCIS-BASILICA-     03-31 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST.-FRANCIS-BASILICA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REASSEMBLING ART SHATTERED IN EARTHQUAKE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Ken Shulman's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was on an
exhibition of Caravaggio's ``Taking of Christ'' in Boston.  
 By KEN SHULMAN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASSISI, Italy _ From afar, it looks like an Italian neo-realist
director's vision of Camelot: the 13th-century Basilica of St.
Francis (San Francesco), its sides ribbed with scaffolding, the
base of its bell tower warmed by a blanket of winter mist.
</P>
<P>
   As a visitor draws closer, the cathedral's solemn mass comes
into view, looming unshakable and solid. Two tonsured Franciscan
friars huddle under an umbrella beneath the archway at the lower
basilica. Only on entering the upper basilica is one reminded of
the recent tragedy, and then only vaguely.
</P>
<P>
   Here 28 miles of gold-hued aluminum scaffolding transform the
narrow nave into a sort of solemn dirigible. The ceiling vaults
above the entryway and the altar _ vaults that collapsed 18 months
ago during an earthquake, shattering ceiling paintings attributed
to Cimabue and Giotto and killing four people _ have been entirely
rebuilt and reinforced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``From a structural point of view, I can say that we are well on
our way,'' says Raoul Paggetta, a director of the architectural
restoration at the basilica. ``For us, the worst is definitely
over.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 26, 1997, at 11:26 in the morning, a violent tremor
shook the earth of the central Italian region of Umbria. In Assisi,
the tremor caused the basilica's vaulted ceiling to contract and
then expand, catapulting into the air more than 1,000 tons of
debris that had been left on top of the vaults from centuries of
renovations.
</P>
<P>
   The mass of leftover stones, bricks and mortar crashed into the
vault over the main altar, blasting away two of its leaves and
sending Cimabue's ``St. Matthew'' and a section of his assistants'
starry sky plummeting almost 60 feet to the stone floor below. At
the entryway, a support arch collapsed, hurling eight painted
saints by Giotto to the ground and burying two Franciscan friars
and two fine-arts inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   A vault leaf decorated with Giotto's ``St. Jerome'' also gave
way. When the tremor finally stopped, more than 1,900 square feet
of ceiling _ about 10 percent of the area _ had collapsed. The
remaining 21,000 square feet were badly scarred. Tons of rubble lay
at the entrance and at the base of the altar. Four people were
dead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though often criticized for its lack of efficiency, the Italian
state responded swiftly and effectively to the Assisi crisis. An
emergency committee was established two days after the disaster
under Mario Serio, the director general of the Fine Arts
Administration of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   During the first critical weeks, Giuseppe Basile, an inspector
at the state Central Restoration Institute in Rome and director of
pictorial restoration at the basilica, orchestrated a force of 300
restorers and volunteers, who sifted through the rubble to recover
and catalog the pieces of the crumbled paintings.
</P>
<P>
   In the following months, Paggetta and his crew of nearly 100
workers rebuilt the missing sections of the ceiling and the
supporting arch above the entrance. As insurance against future
quakes _ the region of Umbria is historically unstable;
seismologists have charted more than 50 tremors since September
1997 _ the entire ceiling was reinforced with strips of Kevlar, the
bulletproof material used in police vests, and strapped across the
back of each vault leaf like giant Band-Aids.
</P>
<P>
   Circular steel braces now anchor the bases of the crumbled
15th-century arches. A calibrated network of sensors monitors the
ceiling, plotting expansions, contractions and, above all, the
shifts caused by earth tremors. The entire operation, expected to
cost $28 million by completion, has been financed by the Italian
government. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To draw attention to the disaster, the Vatican and several
Italian cultural agencies have organized ``The Treasury of St.
Francis of Assisi,'' an exhibition of 100 objects that is on view
at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York through June 27. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as absolute security,'' says Paggetta,
his voice bobbing over a chorus of hammers and electric drills and
chatter from the scores of unseen workers on the scaffolding above
him. ``If a cataclysm occurs, there's nothing we can do. But we can
and have done much to insure that the basilica will suffer little
or no damage if struck by a quake like the one that caused this
damage.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Far beneath the basilica, in the 16th-century stables known as
``Il Stallone,'' the mood is less ebullient. There, in a hastily
constructed but fully modern restoration laboratory, a half-dozen
white-coated restorers struggle with what is probably the most
difficult pictorial conservation effort in Italian history.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Giotto's ``St. Jerome'' lies in a series of milk crates and
plastic trays, shattered into 30,000 pieces. The remnants of
Cimabue's ``St. Matthew,'' another 30,000 pieces _ some of them as
small as one square millimeter _ lie in another series of
containers. The scene is as dramatic, and pathetic, as a Mannerist
deposition.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shards of Giotto's eight saints lie on nine-foot aluminum
tables, spread on top of life-size color reproductions that serve
as visual guides for the restorers. Following experience, and
sometimes only instinct, the restorers try to match pieces by
shape, color and subject. For them, it's almost like working on a
series of giant jigsaw puzzles, except that many of the most
important pieces are either damaged or missing.
</P>
<P>
   Some saints, like St. Ruffino, whose face and body are now
composed into a segmented but wholly legible mosaic, are well on
their way to reconstruction. Others lag behind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a job that has to take a long time,'' says Paola
Passalacqua, chief restorer of the Assisi team. ``The pieces don't
come together automatically. Some days you can be lucky and place
20 of them. Some days you feel lucky if you place just one.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Passalacqua hopes that the eight saints can be reassembled,
mounted onto specially constructed curved supports and reinstalled
along the rebuilt arch in the upper basilica by Christmas when Pope
John Paul II is scheduled to say Mass in Assisi.
</P>
<P>
   For the other damaged paintings, she and her colleagues are far
less sanguine. Cimabue's ``St. Matthew,'' which was executed in
tempera and whose fragments are dangerously fragile, is
particularly problematic. In private, several members of the Assisi
team admit that the question for Cimabue is not ``when'' but
``if.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Basile, who directs Ms. Passalacqua and her restorers,
Cimabue's best chance for survival lies in a novel _ some might say
quixotic _ computer program. ``We are taking photographs of each of
the Cimabue fragments,'' he explains, ``labeling them and creating
a virtual archive of the fragments. We will then turn the project
over to our computer experts, who are working on an algorhythm that
will eventually tell restorers where each of the thousands of
pieces belongs.''
</P>
<P>
   If the still-unwritten computer program works, Basile says, both
the Giotto and Cimabue paintings could be ready within two years.
If not, he says, the completion date will be significantly
extended. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Basile has already drafted several contingency plans for the
space on the ceiling vault should the ``St. Matthew'' prove to be
unsalvageable. One of these involves projecting a photographic
image of the Cimabue painting onto the bare plaster of the vault
over the altar. Another calls for commissioning a contemporary
artist to paint a new mural where ``St. Matthew'' once stood.
Still, he stresses, these are plans of last resort. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every reason to hope that we can recover the majority
of what we had before the earthquake,'' he repeats, in a voice
neither full nor void of conviction. ``We should know whether the
computer program is viable within six months. And if it isn't,
we'll just move on and start trying to put the paintings together
by hand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1557EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     03-31 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: THE PREPARATION AND INSTALLATION OF ATTIC VENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Howto drawing is being sent to both photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week this column discussed the need for proper attic
ventilation with vents. Vents rely on natural temperature
differences within the attic to move the air. They use no
electricity, so they are economical. In most cases, a few
well-positioned vents may be all you need to keep the air recycling
in your attic.
</P>
<P>
   Soffit vents fit in the panels on the underside of the eaves.
There are three types: circular plug vents, rectangular panel vents
and strip vents. Plug and rectangular vents are the easiest to
install. You only have to cut a hole through the soffit boards and
position the vent, but making these cuts may be a little difficult
because the panels are in an awkward location. You will have to
bend over backward to operate the saw.
</P>
<P>
   Strip vents are harder to install because you have to cut
notches in the soffit supports to accept the strip. This may entail
dismantling the soffit to make the cuts, then reassembling it.
Whichever soffit vent you choose, you must make sure that the attic
insulation does not cover the vent opening. So after the vents are
in place, check that the floor insulation does not extend to the
eaves. If it does, trim it back to gain the necessary clearance.
</P>
<P>
   Gable or louvered vents are mounted in the gable walls of the
attic. Ideally, the vent should be centered under the roof peak.
First measure the length and width of the vent housing (not the
surface flanges), then transfer these dimensions to the outside
wall. With a circular saw, cut an opening through the siding and
sheathing.
</P>
<P>
   Next measure the width and length of the surface flanges (these
dimensions will be larger than the housing dimensions) and transfer
them around the newly cut opening. In effect, the lines will look
like a frame around the opening. Set the saw blade to cut through
the siding, not through the sheathing, and cut this part away.
</P>
<P>
   Working from inside the attic, cut away any studs that obstruct
the opening. Frame the opening by nailing two 2 by 4's above and
below the opening between the nearest studs. Next nail two vertical
2 by 4's to these horizontal pieces on either side of the opening.
</P>
<P>
   Working from the outside, push the vent into the opening until
the flanges seat snugly against the sheathing. Nail it in place.
Cover the flanges with trim, and caulk between the trim and siding.
</P>
<P>
   Roof vents are installed through the roof. Naturally you must
cut a hole first. Start from inside the attic. The vent hole should
be centered between two rafters. Select a location, then drive a
nail through the roof to mark the center of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Now move to the roof. A word of caution: working on any roof can
be dangerous, especially if it has a steep pitch. Never work on a
roof on a windy day or if the roof is wet or even damp. Wear shoes
with nonskid soles and be sure to secure yourself and tools and
materials as you work. If you are uneasy when working from heights,
it may be better to leave this job to a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Find the nail in the roof. Cut away the shingles, then cut a
hole in the sheathing to match the shape of the vent. Return to the
attic and nail support boards, 2 by 4's, between the rafters at the
top and bottom edges of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   On the roof, pry up the shingles (be careful: cold shingles can
break when you attempt to bend them) around the hole. Coat the
underside of the vent flanges with roofing cement and slip the vent
beneath the shingles. Secure it with gasketed roofing nails.
</P>
<P>
   The ridge vent is positioned over a gap (this must be cut) in
the roof peak. It runs along the entire length of the roof. Ridge
vents are difficult to install because you must work on the highest
part of the roof while maneuvering the long, unwieldy vent into
place.
</P>
<P>
   Begin by removing the cap shingles. This will expose the black
building felt beneath. Measure one inch down from the roof peak. Do
this on both sides of the roof, front and rear. Snap chalk lines to
connect the marks on one side, then the other. This will give you
two long lines on either side of the peak. Use a circular saw to
cut on the line just through the sheathing. Be careful not to cut
into the rafters beneath _ this could compromise the structural
strength of the roof.
</P>
<P>
   After completing the cuts, pry away the sheathing, then apply a
generous bead of caulking on either side of the gap. Position the
vent on the peak then fasten it down by driving gasketed roofing
nails through the mounting flanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
