<HEADER>
A1091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      03-31 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Potted Azaleas
</P>
<P>
   Q. I was given a large potted azalea at Christmastime. It
bloomed heavily through January. Can I plant it outdoors in the
spring? Would it be better to put it out in the summer and then
take it indoors?
</P>
<P>
   A. The azaleas sold for winter bloom indoors are usually from a
group called India hybrids, large-flowered plants that flourish in
the Deep South but are not hardy in the North. Dr. Robert Hobbs,
editor of The Azalean, the quarterly journal of the Azalea Society
of America, says: ``My idea would be to put it outside for the
summer in a lightly shaded spot. The plant should stay in its pot
but be buried in soil up to the rim. It has to stay moist but not
wet, so if it's in plastic, repot it in terra cotta.'' (Unlike
plastic, terra cotta is porous. Soil in terra cotta pots dries out
faster when the pots are exposed, but stays moist longer when they
are buried.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave it out for a month to six weeks after the first frost,
'' he said. ``In order to bloom, the plant needs a chilling period
at near-freezing temperatures. Thirty-two to 40 degrees would be
ideal, but be sure not to let it get colder than 20. Bring it
inside, put it in a sunny spot, give it a little bone meal or other
bloom-enhancing fertilizer and water it well. It should bloom
around Christmastime.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hobbs didn't mention aphids, whiteflies and red spider
mites, all indoor pests that are likely to find your azalea
attractive, but he did point out that this branch of the
rhododendron family was huge. There are hundreds of other azaleas,
including scores of beauties far hardier than your houseplant.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to learn more, consider joining Dr. Hobbs and his
fellow aficionados, both amateur and professional, in the Azalea
Society of America (P.O. Box 34536, West Bethesda, Md. 20827, 301
855-5269). Membership costs $25 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Elusive Piquillo
</P>
<P>
   Q. I read an article in The New York Times on Jan. 6 about
piquillo peppers from Spain. They sound interesting, but I have
been unable to find a source for seeds. Do you know of one?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I have not been able to find a United States source for
plants or seeds of any pepper called piquillo, as described in ``A
Hot Sweet Taste of the Spanish North'' (Dining In/Dining Out),
which reports that chefs are turning to these horn-shaped sweet,
hot peppers from Navarre, though they are available only in jars
and cans.
</P>
<P>
   Piquillos are probably an old-fashioned seed-saver's variety,
not a modern hybrid. Dr. Paul Bosland, a hot pepper expert, who is
a professor in the horticulture department at New Mexico State
University in Las Cruces, said that in this country ``Hungarian
paprika would be about as close as you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   They're thick walled and sweet,'' he continued, ``but the
hotness does vary. Be sure you get one of the mild kinds.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood roast one of those, and you'll get something resembling the
peppers that sound so appetizing in the article.
</P>
<P>
   Resemblance is as far as you'd be likely to get even if you did
find piquillo seeds, because growing produce is like selling real
estate: location is everything. (Think about the way wine people
are always going on about where the stuff is from.) The flavors of
vegetables and fruits are genetically determined, but how those
flavors are expressed depends a lot on climate and soil. Yours may
be excellent for pepper growing, but they won't be the same as
those in Lodosa, Spain, the piquillos' home ground.
</P>
<P>
   To get as close as possible, try growing peppers that are
described as thick fleshed, sweet and mildly piquant _ bull nose
would be another good choice. Roast and peel samples of everything,
then have a taste test, using canned piquillos as your standard.
It's likely that you'll do well with at least one of your
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   For the widest range of possible peppers, consult The Garden
Seed Inventory, available from Seed Savers Exchange, 3076 North
Winn Road, Decorah, Iowa 52101, (319) 382-5990; $26 for softcover.
The catalog comes close to listing all the nonhybrid vegetable
seeds available commercially in the United States, along with
sources where they can be obtained. Paprika and bull nose are
available from Southern Exposure Seed Exchange, P.O. Box 170,
Earlysville, Va. 22936, (804) 973-4703 (catalog, $2).
</P>
<P>
   Skunks in the Suburbs
</P>
<P>
   Q. I live in a lovely suburb 15 minutes outside Boston, and we
have a large skunk community. How can I keep them out of my yard?
Is there some kind of plant or shrub or other organic matter they
will avoid? It wouldn't be a problem except that my dog cannot stay
away from them. Is there a way to get rid of them?
</P>
<P>
   A. Getting rid of them is not to be. Skunks have adapted very
well to the suburbs, where there are lots of good things to eat _
lawn grubs, earthworms, mice and rats _ and plenty of sheltered
places to build dens. When you remove a skunk from such habitat,
all you do is open territory for the next boarder.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to keep them out of your yard is with a low, tight
wire mesh fence. Skunks don't do much climbing, so two feet tall
should be adequate. They do dig, though, which means you'll want to
bury the fencing six to eight inches deep. Nothing repels them, but
they are easily attracted, especially by grub-infested lawns and
anything fishy, meaty or sweet. (They love moldy cake and stale
cookies almost as much as raccoons do.) Some authorities suggest
drenching the lawn with pesticides to get rid of the grubs, but
even doing that is unlikely to solve the skunk problem completely.
It's important to keep the garbage covered, and to be aware that
such organic fertilizers as blood meal and bone meal are powerful
lures. Keep unused supplies in tightly lidded containers, and be
sure to work the fertilizers well into the soil as soon as you use
them.
</P>
<P>
   As you note, however, the problem is not so much with the skunks
as with your dog, and the easiest solution is probably to control
the pooch rather than the polecats.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York 10036
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
