<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1095 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-DOUBTS-A     03-31 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-DOUBTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETWEEN TECH FANS AND NAYSAYERS, SCHOLARLY SKEPTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Mont., N.Y., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the forces that permeate daily life, perhaps nothing
merits the close scrutiny of scholars more than technology.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of people who are critical of technology. They
range from extremists like Theodore J. Kaczynski, the Unabomber, to
popular authors with a less fanatical approach, like the astronomer
Clifford Stoll (``Silicon Snake Oil'') or the unyielding naysayer
Kirkpatrick Sale (``Rebels Against the Future'').
</P>
<P>
   But relatively few scholars _ a few dozen philosophers,
historians and computer scientists _ concentrate on technology the
way medical and environmental ethicists concentrate on the fate of
the planet or issues related to the human body.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of skeptical view of the human use of natural resources
that characterizes a field like deep ecology is harder to find
among the people who study technology, said Andrew Light, an
assistant professor of philosophy and environmental studies at the
State University of New York at Binghamton who splits his time
between environmental ethics and the philosophy of technology.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Light said, it can sometimes get a little lonely for
those in the business of suggesting that the profound technical
revolution computers have brought about is as much of a problem as
it is a boon.
</P>
<P>
   Three philosophers who take a skeptical approach are Hubert L.
Dreyfus of the University of California at Berkeley; Joseph
Weizenbaum, who retired from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, and Albert Borgmann at the University of Montana. They
all continue to pursue lines of thought about technology that they
first articulated 25 or 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And there are some newcomers trying to move theoretical work in
more practical directions, like Richard E. Sclove, founder of the
Loka Institute in Amherst, Mass. Sclove is actively engaged in
community organizing and public policy issues related to
technology, as is Gary Chapman, director of the 21st Century
Project at the Lyndon B. Johnson School of Public Affairs at the
University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The common thread in all their thoughts is that not enough
attention is being paid to the limitations of computers and the
moral and political consequences of putting computers where people
used to be.
</P>
<P>
   These philosophers are not Luddites. On the contrary, they not
only use computers and other electronic products, but they also
admire and depend on them. ``I have a recordable Walkman that just
blows my mind, it's so beautiful,'' said Dreyfus, 69, a philosophy
professor at Berkeley. ``And I love my laptop.'' Drefyus said he
was also impressed by new software for continuous speech
recognition that allows you to dictate to your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus first drew attention for his views in 1972 with the
publication of a defiant book titled ``What Computers Can't Do''
(Harper &AMP; Row). It challenged the assumptions of the nascent field
of artificial intelligence, saying it was theoretically impossible
to build truly intelligent computers. Dreyfus holds firm to his
view. ``Computers have been getting faster and faster at an amazing
rate,'' he said, ``but as I predicted, they are not getting more
intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Dreyfus has criticized Cog, a humanoid robot
built by artificial intelligence researchers at MIT. ``All I can
say for now is that I am ready to go out on a limb and predict Cog
won't learn a thing,'' Dreyfus said.
</P>
<P>
   He does not deny that computing technology is good for many
tasks. ``My interest is in people who claim more promise for
computers than can be done because they don't understand how
different humans are from computers when it comes to performing in
a human world,'' Dreyfus said.
</P>
<P>
   He is joined in his skepticism of artificial intelligence by
Weizenbaum, an MIT computer scientist who is known for having
written a program more than 30 years ago called Eliza, which
imitated a Rogerian psychologist. His intention in writing Eliza,
he wrote later, was not to prove that a computer could understand
natural language but to demonstrate that language is understood
only in contextual frameworks.
</P>
<P>
   Weizenbaum wrote that he had been alarmed to see people become
captivated with the program and engage in long, typed conversations
with it. ``What I had not realized is that extremely short
exposures to a relatively simple computer program could induce
powerful delusional thinking in quite normal people,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Now retired and living in Berlin, Weizenbaum, 76, continues to
lecture and write on the topic of misguided faith in computers and,
now, the Internet. ``The Internet is like one of those garbage
dumps outside of Bombay,'' he said in an interview. ``There are
people, most unfortunately, crawling all over it, and maybe they
find a bit of aluminum, or perhaps something they can sell. But
mainly it's garbage.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Dreyfus and Weizenbaum have concentrated on what computers
cannot do, Langdon Winner, who is a political scientist at the
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in Troy, N.Y., and is trained as a
social and political theorist, comes to the topic from a more
political viewpoint, focusing more on what computers
(italics)should(end italics) not do.
</P>
<P>
   Winner is known for his view that technological advances have
political implications. A prominent example that Winner cited in
his 1986 book, ``The Whale and the Reactor: A Search for Limits in
an Age of High Technology,'' was the system of overpasses in and
around New York City that were designed by Robert Moses.
</P>
<P>
   The overpasses on the parkway to Jones Beach, for example, were
built low and prevented access by public buses. One consequence,
Winner pointed out, was to exclude low-income people, including
many members of racial minorities, who depended on public
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``As I looked at all kinds of technological systems, it seemed
to me that the stuff of politics is almost always built into
them,'' Winner said. ``A lot of the issues that have concerned
people from Plato to Hannah Arendt are questions located in the
kinds of things we call technology: our experience of being free or
unfree, the social arrangements that either foster equality or
inequality, the kinds of institutions that hold and use power and
authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Winner, who is 54, said he had been inspired as a graduate
student to continue a course of study in technology and politics
after auditing one of the first classes Dreyfus taught on computers
and intelligence at Berkeley in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Winner has examined how the introduction of computers and the
Internet could drive out other styles of living and what he calls
``crucial forms of locally based commerce.'' He refuses to purchase
a book, for instance, from Amazon.com because he worries about the
effect that online bookstores are having on, say, his own local
bookstore in Chatham, N.Y., whose owner is Muriel Faxon. ``I say:
`Think global. Shop Muriel,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a skeptic about the tendency to move agreeable kinds of
human interaction, particularly those that bring us into contact
with strangers, into a digital world. We want to have places that
feel comfortable, secure and friendly. I can't figure out why we're
so busily eliminating those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Dreyfus and Winner, as well as Weizenbaum, are highly
suspicious of computers in education and especially suspicious of
so-called distance learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some nontraditional students who, for one reason or
another, would find it excessively difficult to actually drive to a
university campus several times a week,'' Winner said, ``and I
don't have any problem with that. But there are some very important
parts of education that have to be done in the physical presence of
others.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Luddite label is affixed to Winner and his colleagues,
they bristle. But in these times, their message is easily
misunderstood. ``They reach a public and a media and an industry
that has no room except for friends and enemies,'' said Sherry
Turkle, a professor of the sociology of science at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Like Winner, Borgmann has written extensively on the high social
cost of high tech. And like his fellow skeptics, Borgmann starts
many conversations by pointing out that he is not against computers
per se. ``The question is,'' he said, ``how the computer will
insinuate itself into culture at large, and into leisure, how it
will further isolate people from one another.''
</P>
<P>
   As the veteran skeptics enter their 60s and 70s, it is logical
to assume that a younger generation of scholars will pick up where
they leave off. Indeed, a number of departments devoted to science
and technology studies have sprouted in the past two decades at
places like MIT, Cornell University and the Virginia Polytechnic
Institute and State University.
</P>
<P>
   But compared with fields like environmental ethics, in which
virtually every major academic press is publishing books, young
philosophers of technology remain relatively scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your average graduate student in philosophy is very unlikely
to get any exposure at all to the philosophy of technology,'' said
Light, who is 32. As a graduate student, he said, he was fortunate
to meet Andrew Feenberg, a philosopher at San Diego State
University who encouraged him to pursue the study of technology.
Light hopes not only to bring more philosophers to the study of
technology, but also to make them a more visible part of public
discourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you work on issues like the effects of technology on
society, we're remiss if we don't talk about our work in a public
context,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weizenbaum is not heartened by the level of public discourse
about technology. ``Speaking globally,'' he said, ``society is
suffering from a gigantic failure of critical thinking. In a
certain sense people are getting dumber. People seem to have lost
the capacity for skepticism and what I call critical thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   But Borgmann is relatively optimistic. He said he believed that
the public was more likely now to turn its attention to technology
and its effect on the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come to a point,'' he said, ``where a lot of people are
going from a station wagon to an SUV, or from old-style TV to
high-definition TV, or a machine that runs at 266 megahertz to one
that runs at 500, and they'll ask, `Is that all?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1603EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
