<HEADER>
A1100 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-31 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOYS OF SUMMER WILL JUST HAVE TO WAIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring is officially here. The grass is ripening like a sweet
green apple. Flowers are blooming like colorful microwave popcorn.
And I'm very, very worried.
</P>
<P>
   I'm worried because spring is summer's maid of honor, and summer
is coming down that flower-strewn aisle at a rapid pace.
Unfortunately, I am not ready for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   I thought that I was ready. I maintained my weight over the
winter. You know, nothing ventured, nothing gained. But I think
that my muscles must have melted a little bit under all those
layers of corduroy and wool.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I was trying on my swimming suit recently in preparation
for a family vacation in Florida. My husband wandered into the
bedroom and caught me hiding in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' he exclaimed, his eyes nearly popping out of the
sockets. ``You bought a thong swimming suit! I can't believe it! I
thought you hated those. I've been trying to get you to buy one for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not new,'' I mumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what are you saving it for? Why haven't you worn it
before now? I certainly don't want you to wear it at the YMCA pool,
but you could wear it around the house with those nice, red pumps
that I like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those pumps hurt my feet. The heels are so high that I fell
and sprained my wrist the last time that I wore them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, forget the pumps. Just wear the new swimsuit with some
houseshoes when the kids spend the night with your folks this
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that it's not new, OK! This is the suit that I bought
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year? No way, that thing was huge. It looked like a
shorts set. It was ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's still ugly, and this is it. I think the chlorine
made it shrink or something.''
</P>
<P>
   The merriment danced in his eyes until it came parading out of
his mouth as outright laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, I was in front of the TV working out to an
aerobics video. I did great for the first 10 minutes; then my body
turned on the sweat hydrant. I almost drowned during the next 10
minutes. I was gasping for breath when the video instructor said,
``All right, we're all warmed up now. Let's do some real
exercise!''
</P>
<P>
   I crumpled to the floor, crawled to the VCR and pushed the eject
button. By then, I couldn't have found my thong without exploratory
surgery. My husband finally cut one end with some scissors and the
thing snapped like a broken fan belt. I almost lost an eye when it
whipped by my face.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I've since started a low-fat diet; I gained 2 pounds the
first week.
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, I wrote Congress and asked them to extend spring
by one month this year. I haven't gotten a reply, but I'm hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a word of caution from someone who knows: Never, ever
do tae-bo in a thong bikini. I can't explain the details. Just take
my word for it.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
