<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALLIED-TROOPS (Washington) _ The United States and its
European allies take emergency steps to alleviate the deepening
humanitarian crisis along the Kosovo borders. The effort could set
the stage for possible deployment of British, French and Italian
ground forces in Kosovo backed by U.S. warplanes. By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOSNIA (Sarajevo, Bosnia) _ Some 7,000 Muslim refugees
from another part of Serbia, the Sandzak region, flee to the
Bosnian capital of Sarajevo, bringing accounts of beatings and
murders by Serbians and tanks massing outside their villages. By
LAURA PETERSON.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GROUND (Washington) _ Republican hawks, including former
Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and former U.N. Ambassador Jeane
Kirkpatrick, call for the use of ground forces in Yugoslavia. By
BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EMBASSY (Washington) _ Yugoslav diplomats are rousted out
of their Embassy in Washington. A look at the development and a
discussion of what happens when nations sever relations. By
JENNIFER DAY.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-STATES-RIGHTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court struggles
with state sovereignty vs. federal power in a case involving an
overtime-pay dispute from Maine. The key issue is whether state
employees may legally sue the state in its own courts to make it
follow federal rules regarding such pay. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHER-DRIVING (Washington) _ Could that have been Bill Archer,
the chairman of the House Ways and Means, driving alone in a
suburban Virginia high-occupancy vehicle lane recently? An irate
fellow motorist identified the small car by the license plate
(Texas-7). An aide concedes that it is the route Archer is known to
frequent. But the chairman, in Australia, won't comment. By BENNETT
ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush has raised
$6 million in one month for his potential run for the Republican
presidential nomination, his exploratory committee says. The
Republican vows not to make any decision about running for the
presidency until the state Legislature concludes its session later
this spring. By LAURA TOLLEY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHILDREN (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush hosts a
daylong conference on ``right choices for youth'' in an effort to
burnish his conservative credentials. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES and R.G.
RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   PAROLE-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas Board of Pardons and
Paroles adopts a rule requiring death-row inmates to file their
commutation requests at least 21 days before their executions.
Opponents complain this will make it difficult for some inmates to
get their requests in on time, denying them of due process. By
KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ A $95 billion state budget for
2000-2001 wins unanimous approval in the Texas House Appropriations
Committee, marking a 9.6 percent increase over the current
biennium. Public schools will get the biggest chunk of new money _
a 13 percent increase _ and about $700 million was left for tax
cuts. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JAZZ (Salt Lake City) _ They have struggled a bit lately,
but the Utah Jazz still retain their position as one of the elite
teams in the NBA. And the Houston Rockets will get a chance to find
out how they measure up on Thursday night. By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Salt Lake City) _ Riding high with a nine-game
winning streak, the Houston Rockets head into Utah as the hottest
team in the NBA to face their first meeting of the season against
their longtime nemesis, the Utah Jazz. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ America's intervention in
Yugoslavia raises questions once more about our national interest,
our humanitarian obligations and our leadership in international
organizations created as a result of our conviction that collective
security is essential to peace. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
