<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1116 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-0401-COX     03-31 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-0401-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT TRIAL SUSPENDED AS TALKS CONTINUE
 &HT;    Moving in (f) finance and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- With settlement talks underway, the presiding
judge in the Microsoft antitrust case Wednesday put the trial on
hold until at least May 10, giving the government and the software
giant nearly six weeks to strike a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief status hearing, U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson did not allude to the top-level talks, which began
Tuesday at the Justice Department. When he recessed the high-stakes
trial on Feb. 26 for what appeared then to be a six-week hiatus,
Jackson had pointedly called the warring parties into his chambers
to urge them to use the time wisely.
</P>
<P>
   In taking a joint vow of silence on the courthouse plaza
Wednesday, lawyers for the government and the company signaled that
they were serious in their resolve to settle the case. Microsoft,
the world's largest software firm, has denied the government's
contention that the company illegally expanded its dominance over
operating systems for personal computers into such other realms as
Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But when Microsoft made the first move last week to reach an
accord, several state attorneys general, who are also parties to
the case, were quick to assert that the company's proposed remedies
fell far short of an acceptable outcome.
</P>
<P>
   If there is continuing skepticism on the government's part over
Microsoft's commitment to a settlement, it remained hidden amid an
effort to present a common front on the one area over which there
is seeming complete agreement -- the need to impose secrecy over
the coming negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are going to be productive settlement discussions,
those discussions can't take place publicly,'' said David Boies,
the government's lead attorney. ``Consequently, none of us will
have any comment whatsoever about settlement discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   William Neukom, Microsoft's veteran general counsel, standing
beside Boies, nodded in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Their unprecedented joint statement followed 62 days of
testimony by 24 witnesses, much of it under cross-examination, when
the mood in the small courtroom was often tense and bitter.
</P>
<P>
   But after the hearing, Boies and Neukom emerged from the judge's
chambers to quickly brief their own teams and -- with the courtroom
locked and cleared of spectators -- together draft what would be
said to the press a few minutes later on the courthouse plaza.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, Boies, had flanked Joel Klein, the Justice
Department's antitrust chief when the talks opened in Klein's
guarded third-floor conference room. Also present were Iowa
Attorney General Tom Miller and Connecticut Attorney General
Richard Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Neukom, Microsoft is being represented at the talks by
Richard Urowsky, a silent but potent legal presence at the defense
table who had brokered a 1995 consent decree for his Microsoft
clients, and by Charles Rule, who had held Klein's current
antitrust post during the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   In further suspending the trial -- it was originally set to
resume April 12 -- Jackson has made a virtue of necessity: he is
currently presiding over a murder case that, he noted, could well
run beyond the May 10 date that he has set as the earliest one on
which the Microsoft trial could resume.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the settlement talks fail to produce results, Jackson
will hear from six rebuttal witnesses -- three from each side. The
list of those witnesses is due April 23.
</P>
<P>
   After the rebuttal witnesses, Jackson will give the parties 30
days to submit written proposed ``findings of fact,'' in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson then will issue his own ``findings of fact,'' which in
turn will trigger oral closing arguments. Each side will have more
time to frame their own proposed ruling -- known as ``conclusions
of law'' -- before Jackson will issue the only ruling that counts.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft should lose, Jackson will probably convene the
remedy phase of the trial. No matter which side wins, the other
side is virtually certain to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
