<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1119 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      03-31 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
27)  
 HIS NEW DOORS DON'T CLOSE PROPERLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeaating for Indianapolis and all needing; moved Thursday, March (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. In my new house, there are two interior doors that hit the
top jamb on the latch side of the door when I try to close them.
How can I fix that?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN TOSCANO, Onset, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If it is truly a new house, the contractors should fix those
doors, which may be hung slightly askew. Or, possibly, some
settlement knocked them out of plumb.
</P>
<P>
   Short of all that folderol, this is what you can do. Check the
hinges to make sure they are tightly screwed on. Sometimes just
tightening them will bring the door back into position. If they are
tight, shim out the top hinge; unscrew one leaf of that hinge (the
one on the jamb) and insert a piece of cardboard the shape of the
leaf into the mortise, where the hinge normally goes. Reattach the
leaf and see what happens. This shimming will drop the door's latch
side by a bit, clearing the jamb opening. If the door has three
hinges, you may have to shim the middle one, too. And be careful
that you don't drop the latch side so much that that side binds in
the jamb.
</P>
<P>
   If none of these tricks works, you may have to cut or plane down
the top edge to make it clear.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another idea in the continuing battle against pigeons on
the roof. M.T. of Danvers, Mass. called to say she tried
everything: a fishing line laced zigzag fashion on small stakes, a
fake owl, needle boards, and Tanglefoot (a sticky substance), all
without success. In desperation, she cut two pieces of garden hose
3 feet long and placed them on the roof, looking squiggly like a
moving snake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had no pigeons for 15 years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wow, that is a long time to fool pigeons, but they must have
gotten the message. It may not work for everyone, but you have to
believe it worked for M.T.
</P>
<P>
   I believe any color hose could be used, but I think green or
black would be most appropriate, or effective.
</P>
<P>
   Another caller gave this tip: Water the pigeons down with a hose
as often as possible. Eventually they will get the point.
</P>
<P>
   That latter idea is best for one-story houses. Once again, the
handyman expresses his thanks, and is happy to pass on the tips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q.The mortar between the bricks in my fireplace's firebox are
crumbling. The house is nine years old, and the gaps are 3/8-inch
wide. What's wrong, and how can I fill those gaps and keep the
mortar from falling out again?
</P>
<P>
   TONY TONELLI, Winchendon, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Ordinary mortar in a firebox will burn out fairly quickly; a
firebox like that should be made of fire brick (hard-baked clay,
yellow in color) with fire clay (a special type of mortar) between
them.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have such fire brick, you can repoint: Chip and dig
out all loose mortar to a depth of at least 3/4 inch and as wide as
the joint. Dry-brush any mortar residue, dampen the joints, and
insert fresh mortar. You can buy a high-quality mortar at hardware
and building stores; it is called mortar mix, made by Sacrete. Add
water to make a crumbly, not soupy mix, and insert this in the
joints, using a pointing tool, an inexpensive tool sold in hardware
stores that allows you to push the mortar in compactly. You must
compact that mortar; otherwise it will fail. Another reason why the
original mortar failed is uncompacted mortar. The reason you wet
down the joint is to prevent the dry brick from pulling moisture
out of the mortar excessively and prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am renovating my house, but the floors are a little slanty,
which I do not plan to level. But they slope enough to make double
doors scrape the floor when they are opened. What can I do to
prevent that scraping?
</P>
<P>
   BILL MURKO, Ipswich, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If they are interior doors, you could trim the bottoms of
them. Or, reset the framing so the doors are a little higher. That
latter chore sounds like a lot of work; it is. It even sounds a
little barmy, but the Handyman has done it. One often has to do
some weird things in an old house.
</P>
<P>
   But here is an easy way out: Install rising butt hinges on the
door; these hinges are set on a cam that raises the door when it is
open. They are made by Constantine; telephone 800-223-8087.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The glass stopper is stuck in my antique glass decanter. I
heated the glass, and used some penetrating oil. Neither worked. In
fact, I think someone superglued the two together. What can I do
next?
</P>
<P>
   BOB WARSHAW, Marlborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You did the two classical remedies, but you might not have
worked the heat properly. To do so, soak the decanter in warm
water, and let it heat up. Then pour cool water on the stopper.
Since the decanter is antique, I would be very careful using hot
and cold water on old glass.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of WD40 or penetrating oil, try glycerin, which may
penetrate better than other oils. If this fails, call Trefler &AMP;
Sons in Needham at 781-444-2685. They specialize in restoring and
repairing china, ceramic, porcelain, and other materials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
