<SLUG> BC-BROWN-MYSTERYNOVEL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR LETS A CAT DO THE TALKING IN HER SEVENTH MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 26 years since her lesbian pride novel ``Rubyfruit
Jungle'' established her as an instant and lonely voice for the
literary gay community, Rita Mae Brown has made all sorts of
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's personal life, especially a relationship with tennis
star Martina Navratilova, fueled gossip columns and tabloids. Her
poetry and ``serious fiction'' _ mostly novels combining wicked
humor and social sensibility _ have captivated critics. Brown's
screenplays have emphasized history and human rights, particularly
HBO's ``The Nat Turner Story.'' She founded FREE, the Feminist
Repertory and Experiment Ensemble, to give female writers and
performers a stage for less-than-mainstream stage productions.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a serious woman interested in making a serious
impression. And yet, the 54-year-old Virginia native is currently
touring the country on behalf of ``Cat on the Scent,'' the seventh
in a series of mystery novels whose hero-sleuth is a feline named
Sneaky Pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't think writing the occasional Sneaky Pie book is a
contradiction to my other interests,'' Brown says. ``The cat
consciousness is fun. You've got the human master, and this little
cat is always sort of pushing her to be smarter. See, I live out in
the country, I grew up in the country, and I was always in contact
with animals who were a lot more intelligent and aware than humans.
Did you know a horse can gather seven times more information than
we can because of the way its eyes are spaced?''
</P>
<P>
   Conversations with Brown become minilectures. She knows a great
deal about many subjects, and she isn't shy about demonstrating it.
But her smile is so genuine, and her enthusiasm for topics ranging
from fox hunting to weight lifting is so great, that the effect is
friendly rather than intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to write any book; technically, it's very
difficult,'' Brown says. ``Sneaky Pie books aren't easy, though in
a sense they are relaxation from my real, or serious, work. The
problem often is, though, that when you tackle serious causes like
feminism, when you try and stand up for what you believe in, people
lose their sense of fun. And there's nothing wrong with having fun.
We're not on Earth to be sad or serious all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1973, ``Rubyfruit Jungle'' gave readers and the public a
certain impression of Brown that she hasn't been able to escape.
She accepts her reputation without entirely agreeing with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people just think I'm sort of a gay Girl Scout, hopefully
a good one,'' she says. ``I'll carry that reputation with me until
I die. But I have to say that the early '70s were fearful days,
when nobody in my (gay) situation felt safe admitting what they
were. So in terms of me, well, I said it loud, and all these years
later it feels pretty good, at least to me, that I did it. I was
raised to stand up and fight. I still do. If I see someone kicking
a dog, I'm going to go over and kick the one who's doing the
kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, her primary motivation remains just putting words on
paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live to write,'' she says. ``The English language is just a
cathedral of sounds. It's a privilege to be a writer in this
cathedral. I never want to leave it. I want to be around to write a
really good novel when I'm 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown segues to what aspiring writers ought to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where our language is concerned, if you want to write, then
you must read the great writers and learn from them,'' she insists.
``Homer, of course; Euripides because he invented the tragic comedy
and perfected it; Shakespeare; Virginia Woolf, who can be so
difficult and infuriating; Gertrude Stein, who will also be
infuriating, but still can teach young writers everything they need
to learn about using the present participle.''
</P>
<P>
   Mentioning young writers reminds Brown of Monica Lewinsky, whose
``Monica's Story'' (written by Andrew Morton) briefly topped the
bestseller lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at that girl and I think, `This poor soul,' '' Brown
says. ``It's all too human and too understandable what she did,
what happened to her, but how is she going to feel about it when
she's 50? Right now she gives the impression she's not entirely
sorry; that, in some ways, she's actually proud of what happened
with her and the president. When she gets older, she's going to
realize what a mess she made.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown acknowledges that she's made her share of messes; breakups
with some lovers have been anything but discreet. But she's not
wasting time on regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried, above all, to be honest,'' Brown says. ``I'm at a
point now where I can write my books, do a Sneaky Pie title now and
then, have some fun and indulge my interests. I still have a lot of
things I want to do, like visit the great opera house in Vienna and
fox hunt in Ireland. After a certain age, maybe 40, you always have
to ask yourself, `Do I want more in life or less?' And I always
want more.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
