<SLUG> BC-FILM-MATRIX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MATRIX' KICKS THRILLER GENRE UP A NOTCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's almost worth seeing the sci-fi action thriller ``The
Matrix'' just to catch Keanu Reeves mouth the word he was born to
utter _ ``Whooaaa'' _ in that stoner's deadpan of his. ``The
Matrix'' is another wily genre bend from the Wachowski brothers,
Andy and Larry, the talented pair behind 1997's no-budget pretzel
twist of a noir, ``Bound.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, they've taken on science fiction, and more important,
the Joseph Campbell mythological bent the genre has acquired since
``Star Wars.'' (Not to mention the
``snatch-the-pebble-from-my-hand'' fakey Eastern philosophy from
``Kung Fu''; I always wondered why George Lucas never gave David
Carradine any props.)
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is computer programmer Thomas Anderson, the Luke
Skywalker-ish figure who has to be convinced that he has, if not
the Force, then an incredible simulation. (He's portentously
referred to as The One.) And who could be better at playing
slightly out-of-it incredulity than Reeves? With his coma-dark
eyes, long neck and quizzical expression, he's like a real-life
relative of Olive Oyl from the old Popeye cartoons, and his dazed,
deliberate ``Wha ...?'' makes him look as if his thought processes
operate on a five-second delay.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's dreams of pursuit and arrest, which keep him sweaty
and shocked, have begun to intrude on his thoughts. But he soon
learns that he's not just paranoid. He's told that the world we all
think we exist in is basically a dream state, created by a computer
network to keep everyone blissed out on mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   Morpheus (a sonorous-voiced Obi-Wan Kenobi figure played by
Laurence Fishburne) is the man to emerge from the underground and
inform Anderson _ renamed Neo _ that he is The One. Meaning, Neo
has the gift to defeat the monstrous machine that keeps the world
subjugated. And also to do away with the automatons in
charcoal-gray suits and dark glasses _ human-appearing
manifestations of the computers _ who are out to crush Morpheus'
band. These creatures are led by Bob Smith (Australian actor Hugo
Weaving, from ``Priscilla, Queen of the Desert.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Matrix'' bolts from the block with a rush of adrenaline,
running to keep a few steps ahead of the mold that could be growing
on the cliches. Of course, Morpheus trains Neo to disbelieve what
he sees. And, for some reason, to practice kung fu and other
Oriental fighting techniques. This seems odd, because the
automatons can't be defeated in this way; they're even faster than
Morpheus' artificially enhanced freedom fighters. But the fights
look great.
</P>
<P>
   The Wachowskis use this opportunity to pack in the garish
fluidity of Hong Kong action movies, with the opponents pitted
against one another like video-game warriors. The hand-to-hand
fight sequences are filmed with stop-action cameras that could
probably track a raindrop to the ground frame by frame. The
slender, fit cast looks great whipping into the air, a martial-arts
version of The Gap's ``Swing'' commercial, although most of the men
look as if they've had their heads shaved with a belt sander.
</P>
<P>
   The whole rickety mess is built atop a dystopic cyberpunk vista
influenced by William Gibson. (It's almost as if Reeves chose to
star in this movie to make up for his role in the Gibson-inspired
``Johnny Mnemonic,'' a barking trout of a film.) It's rare, and
kind of touching, really, to see a lushly financed studio
spectacular work so hard to keep everyone's attention. And with
enough symbolism _ Reeves' name, Neo, means ``new'' and is an
anagram for ``one'' _ to keep online chat rooms busier than the day
``Babylon 5'' was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``Matrix'' steals a piece of almost every sci-fi
movie of the past 20 years, from ``Aliens'' to ``Dark City.'' Its
majestic silliness gives the directors a chance to use their
prowling camera around the vast spaces of Sydney, Australia, where
it was filmed. They also came up with a florid visualization of
their allegory: The real world gives everyone a faded, bluish tinge
as if it were lighted with industrial-strength fluorescent bulbs,
but inside the Matrix the colors are Kodak-ad vivid.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, although overlong, is an exhilarating mixture of
pulp-grandiosity and the kind of big-budget thrill-seeking that TV
has been unable to supplant. (Take some earplugs, because this film
is also brain-shaking loud.) And luckily, ``The Matrix'' is smart
enough to have a sense of humor. A knowing smirk dances around its
lips, especially since Morpheus is constantly saying, ``You cannot
know what the Matrix is'' and then taking the better part of the
picture trying to explain it. Based on the kind of box-office smash
it's bound to be, Jason Patric better start working out, in case
Reeves turns down the sequel.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Matrix''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Larry and Andy Wachowski
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Keanu Reeves, Laurence Fishburne
</P>
<P>
   Length: 135 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence and mayhem, adult language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
