<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
IT'S MY BOYCOTT, BUT i'LL WATCH IF I WANT TO 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hard-core baseball boycotters say I'm a wimp.
</P>
<P>
   Nonboycotters say I'm ambivalent, indecisive, confused.
</P>
<P>
   People who don't care about baseball one way or the other say
it's fine by them if I boycott _ or if I don't. They just want me
to shut up about it.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could. But I can't. I've been boycotting, or
semiboycotting, baseball for so long that I just can't stop _ and I
can't stop talking about it, either.
</P>
<P>
   If I gave up my boycott, I'd be in the same situation that the
Clinton-haters will be in once America's bad-boy president leaves
the White House: What in the world will they complain about?
</P>
<P>
   My love-hate relationship with baseball, especially major-league
baseball, is too embedded in heart and mind to be altered. I have
loved baseball since thrilling to the exploits of all-time greats
such as Stan Musial, Mickey Mantle and Willie Mays way back in the
1950s. I have hated it since the early '90s, when overpaid players
and greedy team owners started bickering about their millions and
billions.
</P>
<P>
   I launched my first boycott after a ``labor dispute'' between
players and owners that disrupted spring training in 1990. The
details of the dispute were irrelevant; I was outraged that
big-league ballplayers had the audacity to mention the word
``labor'' in the same sentence with ``baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The boycott has been an on-again/off-again operation since then,
peaking in intensity after baseball's most loathsome affront to its
fans: the 1994 strike that wiped out part of the season, all of the
playoffs and _ horror of horrors _ the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to injury in recent years were the antics of
arrogant, ungrateful creeps such as Albert Belle, whose
considerable accomplishments on the ballfield have been tarnished
by his chronic and apparently compulsive abuse of fans, media and
fellow players. Belle is hardly the only jerk to play baseball _
remember Vince Coleman, who threw an explosive device at a group of
fans? _ but he's as representative a symbol of the game's
degradation as you could name.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately _ or fortunately, depending on your point of view
_ my anger at the participants has not diminished my affection for
the sport that once reigned as America's national pastime. Is it
possible to love the game even while despising the corruption?
</P>
<P>
   Sure it is. Which is why I seem ambivalent and indecisive about
the boycott.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to turn your back on baseball if you really don't care
about it. There is no shortage of other amusements in this day and
age. But if you grew up a baseball fan at a time when baseball was
still a glorious pursuit peopled by true heroes, giving up the game
is easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   So last season, after several years of refusing even to read
game stories or box scores in the newspaper, I modified my boycott
to allow myself the luxury of watching games on television and
reading baseball news in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   This decision earned me the instant disdain of committed
boycotters, who accused me bailing out, copping out and selling
out.
</P>
<P>
   My fellow boycotters jumped on me with both feet. Either you're
boycotting or you're not, they said. You can't have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I say I can have it both ways. It's my boycott, after all;
why shouldn't I make up the rules _ and change them if want to?
</P>
<P>
   My main concern these days is making sure that I don't
contribute in any way to the obscene accumulation of wealth by the
perpetrators of the business we call baseball. That means no
in-person attendance at ball games and no buying licensed
merchandise such as caps, T-shirts, coffee mugs, etc.
</P>
<P>
   That may not seem like much of a boycott, but believe me when I
say that my resolve was sternly tested last September when I
visited the St. Louis area at the height of the frenzy over Mark
McGwire's home-run championship. McGwire memorabilia was
everywhere; someone even offered me a ticket to a game that had
been sold out for weeks. I had to leave town to keep from caving
in.
</P>
<P>
   So with the 1999 season only a week away, the boycott continues.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a wimpy boycott, but it's a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
