<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, April 1. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Brussels) _ NATO today stepped up its attacks
on Yugoslavia as alliance officials said they were preparing for
weeks of bombing. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ A senior NATO general tells of the
meetings and decisions leading up to the attack on Serb forces. By
Craig R. Whitney and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VUKOVAR (Vukovar, Croatia) _ This ruined city beside the
Danube River is as good a place as any to meditate on the years of
misery and score-settling that lie ahead when the Serb campaign in
Kosovo comes to an end. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Budapest, Hungary) _ A news analysis: Kosovo
could be a template for the century to come. The crisis there,
which has produced a stern test for NATO and a catastrophe for the
ethnic Albanians who form the province's overwhelming majority,
bears little resemblance to the Cold War that shaped the last half
of this century. It is not about ideology. It does not involve the
vital political or economic interests of the great powers. It
carries with it no threat of nuclear annihilation. Yet it presents
precisely the kind of problem that the Western democracies, for all
their wealth and military might, find it most difficult to cope
with. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ The president's activities today
and the choices facing the White House. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AID (Washington) _ Developments on NATO efforts to help
the refugees. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-REPORT (Washington) _ The White House said today that 92
percent of the federal government's essential computer systems were
ready for the year 2000, but predicted that Americans would have
difficulty reaching some foreign countries by telephone or airplane
next year, because their computers will not be fixed in time. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-BAPTISTS (Miami) _ The Rev. Henry Lyons, former president of
the powerful National Baptist Convention USA, was sentenced today
to 5{ years in prison for state racketeering and grand theft. After
he was convicted, he apologized for his crimes and said he was
ready to accept his punishment. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-INDICT (New York) _ Four police officers plead not
guilty to second-degree murder charges in the February shooting
death of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed African immigrant; hundreds
protest outside the courthouse. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The presiding judge in the
Microsoft antitrust trial on Wednesday set May 10 as the date for
testimony to resume and laid out a longer timetable for oral
arguments and written submissions, assuring that the trial will not
end much before the end of the year and may drag into 2000. By Joel
Brinkley.
</P>
