<HEADLINE>
STORING E-MAIL: ON DISK OR PAPER? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On many levels of government the debate continues about which is
preferable: archiving printouts of e-mail messages, or keeping them
in their electronic form. In the latter case, the mail is more
easily searched, and important header and address information is
more likely to be retained.
</P>
<P>
   But as technology changes, there is no assurance that electronic
records will be accessible down the road. ``Five years from now,
people may not be able to read those records,'' said Harry A.
Hammitt, editor and publisher of The Access Reports on information
policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Retrieving e-mail can be tricky even with newer computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Murphy, staff director of the Boston City Council, said
some council members had agreed to a newspaper reporter's request
to see their e-mail, but complying might be hard to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their e-mails actually were trashed, so to speak, as soon as
they read them,'' he said, ``so someone would have to go to our MIS
department and try to retrieve them. There are some issues there
because the council doesn't consider themselves a department and
doesn't want other city departments rifling through their computer
records either.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, e-mail was officially labeled a public record that is
subject to the federal Freedom of Information Act. (To include
e-mail in a Freedom of Information Act request, the person making
the request should add a phrase like ``including any e-mail
correspondence that relates to this issue'' in a written request to
the agency.)
</P>
<P>
   So federal officials' e-mail cannot be scrapped
indiscriminately, just as paper documents must be preserved. As
Barry Steinhardt, associate director of the American Civil
Liberties Union, put it: ``The medium is not the message. The
message is the message.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
