A1137 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-STUDENT-SUICIDE     03-31 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-STUDENT-SUICIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRAUGHT TEXAS A&AMP;M STUDENT LEAPS TO HIS DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Texas A&AMP;M University freshman, apparently despondent over
failing grades, jumped to his death from the sixth level of a
campus parking garage as police tried to dissuade him from taking
his life.
</P>
<P>
   William Berry Jr., a 19-year-old agricultural engineering
student from the Waco-area town of Hewitt, died Tuesday afternoon.
Campus police director Bob Wiatt said officers talked to Berry for
20 minutes in an effort to get him to abandon his perch on the
garage ledge.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's death occurred just one day after a 25-year-old graduate
student, whose name was not released, threatened to jump from the
same garage in College Station, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Wiatt said, officers were successful in saving the
man. The student has been admitted to Scott and White Hospital in
Temple for psychiatric treatment, Wiatt said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Berry had just been informed that he would be
dropped from the university because of failing grades. Suicide
messages were found in his truck, which was parked near the scene
of the jump, and in his dormitory room at Crocker Hall.
</P>
<P>
   One of Berry's friends, Cole Sauter of Corpus Christi, described
the student as ``just a good old Ag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just kind of kept up the grades,'' Sauter tearfully
recalled Wednesday. ``That's what finally pushed him over the edge
_ that and a lot of other college problems ... He felt he let his
parents down. That he let everybody down.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sauter said Berry struck his friends as lighthearted. ``The
strangest part,'' he said, ``is that he was really a positive
person. He preferred to help others with their problems. He prided
himself in helping whoever he could whenever he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Sauter said Berry left him a suicide message attached to his
dorm door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Birch Wade, a licensed psychologist who heads the university's
student counseling services, said that on average, one to two A&AMP;M
University students commit suicide each year. Most of those deaths
occur off campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is really low for an institution this size,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While no suicides were reported among the university's 43,400
students last year, 18 unsuccessful attempts were recorded. The
last suicide on campus, authorities said, was in 1983 when a young
man hanged himself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wade, whose office offers around-the-clock crisis intervention,
said the suicide rate for college students is 50 percent higher
than for their non-college peers.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest risk occurs among graduate students and
upperclassmen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not achieving well in school can be a factor in suicides,''
Wade said, ``but I wouldn't underline it as a factor. I wouldn't
say it's the most prominent. Students actually bring many family
problems to campus, where they get exacerbated. They have problems
relating to other students; can't conduct intimate relationships
very successfully ....
</P>
<P>
   ``All suicide attempts have different scenarios, histories. What
underlies them is a common sense of futility, a sense of
hopelessness and alienation. Some type of guilt, lack of support,
depression, low self-esteem ... Those are the more common themes.
No matter what the specific story, you usually find one or more of
those elements.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police director Wiatt said Berry's presence on the garage roof
was first detected by a security camera. A passerby also noticed
the student perched on the ledge and notified officers.
</P>
<P>
   The first campus officer, trained in crisis intervention
responded to the call in about two minutes, Wiatt said. Trained
psychologists also were summoned, but did not arrive in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was talking, but not very much,'' Wiatt said. ``He
responded to questions _ gave his name and where he was from.
Indicated it was his grades. Said he didn't want a counselor or
psychologist ... Then the young man looked at the officer and said,
`I'm sorry I have to do this. You're a good guy,' and then slipped
over the edge. &UR; '' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt said Berry fell at least 50 feet.
</P>
<P>
   He was declared dead shortly after arrival at St. Joseph Medical
Center in Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I care to say if you print this,'' added his friend
Sauter, ``is that William was a super guy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
