<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1140 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-NEWBORNS-ART-2TAK     03-31 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NEWBORNS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATERNITY WARD FASHIONS: KNIT CAPS, CHIP ID'S AND BAR CODES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Texas, N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. _ Jaylen Carr drooled, wailed and burped in
his mother's arms a day after being delivered here at Saddleback
Memorial Medical Center. With unfocused eyes and powerful lungs, he
looked and sounded like a lot of other day-old infants.
</P>
<P>
   So when the nurse entered the room, she carried a handheld
scanner to make sure that Jaylen had not been accidentally switched
with another child in the maternity ward. She scanned a data chip
on one of Jaylen's hospital identity bracelets, then did the same
to his mother, Jacquelyn Carr, who was in bed looking happy but
tired.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, the device played the lullaby ``Hush Little Baby''
to indicate that Jaylen was in fact Jaylen. If the scanner had
found a mix-up, it would have sounded an alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes you feel a little more at ease about letting your
baby go out of your room,'' Ms. Carr said. ``You feel a little more
secure that when he comes back, he is really yours. You want to be
able to say that you would recognize your child by sight, but you
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep infants from going home with the wrong parents, an
increasing number of hospitals are using technology that is more
commonly associated with department stores. Like a pair of jeans,
babies are scanned when their parents check out, and they are
protected from abduction by sensors they wear that can set off
alarms.
</P>
<P>
   But these electronic security devices, which have been on the
market for nearly five years, have drawbacks, including prices that
put them beyond some hospitals' reach. And the technology sometimes
fails or gives off false alarms that make nurses run from their
stations for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Saddleback Memorial Medical Center, located in this middle-class
Los Angeles suburb, has used scanners known as touch probes, from
Talon Medical, based in San Antonio, for nearly three years. There
have been no infant mix-ups in that time, said Jill Kennedy, the
hospital's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers, fathers and infants are fitted with scannable bracelets
just after the baby is wiped clean in the delivery room. They wear
the bands until they are discharged from the hospital; each band
contains a data chip that looks like a metal button and is
programmed with an identity number.
</P>
<P>
   Nurses scan these chips each time they move an infant to or from
its mother's room. The music that plays when the parent and child
are properly matched is intended to make the experience a little
more fun than notification by, say, a flashing green light.
</P>
<P>
   To operate the scanner, nurses touch it to the data chip on the
baby's bracelet, then to the parent's. The device determines if the
numbers embedded in the chips correspond. A similar system has just
been put on the market using bar codes. Nurses can scan the bar
codes, using a laser reader like those used at groceries.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, hospitals have visually checked the numbers on
hospital identification bracelets to keep the identities of
newborns and parents straight. But there have been several
well-publicized mix-ups using this system, including some that were
not discovered for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no way to document the number of babies
accidentally switched at the nation's hospitals because there is no
one agency that keeps those figures, and some switches may go
undiscovered.
</P>
<P>
   In February at St. Joseph Hospital in Orange, Calif., 15 miles
north of here, parents were sent home with the wrong baby. A nurse
discovered the error 90 minutes later. Two nurses were dismissed
after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Such mistakes are worrisome but also potentially dangerous
because of the possibility that diseases like HIV and hepatitis
could be transferred to babies in breast milk. Mistakes also, not
surprisingly, damage a hospital's reputation and put it in jeopardy
of losing accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Ramsey, an obstetrician at Saddleback, said mismatches
occurred for several reasons. Among the most common, he said, is
that nurses misread or forget to check the identity bracelets worn
by a mother and child.
</P>
<P>
   The probe virtually eliminates the chance of garbling numbers,
Ramsey said. Forgetting to use it is still possible, but that is
less likely, he said, because the instrument records when it is
used.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisors can download the information into a computer to
determine whether nurses are following the correct procedures. A
note about each time a child is scanned is included in each baby's
medical report.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey said the likelihood of switching infants was higher in
hospitals that have nurseries where more than a dozen babies may be
kept together and moved several times a day for feeding. At
Saddleback, however, babies are generally kept in their mothers'
rooms, partly to minimize the risk of a mix-up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine a nurse with three babies in a cart to hand out to
mothers and only five minutes until break,'' Ramsey said. ``The
nurse might not be too careful in a situation like that. You can
easily see how switches might happen, though that doesn't excuse
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals must also guard infants against people with malicious
intentions. Every year, a handful of newborns are abducted from
maternity wards. To prevent that, many hospitals have installed the
same kinds of security devices used to stop shoplifters. Babies are
fitted with sensors that set off an alarm if a child is brought
near electronic detectors installed by the door.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Webb, vice president of Talon Medical, was reluctant to
disclose much about the alarm system that his company installed at
Saddleback. He said he was concerned that such information might
help potential abductors.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Webb would disclose that each baby was fitted with a sensor
contained in a sticker. The sticker is placed somewhere on the
infant, he said, although he would not say where (other than to say
that it was not attached to the identity bracelet) to avoid tipping
off would-be abductors.
</P>
<P>
   The alarm system relies on radio waves to operate. It goes off
only when radio waves sent out by the detectors bounce back from
the stickers on the babies.
</P>
<P>
   Other alarm manufacturers are more specific about where their
sensors are placed. For example, Prosec Protection Systems, in
Lakewood, N.J., places its sensors on the umbilical cord clamps
that most babies wear for the first few days of life.
</P>
<P>
   But nurses frequently must take babies beyond the invisible
electronic walls that protect them _ to get X-rays, for example. In
such cases, the nurses must punch in a code on the computer that
controls the alarm system to shut it off for that particular
sensor. If not, or if someone actually abducts a child, an alarm
will sound when the baby nears the door.
</P>
<P>
   At some hospitals, the alarm locks doors automatically and stops
elevators. Other options for alarms include flashing lights,
recorded messages that tell listeners to ``step back'' and security
cameras that are prompted to make a continuous recording, instead
of recording every few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Saddleback's system features only an alarm, partly because the
cost of equipping the hospital's many exits with additional
security equipment would have been too high, Ramsey said. There
have yet to be any attempted kidnappings there, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, nationwide, abductions from maternity wards are rare,
considering that millions of children are born each year. John
Rabun, vice president of the National Center for Missing and
Exploited Children, said that five children were stolen from the
nation's hospitals in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are not high, thank goodness,'' Rabun said. ``But
when you look at this particular crime, it is one of the few crimes
that you should be able to prevent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabun supports electronic security systems in maternity wards,
but only to a point. He called them ``a hundred-dollar cure for a
one-dollar problem.'' He recommends simple precautions like posting
a guard at the door, confronting suspicious visitors and requiring
that babies be moved only in bassinets.
</P>
<P>
   Webb essentially agreed, saying, ``If you take a look at the
number of babies stolen, you have a much greater chance of being
hit by lightning.'' He said accidental infant switching was
probably far more common and thus provided a better rationale for
countermeasures like scanners, which his company also produces.
</P>
<P>
   Maternity ward security systems sometimes go off by accident.
Jan Kidwell, director of women's services at White Memorial Medical
Center in Los Angeles, said nurses and parents there occasionally
forgot about the alarm and set it off by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time that thing goes off, we blast out the door,'' Ms.
Kidwell said. White Memorial's alarm was installed after a baby was
abducted from the hospital in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that only a fraction of the nation's 4,500
maternity wards have alarms or infant identity systems, though the
number is increasing. Rabun estimated that 700 hospitals had
electronic security.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons that hospital executives give for not
installing such systems is the cost. The alarm systems can cost
tens of thousands of dollars, while the scanning system at
Saddleback that uses data chips costs about $20 per baby; the newly
developed bar code system costs $5 to $7 per baby. There are also
complaints about false alarms and the belief that less
sophisticated deterrents are more effective.
</P>
<P>
   One such hospital is Long Beach Memorial Medical Center in Long
Beach, Calif., which has considered buying an electronic security
system. But so far, officials there have decided that training
nurses and parents to be diligent is the best remedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that after spending that much money, you would want a
system that offers 100 percent protection,'' said Paula Gillette,
executive director of the women's hospital at the Long Beach
medical center. ``But it doesn't. The best way to prevent problems
like these is to keep the staff aware and drill to not give their
babies to people who don't have hospital badges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1638EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
