<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV18-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., APR. 18, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am in the process of applying plywood paneling to the walls
of my large family room. There is a brick fireplace and chimney in
the center of one of the long walls and I won't be covering the
bricks with the wood panels. My problem is how to get a neat fit
where the plywood panels meet the brick wall of the fireplace. I
don't want to use any kind of wide molding to cover the seam or
joint, and don't think a wide bead of caulking would look right.
What can you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   A: The simplest and neatest method is to scribe the edge of the
panels so they form a snug fit against the rough edges of the
brick. An ordinary pencil compass is used as shown here so that the
pencil moves along the face of the panel while the metal point is
dragged along to follow the contour of the brick. Before doing this
tack the panel temporarily in place so it is plumb and cannot move
while you are scribing. After scribing use a jig saw or scroll saw
with a narrow blade to trim the edge of the panel along the profile
line drawn on the plywood. This will insure a snug fit when the
panel is installed next to, and butting against, the brick.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After an unexpected cold spell the water pipe leading to my
laundry room froze. After about 36 hours the pipe thawed with no
damage, but I've been told that it is best to thaw the pipe out
promptly _ especially since we were unable to use the washing
machine for two days. If this happens again and I don't want to
wait for the pipe to thaw by itself what can I do to safely thaw
the pipe in a hurry, and how can I prevent this happening next
winter?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you can get at the pipe that supplies water to this spigot
you can thaw it safely by applying mild heat from a heat lamp,
portable hair dryer, or a heat ``gun'' set on low heat. First make
sure the faucet is open, then start applying the heat right next to
the faucet and work away from it gradually. Keep working back to
the faucet so that as the ice melts the water will run out. To
prevent this happening in the future wrap the pipe with electric
heating tape if you can get at it. Otherwise you will have to
install a shut-off valve on that water line somewhere inside the
heated part of the house or basement so you can shut off the water
supply to that faucet when a freeze is expected (remember to open
faucet after you shut off water supply to drain any water in the
pipe).
</P>
<P>
   Q: My house has light brown aluminum siding on the outside and
after 25 years this looks dull and faded looking. I've considered
painting, or completely replacing the siding with new plastic
siding which would be a lot more expensive. Is painting practical?
</P>
<P>
   A: Painting is practical over old aluminum siding. First wash
off all dirt and powdery chalkiness, then paint with two coats of a
good quality latex house paint _ preferably one that says on the
label it is recommended for use on aluminum siding. Most require no
separate primer, but check the label for specific recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a flagstone patio that was laid on top of a poured
concrete slab. Some of the flagstones have come loose and I've been
told that the flagstones can be cemented back with a special
masonry adhesive without need for chiseling out the old concrete.
Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes _ as long as the concrete under the flagstones is still
sound. You can use one of the mastic adhesives that have been
around for some time, but probably the strongest adhesive you can
use is a two-part epoxy cement. Various brands are sold in most
home centers, as well as in hardware stores, marine supply stores
and from masonry supply dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New Yor, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING A PENCIL COMPASS FOR SCRIBING''
goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: A pencil compass can be used to scribe the outlines of
the brick onto the wood panel so that it can be trimmed for a snug
fit to the side of the brick fireplace and chimney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
