<SLUG> BC-CIR-BASEBALL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACKING THE MAJORS, OR A LEAGUE OF YOUR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: in parenthetical equations, replace the word `plus' with
the typographical symbol) 
 (bl)  
 By JIM LUTTRELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each winter I feel the warmth of Florida and Arizona radiating
from every newsstand as dozens of annual baseball preview issues
trumpet the arrival of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   But it has become evident that the canned heat is fueled by
stale news and by analyses that are often amateurish.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a nationally published annual baseball magazine
showed David Wells in pinstripes on its cover with a headline that
said he would be leading the Yankees in search of a second
consecutive World Series title. Retailers will be displaying this
magazine until July, when Wells might very well be with yet another
team. And I wouldn't be surprised if the magazine's Toronto edition
featured Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Like any fantasy-baseball team owner or rotisserie league player
or anyone who plays any of the myriad games that depend on the
stats of major leaguers, I'm looking for the latest news and
insider information that can tell me which players will be primed
for a breakout season and which phenom (pronounced FEE-nom) I can
build my team with.
</P>
<P>
   As a fan of the game _ from the smell of newly cut grass to the
physics of what makes a four-seam fastball rise (yeah, yeah, I know
scientists say it can't rise) _ I'm looking for more than the
fluffy feature articles and the hometown boosterism that are aimed
to excite fans in every city where a magazine appeared.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wide Web has supplied a vast assortment of baseball
information, but seam-heads should be wary. You can't just holler,
yahoo and ride your search engine directly to a field of dreams.
There are thousands of baseball sites on the Web, including those
that just want to sell you baseball cards and memorabilia, sites
that try to entice you into playing fantasy games for cash prizes
and others that promise to process your rotisserie league stats for
fees ranging from $20 to $50 or more per team. (There are perfectly
reputable companies who will manage your league stats free.)
</P>
<P>
   And because starting a Web site is relatively cheap and the
booming popularity of fantasy sports leagues has created a cottage
industry, there is often the possibility that the ``expert'' who is
telling you about the 35-year-old right-hander who has just learned
to throw a change-up might know less than you know.
</P>
<P>
   The more serious sites tend to follow in the tradition of Bill
James, who popularized baseball research and analysis in his annual
Baseball Abstract, and by the Society for American Baseball
Research, a group of more than 6,700 members dedicated to fostering
the study of baseball and disseminating baseball research. (The
word sabermetrics, meaning baseball research, is derived from the
society's acronym, SABR.) Its site (www.sabr.org) contains some of
statistical research, although much of its work is not available to
the public. The site is a good place to visit if you want to have
your own baseball research or ideas published.
</P>
<P>
   Sabermetrics, James wrote in his Baseball Abstract, is about the
search for objective answers about baseball, such as, ``Which
player on the Red Sox contributed most to the team's offense?'' or,
``How many home runs will Ken Griffey hit next year?''
</P>
<P>
   So you must decide whether you want simply the answers to
questions like these or if you want to know exactly how those
answers were derived. If you choose the second path, pocket
protectors are optional.
</P>
<P>
   JIM FURTADO'S BASEBALL STUFF
</P>
<P>
   www.baseballstuff.com
</P>
<P>
   The site's master invites you to pour a cup of coffee and look
around. Decaf is fine, but sip it slowly because there's a lot to
see.
</P>
<P>
   The meatiest page is the Baseball Think Factory. While Furtado
promises information for both fantasy-game players and
sabermetricians, most of the articles were heavy on the math. Not
all of them required advanced degrees, but several left me
remembering why I had struggled through calculus.
</P>
<P>
   The page is dominated by text and virtually devoid of graphics.
One enjoyable feature uses a formula for something called Bases per
Plate Appearance (Total bases plus walks plus hit by pitch plus
stolen bases - caught stealing - grounded into double play) divided
by (at-bats plus walks plus hit by pitch plus sacrifice flies) to
compare how Mark McGwire's 70-home-run season stacks up against the
best of all time. McGwire's BPA of .799 was the best ever in the
National League but third overall, behind a couple of Ruthian
seasons: .863 in 1921 and .862 in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature, Introducing XR, discusses a process to predict
runs scored using an extrapolated runs formula. Like most of the
complex features, this one finds its origins in previous
statistical work, and some background information is available. But
for the newcomer, learning that Estimated Runs Produced equals (2 x
(TB plus BB plus HP) plus H plus SB - (.605 x (AB plus CS plus GIDP
- H))) x .16 can be daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Furtado plays Strat-O-Matic Baseball, originally a board game
using dice and individual player cards and now available as a
computer game. He gives his opinions of the best hitters' cards for
the 1998 version of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The site's Newsstand page supplied quick links to many baseball
publications, including magazines, multimedia and newspapers in
each major league city.
</P>
<P>
   I had high expectations for the Ask the Baseball Scholars Forum
page, but while few of the questions were trivial, too few were
actually answered and only a couple stimulated any debate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stathead Consulting's Baseball Engineering Library
</P>
<P>
   www.stathead.com
</P>
<P>
   What is it with Red Sox fans? Jim Furtado of Baseball Stuff is
an acknowledged Red Sox fan, and Keith Woolner, who is the Chief
Stathead of Stathead.com, manages the team's mailing list, among
other duties. Tom Fontaine and Nate Calvin, two other senior
statheads, also root for the Fenway crowd. I suppose that given
another Red Sox statistic _ the team hasn't won a World Series
championship since 1918 _ their fans must look elsewhere to enjoy
the game.
</P>
<P>
   When not breaking into cold sweats at the thought of Bill
Buckner, the statheads focus on performance forecasting and
economics as they relate to actual baseball decisions. Their
seemingly most important statistic is Value Over Replacement Player
(VORP). That is not exactly one of the triple crown categories, but
the statheads will have you believe it is a key economic factor to
major league teams.
</P>
<P>
   What does VORP mean? Roughly, it is the expected level of
performance a team can obtain if it replaces a starting player at
minimal dollar cost. It puts great weight on playing time and
favors a consistently average player over a short-term flash.
</P>
<P>
   Putting faith in VORP means believing Albert Belle (100.2 VORP)
was more valuable than Mark McGwire (94.7) in 1998, and that Tom
Glavine (76.0), the National League Cy Young Award winner, is
baseball's fifth-ranking pitcher, behind Greg Maddux, Kevin Brown,
Roger Clemens and Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   There are other lists, including one that shows how each ball
park influences players' hitting or pitching. For example, you can
see how playing in a shooting gallery like Coors Field benefits
Colorado's Larry Walker, while the cavernous Astrodome slows down
Houston's Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   The Baseball Engineering Library has a thorough index that makes
it easy to find desired topics. Among the articles on offense,
there are a couple that claim there is no such thing as a clutch
hitter. One study, about 10 years ago, showed that hitters with
reputations as clutch performers actually had only one more hit a
year in late-inning situations or with runners in scoring position
than the average player.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the articles venture into sabermetrics, but an easily
accessible glossary helps the lay person negotiate the mathematical
maze.
</P>
<P>
   A disappointment: There were only two articles listed under Just
for Fun, which were supposed to poke fun at analysts' obsession
with numbers, and one of them could not be found. But luckily, the
archives contained columnist Mike Royko's prediction that no team
with three or more former Cubs players could win a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs. Where would Red Sox fans be without them?
</P>
<P>
   Baseball Database98 Version 5.0
</P>
<P>
   (Shareware, downloadable at www.baseballdatabase.com: $35,
Windows 95)
</P>
<P>
   Any sports tavern worth its lager has a Baseball Encyclopedia
behind the bar to settle disputes. And while the bars may never
replace that eight-pound tome with a laptop, the Baseball Database
could probably settle a few arguments and maybe start a few more.
</P>
<P>
   The database contains career and season-by-season statistics for
nearly 15,000 players, dating back to 1876. There is information on
any team from any season and extensive data on every ball park that
a big-league team has ever called home.
</P>
<P>
   One of the handiest features allows a user to instantly
determine how many times a player finished in the top five in an
offensive or pitching category. It's a great tool when comparing
Greg Maddux to Sandy Koufax or Joe DiMaggio to Willie Mays.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Mays finished in the top five in batting average
seven times, and DiMaggio only four. And Mays was in the top five
in runs 11 times, DiMaggio only six. There were no stats covering
grace or fewest times diving for a fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   Another click enables you to search by category; for example,
which ball parks have the deepest center fields (Coors Field at 415
feet is the deepest, Fenway Park at 390 the shallowest); or which
American League teams had the best earned run average in say, 1982?
(Detroit led the league with a 3.80 ERA but finished fourth, 12
games behind Milwaukee, which slugged 216 homers.)
</P>
<P>
   Using this function for the 1990 season, I was left wondering
how the statistically dominant Mets lost to the Pirates. I guess
there's no statistic for heart.
</P>
<P>
   However, I was disappointed, to not find any post-season
statistics beyond the number of championships for each team.
</P>
<P>
   The program is large (over 14 MB), so make sure you have got
enough spare memory. An attempt to download it ran into some
trouble, but technical support is available.
</P>
<P>
   There are no bells or whistles here. The Baseball Database is
just one spreadsheet after another, easily navigated with a mouse.
But as the author points out, that's what makes it perfect for the
office: a casual glance at your screen gives the impression that
you're hard at work.
</P>
<P>
   Stats Fantasy Advantage
</P>
<P>
   www.stats.com $19.95 for the season; America Online, keyword:
statsbb
</P>
<P>
   Want to know how Mike Piazza hit last season with two strikes?
Stats Fantasy Advantage has the answer (.248). Why was the Yankees'
Orlando Hernandez so tough? Leadoff batters hit .250 against El
Duque, but with runners in scoring position, that average dropped
to .218, and with two out and runners in scoring position, it fell
to .148.
</P>
<P>
   The Stats Fantasy Advantage is aimed at fantasy players, but it
is really a statistical smorgasbord with a sabermetric flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The site runs three columns that are updated at different times
during the week. Two of the three columns during the week of March
22 centered on the injury to the Cubs' second-year pitcher Kerry
Wood. One quoted an article that Bill James wrote for the Stats
e-mail network shortly after Wood's 20-strikeout performance last
season. In it, James discussed the effect that stress could have on
an immature arm, and he predicted that Wood would not win 100
games. The second article used the Wood injury to launch a
discussion of the importance of pitch counts.
</P>
<P>
   Through the Web site, subscribers will also receive At The Park
Scoreboards, which will cover each regular-season game, pitch by
pitch, and will include situational statistics, like
batter-vs.-pitcher matchups. A less-detailed version, without the
situational stats, is available to AOL members.
</P>
<P>
   The Player Portfolio feature allows subscribers to track
individual players over the course of the season. However, an
attempt to register a team required technical help. While the
feature is certainly helpful to follow fantasy players in spring
training, once the season starts, it will duplicate what most
online statistical services supply.
</P>
<P>
   If you depend on this site for a real fantasy advantage, though,
be careful. Under recent injuries listed for March 22, we were told
there were no injuries in the previous two weeks. But Boston's
Nomar Garciaparra, Atlanta's Kerry Ligtenberg and Cincinnati's Pete
Harnisch as well as Wood had all been hurt in the previous few
days. If they were omitted because they had not yet been placed on
the official disabled list, this should have been made clearer.
</P>
<P>
   There are also some inconsistencies. For example, under
Projections, which makes predictions for the 1999 season, the
Angels' Justin Baughman was expected to get 164 at-bats. But under
News and Notes, we read that Baughman might face a second surgery
for a broken left leg and could miss the season.
</P>
<P>
   What you end up with is a contradiction: a great site for the
casual fan, but one that has deficiencies that even the casual fan
would notice.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL SITES ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   After the last pitch has been thrown, the Web springs into
action. Here's a selection of baseball-related sites offering game
reports and current information:
</P>
<P>
   JOHN SKILTON'S BASEBALL LINKS: www.baseball-links.com
</P>
<P>
   The most complete list of baseball sites, indexed by subject.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN.COM: espn.go.com/mlb/index.html Offers up-to-the minute
scores and a healthy amount of statistics. One feature allows you
to see how individual hitters do against certain pitchers.and in
particular ballparks. Transactions, however, are not always up to
date.
</P>
<P>
   ROTONEWS: www.rotonews.com A valuable bookmark for any fantasy
player, offering news and player updates. The site will also
process your league's stats free.
</P>
<P>
   SANDLOT SHRINK: www.sandlotshrink.com This subscription service
also has a lot of free information gathered by longtime baseball
writers.
</P>
<P>
   SEAN LAHMAN'S BASEBALL ARCHIVE: www.baseball1.com This diverse
site includes a free downloadable database, and the history section
is a treat.
</P>
<P>
   THE IOWA FARM REPORT: www.backatcha.com/IFR You can find
profiles of every major league team's farm system here, plus lists
of short- and long-term prospects.
</P>
</TEXT>
