<SLUG> BC-PREHISTORIC-WOMAN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S BONES ARE NOW ESTIMATED TO BE 13,000 YEARS OLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By MELINDA BURNS   
 Santa Barbara News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ A prehistoric woman whose bones were dug
up on Santa Rosa Island in 1959 has turned out to be one of the
oldest-known humans in western North America, according to a new
report from the Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Based on new advances in bone chemistry and radiocarbon dating
technology, the woman's bones have been determined to be 13,000
years old, said anthropology curator John Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The new date makes the Arlington Springs Woman, as she is
called, a contemporary of the Stone Age people who hunted Columbian
mammoths on the Great Plains.
</P>
<P>
   It also places her at the end of the Ice Age and within striking
distance of the pygmy mammoths _ elephant-like animals the size of
cows that roamed the Channel Islands 15,000 years ago. The islands
in the Channel Islands National Park off the Santa Barbara coast
are the only islands in the world where the remains of pygmy
mammoths have been found.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arlington Springs site is a tantalizing glimpse of the
people who were here,'' Johnson said. ``Were those people witnesses
to the last of the pygmy mammoths?''
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington Springs Woman originally was identified as a man
when two of her thigh bones were discovered four decades ago,
sticking out of a canyon wall on the northern side of Santa Rosa
Island. Subsequent dating fixed the age of the remains at 11,600
years, and it is this age that now has been pushed back by more
modern dating methods, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington Springs Woman lived on Santa Rosae, the giant land
mass that once lay offshore of what is now Santa Barbara. Santa
Rosae was largely submerged during the melt-off at the end of the
Ice Age. Today, only its mountaintops are visible: They form the
islands of Anacapa, Santa Cruz, Santa Rosa and San Miguel.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there may be many more skeletons like the Arlington
Springs Woman on the islands, but they are under water.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery that the woman was older than previously thought
is important, Johnson said, because scientists still are debating
how the first humans entered North America. For some time, it had
been hypothesized that they came through a corridor left by
retreating ice sheets in Canada. More recently, scientists have
hypothesized that people also came down the coast in ice-free
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The find on Santa Rosa Island indicates there were people on
the coast when the sea level was 300 feet lower,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Barbara News-Press in Santa Barbara, Calif., is part
of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
