<HEADER>
A1161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYLITE-NYT &LR;      03-31 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYLITE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 March 31, 1999  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR; 
 &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Members of the military that search for downed pilots are called
``pararescuers,'' it's reported. Not, we bet, by them.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Balk, our spring training correspondent, says things
balance out. As some teams head north soon, their odds of winning a
pennant will head south.
</P>
<P>
   The Sweet Sixteen, Elite Eight and Final Four are finally down
to the Obnoxious One _ the office pool winner.
</P>
<P>
   That American pilot rescued after ejecting from his plane near
Belgrade was on the ground seven-plus hours, it's reported. If he'd
had a Yugo as a get-away car, he could have traveled several miles
in that time.
</P>
<P>
   What does NATO stand for these days? Now Against Tito's Oddment?
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have learned the hard way,'' says Mr. Clinton,
``that our home is not that far from Europe.'' Especially Americans
with vacation homes in Morocco, just across the Strait of Gibraltar
from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   For a time this week, 4,000 refugees an hour arrived at the
Kosovo-Albanian border. It's looking as if Slobodan Milosevic isn't
going to win a Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   It looks as if BP Amoco may buy Atlantic Richfield. To keep up
with all these transactions you have to get up pretty oily.
</P>
<P>
   Dolly the cloned sheep in Scotland is about to give birth to her
second lamb, reports say. Wool, wool.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay's president, Raul Cubas, has resigned. And wouldn't it
be nice if Cuba's president were, instead, Raul Paraguays?
</P>
<P>
   There are early signs in Asia of economic recovery. But so far
no one is suggesting the name be changed to Singarich.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll shows Americans support NATO's air strikes by a 2-1
margin. Someone must have asked the three Americans who understand
what's going on there.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls showed 57 percent of Americans couldn't name Kosovo
as the Serbian province under fire. Bet more than that can name the
Oscar winner for best special effects in a foreign film.
</P>
<P>
   People who have read history know that in our Civil War air
strikes meant little more than ballast thrown down at soldiers from
balloons.
</P>
<P>
   After days of work on NATO air strikes, Mr. Clinton broke away
the other day to play golf. Or, as the game is known in his
foursome, ground strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Yeltsin says he'll do all he can ``to put an end to
military actions in Yugoslavia.'' If he can get his nurse call
button to work.
</P>
<P>
   An independent military analyst in Washington says the Serb
military isn't very good and is ``not capable of offensive
operations.'' Wrong. Ethnic cleansing is as offensive as you can
get.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO air campaign has entered what's called its second
phase. Couldn't we get right on to phase three so Serbia can't say
NATO is two-phased?
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Melissa'' and ``Papa'' computer viruses have attacked
many computers. Makes us glad our PC at home is so old it's got the
Y1K bug.
</P>
<P>
   After the NCAA men's basketball championship game, Aunt Ilse
from Oelwein sent this e-mail: ``UConn believe it's the Huskies!''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed anti-climactic when the Dow finally closed above
10,000. But we confess it might have helped to own, say, 10,000
shares of America OnLine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DAVID LETTERMAN LATE SHOW TOP TEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jobs in the New Millenium &LR;
</P>
<P>
   10. Assistant Fight Fixer, Don King Corp.
</P>
<P>
   9. Medical Marijuana Product Quality Tester
</P>
<P>
   8. Sign Remover, Failed Starbucks Locations
</P>
<P>
   7. NBA token white guy
</P>
<P>
   6. NHL token black guy
</P>
<P>
   5. Guy who puts ``Intel Inside'' stickers on every computer
</P>
<P>
   4. Consultant, Hillary Clinton New Husband Search
</P>
<P>
   3. Guy in charge of gathering sharp sticks after Y2K knocks us
back to Stone Age
</P>
<P>
   2. Producer of ``Where Are They Now?'' specials on David
Letterman and Paul Shaffer
</P>
<P>
   1. Human toy for Bill Gates
</P>
</TEXT>
