<HEADLINE>
HAMBURGER TOPPINGS A BLAST FROM THE PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A reader has been told that several years ago the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram ran recipes for hamburger toppings served at two old
Cowtown chains. The first is from Rockyfeller hamburgers, the
second from the old Griddle System's burgers.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKY SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 2 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup salad dressing
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons prepared mustard
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients. Store leftover sauce in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 28 calories, 2 grams fat, 3
grams carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 174 milligrams
sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   GRIDDLE SYSTEM SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup dill-pickle relish
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients. Store leftovers in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 11 calories, trace fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 196 milligrams
sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned pie: Some years back, a reader requested the
recipe for the apple pie served at Jerry's Drive-In during the late
'60s.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry's closed in the 1970s after 35 years of serving customers.
Jerry's wife, Lucile, baked the pies, and she shared the recipe
with us.
</P>
<P>
   Lucile made 24 pies every morning for Jerry's Drive-In. I keep
the staples for this pie in my pantry at all times, and it's always
a last-minute hit.
</P>
<P>
   JERRY'S DRIVE-IN'S FRENCH APPLE PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   2 unbaked pie crusts
</P>
<P>
   18- to 20-ounce can apples packed in water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   4 or 5 thin pats of butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 1/3 to 1/2 cup powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   8 pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   Place one pie shell in 9-inch pie plate. Pour apples and their
juice into the shell. Sprinkle with the lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, flour and cinnamon and distribute evenly over
apples. Place butter pats randomly over apple filling. Top with
second pie crust. Bake in 350-degree oven for about 45 minutes, or
until pie is golden.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 or 10 minutes before pie is done, melt 1 tablespoon
butter. Off the heat, whisk in vanilla and heavy cream and sift in
the powdered sugar until mixture reaches thickness of cream gravy.
As soon as pie is removed from oven, slather with the sugar icing.
Mark off 8 servings with the pecan halves.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 431 calories, 21 grams fat, 58
grams carbohydrates, 12 milligrams cholesterol, 270 milligrams
sodium, 44 percent of calories from fat. Request:
</P>
<P>
   A reader is looking for a recipe for cookies made with
snack-size Snickers covered with cookie dough and on a Popsicle
stick.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
