<HEADLINE>
BANNED BELGRADE STATION TURNS TO INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   SPECIAL iMAC SOFTWARE  
 WORLDWIDE MOBIL PHONING  
 DIFFERENT KIND OF ROAD RAGE  
 YOUR COMPUTER IS CALLING  
 COMPUTER SHARING  
(mk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As part of a clampdown on news organizations last week, Yugoslav
police raided the offices of Radio B92, the single independent
radio station in Belgrade, the capital city, and pulled the plug on
its transmitter. Unfortunately for police, they had no way to pull
the plug on the Internet, where the radio station continues to put
out its reports.
</P>
<P>
   On March 24, police told the station that its broadcasts were
violating transmission laws and arrested the station's editor in
chief, Veran Matic. He was released eight hours later. According to
Ari Schwartz, policy analyst for the Center for Democracy and
Technology in Washington, Matic then began uploading reports onto
the Internet, where they can be accessed on a Web site,
www.opennet.org. (The station also maintains a Web site at
www.helpb92.-xs4all.nl.) The BBC downloaded the content and
broadcast it back into the Balkans by radio.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Democracy and Technology, B92
broadcasts music and news that is not officially sanctioned. In
recent years, the station has been shut down several times by
Yugoslav police.
</P>
<P>
   Until its broadcasts were banned, most listeners in the United
States faced a language barrier _ except for a five-minute English
program every morning, B92 broadcasts in Serbo-Croatian. But since
the ban, the Opennet Web site carries an English translation of its
news content, while the Helpb92 site contains some material in
English.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said the experience of B92 shows that governments
cannot easily stop the flow of information in the Internet age.
``In today's day and age, it is much more difficult to censor,'' he
said. ``Governments have to learn new ways of openness.''
</P>
<P>
   Color-Coordinated Software to Go With Your iMac
</P>
<P>
   With hardware vendors scrambling to create stylish peripherals
to complement Apple Computer's trendy translucent iMac, it was
probably only a matter of time before software manufacturers
followed suit. Grolier Interactive Inc. has just created a special
edition of its popular multimedia encyclopedia CD-ROM that is
specifically tailored for iMac users.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Grolier Multimedia Encyclopedia Deluxe 2-CD iMac
Edition not only offers users a program interface that nicely
matches the original iMac's Bondi Blue case color, but also has
been enhanced to take advantage of the machine's advanced video and
stereo capabilities. The two-disk set contains 36,000 articles,
15,000 pictures and graphics, and 1,200 maps, plus video and
digitally remastered sound clips. An additional 22,000 articles are
available through online access to two more encyclopedias.
</P>
<P>
   The program will work on iMacs or Power Macs running Mac OS 8
(or higher), with at least a 603/200 MHz processor. The program
sells for $59.95, and the company is offering a $20 mail-in rebate
until Aug. 31. And don't worry if you have one of the
second-generation machines. The program interface offers other
color schemes that won't clash with your lime or strawberry iMac.
</P>
<P>
   _ J.D. BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   Spanning the Continents
</P>
<P>
   Paving the way for worldwide wireless phone use (and possibly
some whopping roaming charges), Motorola is introducing a new
mobile telephone that can be used in the United States, Europe, the
Middle East and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The phone will be able to receive radio signals from the
predominant digital frequencies in Europe, Asia and the Middle East
(900 and 1,800 megahertz) and in the United States (1,900
megahertz). The phone will be available in the second quarter of
this year. The price has not yet been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, mobile phone users have not been able to use the same
phone across continents, due to differing frequency standards. Yet
Motorola's development is still just the beginning; it still does
not receive the 800 megahertz frequency, which is a predominantly
analog (as opposed to digital) frequency used by 85 percent of
mobile phone users in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds confusing, that's because it is confusing, points
out Herschel Schosteck, a wireless market analyst from Wheaton, Md.
However, Schosteck said that the significance of the Motorola
announcement is that it paves the way for telephones to work across
numerous standards, technologies and radio frequencies _ and hence
to make the situation far less confusing to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, he said, wireless phones will work in many places
around the globe. ``For the group of people who are international
travelers, this is going to be very useful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An Automotive CD Player That Uses Your Car Radio
</P>
<P>
   The upside of the newest in-car CD player from Emerson is that
it requires no installation. The downside is that there is a slim
chance the CD player will play music in nearby cars, potentially
leading to some ugly music-related road rage.
</P>
<P>
   The Emerson Research Personal CD Player attaches to speakers not
with wires but by radio waves. It sends a signal to the car
antenna, which in turns directs the signal to an unused frequency
on the car's radio dial; the signal then is played through the
car's speakers as if it were coming from a radio station.
</P>
<P>
   The only catch is that it is possible the signal could be picked
up by neighboring cars. It is unlikely, but possible, that use of
the device could lead to some confrontations by the side of the
road between fans of classical music, rap and country and western.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Wake-Up Calls at Home, Complete With Advertising
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Internet, deep sleepers can get the same wake-up
service they enjoy at hotels for free at home. But they'll have to
put up with the dulcet tones of early morning marketing.
</P>
<P>
   A new web site, www.mrwakeup.com, allows people to program in
their phone numbers so they can be called back at a specified date
and time. A computer then places the call, and the recipient is
greeted with a synthesized computer voice intoning a reminder that
it is time to rise.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to wake-up calls, the service can be programmed to
provide short news blurbs, weather updates, horoscopes and 125-word
reminders the recipient types in and that are read by a
text-to-voice synthesizer.
</P>
<P>
   The service is free, with a catch. Each call begins with a
message from the call's sponsor; among the sponsors during the
two-month old consumer test are Amazon.com and Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Yeh, president of iPing Inc., the New York company
behind the site, said he is planning to offer different voice types
for the call. ``Soon you'll have a variety of voices, including
female, one like a comedian, and someone who sounds crazy, like
nuts,'' Yeh said.
</P>
<P>
   Turning a Single Computer Into an At-Home Network
</P>
<P>
   For homes where family members or roommates constantly fight
over use of the computer, a California company offers an answer
short of group therapy: a buddy system that shares hard drives.
Specifically, the technology, which goes for $149 from Vega Systems
in Emeryville, Calif., allows people to use a single computer while
working on different monitors, using separate keyboards and mice.
</P>
<P>
   The system works through a VGA card inserted into a slot inside
the computer. The card is a attached to a cable that runs to a
connector box into which the second mouse, keyboard and monitor can
be hooked.
</P>
<P>
   The technology uses a feature in Windows '98 and '95 that allows
users to work concurrently on two separate applications, such as
word processing and a spreadsheet, but in different windows. The
``buddy system'' essentially moves one of those windows to the
second monitor.
</P>
</TEXT>
