<HEADER>
A1207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUES-THEATER-REVIEW-     03-31 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUES-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT AIN'T NOTHIN' BUT THE BLUES': ROOF-RAISING THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Looking for a sure cure for the blues?
</P>
<P>
   Just head for the New Victory Theater in the new Times Square
and latch on to a ticket for ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, that title bears some parsing, because this rich,
evocative, rousing show, with some 50 musical numbers ranging from
African chants and spirituals to Delta and Chicago blues, with
plenty of stops along the dusty roads, river banks, broken country
hearts and juke joints in between, is more than a musical feast.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its cornucopia of splendidly interpreted song, ``It
Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' through April 11, is a potent blend
of visual eloquence and historical sweep that engages the eye and
touches the heart while its songs soothe the ear, occasionally work
mischief on the funny bone and always raise the spirits.
</P>
<P>
   As the splendid cast assembled by the much-praised Crossroads
Theater Company of New Brunswick, N.J., applies its individual and
collective vocal, musical and actorly talents to songs like ``I've
Been Living With the Blues,'' ``Blues Man,'' ``My Man Rocks Me''
and ``St. Louis Blues,'' photographs projected onto screens behind
the performers brim with history.
</P>
<P>
   Here are sketches of slave auctions and pictures of thirsty
women working the fields with their little children nearby, a black
man dangling from a lyncher's noose, rural poverty, a riverside
baptism, country churches, the great blues man Robert Johnson, and
changing fashions in clothes and entertainment, as well as the
economic, social and cultural upheaval surrounding the great black
migration from the South to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Presented in association with the San Diego Repertory Theater
and the Alabama Shakespeare Festival, ``It Ain't Nothin' but the
Blues'' is based on an idea by Ron Taylor, who wrote it with Randal
Myler, its director, and Lita Gaithers, Charles Bevel and Dan
Wheetman.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, Bevel and Wheetman, with Gretha Boston, Carter Calvert,
Eloise Laws and Gregory Porter, constitute the powerhouse lineup of
singers who step up, step out and put over one number after
another. Depending on the song, they can be heartbreakers,
heartbroken, sexpots or absolute rapscallions. And after
intermission, when they trade their simple attire, rustic airs and
simple instruments for shapely gowns and stylish suits, each seems
good-naturedly determined to outdo another, as they make their way
with the backing of an enhanced band through pieces like ``I'm Your
Hoochie-Coochie Man,'' the sly, slinky, humorous ``Crawlin' King
Snake,'' ``Walkin' After Midnight,'' the bitter ``Strange Fruit''
and ``Let the Good Times Roll.''
</P>
<P>
   By this time the band is making the floor vibrate, and the cast
and audience are raising the roof.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IT AIN'T NOTHIN' BUT THE BLUES'
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Bevel, Lita Gaithers, Randal Myler, Ron Taylor and
Dan Wheetman, based on an original idea by Taylor; directed by
Myler; musical direction by Wheetman; musical staging by Donald
McKayle; vocal direction by Ms. Gaithers; sets by Robin Sanford
Roberts; lighting by Don Darnutzer; costumes by Dione H. Lebhar;
sound by Edward Cosla; production stage manager, Linda Harris;
producing coordinator, Jeff Rowlings; dramaturgue, Lenora Inez
Brown; associate producer, Taylor; co-founder, artistic director
and chief executive, Ricardo Kahn; managing director, Keryl McCord.
The New 42nd Street Inc. presents the Crossroads Theater Company in
association with San Diego Repertory Theater and Alabama
Shakespeare Festival. At the New Victory Theater, 209 W. 42d St.,
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Mississippi Charles Bevel, Gretha Boston, Carter Calvert,
Eloise Laws, Gregory Porter, Ron Taylor and Dan Wheetman.
</P>
</TEXT>
