<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1211 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GOVERNMENT-EMAIL-     03-31 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GOVERNMENT-EMAIL-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND CLOSED E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Wash., Colo., Fla.)  (See also CIR-GOVERNMENT-FOIA) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a politician's nightmare: a request from a newspaper
reporter to read all the e-mail the public official has received in
the past four months.
</P>
<P>
   In Spokane, Wash., that request from a Spokesman-Review reporter
several months ago yielded e-mail messages from two Spokane County
commissioners discussing public business like employee pay raises,
the number of workers to hire and public leases. Since there are
only three commissioners, two constitute a quorum, so such
communications come close to violating laws on open public
meetings, according to experts on ``sunshine laws,'' which require
officials to conduct public business in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a problem that the Legislature has never recognized,''
said Chip Holcomb, a senior counsel at the state attorney general's
office.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail is supplanting to a large extent face-to-face
communications among all sorts of people _ co-workers, relatives,
high-school classmates. Yet e-mail communications about public
business raise new questions: if officials discuss public issues by
e-mail or even, in some cases, make decisions that way, have they
deprived citizens of the right to watch the making of policy? How
do those e-mail exchanges differ from phone calls or voice-mail
messages or, for that matter, letters carried through rain and
sleet and snow? And will the unseen back-scratching of politics be
different if it takes place via e-mail, instead of, for example,
over the phone? Finally, are e-mail messages among public officials
public documents that need to be preserved, or can they be deleted?
</P>
<P>
   E-mail messages can bump into the public's ``right to know'' in
two ways. While state open-meetings laws vary and allow exceptions,
like closed meetings to discuss personnel issues, members of the
public are supposed to be notified about governmental meetings and
invited to attend. The federal government also has a sunshine law.
If a meeting takes place via e-mail, of course, that can be seen as
circumventing a sunshine law.
</P>
<P>
   The public also has a right to see public documents, and e-mail
between public officials is increasingly being put in that
category. E-mail was officially included as a public record under
federal rules in 1996, and local jurisdictions are beginning to
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   After the Spokane commission had to hand over its e-mail, one
thing changed for certain, said a county commissioner, John
Roskelley. ``I found it changed the way we do business here,'' he
said. ``We eliminate all e-mails, delete them instantly from our
mailbox, which in one respect cleans up our hard drive, but on the
other side of the coin, we do not have a history of what goes on. I
just chose to eliminate them rather than have someone else go
through my e-mails.'' The county's server keeps e-mail messages for
just a week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Roskelley's reaction is perhaps understandable, the
fast-changing body of case law on electronic records seems to
indicate that deleting e-mail messages concerning public policy is
a questionable practice and may not even work, as deleted messages
may be retrieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the ingredients in the law, when it comes to the
public's rights, involves the ability to observe the performance of
public officials,'' said Robert J. Freeman, executive director of
the New York State Committee on Open government. ``The point is, we
can't simply obliterate the record because we're finished reading
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, other people might be interested in the making of
public policy via e-mail or records of such activity. In April
1996, a city councilwoman in Phoenix sent an urgent e-mail message
to all the other council members, advocating the sale of the
Phoenix Art Museum to private owners. The discussion of the
proposal occurred via computer, according to e-mail messages
obtained by The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also quoted e-mail messages between council
members calculating how many votes they needed to pass the
financing for neighborhood improvement projects and crime fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it loses 5-4, but I think that it makes some sense
to force a vote,'' one councilman wrote, according to accounts in
the newspaper; another replied, ``Who is the fourth, and who can we
work on to become the 5th?'' At the time, the two councilmen
involved in the discussion made up two-thirds of the Housing and
Neighborhoods subcommittee. (A pending bill in the Arizona Senate
would impose a $500 penalty on anyone using e-mail to get around
the open meetings law.)
</P>
<P>
   Ari Schwartz, a policy analyst with the Center for Democracy and
Technology, based in Washington, said, ``In a lot of cases, it is
the public that gets injured when meeting laws have been worked
around or if people are trying to cover things up.''
</P>
<P>
   When a new technology comes along, politicians have often been
quick to use it to their advantage, prompting watchdogs to try to
determine how to keep the officials from exploiting it. For each
innovation _ telephones, voice mail, conference calls, faxes, chat
rooms, instant messaging and video conferencing, as well as e-mail
_ there have been concerns that the technology could be used to
conduct the public's business outside of public view.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine laws stem from the first open meetings law, which was
passed in Pennsylvania in the 1880s, said Tim Delaney, the chief
deputy attorney general of Arizona. In the aftermath of the
Watergate break-in in the 1970s, ``all the public attention was
focused on trying to get government to behave,'' he said. Both
meetings and records became more accessible. During the Iran-contra
scandal in the 1980s, e-mail recovered between Lt. Col. Oliver L.
North and Adm. John M. Poindexter, then the national security
adviser, yielded information important to the case.
</P>
<P>
   According to most sunshine laws, a majority of a panel is not
allowed to meet to discuss policy unless the public is notified. In
Scottsdale, Ariz., where the school board has been found by the
attorney general to have committed more than 40 violations of open
meetings laws, one board member has complained to the state
attorney general's office about an e-mail message the board
president wrote that summarized the board's closed-session
discussions about the superintendent's midyear review, according to
The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   That board member, Kristy Ryan, has also criticized the
president's request for comment by phone or e-mail on a draft of
the job review for the superintendent, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Delaney, of the attorney general's office, said the Scottsdale
board's ethics monitor had been asked to review the e-mail issue to
see if the open meetings law had been violated. ``We're not quite
sure if there was a violation,'' said Delaney, who is chairman of
the state's Open Meeting Law Enforcement Team. (It is called Omlet
_ ``we break a few eggs,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of that panel, Delaney trains public officials about
the use of e-mail. ``People say it's like a conference call, and I
say that's also no good, and the same with faxes,'' he said. ``I
don't care if you're doing it by pony express, if all of you are
reaching consensus where the public can't see it, it's wrong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is not only e-mail that raises open-meetings questions. In
1995, for example, a school board president in Jefferson County,
Colo., left a voice-mail message for other school board members
about his planned testimony against a state school-governance bill.
Two other board members accused him of violating the state
open-meetings law. They were supported by Troy Eid, executive
director of the Institute for Information, Law and Policy at the
Center for the New West, who wrote an op-ed article in 1995 in The
Rocky Mountain News that said: ``The Jeffco controversy shows how
information technologies can be abused to short-circuit the
public's ability to monitor and influence government
decision-making. The solution is not to abandon these technologies,
but to ensure that the law keeps pace with the people who depend on
them.'' But no formal complaint was ever filed.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1995, the chairman of the board of regents of the Nevada
state university system sent a fax to all but one of the other
regents, seeking their approval to issue a press release
criticizing the regent left out, who had questioned the hiring of a
new president for the University of Nevada at Las Vegas. The state
attorney general's office filed a successful lawsuit that said such
communication violated the law on open public meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Once an official's e-mail is available to the public,
voluntarily or through the filing of a Freedom of Information Act
request, it can present an accurate portrayal of what a politician
was thinking at a certain time _ more accurate, in fact, than most
letters on paper, said Patrick J. Carome, a lawyer in Washington
who specializes in open-government and Internet law.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say things with less care and formality and thought in
e-mail than in a formal document, and therefore what we're finding
is we're getting something akin to the real thought process of
people, as freely stated as in a phone conversation,'' said Carome,
who worked for the House Select Committee during deliberations over
access to e-mail in the Iran-contra affair. ``As a result of the
new technology, we have much more after-the-fact hard evidence of
what was said or done.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is inevitable that some legislative and
administrative deals will be cut outside public view, whether
behind closed doors, on the phone or behind the lid of a laptop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can predict sometime this year two county commissioners will
have a private conversation to which there will never be a witness,
and they will make a decision,'' said Gary Lowe, executive director
of the Washington State Association of Counties. ``It's human
nature. There will never be an end to it.''
</P>
<P>
   And in some ways, that is not a terrible thing, he said.
Referring to three-member commissions, he said, ``I would hate to
see the day come when these three have to read the newspaper to
even know what the other two are thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   While e-mail has been determined to be a public record on the
federal level, the issue is a perennial question on the local
level. Further, as new public officials take office and more people
turn to e-mail and discover its convenience and speed, practices
change and public servants need up-to-date training.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, which has one of the strongest sunshine laws,
written into the state constitution, Mike Berry of The Orlando
Sentinel is able to get all the e-mail messages from the school
board he covers. In Clearwater, Fla., the city manager, Mike
Roberto, prints out all his e-mail for the press to read because
reporters have asked for that. Statewide, one council member can
send letters or e-mail to another council member as long as there
is no response and the message is saved as a public record.
</P>
<P>
   In Longview, Wash., all the e-mail between City Council members
is put in a public folder for anyone to see.
</P>
<P>
   But in Boston, the City Council is fighting a request from The
Tab, a local weekly, to see all the council's e-mail from Jan. 3 to
Jan. 16 as part of the paper's research into the city's
redevelopment of its seaport. While some council members have
complied, the council president, James Kelly, said he would fight
any decision on the part of the state attorney general's office to
make him turn over the files.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I would be committing a major violation of the
confidence that's placed in me if I were to make that available to
the press,'' he said. ``Ninety-five percent of it is something that
I'm sure whoever sent it would not have a problem with me
disclosing that to the public by way of the press, but 5 percent of
it is of a personal nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said he did not want to ask people if he could turn their
correspondence over to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while people might just stop writing to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to notices from Carolyn Kelly MacWilliam, the
supervisor of public records in Massachusetts, ``e-mail created or
received by an employee of a government unit is a public record.''
Starting with the presumption that each missive is public, the
content is judged by her or by the court system as to whether it
should be available for members of the public to read. She said
many people had argued _ unsuccessfully _ that e-mail should be
exempt because it was more personal than letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at the substance of the record, not the medium,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
