<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEVELAND-JOPLIN-NYT &LR;      03-31 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEVELAND-JOPLIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PIECE OF JANIS JOPLIN'S HEART, AND SOUL, IN CLEVELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The combination of theater and rock-and-roll, the
success of which has long been devoutly wished by theater producers
eager to build new audiences, has rarely flourished in regional
theaters, where the subscribers that sustain them tend to be
graying and traditionalist. But at the venerable Cleveland Play
House here (at 83 years old rather graying and traditional itself),
the melding seems to have worked in its current production.
</P>
<P>
   The show, ``Love, Janis,'' is a kind of concert version of the
rise-and-flameout story of Janis Joplin, and it includes 20 of her
songs, played by an onstage rock band cranked up to relatively
earsplitting levels _ relative, that is, to your average production
of Shakespeare if not quite to your average production at the old
Fillmore East in New York, where this psychedelic-era rocker used
to perform before her death from a drug overdose, at the age of 27.
It is a rollicking success story here.
</P>
<P>
   The show has now been extended twice, through April 11, and is
among the top five revenue-generating productions in the theater's
history. And though it has attracted a fair number of people the
Play House hasn't seen before _ Hell's Angels, Joplin impersonators
and other patrons who tend to dance in the aisles during the show _
the older subscribers, by the evidence at a couple of recent
performances, are digging it as well, bobbing their heads in their
subscribers' front row seats even as they hold their fingers in
their ears, singing along with the a cappella Joplin satire of
capitalism, ``Mercedes-Benz,'' and leaping up at the end of the
show to applaud, rock concert fashion, with their hands above their
heads. (The audiences stopped short of lighting matches, but just
barely.)
</P>
<P>
   And though some patrons have complained about the volume (during
intermission at one show the stage manager sent a pair of earplugs
to a man in the front row who looked particularly uncomfortable)
the older audience members mostly seemed giddily energized.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a zinger!'' said Ken Kress, 72, an electrical
contractor from Elyria, Ohio. ``The talent on that stage!'' Kress
said he had never particularly paid attention to Janis Joplin
before, and though he vaguely recalled his children listening to
her music, ``I might have just tuned her out.'' After seeing
``Love, Janis,'' he said: ``I think I'll reconsider and give it a
listen. It's history and it's marvelous.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the show's reception has to do with context as well as
music. And it also has to do with Janis Joplin herself, a brassy,
ambitious woman, sexy without being particularly attractive and
possessed of a potent, gravelly voice with the power of a blues
shouter.
</P>
<P>
   She was, arguably, the leading female icon of rock in the late
1960s and certainly its leading female martyr, belonging, with Jimi
Hendrix, Jim Morrison and Otis Redding, to the pantheon of stars of
the era whose lives ended prematurely. She is, in any case, the
kind of character whose life and legend inspire awe and admiration,
particularly among women and maybe even more particularly among
performers who are women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been so inspired and humbled by the level of this
woman's intelligence, love, passion and her uncompromising focus,''
said Beth Hart, a rock singer from Los Angeles who as one of two
singers sharing the role of Janis is making her theatrical debut in
the show. (Because of the vocal demands of the part she alternates
performances with Andra C. Mitrovich, a singer from Austin, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Janis was really a warrior,'' Ms. Hart said. ``God bless her,
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Created four years ago by Randal Myler, who is also the
director, the show (which has had previous productions in Denver
and Austin) is built on a framework of Joplin's best-known songs,
including ``Piece of My Heart,'' ``Get It While You Can'' and ``Me
and Bobby McGee.''
</P>
<P>
   But the narrative that ties them together is based on letters
that were written by Joplin, mostly from San Francisco, to her
family in Port Arthur, Texas, from 1966, when she first left home,
to 1970, when she died in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The letters (many are being exhibited across town at the Rock
and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum) portray an unfamiliar Janis
Joplin: thoughtful and self-aware but deeply insecure, occasionally
girlish, and frequently lonely. Mostly she reveals herself to be a
loving daughter courting her parents' support and approval, a small
town girl discovering the larger world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people from Mercury records will be there to hear the
Grateful Dead (with a name like that, they have to be good),'' she
wrote in June 1966 about a dance that was to be her San Francisco
singing debut, ``and Big Brother et al., and I'm going to get to
sing. Gosh I'm so excited!''
</P>
<P>
   All in all it's less an image of a profligate rock star than
that of a tremulous college girl, and it clearly resonates with the
theater's older patrons. As one woman said wistfully in the lobby,
``She was so good to her mother!''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hackett, the theater's artistic director, said: ``What
we're finding is with a lot of the older people, they're relating
to the letters. People in 50s and down are getting hooked by
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it turns out that many people are returning to the show
to hear the other Janises sing. Both have strong voices; both have
long brown hair with blond highlights. Ms. Vitrovich, a rock and
cabaret singer who has performed in theatrical parts before, has a
greater sense of stage decorum; Ms. Hart, who has been known to
scold audience members for not looking happy enough and to kick her
shoes off into the crowd during the final musical number, brings
more barroom to the stage. Neither, however, has much introspection
to engage in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to overanalyze Janis,'' Ms. Mitrovich said. ``She
never resolved her issues. So what, man?''
</P>
<P>
   The show has its shortcomings. The storytelling structure is
unwieldy. The script calls for two Janises in each performance, a
kind of split personality; one sings, the other doesn't. The
singing-performing half is supposed to represent the public Janis
(the role shared by Ms. Hart and Ms. Mitrovich); the one who
doesn't sing, ostensibly the private Janis, is played in all
performances by an actress from New York, Catherine Curtin, who is
presenting a reprise of the role she played in Denver and Austin.
</P>
<P>
   As the introspective Joplin, she delivers the contents of the
letters, and Ms. Curtin brought herself nearly to tears talking
about the inspiration she found in the singer's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big deal, who hasn't been there?'' Ms. Curtin said of Joplin's
self-destructive streak. ``That doesn't mean you don't want to go
forward. It doesn't mean you bottom out on life. Men, a lot of
people, thought she was just an ugly chick who could sing, but she
was more than an ugly chick who could sing. Me. I mean, I play this
part every night, and people are cheering and laughing and I still
come off the stage going, `Am I any good?' She's teaching me, man,
teaching me to give more.''
</P>
<P>
   So there are actually  &UR; three &LR;  actresses playing Joplin. And if
that's not confusing enough, the public and private Joplins are
often onstage at the same time, either talking to one another or to
an offstage interviewer. Still, at two recent performances no
audience members seemed to be talking about what they did not
understand. Everybody got it.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Linkow, a small woman with blue-gray hair who would not
divulge her age but said her children were teen-agers in the 1960s,
put it succinctly during intermission at a recent matinee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love rock-and-roll,'' she said, and returned to the
auditorium for the second act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1713EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
