<P>
   DOW-QUARTER _ The first quarter was a wild one for the stock
market. The Dow Jones industrial average hit 10,000 briefly, then
spiraled downward. And technology stocks, a major component of the
Nasdaq, saw their performance under pressure as investors became
increasingly skittish about earnings prospects. This is our end of
the quarter look at the market, with a look ahead to prospects for
the second quarter. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-STRATEGY _ Delta Air Lines is still ``desperately seeking
strategy'' under its new management, according to a stinging
critique by the pilot union's nonvoting representative to the
carrier's board of directors. Mark Halsor, a pilot who's held the
advisory board post since it was created in 1996, wrote in the
union newsletter that Delta's new leadership has focused on
short-term fixes and financial goals more than creative strategy.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-SUMMIT _ The Latin American Association holds its 1999
Latino Summit. The summit serves as an opportunity for participants
to learn firsthand about the fastest growing group in the United
States, the Latino community. This forum provides an opportunity
for participants talk with national and local experts on important
issues relating to this community. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WOLF-EXPAND _ Wolf Camera is aggressively eyeing new services.
The company has recently reorganized management to take on new
responsibilities, including a new portrait studio concept and web
commerce. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ The topic of the moment in the nation's business press
is, in a word, Internet. It's getting hard to tell the traditional
magazines from the new generation of high-tech publications.
(Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
