<HEADER>
A1249 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-10THINGS-TEX     03-31 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-10THINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S LOTS TO LIKE ABOUT `10 THINGS I HATE ABOUT YOU'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The spirited teen comedy ``10 Things I Hate About You'' employs
what could be called the Throw It Against the Wall Rule, i.e, if
you put enough jokes into your script, some are bound to work. Hey,
it worked for the Marx Brothers and early Woody Allen; why not for
an adolescent take on ``The Taming of the Shrew''?
</P>
<P>
   And hey, who knew that Shakespeare dude could be so
entertaining? References to him abound in this messy but enjoyable
movie, right down to the use of a remake of Nick Lowe's ``Cruel to
Be Kind.'' But you don't have to be a fan of the Bard to like this
affable film.
</P>
<P>
   It might help if the film had Cliffs Notes, though: There's a
lot going on, especially for a teen movie. To sort it out: Cameron
(''3rd Rock From the Sun's'' Joseph Gordon-Levitt), a new student
at Padua High, quickly develops a crush on pretty sophomore Bianca
Stratford (Larisa Oleynik of Nickelodeon's ``The Secret World of
Alex Mack''). Two catches, though: Bianca has her eye on hot boy
Joey Keener (Andrew Keegan, who looks like Andrew Shue except that
his mouth forms shapes besides circles); and Bianca's
overprotective obstetrician dad won't let her date till older
sister Kat (Julia Stiles) goes out with a boy.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance. Kat is known around the school for having a chip on
her shoulder; even the teachers are getting tired of her attitude.
But then along comes supposed delinquent Patrick Verona (Australian
actor Heath Ledger), setting into motion a convoluted plan to get
Kat a beau so that Cameron can score Bianca.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is, after all, trying to cram five acts' worth of
material into a little more than an hour and a half. Apparently
sensing this, debut feature director Gil Junger _ who did the
coming-out episode of ``Ellen'' _ films everything fast, rolling
right past the jokes that don't work to get to the ones that do,
sometimes so quickly that they're gone before you realize you
should have laughed.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, by newcomer team Karen McCullah Lutz and Kirsten
Smith, occasionally rings of too much deja vu _ how many more teen
movies are going to include: a) a scene in which the new kid gets a
guided tour of his school's cliques; b) a big party scene; and c) a
big prom scene? But if Lutz and Smith's screenplay is derivative
and formulaic, at least it doesn't take itself too seriously, and
Junger handles it with a surprising amount of unself-conscious
flair for a first-time big-screen director. A longtime TV veteran,
he seems to know instinctively what to do with the more expensive
toys he's allowed to play with here.
</P>
<P>
   As much flash as Junger shows, though, his real coup is in
getting buoyant performances out of his young cast (it helps that
the majority are actually young enough to be in high school).
Oleynik, who is completely charming, has the makings of someone on
the verge of a breakthrough, and Stiles, who many TV critics
thought was the best thing about NBC's ``The '60s,'' radiates an
intelligence that seems less forced than some of her teen
counterparts (see Rachael Leigh Cook in ``She's All That).'' The
adults _ Larry Miller as the Stratford girls' father, plus Daryl
``Chill'' Mitchell, Allison Janney and David Leisure as wacky
faculty members _ steal every scene they're in.
</P>
<P>
   So does the school where ``10 Things'' was filmed, Stadium High
School in Tacoma, Wash. Usually a school setting wouldn't be worth
comment, but this place is amazing; it's a castle-esque waterfront
school that looks as if it was built in the Elizabethan era
(fittingly, the prom scene is filmed as if it took place in the
Globe Theater). The campus alone is enough to make you wish you
were back in high school. So's the movie, which for once is light
on the angst and generous with the humor. It's often uneven, but it
works more than enough to get by.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``10 Things I Hate About You''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Gil Junger
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Larisa Oleynik, Heath Ledger, Julia Stiles, Joseph
Gordon-Levitt
</P>
<P>
   Length: 98 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ strong language, a few moments of crude humor,
some sexual dialogue, and alcohol and drug references
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
