<HEADER>
A1250 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEPHANOPOULOS-BOOK-T     03-31 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEPHANOPOULOS-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIOUS GEORGE CASHES IN WITH SELF-SERVING MEMOIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loyalty is a dubious quality in politics, particularly for those
who work in the White House. Toe the mark no matter how odious the
orders, and you might end up being indicted. Quit, and you're
deserting the leader of the Free World.
</P>
<P>
   Write about everything, noting often how much you regret giving
the impression you're betraying your former boss, and you make a
lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   So, in one sense, we have to hand it to George Stephanopoulos.
The munchkin whose name is impossible to spell signed on to Bill
Clinton's '92 campaign, rode that train all the way into serious
White House power, was essentially shoved out when he lost an
internal power struggle with pollster Dick Morris, and now finds
himself on the receiving end of a $2.75-million book contract and
the chance to take all the cheap shots he wants. ``All Too Human''
(Little, Brown, $27.95) is a masterpiece of literary back-stabbing;
if Ken Starr gets around to writing his version of Monicagate, he
ought to hire Georgie S. as his ghostwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Bill Clinton ``et al'' deserve much loyalty;
Stephanopoulos makes that plain. As depicted by his former senior
adviser, our president is a foul-tempered, foul-mouthed dissembler
who bases his lifetime beliefs on whichever poll he read last.
Hillary Clinton's greatest skill is conjuring up tears and telling
staffers to get out if they aren't 100 percent behind her and her
husband _ in that order.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is a nasty piece of work who holds an
exceptional grudge; Stephanopoulos says he got on the veep's bad
side by daring to work temporarily for Dick Gephardt before signing
on with Clinton. Morris, whom Stephanopoulos clearly hates most of
all, is depicted as a sex-obsessed manipulator who appeals to
Clinton's easily aroused dark side.
</P>
<P>
   Why, to hear Stephanopoulos tell it, during his five years in
the Clinton White House there was just one essentially decent
person in the building: the author. Much of ``All Too Human'' is
taken up by Stephanopoulos whining about all the difficult moral
decisions he had to make, and how, when no one else would, he took
a deep breath and reminded Bill Clinton of the right choices.
(Welfare reform, especially, and darned if that stubborn president
didn't go out and do the opposite of what Stephanopoulos had told
him to do!)
</P>
<P>
   As a result, sweet little George tumbled into depression,
requiring psychologists and medications to sleep at night. He
eventually resigned to teach at Columbia University, although it's
questionable how much his students see of him, since he's now a
ubiquitous presence on TV news shows dissecting the remains of the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   It's just too bad for ``All Too Human'' that Stephanopoulos
exited stage left before Clinton's dalliance with Lewinsky. Since
he wasn't there, all he can do in his book is moan about how he'd
always believed Clinton was too smart to do THAT ``in the White
House.'' But the 38-year-old, at least, has more patience than the
president. ``All Too Human'' was about to go to press when
Monicagate broke, and the book was delayed so that Stephanopoulos
could add a Lewinsky chapter. The object, ostensibly, was to give
readers as much information as possible, not to time the release of
the book to ensure maximum sales on the new tidal wave of scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Too Human'' and ``Monica's Story'' are only the first in a
flood of Clinton books coming in the next 18 months. It will be
just about impossible for anyone to read all of them, so each must
try to make a special case for consumer attention. Stephanopoulos,
to be sure, has an insider's story to tell, and a smooth,
nonself-incriminating way of telling it. Just don't ever hire him
to work for you. In the end, people like Stephanopoulos are always
working for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
