A1251 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERMAN-POPMUSIC-TEX     03-31 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERMAN-POPMUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GODSEND FOR TROUBADOUR BELIEVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As with love or the fortunes of a favorite baseball team, music
can be feast or famine :one good CD after another coming out or
weeks going by with nothing genuinely interesting hitting the
racks.
</P>
<P>
   In folk music, the past couple of weeks have definitely been a
banquet: A trio of great CDs by Terry Allen, Tom Russell and Chris
Smither has just been released.
</P>
<P>
   All three men are serious, veteran troubadours, all have highly
idiosyncratic vocal and/or writing styles, and all have strong
connections to Texas: Allen is part of the large handful of
talented Lubbockites, which includes Joe Ely, Jimmie Dale Gilmore
and Butch Hancock; Russell lives in El Paso; and New Orleans-raised
Smither has recorded for years in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three _ Allen's ``Salivation'' and Russell's ``The
Man From God Knows Where'' _ are overtly concept records, song
cycles based around one subject or series of events.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with Russell, whose CD may be the best of the bunch.
It's a folk opera that traces his roots (Norway and Ireland) and
paints the immigrant experience with fine detail and deft interplay
of folk, Irish instrumentation and traditional songs from Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Russell casts himself as the title character, a sort of
proto-immigrant, and enlists several other vocalists (among them
Iris DeMent, Dave Van Ronk and Dolores Keane) to interweave
different stories and points of view.
</P>
<P>
   It is, Russell says in the liner notes, his shot at letting his
ancestors rise up out of their graves to tell their stories. And as
such, it's all but a complete success. Russell has been one of folk
music's guiding lights, but he has gone to a new level here.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Allen, meanwhile, is still his irascible, semisacrilegious
old self, a uniquely talented Renaissance man who recently hosted a
benefit show in Dallas that also featured appearances by David
Byrne and Lucinda Williams.
</P>
<P>
   He has long mused about our relationship with God: In ``Gimme a
Ride to Heaven, Boy,'' perhaps his best-known song, a hitchhiker
claiming to be Jesus steals at gunpoint the car of a guy who has
stopped to give him a ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salivation'' is like that song to the power of 10. With help
from Charlie Sexton, Lloyd Maines and sons Bukka and Bale, Allen
muses on the impending end of the world in the title track and in
``Southern Comfort,'' comments on how people use God for
fund-raising purposes in ``The Doll,'' and sweetly bids us farewell
with the 1957 country hit ``Give Me the Flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   This last track is one of the loveliest songs ever about
appreciating people while they're alive instead of crying over them
when they're dead, and it perfectly ties these tunes together. In
addition to the new material, he also includes a medley of songs
from his ultra-rare ``Pedal Steal'' CD, which is available only at
Allen's live shows.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Smither's ``Drive You Home Again'' is a fine collection of
songs from a man who has long kept audiences rapt with his mix of
folk and acoustic blues. Smither sings in a weathered voice about
weathered people and weathered emotions, and in that way, ``Drive''
fits well with his previous work.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also something of an artistic left turn. The third CD
he has cut in Austin, ``Drive'' has producer and Fort Worth native
Stephen Bruton fusing Smither's acoustic, lived-in sound with horns
on numerous tracks, such as ``Hold On II,'' which features John
Mills on saxophone as Smither sings about keeping the faith.
``Drive'' is both comfortably familiar and different enough to give
Smither's sound a fresh tweak.
</P>
<P>
   Last year saw a fistful of memorable
folk/Americana/whatever-you-call-it CDs, among them Lyle Lovett's
``Step Inside This House,'' Lucinda Williams' ``Car Wheels on a
Gravel Road'' and the Billy Bragg/Wilco summit meeting, ``Mermaid
Avenue.'' But with the release of these three CDs and ``The
Mountain,'' Steve Earle's immersion into bluegrass, 1999 is shaping
up nicely, too.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
