<SLUG> BC-ARCHER-DRIVING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIFFED MOTORIST STEERS DRIVING STORY ON ARCHER TO MEDIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As chairman of the influential House Ways and Means
committee, Rep. Bill Archer is accustomed to being treated as a
VIP.
</P>
<P>
   But a motorist was miffed that the Texas Republican was
apparently using his status to drive solo on the HOV lanes on
Interstate 66 near his home in suburban Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The commuter tipped off The Washington Post that a car sporting
the license plate ``U.S. Congress Texas-7 '' was sighted on the
lanes restricted to two or more occupants at 8:40 a.m. March 24.
Archer represents the 7th Congressional District in Houston and
parts of Harris County.
</P>
<P>
   The source also informed the Post that the car held up traffic
at the entrance ramp as he tried to see if the Arlington police
were handing out tickets to HOV violators.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Archer had a right to be on the lanes as Virginia laws
grants HOV exemptions to members of Congress when lawmakers are in
session or 15 days before or after the official business.
</P>
<P>
   Archer could not be reached for comment because he is spending
the congressional break this week in Australia, where he is
receiving an award from the Australian Parliament and holding talks
with the finance minister. The trip is being sponsored and paid for
by the U.S.-Asia Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   His spokesman Sean Rushton said he could not confirm whether the
congressman was the person driving in the restricted lanes.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the highway where the car was spotted is ``one
of the main routes that goes back and forth from where he (Archer)
lives to the Capitol.''
</P>
<P>
   Rushton also acknowledged that Archer seeks the most expedient
ways and means to get to and from work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing can be explained by Mr. Archer's anxiousness
to race to the Capitol, to save Social Security, pay down the
national debt and provide tax relief to hard working Americans,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rushton added that rules governing the HOV lanes are confusing.
He noted that Archer's intern, who is staying in the congressman's
home and using his car while he is Australia, was just ticketed
this week on the same HOV lanes where the congressman was spotted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
