<HEADER>
A1256 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-MEMORY-ART-2TAKES     03-31 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-MEMORY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORY TAKES NEW SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. And a graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last few years, computer and electronics stores have
become crowded with handheld digital devices that are capable of
stirring technolust in the most analog of hearts.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how smart, convenient and seductive these devices
_ like palm-size personal organizers, super-high-resolution digital
cameras and elaborate wireless telephones that are compact enough
to get lost in a purse, to name a few _ they have all been hampered
by the same thing: skimpy memory.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't cost _ at current prices, around two cents a
megabyte, memory is cheap and plentiful. The hindrance is physical
size. The 3{-inch floppy disk, one of the most widely used forms of
portable memory storage, has been around since 1981. While it
remains a workhorse for storing data and physically moving modest
files and programs between personal computers, the floppy is too
big to insert in a device like a cellular phone. And with its low
memory capacity, 1.44 megabytes, it is hardly worth the trouble to
try to adapt it.
</P>
<P>
   For greater memory capacity, the increasingly affordable (about
$300 to $500) CD-RW and DVD-RAM drives have made it easy to store
scads of data optically on CD-ROM and DVD platters. But those disks
are even bigger than floppies. Flash memory, the coin of the realm
for most mobile digital devices, is the right size and shape, but
it is expensive. A 40-megabyte Compact Flash memory card costs
about $150 ($3.75 cents a megabyte), about half the cost of some
digital cameras. And some forms of flash memory are too fragile
after they are removed from a device to be reasonably portable.
</P>
<P>
   So small portable devices seldom carry more than eight megabytes
of data storage, a thousandth of the amount on a respectable PC.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that many owners of digital cameras complain that
they can snap only a handful of pictures before the memory is full.
And most palm-size organizers must download information from a
desktop through cable connections because the data cannot be
directly inserted by way of a removable memory card or device. What
consumers need, many industry consultants say, is a form of rugged,
inexpensive memory storage that can be used interchangeably in all
these devices.
</P>
<P>
   Three companies, Sony Electronics, Iomega and International
Business Machines, are trying to provide just that. They have
developed new forms of mini-storage memory and are jumping into the
market, hoping to win converts. Two approaches are new
interpretations of existing technologies, and the third could mean
that digital devices like printers and cellular phones could speak
more easily to one another without using the PC as an intermediary.
</P>
<P>
   The new products are the microdrive, from IBM; the Clik Mobile
Drive, from Iomega, and the Memory Stick, from Sony Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, the microdrive is garnering the most attention
from computer industry consultants because of its engineering and
potential uses. Announced last fall, the microdrive is a
mechanical, magnetic hard drive the size of a matchbook and can
hold up to 340 megabytes of data. It operates like the full-size,
multigigabyte drives in desktop PC's. The device is scheduled to
reach stores this summer, but some consultants pointed out that
earlier deadlines had not been met.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle McIntyre, an IBM spokeswoman, said the microdrive could
be slipped into different devices, giving a digital camera, for
instance, the capacity to store hundreds upon hundreds of pictures,
rather than the few dozen possible now with standard flash memory.
The drive's tiny platter can store the equivalent of 300 long
novels, which would consume 236 floppy disks.
</P>
<P>
   At 1.68 inches long, 1.43 inches wide and just 0.188 inches
thick, the microdrive is designed to fit into slots on portable
devices that now accommodate many flash memory cards, known as
Compact Flash Type II.
</P>
<P>
   While IBM has not said how much the new drive will cost,
industry experts say it will probably run $340 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Ms. McIntyre said, the microdrive is being embraced by
Cannon, Minolta, Hitachi, Clarion and Hewlett-Packard, which are
expected to offer products using it.
</P>
<P>
   In a display of corporate confidence, IBM prefers the lowercase
spelling of microdrive, saying it will be a new standard for
memory, not a brand.
</P>
<P>
   The Clik Mobile Drive has been aggressively promoted since
December by Iomega, known for its popular Zip drive. Aimed directly
at users of handheld computers and digital still cameras, the Clik,
about the size of a silver dollar, stores 40 megabytes of data on a
spinning disk that sells for about $10 when bought in a 10-pack.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the power of portable devices growing exponentially,''
said Michael Joseph, general manager of Clik products for Iomega,
which is based in Roy, Utah. He said the growing use of much
smaller PC's meant that memory needed to be more readily available
and more portable.
</P>
<P>
   Much like Iomega's Zip and Jaz cartridges, the 40-megabyte Clik
disk does not work without its separate drive device, at least so
far. A Clik drive and reader about the size of an electric shaver
works with digital cameras, while a smaller unit, about the size of
a television remote control, is for use with laptop and handheld
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Iomega officials say devices with built-in Clik slots are being
developed or are under consideration by Kodak, Hitachi, Compaq
Computer and Sharp Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Using Clik's disk with an outside attachment takes several
steps. To store digital photographs requires inserting the flash
card memory from a digital camera into one end of a Clik drive
reader and inserting the Clik disk in the other end. Once that is
done, however, the reader takes only seconds to transfer the data
to the Clik.
</P>
<P>
   The Clik drive, which comes with one disk, costs $199 for mobile
computers and $249 for digital cameras; a package of a drive,
reader and attachments to use with both types of devices costs
$299.
</P>
<P>
   J.Gerry Purdy, president and chief executive of Mobile Insights,
a company in Mountain View, Calif., that studies major developments
in mobile computing, said he gave the Clik a few years to be
``supplanted by either flash or microdrives.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most radical rethinking of portable memory comes
from Sony Electronics, which has developed the Memory Stick.
Officially introduced in the United States earlier this year, the
Memory Stick is a collection of microchips encased in purple
plastic that is not quite as big as a stick of chewing gum. Sony
officials say the stick, which comes in 4-megabyte or 8-megabyte
sizes, will slip into a slew of devices, including still and video
cameras, PC's and printers _ made primarily by, of course, Sony.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can get more value if they can get these devices to
work together,'' said Mark Viken, senior vice president for imaging
marketing at Sony Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Highly portable and capable of storing more information than a
stack of five floppy disks (this summer, that capacity is expected
to quadruple, to 32 megabytes), the Memory Stick is designed to
move text, sound, images and graphics easily.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the IBM microdrive and the Clik, the Memory Stick is
chip-based, so it uses no moving parts. At its core is flash memory
with an on-board controller chip, Sony says. The sticks are much
smaller than Compact Flash and Smart Media memory; Sony says they
are more durable.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-megabyte sticks cost $39.99 each. Sony also sells a PC
card adaptor, much like those that accept flash memory cards, that
permits anyone with a computer that has a PCMCIA slot to use Memory
Sticks.
</P>
<P>
   The Memory Stick could become the first dependable form of
memory to free a wide range of users from the PC. A Sony photo
printer scheduled for store shelves next month can accept and print
images directly transferred to it from a camera by way of a Memory
Stick. And a demonstration of a future use of the technology showed
that home movies taken with a digital video camera could
transmitted over phone lines by inserting a Memory Stick containing
the video images in a special telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memory Stick is the next dimension in how you can share
information between products,'' said Jay Sato, vice president for
digital imaging at Sony Electronics' consumer products marketing
group. ``It can do everything. You don't need different mediums in
the future to do different types of applications.''
</P>
<P>
   Memory Stick technology is being incorporated into products by
companies that include Aiwa, Casio, Fujitsu, Olympus, Sanyo and
Sharp, Sony officials say. But not surprisingly, Sony this month
released the first major device to use a Memory Stick, the Vaio
slimtop LCD computer.
</P>
<P>
   Sony is developing some other devices to take advantage of the
Memory Stick. Next month, the company plans to release a $1,000 LCD
picture stand that will display digital snapshots and video clips
that can be turned on and off with a wave of the hand.
</P>
<P>
   What does the dawn of these new storage systems mean for
consumers and the devices they use? Within five years, Purdy said,
memory technology should advance to the point where flash memory
will become cheap enough to have 100 megabytes of the stuff selling
for $50 and 5-gigabyte microdrives will not be unusual.
</P>
<P>
   But no one knows whether a single standard for small, portable
memory will become as ubiquitous as the old 3{-inch floppy disk.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Malmed, senior vice president for marketing and sales for
Sandisk in Sunnyvale, Calif., the leading maker of Compact Flash
memory cards, is understandably skeptical of the new memory
devices. Compact Flash cards can already hold 32 megabytes or more,
he said, have a price similar to that of Memory Sticks and fit into
a broad range of devices _ many more, he contended, than Clik disks
will manage in their first full year. Malmed added that the
microdrive's miniature moving parts would be vulnerable to damage
and that it cost too much for most consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But the makers of the microdrive, Clik drive and Memory Stick
press on. At IBM's offices in Manhattan, an engineer recently
pulled a microdrive from his pocket and talked happily about one
day snapping it into a Walkman-size Thinkpad laptop, a portable
computer that would be worn on the belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be done,'' he chirped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
