<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOUNDS-FILM-REVIEW-NY     03-31 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOUNDS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WOUNDS': SERBIAN THUGS IN A DISINTEGRATING CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Emir Kusturica demonstrated with ``Underground,'' the anguish
in the Balkans may be better conveyed through raucous, stinging
satire than by more conventionally compassionate means. For him and
now for Srdjan Dragojevic in ``The Wounds,'' the madness and moral
chaos of wartime call for rowdy cinematic outrage in response.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tactic that explodes any last trace of ordinary existence
and shows just how uncertain the future appears. And in the case of
Dragojevic's film, it helps to define a new generation of thugs who
arouse both horror and pity. The two young Serbs who evolve during
the course of ``The Wounds'' from relative innocents to flashy
hoodlums are not condemned by the filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a story about young criminals who I believe have a
deep moral right to be violent, even to murder, despite the
political unacceptability of this idea,'' Dragojevic has said. ``An
insensitive society and a totalitarian Serbian regime have made
thousands of Serbian teen-agers dangerous, senseless killing
machines, ironically whose main victims are themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wounds,'' which spans the period from 1991 to 1996, begins
with a glimpse of its two main characters after they have been
molded into the ruthless, anesthetized brutes he describes. Then it
moves back five years to discover just how Pinki and Kraut (played
by two effective newcomers, Dusan Pekic and Milan Maric) got that
way.
</P>
<P>
   With improbable raffishness, it shows how the teen-agers fall
into the orbit of Dickie (Dragan Bjelogrlic), a flamboyant crook
and black marketeer who whispers ``Versace'' as if the word were
magic. Dickie, who could easily have stepped out of Kusturica's own
rogues' gallery, revels in the chance to teach the lads everything
he knows about whoring, drugs, gold chains and illicit commerce.
``Thank god for sanctions!'' is his credo.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed with enough stylistic bravado and sardonic narration to
recall ``Trainspotting,'' ``The Wounds'' sustains its sense of the
tragically absurd while Pinki and Kraut grow tougher. It places
them in the middle of a disintegrating culture where the coolest
criminals become television stars, where a billboard advertises a
brand name called ``Democracy Light,'' and where the right tribute
to a fallen comrade is a bottle of Scotch poured over his grave.
Though Vukovar and Sarajevo are bombarded during the story, the
boys show little interest in the battles raging around them. Only
when they inevitably begin harming each other do the consequences
of their corruption hit home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to care about something,'' Pinki insists late in
the story. ``What if you can't find anything?'' Kraut asks. ``The
Wounds'' is best appreciated as an answer to that question.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE WOUNDS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Srdjan Dragojevic (in Serbo-Croatian,
with English subtitles); director of photography, Dusan Joksimovic;
edited by Petar Markovic; music by Aleksandar Sasa Habic; produced
by Dragan Bjelogrlic; released by Leisure Time Features. Thursday
night at 8:30 and Sunday at 12:30 p.m. at the Roy and Niuta Titus
Theater, Museum of Modern Art, 11 W. 53rd St., New York, as part of
the 28th New Directors/New Films series. Running time: 103 minutes.
This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Dusan Pekic (Pinki), Milan Maric (Kraut) and Dragan
Bjelogrlic (Dickie).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
