<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SECURITY01-COX     03-31 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SECURITY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SECURITY WILL BE TIGHT FOR NATO SUMMIT IN U.S.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With NATO warplanes bombing Yugoslavia, security
will be a priority when the alliance holds its 50th anniversary
summit here this month.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO summit, being held in conjunction with a meeting of the
Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council, will draw 43 heads of state, the
most ever to assemble in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Such a high-profile gathering is an inviting target for
terrorists, so the U.S. Secret Service is coordinating 16 other
agencies in safeguarding the sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Some events will be held at the new Ronald Reagan Building,
which government consultants have repeatedly warned is vulnerable
to terrorist attack because of its large underground parking garage
and unrestricted entrances.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the escalating air strikes against Serb forces in
Yugoslavia, ``canceling or postponing the long-standing NATO
meeting is now now _ nor has it ever _ been considered,'' said a
White House official involved in planning the event.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to security concerns, the April 23-25 summit is
expected to spawn traffic jams of historic proportions. Motorcades
for the world leaders will compete with hundreds of school buses
bringing students from across America on the traditional spring
trips to Washington and the usual tens of thousands of commuters'
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Security and transportation planners are working with the
District government and Metro mass transit system on ``an
appropriate plan so the city is not in total gridlock'' on the
Friday the three-day commemoration opens, said the White House
coordinator, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Some streets will be blocked off and some Metro stops may be
closed. There is even consideration to giving federal workers a day
off to ease the congestion.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 delegates and representatives are expected to attend
the meetings, and 3,000 members of the world's media will be issued
credentials to cover them. In addition to the heads of state, the
foreign ministers and defense ministers of each country will
attend.
</P>
<P>
   From NATO, there will be representatives of the United States,
Belgium, Canada, Denmark, France, Germany, Greece, Iceland, Italy,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain, Turkey, the
United Kingdom _ and the alliance's three newest members, Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   From the Euro-Atlantic council, leaders will come from Albania,
Armenia, Austria, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Bulgaria, Estonia, Finland,
Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Latvia, Macedonia, Moldova,
Romania, Russia, Slovakia, Slovenia, Sweden, Switzerland,
Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, Ukraine and Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the events will be held at the Mellon Center, where the
treaty creating NATO was signed on April 4, 1949. The building is
located on Constitution Avenue, about midway between the White
House and Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton will host two dinners for
the top leaders and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton will welcome
spouses to a luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. Mayor Anthony Williams will host a gala at the National
Building Museum. Most, if not all, of the events are closed to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent press conference, Williams said the summit offers a
chance to showcase Washington as ``a city that can work in the eyes
of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the pomp and parties, the summit will have
substantive sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``recent events underscore the importance'' of this
opportunity of NATO leaders to come together, said the White House
official.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
