<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JENKINS-DANCE-REVIEW-     03-31 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BREATHE NORMALLY': WHEN FATE IS IN THE DRIVER'S SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shards of memory often tell a story best, as Marcel
Proust and James Joyce, among others, have taught us. The Margaret
Jenkins Dance Company from San Francisco took this nonlinear lesson
to heart on Tuesday night at the Joyce Theater with the New York
premiere of ``Breathe Normally,'' a polished mix of speech and
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The impression, from early reports, that the actress Olympia
Dukakis would appear live with the company proved mistaken. But Ms.
Dukakis is heard on tape, and it was her recollection of a family
trauma, a car crash, that was the piece's springboard.
</P>
<P>
   Like most recent works by the Jenkins Company, ``Breathe
Normally'' came out of a collaborative process. Ms. Jenkins has
been more equal than others in the troupe she founded in 1973, but
this time Ellie Klopp, her longtime associate, is listed as
director of ``Breathe Normally.''
</P>
<P>
   With a fragmented but meticulously constructed narration, the
tape and onstage performers fuse a text by Rinde Eckert with music
by Jay Cloidt and Ms. Dukakis' remarks, overlaid at the end with
the recollection of the crash by another woman, presumably Ms.
Dukakis' mother.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, ``Breathe Normally'' makes for compelling theater,
allowing a specific event to resonate into a more universal
meditation on life and death and on memory's coloring of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Fate, here disguised as the unpredictable, is the theme. When
the pieces are gradually put together, the story becomes a simple
tale with complex, even mysterious ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a fabulous set of wood-paneled walls by Tom
Bonauro that evokes Frank Lloyd Wright in his Japanese mood. Philip
Agee has created a set of exquisitely sculptured chairs. Alexander
Nichols' lighting gives a sense of place.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the lives of ordinary people can be transformed by
an unexpected event is not new, but it is given a twist on two
levels in this case. From the start, there is another story in the
text that runs in counterpoint to the car crash tragedy. The
narrators initially refer to a grandfather ``in the old country''
who jumps off a train and dies. Since the man had made such leaps
countless times as his homebound train slowed down, the initial
wisdom is that he had lost his agility as he grew older or had a
heart attack. Additional information throughout the evening raises
the possibility that the grandfather caused his death as a catalyst
for his family to emigrate.
</P>
<P>
   In the new country, or rather Massachusetts, three generations
of the Dukakis family, which is not called by name, pile into a car
driven by an uncle. A photograph of the large family, which Ms.
Dukakis identifies as her own, is repeatedly reduced to close-ups
of two young women that the actress speaks about.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, the narrators speak of another trip taken countless
times, as in the grandfather's case. There are 10 singing and
shouting people in the car. The uncle swerves and only two women
(including Ms. Dukakis' mother) survive. The question asked: Did
the uncle swerve by accident or to scare his passengers into
silence?
</P>
<P>
   The choreography for dancers and actors, ranging in age from 32
to 72, is straightforward, formal stuff, clean in its angular
shapes, spiraling torsos and swinging arms. There was a striking
moment of stillness when the ``family'' posed in profile, evoking
immigrants looking out to sea or shore.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Hiken, the senior performer, is the grandfather and
Everyman who is told to breathe normally, as in the title, while
anatomical images show up on slides. His death onstage is one of
several crises in the piece, but it also suggests death as part of
life. A nuanced actor, he gives the text an added import. As
dancers, Ms. Jenkins and Ms. Klopp, like Paul Benney, Doug Hara,
Sue Roginski and Rebecca Rossen, move through their multiple roles
with a typically luminous clarity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
