<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERSONAL-SERVICE-980(     03-31 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-SERVICE-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELYING ON THE COMPETENCE OF STRANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash., Texas)  (js) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan jury was startled when a woman carrying a
garment bag interrupted a murder trial. She turned out to be the
justice's personal shopper. ``She took out three or four outfits,
and the judge chose from among them,'' said Kevin Scott, one of the
jurors. Then the trial resumed.
</P>
<P>
   A Sun Microsystems engineer in Silicon Valley, his wife and
their 3-year-old son had not slept for two nights after the boy
misplaced his favorite teddy bear. Les Concierges, a San
Francisco-based company that runs bothersome errands
internationally, found a replica 2,000 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   And Linda Rothschild, the president of Cross It Off Your List, a
personal services company in Manhattan, bubble-wrapped homemade
matzohs and sent them to Hawaii by Federal Express in time for a
Passover dinner.
</P>
<P>
   From the specialists who locate objects of desire to those who
locate other specialists, there are now alluring experts for every
household quest. With people spending more hours at work than a
decade ago, the do-it-yourself movement, as an approach to home
decoration and an outlook on life, has declined, giving way to a
wide-ranging ``let others do it'' trend. Its credo is simple: to
save time, just delegate others to pick up the dry cleaning, pamper
the pets, coddle the offspring. Emerson, advocate of individualism,
would be alarmed to learn that these others include professional
organizers, new mentors called ``life coaches'' and household
managers _ updated butlers who will supervise any other others you
may hire.
</P>
<P>
   Some see the boom in personal services as a sign of rising
polarization and specialization: the rich get richer, and the poor
get to run their errands. But some of the runners aren't poor, and
many of their clients aren't rich. What they are is overworked,
insecure and increasingly dependent on the competence of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give that custodian, that administrative assistant,
that salesperson, the feeling that he can get the same thing that
the CEO gets,'' said Phil Wexler, an executive vice president of
Les Concierges, which has 600,000 corporate and private customers.
One client had Les Concierges orchestrate his marriage proposal.
And last Thanksgiving, 27 million Americans ordered in.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to self-reliance? During the last two decades,
employment in private-sector day-care centers increased by more
than 250 percent, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. And
that's not counting the many au pairs and sitters operating without
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Pets now have sitters, too _ not only cats and dogs but also
ferrets, snakes and birds. ``Ferrets are getting popular,'' said
Marianne McDermott, the executive director of the National
Association of Professional Pet Sitters, which is based in
Washington and whose members visit an estimated 169,000 households
a year. For $45, the Puddles pet service, in Manhattan, offers pet
sleep-overs, in which an employee has a slumber party with your pet
when you leave town. And it has a 24-hour beeper service for
last-minute business travelers who suddenly need to page a pet
sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   Things were not always this way.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1976, with the do-it-yourself movement
flourishing, John Spadola, a private-school math teacher, decided
to transplant his family from the Upper West Side to a mountain in
rural Maine. He planned to build a house by himself from scratch,
no contractors or decorators allowed. His 6-year-old daughter,
Meema, learned to build a fire and immersed herself in the ``Little
House on the Prairie'' books.
</P>
<P>
   Like most postmodern pioneers, they found that doing it yourself
is harder than it looks. Spadola's family ended up living in a tent
from June until October. Today, his house is still not finished.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1990s, customers had become so overwhelmed that the Home
Depot, the dream mall for the truly motivated, and Ikea, the
home-assembly furniture empire, added decorating departments with
design consultants. So did ABC Carpet and Home, Pottery Barn, Ethan
Allen and Hechinger's.
</P>
<P>
   A continuing nationwide study begun in 1995 by the Joint Center
for Housing Studies at Harvard University shows that many projects
historically done on a do-it-yourself basis are now being hired out
to professional contractors. ``During the '70s and '80s, there was
an awful lot of do-it-yourself home remodeling,'' said Kermit
Baker, the director of the study and a senior research fellow at
the center. ``And there is less of that done now than there was 10
years ago, and we project there will be less of it in 10 years from
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of hours a woman spent on housework in America
dropped from 27 hours a week in 1965 to 15.6 hours in 1995, said
John Robinson, the director of the Americans' Use of Time Project,
a national survey conducted through the University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in drudgery chores reflects many social shifts _ more
women in the workforce, more men agreeing to vacuum _ but it also
portends the privatization of housework, which now extends beyond
drilling and dusting to the mere act of being at home.
</P>
<P>
   Les Concierges will wait around for the cable guy or the
plumber, take your dog to the vet, pick up a guest from the
airport. Les Concierges procured a live Siberian tiger for one
client and a World War II military tank for a private event. ``It
had to be fully operational,'' said Valerie Raszka, the company's
director of marketing relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Once available only to corporate clients, Les Concierges now
offers a full range of services to private members for a monthly
fee of $500.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rothschild, of Cross It Off Your List, once obtained a
British telephone booth for a party. More typically she helps
customers move households or overhaul closets. ``Paper is a big
problem for a lot of people,'' said Ms. Rothschild, whose rates
start at $65 an hour.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   But many personal services, often part time or once in a
lifetime, are no longer just for the rich. Starting at rates of $15
an hour, errand-service providers will do your holiday
gift-shopping. For $12 to $15, a pet sitter will visit a lonely
tarantula. For $8 to $16 a person per meal, a personal chef will
get fresh groceries, visit your home and make your favorite food
for your family. David MacKay, a co-founder and the executive
director of the United States Personal Chef Association, which
started in 1991 with five members and now has nearly 2,500 members
nationwide, estimates that 60,000 clients use personal chefs. He
said that he and his wife, Susan Titcomb, the other co-founder,
wanted to take having a personal chef ``out of the realm of the
wealthy,'' as housekeeping services had done regarding private
maids. The average combined family income of surveyed customers is
$80,000. MacKay believes the service is so popular because it
caters to individual whims. ``When you go out to your favorite
restaurant, you can't say to the chef, `I really like your beef
stroganoff, but can you make it a little extra spicy and leave out
the onions?' '' he said. Chefs are trained to create anything from
creme brulee to chitlins.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind subcontracting the personal is to simplify one's
life. But it doesn't always work that way. ``Finding the right
people to delegate these things to is not easy,'' said Pepper
Schwartz, a sociology professor at the University of Washington in
Seattle. ``You may be spending more to delegate things than you
should. You may also lose the pride in creation of the actual
experience. You may also lose some experience of your own
creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   All this delegating does create jobs. Eileen Appelbaum, the
research director of the Economic Policy Institute, a Washington
research group, said that countries that have experienced the most
rapid employment growth, like the United States, Britain and
Sweden, are those in which household services and personal services
have increased. ``The real problem confronting the industrialized
economies is how to provide these personal services without
impoverishing the workers who provide them or having a tax burden
that burdens the middle class excessively,'' she said. ``We haven't
solved that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But are these the jobs we really want to be creating? Prof.
Juliet Schor, a Harvard economist, said the rise of personal
services reflects ``an increasing polarization of good jobs and bad
jobs.'' Prof. Schor, an author, whose books include ``The Overspent
American'' (1998), published by Basic Books, said: ``It's a sort of
new servant economy in a slightly different form, because people
are not specialized in one employer. You don't have all-purpose
servants _ you hire five different servants, and the servant has
five different masters.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many others just a cell-phone call away, it is hard to
remember to look for the answers within. Meema Spadola, who is now
29 and a filmmaker living in Manhattan, believes the hands-on ethic
of her childhood taught her crucial lessons. She admits that she
wouldn't try to build a house herself now. ``But I made a film,''
she said. And she still feels nostalgic in hardware stores.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Goldstein, the author of ``Do It Yourself: Home
Improvement in 20th-Century America'' (Princeton Architectural
Press, 1998), said that there is a ``small niche of people who
really take this stuff seriously and have a lot of skill comparable
to a professional level of skill.'' She admires friends who do
their own sanding. But she doesn't have time to do it herself, at
home in Boston. ``I don't really have that many hobbies,'' she
said. ``Nor am I going to go around slapping up aluminum
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than Martha Stewart, few are willing to slap up aluminum
everywhere. ``We don't make our own candles anymore,'' Prof.
Schwartz said. ``Should we spin our own linen? Imagine women's
lives in the 18th century. We don't want to get so nostalgic that
we forget how little of our time was left when we really had to be
self-sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegating one's personal life to others has obvious drawbacks:
the loss of family time, of self-expression, of basic abilities.
And with design consultants and personal shoppers in every other
store, there is no need to develop personal taste. Scott, the
Manhattan juror, not only was surprised that the state Supreme
Court justice allowed her personal shopper in the courtroom, but
also marveled at the justice's other decision. ``If you ask me, I
think she chose the wrong outfit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (This reporter has never consulted a personal shopper but did
once hire an organization consultant. The ``organizer'' completed
two hours of filing and went home, forgetting her sweater. The
irony was too delicious to ignore: I was relying on the
organizational techniques of an individual who had the same drive
toward entropy that I had.)
</P>
<P>
   And a message left one morning for the National Association of
Professional Organizers, a group based in Austin, Texas, with an
answering service stating that calls are retrieved daily, went
unreturned until the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the potential for pure disaster, from the infamous
au pair convicted of shaking a Boston baby to death, to the more
obscure Upper West Side dog walker fired for losing the dog. It was
the walker's first day on the job. Which begs the question of all
who would subcontract important tasks: How do you distinguish
between the truly qualified and the cooing impostor? Worse, how do
you tell if your life coach knows a thing about life?
</P>
<P>
   At least with chitlins, you can tell whether they're chitlins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
