<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1266 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERNEYHOUGH-MUSIC-$AD     03-31 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERNEYHOUGH-MUSIC-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODERNIST PLAYS WITH IDENTITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From time to time one still comes across the idea that modernist
music, by its very nature, is ugly and inexpressive, and that the
newly tuneful composers of the last couple of decades have saved
the art from going down some blind alley.
</P>
<P>
   If evidence were needed to counter that notion, a recent CD of
solo works by Brian Ferneyhough (Etcetera KTC 1206), played by the
extraordinary musicians of the Australian group Elision, would do
the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Ferneyhough, an English-born composer who has been teaching at
the University of California, San Diego, for the last 12 years, is
a modernist by any definition, except in his choice of media. He
uses conventional instruments and even has a penchant for
traditional groupings, notably the string quartet, and for
historical models.
</P>
<P>
   One work on this disk, ``Kurze Schatten II'' (``Short Shadows
II''), for guitar, owes something to the Baroque suite: it has
several short movements in different tempos, a certain dance
flavor, if only intermittently (much in this highly volatile music
being intermittent) and a sense of practical handiwork, of music
springing from the way the instrument is handled and touched.
</P>
<P>
   But Ferneyhough's music speaks in a manner that is very much its
own, and indeed, his great effort is to create works that have
strong independent identities, works that are essentially different
from anything we might have known before. In the case of ``Kurze
Schatten II,'' perhaps the strongest characteristic is a careering
between extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas the fourth of the seven movements seems to be saying too
much too fast, like a person who is breathlessly trying to get to
the end of a crucial message but keeps getting sidetracked and thus
frustrated, the third and fifth are blank, composed of furtive
stutterings and raps on the wood of the instrument. There are
extremes of sonority, too.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ferneyhough acknowledges how well the guitar accepts
arpeggios, his piece is full of unusual, vivid and often beautiful
effects, the most beautiful being its high harmonics and fast, wide
glissandos.
</P>
<P>
   The work also estranges the guitar by retuning its strings to
make quarter-tones available. As the sequence of movements
proceeds, the strings are returned one by one to their normal
tuning, until only one distorting string is left. This is a
brilliant and original justification for the division into
movements: there have to be gaps so the player can retune. But in
addition, the gradual normalization of the music's harmonic world
contributes to the formal shape.
</P>
<P>
   In an essay that gave the work its title, Walter Benjamin
writes, according to the composer, of ``the sun which, as it
approaches its zenith, casts shadows which become progressively
shorter and darker until, at noon, they are so perfectly united
with their objects that the latter stand uniquely and completely
themselves, naked, without residue.''
</P>
<P>
   To follow this analogy, each movement of ``Kurze Schatten II''
is a shadow cast by a new tuning on the multifarious possibilities
of the guitar. Or one might imagine in each movement a new net, a
different mesh, being used to catch different glittering fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurze Schatten II'' is brilliantly played by Geoffrey Morris.
But perhaps the most sheerly stunning performance here is Carl
Rosman's of ``Time and Motion Study I'' for bass clarinet, an
earlier piece, from the 1970s rather than the '80s, going back to a
steamier period in Ferneyhough's music.
</P>
<P>
   Rosman suggests something of the sound and atmosphere of a jazz
improvisation, and perhaps for Ferneyhough the bass clarinet was a
more eloquent, precise and versatile alternative to the baritone
saxophone. But those extras are vital. The piece covers the ground
from frenetic burblings to intense tones in a register one never
thought this instrument could reach, moving to a powerful climax,
after which all that is left is dust in the air.
</P>
<P>
   A companion piece, ``Time and Motion Study II,'' has a solo
cellist bound with contact microphones and tape delay systems; it
probably needs to be seen in performance as well as heard. Even so,
Friedrich Gauwerky's performance is forceful.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are ``Bone Alphabet,'' a labyrinth of pattering
cross-rhythms for a solo percussionist, and ``Unity Capsule'' for
flute.
</P>
<P>
   Another new Ferneyhough release (Accord 205 772) includes larger
and more colorful works, among them ``Carceri d'Invenzione III''
for an orchestra of winds and percussion, the clarinet
mini-concerto ``La Chute d'Icare'' and ``On Stellar Magnitudes,'' a
setting of weird little acrostics by the composer for soprano with
the instrumental ensemble of Schoenberg's ``Pierrot Lunaire''
(another historical choice of medium).
</P>
<P>
   ``Carceri d'Invenzione III'' (``Prison of Invention III'') _ in
which a red-hot clarinet solo sparks a whirlwind of fire that burns
itself out to leave ashes of alto flute and percussion _ is
Ferneyhough's closest approach to the sound world of his compatriot
Harrison Birtwistle: it is imposing and gradual, though figured
with furious activity typical of its composer.
</P>
<P>
   With the explosive piccolo solo ``Superscriptio,'' also included
here, it forms part of a concert-length succession of seven works _
a supercomposition that desperately needs to be performed and
recorded complete. But all the performances here, by the Ensemble
Contrechamps of Geneva, are exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Stellar Magnitudes,'' sung by Luisa Castellani, is not the
only recent work by Ferneyhough to suggest a certain humor along
with the headlong inventiveness. And ``La Chute d'Icare'' (``The
Fall of Icarus'') is a gem. Listen to the star bursts of tuned
percussion and string glissandos around the romping soloist at the
start, or to the way the energy of the cadenza breaks out from the
solo instrument in a spurt of piccolo. This is a rare noise these
days: the exhilaration of discovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
