<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GROUND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUND TROOPS NECESSARY IN KOSOVO, SAY FOREIGN POLICY EXPERTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A number of prominent foreign policy experts,
including two former advisers to President Reagan, on Wednesday
urged NATO to send ground troops into Kosovo to ensure that Serbs
are defeated in their rampage against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you are in a war you need to do what is necessary to
prevail,'' said Frank Carlucci, former Reagan administration
defense secretary and national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   He was joined in his call for a more aggressive military
campaign in Kosovo by Jeane Kirkpatrick, former U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations under Reagan, and several other former State
Department officials, at a National Press Club news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkpatrick said that NATO was justified in launching the
airstrikes against Yugoslavia because of the heinous acts of its
leaders, including ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conduct of the Serb government in regard to Kosovo is
unacceptable and uncivilized,'' she said. ``This has been an
assault on civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   She defended the NATO actions, arguing that world wars in Europe
might have been prevented if the allies had struck earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler would have been easy to deal with if he had been turned
back when he occupied the Rhineland,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While urging patience with NATO's current strategy, Kirkpatrick
said that air power cannot stop the Serb troops from committing
atrocities on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of public backlash and congressional opposition, the
Clinton administration has rejected the use of ground troops in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But Carlucci said politically it might be worse for the
president if he does not eventually consent to ground presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically it is very difficult for a president to lose a
war,'' he said. ``And it is quite clear that air strikes cannot
stop the slaughter and displacement of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlucci acknowledged that a ground campaign would be difficult
considering the mountainous terrain and unpredictable weather in
the region. Furthermore, he said there are only 16 access roads
into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   None of the experts could predict how long and how many ground
forces it would take to defeat the Serb army.
</P>
<P>
   ``One must expect the worst,'' said Morton Abramowitz, the
former U.S. ambassador to Turkey and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Abramowitz also said that even if NATO forces Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to the peace table, ground troops will be needed
to ensure the safety of displaced Kosovo refugees when they seek to
return to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The experts also said that the United States should scrap the
current peace treaty negotiated with the Kosovars earlier this year
at Rambouillet, France. They added that Milosevic should be treated
as the enemy and not someone to be negotiated with.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether defense hawks such as Carlucci and
Kirkpatrick will have an impact on congressional Republicans, many
of whom have been more influenced by the isolationist strain in
their party in recent years. A number of GOP lawmakers have been
highly critical of the Kosovo operation, arguing that the United
States should not be meddling in a civil war in a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   Carlucci said he had not advised Republicans in Congress.
Kirkpatrick noted that a number of Republicans, including former
Senate Republican leader Bob Dole, have argued for military action
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no Republican position on this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts calling for the use of ground troops were Helmut
Sonnenfeldt, a former State Department official, and William Howard
Taft IV, former deputy secretary of defense and U.S. ambassador to
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
