<HEADER>
A1270 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PILGRIM'S-PROGRESS-AR     03-31 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILGRIM'S-PROGRESS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PILGRIM'S PERILS IN AN ANCESTOR OF B-MOVIES  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Pilgrim's Progress,'' written in 17th-century England by a
Puritan preacher named John Bunyan, is a book many people have
heard of but few have read. Yet it was, along with the Bible, one
of the runaway best sellers in America before the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story in two parts. The first was completed while Bunyan
was in prison for his dissident religious beliefs and describes the
journey of a man named Christian from the worldly City of
Destruction to the Celestial City, or Heaven. The sequel, published
years later, concerns the less pioneering tour of the same terrain
by the protagonist's wife, Christiana.
</P>
<P>
   Both excursions are a mix of character-building adventure and
leisurely travelogue. Both are written in a straightforward style,
with allegorical characters ( Worldy-Wiseman, Mercy, Lord Hategood)
and homely metaphors sprinkled like raisins in a pudding. And both
have the essential ingredients of fairy tales: goblins and spirits,
exotic locales, spine-chilling dangers and heroic acts of
derring-do.
</P>
<P>
   References to Bunyan linger on in American culture. Two of them
can be found on any newsstand: the magazine titles Vanity Fair and
House Beautiful are lifted straight from his book. And the story
itself, ``a psychological drama of salvation,'' as the art
historian Perry Miller described it, played an important role in
shaping a young country's self-image.
</P>
<P>
   The book no doubt had resonance in colonial America, where a
perilous wilderness and a Promised Land were immediate realities.
But it was during the early 19th century, when the wilderness was
all but gone, Westward expansion was under way, and a wave of
Protestant revivalism, charged with millenarian urgency, was in the
air, that ``Pilgrim's Progress'' caught the popular imagination,
and even generated an entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1830s and 40s, the book appeared in countless editions,
some lavishly bound, others produced on the cheap, with streamlined
text for easy reading. It was illustrated in penny prints, but also
in paintings by leading artists like Thomas Cole and Daniel
Huntington. But perhaps it's most accessible form was the moving
panorama.
</P>
<P>
   Such panoramas are often described as early versions of motion
pictures, and so they were. Shown to paying audiences in theaters
and church halls, they consisted of long strips of cloth painted
with sequential scenes. Attached to vertical hand-cranked spools,
the cloth was unrolled horizontally behind a proscenium, to the
accompaniment of sound effects and live commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these productions were quickie jobs turned out by hacks.
But in 1850 in Manhattan, a ``Pilgrim's Progress'' panorama was
created that had the cachet of an art-house film. Not only was it
executed by academically trained painters, but it included scenes
designed by Huntington and by rising art-world stars like Frederic
Edwin Church and Jasper Cropsey. The result was a smash hit so
successful that a road show edition was quickly whipped up to
travel the country.
</P>
<P>
   Few panoramas have survived, and the ``Pilgrim's Progress''
versions were assumed to have vanished, worn out from use or
discarded once their vogue had passed. Then in 1995, the traveling
edition was discovered at the York Institute Museum in Saco,
Mainee, where it had been hidden away in storage for almost
century.
</P>
<P>
   The painting was sent to the Williamstown Art Conservation
Center in Massachusetts for restoration. And about a third of its
1,200-foot length is now on view through May 2 at the Montclair Art
Museum in New Jersey, in an exhibition organized by Gail Stavitsky
and Diane P. Fischer of the museum, Tom Hardiman of the York
Institute and Kevin Avery of the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   A long-lost masterpiece of American art it's not. Meant to be
seen from a distance and in motion, the painting is done in the
broad-brushed, shorthand manner of a stage drop, and its figurative
style, much of it lifted from book illustrations, is bland. Yet as
an example of the melding of moral thought and popular art at a
particular moment in American history, the panorama is an valuable
and complex document.
</P>
<P>
   The sections on view at Montclair, wrapped floor to ceiling
around the walls of two galleries, begin well into the book, with
Christian escaping from the prison of Giant Despair. The panorama's
basic dramatis personae are in place: the hero dressed in Prince
Valiant armor; his blond male sidekick, Hopeful, in mustard yellow;
and, in the character of Despair, one of the several dark-skinned,
Incredible Hulk-ish villains they will encounter.
</P>
<P>
   From this point on, high action alternates with pastoral repose.
Episodes illustrating ``The Fight With Apollyon'' (not included at
Montclair and in storage in Saco, Maine.) and ``The Fate of the
Apostate'' (which is on view) are monster-movie-style
extravaganzas. But in the scene where the pilgrims, looking a bit
like government surveyors, view the Celestial City from the top of
Mt. Clear, it is the wide expanse of open land and
pink-and-lavender sky that catches the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly, in fact, spiritual drama is expressed through
landscape. In the lush, Edenic ``Land of Beulah,'' figures are all
but absent. The design for this sequence is thought to be by Jasper
Crospey. Both he and Church were already leading lights in what
came to be known as the Hudson River School. And their
contributions to the panorama make explicit the religious and
ideological underpinnings of much of the painting produced by that
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Beulah, in Cropsey's hands, is a familiar Catskill landscape of
mountains and fertile valleys, with the Hudson winding its way in
the distance. But here, upstate has turned transcendent. Jumbo
flowers in psychedelic colors fill the foreground; tiny angels, no
more than calligraphic scribbles, hover like Christmas ornaments on
high; an immense cross glows in the center of a refulgent sunset.
American nature and divinity are one.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The depiction of Beulah, in fact, closely prefigures one of
Crospey's later paintings ``The Millennial Age'' (1854), with its
apocalyptic melange of lions, lilies and lambs. And the sentimental
piety of the scene saturates the second half of the panorama
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Here the setting shifts to a Middle Eastern ``Holy Land'' of
fertile oases. The main characters are women and children. Picnics
outnumber battles. And although there are moments of tension _
including the rescue of all and sundry from the Valley of the
Shadow of Death by a strapping Roman centurion type _ gentility
prevails. It is in this section that a copy of Daniel Huntington's
1841 ``Mercy's Dream'' appears, one of the best-known pictures of
its day. And the whole story ends with Christiana and her party
ascending to their technicolor reward.
</P>
<P>
   But then, examples of moral uplift were everywhere in American
culture of the time, and Bunyanesque allegory was often used to
express them. One sees this at work in Thomas Cole's unfinished
painting series titled ``The Cross and the World'' (1845-46), two
oil sketches for which are included in the Montclair show.
</P>
<P>
   Riffs on Bunyan run throughout didactic literature. A book
titled ``Pilgrim's Progress in the Last Days'' published in the
1840s was an antislavery tract with a protagonist named Christian
Abolition. Another, titled ``The Pilgrim's Progress in the 19th
Century,'' was both a vehement reformist diatribe and a how-to for
stage-managing religious revival movements. A third, ``The
California Pilgrim,'' was set during the gold rush and combined
travel brochure descriptions of the far west with scathing accounts
of the iniquities of life in frontier towns.
</P>
<P>
   Bunyan's Everyman metaphor even found its way into the work of
some of the era's best writers. Notions of pilgrimage and progress
_ minus overt religiosity but infused with spiritual grandeur _ are
at the heart of Walt Whitman's great poem ``Song of Myself''
(1855). ``I tramp a perpetual journey,'' the poem reads, ``My signs
are a rainproof coat, good shoes and a staff cut from the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Whitman was writing, ``Pilgrim's Progress'' had lost
much of its status as edifying literature and was regarded
primarily as fiction. That's surely how many people in the New York
audiences in 1850 approached the panorama: as improving fun of a
kind that Disney specialized in a century later. And given its
``Fantasia'' flowers and ``Night on Bald Mountain'' atmospherics,
one is inclined to view the fragment at Montclair that way today.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Pilgrim's Progress'' embodies a cultural history worth
remembering. Its narrative of a righteous journey through the
wilderness to stake a claim on a piece of Paradise was part of the
American foundation myth, one of struggle and entitlement, in which
ideas of divine mission, national destiny and nostalgia for the
past merged.
</P>
<P>
   The story's plain style _ hymnbook sonorities and folk-tale
flatness _ matched a nation's ``no-frills'' democratic self-image.
And its division of the world into clear-cut forces of good and bad
was suited to an American temperament unwilling or unable to deal
comfortably with the shades of moral ambiguity or paradox.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the polarities of cautionary pessimism and spiritual
utopianism that sit at the very heart of Bunyan's tale are still
alive in America, though often difficult to sort out. They account
for both the most conservative and the most progressive aspects of
our culture, popular and otherwise, as the heaven-and-hell struggle
for a national soul that consumed the country in the 1960s
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   And if Bunyan's spirit seems to have survived primarily in
literature (where it began), we can also still detect its presence
in some of our century's art. In 1961, the Abstract Expressionist
painter Clyfford Still described his life in these words: ``It was
a journey that one must make, walking straight and alone. No
respites or shortcuts were permitted. And one's will had to hold
out against every challenge of triumph, or failure, or the praise
of Vanity Fair. Until one has crossed the darkened and wasted
valleys and come at last into clear air and could stand on a high
and limitless plain. Imagination, no longer fettered by the laws of
fear, became as one with vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Abstract Expressionism may not spring immediately to mind when
looking at the often maladroit, feature-length painting strung
around the gallery walls at the Montclair Art Museum. But the
colossalist impulse and driven idealism in American art, from
Church to Pollock, is certainly discernable here and is well worth
pondering. The rediscovered panorama may be little more than a
cultural artifact, but it is also, for better and for worse, a
mirror of ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
