<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO WRECK LIKE HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We had planned to remodel our home at some point.
</P>
<P>
   You know how things get after a few years with a growing family.
The paint is covered with fingerprints.MDNM/ and the carpet is
permanently stained. It's inevitable that a home that's truly lived
in will suffer wear and tear. However, I had hoped to remodel our
house all at once instead of slowly, piece by piece. But every time
I turn around, something else is broken and has to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   This week it was a light fixture. I had gone upstairs to water
the plants. When I walked into my son's room, I noticed that
something seemed odd. I couldn't put my finger on it until I
started to walk out and realized that one side of the room was much
brighter than the other. I looked up at the ceiling and discovered
that one of those glass deals on the ceiling fan was smashed. I
don't know exactly what they're called, but I know that they don't
self-destruct. There wasn't a micron of glass on the floor, either,
and the thing had been turned so that the side with the most damage
was facing the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   I should have known something was up when I heard my son
vacuuming last Thursday. It's hard enough to get him to do chores
on Saturday, but voluntary vacuuming in the middle of the week?
Yes, I should have run for the nearest exit right then.
</P>
<P>
   So I summoned little Benson and inquired about the damaged
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``What light?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one,'' I said pointing at the offending glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's broken?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's broken, and I'm sure that you broke it because this
is your room and someone cleaned up the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Dad cleaned it up.''
</P>
<P>
   I noticed that he didn't go so far as to say that his father had
broken the light, but he was definitely stalling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shall we call Dad and ask him? He's watching the playoffs, you
know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No! Don't call him! Hmmm, let me think. Yes, I guess it did
accidentally get broken one day when I was playing with my brother.
It's kind of his fault.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What does your brother have to do with this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he wanted to see me do this trick with my yo-yo, and
when it went up into the air, it hit the light and broke it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't you tell someone?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You were real busy making a grocery list or something and Dad
was washing his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't you tell us later?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know how much it costs to repair a hole in a sofa
cushion? Do you have any idea what damage a spoon in the garbage
disposal can do? Just try to repair a rip in the wallpaper.MDNM/
and make it look as good as new.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead. I dare you.
</P>
<P>
   The really bad news is that I only have a few more years until
my children leave me to go seek their fates in the great big world.
That's the sudden plot twist in every parent's life.
</P>
<P>
   We all know you can replace a light fixture.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is an Arlington wife, mother and
dentist, 548-5564. Write in care of the ``Arlington Star-Telegram''
at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
