<HEADER>
A1277 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLUENOTE-RECORDS01-CO     03-31 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUENOTE-RECORDS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blue Note tour a bold showcase
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Promising jazz musicians can find themselves caught in
a weird double whammy. Here's a signature American art form with
nearly a century of history behind it, a history of innovation.
Here also is a music that has, especially since the 1980s, fostered
a cult of youth that, lacking mastery, has often merely recycled
what came before.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bind that mainstream jazz has finally begun to wriggle
out of, as each new year seems to herald another generation of
talents sprung from late-night jam sessions or conservatories, high
school bands or intensive apprenticeships with more established
players. These musicians can't help but be mindful of tradition.
What's different is their commitment to sounding as much like
themselves as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In a fairly bold promotional move, Blue Note, the legendary jazz
label that celebrates its 60th anniversary this year, has
dispatched some of these musicians on a 20-city tour, one that
deliberately avoids jazz venues in favor of ``alternative'' sites
such as the Echo Lounge in East Atlanta, where they'll perform
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the threshold of another creative cycle,'' says Greg
Osby, the 38-year-old alto saxophonist who has welcomed several of
these players into his bands. He's the elder statesman on what Blue
Note has dubbed its ``New Directions'' tour, which also features
vibraphonist Stefon Harris, 25; tenor saxophonist Mark Shim, 23;
and pianist Jason Moran, 24. (Bassist Tarus Mateen, well-known to
local audiences, and drummer Nasheet Waits complete the sextet.
Unlike the others, however, they have no new or recent Blue Note
releases to tout.) ``We had endured this impasse throughout the
'90s where people were riding the wave, people coasting on their
reputations and not offering anything dynamically conceptual.''
</P>
<P>
   Osby, whose 20-year career has ranged from stints with Dizzy
Gillespie to co-founding the Brooklyn M-BASE collective in the
1980s, always has been one to whittle an edge: whether attempting
to fuse jazz with hip-hop or capturing his latest album, the
spirited ``Banned in New York,'' on a mini-disk recorder during a
club date. If Osby often felt like he was thrashing amid a stasis,
he doesn't anymore. ``I'm seeing it on all sides,'' he says of the
surge. ``You go into these little clubs, see these new arrivals to
New York at little jam sessions. These cats are really burning.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for many potential fans, the heat can feel mighty distant.
``The touring circuit is dead,'' says Tom Evered, general manager
and vice president of Blue Note. ``Jazz musicians traditionally
made a living on the road because record sales can hardly be
considered a source of income.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true: Jazz accounts for about 3 percent of total domestic
record sales. Radio stations that play mainstream jazz, such as
Atlanta's WCLK-FM (91.9) and WREK-FM (91.1), tend to be
noncommercial.
</P>
<P>
   But artists such as Harris, perhaps the most widely noticed
up-and-comer on the New York scene, project an articulate
confidence. ``I'm not a person to record a bunch of standards.
There's no point in rewriting the same book over and over,'' says
the Albany, N.Y., native, who debuted on Blue Note with last year's
``A Cloud of Red Dust'' album.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best approach to dealing with Dexter Gordon,'' he adds,
referring to the influential tenor saxophonist, one of the most
romantic players to pick up a horn, ``is don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   CONCERT PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Blue Note New Directions Tour
</P>
<P>
   10 tonight (doors open at 9). $10. Echo Lounge, 551 Flat Shoals
Ave. S.E., Atlanta, Ga. 404-681-3600.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1278 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONDUCTOR-MCGEGAN01-C     03-31 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDUCTOR-MCGEGAN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's spring, the world is mud-luscious and the Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra _ along with every other orchestra in the land _
sighs and pays its annual lip service to the pre-Mozart repertory.
</P>
<P>
   But it offers a twist this season in the person of Nicholas
McGegan, its British-born guest conductor for a program of Baroque
_ or ``ba-ROCK,'' as he pronounces it _ music.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been put off by the parade of penguins on the ASO
podium this season, take heart. McGegan, 49, is not a contender to
replace music director Yoel Levi. He likes what he does just fine,
thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Short, spry and puckish, with thinning blond hair, sharp eyes
behind gold-rimmed specs and an irreverent sense of humor, he's
also a jack-of-all-trades.
</P>
<P>
   But for a few works by Bach and Handel that have made it into
the standard repertory, music before 1750 is still a scholar's
field. In addition to being a conductor, McGegan is a researcher,
an editor, a translator and a storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a flutist, he also plays (and conducts from) the
keyboard, and he can turn his hand to other tasks. After his first
rehearsal with the ASO this week, he took a few sheets of music
manuscript paper back to his hotel, intending to rewrite the
timpani part.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this stuff,'' he said, ``the composers don't give you
much.''
</P>
<P>
   McGegan conducts Philharmonia Baroque, a San Francisco orchestra
that specializes in music from 1725 to 1800. With 50 subscription
concerts a year, it is the third-busiest orchestra in California.
It tours widely and records prolifically (on BMG).
</P>
<P>
   When McGegan took over Philharmonia Baroque in 1985, it was in
its ``Berkeley-Birkenstock'' mode: earnest, threadbare, resolute.
Fourteen years later, it has become -- after several English groups
_ the best-known ensemble of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   McGegan's cheerful presumption of interest is one of his most
marketable assets. When he works, as he often does these days, with
full symphony orchestras, he walks in without that early-music
attitude. ``I'm remarkably dogma free,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with today's musicians far more likely than their
grandfathers to have played music before Bach's time, they are more
than ready to give him a knowledgeable argument.
</P>
<P>
   His is not a world of quirky tunings, gut (instead of metal)
strings, clickety clavichords or illegible scores scratched out by
genuine 18th-century quill pens. McGegan comes armed with scores
and parts rewritten by Finale, a computer program for musical
notation.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise ASO flutist Amy Porter, whom he'll accompany in a
concerto by C.P.E. Bach, will play her own silver flute, not an
authentic wooden one from a collection of archaic instruments.
</P>
<P>
   About the only difference the ASO audience will notice is that
there will be fewer musicians onstage than it's used to seeing:
about 25, give or take a couple. That's to preserve clarity and
precision _ ``Otherwise it all begins to sound like Barbara
Walters,'' he said _ in a hall that was not designed with baroque
music in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't think that modern orchestras could play this
music,'' he said, ``then I wouldn't conduct modern orchestras. . .
. And if the orchestra's not having fun, there's not much hope for
the audience, really.''
</P>
<P>
   CONCERT PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Symphony Orchestra
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas McGegan, conductor; Amy Porter, flute. 8
tonight-Friday; 2 and 8 p.m. Saturday. $19-$48. Symphony Hall,
Woodruff Arts Center, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E. 404-733-5000.
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK'S REPERTORY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Suite from the opera ``Nais'' (Jean-Philippe Rameau).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Music for the Royal Fireworks'' (George Frideric Handel).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a connection,'' McGegan says. ``These works were both
written to celebrate the same peace treaty: the Treaty of
Aix-la-Chapelle,'' which ended the War of the Austrian Succession
in 1848.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fireworks were a big fiasco _ they all blew up at once _
but luckily it was at the beginning of the program so everyone had
to sit down and listen to the music.''
</P>
<P>
   The opera acknowledges the recent treaty by presenting a battle
of gods and Titans. ``It's basically in favor of world peace,''
says the conductor, ``as are we all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brandenburg Concerto No. 4 (J.S. Bach). Soloists will be Paul
Brittan and Carl David Hall, flute, and Cecylia Arzewski, violin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Flute Concert in D minor (C.P.E. Bach). The son of J.S. Bach,
Carl Philip Emmanuel Bach was court composer to Frederick the Great
of Prussia, who in addition to being the greatest military
strategist of his age was also an excellent flutist.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
