<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1279 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     03-31 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With 218 beers on tap, the just opened Toco Mac in Cumming, Ga.
may be the largest draft beer emporium in the world
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The red-and-white sign would lead you to think it's
another Tex-Mex hash house. Taco Mac, it says, and beneath that a
claim about the wings. You can get tacos and you can get wings, and
connoisseurs of the latter delicacy give it four stars.
</P>
<P>
   But wings and tacos weren't the only reasons people were waiting
in line for an hour _ and then another hour for food to arrive _
when Taco Mac opened in Cumming last month. Many, perhaps most, had
come because it's the Taj Mahal of draft beer.
</P>
<P>
   From one end of the gleaming wood and brass bar to the other are
218 tap handles, and fittings are in place for 10 more. They
stretch almost 40 feet, one row atop another, like exotic birds on
power lines.
</P>
<P>
   In fast-growing Forsyth County, Andy Klubock has built what is
perhaps the largest draft beer emporium in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a record to me,'' says David Edgar, director of
the Institute for Brewing Studies in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The only competitor, says Tom Dalldorf, editor and publisher of
Celebrator Beer News, could be The Yard House in Long Beach,
Calif., but its 250 taps include many duplicates of the same beer.
Remove the duplicates, manager Peter Carney says, and the Yard
House only has 186 beers on draft.
</P>
<P>
   Only? K-2, at 28,250 feet, touches the clouds, but still looks
up to Mount Everest. At the lower ranges, a few multi-tap pubs in
such beer meccas as Denver, San Francisco and Seattle might have
upward of 100 selections. But Klubock's two other Taco Mac
locations, one in Snellville and another in Sandy Springs, already
top those with 120 each.
</P>
<P>
   Now those are in the shade.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I want 228 taps just to say I have the biggest in
the world, but that's not true,'' says Klubock. ``I want to give
people variety.''
</P>
<P>
   You might wonder how much variety a person wants _ or how much a
pub can adequately take care of. Once tapped, a keg of beer has a
shelf life of perhaps two weeks, three at the most. Beyond that,
the beer is no longer fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd prefer to see a somewhat smaller, well-chosen
selection,'' says Jim Dorsch, a beer writer based in Alexandria,
Va., ``Forty or 50 beers that were truly excellent would suit me.''
</P>
<P>
   Klubock bristles if you ask how he can keep 228 draft beers
fresh. ``We keep strict records of when each keg is tapped and when
the lines are cleaned,'' he says. ``If a beer doesn't move, it's
gone.'' He also insists that some breweries, whose beer might not
sell as rapidly as better known brands, ship him smaller kegs.
</P>
<P>
   But even Klubock's critics _ and he has them _ give him his due:
No one has done more to educate Atlantans about the many styles of
beer, from assertive pilsners to hoppy India Pale Ales to robust
porters and stouts. Klubock is passionate about beer as art and
craft, and wants Americans to know it's part of their history:
``The Founding Fathers were home brewers, you know. Apparently,
George Washington put out a pretty good porter.''
</P>
<P>
   For Europeans, beer is still an agricultural product that's part
of daily life, not a label or an ad line. ``They live much closer
to the product,'' Klubock says. ``In Germany, every region has its
own beer, and they're all different. We don't have that here. We've
standardized it to where it has no character.''
</P>
<P>
   Klubock seeks out individualistic beers that have fervent
followings elsewhere _ the 17 Rogue beers in his lineup, for
example, or Tuppers' Hop Pocket Ale and the companion Hop Pocket
Pils _ and gives them a chance to make it in a local market
dominated by industry giants Anheuser-Busch, Miller and Coors.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a glass of Bud Light, Taco Mac will sell you a glass
of Bud Light. But if you want a Schneider Aventinus from Munich, it
will sell you that, too. Or it will sell you a glass of Bruegel
Amber Ale from Belgium, Rogue Shakespeare Stout from Newport, Ore.,
or Fuller's Extra Special Bitter from London. There are beers from
13 countries (and 16 states), all sitting in silver kegs in a
cooler that's set at 38 degrees Fahrenheit, each keg hooked to a
tap handle by a short plastic hose (''It's the only restaurant in
the country where the cooler was built first and everything else
was built around it,'' Klubock says).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell you people haven't been buying Bud or
Miller, because some have,'' he says. ``And that's fine with me. I
just want people to try different beers, something they didn't know
before. This is my calling.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul was struck on the road to Damascus. Andy Klubock, who's
39, was struck at some point while studying political science and
history at Emory University. A native of Newton, Mass., he began
working at a Taco Mac in Virginia Highland in 1982 and took over
management of the Sandy Springs location on Roswell Road in 1990.
Three years later he opened a Taco Mac in Snellville.
</P>
<P>
   Both quickly became houses of worship for beer lovers, and not
just those from Atlanta. Klubock counts among his patrons a dentist
in Birmingham, Ala., and a psychotherapist from South Carolina who
make periodic visits to Atlanta, checking into a nearby motel for
the weekend to sample the variety and drink beer they could find
nowhere else in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, when the brewmaster of the renowned Pilsner
Urquell, the original pilsner beer, visited the United States two
years ago, he made a point of dropping by Taco Mac in Sandy
Springs. Even in the Czech Republic, brewers know who the opinion
leaders are in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very good at selling myself, but I can sell beer night
and day,'' Klubock says. ``I haven't taken a vacation in 15 years
that didn't involve visiting a brewery.'' He has visited more than
300 breweries here and abroad. Last year he traveled to monasteries
in Belgium and Holland, watching Trappist monks make beer and then
staying for vespers.
</P>
<P>
   When people ask him why he opened the world's biggest draft bar
in Cumming, a town of 4,400, he answers, ``Because I'm a
missionary, that's why.'' He leaves it to them to figure out the
northward movement of commerce and the growth in Forsyth County.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that he is a missionary. Put a brown robe on
him and he could pass for Brother Dominic, the sly friar in the old
TV ad who found it easier to photocopy the abbey's sacred texts
than labor over them by hand. He believes people will try something
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were telling me people don't drink good beer, and I'm
here to tell you they do,'' he said a few days after Taco Mac
opened. The first keg that sold out was Hoegaarden White Ale, a
delicate, spiced beer from Belgium. It wasn't long before Sierra
Nevada Pale Ale, a benchmark in the new generation of American
craft beers, also sold out. And, oh yes, Bud Light was doing well,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a starvation for it up here,'' Roger Perkins
said. On a Saturday evening, Perkins waited in line while his wife,
Barbara, stood outside comforting a hungry 16-month-old. The
Perkinses are home builders and home brewers who moved to Forsyth
from Fulton County two years ago, and now they no longer had to
drive back to Sandy Springs to explore the wide world of beer.
</P>
<P>
   Around noon Tuesday, Mark Fitzgerald, a sales representative for
Guinness, sat at the bar in an immaculate white dress shirt and
paisley tie. ``Where next, Andy? South Carolina ?'' he asked as a
plate of tacos and a pint of Guinness _ what else? _ were set
before him.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the polished bar, Brother Andrew nodded not very meekly
and said, ``Where there's bad beer, I'll go next.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
