<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-DOSES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON HEALTH NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAKE MINE MEDIUM-RARE
</P>
<P>
   Women who eat their hamburgers, steaks and bacon very well-done
may be putting themselves at higher risk for breast cancer,
according to a recent study reported in the ``Mayo Clinic Women's
HealthSource''.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers surveyed nearly 1,000 women and concluded that women
who eat all their meat very well-done, even charred, have a breast
cancer risk more than four times greater than those who like their
meat rare or medium.
</P>
<P>
   Substances known as ``heterocyclic amines'' are suspected as the
cause. The substances form when meat is fried, grilled or broiled
at very high temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, researchers were unable to show that eating
greater amounts of very well-done meat increased the breast cancer
risk. How much meat the women ate did not make a difference, they
said, only how well it was cooked.
</P>
<P>
   BIASED PYRAMID?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Dietary Guidelines recommend two to three servings of dairy
products daily for every American even though the majority of
African-Americans, Asian-Americans, Hispanic Americans and American
Indians are lactose-intolerant, the Physicians Committee for
Responsible Medicine pointed out at a news conference last week.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali and a contingency of doctors led by former Surgeons
General Joycelyn Elders and C. Everett Koop said they are seeking
to rid federal diet guidelines of old racial biases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guidelines don't do enough to help prevent the many
chronic diseases, such as diabetes, heart disease, cancer and
hypertension, that take a disproportionate toll among minorities,''
says Dr. Neal D. Barnard, PCRM president. ``To help reduce our risk
of serious disease, the guidelines need to more vigorously promote
low-fat and vegetarian diets rich in vegetables and fruits.''
</P>
<P>
   MILD EXERCISE FOR HEART PATIENTS
</P>
<P>
   Moderate physical activity _ not bed rest _ seems to be the best
medicine for individuals who suffer from ``stable'' congestive
heart failure, according to a study conducted by researchers in
Italy and the United States and reported in the latest issue of
``Circulation: Journal of the American Heart Association.''
</P>
<P>
   Individuals with congestive heart failure who participated in an
exercise program lived longer and required fewer hospitalizations
during four years of follow-up than those who did not exercise.
</P>
<P>
   CHF is the most frequent cause of hospitalization for people 65
and older. It is the only form of heart disease that is increasing,
with about 400,000 new cases diagnosed each year.
</P>
<P>
   The hearts of CHF patients no longer pump blood efficiently
throughout the body, and the patients typically have difficulty
breathing during exercise because of fluid accumulating in the
lungs.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes about health for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
