<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-STATES-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT WEIGHS WHETHER STATE WORKERS CAN SUE USING FEDERAL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case that could affect state workers around
the country, the Supreme Court heard arguments Wednesday about a
dispute pitting the state of Maine against a group of probation
officers over time-and-a-half pay.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision in the case, which is expected in
June, could define how vulnerable state governments are to being
sued when they violate someone's federally protected rights.
</P>
<P>
   The state-employed probation officers sued Maine in 1992 in
federal court, saying they were owed the extra pay guaranteed by a
federal labor law.
</P>
<P>
   But while their lawsuit was pending, the Supreme Court ruled in
1996 in another case that the Constitution's 11th Amendment, which
limits the judicial power of the federal government, shields states
from being sued against their will in federal court. The U.S.
District Court then dismissed the probation officers' suit, and
they refiled it in state court, still depending on the federal law,
known as the Fair Labor Standards Act.
</P>
<P>
   However, a year later a Maine Superior Court in Cumberland ruled
that the 11th Amendment makes states immune from state court
lawsuits that would be barred in federal courts. The court also
said that the 11th Amendment makes a state totally immune from
being sued by employees who allege labor-law violations, although
it said federal labor officials still could sue the state seeking
to make it enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Maine Supreme Judicial Court agreed with that
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing before the U.S. Supreme Court Wednesday, Laurence Gold,
representing the probation officers, urged the justices to allow
his clients to file their lawsuit in state court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state must be bound by federal law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gold was supported by the Clinton administration. Solicitor
General Seth Waxman told the justices that because lawsuits against
states are now generally barred from federal court, citizens need
state courts to protect their federal rights. Waxman said that
without the option of going to a state court, a citizen's federal
rights might as well be ``written in disappearing ink.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``State courts may not deny a federal right absent a
valid excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maine Solicitor Peter Brann said the Constitution ``clearly
immunized states from being sued in their own courts.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that if a state violates a federal law, citizens may
bring their case to federal officials who may then sue the state in
federal court to enforce the law. ``The law still applies,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the arguments, the justices struggled over how to
balance states' sovereignty against the federal government's power.
</P>
<P>
   In recent rulings over the issue, the court has split 5-4 with
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day
O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas
prevailing in favor of the states.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday it again appeared that the conservative justices
were again siding with the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're saying states are not sovereign where federal law is
concerned,'' Scalia told Waxman. ``What if there was a federal law
allowing the federal government to raid state treasuries?''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said it was ``hard to conceive the founding fathers
believed states could be sued in their own courts.''
</P>
<P>
   But later in the arguments, Justice Stephen Breyer told Brann
that ``if you prevail, we're going to get some kind of hodgepodge
... of enforcement of federal law.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Maine case, the court has agreed to decide three
other states-rights issues within the next year. The questions are
whether states may be sued for patent infringement and for
violating a federal false-advertising law and whether state
employees may sue over alleged violations of the federal law
banning age bias in the workplace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1806EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
