<HEADER>
A1286 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-31 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIGH AND THE MIGHTY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ The perennially strapped  &UR; Duchess of York &LR; , who announced last
week she would remain under her ex-husband's roof and return a
house given to her by the Queen because she can't afford to pay for
its upkeep, is thinking about moving to Switzerland to avoid paying
taxes, reports the Mirror of London.
</P>
<P>
   Mean old Buckingham Palace continues to refuse her requests for
more dough. ``She feels the only thing left is to try to make a
life in another place,'' said a royal aide.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fergie's advance men have announced her plans to be
in San Francisco on April 27 promoting ``Dieting With the
Duchess,'' her new book for Weight Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hiking atop Mount Tamalpais, where  &UR; Christina Walcoff  &LR; sat
down for a snack and tried to get away from tales of scandal by
concentrating on  &UR; Ralph Waldo Emerson &LR; 's ``Nature and Other
Writings,'' she came upon the passage:
</P>
<P>
   ``The farmer imagines power and place are fine things. But the
President has paid dear for his White House. It has commonly cost
him all his peace, and the best of his manly attributes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The March issue of the National Puzzlers' League newsletter
reports, to  &UR; Barry Traub &LR; 's delight, that ``October Sky'' is an
anagram of ``Rocket Boys,'' the book on which the movie is based.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A TIMES FOR APRIL FOOL'S DAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A hundred thousand copies of a 32-page, four-section I Can't
Believe It's Not the New York Times satire are on sale today, for
$4, at newsstands in New York, Los Angeles, Chicago, Boston and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The front page features stories about Congress canceling
personal income taxes, Gore-a-Mania, the resignation of the public,
the Anglican church reuniting with the Catholic Church, and,
predictably,  &UR; Richard Branson &LR; 's plans for a manned flight to
Pluto. The Branson story is bread and butter; Virgin Airlines,
which has the only real ads in the issue, sponsored the project.
</P>
<P>
   The lead editorial calls for readers to ``Take This Page More
Seriously,'' and the list of unattributed columnists includes Frank
Bitch, William Surefire and Maureen Cowed.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of contributors, many of them editors at New
York publishing houses, novelists and magazine writers, is 25, and
their greatest inspiration is the National Lampoon, said
editor-in-chief Matthew Polly, 27. Polly, who was a Rhodes scholar
last year, is hoping that the success of the Times knockoff will
lure enough investors to enable him to start his own humor
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LARRY'S STORE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Larry Flynt  &LR; has opened Hustler Hollywood, reports Metropolis
magazine, and is thinking of opens others _ a la the Hard Rock cafe
_ in New York, Miami and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The store, which is on Sunset Boulevard, includes adults-only
merchandise, a bookstore, clothing section and cafe. Counters are
low so that customers can't lurk unseen by staff members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW JOE WOULD HAVE WANTED IT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Joe DiMaggio &LR; 's lawyers have asked that his will, stored in the
Broward County clerk's office, be kept in a safe to protect it from
collectors who might want to steal it. Wills are normally
accessible to anyone who requests to see them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't ever had another request like this one,'' said
Probate Judge  &UR; Mel Grossman &LR; , ``but then, I'm not sure we've had
anyone else whose signature was really worth something.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a reader who saw DiMaggio socially three or four
times a year says that he would have been very upset at the notion
of Bill Clinton attending his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio loved to talk politics, said the caller, and was a
``staunch, staunch conservative.'' He went out of his way to say
how much he disliked Clinton, insisting ``We've got to get rid of
that guy'' well before the Lewinsky scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger people are in life, the more big-league they are.
That's been my experience. You meet less s_s the higher up you
go.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Ted Williams in Esquire magazine. He also calls Joe DiMaggio
``the greatest player I ever saw.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
