<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVE-BIZ-740(2TAKES)     03-31 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVE-BIZ-740(2TAKES)-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCERS OF OLIVE OIL NOT IN IT FOR THE PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also OLIVE-ETIQUETTE-NYTR) 
(rk) 
 By   TIM TESCONI and MIRIAM SILVER   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Olive trees can't compete with wine grapes
when it comes to profits, but that isn't stopping a growing cadre
of hobbyists, grape growers and corporate millionaires determined
to make olive oil from Northern California as well-known as the
area's finest wines.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to olives and the precious oil they yield, there's
more passion than profit among Wine Country producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much the money. It's the romance of rebuilding an
old industry that was once so important in Sonoma County,'' said
Sonoma Valley vineyard manager Philip Coturri, who runs an olive
tree nursery in Sonoma and makes an olive oil marketed under his
family's Poggiolo label.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, only three California producers made small
batches of fine olive oil. Today, oils under more than 50 different
labels _ the majority of them from Northern California _ are
pressed or extracted in more than 14 mills.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, thousands of Italian varietal olive trees have
been planted in Sonoma, Napa, Mendocino and Marin counties by
landowners lured by the romance of recreating a touch of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   As an industry, olive oil has little economic impact _ the value
of last year's crop in Sonoma and Marin counties probably does not
even approach $1 million. But it gets star billing among the
image-conscious who see the area as the nation's premier wine and
food region.
</P>
<P>
   The high-end premium olive oils sell for $20 to $50 and showing
up in New York restaurants and boutique groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in cultivating California olive trees and fine oil
include Ed Stolman, the creator of the Dove ice cream bar; Ridgley
Evers, who made a fortune designing computer software for Intuit,
and Nan McEvoy, the 79-year-old San Francisco Chronicle publishing
heiress whose west Marin County ranch is the largest purveyor of
estate-grown, extra virgin olive oil in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appetite for olive oil in this country is insatiable,
especially after all the press about how good olive oil is for
you,'' Stolman said.
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the century, more than 3,000 acres of olive trees
were planted and then dwindled away. Today, some 400 acres in Napa
and Sonoma counties remain from those days and about 200 more acres
have been planted in the last decade, says Sonoma County
horticultural adviser Paul Vossen, an expert on olive production.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 13 olive oil growers, hobbyists and wineries bought a
half-million-dollar olive press from Italy, set up The Olive Press
in Glen Ellen, and are in the second year of processing their own
olives. They are increasing the number of olives coming into
production at wineries and country estates.
</P>
<P>
   Wineries such as B.R. Cohn are harvesting olives and pressing or
buying their own oil, labeling it ``estate-bottled'' and selling it
in their gift shops for up to $50 alongside premium cabernets and
silk-screened logo sweatshirts.
</P>
<P>
   Other wineries such as Iron Horse and Jordan, which are not open
to the public, are pressing their own oil to cultivate the fine
food and wine image they already enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   The intense interest in olive oil, however, is not matched by
financial success. Land is expensive and labor costs are high.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can earn three or four times more money per acre with
grapes than you can olives,'' Vossen said. Even so, he believes
olives have a place as a supplemental crop for some landowners.
</P>
<P>
   Often the olive trees are planted along driveways or rocky
hillsides that are inhospitable for grapevines.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their high profile, the number of olive trees in
Northern California's wine-producing areas are no more than 1
percent of all the olive trees in California. Most California
olives are used for canning olives or ordinary cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
   And California itself contributes less than 1 percent of the
world's production, which is led by Spain, followed by Italy and
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil entrepreneurs compare their industry to California
wine production 20 to 25 years ago. They say winemakers, obsessed
with quality, proved California could make world-class wines
commanding premium prices.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Americans consume far less olive oil than their
Mediterranean counterparts, in the past decade olive oil
consumption has risen steadily among the health-conscious. Olive
oil is a cholesterol-free, mono-unsaturated fat. Such fats tend to
lower levels of LDL cholesterol, the so-called bad cholesterol that
causes arteries to clog.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But comparisons between olive oil and wine only go so far,
particularly when it comes to consumption, says a leader in the
olive oil industry who has become soured on the economics of olive
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I like a bottle of wine, I will go back and buy a case. If
I like a bottle of olive oil, I will go back a month or two later
and buy a bottle,'' said Ridgley Evers, who beginning with trees
imported from Italy in 1990 has planted more than 4,500 trees on
over 20 acres at Healdsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Evers is one of the most successful people in the California
premium olive oil industry. In 1997, his DaVero Extra Virgin Olive
Oil was the first American olive oil to meet the standards of the
International Olive Oil Council. And it can now legally be labeled
and sold in Europe as extra virgin, alongside the best that comes
from Italy and France.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, DaVero won a tasting in Italy, beating out top French
and Italian olive oils.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Evers said that knowing what he's learned in the past 10
years, he would not go into the olive oil business if he had it to
do over. Even by charging $17 for a bottle, he is losing money,
Evers said. He believes the only people who will survive in the
olive oil business are those who don't have to make money at it.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper heiress McEvoy is the rising star in California's
olive oil industry, garnering lots of press attention for her olive
oil and the industry. With an estimated worth of more than $350
million, McEvoy is having the time of her life transforming her
550-acre former cattle ranch into America's leading olive oil
estate.
</P>
<P>
   She has imported and planted 11,000 olive trees and bought
expensive olive presses from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Like DaVero, McEvoy's olive oil is a rich, peppery Tuscan-style
oil that, at $15 to $40 a bottle, costs a lot more than most
consumers are used to spending for olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy didn't plan to become an olive grower. She just wanted
some land as a rural retreat for herself and her grandchildren who
live in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   A maverick, she didn't want cattle and didn't want to be the
``5,999th'' person to plant wine grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Olives piqued her interest as she recalled visits to Italy when
she would cart home a few gallons of precious extra virgin olive
oil with her.
</P>
<P>
   McEvoy says the more competition, the better because it expands
interest in olive oil among consumers. But the hardest part of
making olives go as a viable industry will be convincing Americans
to pay the higher prices for high-end oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously not everybody will like it. And you have to have a
little bit of extra money to want to spend $20 a bottle,'' McEvoy
said. ``But after you know what olive oil tastes like, you develop
a taste.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1812EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1293 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS &LR;      03-31 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release THURSDAY AMs, April 1, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
