<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
 
 REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
BOOK REVIEW
<TEXT>
<P>
   God, Sex and Women of the Bible
</P>
<P>
   By Rabbi Shoni Labowitz
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23
</P>
<P>
   What if women, instead of men, had translated the Old Testament?
</P>
<P>
   With a feminist view, Rabbi Shoni Labowitz demonstrates the
possibilities. Parsing Hebrew words to their roots and turning
letter combinations into acronyms, Labowitz reveals the women of
the Bible in a positive, sympathetic light. Among the matriarchs,
she finds not temptresses, but uncanny women of valor.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Eve, traditionally the source of original sin,
emerges as a wife who shares discoveries with her mate. Leah, the
plain sister married to Jacob by a ruse, emerges as victim rather
than victor. She remains overshadowed by her pretty sister, Rachel,
who weds Jacob within a week.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional translation of Numbers 12 depicts Miriam as a
gossip, punished with an attack of leprosy. This book's broad
translation of the passage paints Miriam as a concerned
sister-in-law overcome with God's warmth and light. Although this
analysis seems a stretch, many of Labowitz's interpretations are
sound, and all are intriguing. Altogether, her fresh perspective on
the matriarchs is a welcome addition to theological literature
dominated by patriarchal thought.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Labowitz extends her interpretations a giant step
further into the field of contemporary counseling. In rambling,
pedantic discourses, she uses the matriarchs as case studies to
help women cope with low self-esteem, stress, infertility,
menopause and widowhood. More biblical thought and less therapy
could have made God, Sex and Women of the Bible a more substantial
volume with wider appeal. _ Reviewed by Hollace Weiner &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weiner is the author of the forthcoming book ``Texas Rabbis:
Mixers &AMP; Mavericks''
</P>
<P>
   CD LABEL
</P>
<P>
   The Songs of Keith Green Series
</P>
<P>
   Keith Green
</P>
<P>
   Sparrow Records
</P>
<P>
   Before there was Point of Grace, dc Talk, Jars of Clay or
Michael W. Smith, before contemporary Christian music was a
recognized genre, there was a man named Keith Green.
</P>
<P>
   He sang songs of total commitment to God, about living an
uncompromised life for Christ. He provided much of the sound track
for the Jesus movement of the late '70s and early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Green sang until he was killed in an airplane accident in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   His songs are now available to a new generation, thanks to this
four-CD set (sold separately). The disc titles are ``Songs of
Testimony, Songs of Evangelism, Songs of Worship'' and ``Songs of
Devotion.'' Each includes cuts from his albums as well as live
versions, and each ends with a spoken message from Green.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the music sounds a little dated; after all, it is 20
years old. However, the message is as relevant and fresh now as it
was then, or as it was 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Green's passion for Jesus is unmistakable. His songs are
challenging, comforting and encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   They inspired believers 20 years ago. They should do the same
for a new generation. _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
