<HEADER>
A1297 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOWNERS-REVIEW-LADN     03-31 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWNERS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OUT-OF-TOWNERS' REMAKE NEVER GOES FOR BROKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Friday, April 2 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ What made ``The Out-of-Towners'' appealing in
1970 also makes it appealing in 1999. It's a fish-out-of-water
story about something most of us can relate to: what it's like to
fight the big city _ and have the city win. It also showcases two
likable stars _ in this case, Steve Martin and Goldie Hawn.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, what made the original unappealing still makes it
a little hard to take today. The new movie, based on Neil Simon's
script for the Jack Lemmon-Sandy Dennis version, is basically a
series of harrowing events in search of a story. After the first 45
minutes (or possibly sooner), part of you just wants the
beleaguered protagonists to admit defeat, turn tail and get the
heck out of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, then you wouldn't have a movie. And for all its
faults, this new film does have its moments and fills a need for a
light, adult comedy. It's just too bad that it's not better, given
all the talent involved.
</P>
<P>
   As Henry Clark, Martin subdues his wacky side to portray a
middle-age suburbanite who's a little tired of life _ and too proud
to tell his wife that he's lost his job as an advertising executive
to a younger man.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's subtlety comes at the expense of his wackier side, for
which he's best-known. The TV ad for the movie highlights the one
scene where Martin really gets to cut loose: After unknowingly
ingesting a hallucinogen, Martin is lovestruck in Central Park,
running after a young woman and calling out to Hawn, ``Honey, let's
do her!'' (actually, the line has been altered in the ad so that
Martin says, ``Let's get her!'').
</P>
<P>
   Hawn is Nancy Clark, Henry's sensitive and somewhat ditsy wife.
After their youngest son (played by Hawn's real-life son) leaves
the nest, Hawn wants to ``suck the marrow out of life'' and take on
new challenges and opportunities. Henry, of course, wants none of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Hawn is good, as usual, and looks lovely (so much so, in fact,
that one wonders why it was deemed necessary in several scenes to
shoot her in soft focus). But whereas Martin's character may stray
too far from his specialty to really delight, we've seen Hawn play
this character before. In fact, we've seen a lot of women play this
character before _ the free-spirited girl who eggs her man on to
new things.
</P>
<P>
   The two go to New York to visit their older daughter and so
Henry can interview for a job. Unbeknownst to Nancy, Henry really
needs the job. Together, the couple experiences the Ten Plagues of
New York City. These include transportation woes, not having enough
money, getting mugged and stumbling into a kinky group therapy
session.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to portray such a series of woes and make it
screamingly funny. But it requires going for broke, something this
movie never does.
</P>
<P>
   As a prime representative of caustic British humor, John Cleese
almost pulls off this kind of transcendence in his few scenes.
Playing a condescending and secretly cross-dressing hotel manager,
Cleese gives the movie a kick in the pants whenever he's on screen.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, of course, everything is neatly wrapped up and
everyone is happy. The filmmakers miss an opportunity to give the
end a twist, but then, that's probably too much to ask of a remake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1816EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1298 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARTHA-SPEAKS-TEX     03-31 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHA-SPEAKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERVIEW WITH A VAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, Orson Welles called Eartha Kitt ``the most
exciting woman in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a phrase that has stuck with her over the years, even
becoming the title for the 1991 film version of her cabaret
performances. And it's a good bet that if Welles were alive nearly
half a century later, he'd no doubt say the same thing about the
legendary entertainer for whom the word ``fabulous'' was invented.
</P>
<P>
   Eartha _ to call her Kitt doesn't seem right _ is once again
touring the country with intimate cabaret performances.
</P>
<P>
   After five decades of performing in concerts, movies, theater
and television _ who could forget her as the best Catwoman ever? _
Eartha still prefers to do it live.
</P>
<P>
   Performing live ``is my favorite,'' she says by phone from
Seattle. ``I wonder why we don't record live all the time. You have
an honest feeling from the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Her shows are always a surprise, a mixture of classics such as
``C'est Si Bon'' and ``St. Louis Blues'' and new tunes. At age 72,
she's in great shape, and still dresses to show off those
sculptured cheekbones, that trim figure and beautiful skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like songs that I can connect with other songs that connect
with a story,'' she says. ``That way the whole evening has been
like a little vignette of plays.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that she still doesn't get a little nervous.
``I think any of us, every time we step on the stage, it's another
request for another job. You never know what the audience is going
to be like. Especially after traveling, when the voice is tired and
the throat is dehydrated.''
</P>
<P>
   As famous as she is for her svelte purr of a voice, Eartha will
go down in the history as a woman who was not afraid to speak her
mind. In 1968, she was invited to a White House luncheon hosted by
Lady Bird Johnson, at which she condemned the Vietnam War. As a
result of spinning by President Johnson and of American sentiment,
Eartha was blacklisted by the U.S. entertainment community almost
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in a free democratic (country) that says you're
entitled to your opinions. I was asked a question, and I gave my
opinion in a well-mannered way. I did not expect to be out of work
within two hours in my own country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they wanted to hear the opinion of the 50 women in
the room. When I sat down, the lady sitting next to me bowed her
head so she wouldn't be heard, put her hand on my knee and said
`Thank you for what you said.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Eartha subsequently lived and performed in Europe and found
greater popularity when she returned home in the early '70s. Her
thoughts on war remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the situation in Kosovo, she likens it to the Bay of
Pigs. ``I think that it has not been explained to the American
people enough for us to understand what is going on there. The
president doesn't want us to know, and he probably doesn't know.
He's told by his advisers what to do and what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you're going to settle wars, darling, is to be
able to control the population. Wars start because the population
outgrows the space and they need more territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't changed my mind about anything. I'm on the side that
is right,'' she says with an irrefutable assuredness. And who would
argue with Eartha?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1816EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUPONT-DAUGHTER-ART-2     03-31 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPONT-DAUGHTER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HOME WITH RUTH ELLEN LORD, A CHILD UNNOTICED AMID THE ANTIQUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Conn., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Did the du Ponts have any small children?'' a middle-aged man
asked the docent as the tour group stood in the delicate
18th-century yellow-cream-paneled dining room of Winterthur, the
175-room mansion created by Henry Francis du Pont for his
collection of American decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   Little did he know that a child was still loose in the house,
now a public museum. She was the 77-year-old woman with the
Claudette Colbert hair and the large shaded eyeglasses who had just
passed behind him on her way to the private elevator, du Pont's
younger daughter, Ruth Ellen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glad to see you,'' she said in a low, likable voice to the
older guard at the new visitors' entrance, where her bedroom once
looked out over a meadow and cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always good to see you,'' he said, as he removed her visitor's
badge, signing her out. ``I hate to do that, but I've got to.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Ellen Lord has a very nearly unique relationship to
Winterthur. With her older sister, Pauline Harrison de Broussard,
she grew up there. Winterthur, a 2,400-acre estate in the
Brandywine Valley outside Wilmington, Del., was one of four family
homes. But by her account, Henry du Pont, who died in 1969, might
have been as surprised as the tourists visiting his house to
discover that there were small children who grew up in it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lord, a research affiliate with the Child Study Center at
Yale University, has written a book about her father and his house,
``Henry F. du Pont and Winterthur: A Daughter's Portrait'' (Yale
University Press), being published this month. It is a portrait in
search of its sitter.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone, Ms. Lord is still growing up, and she is looking
for her father _ an elusive man, born in 1880, whom because of his
own shyness and the Victorian secrecies of his class, she hardly
knew. In her book and in conversation, she speaks of him with loss
and love, as though he were alive, and missing. In reunion, there
is hope for resolution, that he can prove he loves her, too.
</P>
<P>
   Where Ms. Lord had to look is at Henry du Pont's self-professed
legacy _ a monumental house where she, as though by coincidence,
had also lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decorative arts aren't particularly my thing,'' she said. ``I
don't really know anything about antiques or care much about them.
I appreciate them, but I've never studied them in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, Ms. Lord has kept Golf Cottage, a small,
19th-century house across a road from the nine-hole golf course on
the Winterthur property. She asked her father to leave it to her
instead of the large house he built to move into when the mansion
became a nonprofit museum in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   On a low butler's table in the tiny living room was a florist's
arrangement of flowers that Winterthur's publicity agent had had
sent for the interview. ``I didn't get around to tearing that up,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like everything plain,'' she said, asked about a handful of
fresh daffodils in a teacup on the windowsill. ``The furniture?
It's nothing. Most of it came from Lord &AMP; Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   If objects tell stories, for all of the magnificence of
Winterthur, du Pont's relationship with his daughter was thinly
furnished _ a man with 58 sets of china who recorded in detail his
table settings for lunch and dinner for 50 years but found it hard
to choose words for his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He almost never spoke,'' said Ms. Lord, who worked with
archives at Winterthur and cases of correspondence to construct her
parents' half of her childhood. ``He was a very sort of kindly
person, but he was not intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   As is clear to a visitor, du Pont saved much of his affection
for things.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my father died, there was an Oriental rug that wound up
in Connecticut, in my house, which I thought was very pretty,'' Ms.
Lord said. ``One day I noticed that sewn into one of the corners,
which said `Albany' _ that was my room _ was, `When Miss R.E. is in
residence.' That was me. Ruth Ellen.'' Her father had what he
considered ``an inferior rug,'' Ms. Lord said, put down when she
was expected home. ``Obviously my father had a terrific distrust of
children, and he thought I was going to ruin everything, so the
good stuff was apparently moved out when I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf Cottage was empty when Ms. Lord was a child at Winterthur.
She went there, with her nurse, to row on the pond and catch
tadpoles. As a girl, she sat inside to smoke cigarettes ``with
pals,'' as she put it.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, she has moved into her playhouse, maintaining it for
visits to Winterthur with her own family. Ms. Lord has three
children; her second husband, John Holmes, died in 1997. Golf
Cottage is everything Henry du Pont neglected to install in his
period rooms _ comfortable, cozy, familiar and worn, with what Ms.
Lord calls the ``relatedness'' that a small house excels at. At
Winterthur, her bedroom was two floors away from her mother's and
father's.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my parents weren't there, which was a lot,'' she said,
``I used to put obstacles all the way down the hall on the third
floor and zoom over them, pretending I was in the Olympics.'' In
one event, Ms. Lord recalled, she broke her nose.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lord's book is not an ugly backstage peek, but a curious one
_ revisiting scenes from her childhood, like an adult's recurring
dream. The portrait that emerges of Henry du Pont is one of another
child _ as a boy, frail, awkward, insecure, the only surviving son
of seven children born to Henry A. du Pont, a Civil War hero and a
senator.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, he was a bad student who was fond of flowers.
His best grade at Harvard was a B minus, for a garden study class.
He collected birds' eggs. He was dilettantish but acutely detailed,
describing in a list his birthday wish for waterproof cushions for
his canoe, not ``swell, just plain'' and ``fashionable English
paper with my initials on it.'' He was immature and close to his
mother, who died when he was 22.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shock that he later said defined him, a rare reflection
he shared with his daughter. ``To have someone say, `When I was 22,
I gave up feeling,' was such an astonishing thing to hear,'' Ms.
Lord recalled. ``I speculate it had something to do with having
such an intense instinct for collecting. People who've had early
loss find collecting a kind of reassuring thing to do. Sort of an
island of safety, inviolable.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He was still emotionally hesitant 13 years later, living with
his father at Winterthur and running the farms, when he became
engaged to Ruth Wales, of Hyde Park, N.Y., warning her in a letter
that she was about to embark on an ``uncongenial alliance.'' They
were married the next year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1924, now a father, du Pont began buying American furniture,
decorative objects and rooms of fine woodwork, inspired by a visit
to two houses, the 18th-century farmhouse of Watson and Electra
Webb in Shelburne, Vt., and Beauport, Henry Davis Sleeper's house
in Gloucester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Though a reticent man, he created a mountain of marvelous
things, like a gigantic toy, expanding Winterthur with 23 new
period rooms, an internal telephone line, a badminton court and a
bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to know where I was _ I was 9,'' Ms. Lord said,
like Eloise undelighted by the Plaza. ``But then there were these
wonderful things, like a swimming pool. I mean, the modern stuff
was just fantastic. The bathhouses were full of chrome and Art Deco
_ so there was a huge contrast to the antiques.''
</P>
<P>
   The mechanics of domestic life gave du Pont an adult's
confidence. He liked running Winterthur.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was much more of a house person than Mother was,''
Ms. Lord said. ``It was he who planned the meals and planned what
the table was going to be set with. It was all determined by what
flowers were available. My father used to say, `The average person
never notices anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   By putting his interests on display, Henry du Pont might have
hoped to be able to share himself. But his wife hated Winterthur
and made no show of wanting to be there, spending most of her year
at their apartment in New York. She called the estate ``Frog
Hollow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine,'' she wrote to her own mother, ``inside your own
house, having to reach your husband by telephone.'' With du Pont
``knee-deep in flower and antiques catalogs or in journals like The
Holstein-Friesian World,'' Ms. Lord writes that her mother remarked
to her grandmother, ``Please deliver me from farming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very outgoing, great fun, a wonderful mimic,'' Ms.
Lord said. ``But she had a very dark side to her. She said she
thought nobody should be born in this `vale of tears.'''
</P>
<P>
   The collection and its costs also provoked a tragicomic kind of
subplot. Henry du Pont spent money like a du Pont, borrowing from
cousins when he got ahead of even his own fortune, cutting staff or
salaries and hiding the expenses of incessant buying from his wife.
He had 18 bank accounts and used aliases on shopping trips. During
the Depression, when he doubled the size of the house, du Pont's
lawyer warned him that Winterthur might be hard to mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the only regret he had about this was the things he
hadn't bought,'' Ms. Lord said. ``I speculate that there weren't
many.'' Her mother saved string and ribbon compulsively. She had
letters delivered by car to save the cost of a stamp.
</P>
<P>
   If families are trees, Ms. Lord made trees into her family. It
is an attachment she shared with her father. As the story has it,
Henry du Pont instructed his staff that if Winterthur caught fire,
they were to save the trees before the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a tree in this place that I didn't climb,'' his
daughter said. Many are now more than 200 years old. She speaks of
them like relatives. Perhaps she tackled them for their own kind of
living response _ rewarded by a rich solitude and a swaying vista.
Or perhaps a tree is a kind of lap to crawl into.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 34, she asked her father for Golf Cottage in a
letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a plea for a closer relationship with him,'' Ms. Lord
said. ``I sweated blood over the letter, finally mailed it, and
then, you see, he never answered it.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he discussed the arrangements for her use of the
house, telling her at the end of a letter that he was pleased she
would enjoy the ``hills, streams and woods'' of Winterthur as he
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't dared call up and say, `Why in the world haven't you
replied?''' Ms. Lord recalled, pausing. The modest room went still.
``Maybe I thought he'd say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Winterthur is open Monday through Saturday, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.,
and Sunday, noon to 5. Information: (800) 448-3883.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
