<HEADER>
A1313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-VATICAN-380&AMP;AD     03-31 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VATICAN-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN TO SEND TOP DIPLOMAT TO BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-VUKOVAR,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REBELS,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES, KOSOVO-SOLANA, KOSOVO-HACKERS,
KOSOVO-AID, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ARMS, KOSOVO-IRELAND,
KOSOVO-LEGAL, KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-SERBS-NY, KOSOVO-UPDATE) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Pope John Paul II, seeking to open a diplomatic channel
to end the violence in Yugoslavia, is sending the Vatican's top
diplomat to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican diplomat, Monsignor Jean-Louis Tauran, plans to fly
to Belgrade on Thursday and is expected to be received by President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Tauran, a French prelate serving as a kind of Vatican foreign
minister, will also meet Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin
Jovanovic and the leader of the Serbian Orthodox Church, Patriarch
Pavle.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican said it was also ``very likely'' that John Paul
would issue an appeal in coming days for an interruption of the
hostilities during the Easter season that begins this weekend. But
a senior NATO official in Brussels ruled out such a temporary
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Tauran could also be expected to sound out the Yugoslav
government as to what conditions it would accept in return for a
halt to the NATO air strikes; NATO's conditions include accepting
non-NATO forces from the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe or an armed U.N. peacekeeping force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A Vatican spokesman, the Rev. Ciro Benedettini, said it was
``very likely'' that the pope would make an appeal for an Easter
holiday cease-fire. Roman Catholics celebrate Easter this year on
Sunday, while a majority of the Orthodox churches do so one week
later on April 11.
</P>
<P>
   But in Brussels, the chairman of NATO's military committee, Gen.
Klaus Naumann, said NATO rejected such a cease-fire proposal as
``deeply inhumane'' because it would give ``carte blanche to
Milosevic to continue with slaughter and ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican's intervention follows the failure of Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov to obtain concessions from Milosevic
acceptable to NATO leaders. Tauran plans to fly to Belgrade on
board an Italian military aircraft and to return to Rome on
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the NATO bombing, Pope John Paul has
called repeatedly for a cessation of the hostilities in Yugoslavia,
though he has been careful not to single out NATO or Belgrade as
the main instigator, possibly to avoid the image of being
anti-Yugoslav, an accusation that was made against the Vatican
during the NATO raids on Bosnia in 1995.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week, the Nobel Peace Prize laureate Elie Wiesel, in an
interview with an Italian newspaper, chided the Vatican for failing
to speak out against the brutal treatment of the Kosovo Albanians
by the Yugoslav Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican initiative is a relief to the Italian government of
Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema, which has come under attack from
the left for supporting the NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Cossuta, the leader of a splinter Communist party that
supports D'Alema's government, said Wednesday that his group would
withdraw its backing unless there was an Easter cease-fire. But
Italian officials said they doubted that would prompt an immediate
government crisis, given the availability of opposition
parliamentarians who back the government in such situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1822EST &QL; 
