<HEADER>
A1315 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AID-0401-cox     03-31 0279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AID-0401-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON OKs $50 MILLION IN REFUGEE AID
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON President Clinton on Wednesday approved $50 million
for food, shelter and medical aid for the thousands of refugees
that fled Kosovo this past week.
</P>
<P>
   The president plans to give $25 million from the Emergency
Refugee and Migration Account to the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), an international organization
already involved in the relief efforts in Kosovo. An additional $25
million will come from the Department of Defense in the form of
food, shelter, and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Taft, assistant secretary of state for population,
refugees and migration, said 107,000 refugees have fled Kosovo in
the past week. In the past 24 hours, 18,000 refugees entered
Albania, Taft said. Others are going to Macedonia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said warehouses in Kosovo used by many relief
organizations, including the Mother Theresa Society and UNHCR, have
been destroyed. There are supplies at relief warehouses that
haven't been destroyed, but the agency can't get to those sites.
</P>
<P>
   Shelter is also a problem. Because of that, the U.S. Agency for
International Development (USAID) is ``moving tents, plastic
sheeting, sanitation kits, the type of items you need, into
Macedonia and Albania,'' said Roy Williams, who directs disaster
relief for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the agency also sent additional disaster relief
teams to Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
