<HEADER>
A1322 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-WNBA-UNION-DRAFT-     03-31 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-UNION-DRAFT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA, UNION STILL AT ODDS ON 2 ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A minimum salary gap of $25,000 separates proposals from WNBA
players and the league, as collective bargaining negotiations draw
within 11 days of a league deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Agents confirmed that the players twice have reduced their
minimum-salary demand from $60,000 to the current proposal of
$45,000. The league is offering $20,000, a 33.3 percent increase
from 1998, when the salary range was $15,000 to $62,500 for all but
a handful of elite players with personal services contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The total salary difference between the two sides is between
$1.8 million and $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA officials have set an April 10 deadline for completion of
its first deal with the new players union, claiming that its
32-game season cannot begin on time past that date.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll never be a situation where there is a lockout,'' said
New York Liberty forward Rebecca Lobo, who has sat in on several
negotiating sessions. ``The season would be a week long.''
</P>
<P>
   All first-year WNBA players, including the Mercury's Jennifer
Gillom and player representative Michele Timms, must be re-signed.
Training camps are to open May 14, and the season kicks off June 10
for some of the league's 12 teams. The Mercury's first game is June
12.
</P>
<P>
   The other key issue is the absorption of players from the
defunct American Basketball League. The league essentially wants an
open door, asking for a limit of 52 ABL players, while the union
wants protection for current WNBA players and a limit of 24 ABL
players.
</P>
<P>
   ABL players earned an average of $80,000 for a 44-game season,
but without sufficient television or sponsor support, the league
survived less than 2{ seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues include creation of a 12th roster spot, health and
pension benefits and marketing rights.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA officials, including President Val Ackerman, are not
commenting publicly but do plan to allocate another player to each
of the two expansion teams Tuesday in conjunction with the
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   The allocated players almost certainly will be former ABL
players, with speculation centering on guard Shannon Johnson to the
Orlando Miracle and forward Katie Smith to the Minnesota Lynx. Both
formerly played for the two-time ABL champion Columbus Quest.
</P>
<P>
   If the sides cannot settle, the WNBA could attempt to play with
only former ABL players, if they would sign, and college draftees.
A more likely scenario is that a settlement will be reached for a
minimum salary of about $30,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
