<HEADER>
A1327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      03-31 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, April 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Two inches of snow fell in just one hour at Boise, Idaho, on
Wednesday, as the center of a cold, sprawling low pressure system
in the upper atmosphere drifted overhead. This slow system will
pose a variety of weather problems over the course of the next two
days across parts of the Rockies and Middle West.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, heavy, wet snow will fall across parts of northeast
Wyoming, southeast Montana and the western Dakotas as a jet stream
disturbance streaking northeast ahead of the sluggish upper-level
low causes low pressure to develop over eastern Nebraska. In turn,
moist, cold winds from the east-northeast on the northern flank of
the low will fuel a swath of snow. Snowfalls will be greatest on
high terrain, with a foot or more possible in the mountains of
northeast Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon, a second volley of moderate to heavy snow
will develop over parts of the same area as the sluggish
upper-level low follows on the heels of Thursday's system.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, clusters of showers and thunderstorms will develop
across parts of eastern Nebraska, Iowa, southern Minnesota and
eventually Wisconsin as increasingly moist winds from the south are
lifted by the Nebraska low and its associated warm front. A few of
the thunderstorms could approach severe levels, with hail and
strong winds possible in isolated spots.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms, a few with moderately heavy rains,
will develop from the eastern Carolinas to north Florida as a jet
stream disturbance and a pool of tropical moisture push slowly east
toward the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Rain Error
</P>
<P>
   The official rainfall measurements at San Francisco have been
erroneous for most of the current rainy season. During this decade,
many major cities around the nation have converted from human
observations to automated weather observing systems. The automated
gauge at San Francisco began reporting consistently low values for
rainfall during fall 1998. It is estimated that the reported
seasonal rainfall is about 25 percent too low. Now, the official
rainfall data must be carefully reconstructed so that
representative values can be archived at the National Climatic Data
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Extended Forecast For Thursday, April 1
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sunday: A push of polar air into the Northeast will
bring lower readings and mainly dry weather. Clouds and scattered
showers will mark the advance of cooler air into the Middle
Atlantic region. The Southeast will stay very warm and rather
humid. A disturbance moving across the southern Plains will trigger
strong thunderstorms in the Gulf states. Snow showers and chilly
conditions are likely across the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Tuesday: Cool air will reside over the Northeast as low
pressure in the Tennessee Valley is projected to pass through the
Carolinas. As a result, clouds and some rain will dampen the region
from the Ohio Valley to the Middle Atlantic states. The Southeast
will turn cooler, while the western Plains become brighter and
milder. A new disturbance moving into the Southwest will produce
clouds, cooler air and some showers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1837EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1330 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-HNS &LR;      03-31 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARFUL REFUGEES TRY TO HEAD OFF MILOSEVIC'S BRUTALITY BY FLEEING
SANDZAK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LAURA PETERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia _ They cluster outside the Sarajevo bus station
after descending from a row of tour buses, men standing in groups
and looking around expectantly, women sitting on overstuffed duffel
bags with their heads in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   They have all left their homes behind to escape the crusade of
brutality unleashed by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But these are not refugees from Kosovo. They are from the
Sandzak, another region of Yugoslavia with a deep Muslim tradition
that may be next in line to suffer the fate of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 7,000 Sandzaki refugees have arrived in Bosnia since last
Wednesday, bringing stories of beatings and murders by Serb
soldiers, forced conscription into the Yugoslav army, and tanks
massing outside their villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
   But having witnessed Serb attacks against fellow Muslims in
Bosnia and Kosovo over the past seven years, and the West's
apparent inability to stop it, the Sandzaki are trying to head
Milosevic off by escaping to Bosnia and talking about what they say
is happening in their homeland. Their region is split mainly
between the Yugoslav republics of Serbia and Montenegro, with
portions in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here because we are afraid of our Serbian neighbors,''
said Bjelak Latif. ``They are threatening us with death, and
Sarajevo is our only exit.'' He and his daughter traveled by bus to
Sarajevo from Prijepolje last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights abuses have been documented in the Sandzak ever
since Milosevic assumed power in Yugoslavia in 1989. The area takes
its name from the Turkish word ``sancak,'' or district, which it
inherited from the Ottoman Turks, who conquered the region from the
Eastern Orthodox Serbs and the Roman Catholic Croatians in the 15th
century. Over the centuries a number of Slavic families gave up
Christianity and adopted the religion of the conquerors, Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Before the three-year war between Muslim Bosnia and Serbia
erupted in 1992, roughly 54 percent of the Sandzak's 420,000 people
were Muslim. But since Milosevic rewrote the Yugoslav constitution
in 1992, Muslims have been denied constitutional status as an
ethnic minority.
</P>
<P>
   During the Bosnian war, Milosevic cracked down on the region in
order to quash burgeoning Muslim independence movements. The Serbs
removed Muslims from local governments and police forces, and
surrounded the Sandzak's principal city of Novi Pazar with tanks.
According to human rights organizations, Serb soldiers and police
embarked on a campaign of intimidation that included kidnapping,
murdering and assaulting hundreds of Muslims, often during random
house searches for weapons ostensibly stockpiled for secessionist
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Though some estimate that as many as 80,000 Muslims have fled
the Sandzak region since 1992, most have stayed put, reluctant to
leave the area's booming, Muslim-dominated shoe and
clothing-manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
   A recent repeat of the events of the Bosnian war, however, have
struck fear in many Sandzakis. Refugees arriving in Sarajevo say
tanks and troops are again building up around Novi Pazar, leading
them to fear that the Sandzak is the next frontier in Milosevic's
odyssey to cleanse Muslims from ancient Serbs lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Sandzaki, it's a pre-emptive flight. They're worried
because they see signs that they're next,'' said Wendy Rappaport,
Sarajevo spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is enough of a threat for these people to leave their
country and homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety increased in the region when Yugoslav soldiers began
rounding up Muslim men in the area Thursday to serve in the
military force Milosevic is mobilizing for the ground war against
NATO he anticipates over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Buses from the Sandzak region have reportedly been stopped at
the Bosnian border by Serb police who order men off at gunpoint.
One man who gave his name only as Alam said he escaped from the
army by faking sickness after he and other Muslims were beaten by
Serb soldiers and told that they would be placed on the front lines
without weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Though reports of abuse cannot be independently verified because
of the expulsions of truce monitors and journalists from
Yugoslavia, they match Milosevic's pattern of attacking ethnic
minorities to drum up support among Serb hard-liners in times of
stress such as the current NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the experience we've been having in the Balkans for
the past 10 years, and we had a very bitter experience here in
Bosnia,'' said Nudzeim Recica, the Bosnian government official who
oversees refugee issues.
</P>
<P>
   Recica said the Bosnian government is lobbying the international
community to monitor the situation in the Sandzak to ensure the
conflict doesn't spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tensions (in the Sandzak) are rising and I'm afraid something
drastic could happen, but we're praying it won't'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason fleeing Sandzakis have chosen Sarajevo as their
destination is its proximity to Bosnia, while Kosovars head mainly
to Macedonia and Albania, which they can reach by foot. Another
reason is the Sandzak's long historical and political ties to
Bosnia, the post-war population of which is overwhelmingly Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Few Sandzak refugees arriving in Bosnia have requested aid
because they are receiving shelter from family, friends or others
in Bosnia's Muslim community, Recica said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the aim of many Sandzaki refugees at the Sarajevo bus
station has been to enlist Bosnian Muslim politicians in supporting
the rights of Muslims in the Sandzak, a goal that, if reached,
could fan the flames of Milosevic's wrath even higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here because we want to make people aware of the
position of Muslim people in the Sandzak,'' said Fahrudin Mekic of
a Muslim political party with branches in Bosnia and Yugoslavia.
``We helped the Bosnian refugees when they came to Sandzak in 1992,
so we hope they will help us out now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
