<SLUG> BC-JONES-RELIGION-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIO PREACHER'S FRISCO CHURCH IS A BOOMING SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRISCO, Texas _ Deborah Griffith beamed. She had just left a
church service after hearing Chuck Swindoll, one of the most
popular radio preachers in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's great,'' said Griffith, a sculptor who recently
moved to Texas from New York. ``I've listened to him for years on
the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she and about 2,000 other people hear him in person each
Sunday at the Stonebriar Community Church, a remarkable new
congregation founded by Swindoll in October.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation, meeting in temporary quarters in the gymnasium
of Collin County Community College's Preston Ridge Campus, is being
referred to by some church-growth experts as an ``instant
megachurch.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary dirt work began this month on a 2,500-seat church
sanctuary on 60 acres of prime real estate in Frisco. And that $7
million project is just the first phase. Ultimately, several church
buildings, including a 6,000-seat sanctuary, are to be built on the
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a surprise; it's all a surprise. I never would have
guessed it,'' said Swindoll, who was born in El Campo, 75 miles
southwest of Houston. ``God is at work here, or this would not have
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a celebrated radio evangelist, Swindoll is
president of Dallas Theological Seminary. He is a prolific author,
and his ``Insight for Living'' programs, which began in 1997, are
broadcast 1,600 times daily on 400 radio stations worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds have been increasing at the new church each week. Those
lucky enough to get a seat plop down on white plastic lawn chairs
bought at Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love us at Wal-Mart,'' said Emily Edwards, an aide to
Swindoll. ``We just kept going back to buy more chairs. We've about
cleaned them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Kathy Seei, who has seen her town grow from 6,000 to
27,000 in the past 10 years, says Frisco welcomes the church. The
city has accelerated street projects to help the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have worse things happen to you than having 6,000
Christians coming to your city,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Swindoll, 64, has experience in building large churches. For 23
years, he was pastor of the First Evangelical Free Church in
Fullerton, Calif., which grew to 6,000 members under his
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But he emphasizes that the Texas church will have its own
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not interested in building a Fullerton, Calif., church in
Frisco, Texas,'' he said at a January town-hall meeting held to
discuss building plans.
</P>
<P>
   The newness of Swindoll's church will attract many, said Carol
Childress, communications director of Leadership Network, a Dallas
church-growth organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the new kid on the block,'' she said. ``The real question
will be three or four years from now. There will be a certain
amount of fallout. It's a normal thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She predicts success for Swindoll, though, because of his
popularity and his experience in creating churches in high-growth
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Swindoll's style attracted Jim Gunn of Plano to become a regular
attendee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck is real. He comes down to our level. He appeals to the
common man,'' said Gunn, who formerly drove to downtown Dallas to
attend First Baptist Church. ``He's not only a preacher, he's a
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Preaching is Swindoll's first love. When he accepted the
presidency of Dallas Theological Seminary in 1994, he told trustees
he ultimately would be pastor of a church, too. Seminary trustees
are supportive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically a pastor,'' Swindoll said during an interview at
his office on the seminary campus east of downtown Dallas. ``I love
what we are doing here at the seminary. But my world is a
practical, hands-on world. I try to help people who are hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   The phoenixlike church began springing up in mid-October when
admirers of Swindoll persuaded him to begin Wednesday-night Bible
studies in the club room of the Stonebriar Country Club in Frisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had 200 people show up the first night,'' Edwards said.
``That went to 400 the next week and doubled again the third
week.''
</P>
<P>
   The church advertised only once, and the attendance jumped from
1,100 to 2,000, said the Rev. Mark Dane, associate pastor. No more
advertising is expected until the church moves into larger
quarters, Dane said.
</P>
<P>
   Swindoll is an evangelical conservative who believes that the
Bible holds the answers to life. While strongly opposing abortion
and supporting many views of the Christian right, he pointedly
stays away from politics. He centers his preaching on everyday
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been criticized for not taking a higher profile in
political things,'' Swindoll said. ``But I've found that when you
mix church and politics, the politics will eventually take over and
eat you up.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's annual budget is $1.7 million, including five
full-time and four part-time employees, church officials said.
Swindoll said he chose not to receive a salary at this time.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
