<HEADER>
A1338 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-31 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTRODUCING ALEX RODRIGUEZ: NEW MARINERS OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (begin ital) News story, Jan 22, 2003: To avert another work
stoppage that this time threatened the entire 2003 season, major
league baseball owners and the players union reached an historic
agreement unprecedented in sports: The owners sold all franchises
to the players. (end ital).
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The idea had been whispered quietly for months, but
didn't really become a plan, according to outgoing commissioner Bud
Selig, until Yankee owner George Steinbrenner six weeks ago weighed
in on a conference call with chilling news.
</P>
<P>
   ``George said that after projecting revenues from the new
Amazon.com/Giuliani Stadium, as well as TV revenues from moving the
Yankee broadcasts to the Playboy Channel, it still didn't pencil
out,'' Selig said. ``We were all shaken. George had been the last
big-time holdout, and when he said he couldn't make money in
baseball, well, it didn't take long to conclude that nobody wanted
to be the last fool out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The key was secrecy: Any disclosure and the subsequent
controversy might have doomed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to rare cooperation from players' union chief Don
Fehr, who is succeeding Selig as commissioner, an ownership group
negotiated quietly with Fehr and Alex Rodriguez, the Seattle
Mariners' All-Star shortstop who became major league sports' first
player-owner last year.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the transfer of ownership was patterned after the
Seattle model of 2002, when Rodriguez became the first player whose
contractual worth exceeded the value of the franchise. The Seattle
owners, a group of billionaire high-tech executives who never
figured out how to make a profit despite a new public stadium and a
successful team, deeded over the franchise to Rodriguez rather than
give him a contract extension that exceeded the club's estimated
$200 million value.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Seattle model, in which the franchise was held
and operated in a blind trust so that Rodriguez would not vote on
ownership matters while a union member, the players will now have
full control of each team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have no one to blame but ourselves,'' said Rodriguez
at a press conference, although he admitted after questioning that
that very point was troublesome for many players. After years of
laying off prolonged slumps and 100-loss seasons to lousy
ownerships and poor management, many were fearful of having to
assume personal responsibility and be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them it wasn't a big deal,'' Rodriguez said. ``I said
we still have umpires, fans and the media.''
</P>
<P>
   What would seem to have been the most difficult issue, price,
was not a major stumbling block. Since all franchises were losing
money, thanks to soaring salaries, decline of broadcast revenues
and weather postponements of the last two World Series until
spring, nearly all ownerships were happy to receive merely the sum
of their net investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, some of the owners quite naturally wanted to get the
appreciated value,'' Selig said. ``We had some arguments, but the
fact that was irrefutable was that we were losing so much money
that we needed to dump this dog fast while we could come out
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fehr and Rodriguez considered waiting another year
until franchise values plummeted, but realized that timing was
important and the secret could not be kept.
</P>
<P>
   Financing the purchases was not a problem, either. Since the
takeover of world commerce by Microsoft in 2001, loans to large
entities such as the players union _ rated recently by the United
Nations Trade Commission as the world's 13th largest economy _ has
become easy. Fehr estimated that the players paid about 5 percent
down on the estimated $18 million collective purchase price.
Microsoft has its usual one-year balloon payment on the loan
balance, so the assumption is that major league baseball will
become absorbed into the Microsoft entertainment arm,
OpiatesForTheMasses.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior offered to pay the down himself,'' said Rodriguez,
laughing about his former teammate, Ken Griffey Jr. He said it was
hard to take the Los Angeles Dodgers center fielder seriously
because his recent purchase of Universal Studios left him a little
strapped.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was some concern on both sides about how the
federal government would react to such an unprecedented shift in
what was once the national pastime, the White House reacted swiftly
with approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball doesn't need owners; hey, I never needed one when I
was rasslin','' said President Jesse Ventura during his first press
conference following inauguration. ``The Dubya Dubya Eff did just
fine without 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `Play ball with ballplayers!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
