<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDESPREAD SHELLING DRIVES 10,000 MORE REFUGEES INTO ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-VUKOVAR,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES,
KOSOVO-SOLANA, KOSOVO-HACKERS, KOSOVO-AID, KOSOVO-CLINTON,
KOSOVO-ARMS, KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-SERBS-NY, KOSOVO-UPDATE,
KOSOVO-VATICAN) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Serbian forces are now shelling villages, towns
and cities across a wide swath of Kosovo, driving over 10,000 more
ethnic Albanians from their homes, refugees arriving here Wednesday
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Bombardment from tanks and mortars began in some areas around 9
p.m. Tuesday and continued Wednesday, refugees said. Villages and
towns were reported in flames in an arc surrounding the cities of
Prizren and Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees said they were from Pristina, the Kosovo capital,
the first large group to arrive here from the city. They reported
that the city was in flames, with widespread death and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels on Wednesday, Air Commodore David Wilby, a NATO
spokesman, said that a ``large number'' of refugees and some
separatist rebel troops were trapped in the Pagarusa valley, about
30 miles southwest of Pristina, where three brigades of Yugoslav
and Serb forces were ``raining artillery fire'' on them.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to confirm refugees' accounts, but there was a
stark difference in the appearance of the refugees who arrived in
Kukes on Wednesday from those who crossed the border on Tuesday,
having heeded Serbs' orders to leave or be killed.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the refugees seemed stunned, their faces frozen. On
Wednesday they look shattered, their faces contorted, many openly
weeping or on the verge of tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were driving down the street, all the shops and houses
were burning on both sides around us,'' said an elderly man aboard
one of three city buses packed with frightened people that arrived
Wednesday afternoon from Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombardment has been going on since yesterday,'' said
Gjergj Mertur, 33, from the door of the first bus from Djakovica.
``There are hundreds of dead people. The police and the
paramilitaries are burning the houses.''
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man driving a tractor pulling a cart full of
refugees, said that in Prizren ``they attacked at 9 o'clock in the
evening _ boom, boom _ they fired with many types of guns.''
</P>
<P>
   At the wheel of the next tractor, Zenel Kadashi said: ``All the
villages surrounding Prizren are burned down. On this tractor are
people from 10 different villages.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from Prizren and Djakovica said that in both cities,
Serbian forces had moved from military-style encampments and taken
shelter in factory buildings to avoid becoming targets of the NATO
air strikes. There have been similar reports from other areas of
the Serbs dispersing their men and equipment for cover in civilian
areas.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 o'clock Wednesday evening, 10,000 people had passed the
border crossing at Morini, according to figures compiled by the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, joining 84,600
since the crossing was opened on Saturday after being sealed for 11
months. About another 3,000 have managed to get over the border in
the rugged mountains northwest of here and are being assembled in
Kruma, Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, as rain began to fall, Albanian officials instituted a
new and cumbersome system of registering all refugees, who have
been routinely and methodically stripped of passports and all other
identity documents, and they processed only 200 in the space of an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   A long line of refugees, many of them on foot, was left
stretching back across the border into Serbian territory. Some
refugees estimated the length of the line at almost 10 miles.
Serbian officials asked the Albanians to please hurry up.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier in the day it was the Serbs who delayed the flow. It
has become the custom of the Serbian border guards, after a morning
of robbing refugees and unbolting their license plates, to close
the border at midday while they enjoy a long lunch, coming back to
work at 2.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Wednesday's refugees had been walking for three days
without food or water, they said. In some rural areas, people in
outlying hamlets went to a more central, larger village thinking
they would be safer there. One such gathering point was Rugova,
which took in people from a half dozen smaller places.
</P>
<P>
   But about 3 p.m. on Tuesday, the Serbs began shelling Rugova,
refugees from there said. They crossed the border during the night
and spent the dawn in an open field on the edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rugova doesn't exist anymore,'' said Hasan Hyesenan, 45, who
had been a history teacher in the school there.
</P>
<P>
   Hazar Shala, 53, added: ``They started a heavy bombardment at 3
o'clock. I was one of the last to leave. They fired with tanks and
afterward they burned the village.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the rural villagers said they had hoped to be able to
remain in their homes, perhaps because they were too isolated, and
perhaps because they had not been visited by Serbian forces giving
the orders to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have an ultimatum, but hearing the shelling we left
on our own,'' said Rakip Kryezim, 30. ``At the border they took our
money, cars and identity cards. They also took 15 of the best cars,
Golf, Renault, Mercedes.''
</P>
<P>
   Another man put in: ``The situation is very bad. We have nothing
with which to live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
