<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EMBASSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. EVICTS YUGOSLAV DIPLOMATS, CLOSES EMBASSY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENNIFER DAY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department closed the Yugoslav Embassy
here, evicting diplomatic personnel, some still clad in night
clothes, early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia declared it had severed diplomatic relations March 25
with the United States in response to NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, the United States notified Yugoslav officials that
under the Vienna Convention of 1961, which regulates diplomatic
relations, the Washington embassy had to be vacated by midnight
Tuesday, said Lee McClenny, a State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We followed our standard diplomatic practice for cases of
broken relations,'' he said, adding that Yugoslav officials were
informed that the embassy was to ``cease operations, vacate its
diplomatic premises and send home all personnel who are not part of
a future interests section.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Wedgwood, a senior fellow for the Council on Foreign
Relations, said it was a little strange that Yugoslav officials
wouldn't leave immediately after breaking off diplomatic relations,
but that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ``probably thought
he could have his cake and eat it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin said that although most
of the embassy's personnel have left the country, one Yugoslav
diplomat and a small support staff will remain with an ``embassy of
a protecting power.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements with another embassy, which under the Vienna
Convention would protect both Yugoslavia's national interests and
property, have not been made yet.
</P>
<P>
   Reports indicate that China is interested in serving as a
``protecting power,'' but the Vienna Convention states that the
third-party country chosen would have to be acceptable to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, McClenny said, the United States will not
disturb any documents or property left inside the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. will respect and protect the properties without
prejudice to the eventual settlement of property issues among all
the successor states to the former Yugoslavia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The former nations of the old Yugoslav union have been fighting
over assets such as embassies since its breakup in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia had refused to turn over diplomatic missions and joint
financial accounts, but the takeover of the embassy may free that
property in Washington for settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Similar embassy closings occurred after the Iranian revolution
in 1979 and the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
