u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      03-31 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS SEEN IN PATRIOTS STADIUM PROJECT STALEMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Mass. _ After weeks of stalemate, there may be
progress here in clearing the proposed stadium site for the New
England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Governor John G. Rowland Wednesday said the power
plant standing in the way of the $374 million project is a step
closer to moving.
</P>
<P>
   However, both sides said they did not believe a final agreement
assuring the steam producer's relocation would be in place by
Friday, the deadline by which the state must provide a status
report to team owner Robert Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft is not convinced the open-air stadium can be built
along the Connecticut River by 2002, he can pull out of the deal
within the next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the steam plant quickly is critical to that time frame
because the location would need to be cleaned and ready for
construction by next spring to meet the 2002 date.
</P>
<P>
   A Patriots spokesman declined to comment on the news, other than
to say, ``We're waiting to see and review the reports that we
expect to get on Friday and then we'll take the time we need to
review those reports.''
</P>
<P>
   Some skeptics said privately they expected Rowland to say,
before the deadline, that progress had been made, to avoid a public
relations disaster surrounding an issue that has won him national
attention, for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the governor's office said CTG Resources Inc., the
owner of the power plant, had become more flexible in its
negotiations with the Connecticut Resources Recovery Authority, the
nearby quasi-public agency that is trying to replace the need for
the steam plant.
</P>
<P>
   With talks stalled for weeks, CTG seems more willing to accept
some of the environmental responsibility for the contaminated site
and seems more agreeable to some tax issues.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if a deal to move the steam plant succeeds, another
major problem looms: Moving CTG's corporate headquarters, which
also sit on the proposed stadium site.
</P>
<P>
   CTG's chief executive Arthur Marquardt has said the company
wants $48 million to replace the 1960s building, but experts
working for Rowland have insisted that figure is too high.
</P>
<P>
   Connecituct business leaders have pledged as much as $25 million
in private donations to help defray the moving costs for the
headquarters building. None of the $374 million in funding approved
by the General Assembly in December would pay for clearing the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland met with about 20 other business leaders in the state
Capital Wednesday, reportedly to ask them for additional monetary
help.
</P>
<P>
   But after the meeting, which increasingly skeptical local
reporters were calling a ``death watch,'' the governor said he had
asked for no such thing. Rather, he requested aid in the form of
in-kind help, such as donations of free legal work and loan
guarantees, to help defray costs.
</P>
<P>
   And with a University of Connecticut poll showing public support
for the project sagging, he also asked the executives to get out
and trumpet the civic and economics benefits of a downtown stadium
_ effectively a not so-subtle pressure campaign for CTG to move
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   While it is still unclear how moving the corporate headquarters
would be fully paid for, a spokeswoman for CTG said the company was
now willing to consider other less-expensive relocation sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're much more optimistic,'' said CTG spokeswoman Lynn
Blackwell, adding that the company has ``moderated our position. .
. . The point is, we're flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   That position is a change from earlier this month, when
Marquardt and Rowland held dueling press conferences criticizing
each other and saying negotiations were going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides seem to be communicating much better now,''
Blackwell said. ``Sometimes a deadline will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching an agreement by Friday ``would be pretty optimistic,
but anything can happen,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said significant progress was made over the last two
days and that the report will be delivered on time to Kraft.
``They've been briefed,'' Rowland said of the Patriots owners.
``And it looks as if they may be opening an office here soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure is not an option. The Patriots will be playing in
Hartford.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
