<P>
   &UR; web site http://cns.jrn.columbia.edu/ &LR;  This week's stories:
</P>
<P>
   ACUPUNCTURE FACE-LIFTS _ Acupuncture, the 5,000-year-old Chinese
healing practice, is used in the United States not only for
preventing and treating diseases, relieving pain and anesthetizing
patients for surgery, but also for face-lifts.
</P>
<P>
   AUCTIONS _ While on-line auctions have become the World Wide
Web's latest big thing, with such sites as eBay and Auction Auction
holding 24-hour global sales of everything from jewelry to
jukeboxes, the public auction is here to stay. From the community
event of a farm equipment and livestock sale to hushed art
offerings at Sotheby's on Manhattan's Upper East Side, millions of
people still buy and sell the old-fashioned way. According to the
National Auctioneers Association, 17,000 auctioneers sell an
average $162 billion of merchandise yearly.
</P>
<P>
   BAGPIPES _ Above the wail of the bagpipes, the sharp roll of the
snare drums and the silent march of sneakered feet, there is the
faint but unmistakable smell of garbage. It is the minor
inconvenience the New York City Department of Sanitation's bagpipe
band puts up with when practicing for several St. Patrick's Day
parades coming up. But for the band, whose members ordinarily spend
their days navigating a massive Staten Island landfill or operating
mechanical street sweepers, the cavernous sanitation truck garage
on the shores of the East River seems a fitting practice locale.
</P>
<P>
   BLUES _ Scott Sharrard takes the stage at Terra Blues in
Manhattan. At 22, he hardly resembles a veteran blues man. His
scanty brown goatee does not hide his fair complexion. Yeah,
Sharrard is white. But so are most of the people in the audience.
And judging from the way the crowd is swaying at the Greenwich
Village club, Sharrard can play the blues.
</P>
<P>
   CLOCKS _ Digital displays counting down the seconds to the year
2000 are cropping up faster than you can say Y2K. Countdown clocks
can be found everywhere from Times Square in New York City to the
Eiffel Tower in Paris to the desktops of computer programmers
trying to solve the millennium computer problem. But the cottage
industry that has sprung up as a result of this fascination with
the year 2000 is counting something else _ dollars.
</P>
<P>
   DATING _ A New York-based organization is playing Cupid for the
mentally retarded. The National Institute for People With
Disabilities, the largest nonprofit of its kind in the state, is
introducing a program to teach mentally retarded people dating
skills _ and then let them mingle with potential partners.
</P>
<P>
   MORMONS _ The Mormon church is taking root in Harlem. Last
November, the Mormon congregation of Harlem moved into its own
small church and membership is growing. The Church of Jesus Christ
of Latter-day Saints, as the church is officially known, did not
even allow black men to attain the priesthood until 1978. But
Harlem is one of the communities here where the church is growing
the most quickly.
</P>
<P>
   TOKEN GARB _ A clothing company, Straphanger Designs, has put
out its new line of ``subway chic'' casualwear. The buttons and
snaps in each of the shirts are authentic ``Y-cut'' subway tokens,
direct from the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUAL _ A new technology promising high quality audio and
video on PC's may one day bring scripts shunned by Hollywood to
people at home, complete with a virtual cast, and any musician will
be able to have music performed on computer-constructed
instruments. These are the scenes painted by visionary engineers
and analysts about the MPEG-4, a small ripple in the growing tide
of computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   WEDDINGS _ Increasingly, African-Americans are embracing what is
now called Afrocentric weddings for reasons that range from the
symbolic to the aesthetic to the cultural.
</P>
