<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC AUCTIONS: STAYING ONCE, STAYING TWICE, HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By DAVID BERNARD  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From a raised lectern in a hardware-cluttered
workroom, Tom Perillo glared out over the hundred or so men waiting
for a piece of the action. Time to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirtythreehundred, thirtythreeyeah, thirtyfourthirtyfour
too-slow,'' Perillo sang out. Burly, hard-handed contractors
nodded, raised fingers, and flashed numbered cards with surprising
grace and speed. Perillo seemed to need another pair of arms to
signal each bidder. ``Fortythreesir. Now fortyfour yes-or-no,
yes-or-no? Fortythreehundred I've-got-it-now, sold! At
fortythreehundred to buyer number seven-four-nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Perillo had unloaded a floor-to-ceiling rack of sheet metal
before the second hand of his watch hit 60. The next item, enough
fasteners to fill a truck, moved even quicker. Piece by piece, the
mild-mannered, business-suited auctioneer sold off a Bronx
metalworking and roofing company _ $95,000 worth of materials,
power tools, and heavy machinery _ in under four hours.
</P>
<P>
   While on-line auctions have become the World Wide Web's latest
big thing, with such sites as eBay and Auction Auction holding
24-hour global sales of everything from jewelry to jukeboxes, the
public auction is here to stay. From the community event of a farm
equipment and livestock sale to hushed art offerings at Sotheby's
on Manhattan's Upper East Side, millions of people still buy and
sell the old-fashioned way. According to the National Auctioneers
Association, 17,000 auctioneers sell an average $162 billion of
merchandise yearly.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Despite the convenience of an on-line auction,
nothing compares to the retail theater of a live event. At
Perillo's auction, even the company's former owner, retiring after
50 years, watched the show. ``It's not sad at all,'' said Leonard
Kent of Pelham, N.Y., who attended with his wife Jan. ``I have a
lot of interest in what things go for.''
</P>
<P>
   The public auction also offers an in-person look at the
merchandise. ``You want to kick the tires. You get a total view,''
said Dennis Hado, a New Jersey machinery dealer. Hado visits
auctions to hear what people will pay for used equipment. He's
usually surprised _ as he was when an industrial press he'd valued
at $18,000 went for double that price.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really no bargains at auctions,'' Hado said. ``People
get auction fever and they're hoping to win the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Rittenhouse, a plumbing contractor from Quakertown, Pa.,
added, ``You got to know what you got going in. [Most people] get
it in their minds they want it, they'll go home thinking they got a
good deal whether they did or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Most auctiongoers disagree. Tom O'Donoghue, a metalworker from
Mount Vernon, N.Y., insisted he had not only beaten the market
price on a drill press and several other items, but also purchased
quality in the sturdy old hardware. ``You can't buy that anymore.
If you can't buy it, it's a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Other advantages of the public auction include the efficiency of
a one-day sale; the thrill of live, competitive bidding; and, of
course, the auctioneer's chant, a way to move a lot of property in
a little time that no computer scoreboard can rival. ``That's
something that can't be duplicated,'' Perillo said.
</P>
<P>
   As the most memorable aspect of the auction, the chant has,
fairly or unfairly, stereotyped the auctioneer. ``So many people
have this image of the auctioneer as rural, wearing a cowboy hat,
who talks fast,'' said Holly Neuman, director of publications for
the National Auctioneers Association. A good auctioneer, she said,
is also a skilled businessman, or businesswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good career for someone who wants to be fairly
independent,'' she said. ``You own your own business, set your own
hours, and can earn a lot of money doing it. Plus it's a family
atmosphere.'' Many in the business today follow in the steps of a
parent or grandparent.
</P>
<P>
   If Dad wasn't an auctioneer, though, an aspiring bid-caller can
still learn the ropes at auction school. The Missouri Auction
School in St. Joseph, Mo., founded in 1905, is the oldest and
largest. Six hundred students a year attend the school's nine-day
course to earn the 85 credit hours some states require for
licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Classes are diverse, said K Talbot, assistant to the president.
``Small towns, big towns, they come from overseas. Doctors,
lawyers, judges, we've had a nun. These are not farmers and
hick-town people.''
</P>
<P>
   For $625, the school Newsweek dubbed ``the Harvard of
auctioneering'' teaches practical business, product knowledge, and
yes, public speaking. Under the instruction of state champion
bid-callers, students develop a patter through the use of ``filler
words'' _ any word that isn't a price _ tongue twisters, and smooth
elocution. Homework includes nightly practice at Kansas City
auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Students don't compete against each other, Ms. Talbot said. They
just better themselves. ``They don't have to be fast. They just
have to be clear.'' Overcoming stage fright is not an issue at the
school. ``If you're scared of that,'' she said, ``you're in the
wrong profession.''
</P>
<P>
   For graduates, though, the job is guaranteed to splash into
their personal life. ``It's a novelty, not like accountants or
attorneys,'' Tom Perillo said. ``People always want to you talk
fast, or sell something. They try and become an auctioneer
instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: David Bernard is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1903EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
