<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1357 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-BLUES &LR;      03-31 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BLUES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE BOYS SING BLUES: NEW GENERATION REINVENTS TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By MICHAEL SANDLER  
 c.1999 COLUMBIA NEWS SERVICE  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scott Sharrard takes the stage at Terra Blues in
Manhattan. At 22, he hardly resembles a veteran blues man. His
scanty brown goatee does not hide his fair complexion.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Sharrard is white. But so are most of the people in the
audience. And judging from the way the crowd is swaying at the
Greenwich Village club, Sharrard can play the blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blues is really your love,'' said Sharrard, the lead
vocalist and guitarist for the Chesterfields, a three-piece blues
and R&AMP;B band from Milwaukee. ``It's your voice. It's got nothing to
do with race.''
</P>
<P>
   A few miles north of the club, one longtime music producer says
that while white guitar players have plenty of talent, they will
never understand the roots of blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't play it because they haven't lived it,'' said Bobby
Robinson, a music producer in Harlem who has been recording blues
artists in New York for nearly 60 years, including the legendary
Elmore James. The crowd hanging around his store, Bobby's House of
Music on Eighth Avenue, echoed this sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not stopped a growing number of fans from plunking
down cash and credit cards for CDs by white blues musicians. In the
past few years, blues music has enjoyed a major resurgence and
crossed over to pop charts. New York club owners report larger
crowds at blues shows. House of Blues, a mega restaurant and
merchandise corporation, has spread to six cities. The franchise
has hotels in Chicago and Las Vegas and its own music label.
</P>
<P>
   While the blues were originated by black sharecroppers singing
about hard times, today's two hottest blues stars are young and
white. Both musicians are being marketed to an audience younger _
and whiter _ than the legendary Delta could ever have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Take Kenny Wayne Shepherd, a 22-year-old guitar player from
Louisiana. His second CD, ``Trouble Is...,'' went platinum and was
named Blues Album of the Year by Guitar World Magazine, which also
named him its Blues Artist of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Or consider Jonny Lang, an 18-year-old whiz from Fargo, N.D. His
debut CD, ``Lie To Me'', went platinum in 1996 when he was just 15.
His current release, ``Wander This World,'' was No. 1 on Billboard
magazine's blues chart, No. 109 overall and has sold more than
412,000 copies since its October release.
</P>
<P>
   These young musicians are reaching new audiences. And in some
stores, their CDs are found in new sections _ easy listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think young people are more hip to it,'' said Duggins King,
a part-owner of Terra Blues, which features live blues seven nights
each week. ``I think it is becoming a lot more in the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   And while both Lang and Shepherd win praise for their guitar
playing, the blond lads also have sex appeal that promoters have
been quick to market. Vanity Fair photographed the pair for its
January 1999 issue. The black-and-white glossy of Shepherd shows
him lying outdoors, his long dirty blond mane mussed in the grass.
Lang gets two pages where he looks more like a J Crew model than
America's No. 1 blues artist. Think Hanson. Think the Gap, for whom
Lang played a riff on a TV ad. Both musicians have Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish well for any artist,'' said Clarence Spady, 35, a
Pennsylvania blues guitarist who is black. ``But to give Jonny Lang
a blues riff in a Gap commercial? How many Gap commercials have you
seen Johnny Copeland in? Today, when people come to see a blues
band, they expect to see a zoot suit. The record companies are
really playing a marketing game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gap is a long way from the Mississippi Delta where Robert
Johnson and Charlie Patton helped found this innovative sound in
the 1920s and 30s. It was the music of sharecroppers during the
Depression. They sang hard-luck stories about women who done them
wrong. Many lamented the racism of the day. Some of the saddest
songs were written from prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know guys who earned 50 cents a day-half a dollar a day!''
said Robinson, who as a child listened to the original blues men in
South Carolina of the 1930s. ``These guys came up with a rough
time. Sharecroppers on cotton farms. They had no money and they had
to do something on Saturday night.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s Chuck Berry incorporated the roots of blues into a
style now known as rock-n-roll, and Sam Cooke and Marvin Gaye
blended it into soul and R&AMP;B in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, white musicians sang the blues long before Shepherd,
Lang and Sharrard were born. Elvis Presley used it to jumpstart his
career. Eric Clapton and Jeff Beck updated the sound in the 1970s
by using slow, pronounced guitar strokes. And the late Stevie Ray
Vaughan added a raw style of guitar that crossed over to white
fans.
</P>
<P>
   With these white artists, the guitar _ not the singer _ became
the dominant element of the blues. Purists insist the blues must be
sung. But superstar Kenny Wayne Shepherd doesn't even sing on his
CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are guitar players,'' said Bill Sims, 50, a blues
singer and musician who is black and has been playing blues since
the age of four. ``The audience became predominantly white. For me,
the blues has always been a vocal tradition of what is around
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Most musicians agree that rap music is the new blues. And once
again, the voice is the vehicle. Today's stars still sing about
racism and women, but they also criticize the new hard times in the
inner city. Robinson added rap artists to his list in 1979 with
groups like the Funky Four and Treacherous Three. With the
exception of the Beastie Boys, few white artists have sustained
lasting rap careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rap music is in the tradition of the blues,'' said Sims,
who was turned on to the music by his four children. ``They are
talking about the blues, about hard times.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharrard concurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rap is about oppression,'' said Sharrard, a rap fan. But
``blues is about pure human suffering and it does not have to be
black or white. It is American music. It belongs to all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Michael Sandler is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
