<HEADLINE>
THE END IS NEAR AND THAT'S GOOD FOR BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By BRAD FOSS  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Digital displays counting down the seconds to the
year 2000 are cropping up faster than you can say Y2K. Countdown
clocks can be found everywhere from Times Square in New York City
to the Eiffel Tower in Paris to the desktops of computer
programmers trying to solve the millennium computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   But the cottage industry that has sprung up as a result of this
fascination with the year 2000 is counting something else _
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going very well,'' says John Leung, president of
the Acimex Corporation of Northfield, Ill. Leung anticipated that
American companies would be interested in millennium promotional
products two years ago, when he began importing countdown products
from the Far East. Today he buys thousands of mass-produced key
chain clocks, watches and calculators, affixes a company logo and
resells them to clients such as ADP and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good idea,'' Leung said, ``even though it is not really
the millennium.'' Technically, the new millennium does not begin
until 2001, but that makes little difference to those cashing in on
calendrical fever.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Levitt, president of Philadelphia-based Data Display
Systems, plans to spend New Year's on a quiet beach. Nevertheless,
like other countdown clock manufacturers, he is enjoying the
booming business while it lasts. His company sells $15 desktop
clocks as well as more expensive, larger displays to retailers,
like Bloomingdale's. ``This is one of the biggest events ever in
the way of promotions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomingdale's, for instance, has 20-foot-long clocks on display
outside its stores to promote gifts priced from $5 to $95 that
include T-shirts, hats, hair clips and, of course, miniature
countdown clocks. JC Penney, Macy's and other retailers offer
similar products.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Postal Service, which purchased 8,000
eye-catching countdown clocks from Data Display Systems, is using
them to advertise its ``Celebrate the Century'' stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch handed out countdown clocks last year during a
conference it sponsored to examine the various industries that
would be affected by the year 2000. None of the company's analysts,
it turns out, specifically monitors digital clock manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 is not a huge money maker for all clock
manufacturers. Franklin Instrument Company of Warminster, Pa., says
millennial countdown clocks are only a fraction of its overall
business, which consists primarily of developing clocks and timers
for schools, drug companies and the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's just another date,'' Larry Fischer, vice president
of sales at Franklin, said of the turn of the century. ``But I
guess as a public service or a novelty, the millennium is a big
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Franklin recently sold a customized 2-foot-long timepiece with
5-inch digits to an ABC-News affiliate in Tampa, Fla., for $600.
But the company hopes that before too long it can land a multiple
clock order like its competitor Data Display Systems. ``I'm
disappointed that we didn't get to bid on the government
contract,'' Fischer said of the lucrative postal service deal.
</P>
<P>
   A.H. Greenwald, 54, a mail handler at the 112th Street post
office in New York City, says customers have told him that the
millennial countdown clock in the lobby is incorrect. ``Someone
said the clock is off,'' he said. Nevertheless, Greenwald is so
used to the rapid-fire backward counting that he has become
proficient at reading the large digital display as a regular
timepiece.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the model, once the clocks finish counting
backwards, they will either function as regular clocks that count
hours, seconds and minutes or as digital calendars that mark
months, days and years.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the days are numbered for digital clock
manufacturers and retailers, who realize that no matter how good
business may seem today, all the fuss will be over in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   This comes as a relief to Adrienne Casco, 31, a graphic designer
at Bernard Hodis Advertising in San Francisco. Casco says the large
digital displays are disconcerting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one outside of Macy's is constantly ticking,'' she said.
``It's kind of nuts. I feel like I'm going to blow up.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Brad Foss is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
