<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BAGPIPES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANITATION WORKERS PLACE MUSIC IN A DIFFERENT BAG 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ANDREAS TZORTZIS  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Above the wail of the bagpipes, the sharp roll of the
snare drums and the silent march of sneakered feet, there is the
faint but unmistakable smell of garbage.
</P>
<P>
   It is the minor inconvenience the New York City Department of
Sanitation's bagpipe band puts up with when practicing for parades.
But for the band, whose members ordinarily spend their days
navigating a massive Staten Island landfill or operating mechanical
street sweepers, the cavernous sanitation truck garage on the
shores of the East River seems a fitting practice locale.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's nice, we march out on the pier, with the beautiful
yachts and water,'' said the band's president, Jim Moran. ``When
the weather outside is bad, we march up and down rows of sanitation
trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   From the quietest hamlet to the busiest metropolis, the powerful
cacophony of bagpipe music is wont to sound on any holiday marked
by a parade, traditionally from a police or fire department
ensemble. But in New York City, where the department of sanitation
wears uniforms and features a hockey team and a resident artist who
crafts art out of garbage, it's almost a foregone conclusion that
the department's employees should form a bagpipe band to join the
city's police officers and firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to kill me to hire a band,'' said Dennis Diggins, the
band's pipe sergeant, and the lead soloist. ``We have 7,000
uniformed members. For us not to have a bagpipe band, to me, was
blasphemy.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Moran assembled 15 pipers and drummers in 1993, all of whom
had no idea how to play. It took the sage instruction of
ex-sanitation department employee and pipe playing veteran Danny
Sprague to get the group ready for its first gig: the Emerald
Society's annual dinner in April, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped get us over the wall.'' Diggins said of Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   Since those awkward first two years, the band has been building
a reputation. Last year, the now 30-piece ensemble, which includes
one woman, played at Shea Stadium, in parades all over New York on
Memorial Day, and for John Glenn's ticker-tape celebration on Fifth
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have in a very short time shown themselves to be full of
beautiful hot air,'' said Paula Young, a spokeswoman for the
sanitation department. ``They certainly do show that we are strong
and proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from New York City's three uniformed departments, a host
of state and city agencies and groups also have bagpipe bands. The
large number is indicative of the instrument's popularity, which
has rocketed over the past 20 years, according to Jock Nesbit, the
owner of the Pipers Cove in New Jersey, a store carrying Scottish
and Celtic items.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old Scottish immigrant has been playing the bagpipes
since he was 10. He has owned the Piper's Cove _ where a full St.
Patrick's Day kilt set rents for $110 a day _ for 20 years and has
seen business expand with the popularity of the instrument.
Recently, he compiled a list of local bands in the metropolitan
area and discovered the number has climbed from 10 to 80 since the
late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Nesbit attributes the growth to the burgeoning Irish population
in New York City. But Judy Collins' recording of ``Amazing Grace''
probably didn't hurt either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they want a piper when somebody dies,'' he said.
``They want to be buried to the sound of Amazing Grace. ''
</P>
<P>
   For band members, making a connection with an Irish heritage is
interesting, but not crucial. Other than becoming a member of the
Emerald Society, a city organization that celebrates Irish culture,
there is no requirement that band members be of Irish descent.
</P>
<P>
   Pipers must pay for their own bagpipes, which start at $1,000,
and drummers for their own drums. The group's board of directors
organizes fund-raising drives to cover the costs of kilts, reeds
and instructors, which sometimes climb to $25,000, Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid success the band has experienced has a lot to do with
the time its members put in, Sprague said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy because they put so much into it,'' he said.
``They meet extra days a week. There was never a time when I
thought they'd never make it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The band practices once a week together, but many of the pipers
and drummers take private lessons on the side. The pipers also
bring their brand of Irish and Scottish culture home to their
living rooms and basements.
</P>
<P>
   But their neighbors and spouses alike were glad to hear that, to
become a successful piper, band members must first practice on the
long-stemmed recorder known as the chanter, Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those chanters probably saved a couple of marriages,'' said
Mark O'Brien, 46, who would play in the basement at work and move
to the roof when it got too loud.
</P>
<P>
   Above all else, polishing their skills and performing is
important to the members because they see their band as a way to
dispel a stereotype of the New York sanitation worker as
uncultured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive image,'' said Dennis Shock, a union
representative for the sanitation workers by day and band member by
night. ``People see that we're not just sanitation, we're people
who play pipes and do other things.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Andreas Tzortzis is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
