<HEADLINE>
DATING SERVICE FOR THE MENTALLY RETARDED 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired. (EDITORS: In graph 4, Bobra is correct.)   
 By ALISSA LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For mentally retarded people, dating can be an
insurmountable challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Their acquaintances are typically limited to housemates,
co-workers or people they meet at day habilitation facilities. Not
only is their pool of potential partners constricted, but they
sometimes lack the social skills necessary to successfully develop
romantic relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a New York-based organization is playing Cupid. The
National Institute for People With Disabilities, the largest
nonprofit of its kind in the state, is introducing a program to
teach mentally retarded people dating skills _ and then let them
mingle with potential partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person's sexuality is a human right,'' said Bobra Fyne, who
developed the program, ``the same as the right to breathe and eat,
and we'll support that.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit organization, commonly referred to by its previous
name, the Young Adult Institute, provides support services for more
than 12,000 mentally retarded individuals in New York City, Nassau,
Suffolk, Westchester, Rockland, Orange and Sullivan counties.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency's clients were largely on their own when it came
to romance. And that led to frustration and hurt feelings. Fyne
recalled an instance when someone in the agency joined a dating
service and was continually turned down by non-retarded women.
``That's the disappointment we don't want people to have,'' Fyne
said.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles that mentally retarded people face in their love
lives may get considerable attention soon. The new film ``The Other
Sister,'' starring Juliette Lewis, tells the story of a ``slightly
retarded young woman'' who finds love and etches out a life for
herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Hollywood to acknowledge that people with a disabilities
need to date is unbelievable,'' said Pat Sutherland-Cohen, who
supervises the new dating program.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called ``You And I,'' came about after seven months
of discussions among agency staff. Applicants must have a standing
relationship with the agency, be capable of consenting to sexual
relations, and have three letters of recommendation confirming that
they do not exhibit behavior potentially harmful to others.
</P>
<P>
   After satisfying those criteria, the person schedules an
interview with a program volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid disappointment and frustration, the staff strives to
ensure that ``everyone is on the same page _ looking for a
potential companion,'' though not necessarily a sexual
relationship, Fyne said. The organizers weed out people who are
merely looking for ``brunch dates,'' she explained. People who
answer with statements like, ``I want to be somebody's soul mate''
and ``I want to find the right person to share my life with,'' are
prime candidates for the service.
</P>
<P>
   After passing the initial screening process, program members
attend skill-building socials. At the first one, held last month,
about 30 people participated in activities intended to maximize
interaction, such as a scavenger hunt, picking conversation
starters from a bowl of prepared questions and finding someone with
whom they had ``three things in common.''
</P>
<P>
   At the socials, agency staff teach classes that address topics
as serious as preventing sexually transmitted diseases and as light
as 101 places to go on a date. Participants also learn dating
basics, such as making sure they leave the house with money, who to
call when in danger and how to walk away from a potentially
hazardous situation.
</P>
<P>
   While the staff does not play ``matchmaker,'' they do try to
offer encouragement and suggestions to the inexperienced
participants. At the first meeting, one woman finally had the
chance to talk to the man she had had a crush on for the past year,
Fyne said.
</P>
<P>
   Program leaders don't know yet if any love connections were
made, but they did see people exchanging numbers. ``It went 1,000
times better than I expected,'' Fyne said. ``I really thought we
would have to work much harder as staff to make sure people were
mingling.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``You and I'' is clearly serving a need, there are plenty
of mentally retarded couples within the agency that have found each
other without the help of a dating program. Larry Weiss, a
51-year-old Manhattan native has been dating Elaine Bernstein, 52,
for 19 years. The couple, both mildly mentally retarded, met while
living together in a group home in Astoria, Queens. Now on separate
floors of a group home on East 36th Street in Manhattan, the couple
do laundry every Friday, watch television and visit each other's
families during the holidays. On the weekends, they venture out
into the Murray Hill section of Manhattan to find a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Elaine wouldn't speculate. But Larry had
definite ideas.
</P>
<P>
   After almost two decades, ``as far as marriage,'' Larry said,
``I'm ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Alissa Leibowitz is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
