<HEADER>
A1361 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-MORMONS &LR;      03-31 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-MORMONS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MORMONS BRANCH OUT IN HARLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By TANYA WEINBERG  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Freckle faced, smiling, and with his brown hair
freshly clipped, Shawn Warren looked like he just stepped out of a
Norman Rockwell painting on a recent Saturday afternoon. But the
wide concrete sidewalk was part of a New York City landscape,
complete with boxy housing projects. In midtown Manhattan, he said,
he'd be lucky if one person stopped to hear what he had to say as a
Mormon missionary. But he likes approaching passers-by in this
neighborhood. This is Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Warren, 20, is from Provo, Utah, and prone to calling things he
likes ``neat.'' In navy suit and a name tag, he walked up to three
middle-aged black men who chatted along a wire fence outside the
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, how you guys doin'?'' he asked, broadening his smile.
</P>
<P>
   The men stopped their conversation and each in turn took
Warren's extended hand in greeting. He introduced himself as Elder
Warren and told them he had an important message about Jesus
Christ, a message that would strengthen families.
</P>
<P>
   The men did not interrupt, but politely declined to make an
appointment for another day. Warren told them to call the number on
the church's television commercials if they changed their minds or
wanted a free video, Bible or Book of Mormon.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed and another round of handshaking and smiles
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell Karl Malone to get out of Utah and come play for the
Knicks!'' one of the men joked, calling after Warren.
</P>
<P>
   The Mormon Church's taking root in Harlem may seem as
incongruous as the presence of an eager, young man from Utah. But
last November, the Mormon congregation of Harlem moved into its own
small church and membership is growing. The Church of Jesus Christ
of Latter-day Saints, as the church is officially known, did not
even allow black men to attain the priesthood until 1978. But
Harlem is one of the communities here where the church is growing
the most quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Race is an issue for Warren and his partner missionary, or
``companion,'' Robert Ferguson as they preach the gospel to the
black and Hispanic residents of Central and East Harlem. They have
been shouted at on the streets, called ``cracker'' and ``white
devils,'' and they encounter people who say the Mormon Church is
racist. But over all, they say, they are received warmly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the graciousness and cultural hospitality that you will
find in most black communities around the country,'' said the Rev.
Raphael Warnock, assistant pastor of Harlem's Abyssinian Baptist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Warnock said he was aware of Mormon evangelism in Harlem: ``I'm
suspicious of it, quite honestly.'' He said that most white
churches have some racist history and the Mormon Church once had
explicitly racist policies.
</P>
<P>
   But the church denies any racism and points to recent growth in
Africa and South America. Since the early 1980s the Mormon Church
has doubled its membership to more than 10 million. The church does
not keep statistics based on race, a spokesman said, but it has
noticed growth in urban, multi-ethnic neighborhoods in the United
States. Roughly half of the growth in the New York area is among
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The church sends about 60,000 people, most of them young men on
a two-year mission, and some women, to 160 nations or territories.
Stationed in the metropolitan area, Warren and Ferguson rotate
through different neighborhoods and will spend only a few months in
Harlem. ``It's kind of like going to a foreign country,'' said
Ferguson, 20. He said he loved the people he had met, but he missed
the mountains of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday services the congregation meets in the small building
acquired from the Jehovah's Witnesses. For a year before the move,
they met in the banquet rooms of Sylvia's Restaurant, famous for
its soul food. The congregation's president, Ron Anderson, who is
white, introduced two guest speakers, who were white, to the 53
mostly black congregants.
</P>
<P>
   Frank McCallister, a member of the church high council,
illustrated a talk on self-reliance with anecdotes about growing up
in Happy Valley, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Fanny Wells, 42, who grew up in the Bronx and lost her husband
in a shooting, was baptized into the church the week before, along
with her five of her children. At the service they became full
members. Four white men and one of the president's two black
counselors, or assistants, put their hands upon her head and called
upon the Holy Spirit to enter her body.
</P>
<P>
   Before Christmas, Wells had nearly been evicted from her
apartment. When an agency came to her rescue, she credited God.
Wells called the Mormons after seeing the television ad offering a
free Bible. She knew nothing about the church. After the
missionaries came to her apartment a number of times to teach her
about the church, she decided to join. ``I'm looking for a better
life, a happy life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After services the men and women broke off into separate groups.
Brenda Woods, one of the leaders of the Women's Relief Society,
searched the hymnbook for a song people knew. She had little luck
and the women had trouble following the tune she picked.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who is black, said things would have to change for the
branch to prosper. Church officials said that they wanted people
from the community to run the Harlem branch themselves but that the
membership was not ready. Although average attendance has doubled
to 60 in the last year, almost all the members are new to the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' husband, Van, is one of the church counselors and the son
of Sylvia, of Sylvia's Restaurant. He became a Mormon in 1979 in
South Carolina. ``It was just something that felt right,'' he said.
But he is too busy running aspects of the family business to take
on the branch presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, we want to see some blacks up there,'' he said,
nodding to the humble dais. ``That'll make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Tanya Weinberg is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
