r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-TOKEN-GARB &LR;      03-31 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-TOKEN-GARB </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION GOES UNDERGROUND  
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By STAN CHOE  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ride it or wear it. The public now has a choice when
it comes to the subway, one of New York City's leading tourist
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   A clothing company, Straphanger Designs, has put out its new
line of ``subway chic'' casualwear. The buttons and snaps in each
of the shirts are authentic ``Y-cut'' subway tokens, direct from
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tokens are a real piece of New York history,'' said
Straphanger owner George Stydahar. ``New York City is identified by
its subway system, one of the biggest in the world. Why not make
something to commemorate that?''
</P>
<P>
   When the New York subway fare was raised from 10 to 15 cents in
1953, the Metropolitan Transit Authority introduced the Y-cut
token. Commuters had previously dropped nickels and dimes into the
subway turnstiles.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller than a dime, the token displayed an ``NYC'' logo in the
center. The Y was cut out, so commuters could easily distinguish it
in their pockets from other coins. The Y-cut tokens were retired in
1970 in favor of larger tokens.
</P>
<P>
   The Metrocard, a small plastic card used to swipe in at the
turnstiles, was introduced a few years ago. There speculation among
some subway riders that the Metrocard could eventually phase the
token out of use. Don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The token is just a cool piece of memorabilia,'' said David
Adelson, 22, a day-trader from Manhattan, who bought a shirt from
the Straphanger line. ``It's just classic, the definition of
classic.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Stydahar's customers are baby-boomers who ``want
to own a piece of New York history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear a lot from the customers, especially when they're
ordering online,'' Stydahar said. ``A lot of them talk about how
when they were growing up, they remember taking that subway ride to
Yankee Stadium with their buddies. They said that the token
represents their youth and New York's wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Will something so utilitarian be accepted as fashion statement?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about anything goes in fashion these days,'' said Bob
Antoshak, a fashion consultant with Information Resources
International, which deals with international textile trade. ``It's
certainly a new thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Antoshak said the token-as-button idea was too new for him to
predict success, but he asked, ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   The subway token as accouterment is not new. Ms. Johnson, a
jewelry artist in Manhattan, used tokens to make pendants during
the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what I did was legal,'' she said, not wanting to
publish her full name. ``I did change the wording on the token.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson etched ``Native New Yorker'' onto each of the pendants
and plated them with 14-karat gold. She sold the pendants for $75
each in her booth in the Diamond District. What galvanized all of
her customers was that each wanted to grab onto something that is
truly New York, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The MTA and the Straphanger Design are banking that same emotion
will build business. Each shirt in the subway chic line has more
than two buttons, so consumers will be able to display both sides
of the token. The face reads, ``New York City Transit.'' The back
reads, ``Good For One Fare.''
</P>
<P>
   Straphanger received a license from the MTA to use the vintage
tokens. When the company approached the authority to ask if tokens
were available, ``they told us that they had about two million of
them stashed away in a warehouse in Queens,'' Stydahar said.
``They're in a secret location, and they won't tell us where it is.
That's a lot of tokens, but if we need more, the MTA will
manufacture them.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the subway chic line are T-shirts, a sweatshirt and
a denim button-down shirt. Prices range from $20 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   The shirts are on sale at New York Transit Museum gift shops,
FAO Schwarz, Pants And..., located in Rockefeller Center, and
online at www.straphanger.net.
</P>
<P>
   The precocious Straphanger line is doing well, especially at the
New York Transit gift booth in Times Square, said employee Julia
Mulero.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold out of our entire stock, with people coming in and
buying stuff for Valentine's Day,'' she said. ``They're just doing
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Being in Times Square, Mulero said, she sells shirts mostly to
tourists. They are also a big hit among Transit workers who want to
take their work home with them, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people who come in here to buy the shirts, they
know what they're coming for,'' Mulero said. ``The only
advertisements I've seen for them is in the MTA employee newspaper,
but a lot of people seem to know about it, the New Yorkers do.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Stan Choe is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
