<HEADER>
A1363 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-VIRTUAL &LR;      03-31 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-VIRTUAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN A PICTURE AND A THOUSAND WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By JEANINE PREZIOSO  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A new technology promising high quality audio and
video on PC's may one day bring scripts shunned by Hollywood to
people at home, complete with a virtual cast, and any musician will
be able to have music performed on computer-constructed
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   These are the scenes painted by visionary engineers and analysts
about the MPEG-4, a small ripple in the growing tide of computer
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Though it may take a few years, the technology is expected to
change the way people do business, shop, watch television, view
film, listen to music and interact with one another by computer.
</P>
<P>
   MPEG-4, or the Motion Pictures Expert Group 1, layer 4, which
compresses data and sends it over phone or Internet connections in
smaller bits at a faster pace, was approved last October by the
International Organization for Standardization, an international
group of engineers and academics.
</P>
<P>
   A non-governmental organization, ISO _ which comes from the
Greek word ``isos'' or equal _ established a standard for MPEG that
will allow corporations to create products that can be used
interchangeably, like a Panasonic VCR can be used with a Sony TV.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp is working on a handheld video recorder that can be used
with Windows software to play videos on a PC. Microsoft has already
begun working with the technology, said Gary Schare, product
manager for Windows Media Technology. One example: corporate
training videos available over the Internet that would eliminate
the need for executives to travel for training or bring carts of
video equipment into a conference room to play a VHS tape, he said.
News broadcasts will also be available at the click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Small or individually owned businesses are also likely to
benefit from the technology. For example, an architect could
recreate the design of a house and all its furnishings in three
dimensions without eating up space on the PC, said Peter
Glaskowsky, senior analyst for Microprocessor Report newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's literally the difference between a picture and a thousand
words,'' he said. ``You will be able to recreate a scene by giving
your computer a description, not just transferring a photo.'' The
computer with MPEG-4 technology has the ability to decode the
description and the capabilities to create the described in a very
refined form.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual orchestra could be brought to life on a home computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an instrument sounds like is very different than digital
music,'' Glaskowsky said. ``It's much more sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   MPEG-4 will also deliver interactive TV, said Professor
Alexandros Eleftheriadis, associate professor of electrical
engineering at Columbia University. Consumers will be able to order
their household appliances and jewelry by opening a small window on
a shopping channel. Sports fans could call up data on their
favorite player at will during a game and movie buffs will be able
to channel-surf during films, keeping up with a small summary in a
window to one side. Chat rooms will be furnished with graphics and
video images.
</P>
<P>
   It will be like VH-1's Pop-Up Video. Except, ``instead of VH-1
making those comments you could make them and only your friends
would see them,'' said David Card, a senior media analyst at
Jupiter Communications, a new media research company.
</P>
<P>
   Card likened the ISO's standards for MPEG_4 to buying a wrench
at Sears. ``Somebody has decided the size of the nuts and bolts,
otherwise you could have never made wrenches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MPEG-4 is another tool that has its good and bad points like
anything else. If it takes off in the next 10 years, Glaskowsky
said, the real influence it will have will be on the film and
television industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Hollywood and New York have interesting ideas,'' he
said. ``But there's a whole lot more interesting people and ideas
that we don't get to see. I have no access to those people or ideas
until they get work in Hollywood or on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   But if they have the tools, ``500 digital TV channels are
nothing compared to 500,000 TV transmissions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced that MPEG_4 will bring interactivity
to television.
</P>
<P>
   Though the technology will bring television-quality images to
the Internet, said Joe Jennings, a vice president for InterTrust
Technologies Corporation, the people who use computers and those
who watch television are very different.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TV market is a 'sit back and view,' the computer market is
a 'sit forward and interact,' '' Jennings said. ``I hate to be a
skeptic but I'm not convinced that TV viewers are going to want to
interact with their television.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Jeanine Prezioso is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
