<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1364 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-WEDDINGS &LR;      03-31 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-WEDDINGS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TYING THE KNOT, THEY REJECT TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 WAZIRI ADIO  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Wanda Wright talks about her recent,
African-theme wedding, she glows with a contagious excitement
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally different,'' Mrs. Wright said, her voice liquid
with laughter. ``Absolutely beautiful. I couldn't believe it
myself. I cried.''
</P>
<P>
   It was her second wedding. Ms. Wright, 44, cried not because she
ended a 13-year spell as a divorcee, but because of the
symbol-ridden ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Her runner was hand-painted in gold with African mystic symbols;
the altar of the church in Brooklyn was draped with an image of a
slave ship.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Sherman Wright, wore head-turning, flowing
African attire. They invoked the spirits of their African ancestors
and poured libations. Then, they jumped the broom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has more meaning,'' Wright said in reference to how her
second wedding compared to her first, which was totally Western.
``We wanted a ceremony that would reflect who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   They are not alone in this yearning. Increasingly,
African-Americans are embracing what is now called Afrocentric
weddings for reasons that range from the symbolic to the aesthetic
to the cultural.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for ways to connect uniquely to their own
history and fortify their unions,'' said Harriette Cole, former
fashion editor of Essence Magazine and the author of ``Jumping the
Broom: An African American Wedding Planner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``White wedding dress, for example, is Victorian,'' said Cole
who married in African fashion in 1993. ``But I am not part of
Victorian history. It is important for us to know that there are
aspects of our culture that are powerful and useful. That awareness
has grown dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Afrocentric weddings have grown in the last five years, as have
the number of African-American wedding dress designers and
Afrocentric wedding fairs in response to this trend, said wedding
consultants and planners.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. David Brawley, who officiated at the Wrights' wedding,
said his church has performed 35 Afrocentric weddings in the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the African traditions resonate with us more than the
Western ones,'' said Brawley, an assistant pastor at the St. Paul
African Baptist Church in Brooklyn. ``We keep Christ, but we also
have culture. For us as a church, Afrocentric wedding has more
meaning. It is spontaneous, personal and communal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, people are now realizing that they have an
alternative,'' said Gboyega Adewunmi, a Brooklyn-based designer
with Nigerian Fashion and Fabrics, the fashion outfit that designed
the Wrights' wedding clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Afrocentric weddings you can live your culture,''
Adewunmi said. ``You can choose fabrics that appeal to your taste
and shape. You can choose from a range of colors, not just white.''
From a shy start in 1992, he now takes about 50 wedding orders a
year.
</P>
<P>
   This evolving tradition takes different forms. Some differ only
in the use of African fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Others incorporate pulsating African drums and music and dance,
and serve African food at receptions. And yet others invoke
ancestors' spirits and pour libations. Some use spices to explain
married life and bless their union. Many more jump the broom, a
trend gaining popularity in marriage ceremonies of middle class
African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jumping the broom was started during slavery when it was
illegal for slaves to marry,'' Brawley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But our forefathers found a way of marrying without alerting
the slave masters,'' he added. ``So when we do this now, it is a
tribute to the resourcefulness of our ancestors. We are saying if
it wasn't for their struggle we would not be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   It also symbolizes jumping to a new life, others say.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Willie Wilson of the Union Baptist Church in
Washington, D.C., uses 12 different symbols in his wedding
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use the spear and shield to talk about protection and
leadership in marriage,'' said Wilson who is also the author of
``The African American Wedding Manual.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he also used the kolanut, a two-sided, bitter tropical
nut, ``to talk about the difficulty of being one, that there would
be bitter moments in marriages and there should be commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Symbols help us to explain and remember things that could be
abstract,'' said Wilson, who was ordained as a traditional African
priest in Gambia and Ghana. ``Then we have the drummers and the
dancers. Apart from having more meaning, African weddings have more
excitement when compared to the non-feeling, staid and more solemn
European weddings.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole said Afrocentric weddings started gaining popularity in the
United States after a television series was made out of ``Roots,''
a novel by Alex Hailey. Increased cultural awareness in
African-Americans in the 1980s, and the proliferation of African
magazines, wedding books, wedding fairs and street festivals also
broaden the appeal of African marriage ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Some ceremonies, such as pouring libations and invoking spirits
of the ancestors, seem at odds with Christianity and Islam. Some
ministers would never have them in their churches. Wilson is not
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not antithetical to Christianity,'' he said.
``Communion in Christian church is nothing but libation. There is
not lot of difference at the core of all religions. For long,
Europeans made us reject our culture as primitive or pagan.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those taking to African wedding thus see it as a
political point, an attempt at redeeming values that have been
demonized and despised. ``People are saying I choose to reject many
of the wrong assertions made about us for many years,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people think ancestral ceremonies and values help spice up
ailing marriages. ``A major difference is that African weddings are
unions of two families not just two individuals,'' said Cole, who
said the web of family support has helped in her marriage. ``If you
get the blessing of all family members and everybody was involved,
this could be an insurance for the marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have high divorce rate in America,'' Cole said. ``People
are asking, 'How can we fortify our marriages?' They are not
finding the answer in Western traditions. The values of African
culture could be useful to all, not just people of African descent.
This is an alternative that works.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Waziri Adio is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
