<P>
   The New York Times is planning a five-page package of stories
and graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Brussels) _ NATO launched its expanded bombing
campaign today against Yugoslavia and alliance officials said they
were planning weeks of air strikes intended to undermine President
Slobodan Milosevic's hold on power. The escalated bombing is
intended to give the alliance a more effective tool to pressure Mr.
Milosevic into halting the Serb onslaught in Kosovo, NATO officials
said. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ A senior NATO general tells of the
meetings and decisions leading up to the attack on Serb forces. By
Craig R. Whitney and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AID (Washington) _ Developments on NATO efforts to help
the refugees. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ On the choices facing the White
House. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ Serbian forces are now
shelling villages, towns and cities across a wide swath of Kosovo,
driving more than 10,000 more ethnic Albanians from their homes,
refugees arriving here today reported. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ A Russian military reconnaissance ship
assigned to monitor the conflict in Yugoslavia is due to set sail
for the Mediterranean Friday, sending mixed signals about Moscow's
intentions as NATO's bombing intensifies. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SOLANA (Brussels) _ A man-in-the-news profile of the head
of NATO: Javier Solana Madariaga, who as secretary general of NATO
is running the biggest air war the alliance has ever fought in 50
years of existence, opposed Spain's entry into the organization as
a young Socialist opposition politician in the early 1980s. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HACKERS (Undated) _ In an electronic assault on NATO's
presence in cyberspace, computer users in Serbia managed to
temporarily disable the alliance's site on the World Wide Web last
weekend and cause intermittent outages over the last few days, NATO
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Cacak, Yugoslavia) _ In the first guided tour
conducted by the Yugoslav Army since it issued wartime press passes
on Tuesday, journalists were shown significant bomb damage today in
two central Serbian towns roughly 60 miles south of Belgrade. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WARCRIMES (Paris) _ The Yugoslav war crimes tribunal
announced today that it had indicted a notorious Serbian militia
leader known for his vicious actions in Bosnia and Croatia, a man
widely known as Arkan. The indictment of ''Arkan,'' whose real name
is Zeljiko Raznatovic, was in fact signed on 30 September 1997 and
had been kept secret until now. But officials at the tribunal in
The Hague, The Netherlands, said they decided to publicize it now
because of reports that the much-feared militia leader and his men
were becoming involved in terrorizing civilians in Kosovo. By
Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VUKOVAR (Vukovar, Croatia) _ This ruined city beside the
Danube River is as good a place as any to meditate on the years of
misery and score-settling that lie ahead when the Serb campaign in
Kosovo comes to an end. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STEALTH (Undated) _ In the wake of the recent downing of
the stealth fighter over Yugoslavia, a look at how stealth
technology works _ and doesn't work. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VATICAN (Rome) _ Pope John Paul II, seeking to open a
diplomatic channel to end the violence in Yugoslavia, is sending
the Vatican's top diplomat to Belgrade. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-IRAQ (Washington) _ The British Government said today
that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had formed a ``close
relationship'' with President Saddam Hussein of Iraq and that they
had stepped up their military cooperation in the face of a common
threat from American air strikes. American officials, however, were
skeptical about the degree of cooperation. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Dateline to kum) _ A news analysis on the Kosovo
crisis. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   This stories, budgeted earlier, are now scratched:
</P>
