<HEADER>
A1366 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-RODRIGUE     03-31 1489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-RODRIGUEZ-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-ROD'S NUMBER, PLAYING STYLE HONOR BOYHOOD IDOL DALE MURPHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For the generation that grew up south of Baltimore and
east of St. Louis in the 1980s, there was only one baseball team _
and it was something of a national joke. Every night, on every
cable system, TBS pumped in the Atlanta Braves, hyping them as
``America's Team.'' Problem was, the Braves lost 90 games a year
and were about as popular as mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   One Miami boy felt sorry for them. Alex Rodriguez would finish
his homework and hop over to the couch every night at 7:40, ready
to call balls and strikes for Rick Mahler or Pascual Perez or some
other hapless hurler. He admired the way the Braves played hard, no
matter the score. And he couldn't take his eyes off the guy wearing
No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Murphy won the National League Most Valuable Player award
in 1982 and '83, and excelled in all phases of the game. A
prodigious power hitter who also could run and field, the Portland
native has Hall of Fame credentials. But what impressed Rodriguez
most was Murphy's attitude: he never complained, never argued,
always carried himself with dignity and class.
</P>
<P>
   So Rodriguez wore Murphy's number. He still does. When he was
17, and Miami had a major league team of its own, Rodriguez went on
the field before a Marlins game to accept an award as the national
high school player of the year. The Marlins were playing the
Colorado Rockies, and Murphy was in his last days as a major
leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just walked up to him, I didn't say much,'' Rodriguez said.
``I was very shy. I was in awe.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy greeted Rodriguez warmly, and wished him luck. Now living
in Belmont, Mass., while supervising a five-year Mormon mission,
Murphy said he wants to see Rodriguez again.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of these days, I'd like to thank him for what he's doing
for the game,'' Murphy said. ``He is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez is humbled by those words, the same way Murphy is
humbled to know Rodriguez wears his number. A father of eight,
Murphy said he appreciates the positive impact players like
Rodriguez have on children. The ex-player in Murphy calls Rodriguez
the player he always wanted to be, an infielder who could do it
all.
</P>
<P>
   The 21st century approaches with Rodriguez poised to be what
Murphy was for a five-year period in the '80s: the very best in
baseball. At 23, Rodriguez already has a batting title and a 40
home run/40 stolen base season. His ``understated excellence''
recently drew comparisons to Christy Mathewson, Joe DiMaggio and
Cal Ripken in a Newsweek piece by George F. Will.
</P>
<P>
   And his looks and charisma make him one of the most marketable
athletes in sports. Think you've heard the name ``A-Rod'' a lot
already? Just wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex is going to be one of, if not the, icon of baseball for
the next 15 years,'' said Rodriguez's agent, Scott Boras. ``He's
that type of player, he's that type of person. Really, the sky's
the limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a baseball player that will end up with national
endorsements, end up as an icon, it will be him. When we
copyrighted the `A-Rod' name when he was in the minor leagues, he
kind of laughed. I said, `That monicker is going to be used quite a
bit.' Sure enough, that's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A-Rod active wear? A-Rod breakfast flakes? Eu d'A-Rod cologne?
Rodriguez said he will take it as it comes. As the A-Rod tidal wave
comes in, it is the old-school values, instilled partly from
Murphy's example, that Rodriguez calls on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing concerns me about him, because he's already shown such
good perspective at such a young age,'' Murphy said. ``But I think
one thing that's always a challenge for an athlete is losing
perspective of who he really is, his place in the game, putting
himself on a different level than everybody else. That can tend to
happen with athletic success, and you lose respect of people inside
and outside the game when you do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex has a great gift, but I think he knows it doesn't really
make him any different than everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez nods in agreement. He said he wants coaches and older
teammates to get on him when they see the need. He likes that about
baseball, and points to the educational system as a parallel. There
is a hierarchy, Rodriguez said, with coaches and teachers above and
players and students below. It's the way things should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people treat you like you're a king or something, which
is not really right,'' Rodriguez said. ``See, that's the one thing,
you cannot be complacent about treating people right, treating
people with respect and really staying grounded. And my attitude
is, I do everything in life _ the way I save my money, the way I
try to pursue my education, the way I treat people _ like I've
played my last day yesterday. Just realize, hey, this is almost a
fake world we're living in, because everything is catered to us.''
</P>
<P>
   And when you are not expecting it, Murphy said, that world can
disappear. Age caught up quickly to Murphy, who retired at 37 two
homers shy of 400, and he cautioned that Rodriguez must maintain
his work ethic without being consumed by increasing demands on his
time.
</P>
<P>
   But one of those demands _ for all people, Murphy said, not just
athletes _ should be community service. Rodriguez took that to
heart this winter, building lights at a Miami youth baseball field,
donating $20,000 to the Sammy Sosa Foundation for hurricane relief
in the Dominican Republic and raising $140,000 for the Boys and
Girls Clubs of Miami at his annual dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Other financial concerns will occupy Rodriguez's time before
long. Rodriguez's contract expires after the 2000 season, and
speculation already has begun on the when, where and how much of
his next deal.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said, and Rodriguez agreed, that contract negotiations
are the least enjoyable part of a player's job. Murphy never
shopped his talents as a free agent, and Rodriguez signed a
four-year contract in 1996 that let the Mariners buy out his
arbitration years for $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ridiculed by everybody for my contract, but at 20 years
old I was secure for the rest of my life,'' Rodriguez said. ``I
know exactly what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   His next decision will be more complicated. Like Murphy with
fans in the South, Rodriguez has developed a bond with fans in the
Northwest. He treasures that, he said, but he also doesn't want to
end up without a World Series ring.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who spent his prime with poor Atlanta teams and never
reached the World Series, understands Rodriguez's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard thing for fans to understand why a player would
leave,'' Murphy said. ``It's nothing personal. It happens all the
time in the business world, but nobody knows about it. He can have
an impact wherever he plays, but when you become part of a
community, you can just be part of some great things for a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But wanting to win, I think that's a healthy attitude for him
to have. That's why he's out there, and that's what he should
desire in his career. I regret the chance not to have a ring, sure.
Those were some frustrating times. I was optimistic we'd be on the
verge of something, but it never worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez doesn't want to say the same thing when his career
ends. Players in Murphy's era made millions, too, but as Rodriguez
points out, teams like Minnesota and Kansas City still won
championships.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether the Mariners ever can. Rodriguez is
anxious to see the impact of Safeco Field on the Mariners'
competitiveness in a system increasingly weighted toward
high-spending clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not on three or four teams, you're not going to
win,'' Rodriguez said. ``Bottom line. You're not going to kid each
other. The team that's going to spend $90-115-140 million in the
future is the team that's going to win. That's a sad situation, how
baseball let it get to this. So if you say, well, I'm going to play
for a team in Milwaukee, you're going to choose to stay in
Milwaukee your whole career and you're 100-percent guaranteed
you're not going to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when Dale Murphy played, all it took was probably two
good pitchers who weren't going to cost you $100 million, probably
more like $14 million between the two, and you had a chance to win.
So the difference between a middle team and a great team wasn't all
that huge, money-wise. Now you're talking about the Yankees' $100
million payroll compared to Montreal at $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest thing is I love the people in Seattle and the
following I have with the people in Seattle, and the organization
has been really good to me, too. I still feel we have a chance to
win here. It's just a matter of getting the right pieces to the
puzzle. We have a new stadium now, so we'll see what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
