<HEADLINE>
LET'S SAVOR DOW'S RISE TO 10,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) To paraphrase Bogie's wistful remark to Bergman in
``Casablanca,'' ``We'll always have Dow 10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the Dow Jones industrial average does in the
months ahead, its close Monday above 10,000 was a memorable moment.
If you have any emotional stake whatsoever in the stock market,
cherish it.
</P>
<P>
   Those who dismissed it as inconsequential should be reminded of
Oscar Wilde's definition of a cynic as someone who knows the cost
of everything and the value of nothing.
</P>
<P>
   They're intellectually impaired, because they have no sense of
history. Either that or they're too young to have ever experienced
a spirit-crushing bear market. Remember that bleak December day in
1974 when the Dow bottomed at 578? That was almost 460 points lower
than its then-record closing high in December 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a longer-range perspective, from May 1969 to November
1979 the industrials lost almost 18 percent. It didn't get better
as the '80s dawned. The market tried to recover but fell back with
a thud. Remember the depths of despair reached in August 1982, when
the Dow industrials bottomed in that bear market at 777? From peak
to trough, the average plunged nearly 25 percent in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   From January 1980 to November 1982 there was a double-dip
recession. Unemployment was in double digits, and the economy
wasn't growing. Unless you were there and actively involved in the
market, there is no way to understand the atmosphere of utter
hopelessness that existed for stock investors. For the better part
of 15 years there had been no sustained period during which
Americans could feel unreservedly optimistic about their economic
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   It was, as it turned out, an extremely difficult time to make
money in the stock market. Not surprisingly, many individual
investors lost interest and withdrew to lick their wounds.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, those who have been involved in the stock market
only since the mid-1980s have experienced a few brief scary moments
and some protracted periods of doldrums. Nevertheless, none of them
can relate to the sort of despair that preceded the current market
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Making money in stocks today must seem the easiest thing in the
world. Polls of investment-oriented Americans bear this out
regularly. Most surveyed expect double-digit returns from stocks in
the years to come, but this view ignores the reality of history.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed over the long 20th-century continuum, the last few years
have been the exception, not the rule. The exception may continue
its run for a good while longer, but this doesn't make the Dow's
ascent to 10,000 any less impressive.
</P>
<P>
   It took more than 16 years from the first time the Dow briefly
crossed 1,000 during intraday trading in early 1966 until it
finally closed and subsequently held above this elusive plateau for
good.
</P>
<P>
   From then to now, it took just a tad longer to add 9,000 points.
By any standard, this is impressive stuff. Stock market winners of
the last few years who try to pretend otherwise betray an inability
to appreciate the good fortune they probably don't deserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
