<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLEANSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC CLEANSING ALMOST COMPLETE, SURVIVORS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KULA PASS, Kosovo _ Driven from their homes, stripped of every
official document that might prove their identities, numbed by
shock and bitter cold, the refugees, in their long columns,
materialized from a driving snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``God alone knows where my family and I are going,'' said Kurtes
Rama, a 30-year-old postal worker from the Kosovo city of Pec
(pronounced Pesh), as he floundered through the drifts late
Wednesday with his wife and two small children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are friendless in the world. I don't even have a scrap of
paper to show my name. They took my work card, they took my
passport, they took my driver's license.''
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic cleansing of Kosovo is not only continuing in the
face of NATO's bombing campaign against Yugoslavia, it is rapidly
heading toward completion. Refugees trying to escape the tormented
province told of whole communities emptied of ethnic Albanians, and
all but obliterated by rampaging Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a few days, there will be no one left in Kosovo except the
Serbs and the dead,'' said Shureje Gogon, 41, who with her
9-year-old daughter, Fitore, pushed for three days through the
frigid mountains to escape the ethnic vengeance of Serb
paramilitary forces in Pec.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the houses in the Albanian neighborhoods were burning,''
she said, trembling greatly, her eyes vacant of everything but
sheer exhaustion. ``The smoke was so thick it blotted the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Until a few days ago, Pec was a thriving community of 100,000.
More than 80 percent of its population was of Albanian heritage.
Today, according to fleeing inhabitants, the city is a smoldering
ghost town, as Serbs torch Albanian houses and level larger
structures with tank shellfire.
</P>
<P>
   In a cruel twist, Serb squads are confiscating all
identification documents, and even children's medical
perscriptions. ``It is the way they say to us, `See, you don't even
exist,' '' said Halid Madupi, a middle-aged factory worker. His
face was swollen and reddened from what he said were blows from
Serb police angered when he did not hand over his work card quickly
enough. They said, `You have no job, from right now. There is
nothing for you. You must leave.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Madupi said he and his wife were force-marched from the city of
their birth in a long column flanked by armed Serbs dressed in
camouflage and jaunty red berets. ``They said, `Stay in line. If
you turn left, we will shoot you. If you turn right, we will shoot
you. If you stop, we will shoot you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   According to Madupi, when a boy of about 16 panicked and tried
to break ranks, he was shot dead. An older man also sought to
escape and was shot, though Madupi said he was unsure if that man
died.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo has been sealed from the outside world by the Yugoslav
military since the start of the American-led NATO bombing campaign
meant to force the regime of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
to pull back his army from the province and allow an international
military force to guard the province's ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be few Albanians left to protect. A pair of
American reporters who entered Kosovo Wednesday by way of a remote
mountain pass near Pec encountered a seemingly endless stream of
refugees, many driven from their homes just hours before.
</P>
<P>
   The escapees told consistent tales of Albanian neighborhoods
methodically emptied, then destroyed. All the refugees interviewed
said the ultranationalist Serb militias seemed especially obsessed
with taking away every form of identification.
</P>
<P>
   The luckiest refugees were allowed to escape in cars. Others
traveled crammed into the backs of trucks. One elderly man drove a
vintage tractor, pulling a produce wagon loaded with 30 members of
his extended family. He declined to give his name. ``I am too
scared to tell you,'' he said. ``At 6 this morning, Serbs pushed
into our home and said we must leave immediately. They told us this
land we call our home can never be our home again. We must go
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of refugees were trudging out of Kosovo on foot, some
wearing only sweaters and shivering uncontrollably in the fierce
cold.
</P>
<P>
   They did not fit the world's usual image of refugees _ they were
not starving or ragged wretches fleeing some Third World horror.
Instead, the tragedy unfolding in Kosovo is one of ancient
animosities flaring against an eerily modern backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees were often ill-dressed for the weather, but they
were well-dressed, a few men even in suits and ties and many women
in brand-name outdoor wear. And if the narrow road they followed
led mainly through thick forest, they also marched miserably past a
new ski area, its fancy chalet lodge and lifts closed because of
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   None of the refugees interviewed seemed to harbor much faith
they would ever return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are finished,'' said Maslum Redepi. ``Kosovo has been
ethnically purified. The Serbs laughed as we left and said we would
never dare come home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
