<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUSH WITH CASH, BUSH HINTS AT PRESIDENTIAL RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Bolstered by more than $6 million in donations
in less than a month, Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Wednesday he
was leaning more toward announcing a campaign for the presidency
because of the early outpouring of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good sign,'' said Bush, who formed a presidential
exploratory committee last month. ``I wanted to make sure that
behind the polls and the phone calls that there was some substance.
I think this is the first indication that there is good support.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was inching closer to making a decision to seek the
Republican presidential nomination, he responded: ``More than
inches. It's feet and yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's presidential exploratory committee, which he formed to
test the waters for a possible run for the White House, opened a
bank account on March 4. By Wednesday, more than $6 million was on
deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not held a single fund-raising event and has made few
political appearances outside Texas. The committee raised the money
through ``friend-to-friend'' contacts and mailings.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
front-runner, has campaigned steadily and has held several
fund-raising events. Gore's campaign has raised $7 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honored that we've raised, I think, a little more than $6
million, and our accountants are still counting,'' Bush said after
giving a speech to the Conference on Right Choices for Youth.
``This is just the beginning, and I've got a lot more work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted to see if there was true support for his
candidacy before officially deciding to become a candidate _ a move
he won't make until after the state Legislature wraps up its
business May 31.
</P>
<P>
   The first quarterly reporting period ended Wednesday, and Bush's
committee will release the names and home states of contributors
when it files its report with the Federal Election Commission on
April 15.
</P>
<P>
   All presidential hopefuls must report to the FEC on April 15 how
much they raised between Jan. 1 and March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been ahead of his potential GOP opponents in the polls
and appears to be leading them in terms of fund-raising as well.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle, the vice president under Bush's father, former
President George Bush, is expected to have raised about $2 million
in the first reporting period, a spokesman said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, conservative leader Gary Bauer and
Ohio Rep. John Kasich are expected to report at least $1 million
each in contributions, their campaign officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is considering bypassing federal matching funds for the
primary campaign, a move that would allow him to disregard federal
campaign spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   If he isn't tied to financial restrictions in the primary, he
might be able to compete better against millionaire publisher Steve
Forbes, who is financing his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matching-fund decision will be made later on next fall,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign advisers have said the governor would need to raise
about $50 million to forgo the federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be pleased if we can raise double the amount of money
we've raised thus far by June 30,'' Bush replied when asked how
much money he expected to raise in the next quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, Bush visited with another GOP delegation that
wants him to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to ask Texas to share him with America,'' said Alan
Novak, the GOP state committee chairman in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Novak was joined by Republican National Committee members Bob
Asher and Christine Toretti and other GOP officials from
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been approached by a number of delegations of
Republican state lawmakers, other governors and members of
Congress, urging him to seek the nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
