<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON CENTRAL TO BRUINS' EFFORT AGAINST CANADIENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- No. 1 in the draft. No. 1 in the hopes and wishes of
Bruins fans. And Thursday, in the city that once boasted the Forum
of Horror, Joe Thornton is expected to be in the middle of the
Bruins' No. 1 line when they face the Montreal Canadiens at the
Molson Centre.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton practiced Wednesday at the Ristuccia Center outside of
Boston with Sergei Samsonov and Dmitri Khristich as his wingers.
Until further notice, which in these changing times could be as the
puck leaves the referee's hand for the opening faceoff, that would
make Jumbo Joe the center between the club's two most talented
wingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good with the puck, just great with their hands,''
said Thornton, less than 24 hours after the Bruins played in a
lethargic, near-hitless 2-1 loss to the Kings on FleetStreet. ``All
I have to do is get them the puck in open space and let 'em do
magic with their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's ascension to the No. 1 pivot comes at a time when
center Jason Allison, who assumed the top job last season, is
struggling with a hand injury. It also comes at a time when the
Bruins are in need of re-establishing their skating and hitting
games. Allison wasn't anywhere close to his `A' game in the loss to
the Kings. Team-wide, the Bruins were far too lax in their skating
and, consequently, nearly non-existent with their hitting game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were cleaning the pool,'' said an animated Pat Burns,
implying that their sticks were nothing more than vacuums meant to
keep a pool fit for swimming. ``I was trying to be positive behind
the bench. I was back there, saying `C'mon, get in their faces . .
. get in their legs . . . lock 'em up.' I wouldn't say it was like
beating a dead horse _ because you would have shot it after two
periods.''
</P>
<P>
   A new line of Samsonov-Thornton-Khristich isn't going to change
all that. The Bruins are a troubling 0-1-2 in their last three and
need an 18-skater, 60-minute commitment to regain some momentum
before the playoffs start. For that matter, they still haven't
locked up a playoff berth, still in need of distancing themselves
from the Panthers and Rangers to solidify a second straight
postseason invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, provided he keeps the new combination intact, will look
for his new SKaTe line to rejuvenate an offense that has averaged
only two goals per outing over the last three games. Samsonov ended
a personal 10-game scoring drought Tuesday with his 21st goal.
Other than that, the Bruins rarely caused a threat once inside the
offensive blue line. Thornton had a golden opportunity to drill a
15-foot slapper from the slot but opted instead to carry deeper
toward the net, only to close so deep that he completely lost the
scoring opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came down to (the Kings') level,'' said Thornton. ``We
didn't skate and we didn't hit. We thought that it was going to be
easier than it was, and because of that we didn't get everyone to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of what challenges the Bruins now, too, is their talent
level _ a point Burns subtly reminded the media of after practice.
He made a point of saying he called together his young line of
Landon Wilson, Shawn Bates, and Cameron Mann (the Baby BMW line)
between periods Tuesday night and showed them video of how they
missed opportunities to check and deliver hits that have to be made
if they want to remain off the route 95 shuttle to Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `Hey, I hear this stuff all the time _ the coach
doesn't like me, I don't get playing time, I'm not getting a
chance,' '' said Burns. ``Well, here's their chance. And I showed
'em on the video, they're out there checking with their hands and
sticks. You can't do that here, not in this league . . . I wish
people would understand that . . . I wish everyone would understand
that. Imagine going up against Rob Blake with a hand or a stick?
C'mon.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach added that the BMW trio wasn't alone in its lack of
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Anson) Carter's got to be more physical, too,'' he said.
``And Heinzie (Steve Heinze), there's no reason for him not to
finish his hits. Allison is hurting a little bit, too, but he's
been so competitive lately _ I've no complaint there.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, what Burns has is Thornton in Allison's spot. Nine
games to go and still tinkering. As the season draws to a close,
the Bruins are still a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were 5-4-0 over their last nine games last season, a
mark that would all but guarantee their locking up a playoff berth
this season. The Rangers, with eight games left as of Wednesday
morning, would have to collect 15 of an available 16 points just to
tie the Bruins at 87 points. The Panthers, who began the day with
10 games remaining, would have to collect 15 of an available 20
points . . . With Thornton paired with Khristich and Samsonov,
Allison moved into a trio with Heinze and Carter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
