<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1386 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAROLE-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      03-31 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAROLE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BOARD CHANGES DEADLINE FOR CLEMENCY FILINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Death row prisoners will have to file their
requests for mercy at least 21 days before they are scheduled for
execution, rather than just five, under new rules adopted Wednesday
by state parole officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Pardons and Parole's six-member policy
council unanimously approved the new rule, which will take effect
in June. Board Chairman Victor Rodriguez has said the new deadline
would give board members more time to review clemency and
commutation requests.
</P>
<P>
   For at least the past two decades, the board has rejected almost
all clemency requests. The governor cannot grant such requests
without a recommendation from the board.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the rule will make it more difficult for condemned
killers to seek a reprieve or commutation of their sentences.
That's because many death row prisoners and their lawyers likely
will not be notified that an execution date has been set in
sufficient time to meet the filing deadline, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a worst-case scenario and the attorney is not notified of
the (execution) date, it's not outside the realm of possibility''
that an inmate will be precluded from seeking clemency, said Austin
defense lawyer Maurie Levin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time that happens, when there is a valid clemency
petition, is when this is going to blow up on them,'' said defense
attorney Bill Habern of Riverside, who testified on behalf of the
Texas Criminal Defense Lawyers Association.
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas junior Imelda Garcia of El Paso admonished
the board to remember with whom it is dealing, regardless of the
rules it adopts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life and death is in the balance ... and that's not something
to be taken lightly,'' she said. ``It's not just papers and files
you are dealing with. They are human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Death penalty appeals often involve a flurry of frantic,
last-minute legal pleadings, court appearances and even arguments
via telephone conference calls.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, however, noted that nothing precludes death row
prisoners from filing clemency petitions in advance of getting an
execution date.
</P>
<P>
   Levin also acknowledged that death row inmates usually get
anywhere from three to 10 execution dates, resulting in multiple
clemency applications and supplements being filed with the board.
</P>
<P>
   Levin and defense lawyer Rita Radostitz had proposed setting the
filing deadline 10 to 14 days ahead of the execution date. The
parole board had proposed 25 days, but amended it to 21 days after
Wednesday's public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The filing deadline is the first change the board has made in
its clemency rules in years.
</P>
<P>
   Clemency procedures came under intense scrutiny last year with
the execution of Karla Faye Tucker, the first woman put to death in
Texas in modern times and a widely recognized born-again Christian
whose religious transformation behind bars carried no weight with
the board. Procedures came under fire again later with the
near-execution of Canadian Joseph Stanley Faulder.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Faulder is facing a June 17 execution date and will
be one of the first inmates subjected to the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' clemency procedures have been upheld by state and federal
courts as meeting the minimum requirements of due process. But the
judges have sharply criticized the parole board, particularly over
its secret meetings and refusal to say what criteria it uses in
evaluating clemency petitions. The parole board is exempt from
complying with the state Open Meetings Act.
</P>
<P>
   At least three bills are pending in the Legislature that would
address those issues.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, and Rep. Elliott Naishtat,
D-Austin, both have bills pending to require public meetings of the
board on clemency matters, Senate Bill 1698 and House Bill 397,
respectively. Naishtat also has filed legislation, HB 398, that
would specify criteria the board must consider in evaluating
clemency petitions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
