<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1391 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      03-31 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bagwell, Biggio, Caminiti: Astros throwbacks
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By iBy ts very nature, baseball is a game that almost forces us
to look to the past with a sense of romanticism.
</P>
<P>
   We genuinely believe the players of yesteryear played harder and
with more passion and zeal than today's major leaguers. We believe
they would have done so whether it made them wealthy or whether it
paid them like peanut vendors. We believe they would have done so
regardless of the fame or the status that comes with being among
the best athletes in the world.
</P>
<P>
   We long for that type of player; we search for any semblance
among today's stars and, if we're fortunate enough to find one, we
call him a throwback _ as in a throwback to the good old days, when
the game was played the way it was meant to be played.
</P>
<P>
   If such a player exists today, he plays for the Astros and he
answers to the name Jeff Bagwell, Craig Biggio or Ken Caminiti. All
three are throwbacks in every sense of the word.
</P>
<P>
   When you see Biggio covered in dirt from head to toe, there can
be no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Throwback.
</P>
<P>
   When you see Bagwell hustling down the first-base line on an
obvious ground-ball out with the enthusiasm of a Little Leaguer,
there can be no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Throwback.
</P>
<P>
   When you see Caminiti willing himself onto the field with
injuries that would disable less courageous players, there can be
no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Throwback.
</P>
<P>
   They all are, and it's that type of will and desire that ranks
each among the best players to wear an Astros uniform.
</P>
<P>
   From the days of the shooting-star logo to the wild colors of
the rainbow jerseys, if you're looking for Houston players who
elicit memories of baseball's glory years, look no farther than the
three stars the Astros are counting on to lead them to a third
consecutive National League Central Division title and the
franchise's first World Series appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three guys play the game as well as it can possibly be
played from the standpoint of effort, determination and so on,''
Astros president Tal Smith said. ``I don't necessarily subscribe to
the fact the game was played so much better years ago, from a
standpoint of intensity, as it is today. We always _ from a
standpoint of nostalgia _ think it was better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've followed baseball since the 1940s, so I can recall it
vividly. There are players today _ certainly (Bagwell, Biggio and
Caminiti) _ who are the epitome of anything anyone could ask for in
a ballplayer. Twenty years from now, I suspect people will be
referring to players as throwbacks to the way Cammy, Craig and
Baggy played the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti broke into the big leagues in 1987; Biggio made his
debut the following year. They were fortunate enough to play with
veterans such as Nolan Ryan, Mike Scott, Buddy Bell, Terry Puhl,
Craig Reynolds, Bill Doran and Alan Ashby, who taught them how to
play the game ``the right way,'' as Biggio often says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a 22-year-old kid at the time,'' Biggio said. ``I
thought I knew everything when I actually knew nothing. I learned a
lot just by sitting, watching and listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell wasn't so fortunate. When he arrived on the scene in
1991, the Astros were in the midst of rebuilding, and there were no
seasoned veterans to set an example for younger players _ only
Biggio and Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   What they may have lacked in baseball savvy, they made up for
with the effort that is their calling card to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one way that I know how to play the game, and
that's to go all out,'' Bagwell said. ``I don't try to do it that
way; that's just the way it is. That's the way you should go out
there every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, Biggio and Caminiti first shared a big-league diamond
during the spring of 1991. Things were different then; Biggio was a
catcher, and Bagwell had come to camp to unseat Caminiti as the
Astros' third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Yogi Berra, an Astros coach at the time, solved
that problem by suggesting Bagwell be shifted to first base. The
rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me all spring to make my conversion from catcher to
second base,'' Biggio recalled. ``But that spring, Baggy learned
how to play first base in two weeks because that's all the time he
had after they decided he was going to play first base.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros lost 97 games in 1991, but it was obvious they could
build around their three stars-in-the-making, who were becoming the
best of friends. They were clueless as to the heights their careers
would reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a rookie, and they were only in their third year or
so,'' Bagwell said. ``I didn't even know if I belonged in the big
leagues. Who could have known at that time what kind of players we
would become?''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, they made the All-Star team together and
Bagwell won the National League's Most Valuable Player award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the year we knew that we had kind of arrived,''
Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, one of the triplets was about to exit. After the
1994 season, the Astros' foundation was cracked by the rapidly
changing economics of baseball. With Biggio, Caminiti and Steve
Finley approaching free agency, the Astros were at a financial
crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't agree on a new contract with Caminiti, so they
traded him and Finley to San Diego in a blockbuster deal that
brought current starters Derek Bell and Ricky Gutierrez to town.
</P>
<P>
   Almost overnight, the Astros' building blocks had been reduced
from three to two.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough one,'' Bagwell said. ``But we knew there was
a chance our team would be broken up if we didn't win in 1994. I
guess we just didn't know it would happen the way it did. We all
hated to see Cammy go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros knew they were trading away a good player when they
dealt Caminiti to San Diego; Bagwell and Biggio believed their
sidekick was on the verge of a career breakthrough. But it's
doubtful anyone predicted the extent of Caminiti's breakout.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged 30 home runs and 99 RBIs in four seasons with the
Padres _ his bests with the Astros were 18 and 80, respectively _
and won an NL MVP trophy of his own in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was capable of that, but he needed to prove to
himself that he was that type of player,'' Bagwell said. ``Cammy is
very emotional, and I would even say that he's insecure at times.
After that year, he believed in himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti played two more seasons for the Padres before they
decided not to re-invest in the 35-year-old switch hitter. Now that
the choice was all his, there was no doubt where Caminiti wanted to
play. He turned down significantly more money from Detroit ($21.5
million over three years) to sign a two-year, $9.5 million deal
with the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with this organization,'' Caminiti said. ``This is
where my family calls home, and this is where my two best friends
are. I was going to do everything I could to get back to the
Astros.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years have passed since that spring day when the three
first took the field together. They have reached levels of success
others always knew possible, but Bagwell, Biggio and Caminiti never
gave it much thought. They were too busy enjoying the game and
playing it the only way they know how.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all said and done, hopefully we'll all be able to
sit back and say we had a positive impact on the game,'' Biggio
said. ``But for now, we just respect the fact that we're able to go
out and play the game every day, because the fact is, this is
really what we all love doing. We've gotten a little older, but
that part hasn't changed from the beginning. We still just love to
play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   There can be no doubt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1924EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
