<HEADER>
A1392 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLEAST-HNS &LR;      03-31 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL </SLUG>
 EAST-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Braves still class of division
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite their dominance during the 1990s _ winning seven
National League division titles _ the Atlanta Braves only have one
World Series championship to show for their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently deciding enough was enough, the Braves did the
unthinkable _ they de-emphasized pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Of course they still have Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and John
Smoltz, but they used the other member of the Fab Four _ Denny
Neagle _ to acquire Bret Boone, who will shore up their defense and
provide more offense at second base than this team has seen in
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves also upgraded the defense in right field, where
free-agent acquisition Brian Jordan takes up residence. Jordan also
will be a nice addition to the lineup, adding speed and additional
run production. Atlanta will need it in the absence of Andres
Galarraga, who is out for the season because of lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves weren't the only team revamping in the NL East.
The Mets improved an already strong defense by signing third
baseman Robin Ventura and moving Edgardo Alfonzo from third to
second base.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Rickey Henderson gives the Mets an experienced
leadoff hitter and a proven winner. If Bobby Bonilla stays healthy,
New York will have a better everyday lineup than the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   This is still Atlanta's division to lose, but the Mets should at
least be in the wild-card running. There's not much hope for the
Phillies, Expos or Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the rise
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Phillies: They've tried to rebuild with a mixture
of young talent and veterans. But they've clearly had more success
with youngsters such as Scott Rolen, Bob Abreu and Doug Glanville.
If they don't lose sight of their long-range goals, the Phillies
could return to contention sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the slide
</P>
<P>
   Florida Marlins: Although they had plenty of talent in their own
system, the Marlins didn't do as well as they should have in
securing talent during the salary purge of a year ago. First
baseman Derrek Lee is the only regular they received in one of
their many cost-cutting trades. They're still far from
respectability.
</P>
<P>
   Overrated
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko, Braves: His power numbers have fallen each of the
past two seasons, all the way down to 18 homers and 70 RBIs in
1998. Manager Bobby Cox doesn't seem comfortable playing him
against lefthanded pitching, and his outfield defense has been
atrocious. Perhaps the move to first base will help.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine, Mets: He carries himself as if he were one of
the top managers in baseball, and some people actually buy into it.
But he's under .500 as a big-league manager and has never taken a
team to the postseason. And let's not forget the way the Mets fell
apart down the stretch last season.
</P>
<P>
   Underrated
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed, Mets: As a former replacement player, Reed may not be
among the most popular players in the league, but he sure knows how
to win. He doesn't have the best stuff, but he may be the Mets'
best pitcher. Last year's 16-win season was not a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Rico Brogna, Phillies: First-round draft pick Pat Burrell is on
the way, which could spell the end of Brogna's tenure in
Philadelphia. But don't fret. There are plenty of teams who can
make use of a first baseman capable of driving in 100 runs a year.
</P>
<P>
   Up and coming
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Anderson, Phillies: If the Phillies can be patient while
his defense catches up with his offense, Anderson could very well
challenge J.D. Drew for the NL Rookie of the Year award. He hits
for average and has decent power for a middle infielder.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Gonzalez, Marlins: The Marlins thought enough of him to
trade the best young shortstop in the National League, Edgar
Renteria. Gonzalez won't make anyone forget Renteria at the plate _
at least not initially _ but he can pick it with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   Down and out
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Brantley, Phillies: He never quite recovered from shoulder
surgery two years ago, and his one-year stint in St. Louis was a
disaster. By midseason, the Phillies will be regretting the day
they decided Brantley was a better late-inning option than Ricky
Bottalico.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser, Mets: He's all you need to know about how thin
big-league-caliber pitching is. Teams were lining up for the
services of this former Cy Young winner. Hershiser's best days are
behind him, and he'd better hope umpires never start cracking down
on pitchers who doctor the ball.
</P>
<P>
   On the spot
</P>
<P>
   Ed Wade, Phillies: Like Woody Woodward and Gord Ash before him,
Wade will be holding the prized pitching possession at some point
this season. Once the Phillies fall out of the race, Wade's phone
will start ringing with offers for Curt Schilling, and he'll be
under pressure to make the right deal.
</P>
<P>
   City of Montreal: You're about to lose your team if you don't
give commissioner Bud Selig a reason _ any reason _ to believe you
actually care. This could be your last chance. Otherwise the Expos
will become the first baseball team to relocate since the
Washington Senators moved to Arlington in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   What if
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bonilla finally gets healthy and plays the way he did in
1997 when he helped the Marlins win the World Series? The Mets look
good on paper _ real good. But they can't afford to have any
serious injuries if they want to end the Braves' dominance in the
NL East.
</P>
<P>
   On schedule
</P>
<P>
   How many times do you think we'll hear the phrase ``Preview of
the Subway Series'' June 4-6 when the Mets visit Yankee Stadium?
During the first month of the season, the Braves only play three
games against teams that finished above .500 in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
