<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1393 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALEAST-HNS &LR;      03-31 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL </SLUG>
 EAST-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By CARLTON THOMPSON 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The initial urge is to assume the Yankees couldn't possibly be
better than they were in 1998, when they won an American
League-record 114 games and claimed yet another World Series
championship.
</P>
<P>
   And yet we all know what they say about assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   There is reason to believe the Yankees could be even better in
1999. The main reason is five-time Cy Young Award winner Roger
Clemens, who won 20 games for the Blue Jays in 1998. If he pitches
the way he has over the last two seasons, 25 to 30 wins are not out
of the question for him on a team of this caliber.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, Tino Martinez and Andy Pettitte have all had
better individual seasons than 1998, and we have not seen the best
of Derek Jeter or Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   That can't be a pleasant thought for the Orioles, as they try to
rebound from a complete fallout of a season, or the Red Sox, who
played well enough to win the AL's other two divisions in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   They can only hope the Yankees don't get any better and that
they fall far enough back to the pack to make this a fair fight.
Otherwise, the wild card is the only chance the Orioles or Red Sox
have of making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the rise
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Blue Jays: Although they didn't seem to get fair value
in the Clemens trade, the Blue Jays are moving in the right
direction. They have a nice collection of young players, and they
won't be fun to play. They'll probably take a few steps backward
before moving forward, but the future looks bright.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the slide
</P>
<P>
   Boston Red Sox: They overachieved in 1998, but they'll have no
such luck this time around. General manager Dan Duquette ran off
Clemens and Mo Vaughn and got nothing in return for either. Sooner
or later, that sort of mismanagement will catch up to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Overrated
</P>
<P>
   Joey Hamilton, Blue Jays: At one point he looked like one of the
best young pitchers in baseball. But his development ended
abruptly. His stuff is plenty good enough, but this guy is a mental
mess and he hurts himself by thinking too much.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stocker, Devil Rays: Tampa Bay thought so much of Stocker
that when it drafted Bob Abreu in the expansion draft, it
immediately shipped him to Philadelphia for Stocker. Abreu hit
.312; Stocker hit .208.
</P>
<P>
   Underrated
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada, Yankees: His fine season almost went unnoticed in
the Yankees' magic of 1998. But Posada is just a notch below
Charles Johnson and Ivan Rodriguez when it comes to defense behind
the plate, and don't forget that he hit 17 homers and drove in 63
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Portugal, Red Sox: He never seems to get his due because
he's always out of shape, injured or both. But when Portugal is
healthy, he produces. If the Red Sox have success this year, he'll
be a key figure.
</P>
<P>
   Up and coming
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon, Red Sox: He hits for average and power, runs with
speed and is above-average in the field. This Rookie of the Year
candidate could become the next star in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Smith, Devil Rays: This might not be his year to shine,
but give Smith time. His stuttered playing time doesn't reflect his
level of ability. Unfortunately for Smith, he plays third base, and
the Devil Rays want to see Wade Boggs reach 3,000 hits wearing
their uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Down and out
</P>
<P>
   Geronimo Berroa, Blue Jays: There must be some reason he is with
his fourth team in three years. He offers the promise of power, but
he failed to produce at his last two stops. He only homered once in
191 at-bats for Cleveland and Detroit last season.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson Alvarez, Devil Rays: He could have just as easily made
the overrated list. Don't be surprised if he's not completely over
the injuries that contributed to his 14-loss season in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On the spot
</P>
<P>
   Ray Miller, Orioles: His first year as Orioles manager was a
disaster, and you can bet owner Peter Angelos expected more than 79
victories for his $73 million payroll. Angelos is very reactive,
and he just might stick a quick hook in Miller if the O's don't run
off some early W's.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette, Red Sox: How does this guy keep his job,
especially in a sports-crazed town like Boston? First he ran off
Clemens, then Vaughn. He's one of the most unpopular people in
town. Alienating Vaughn could blow up in his face.
</P>
<P>
   What if
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken Jr. starts taking regular days off and his production
still doesn't increase? The popular theory over the past few years
has been that Ripken's production has tailed off because of
fatigue. The Orioles can only hope that's the case. Few AL teams
would be happy with a third baseman who hits only 14 homers with 61
RBIs, as Ripken did last year.
</P>
<P>
   On schedule
</P>
<P>
   May 18-20 could be interesting if Clemens' turn in the rotation
pops up. If the Fenway faithful was peeved at seeing him return in
a Blue Jays uniform, how do you think they'll react to seeing the
Rocket sporting the road gray of the hated Yankees? There's no
excuse for the Red Sox to get off to a poor start. Their first 15
games are against Kansas City, Tampa Bay, the Chicago White Sox and
Detroit. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
