<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1395 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0401-     03-31 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0401-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFUGEES CONTINUE ARRIVING IN ALBANIA WITH ONLY STORIES OF DEATH
AND SUFFERING
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Vesa Guci's face will heal, but her heart is
another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had three children; now I have two,'' she says, sitting on
the edge of a hospital bed, her face scored with tiny cuts, her
right eye swollen and bruised. She doesn't cry. Her eyes seem
empty.
</P>
<P>
   About 4:30 Sunday afternoon, Serb forces surrounded her Kosovar
village of Demjan, Guci says. As she talks, she tends
absentmindedly to her small children, six and four. They also bear
wounds and bandages.
</P>
<P>
   Without warning, the soldiers began a grenade attack on the
village, she says. A grenade came through the window of her house
as she held her 18 month old daughter, Ndricesa (CQ). ``The grenade
exploded,'' she says. ``I didn't any more see my child.'' Her skirt
is splattered with blood.
</P>
<P>
   In the next bed, beside a large open window that offers a view
of Kosovo's snow-capped mountain, her husband, Dulles (CQ), lies
curled under a thick wool blanket. His face also is flaked with
scabs. He says nothing.
</P>
<P>
   As refugees continue to pour into Albania from Kosovo, the
cumulative scale of their tragedy is nearly overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Fathers tell of losing children. Wives cry for their husbands.
Many weep for homes they may never see again.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how many refugees crossed the border near
here since NATO air strikes began eight days ago. Almost no ethnic
Albanians coming from Kosovo have passports or other identifying
papers, and registration with exhausted border guards has been
haphazard at best.
</P>
<P>
   NATO estimates that 85,000 of the more than 120,000 refugees who
have fled Kosovo have come to Albania, the poorest country in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite photographs shown on television here reveal waves of
refugees heading for the border. Serb TV broadcasts have shown
thousands of refugees leaving the provincial capital, Pristina, on
foot.
</P>
<P>
   About 17,000 refugees arrived in Kukes Tuesday, officials said.
Of those, about 9,000 arrived after dark and passed the night in a
muddy field strewn with rocks and litter just outside this small,
extremely poor town.
</P>
<P>
   Some slept on the blankets they carried from their homes. Others
slept on beds of straw spread on the floors of carts towed from by
tractors from Kosovo. Before the refugee crisis, the local Red
Cross had only 500 blankets in stock, never expecting such a flood
of humanity. Babies slept in wooden cradles carried by their
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   There were no camp fires to ease the chill of the cold mountain
air. Many found protection from the biting wind only by huddling
against a waist-high stone wall that runs between the narrow road
between the border and Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   Once they make it to Kukes, most refugees are dispersed to other
towns and villages in Albania. About 12,000 were sheltered
Wednesday in this town of 50,000, where unemployment is extreme and
an average family of five makes $40 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions for the refugees here are miserable. Most stay in
private homes, but some have moved into vacant buildings and
covered the open windows with clear plastic to block the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Those with nowhere to stay must arrange for a place to sleep
every day. Many go door to door until they find a room.
</P>
<P>
   Housing them has been complicated because Kosovar families _
many numbering more than 30 _ often refuse to be separated.
</P>
<P>
   Bajram Sulaz, (CQ BOTH) an official with the local Red Cross,
said this tendency is a source of his greatest frustration. ``You
can find people to host five or six people, but 30? Who can host
30?''
</P>
<P>
   For the young in particular, these frustrations shield darker
feelings. Ramadan Shigjeci (CQ BOTH) is angry enough to kill. He
says his 18-year-old heart is full of hatred for the Serbs, and he
wants to join the guerrilla Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) to free
his homeland by force.
</P>
<P>
   ``For God's sake, they are driving our spirit out of us,'' he
says, his shoulders tensing when he projects the words.
</P>
<P>
   He cannot think of a future beyond the day he can go home or
conceive of ever accepting life under the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart cannot allow this because they have killed our people
and burned our homes. We sleep out under the sky. Our hope now is
with NATO,''
</P>
<P>
   He taps a foreigner on the chest and asks ``When will we go
home. When will the Serbs be gone?''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of an answer only causes more agitation.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, it has become common to see KLA fighters in
camouflage walking the streets of Kukes. Before, such brazen
openness would have been shocking. But the war has given Kukes the
feel of a city on the front line, with the KLA one of the forces
waiting to attack.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the tragedy, there are also moments of joy.
</P>
<P>
   For five days, Skender Berisha (CQ BOTH) had been waiting at the
checkpoint between Kosovo and Albania. In the confusion following a
weekend Serb order for ethnic Albanians to evacuate the town of
Suva Reka (CQ BOTH), he became separated from his 13-year-old
daughter, Dasina (CQ). The elementary school teacher had found his
wife but hadn't heard from his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, he again he took up the vigil, gazing down
the road back into Kosovo, studying the thousands of passing faces.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the morning, something caught his attention. He wiped
his eyes and looked down the rolling column of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Then his face opened into a smile. He ran to a cart behind one
of the tractors. It was his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Convulsing with tears, Dasina put her arms around her father's
neck. He cried with her.
</P>
<P>
   He pinched her cheek, as if to remind himself again that she was
real. ``The world makes no sense,'' he told her as he walked with
her toward their uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
