<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTRODOME-HNS &LR;      03-31 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTRODOME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astrodome's last hurrah
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was only fitting that the seven original Mercury astronauts
simultaneously threw out the first pitch at the Astrodome's
regular-season debut in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The futuristic building was best described as ``out of this
world.'' These seven men had literally been out of this world.
</P>
<P>
   So it's just as fitting that Neil Armstrong will be the one to
throw that first pitch when the Astros play their final season
opener at the Astrodome on Tuesday. Like the first man to step foot
on the moon, the Astrodome also is an American original.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Astrodome was an extravaganza; it was unique,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said. ``For me, it's still the best domed
stadium I've ever seen. It has stood the test of time as a
structure. But as a place to watch a baseball game, its time has
passed.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only a few years ago that the Astrodome celebrated its
30th birthday. Four years later, the stadium that once set new
standards for comfort and ingenuity is being put out to pasture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very sentimental person,'' said Astros owner Drayton
McLane, who led the charge for a new downtown stadium. ``I'll
always have great memories here, but we had to focus on what we
needed to be competitive and that was a downtown new arena, a place
where you can see the sun, the stars at night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome has seen its share of stars. Billy Graham led a
crusade there and is credited with tagging it the ``Eighth Wonder
of the World.'' Muhammad Ali fought Cleveland ``Big Cat'' Williams
there in 1965 to put it into boxing's international spotlight.
Billie Jean King and Bobby Riggs battled there for the sexes, the
30,472 fans in attendance setting a tennis record. There was the
``Game of the Century'' with Elvin Hayes and the Houston Cougars
vs. Lew Alcindor and the UCLA Bruins. There have been numerous NFL
games, college games, bloodless bullfights, rodeos, motocross,
gymnastics and rallies of all kind.
</P>
<P>
   But in most minds, the Astrodome will always be associated with
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It was ingenious and practical in a city where even the nicest
summer nights can be sweltering and much of the sport's schedule
coincides with the rainy season. People came from all parts of the
world just to see it in the building stages. Never has a sports
arena drawn so much international attention at an opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've covered several stadium openings, but this is the first
time I've ever had the stadium cover me,'' said Charlie Maher of
the San Diego Evening Tribune, one of the reporters on hand _ along
with 47,876 fans _ to watch the Astros beat the Mickey Mantle-led
New York Yankees 2-1 in an exhibition game. And it somehow seemed
appropriate that Mantle would etch his name into Astrodome history
with the first base hit and home run.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker was an 18-year-old pitcher with the Astros when the Dome
opened. Like many others who walked in behind him, he was in awe
upon first sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget the feeling I had when I first walked into
the Astrodome,'' Dierker said. ``I felt like I was walking into the
next century. It was a very dramatic experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were coming in from spring training, and it was nighttime.
The roof was just glowing. It was breathtaking. I had never seen
anything like it before.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Judge Roy Hofheinz intended. He was the visionary
who was convinced that air conditioning, theater-style seats and
skyboxes would put Houston on the map. It put Houston on the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first game I went to that first season,'' said
McLane, who wasn't at the opener but made sure to get his first
Dome experience that inaugural season. ``It was a Saturday night
game and I was driving to the parking lot and it was raining
really, really hard, and I thought, `This is crazy. They don't play
baseball when it rains really hard.' But of course, they did now.''
</P>
<P>
   They did a lot of things that had never been done before, using
4,500 skylights that stretched 208 feet tall, 6,600 tons of air
conditioning that blew so strong it could actually alter the path
of the ball, and those skyboxes, where hot meals were waiting for
special guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to look back now, with the technology we have, and
remember, but it was unique,'' said Astros president Tal Smith, who
was the Houston Sports Authority's liaison during construction of
the Dome. ``It was such a thrill to be associated with it. I think
everybody who had anything to do with it, down to the last
construction worker, had great pride and elation.''
</P>
<P>
   The most incredible sight was the giant scoreboard, with
electronic fireworks, charging bulls and cartoons. Fans, who in the
past only saw the basic game statistics, were suddenly bombarded
with information about pitchers and batters.
</P>
<P>
   That scoreboard, however, became extinct in 1988, when it was
torn up as part of a $50 million renovation that added 10,000 new
seats and 65 luxury boxes as a concession to Oilers owner Bud
Adams, who was threatening to move the team to Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the one thing that really set the stadium apart,''
Smith said. ``Once you accepted that it was a domed stadium, that
scoreboard was the one really unique thing. That was something the
county didn't pay for, the club arranged. The judge (Hofheinz)
wanted something that was really different, really creative. That
was my biggest regret, losing that scoreboard.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a few mistakes along the way, but they mostly were
the result of having no proven blueprint from which to work.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have known that the sun coming through the skylights
would sometimes blind the outfielders, making fly balls an
interesting challenge? Nobody had played baseball under skylights
before.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have known that when they painted those skylights to
remove the glare, the grass would die? Nobody had tried to grow a
baseball field indoors before.
</P>
<P>
   But those glitches did nothing to dampen the enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, there were plenty of skeptics,'' Smith said. ``But the
problems we had were because nothing had been tested before. There
were only two relatively new stadiums at that time, Dodger Stadium
and Candlestick Park. Candlestick Park wasn't a model anybody
wanted to use, and Dodger Stadium was an open-air stadium that
couldn't really compare. This was a novelty. Everything was for the
first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine domes have been built since then, the most recent being the
Alamodome, which opened in San Antonio in 1993 and is still looking
for a football or baseball team to call it home. The one with the
biggest price tag is Toronto's SkyDome, which cost a phenomenal
$500 million to build, more than twice any other (Atlanta's Georgia
Dome is second with a $220 million price tag).
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome, which was financed by a combination of public and
private funds, cost a mere $31.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   But with those new domes came new standards, most of them set by
SkyDome, which opened in 1989 and debuted the retractable roof,
guaranteeing perfect weather on any day or night. The SkyDome also
boasts a hotel, with rooms that overlook the outfield, a fitness
club, theater and seven restaurants and bars, including a Hard Rock
Cafe and the largest McDonald's in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Even non-domed stadiums have raised the sports-experience
expectation level with such amenities as shops, gourmet concession
stands, picnic areas and playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Astrodome, on which there have been minor improvements over
time, needed a major face-lift to bring it up to those 21st-century
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were about five years when the building itself drew
people,'' Dierker said. ``It was something to see. After that, it
wasn't such a wonder of the world anymore. The judge went bankrupt,
and it wasn't maintained the way it had been. By the late '70s, it
was an embarrassment. They later cleaned it up and it was looking
good again, but then they took the scoreboard down, and it was
never the same. It lost the look of being a ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   After this season, it will no longer be one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1929EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1397 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALLIED-TROOPS-     03-31 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALLIED-TROOPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE RAISES POSSIBILITY OF EUROPEAN TROOPS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and its European allies launched
emergency efforts Wednesday to alleviate the deepening refugee
crisis along the borders of Kosovo in a move that raised the
possibility of British, French and Italian ground forces entering
Kosovo to create safe havens backed by U.S. warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   An official at the White House's National Security Council
official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said European allies
have the option of dispatching ground troops to Kosovo at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The rising number of refugees has raised the prospect that NATO
ground forces might be called upon to thwart the campaign of
``ethnic cleansing'' that the Yugoslav government is carrying out
against the predominantly Moslem Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   To date, U.S. officials have ruled out the use of American
ground troops to supplement the eight-day U.S.-led allied air
assault against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in an interview with CBS News broadcast
Wednesday night, continued to rule out U.S. ground forces entering
the fray in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that he has chosen his words carefully in
describing U.S. policy about ground troops, Clinton said: ``The
thing that bothers me about introducing ground troops into a
hostile situation _ into Kosovo and into the Balkans _ is the
prospect of never being able to get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that by inserting U.S. ground forces into Kosovo to
stem ethnic cleansing ``you could be put in a position of, for
example, creating a Kosovar enclave that would keep you there
forever. And I don't believe that is an appropriate thing to be
discussing at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, emphasized earlier
that: ``We have no intention of sending ground troops into a combat
situation. Unless and until there's a peace agreement to implement,
the U.S. has no intention to send in ground troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether NATO troops other than American forces could be
used in Kosovo, White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said
European nations could decide at any time to deploy ground forces
into Kosovo to protect besieged civilians and provide humanitarian
relief to tens of thousands of ethnic Albanian Muslims driven into
the mountains and forests by a relentless Yugoslav onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart added: ``I'm not aware that we would oppose or have any
objection. It would be up to those nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the United States would provide close air support to
European ground forces dropped into Kosovo, Lockhart replied:
``That's a hypothetical question that I haven't heard raised or
answered.''
</P>
<P>
   A precedent for such a move was created in 1995 when U.S.
warplanes provided close air support to British and French ground
troops guarding U.N.-declared ``safe havens'' in Bosnia where
thousands of Bosnian Muslim refugees sought refuge from attacks by
Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, has recently
overhauled its command structure to enable European nations within
the 50-year-old military alliance to launch independent military
operations using manpower, arms and materiel from the 19-member
Cold War-era alliance.
</P>
<P>
   British, French and Italian officials have underscored the
plight of civilians in an apparent effort to build up domestic
public support for possible troop deployments.
</P>
<P>
   Italian forces have moved across the Adriatic Sea into
neighboring Albania to help with relief efforts for an estimated
100,000 Kosovars who have fled into Albania. NATO officials have
dispatched an assessment team to Albania to examine what additional
assistance might be provided by allied forces.
</P>
<P>
   British Defense Secretary George Robertson likens the Kosovo
massacres to the ``killing fields'' of Cambodia in the 1970s in an
apparent effort to sustain the support of 52 percent of the British
public who say they support the insertion of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, five former national security officials in
past administrations _ including former Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci and former U.S. ambassador to NATO, William Howard Taft IV
_ urged the introduction of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department spokesman Kenneth Bacon emphasized the
difficulty of moving allied ground forces into Kosovo, a
land-locked nation accessible only by air and 14 mountainous roads
that traverse either Albania or Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be easy to go into Kosovo,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Haass, a former National Security Council official in
the Bush administration, said individual NATO members could move on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not obvious to me that you will necessarily continue to
have consent or consensus,'' Haass said, referring to NATO's
traditional approach to decision making. ``Clearly, not all 19
members of NATO are going to be sending ground forces _ a much
smaller number are if we get to that point. This is going to come
down to the few countries who are really able to contribute at that
point.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration launched a wide ranging humanitarian
relief effort to augment allied efforts to deal with the
displacement of 580,000 ethnic Albanian Muslims in the Yugoslav
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Rubin said tens of thousands of
defenseless ethnic Albanian refugees have fled into the mountains
and forests of Kosovo to escape a relentless onslaught by some
40,000 Yugoslav troops and 300 Soviet-era tanks.
</P>
<P>
   More than 120,000 of the displaced Kosovars have fled into
neighboring nations, including Albania, Macedonia and the former
Yugoslav republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, announcing wide ranging U.S. efforts to lend a hand, said
the refugees were ``fleeing a murder machine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration funneled $50 million in new relief
assistance _ including $25 million to airlift food and relief
supplies to the Balkans and $25 million to U.N. High Commission on
Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials said up to 75,000 Albanian civilians and Kosovo
independence fighters were trapped in the Pagarusa Valley, about 30
miles southwest Kosovo's capital of Pristina, where Yugoslav forces
were ``raining artillery fire'' on them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
