<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CENTRAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Consecutive division titles give '99 Astros lofty goals
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By JOSEPH DUARTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Lucky for the Astros they move into a plush new ballpark next
season. It was becoming difficult to find space for division-title
banners in the Astrodome rafters.
</P>
<P>
   After winning two division championships in the first
quarter-century of the franchise's existence, the Astros begin the
season Tuesday in search of a third National League Central title
in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team comes into spring training expecting to get into the
postseason,'' said first baseman Jeff Bagwell. ``That's a realistic
goal. A lot of teams say it, but the realistic goal for our team is
to get to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The baseball landscape in Houston has undergone some changes.
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly two decades and a name change before the Astros
got their first division title in 1980, and another six years to
bring the second in '86. Who could forget the frustration from the
near misses that seemed to haunt the team over the next 11 years?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not winning for 11 years and all of a sudden doing it two
years in a row is something really special,'' second baseman Craig
Biggio said. ``We're now at the stage where we want to continue
that winning. It's a contagious feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, the elder statesman of the club who is entering his 11th
season, remembers a time when winning didn't come so easy. In fact,
it sometimes didn't come at all.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, his third major-league season, the Astros underwent a
transformation period and lost a club record-tying 97 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when reality set in,'' Biggio said. ``It was like,
``You guys don't have a chance this year. You're not going to win.'
We had a good team, we just didn't know how to win.''
</P>
<P>
   They haven't had a losing season since.
</P>
<P>
   After a break-even 82-82 season in '92, the Astros began their
current string of six consecutive winning seasons, a string
surpassed only by the Atlanta Braves (eight). Since 1993, the
Astros have the second-best winning percentage in the National
League (.546) and have finished no lower than third in their
division under current owner Drayton McLane Jr.
</P>
<P>
   And they've done it without the greatest resource of all _
money. In each of the past two seasons, the Astros have had the
lowest payroll among playoff qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last four or five years, we've seemed to be in the
division race.'' Bagwell said. ``I think you have to start putting
us in the category (of successful clubs). We'll see what happens in
the years to come. Hopefully the new stadium will help out and we
keep the payroll up to continue having great players like we have
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with winning on the field has come a different attitude in
the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros called it ``a relief'' to finally end their 11-year
string of futility in '97. Last season, many believed they had the
most talented club in the NL after they won a club-record 102 games
and put the Central Division race to bed long before the September
stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   Each venture into the postseason, however, has ended
prematurely. Because of that, the Astros are even hungrier entering
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys in this clubhouse that want to get back to the
dance and lose that black cloud hanging over us,'' Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is set.
</P>
<P>
   Winning is no longer a wish, but an expectation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be a part of,'' Bagwell said of the team's
newfound success. ``Every year is a different year. I don't know if
we're going to win 102 games and have that special club like we had
last year again, but with the talent we have anything is
possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
