<SLUG> BC-BBA-COUNTY </SLUG>
 STADIUM-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Brewers' declining County faces last call
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ALAN TRUEX &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
In its final year of major-league service, Milwaukee's County
Stadium clearly is past its prime. If it had one.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Ahuja, author of Fields of Dreams: A Guide to Visiting and
Enjoying all 30 Major League Ballparks, calls it ``the league's
shabbiest outdoor stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't matter which league it's in. It has switched from
the National to the American and back to the National and found few
admirers in either place.
</P>
<P>
   It was gray and charmless when built, and a 1973 remodeling did
not redeem it. Technology has made limited inroads here; the
scoreboard graphics are basic.
</P>
<P>
   But however wonderful the new and nearby Miller Park turns out
to be, it's unlikely to match the welcome its forerunner received.
On March 15, 1953, some 10,000 people withstood freezing weather
for the first tour of County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, a stadium with 27,982 seats accommodated 53,357
as the Milwaukee Braves, formerly of Boston, beat the St. Louis
Cardinals 3-2 on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves drew a major-league record 1,826,397 in their first
season, and they set new attendance standards the next two years.
The honeymoon was extended when they won the World Series in 1957
and a pennant in '58, before losing a two-game playoff in '59.
</P>
<P>
   From 1953 to 1961, the Braves were consistent contenders. A
heavy-wooded lineup helped pitchers Warren Spahn and Lew Burdette
collect a combined 344 wins during that nine-year period.
</P>
<P>
   But crowds dwindled when the pitching faltered and the Braves
slipped. By 1966, they were standing in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   County Stadium then lay dormant, except for a few Green Bay
Packers football games, until 1970. That year, automobile dealer
Bud Selig, who is now the baseball commissioner, bought the Seattle
Pilots, moved them to Milwaukee and renamed them the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Squeezed by a small-market budget, the Brewers haven't won a
division title since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium rarely fills its present capacity of 53,192. But
some say if the crowds were bigger, they'd be dangerous. This city
may be more interested in drinking beer than winning pennants.
</P>
<P>
   The County Stadium mascot, Bernie the Brewer, slides from his
chalet into a giant foamy mug following every homer by the home
team. Instead of the 1908 Broadway hit ``Take Me Out to the Ball
Game,'' Brewers fans in the seventh-inning stretch sing ``Roll Out
the Barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Brewers are losing, fans can drink to forget. But they
also have their fond memories. County Stadium was the workplace of
Eddie Mathews, Rollie Fingers, Paul Molitor and Robin Yount. It was
the first and last domain of home run king Hank Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   And there are more subtle memories, equally cherished. Jeff
Torborg, a former big-league catcher and manager, has said: ``What
I remember most about the old stadiums are their smells. Ebbets
Field smelled like popcorn.''
</P>
<P>
   County Stadium smells like spilled beer and smoked meats. The
juicy bratwurst beats a hot dog, and fans also appreciate a
convenient setting by Interstate 94 and an upper deck that offers a
panorama of steeples, smokestacks and the Allen Brady Tower's
imposing clock. The bleachers are inviting, with unobstructed sight
lines. On the other hand, the bullpens are the only ones in the
majors with restricted views of the field.
</P>
<P>
   The foul area is narrow, and fans are close to the action. A
longtime favorite Brewer, Gorman Thomas, observed: ``They know when
to cheer, they know when to boo, and they know when to drink beer:
They do it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The drinking begins in the pre-game tailgate parties and flows
from there. Next year, the party moves to a park named for a beer
company. Expect the scene to be essentially the same. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
