<HEADER>
A1402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TUBES-ART-1185(     03-31 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TUBES-ART-1185(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE COMPANY LOOKS TO RIDE HDTV-WAVE INTO U.S. MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Md., Fla.) (ART ADV: Graphic of timeline of Japanese and Korean domestic
television production and exports to the U.S. is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think ``Made in China,'' and plastic toys, T-shirts, sneakers
and simple tape recorders come to mind, all assembled cheaply in
anonymous factories for foreign brands.
</P>
<P>
   One Chinese manufacturer, Konka Group Co., wants to change that
image. With considerable hubris, Konka is seeking to make the leap
from a well-known brand in China to global consumer electronics
maker by grabbing a share of the U.S. market for television sets.
</P>
<P>
   The American market is among the toughest in the world, but
Konka is betting that it can compete in large part by being among
the first and the cheapest to offer Americans the next generation
of TV sets: those that will offer the digitally improved picture
and sound of high-definition television.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to come up the food chain in terms of
technology,'' said Jack C. Fensterstock, president of the China
Capital Corp., a venture capital firm in Bethesda, Md., that
invests in Chinese companies, but not in Konka.
</P>
<P>
   While it is too early to start talking about China Inc., Konka's
plans point to new ambitions among Chinese manufacturers, ambitions
that echo those of young Japanese and South Korean manufacturers in
earlier decades. A slowdown in China, after two decades of
explosive growth, combined with fierce domestic competition, has
forced Chinese companies to consider how to pursue growth in
foreign markets more aggressively _ even if it means going
head-to-head against the world's leaders in technology and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese manufacturers ``really want to show that they've come a
long way,'' Fensterstock said. ``It's a national strategy to do
this in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Wu, Konka's head of sales and marketing in the United
States, said: ``We think we are strong enough to come to this
country. This is the right time. We don't see the right time in
another five years.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that other Chinese companies were tracking Konka's
progress in the United States. ``Everybody's watching us,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But breaking into the $8 billion U.S. television market will not
be easy. Some 98 percent of households already own at least one
set. And Konka must still enlist a major distributor to get its
products in national chains if it is to face up to the firepower of
bigger and better-known manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans take their televisions very seriously,'' said
Nick Donatiello, president and chief executive of Odyssey Group, a
market research firm in San Francisco. ``This is not a frivolous
thing. Brand names matter a lot, and the top brands are very
powerful. It's not enough to have your televisions sitting in Good
Guys or Circuit City.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Konka's history fits a familiar pattern in consumer
electronics. Like the Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. of Japan,
maker of the Panasonic brand, and LG Group of South Korea, maker of
Goldstar, Konka began assembling electronics for foreign
manufacturers drawn by cheap labor. And as those Asian giants did,
Konka is counting on taking a great leap forward in consumer
electronics through technology.
</P>
<P>
   Konka contends that high-definition television, still in its
infancy, offers an opening for a newcomer. The sale of HDTV sets is
but a trickle _ fewer than 20,000 sets since their introduction in
August _ and programming is limited. Yet as HDTV's bright, vivid
picture and crystal-clear sound seduce more consumers, and as
broadcasters step up their transition to digital programming, the
potential is vast in a nation of 250 million conventional sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the HDTV revolution as a great opportunity,'' Wei
Rong-chen, Konka's president, said in a telephone interview from
Hong Kong. ``As a new brand bringing in a new technology, we can
deliver a message to the consumer that Konka is not just a common
television manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   If Konka puts its sets on American shelves, _ no major regional
or national retailer has so far agreed to carry them _ many
consumer electronics analysts expect its greatest selling point
will be price. Konka plans to introduce a $3,000 32-inch-screen
HDTV set this fall. At the moment, that is less than half the price
of sets with more familiar names, now selling for $7,000 to $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, however, the price advantage will narrow
somewhat, as HDTV sets from RCA, made by Thomson Multimedia of
France, and from Panasonic and other big names are expected to be
offered for several thousand dollars less. Hitachi of Japan is
already selling an HDTV set for $2,999. Hitachi's and Konka's sets,
as well as most others, will still require the purchase of a
set-top box, costing at least $700, to translate analog signals
into digital ones until more HDTV programming becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   Konka says its digital set is made with technology the company
developed in China and at its new research and development plant in
San Jose, Calif. The company will provide the cabinets and much of
the circuitry for the sets. The picture tubes, the most costly part
of a set, are provided by other electronics companies like Thomson
and Toshiba _ a common practice in the industry. And the HDTV chip
which powers the sets will also come from a foreign maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably won't be the highest resolution set,'' said
Richard Doherty, director of research at Envisioneering, a market
research firm, who saw a Konka set at a recent trade show.
Nonetheless, he believes that price alone can attract buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it's the full quality of a Sony,'' he said,
``but wow, it's going to be an awful lot of value for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   While price may give Konka an in-road in the United States, it
will never be able to compete with Sony and the other giants until
it develops its own technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time they have to wait for the Japanese companies to come
up with a new product, and then they copy,'' said Yasheng Huang, an
associate professor at the Harvard Business School. ``No Chinese
company has permanent competitiveness. You try to catch up with the
innovators, but you're never the first.''
</P>
<P>
   Konka is not wanting for ambition. It is entering the United
States on its own, a difficult task given that two much bigger
companies, Thomson and Royal Philips Electronics of the
Netherlands, established themselves by buying American brands.
Thomson bought RCA in 1987, and Philips bought Magnavox in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Konka began selling some of its conventional analog
sets, including models in bright blue or silver cabinets, in
California and Florida through small, regional consumer electronics
retailers like Brandsmart U.S.A and Fry's Electronics. The Home
Shopping Network has begun offering a white 13-inch Konka set for
about $120. Konka will also sell digital video disk players and two
television set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Konka says it has shipped 25,000 conventional
televisions to the United States; its goal is 250,000 sets this
year, anticipating that only 2,000 will be HDTV sets. Those are
very modest goals, given that more than 26 million sets were
shipped to United States dealers last year, according to the
Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Konka, based in Shenzhen, a boom town on Hong Kong's border,
started assembling small, portable television sets for Thomson, and
others in 1979, when the Chinese economy first opened up. The
company began selling televisions under its own name in 1993 and
now has 25 percent of China's television market _ more than
Panasonic or Sony. Konka sold 4.7 million sets in China last year.
</P>
<P>
   It also tackled overseas markets in Australia, Russia, Latin
America and the Middle East. In those markets, Konka was able to
gain market share by using the same price strategy that made it a
success in China: underpricing better-known brands and offering
retailers greater margins to entice them to carry the sets. And
Konka placed stronger emphasis on advertising, marketing and brand
image than other Chinese exporters had done in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing strategies that worked well in China and elsewhere,
however, may not translate in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're aiming their pitch directly at price and at Sony,''
said Kathleen Maher, editor in chief of The Peddie Report, which
follows the graphics and multimedia industries. ``They have
televisions in colored boxes. I have no idea why American consumers
would be interested in colored boxes. If you're trying to compete
with Sony, it seems contradictory to have  &UR;  &LR; purple television
sets.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Konka does have other advantages. All its products are now
manufactured in China. Beginning in July, conventional television
sets destined for the United States will be made at a
30,000-square-foot plant it is building in Tijuana, Mexico.
Manufacturing in China and Mexico will help keep Konka's costs low.
Konka says it costs the company about $2,000 to produce an HDTV set
and about $400 to $500 to manufacture a 32-inch conventional set.
</P>
<P>
   It costs the big manufacturers on average about $12,000 for an
HDTV _ more than its price, as demand is still low _ and $650 for a
32-inch conventional set, Doherty of the Envisioneering Group
estimated. Konka has ``cost structures few companies can afford to
beat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Konka is barely on the radar screen of the
consumer electronics industry.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Arland, a spokesman for Thomson, said the company was not
worried about the prospect of a $3,000 HDTV set from Konka, noting
that ``$3,000 is still a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   `` People pick names that they know, that have figured out this
technology and that they know are not going to disappear,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Konka executives are able to dispel whatever doubts
American shoppers may have about quality or about the wisdom of
purple TV sets, they can take heart in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point,'' Doherty noted, `` no one had heard of the
brand name Sony either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
