<HEADER>
A1405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-TIGERSTADIUM-HNS &LR;      03-31 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TIGER </SLUG>
 STADIUM-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
It's the final season for Tiger Stadium, an eyesore to some, a
keepsake to others
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
In this decade, the walls of baseball shrines are tumbling down:
Shoeless Joe Jackson's haunt, Comiskey Park, in 1991; Hank Aaron's
Atlanta Stadium in '96. And the pace of obsolescence is quickening.
Within the next year, Major League Baseball will abandon five
ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Few may mourn the exodus from dowdy County Stadium in Milwaukee,
the wind-slapped Candlestick of San Francisco and the
once-futuristic domes of Houston and Seattle that are derided now
as synthetic and sterile.
</P>
<P>
   But Detroit's Tiger Stadium is another story, one that binds
history and myth and generations. On a sliver of acreage at the
fringe of downtown, Ty Cobb menacingly roamed, Al Kaline
methodically churned base hits, and Mark Fidrych stood on the mound
and talked to the baseball as he massaged it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone denies Tiger Stadium is long in the tooth. Its
annoying anachronisms include 5,000 obstructed-view seats and zero
parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Sparky Anderson, former Tigers manager, called it ``a rundown
shack'' and said, ``Those people who want to keep it for their
grandchildren have lost their marbles.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some baseball fans value tradition over marbles and
money. They claim the demise of Tiger Stadium was ordained only to
extract more revenue from luxury suites and the naming rights for
the new Comerica Park.
</P>
<P>
   When their storehouse of memories was assailed in 1988 as
outdated and worn-out, some 1,200 fans congregated on a chilling
rainy April day for a ``stadium hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Buchta, co-founder of the Tiger Stadium Fan Club, said,
``There isn't a single spot in Detroit that carries more
associations for the people of this city than Tiger Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Some associations were pleasant, such as the 1984 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Some were not, such as the riot that followed that Series and
the accompanying fireworks: a police car billowing flames a few
yards from the ballpark's gates.
</P>
<P>
   But no one can blame the stadium, a classic on which the
fawned-over Oriole Park at Camden Yards in Baltimore was loosely
based.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's traditionalists eschew the new; they believe in
stadium reincarnation and prayed for it to happen one more time at
the corner of Michigan and Trumbull.
</P>
<P>
   From 1896 to 1912, that ground supported the wood-walled Bennett
Park, which originally seated 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the steel-and-concrete beginnings of Tiger Stadium,
which first seated 23,000 and was called Navin Field. This was the
stage for the indomitable Cobb, the spike-glinting, marauding
psychopath of the basepaths.
</P>
<P>
   In 1923 the grandstand was double-decked to seat 30,000. By
1938, the double-decking encircled the park, bringing capacity to
52,416. The seating has since been reduced to 46,000 with the
installation of a patio grill.
</P>
<P>
   The 1938 renovation brought an endearing architectural anomaly.
An overhanging deck protrudes in right field, turning 315-foot fly
balls into home runs. Below, a 325-foot drive can be an out or a
blooper-film highlight, depending on how the fielder negotiates
shadows caused by the overhang.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium has a triples-inducing center field distance of 440
feet and homer-boosting power alleys of 365 and 370.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are closer to players than in any other big-league venue.
Detroit's Hall of Fame third baseman George Kell said, ``I always
liked to hear the people, and at Tiger Stadium I could hear
everything that was said.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon they'll all say goodbye to this eroded landmark, while
other baseball cathedrals are similarly besieged. The fall of Tiger
Stadium puts more pressure on Boston's quirky, cozy Fenway Park and
on New York's towering pantheon, Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The writing is on the angled, aging walls. Owners of today's
baseball teams seem more interested in luxury suites than sweet
memories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
