<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL </SLUG>
 WEST-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Dodgers, Diamondbacks and Rockies lay out millions to improve their
chances
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The most competitive division in baseball got a bit tighter during
the offseason, with every team in the National League West except
the Giants making major news.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers broke the bank by making Kevin Brown the
highest-paid player in the game, and they also hired Davey Johnson
to manage their pricey collection of players.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Colorado hired the man considered by most to
be the best strategic manager in the business. If Jim Leyland can't
figure out how to win consistently at Coors Field, perhaps no one
can.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks made their share of headlines, signing Randy
Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre and Armando Reynoso to upgrade their
starting rotation significantly.
</P>
<P>
   The defending league champion San Diego Padres were in the news,
but for all the wrong reasons. They lost many key members of their
1998 team, including Brown.
</P>
<P>
   So which team maneuvered itself into the best position? Probably
the Dodgers. They are the early favorites to represent the NL in
the World Series, and with good reason. In addition to Brown, they
added Devon White and Todd Hundley, who, if healthy, gives them a
murderous lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies will be waiting in the wings if the Dodgers slip up,
and you can never count out the feisty Giants, who always seem to
find a way to plant themselves in the middle of the postseason
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the rise
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Diamondbacks: Even after adding Johnson and the others,
perhaps they're premature when they talk of reaching the postseason
this year. But success is not far away. Give this team a year
together and some time to learn how to win, and they just might
make some noise.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the slide
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Padres: The dismantling of their World Series team
wasn't quite as dramatic as what the Marlins did after the 1997
season, but it was enough to represent a major setback for the
Padres. They'll drop from the proverbial penthouse to the outhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Overrated
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Sanders, Padres: We'd rather not hear anything else about
how talented he is. We'd just as soon see it, and so far, we
haven't _ at least not with any consistency. The oft-injured
outfielder will break hearts in San Diego just as he did for years
in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek, Dodgers: As long as he was hitting, everyone
seemed willing to overlook the fact he was a defensive liability at
shortstop. But his offensive numbers have dipped in each of the
past two seasons, and his defense hasn't gotten much better.
</P>
<P>
   Underrated
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kent, Giants: There are so many good second basemen in the
majors that Kent often gets overlooked. But it's hard not to notice
his remarkable production. He hit 31 homers and drove in 128 runs
despite missing a month of the 1998 season because of a knee
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bochy, Padres: This soft-spoken former Astros catcher is
respected by his peers, and players love to play for him, but he
seldom gets mentioned among the top managers in baseball. He pushed
all of the right buttons during the 1998 postseason. If the Padres
avoid the basement in 1999, it will be because of Bochy.
</P>
<P>
   Up and coming
</P>
<P>
   Matt Clement, Padres: Management fought the temptation to rush
him to the big leagues last season, and it proved to be the right
move. The Padres went to the World Series without him. But now that
Kevin Brown is gone, they're looking for an ace in San Diego, and
Clement might ultimately fit the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre, Dodgers: The 20-year-old Dominican had no
business being in the big leagues last season. Then again, few
decisions made sense during the time Tommy Lasorda ran the Dodgers
last season. Is Beltre ready this year? We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   Down and out
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Olson, Diamondbacks: Perhaps his 30-save season of a year
ago was a sign Olson is back. We think not. He's a good bet for the
biggest comedown of the season, and the Diamondbacks would have
been wise to sign a proven insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Rojas, Dodgers: A few years ago he was one of the
up-and-coming closers in baseball. But after failed stints with the
Cubs and Mets, Rojas is merely an overpaid middle reliever. He hit
bottom last season with a 6.05 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   On the spot
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, Dodgers: We already expected a lot from him;
imagine how those expectations will increase now that he's being
paid $15 million a year. If he doesn't pitch the Dodgers to the
World Series, his seven-year, $105 million contract will face even
more criticism.
</P>
<P>
   John Moores, Padres: He truly is one of the most likable owners
in baseball, but the offseason series of events has threatened his
popularity after voters approved a new downtown baseball stadium.
The Padres better not finish in last place.
</P>
<P>
   What if
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown finally has an off year, Gary Sheffield's back
problems persist, and Todd Hundley never gets healthy enough to be
the player he was two years ago? The Dodgers would be in big
trouble under that scenario, and with an $86 million payroll, no
excuses will be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   On schedule
</P>
<P>
   There will be several marquee pitching matchups on Opening Day,
but none better than the one at Dodger Stadium, where Kevin Brown
and Randy Johnson lock horns. Don't you just know Johnson is hoping
his turn in the rotation will come up during the July 18-20 series
when the Diamondbacks play at Seattle. The Big Unit makes his first
return to the Astrodome April 26-29. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
