<SLUG> BC-BBN-CANDLESTICK-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Giants finally escape from Candlestick
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ALAN TRUEX &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
It has withstood raging gales and a deadly earthquake that barely
made it shudder. But Candlestick Park no longer can keep its
lifelong tenants. Next year the San Francisco Giants move to a new
home downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Many say good riddance. Whenever National League players are
polled on which stadium they least enjoy, cold, damp and blustery
Candlestick (now officially 3Com Park) wins overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
   A former Giants first baseman, Jack Clark, was asked what could
improve the stadium, and he replied, ``Dynamite.''
</P>
<P>
   Accessible only through a snarlway of traffic, a remote 12 miles
from America's most scenic city, Candlestick is the Mistake by the
Bay, a veritable Cave of Winds.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Stu Miller was blown from the mound as he began
his windup in an All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   This is where popups are adventures and outfielders run through
hot-dog wrappers leaping along the grass like baby kangaroos. The
Astros' Derek Bell was picked off base while enthralled by such
dancing garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Giants marketing director Mario Alioto said the team ``wants to
have some fun'' promoting the park's farewell season. So its
publicity campaign shows a picture of ballplayers turning double
plays while a tornado whirls around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love it or hate it,'' Alioto said, ``this park is where we've
had our baseball memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most memorable event occurred on Oct. 17, 1989, when
an earthquake struck just before Game 3 of the World Series between
the Giants and Oakland A's. Remarkably, the sold-out stadium held
up to the magnitude 7.1 quake without anyone being injured.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, more soothing memories. Candlestick housed
four Hall of Fame players in the 1960s: Willie Mays, Willie
McCovey, Orlando Cepeda and Juan Marichal. The wonder is this
surfeit of talent never produced a World Series championship. Hal
Lanier, a Giants shortstop in the '60s, said the reason was that
``all that team tried to do was hit home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was understandable. The gusting wind suits fly-ball
hitters, though it favors lefthanded power over right. Originally,
the stadium seated 42,500 and was open-ended and even windier than
today's enclosed edition that accommodates 63,000.
</P>
<P>
   While Candlestick can be sunny and pleasant in early afternoon,
it turns into a baseball torture chamber near sunset, when dense
fog and 30-60 mph winds rush in. Fans know to bring coats and
blankets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, the team began rewarding those who stayed for extra
innings of night games by issuing the Croix de Candlestick, a medal
portraying icicles hanging off the letters of the Giants logo.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Giants schedule more day games than any
team in baseball other than the Chicago Cubs. Of course, this means
attendance and revenues suffer.
</P>
<P>
   As ill-conceived as this facility seems, it made sense for
developer Charles Harney, who sold Candlestick Point to the city of
San Francisco in 1957 for $2.7 million. Harney showed the land to
mayor George Christopher and Giants owner Horace Stoneham in the
morning, when the weather is calmest.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was fooled. As the stadium was being finished, Vice
President Richard Nixon, a native Californian, gushed that it would
be ``one of the most beautiful baseball parks of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   However, soon after opening in 1960, it became one of the great
white elephants of the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are confident baseball will boom in popularity when
Pacific Bell Park debuts next spring. The new stadium is located in
what is said to be the warmest part of the city. But it will be
nestled up to the bay, and many San Franciscans suspect it, too,
will be tormented by fog and wind.
</P>
<P>
   And they wouldn't have it any other way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
