<SLUG> BC-BORDER-BODIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE BODIES PULLED FROM RIO GRANDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL CENIZO, Texas _ Five bodies were pulled from the muddy Rio
Grande here Wednesday, and investigators were trying to determine
whether they drowned while trying to sneak into Texas or were the
victims of foul play.
</P>
<P>
   This much was known: Four of the men died with their boots on.
</P>
<P>
   The decomposed bodies, first spotted by a Border Patrol
helicopter, were found along a four-mile stretch of the river near
the poor community El Cenizo, 15 miles south of Laredo, and nearby
Rio Bravo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a possibility of foul play because they were wearing
their boots,'' Santos Benavides, a justice of the peace, said.
``Nobody crosses the river with their boots on.''
</P>
<P>
   The bodies, all male, were found along stretches of the river
that are notorious for smuggling and illegal immigrants, but most
people wade the river in shorts and with their clothes wrapped in
plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen anything like this,'' Benavides said as he
stood along a bank of the river where the bodies were photographed
and placed in plastic bags. ``Five at the same time _ never.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities reportedly pulled a sixth body from the
river.
</P>
<P>
   No identification was found on the bodies, but one had a silver
pendant of an elephant and two others had tattoos, one of a rose,
the other of the initials ``J.M.'' One was nude.
</P>
<P>
   The gruesome discovery came in the wake of a Sunday incident in
which a Border Patrol agent jumped into the river and rescued three
Mexican men who were trapped in the current while trying to cross
on an inner tube.
</P>
<P>
   The river is swollen by rains and the heavy release from a
nearby reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican consular officials were dispatched to the morgue in
Laredo late Wednesday to try to determine if the men were from
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very sad,'' Luis Humberto Ramirez, the Mexican consul
said. ``We still do not know if they were Mexicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of their national origin, Ramirez said, the bodies
serve as a reminder that illegal immigrants risk their lives trying
to sneak across the river, known as the Rio Bravo, or Brave River
in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rio Bravo is a river that looks calm, but it is always
dangerous,'' said Ramirez, who earlier this week met with Border
Patrol officials to discuss how to prevent more people from dying
along the river.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Mexican officials have again agreed to launch a joint
operation to warn people of the dangers of crossing into the United
States. They risk drowning in the Rio Grande, dehydration, falling
under the wheels of freight cars heading north out of Mexico, and
tangling with thieves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is always dangerous,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogelio Nunez, the head of a Harlingen, Texas-based immigration
rights group, said more deaths would likely occur as new Border
Patrol operations force people to cross in more desolate and
unfamiliar areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in favor of increased enforcement and this policy
where they knowingly move folks from safer crossings,'' said Nunez,
executive director of Proyecto Libertad. ``Deaths will occur.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1936EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
