<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Thursday, April 1, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact David Brady at the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   CURFEW-SUCCESS (Los Angeles) _ Stiff enforcement of a teen-age
curfew in the suburban northeast San Fernando Valley area of Los
Angeles has driven down burglaries and property crimes by 25
percent so far this year, but crime is up in other areas where the
curfew is not a priority. Civil libertarians and teen-agers hate
the curfew, however. By Phillip W. Browne. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEAF-PASSOVER (Burbank, Calif.) _ For Jewish families worldwide,
the Passover meal is a time for stories and prayers read aloud
about the exodus of Jews from Egypt, a ritual that leaves many deaf
Jews feeling left out. This year, the Jewish Deaf Community Center
in Burbank won a $5,000 grant which will allow them to set up a
multimedia seder at Temple Emanuel. The money will pay for special
projectors and translators.By Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ARCO-EXIT (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles is losing another Fortune
1000 company. This time it's Arco, the multinational oil company,
which is being bought by London-based BP Amoco according to reports
Wednesday. Once the deal is completed, as is expected, only a few
major companies will be headquartered within Los Angeles city
limits. By Gregory J. Wilcox. (Will move in the ``f'' financial
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WELLPOINT-BID (Los Angeles) _ Officials at the nonprofit Rocky
Mountain Hospital and Medical Systems said Wednesday they have sent
a letter to Woodland Hills, Calif.-based WellPoint Health Networks
asking the company to clarify its bid for the plan. Earlier this
week WellPoint offered to buy the insurer for between $200 million
and $240 million after learning Rocky Mountain had agreed to be
bought by another managed care firm for $165 million. By Ben
Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
