<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRASH-$ADV04-COX     03-31 1700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRASH-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE GARBAGE BUSINESS IS BECOMING COMPACTED
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the government presses its widely publicized
charges that Microsoft Corp. tried to unfairly dominate America's
access to computer software, a rapid consolidation of corporate
power is quietly taking place around a humbler but equally
pervasive part of life: garbage.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some critics think, your garbage bill inevitably
will go up and the national trend toward recycling will reverse.
</P>
<P>
   If a series of announced mega-mergers is approved, the country
will enter the next millennium with two companies in control of
picking up, hauling off, dumping and recycling more than half its
municipal and industrial solid waste.
</P>
<P>
   The two corporations will be Waste Management Inc. of Houston
and the entity created by the merger of Browning-Ferris Industries,
also of Houston, and Allied Waste Industries of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   They will share more than $18 billion in annual revenue for
handling what's left when we get through with newspapers, coffee
grounds, milk jugs and, for that matter, just about everything
else.
</P>
<P>
   That's more than half of the estimated $35 billion Americans pay
every year for garbage collection and disposal. What's left will be
divided among local governments, one other national garbage
collector and several thousand small local and regional haulers.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidations are being driven primarily by the companies'
efforts to deal with depressed revenues caused by a national glut
of landfills and have been followed by price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts also say the national trend toward recycling will
reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Big solid waste companies lose money every time something is
recycled instead of going into one of their landfills, said Peter
Anderson, a Madison, Wis., solid waste consultant and recycling
promoter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern I have is that recycling is going to be hitting
some rough times,'' he said. ``An oligopoly in waste will naturally
extend itself over recycling and put the brakes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone thinks consolidation in the business is necessarily
a bad thing for consumers. Large companies may be more efficient
and cost-effective than small, ``mom-and-pop'' garbage haulers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running a landfill has gotten to be a pretty complex business
in a lot of respects,'' said Winston Porter, president of the Waste
Policy Center and a former assistant administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency. ``When I was at EPA eight or 10
years ago, there were 6,000 to 8,000 landfills in this country.
Today there are 2,900.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of their size or the size of the company that owns
them, all landfills must meet federal environmental standards,
Porter pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation in the business of hauling and disposing of
municipal and industrial solid waste has been going on for years.
It has accelerated in the past decade, first because of new federal
regulations for waste disposal, and second because of an unexpected
national ``glut'' in waste disposal sites, industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations were put into effect in 1989 and 1990 by the
EPA. They required that landfills be lined with thick plastic and a
layer of compacted clay several feet thick. The landfills also must
have systems of collecting and removing the water that leaches
through buried waste, wells for monitoring underground water
supplies, and systems for managing gases, principally methane,
given off by virtually every landfill.
</P>
<P>
   With these regulations, the local city dump was replaced by a
``solid waste landfill,'' a highly engineered system for managing
millions of tons of garbage. As economies of scale took over, the
landfills became very large.
</P>
<P>
   The country's busiest landfill, the county-owned Puente Hills
Landfill in Los Angeles, received 3.7 million tons of garbage and
other solid waste in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But while city and county governments operate dozens of
``mega-landfills'' built or modified to meet the new EPA standards,
most facilities are privately owned. Until this year, four
companies _ Waste Management Inc., Browning-Ferris Industries, USA
Waste Inc., and Allied Waste Industries _ owned most of them.
</P>
<P>
   This year, USA Waste, the third-largest company, took over Waste
Management, the largest. And last month, Allied Waste Industries,
until last year the fourth largest, announced that it was taking
over Browning-Ferris Industries, the second largest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the culmination of many years of activity,'' said Neil
Seldman, president of the Washington-based Institute for Local
Self-Reliance, a recycling advocacy group. ``The large companies
have spent years driving small haulers out of business or buying
them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Seldman said that because they now control so many landfills,
the big companies can control the industry by setting the price for
dumping.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials say that when they issued the 1990 rules, they
expected large regional landfills to replace smaller local dumping
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not make good economic sense to build a small
landfill, if you could get together with your neighbor and build a
larger landfill,'' said Robert Dellinger, director of the EPA
division of municipal and industrial solid waste. ``We projected
there would be a reduction of the number of landfills.''
</P>
<P>
   What was not anticipated by EPA _ or anyone else _ was that the
a country that was worrying in 1990 about ``running out of places
to put garbage'' would overbuild and suddenly find itself with too
many landfills. As they grew and bought up competitors, the handful
of national solid waste haulers were largely responsible for this
development.
</P>
<P>
   Now, said Anderson, a landfill glut has developed in the past
few years, resulting in prices that are depressed by competition.
Small ``mom and pop'' haulers, who typically empty their trucks in
downtown ``transfer stations'' operated by regional haulers and
landfill operators, could shop for the lowest fees.
</P>
<P>
   But as weaker landfill operators were bought up by the national
firms, these fees started rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 'problem' pricing entities have been removed from most
markets,'' the investment banking firm Deutsche Morgan Grenfell
noted approvingly in a 1997 report. ``Mid-American Waste, which had
been in financial trouble for years, had been pricing low in order
to maximize cash flow throughout the Midwest and several other
markets. Mid-American was acquired by USA Waste in (the second
quarter of the year) and pricing was improved immediately
throughout these markets.''
</P>
<P>
   When a Deutsche Morgan Grenfell stock analyst says landfill
prices have ``improved,'' she does not mean your garbage bill just
went down.
</P>
<P>
   After USA Waste took over Waste Management Inc., it kept the
former company's name. It did not keep its landfill prices. Within
weeks of the Justice Department's approval of the deal, USA Waste
announced a 40 percent increase in these prices at many landfills.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said that while the Justice Department requires merging
companies to divest themselves of landfills in areas where mergers
would otherwise depress competition, he believes ``price
signaling'' and other informal means of avoiding competition will
inevitably lead to continuing price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Pressures on the industry will almost demand that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the industries of hauling and disposing of garbage
should be divided, so that haulers compete for local and regional
hauling contracts, and landfill operators then compete for the
haulers' business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solid waste industry is about to reach its end game after
nearly three decades of consolidation,'' he said. ``That is the
point where two or three major integrated firms control the
landfills in many of the major markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the Department of Justice seems to be
preoccupied with the giant Microsoft case and has little resources
to spare for the extensive effort that massive divestitures would
require,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the industry is under ``enormous pressure from
Wall Street to continue to demonstrate high earnings,'' but without
monopoly or oligopoly power is too low-tech to do that. The only
way to meet the pressure is to artificially raise prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the depressed landfill market is only one thorn in
the industry's side.
</P>
<P>
   Recycling is another.
</P>
<P>
   Seldman said studies have shown that hauling a piece of garbage
to a landfill is six times as profitable to a waste disposal
company as recycling it, even when the company collects an extra
fee for handling recyclable materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way they do recycling is under duress,'' he said.
``They will use their size to control the bins and the trucks and
to discourage recycling wherever they can.''
</P>
<P>
   According to some estimates, about 27 percent of America's waste
stream is now recycled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get to 55 or 60 percent diversion into recycling, then
the waste component will be the minority portion,'' Anderson said.
National waste firms ``are not stupid. They are not going to let
that happen. They have to make sure that recycling does not
maintain the option of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Railel, a spokesman for Waste Management, said the company
will continue to ``grow'' its recycling operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple answer is that recycling is part of our core
business,'' he said. ``We are continuing to grow that business. It
is part of the service that our customers are requesting, and we
will continue to provide it.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Waste Management is the ``largest operator of
recycling facilities'' in the country and last year processed over
5 million tons of recyclables. Recycling accounts for slightly less
than 5 percent of the company's total revenue, he said, down by
about one-sixth from the revenue share it generated for the
previous Waste Management Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Allied Waste Industries did not respond to
telephone messages.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
