<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REYNOLDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' Reynolds might become an ace in place
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
When it comes to the Astros' pitching staff, the talk always comes
back to the team's need for a No. 1-type pitcher, somebody to call
``ace.''
</P>
<P>
   They may already have one.
</P>
<P>
   In the past nine months, righthander Shane Reynolds has faced
the acquisition of Randy Johnson, rumors of his name being on the
trading block and a failed attempt to land Roger Clemens. Through
it all, he remains in an Astros uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like Randy Johnson and Roger Clemens are few and far
between,'' said Reynolds, set to make his fourth straight Opening
Day start Tuesday against the Chicago Cubs. ``If you are lucky
enough to have one of those guys, that's something special. We
found that out last year with Randy Johnson. None of us are
veteran, power-type pitchers that have that kind of leadership and
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   But last season, Reynolds had something equally important _
victories.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he posted career highs with 19 wins and 209 strikeouts,
while ranking among the National League's top 10 in six different
categories. Only four pitchers had more victories. Two of them took
home Cy Young Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker, a former major-league pitcher for 14
years, thinks the only thing preventing Reynolds from gaining
mention among baseball's best is the ability to record successful
back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Only once has Reynolds, 31, posted double-digit victories in
consecutive seasons, winning 10 games in 1995 and 16 in '96. He
dropped to nine wins during an injury-plagued '97 season before
last season's breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds came within one victory of being the first Astros
pitcher to win 20 games since Mike Scott in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on the verge of being classified as a No. 1 pitcher. I
think Shane has pretty much gotten the respect of everyone around
the league,'' Dierker said. ``Most guys that you project as No. 1
pitchers are guys that throw real hard. What it boils down to is
making good pitches. Hitting the spots and having movement on your
pitches is more important than running the radar gun up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He not only gives you the aspect of a guy who doesn't walk
people, but he makes the hitters beat him instead of beating
himself,'' Dierker added. ``He can also get a strikeout with a man
on third and one out, which is one of the things you look for in a
No. 1 pitcher, a guy who can get out of a really tough jam by
getting strikeouts.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no shortage of No. 1-caliber pitchers during the
club's 35-year history:
</P>
<P>
   Knuckleballer Joe Niekro won 21 games during the 1979 season and
followed with 20 wins during the Astros' National League West
championship season in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Richard, one of the most overpowering pitchers in franchise
history, became a 20-game winner in 1976. He won 18 games each of
the next three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, with his bottom-dropping split-finger fastball, had
18-win seasons in 1985 and 1986 before breaking the 20-win barrier
in '89.
</P>
<P>
   After the departure of Darryl Kile to free agency last season,
Reynolds took on the responsibility of wearing the ``staff ace''
tag. Of his 19 wins last year, eight came after an Astros loss. He
went 7-1 following the July 31 trade for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In five full seasons, Reynolds' 63 victories rank 10th on the
club's all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to take his place among the best (in club history)
if he does this for a few more years,'' Dierker said. ``If you
start getting yourself into the Top 10 pitching categories with any
team, that's a pretty good accomplishment. I don't think he's far
away.''
</P>
<P>
   What sets Reynolds apart is the way he is successful, relying on
placement rather than power. His split-finger fastball averages 87
to 90 mph, complementing a good curveball and cut fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``A key to success is when you go out and don't have your good
stuff, or don't feel good, and battle through it and keep a team
close, giving yourself a chance to win,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   This winter the Astros paid Reynolds the ultimate compliment,
signing him to a three-year, $21 million contract extension that
included a bonus: To quiet speculation of Reynolds' inclusion in a
possible deal with Toronto for Clemens, the extension had a
one-year no-trade clause and a limited no-trade clause for the
remainder of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' message: While a pitcher like Johnson or Clemens is
hard to find, so is a Reynolds. As long as he continues winning,
the Astros will possess the security blanket of an ``ace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nice (to be considered the No. 1 pitcher),'' Reynolds
said. ``I think those guys are picked at the end of the year. The
guy you want to get the ball in a losing streak, the guy who took
the ball when we needed to win in a crucial situation. Those are
your No. 1s and your aces.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
