u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-WAGNER-HNS &LR;      03-31 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WAGNER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Wagner burns to join baseball's elite closers
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
For 24 outs, Billy Wagner finds a comfortable seat in the bullpen
and waits.
</P>
<P>
   And when it's time for the Astros' closer to make a cameo
appearance in the ninth inning, he suddenly can be thrown into the
leading role _ or become the fall guy.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's job is simple, he says: ``Get the final three outs.''
</P>
<P>
   Long gone are the days when legendary relief pitchers like Goose
Gossage or Rollie Fingers pitched three, sometimes four, innings to
pick up a save. Today, power has replaced endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever a hitter hits the ball, there's a potential that the
fielder could make an error or the ball could fall in for a hit,''
manager Larry Dierker said. ``When you don't let the guy hit the
ball, there's nothing left to chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The role of closer has taken on a specific definition, conjuring
the image of flamethrowing, strikeout-type pitchers. Only 27 years
old and with just two full seasons of experience, Wagner has
emerged as one of the game's best closers.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on a fastball that can approach 100 mph, the lefthander
saved 30 games last year while striking out 97 in 60 innings. In
1997, he saved 23 games and struck out 106 in 66 innings. Each
season, the Astros won the National League Central with Wagner as
closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how the game has changed,'' Wagner said. ``I
remember Gossage used to come in, throw three innings and get a
save. Now there are times when I might throw to one hitter and get
the save.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner didn't even begin his professional career as a closer.
The 12th overall pick of the 1993 draft was a starter until coming
up to the majors toward the end of 1995. He began 1996 as a starter
at Class AAA Tucson before making a full-time switch to closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a starter, I had to be able to pace myself and try and keep
my pitch count low to get to the sixth or seventh innings,'' said
Wagner, who converted 19 straight save opportunities last season.
``As a closer, I just come in and have one inning, trying to get
batters out any way I can. If it takes 20 pitches, so be it. If it
takes five pitches, it's just as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Wagner's 30 saves last season, third-most in the 37-year
history of the Astros franchise, 10 came when he faced three or
fewer batters. Even more impressive: He struck out the side 11
times.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner likely will challenge Doug Jones' single-season record of
36 saves this season. No Astros pitcher has twice saved 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   Already Wagner ranks fourth on the club's career saves list with
62. Dave Smith holds the record with 199, set during an 11-year
career.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros believe the best is yet to come for Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Dave Smith, you knew he would throw strikes,'' Dierker
said. ``With Billy, there is still the chance he may be a little
erratic, but he has the chance to be better than all of (the former
Astros closers). This year I think he may approach Smith in terms
of being consistently reliable. I still believe he can get even
better. If he doesn't encounter arm trouble, (he could) be the best
we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner said there is no added pressure after the Astros gave him
one of the biggest raises, percentage-wise, in baseball history _ a
$10.3 million, three-year contract that boosted his 1999 salary to
$2.1 million from $280,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wagner has set his sights on reaching 40 saves,
generally the benchmark for closers. Last season, eight closers had
at least 40, including an NL record-tying 53 by San Diego's Trevor
Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an opportunity to get 40 saves, where in the last
couple of years it wouldn't have mattered if we had 160 chances
because I wouldn't have gotten 40 saves,'' he said. ``Last year I
got 30 and it was like scrapping to get there. In my mind, 30 saves
anybody can get there.''
</P>
<P>
   To help become one of the game's best, Wagner took notes during
an all-star tour of Japan last November. Tom Gordon, Dan Plesac,
Mike Jackson and Ugueth Urbina all suggested Wagner add a second
pitch to his repertoire. He spent the rest of the winter working on
a slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a step to being a complete pitcher,'' Wagner
said. ``If you've got guys coming up to the plate looking for that
first-pitch fastball and I throw them a slider they are still going
to look for that fastball. They would be crazy not to. Now I can go
out there and throw a slider, and every time they'll be going, `Now
what are you going to throw me?' It's a process that's going to
take some time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
