<HEADER>
A1419 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-PLAN-SPI     03-31 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-PLAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS FUTURE IN THE STARS: GRIFFEY AND RODRIGUEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Every night before he goes to sleep, Chuck Armstrong
says, he thinks of four words: faith, hope, competitive and fans.
With those thoughts on his mind, the president of the Mariners must
dream of a time when Safeco Field's roof is open and the stars are
aligned just right.
</P>
<P>
   The enormity of his task _ making baseball thrive in Seattle
well into the 21st century _ must arrive with that first splash of
cold water in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   If history is a guide, the Mariners' stars will be crossed, not
aligned. This, after all, is a franchise that took 15 years to win
more games than it lost. Just when it seemed time to print World
Series tickets for the next decade, along came a year like 1998,
when optimism crash-landed at nine games below .500.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Field, opening in July, was thought to ensure long-term
prosperity. Now, with salaries skyrocketing and two-thirds of all
teams soon to be playing in new or remodeled parks, it has been
reduced to only part of the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mariners' blueprint for long-term success begins with
the $498 million retractable-roof ballpark. The Mariners expect it
to make them an additional $20-30 million a year, much of it
earmarked to pay loans on the $80 million in construction overruns.
Armstrong is projecting a slight loss this year but would like to
break even, and the club hopes to start making money by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a pleasant change for an ownership group that has,
on average, lost almost $12 million a year since taking over in
1992. It's incentive enough to stay together, even after
accomplishing the initial goal of keeping the team in Seattle and
building a new park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ownership group is absolutely stable,'' said chairman and
CEO John Ellis. ``Why in the world would it be otherwise? They've
taken all the beating and they've lost all the money. They're just
at the stage now where all the work that we've done should begin to
pay off in terms of a great facility and a competitive team,
hopefully a team that at least is in the black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense no inclination on the part of any portion of our
ownership to do anything. In fact, they're all looking forward to
probably the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, at 70, makes no promises about remaining with the club
past the opening of Safeco Field. But for now, as the newest member
of Major League Baseball's executive council, he is campaigning for
greater revenue sharing and other ideas to temper the growing
payroll disparity among teams.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect the Mariners to leap to the wealthy side of that
payroll gulf. Neither Ellis nor Armstrong said Safeco Field will
significantly change the way the club pursues high-priced talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody gets a new ballpark and they take the increased
revenues that the new ballpark brings and they spend it all on
players, then we're back in the same fix,'' Armstrong said. ``We
haven't really improved ourselves; we've just racheted it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward, M's vice president of baseball operations, said
this fact is undisputable in today's game: to compete every year, a
team must be among the top 10 in payroll. The Mariners were seventh
in 1996, 11th in '97 and eighth at the start of last year. This
year, they will be 15th or 16th. Woodward is hopeful of returning
to the top 10, but said it will take more than a ballpark to stay
there year after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new stadium should help us,'' Woodward said. ``(But) in
the long run, it's going to take a new system in baseball to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Until that happens, the Mariners will have to make money in more
creative ways. Armstrong said the team has studied English soccer
fields to find out how to host non-sports events such as concerts
without damaging the turf. The team also would like greater
visibility throughout the Northwest with increased marketing of the
compass rose logo and farther-reaching TV coverage.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, the Mariners have drawn the highest cable
ratings share in baseball. Last year, the M's collected $16.2
million in local broadcasting rights. But, Armstrong said, the
Mariners are limited in how much they can make from TV because so
many road games start so early. The club still favors re-alignment
along geographic lines, which would make its TV package more
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they do, and however the system is changed, it won't
change the fact that Seattle never will be New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our market will ever put us in position just to
buy a pennant,'' said Roger Jongewaard, vice president for scouting
and player development.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the burden for the Mariners' future falls on Jongewaard
and his staff, who have signed more major leaguers in the 1990s
than all but three teams. One way to get more of an edge on other
clubs is through international scouting, which essentially is a
free-for-all outside North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell our scouts they probably won't make as much money and
they'll probably have to work harder,'' Jongewaard said. ``But
ownership has been very cooperative, and if we want a player bad
enough, they help us get him. We just don't get every player out
there. We have to be more selective and make fewer mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan and Korea have been fruitful for the Mariners, and Latin
America should play an increasingly important role with the opening
of a Venezuelan academy last year and expected forays into Colombia
and Panama. Jongewaard believes untapped talent sources remain,
including mainland China, Africa and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to keep any elite prospect a secret. Last spring,
the Mariners lost out on Orlando Hernandez when the Yankees gave
him more than $6 million, double the offer of other clubs. Seattle
favors a worldwide draft, Armstrong said, which would eliminate
bidding wars it could not win.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jongewaard can only do so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger Jongewaard's track record is tremendous, and it's
overlooked far too often,'' Woodward said. ``This organization's
problem has not been bringing players through the system. It's been
being able to keep them.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella and six players are signed through 2000. No
Mariners are signed beyond then. Ellis said Safeco Field should
make the franchise ``self-sustaining,'' finally able to keep its
own players. But the price for two of those could be staggering.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez, twin free agents after the
2000 season? The Mariners grappling with 29 teams for the two best
players in the game? It's a frightening thought, and the M's have
made it known they'll negotiate seriously whenever the players are
ready.
</P>
<P>
   The players also have made something clear: they won't come back
unless they know the team will be a consistent winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a third guy that says the very same thing,'' Woodward
said. ``Nobody thinks of that, do they? Do you ever hear me take
opposition to their comments about that? Because I'm the third guy.
I want to be able to compete and to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Jongewaard, who has stocked the farm system with pitching, has
begun to shift the focus to position players, in part because it's
unknown what Griffey and Rodriguez will do. But Woodward said he
has not contemplated a Mariner roster without either star. He is
confident, he said, because Armstrong and Ellis are committed to
bringing both back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason that would prevent us from doing that,''
Ellis said. ``Anybody who thinks opposite is just crazy. If they
decide they don't want to, I don't have any control over that. But
we're going to do whatever it takes to sign these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   If that means being the highest bidder in the mother of all free
agent sweepstakes, Ellis isn't saying. But if this winter's Kevin
Brown derby showed anything, it's that some teams can pay any price
for a player they think they need.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong acknowledges this. It's one reason the Mariners want
to sign the players before they reach free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what history says, because once a player goes on the
free agent market, you've got 30 bidders, and all it takes is one
to go (make an offer beyond baseball's established market) and you
lose your guy,'' Armstrong said. ``I think, and I've discussed this
with player agents too, that sometimes they're finding players
think the grass looks greener when they go someplace for the
short-term money, and the grass isn't greener. It becomes
unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners probably will try to sell the players on the
benefits of spending an entire career in one city. Armstrong speaks
hopefully of Griffey and Rodriguez becoming to Seattle what Tony
Gwynn and Cal Ripken are to their cities.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this will come down to money. When asked if he was
confident the Mariners could make the financial commitment, Ellis
said, ``Sure,'' and would not elaborate. Armstrong answered the
question with two questions of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're going to have to pay whatever the market is,''
he said. ``But what's the market? At what point is the market going
to go down?''
</P>
<P>
   Fair questions. Perhaps only this much is known: If either
player leaves, those comforting dreams of faith and hope quickly
turn into nightmares. The skies rumble, the roof closes up. Storm
front ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
