<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL </SLUG>
 CENTRAL-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Indians have another easy road to division title, but postseason
questions linger
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Forget about the Yankees being the best bet in baseball to make the
postseason. How about the Indians?
</P>
<P>
   They play in a division so weak _ the American League Central _
that no other team managed to play .500 ball last year. Still, the
Indians only finished nine games ahead of the second-place White
Sox, which is why some are starting to question their prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Indians have the second-best record in the AL over
the last five years, they have fallen short of 90 wins in each of
the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Does playing in the weakest division in baseball make the
Indians soft when the postseason rolls around? Probably not, but
that's the popular theory these days. That doesn't take into
account the fact the Indians played in the World Series two years
ago and reached the AL Championship Series in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there's talk that manager Mike Hargrove's job
might be in jeopardy if the Indians don't find a way to dethrone
the Yankees in 1999. Of course, it should come as no surprise that
the Yankees are used as the standard when it comes to evaluating
the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland certainly has no competition in its own division.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the rise
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Tigers: OK, we said the Tigers were ready to make a move
last season, and all they did was lose 97 games. Looks like the
rise to the top is going to take longer than anyone anticipated.
But you can expect to see progress this season, although they
aren't quite ready to compete for a postseason spot.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the slide
</P>
<P>
   Chicago White Sox: The White Sox didn't have far to fall, but
they managed to spiral themselves closer to the basement by losing
Albert Belle and Robin Ventura during the offseason. If Frank
Thomas ever returns to the playoffs, it won't be with the White
Sox. Expect to hear his name in a few trade rumors as the trading
deadline nears.
</P>
<P>
   Overrated
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter, Tigers: He's had plenty of time to establish
himself as the next Kenny Lofton, which is what some observers said
the Astros traded away when they dealt Hunter to the Tigers three
years ago. He's still young, so there's hope; but any leadoff man
with a .298 on-base percentage has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Blair, Tigers: He won 16 games for the Tigers two years
ago and earned a fat contract from the Diamondbacks worth almost $7
million a year. He's not worth it, as last year's 5-16 record with
the Diamondbacks and the Mets proved.
</P>
<P>
   Underrated
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Higginson, Tigers: He doesn't get much notice because he's
played only on losing teams. But Higginson is a gamer who will hit
for power and average. He has more support in the Tigers' lineup
this year, and it could lead to a breakthrough season.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Durham, White Sox: And don't say he only made the All-Star
Game last season because every team must have a representative.
While Durham isn't the best second baseman in the AL, he's
certainly becoming one of the best. His all-around talents are
among the few bright spots on an otherwise dismal team.
</P>
<P>
   Up and coming
</P>
<P>
   Richie Sexson, Indians: He hit 11 homers in 174 at-bats last
season, and the Indians plan to use him as a designated hitter in
1999. Don't let his basketball player's build fool you. This kid
has some serious power, and he will become a fixture in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Magglio Ordoez, White Sox: With one full season under his belt,
the expectations will go up; especially with Belle and Ventura out
of the picture. But the 25-year-old outfielder has the tools to
live up to his billing. He could hit .300 with 20-25 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Down and out
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden, Indians: He's hardly the pitcher he once was. His
velocity isn't the same, and he's no longer a threat to toss a
shutout every time he takes the mound. He'll win games simply
because he pitches for a great team, but time is running out for
this once-great pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Navarro, White Sox: Signed three years ago to be the ace
of the staff, Navarro has been a major bust. He's just barely
hanging on to the fifth spot in the rotation. The White Sox have
tried to trade him, but they can find no takers. His best years are
past.
</P>
<P>
   On the spot
</P>
<P>
   Brad Ausmus, Tigers: His reputation for aiding the development
of pitchers has made the expectations almost unrealistic. If the
Tigers' pitching staff doesn't show improvement, Ausmus surely will
take some of the blame. However, if they do improve, his stock will
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas, White Sox: He hit just .265 and struck out 93
times last season, and he spent most of his time complaining about
the strike zone and how umpires were out to get him. It appears the
1999 strike zone will be more favorable to hitters. If Thomas
doesn't rebound, who's he going to blame this time?
</P>
<P>
   What if
</P>
<P>
   the Tigers reversed their luck from a year ago and actually got
off to a fast start? That could make things interesting for the
Indians, who have grown accustomed to virtually wrapping up the
division before the All-Star break. If the Tigers' lineup is solid,
and if they get decent pitching, it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   On schedule
</P>
<P>
   A good start seems certain for the Indians, who play Minnesota,
Kansas City and Oakland 16 times during the first month of the
season. The first possible preview of the ALCS won't take place
until July 23-25 when they visit Yankee Stadium. Meanwhile, the
Tigers' first six games are on the road against the Rangers and
Yankees. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
