<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HIDALGO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Left a spot by injury, Hidalgo must produce
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Richard Hidalgo will eventually make a name for himself in the
major leagues. In the meantime, he will try to make people forget
another name _ Moises Alou.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfair to think Hidalgo can replace Alou, who fell off a
treadmill and onto the disabled list in February. What the Astros
envision, though, is Hidalgo establishing himself in his first
full-time gig in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to blossom,'' bench coach Matt Galante
said. ``He got his feet wet last year. It's not like he hasn't had
an opportunity to play. He's had enough at-bats in the big leagues
to come into his own. I would be very surprised if Richard didn't
have a really solid season.''
</P>
<P>
   With Alou out until at least August with a knee injury, the
Astros are counting on it.
</P>
<P>
   Alou, 32, has been one of the game's best throughout his
nine-year career, but never more than last year, when he finished
third in voting for National League Most Valuable Player after
hitting .312 with 38 home runs and 124 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, 23, doesn't even have a full year under his belt. He
hit .303 with seven home runs and 35 RBIs in 74 games last season.
But since he was discovered in Venezuela and nurtured through the
Astros' farm system, Hidalgo has just wanted a chance to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nervous,'' said Hidalgo, who shared center field with
Carl Everett last season before missing two months with a shoulder
injury. ``I've been waiting for a chance to play for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe in me.''
</P>
<P>
   More than he might imagine.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros protected Hidalgo instead of fellow Venezuelan Bobby
Abreu in the 1997 expansion draft. And they refused to include him
in trade negotiations last July with Seattle for Randy Johnson or
this winter with Toronto for Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should certainly reinforce in his mind that he belongs
here, that he's capable of playing here, and he's primed to take on
a greater role,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   In a short amount of time, Hidalgo has left a lasting impression
on the Astros' coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hungry,'' said first base coach Jose Cruz, one of the
greatest to play in the Astros' outfield. ``Too bad somebody plays
because another guy got hurt. But he was going to get a chance
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo is projected to hit 25 to 30 home runs and drive in 100
runs someday. His biggest asset will be in left field, where he
will have one of the top arms in the NL. Since turning pro, Hidalgo
has played center field and right field. He will play left for the
first time in his career this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope some of those guys take chances on him,'' Galante
said, ``because normally your left fielder has the weakest arm of
the three outfielders. We have it where he is basically our
strongest arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Everett, ``Not to knock Moises or anything, but Richard is
a better outfielder. As far as hitting 40 homers and driving in 130
runs, you don't know that yet because he hasn't played a full
season.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems inevitable that every time Hidalgo, Everett and right
fielder Derek Bell take the field, they will be scrutinized more in
the absence of Alou. That's something they plan to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose any games and, say, the outfield goes
0-for-whatever, they are going to say, `What if Mo was here?'
Regardless, you're going to have your critics,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hidalgo) will not replace Mo,'' Galante said. ``Nobody can
replace Mo by themselves. We have to replace him by other guys
picking it up. Down the road, Richard may be a great player. It's
not his rookie year anymore and he's ready to take off, but
certainly he isn't in Alou's class at this point and time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
