<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL </SLUG>
 WEST-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Division full of big bats may be decided by pitching
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The American League West produced the only race in the junior
circuit in 1998, and it appears to be the most balanced division in
the league this year, too.
</P>
<P>
   Defending division champion Texas and Anaheim both sought
pitching help during the offseason but came up empty-handed. So
they settled for upgrading their offenses, and both acquired impact
players.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, who had 40 home runs and 115 RBIs last year in
Boston, gives the Angels the feared slugger they have lacked for
years. Along with Tim Salmon, Darin Erstad and Jim Edmonds, the
Angels' lineup now looks formidable. Vaughn also will bring
attitude to a team that has been considered soft.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers countered by signing Rafael Palmeiro, who hit 43
homers and drove in 123 runs last year in Baltimore. They already
had AL Most Valuable Player Juan Gonzalez (.318, 45 HR, 157 RBIs)
and five other players who hit 10 or more homers last season.
Scoring runs won't be a problem for either team.
</P>
<P>
   With Ken Griffey Jr., Alex Rodriguez and Edgar Martinez leading
the way, the Mariners potentially could have a more potent offense
than either of the front-runners, but they also lack pitching
depth. A pair of 36-year-olds _ Jeff Fassero and Jamie Moyer _ lead
the Seattle rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Expect all three teams to be on the lookout for a legitimate No.
1 starter sometime before the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever team strikes first could move into the driver's seat.
Oakland has the best starting pitcher in the division _ Kenny
Rogers _ and some of the best young talent in the game, but the
Athletics are not quite ready to bang with the big sluggers of this
division.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the rise
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Mariners: Surely they can't get much lower than they
were last year, when their best pitcher didn't want to be on the
team and their relievers couldn't protect a lead to save their
lives. With a few breaks, they could contend for the division
title.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the slide
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Athletics: Only because someone has to fall into this
category. They haven't quite come out of the slide that has
engulfed them since their glory days of the late 1980s and the
early 1990s. But with a nice collection of young players, there is
hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Overrated
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey, Mariners: The former top prospect of the Mets put
up good numbers in the minors but hasn't done much at the
big-league level. If he doesn't hit homers at the Kingdome, he's
not going to hit them anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clark, Rangers: He already was overrated; the Cubs made him
overvalued when they signed him to a one-year, $5 million contract
before last season. All they got in return was a 9-14 record. Now
he's the Rangers' problem.
</P>
<P>
   Underrated
</P>
<P>
   David Segui, Mariners: You can always count on his batting
average to be near .300, and his power numbers are decent. But
Segui's best talent _ his defensive skills _ often goes unnoticed.
He's worthy of a Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin, Rangers: He's one of the best leadoff hitters in
the majors, and also one of the most overlooked. Goodwin had a .378
on-base percentage and stole 38 bases last season.
</P>
<P>
   Up and coming
</P>
<P>
   Eric Chavez, Athletics: He hit 33 homers and drove in 132 runs
while jumping from Class A to Class AAA last season. Many believe
he will give Oakland its second AL Rookie of the Year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Guillen, Mariners: He's the jewel of the package Seattle
received from the Astros in exchange for Randy Johnson. Guillen is
a flashy fielder who will post impressive offensive numbers for a
second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Down and out
</P>
<P>
   Esteban Loaiza, Rangers: He once was one of the most promising
young pitchers in the National League; now he's frustrating to
watch. The Rangers must be having second thoughts about trading
second-base prospect Warren Morris to acquire Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Davis, Mariners: He may as well play third base without a
glove. He couldn't do much worse. Davis committed 32 errors last
season, prompting the Mariners to move him to left field. He was
even worse there, so now he's back at third.
</P>
<P>
   On the spot
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward, Mariners: Ownership let the GM slide after last
year's fallout, but he probably won't be so lucky if things don't
get better in 1999. It would help his case if the three prospects
he acquired in the Johnson deal make contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Phillips, Athletics: He was lucky to get a job after a poor
showing in 1998 and drug problems in 1997. The 39-year-old veteran
simply can't afford another slip-up.
</P>
<P>
   What if
</P>
<P>
   the Mariners get a step-up pitching performance from someone in
the bottom of the rotation _ perhaps rookie Freddy Garcia _ and
closer Jose Mesa finally rediscovers his dominant form? The
Mariners already have a potent offense. Maybe the AL West isn't a
two-team race after all.
</P>
<P>
   On schedule
</P>
<P>
   It won't take long for the Rangers and Angels to have their
first meeting. They will get together for a four-game series April
9-12 at The Ballpark at Arlington. The Mariners host the Rangers on
June 25-27 in their final series at the Kingdome, and they
entertain the Padres on July 15-17 in their inaugural series at
Safeco Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1941EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
