<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1429 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLCENTRAL-HNS &LR;      03-31 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL </SLUG>
 CENTRAL-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Division front-runners are patching holes after season-ending
injuries in spring
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The early focus of the National League Central will involve who's
in the trainer's room rather than who's on the field.
</P>
<P>
   No contending team in the division has a right to cry about
injuries; they all know the feeling. The Astros are without Moises
Alou, the Cubs must learn to face life after Kerry Wood, and Matt
Morris will miss the season in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Cardinals can look forward to getting Alan Benes
back after the All-Star break. The aforementioned players likely
will miss the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   Depth takes on an added significance, and the Astros enjoy a
luxury in that department. They have enough firepower to sustain
the loss of Alou and claim their third consecutive NL Central
title.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely they will repeat their 102-win season from a year
ago, but they probably won't need to.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs don't appear to be as good as they were in 1998, and
the Cardinals enter the season with the same problem they had last
year _ injured pitchers. Without Benes and Morris, they'll be
tempted to rush some of their best young prospects into the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa no doubt will pick up where they
left off last year when it comes to hitting home runs, but long
balls don't win divisions; pitching does.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates and Brewers will battle to stay out of the basement,
but keep an eye on the Reds. They figure to be the most improved
team in the division.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the rise
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Reds: They added Denny Neagle, Greg Vaughn and Mike
Cameron over the offseason, which filled three big needs. If Barry
Larkin stays healthy, this team could be the surprise of the
National League. Regardless, they are certainly headed in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Team on the slide
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs: They won 90 games last season, and Sammy Sosa
provided a truckload of excitement. But losing Kerry Wood will take
some of the air out of this aging team. The guess here is that the
Cubs will take a step backward in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Overrated
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Blauser, Cubs: His range at shortstop has been on the
decline for years, and the Cubs should have known better to expect
him to come near his impressive offensive numbers of 1997. He could
lose his starting job by midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan Osborne, Cardinals: He says, ``Everyone knows what I can
do if I'm healthy.'' But when is that? All he does is get your
hopes up for a letdown. It's not like we're talking about a 20-game
winner, even when he is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Underrated
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell, Astros: All he does is hit .300 and drive in 100
runs with 15-20 homers year after year. Nevertheless, he's the
subject of trade rumors every offseason, and a perennial snub on
the All-Star team. It's a good thing he's so resilient.
</P>
<P>
   Jeromy Burnitz, Brewers: Funny how no one ever talks about this
guy. In only his second full season in the majors, Burnitz hit 38
homers and drove in 125 runs. If he played in New York, Burnitz
would be a bona fide star.
</P>
<P>
   Up and coming
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Drew, Cardinals: OK, we all took our shots at him during
his contract holdout, but Drew is the real deal. He hit five home
runs in just 14 games last season and is the favorite to win the
NL's Rookie of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Meluskey, Astros: Say what you will about his defense or
his ability to handle pitchers, but this kid can flat-out hit.
Because he'll be splitting time with Tony Eusebio, we may not see
just how good Meluskey is in 1999. But given time, he will impress.
</P>
<P>
   Down and out
</P>
<P>
   Gary Gaetti, Cubs: Don't get too caught up in his strong finish
to the 1998 season. The 40-year-old Gaetti has seen his best days
on a baseball diamond. Cardinals manager Tony La Russa loves the
older players, and even he gave up on Gaetti.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Avery, Reds: Once an up-and-coming star with the Braves,
injuries have made Avery a different pitcher. Reds general manager
Jim Bowden likes to try to rejuvenate the careers of fallen stars,
but he may be hoping against hope in Avery's case. Watch him lose
his spot in the rotation to Dennis Reyes at some point.
</P>
<P>
   On the spot
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner, Brewers: It's no secret. Garner is in the last year
of his contract and, if he doesn't work miracles, his days in
Milwaukee are numbered. That's asking a lot, considering the
Brewers are a mess. Don't worry about Garner. If it doesn't work
out in Milwaukee, he'll have no trouble finding another job.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo, Astros: The Astros have been projecting stardom
for the 23-year-old Venezuelan, and this is his chance to show it.
Because Moises Alou is likely out for the season, Hidalgo will get
his first opportunity to be an everyday player. All eyes will be on
him.
</P>
<P>
   What if
</P>
<P>
   the Cubs had not rushed Kerry Wood back to the mound last
season? Perhaps that had something to do with the elbow injury that
has wiped out his 1999 season. We can only hope Wood will make a
full recovery. Baseball needs a presence like his to take the game
into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   On schedule
</P>
<P>
   It won't take long for the division's two top teams from a year
ago to square off. The Cubs visit the Astrodome Tuesday through
Thursday for the season-opening series. Mark May 28-30 on your
calendars; that's the first time sluggers Mark McGwire and Sammy
Sosa will be on the same diamond. It's a weekend series at Wrigley
Field. The Astros will help to shut down stadiums. They play
Milwaukee Sept. 24-26 in one of the last series at County Stadium,
and they host the Dodgers on Oct. 1-3 _ the last regular-season
baseball games at the Astrodome. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
