<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-N     03-31 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY FLOCKS TO ARAB TOWNS ON ISRAELI CAMPAIGN TRAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHFAYIM, Israel _ The roar of the crowd's shouting, ``Bibi go
home!'' was barely audible in the tightly guarded City Hall, where
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was whisked to speak to a
handpicked audience from this Israeli Arab town.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by his wife, Sarah, who wore a dove-shaped brooch,
Netanyahu brushed off the demonstration, organized by members of a
leftist Arab party, and promised his listeners another peace treaty
by the millennium and swift action to bring equality to the 1
million Arab citizens in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``My government and I are committed to equal opportunity and to
closing the gaps,'' Netanyahu said, listing statistics that show
increased aid to neglected Arab communities. ``A human being is a
human being, and a citizen is a citizen. For me, the children here
are no different than Jewish children, and they deserve exactly the
same future. The real record shows what we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Battling for every vote they can obtain in a tight race,
Netanyahu and his opponents took their campaigns this week to Arab
villages and towns, paying holiday visits during the four-day
Muslim Feast of the Sacrifice. Arabs make up 12 percent of the
electorate, and their votes could be crucial in determining the
outcome of the balloting on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   In the election in 1996 that brought Netanyahu to power, Arabs
voted overwhelmingly for Shimon Peres of the Labor Party,
preferring his dovish views to the harder line of Netanyahu, who
received 5 percent of the Arab vote.
</P>
<P>
   Many Arabs are quite likely to vote again for the Labor
candidate, this time Ehud Barak, although significant numbers could
support Yitzhak Mordechai, leader of the new Center Party and the
third main contender. Others might back a newly declared Arab
candidate, Azmi Bishara.
</P>
<P>
   On the Arab campaign trail, Netanyahu, Barak and Mordechai all
make the same double-barreled promise of peace and equality. They
pledge to make peace with Israel's neighbors and to solve the
problems of the Arabs in Israel, who lag significantly behind Jews
in living standards, employment rates and quality of government
services.
</P>
<P>
   Barak portrays himself as the successor of assassinated Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, following his policies of peacemaking and
improving the Arabs' lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we look our Arab neighbors in the eye while we have
such deep inequality in this country?'' Barak asked on a visit to
Baqa al-Gharbiya. ``There can't be one town with red-brick plazas
and another that has no sewage in the same country. That's not
equality. We are going to bring peace and equality.''
</P>
<P>
   Mordechai promises to appoint an Arab minister to the Cabinet
and to draw up five-year plans to upgrade roads and sewage systems
in Arab communities. The Iraqi-born son of Kurdish Jewish
immigrants, Mordechai peppers his holiday greetings with Arabic
phrases, showing off his Middle Eastern roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that next year we can be in Damascus and wish the
Syrians a happy holiday,'' Mordechai said on a visit to Abu Ghosh,
where he pledged to work for peace with Syria, Lebanon and the
Palestinians. He drew loud applause when he declared, ``I promise
you that when I am elected prime minister there will be an Arab
minister in my government.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with his opponents, the hawkish Netanyahu has a tough
job of selling himself to Arab voters. The protesters who greeted
him here held up signs saying, ``Netanyahu is persona non grata in
Shfayim,'' and denouncing him as ``an enemy of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   His emissary to the Arab communities, Gideon Ezra, a former
deputy chief of the Shin Bet security agency, was mobbed by an
angry crowd and had to be hustled away by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   At the City Hall meeting, Mayor Ursan Yassin, a political ally
of Netanyahu, read a checklist of troubles that plague this town of
30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shfayim is a city in name only, but it's actually a big
village,'' Yassin said. ``There are no pool, no youth clubs, no
public parks, and only 50 percent of the sewage system is complete.
In the Bedouin neighborhood there are no roads, no infrastructure,
no play fields. It breaks my heart to see our young people with no
place to spend their time. There are no budgets, no resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu responded with his own list of government-financed
public works in Arab villages and towns, noting that the sums had
grown despite budget cuts. He promised $7 million to Shfayim by
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of additional aid is Netanyahu's most potent weapon
in his campaign to woo Arab voters. In similar fashion, the
Sephardic religious party, Shas, whose control of the Interior
Ministry gives it power over local budgets and building plans, is
appealing for support from Arabs in the vote for Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The power of an incumbent prime minister will win Netanyahu more
Arab votes than he received in the last election, Ezra predicted.
``People are tired of the empty promises of a sterile opposition,''
he added. ``They want to be partners in government.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Abu Ghosh, Thabet Abu Ghosh said he was tired of all the
candidates' promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hearing this now for 50 years, and I'm not
impressed,'' he said. ``Every four years they come around and
promise that if you vote for them they'll appoint you director of
some government office. After the elections you knock on their
door, and they don't even recognize you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
