<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money magazines getting tech-oriented
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's getting hard to tell mainstream business
magazines from high-tech, computer publications these days.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Money (April), The Wall Street Journal's personal finance
magazine, is the latest example with a 1999 Internet guide that
looks at topics from stocks to computers to travel deals.
</P>
<P>
   Given the thousands of sites on the Web, this is a reader
service, with a selection of Web sites the editors regard as
useful, and organized with 25 sites in 10 categories.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Smart Money looks at the next round of high-tech
winners in the stock market: ASM Lithography (ticker symbol ASML),
Broadcom (BRCM), Lucent Technologies (LU), PMC-Sierra (PMCS), PRI
Automation (PRIA), RF Micro Devices (RFMD), Texas Instruments (TXN)
and Uniphase (UNPH).
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned stocks
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the high-tech trend, not all investors are
comfortable with stocks that have ``.com'' in their names.
Bloomberg Personal Finance (April) recommends stable, growth stocks
from the food, drug and beverage industries that offer predictable
profit growth and beat the market over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   These stocks hold up well during economic slumps and down
markets because they are the stocks of companies that make products
that are always needed by consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Among stocks on Bloomberg's list are Abbott Laboratories (ABT),
ConAgra (CAG), Merck (MRK), Schering-Plough (SGP), Bestfoods (BFO),
H.J. Heinz (HNZ), Kellogg (K) and Pfizer (PFE).
</P>
<P>
   Rescuing a TV network
</P>
<P>
   The CBS television network almost became a property of media
mogul Ted Turner some years back. Turner went on to do well for
himself, but CBS continued to stumble, according to Business Week
(April 5).
</P>
<P>
   Now, CBS' new chief executive, Mel Karmazin, has set out to turn
the network around with a formula of glitzy special events aimed at
wooing a young audience, NFL football and old-fashioned
cost-cutting. He paid top dollar for events such as the Grammy
awards, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning...
</P>
<P>
   _ Business to Business celebrates its second anniversary as an
Atlanta business magazine with a cover profile of ``warriors'' who
have made sports their business. Among them are Evander Holyfield
(featured on the cover), Billy Payne, Stan Kasten and Hank Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Milken, best known as the 1980s junk bond king who was
jailed for securities fraud, resurfaced in the '90s in several
enterprises. Now, says U.S. News &AMP; World Report (April 5), he is
about to become an entrepreneur with a stock offering for an
educational company known as Knowledge Universe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
