<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-PACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFITS OFF DESPITE CONSUMER PACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only days after investors pushed the Dow Jones
industrial average over 10,000, the government reported Wednesday
that corporate profits fell last year for the first time since
1989.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said after-tax corporate profits slumped
by 2.2 percent in 1998, the first drop since just before the
recession of 1990-1991.
</P>
<P>
   With investors paying record-high prices for stocks, the profit
squeeze adds new urgency to the question of whether today's high
stock prices are justified, or due for a fall.
</P>
<P>
   On average, stocks in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index are
trading at 34 times earnings, compared to 21 times earnings just
before the market crash of 1987. ``We're not only at a record high,
but blowing away anything we've ever seen before,'' said Greg
Jones, chief economist at Briefing.com, an on-line market analysis
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The dim profits news was accompanied by a report that the US
economy ended 1998 with a burst of growth. People are buying plenty
of goods and services, though at prices that do not produce profits
for companies.
</P>
<P>
   The government said US gross domestic product surged in the
fourth quarter of 1998 at an annual rate of 6 percent, a revision
from an earlier estimate of 6.1 percent. For all of 1998, the US
economy grew by a robust 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said those reports, as well as concerns over the
bombing in Kosovo, were behind a 127-point drop in the Dow Jones
industrial average Wednesday. The index closed at 9786.16, down
1.29 percent. .
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have said stocks will rise in 1999 as the world
recovers from the Asian financial crisis. But Roger Brinner, chief
economist at the Parthenon Group, a Boston consulting and
investment firm, said the stock market is overvalued by about 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Key to his analysis is the fact that bond yields have been
rising, making them a more attractive investment that could lure
money from the stock market. Bonds might become even more
attractive after the latest profits report, he said, ``because
rising share prices can't be defended by rising earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, the United States is living through
``a peculiar economy where people are investing in `dot.com' stocks
with no profits.'' There's been considerable debate over whether
fast-rising Internet stocks are too expensive compared to their
profits, or if the dizzying prices of Amazon.com and America Online
are well-justified because those companies are on track to become
the brand-name giants of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the market will be flat or down somewhat this year.
``We will still see some numbers over 10,000, but the valuations
are a problem. . . . They're too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate profits had jumped 7.5 percent in 1997, 7 percent in
1996, 22 percent in 1995 and 16 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   They declined last year, analysts said, because the tight labor
market pushed up wages, which are the largest cost in producing
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, companies have not been able to pass that cost
on to consumers. The key reason is the Asian crisis and its ripples
throughout the world. That has cut the demand for all kinds of
goods, leaving the world with an oversupply of everything from
soybeans and steal to automobiles. When consumers can pick among
competing products, companies find it hard to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   In service industries, intense competition has also made it hard
for companies to raise prices. ``Just look at telecom. Sometimes I
wish the competition wasn't so stiff,'' said Cynthia Latta, chief
US economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's/DRI in Lexington, Mass.,
referring to incessant telephone marketing campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Latta said, ``the pricing power of companies is nil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But American workers are thoroughly enjoying it,'' Brinner
said. ``What's a profit problem for business is a real wage and
price bonanza for the worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's government reports also showed inflation to be well
in check. A price index tied to the gross domestic product rose
just 1 percent in 1998. There hasn't been a rate that low since
1959, when it was also 1 percent, and there hasn't been one lower
since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
