<SLUG> BC-DELTA-STRATEGY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta strategies weak, board member says
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines is still ``desperately seeking
strategy'' from its new management, according to a stinging
critique by the pilot union's nonvoting representative on the board
of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Halsor, a captain who holds the special board post, said
Delta has achieved strong results in some areas but remains weak in
overall strategy, especially regarding international routes and
customer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``With new managers in about 90 percent of Delta's top
management positions, the time for laying out a plan for needed
change is now,'' Halsor wrote in the latest pilot union newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   The article conveyed Halsor's personal opinion. But his board
position lends weight to his views, and his open dissent
underscores shaky union-management relations as contract talks loom
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry said the carrier ``disagrees with Mr.
Halsor's comments. The company's strategic agenda is producing
record financial results, strong improvements in customer service
and aggressive moves in Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   Halsor, who attends board meetings but has limited input, said
that Delta's global position is weak despite statistical power in
Europe and a Latin expansion. CEO Leo Mullin's management team
``must simply lay out a plan to be the No. 1 carrier, or be part of
a No. 1 network, in all major world markets,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Halsor said customer service gains are offset by other changes
that ``appear to be focused on the customer as a problem or an
irritant.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited a failed effort to impose a surcharge on non-Internet
bookings, an aborted plan to charge for Crown Room drinks and the
removal of sandwiches from ``an already pathetic'' SkyDeli lunch on
certain flights.
</P>
<P>
   Halsor also said management is wasting time and money trying to
prevent further unionization at Delta, the least unionized large
carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``New management tells us we have a clear advantage over those
chumps at Southwest, American, United and British Airways. But ...
these companies regularly beat us in the marketplace even though
they must 'accommodate' their highly unionized workforces.''
</P>
<P>
   Halsor even berated Delta's advertising. ``Even a parrot
plinking on a piano beats us every time,'' he wrote, referring to
United's Gershwin melody theme.
</P>
<P>
   He moderated his comments when reached Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do support our management team,'' Halsor said. ``Overall
they've done a good job. I do disagree with certain steps they've
taken and some they've inherited or continued.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
