<HEADER>
A1435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-QUARTER01-COX     03-31 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-QUARTER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quarter ends with dim outlook
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stock market investors put an historic first quarter
behind them on Wednesday with heavy across-the-board selling and
not especially bright expectations for the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter saw the Dow Jones industrial average top and
then retreat from 10,000, the impeachment of a U.S. president, the
outbreak of limited war in the Balkans, the spread of global
recession to Brazil and a classic investment ``bubble'' involving
Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the major stock market indexes rose during the three
months ended March 31, but the gains were significantly smaller
than a year ago, and one index _ the small-stock Russell 2000 _
continued to retreat in a two-tiered market.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, analysts blamed the Dow's decline on Philip
Morris, a Dow component, whose share price fell $2.56 1/4 to $35.18
3/4 after an Oregon jury ordered the cigarette maker to pay $81
million in settlement of a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite was buoyed by a strong performance in
technology shares, although the index ended with a loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's drop below 9,800 just two days after closing above
10,000 for the first time was indicative of the market's extreme
volatility in recent years, analysts said. They see little reason
to expect a change.
</P>
<P>
   With bond yields expected to decline and short-term interest
rates stable, the biggest influence over stocks in the next month
will be the barrage of first quarter corporate earnings reports.
The near-term outlook is not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   I/B/E/S International, which tracks analysts estimates, said
S&AMP;P-500 earnings fell 1.8 percent in 1998, the first decline since
1991. And while many analysts look for a return to double-digit
earnings growth for 1999,
</P>
<P>
   I/B/E/S analysts said it will be more like 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the bullish side, however, analysts continue to cite the
economy's performance as an underpinning for further stock market
gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market's resilience has been impressive despite two
negatives,'' said Robinson-Humphrey strategist Robert S. Robbins,
citing the recent rise in Treasury yields ``and the uncertainty
associated with NATO involvement in Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said the strength of the market's gains since the 1998
correction ended last October _ a 28 percent rise for the Dow and
75 percent for the Nasdaq composite _ makes the market vulnerable
to a routine correction of 7 percent from market highs.
</P>
<P>
   But a 7 percent drop from the Dow's closing high of 10,006.78 on
Monday would take the index back to about where it regularly traded
in early January.
</P>
<P>
   A major concern of analysts is the development of a two-tiered
market, where big blue chip stocks lead the rally while smaller
stocks lag behind.
</P>
<P>
   At Interstate/Johnson Lane, technical analyst Ricky T.
Harrington said the average U.S. stock is still trading 22 percent
below its April 1998 high.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the stock market was not greatly concerned with
events in the world beyond Wall Street during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment of President Clinton was basically a nonevent,
because most traders assumed he would not be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's move to let its currency slide was a momentary fright,
which improved when a combination of outside help and internal
political moves appeared to ease the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The start of bombing in Yugoslavia did not have a major impact
in the first quarter, although analysts say it is the kind of event
that has the potential to depress stocks if it becomes a source of
major uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   And economic fundamentals were favorable enough to prevent the
Federal Reserve from making any change in interest rates at its
meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Alan Greenspan had nothing to say about the decision,
but most analysts said that means the Fed is satisfied with the
economy's relatively inflation-free expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
