<SLUG> BC-BBA-BASEBALL-FUTURE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPARTITY BETWEEN HAVES, HAVE-NOTS ONLY GETTING BIGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The greatest shame of the 1994-95 baseball strike was
not the rupture of two seasons or the cancellation of a World
Series. Worse than that, over 232 days in which the game's problems
were open to correction, baseball accomplished nothing. A judge
sent the players back to work, and the Basic Agreement reached in
late 1996 has failed to solve much of anything.
</P>
<P>
   Last season was filled with so many glorious highs that it was
easy to believe baseball was healthy again. Then came the winter,
filled with so many can-you-top-this free agent signings. A host of
teams enter the season with no hope of truly competing _ not just
now, but ever.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make future labor standoffs seem more ominous
than the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they shy away from correcting the problems the next time
around because they think they can't endure another work stoppage,
they're crazy,'' said NBC's Bob Costas, a leading baseball expert.
``What the game can't endure is another (begin ital)stupid (end
ital) work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA actually learned everything from baseball: a) you've
got to stop the problem before it gets totally out of control, and
b) if you're going to provoke a fight like that, you've got to come
out of the alley with something tangible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If owners have to blow off the entire 2002 season, if that's
what it takes, that's what they should do _ but do it with a plan
and an intelligent program.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's collective bargaining agreement expires after the
2000 season, but the players' union is expected to exercise its
option to extend it through 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But as baseball crosses into to the 21st century, several teams
are stranded in the breakdown lane while others zoom by. No team
with a payroll under $48 million made the playoffs last season,
further evidence that in the post-strike era, you almost always get
what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that some teams can pay more than
others. High-end teams have operating revenues in the $175 million
range, five times the resources of some low-end clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap's going to get larger and larger and larger,'' said
Ken Towers, San Diego Padres general manager. ``From a business
standpoint, I think a lot of us have probably peaked. We're going
to have to keep payroll somewhere in the $50-60 million range.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenue sharing is a possible solution, and commisioner Bud
Selig expects the top six teams to transfer $140 million to the
bottom six teams this season. But the problem with revenue sharing
has been the way funds are used: seeing no point in boosting a
payroll that can't grow big enough to produce a winner, some teams
use the money to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners chairman John Ellis, a member of baseball's Executive
Council, wants large-revenue teams to share proportionately with
teams in the middle, where Seattle now resides. But any large-scale
change in baseball's economics, he said, can't come from owners
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, we need to create a partnership with the players
where we say, OK, guys, we divide up our revenues with you, all
revenues from baseball. You take X percent, and we'll take Y
percent, and now you figure out how you want to divide it up,''
Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like salary caps _ it could be that, it could be
some other system.''
</P>
<P>
   But for players to agree to substantial changes in the game's
economic system, they first have to believe there's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a lack of competitive balance yet, to
be honest,'' said Mariners catcher Dan Wilson, the team's player
representative. ``Just because the Yankees won it last year, I
mean, there's been a lot of teams that have done very well that
weren't up there like the Yankees and Braves. I don't think there's
enough evidence of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Former union head Marvin Miller, whose efforts led to the end of
the reserve clause and the creation of free agency for players in
the 1970s, also has doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wholesale revenue sharing is the obvious answer in an industry
where revenues are ample but the problem is simply distribution,''
Miller said. ``... The owners always give the poor man's talk. They
kind of exaggerate problems like this when it's to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were concerned about all the problems caused by a
disparity, self-interest would tell them they'd better do something
about this, have more revenue-sharing and stop complaining. Because
sooner or later, if the disparity is a real problem, the haves will
be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig said the ``haves'' already are affected. Some have
suggested simply folding teams that can't make it, a notion the
commissioner rejects. If a team fails in any market, he said, it
benefits no one.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to imagine the players union ever agreeing to
let teams fold, since doing so would eliminate jobs. Likewise, the
union would be skeptical of any form of salary cap. Even a salary
floor, which could help avoid the annual payroll purge of several
teams, might may not be popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe any owner in this game should have players
telling them what they should spend or not spend,'' said agent
Scott Boras. ``I know from labor-management relations, we don't
want to put any restrictions on them (or have) them put
restrictions on players. That reduces the free flow of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at salary restrictions, the NFL is now giving us
a very interesting model: when you put caps on something, you take
away something that's very, very much a part of our game _
intellect.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners president Chuck Armstrong takes the opposite view.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the industry truly was competitive and truly had a level
playing field, then it's up to how smart you are, and that's what's
going to make it fun,'' Armstrong said. ``Because then you can
truly compete. The best model is the NFL. I mean, how can a team
exist in Green Bay, Wis.?''
</P>
<P>
   One proposal Towers favors is reducing free agent service time
from six years to four and eliminating salary arbitration. The idea
has been floated before, but it could make more sense than ever.
With the Yankees' Derek Jeter winning $5 million in arbitration
this winter after only three years' service time, it is becoming
harder for teams to lock up similar young stars through their
arbitration years.
</P>
<P>
   Some say these issues are really nothing new. Teams like the
Yankees always had greater resources than teams like the old St.
Louis Browns, Miller said, but the difference never showed up in
payroll because owners still held the reserve clause.
</P>
<P>
   Now that players have more freedom, he said, it's not up to them
to correct owners' problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players can't say, `I'm going to strike if you don't do this
or that to help yourselves,''' Miller said. ``Despite all the
propoganda, there is a bigger percentage of clubs in contention now
than in the so-called good old days before free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   The good old days. Baseball has more of them than any other
sport. As the game moves forward and gets its financial house in
order, Costas said, it also must celebrate its past. The only
unqualified success in the '90s, he points out, has been the
building of new ballparks with old-time charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try to out-hip or out-Gen-X basketball, or match the
violence and testosterone-fueled rage of football, if you try to
play that type of game, you lose,'' Costas said. ``You can't crank
up the volume on baseball to that extent. They should be
unapologetically retro as their guide to the future. That doesn't
mean you can't use modern marketing techniques, but the essential
experience should be timeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig said he hopes to refine recent changes in the game, such
as interleague play, which still is limited to West vs. West, etc.,
and ``modest'' realignment, which he said is needed to fix
scheduling problems. Selig also wants to expand baseball's
international presence. He knows the time to act is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hope these years will provide is the ability to take
this wonderful game and set up enough conditions so its competitive
nature is increased, its popularity is increased, we do go
international, do all the things that we're trying to do now,''
Selig said. ``What we do in the next four or five years hopefully
will ensure baseball's great popularity the first 20-30-40 years of
the 21st century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
