<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL APPROVES $97 BILLION SPENDING BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ House budget writers Wednesday approved a $97
billion spending plan for the next two years that maintains or
enhances current services while putting $4.3 billion in new
revenues into public schools and universities.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, a 9.6 percent increase over the current budget, would
spend $5.5 million every hour to operate Texas government with a
combination of state and federal funds. It requires no new taxes;
accommodates at least $500 million in tax breaks and leaves $200
million unspent to keep the state's checkbook balanced, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The increased education funding includes $3 billion earmarked to
enhance public-school teachers' salaries and benefits, and provide
some property tax relief. How that sum will be divided among those
purposes will be decided later.
</P>
<P>
   With House Speaker Pete Laney, D-Hale Center, looking on, House
Bill 1 was approved unanimously by the House Appropriations
Committee, which began its line-by-line review of state agency
funding requests in February. The mammoth bill, which complies with
constitutional spending caps, is scheduled for a vote in the full
House on April 13.
</P>
<P>
   The sum, which is for fiscal years 2000 and 2001, includes $59.2
billion in state funds; $27.4 billion in federal funds; $1.8
billion from the settlement with tobacco companies; and $8.5
billion from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best it's gone. This is the best product we've
ever had,'' said a jubilant Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell,
D-San Angelo, who handed out Easter baskets to committee members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe a bit of it is that we did have a little bit of money to
spend,'' he said, referring to a projected 1998-99 budget surplus
of at least $2.5 billion that makes the extra education funding
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good, tight bill,'' added Rep. Talmadge Heflin,
R-Houston. ``We're doing what we need to do in state government.''
</P>
<P>
   A total of $43 billion will go to education _ $30 billion for
public schools and $13 billion for universities. The outlay for
public schools represents a 13.4 percent increase from 1998-99,
while university spending would increase 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, lawmakers applied 63 percent of new revenue to
education; this time, they're applying 69 percent, said Rep. Henry
Cuellar, D-Laredo, who oversaw that part of the House budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go home and say that the commitment from the
Legislature is going to be in public and higher education,''
Cuellar told colleagues before they scattered for the holiday
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in several budget cycles, no big-ticket
prison construction was authorized, though $41 million was set
aside for repairs. Additionally, $13 million was included to
continue the Harris County boot camp, with the understanding that
the county would share expenses in 2002, said Rep. Sylvester
Turner, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've dealt with some tough issues, but one thing that we can
say is ... the process was fair,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diversity works,'' added Rep. Paul Moreno, D-El Paso, who
praised Laney for appointing a spectrum of Texans to the 27-member
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Laney said the committee's attention to detail would make it
unlikely that other members would be able to attach pet projects on
the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of you realize how much time you save the
members, because I've been here when we wrote the appropriations
bill on the House floor,'' Laney said. ``You've done a tremendous
job.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
