<HEADER>
A1441 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KINGDOME-HNS &LR;      03-31 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGDOME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Mariners first to go back outside to play, leaving gloomy Kingdome
for new park
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ALAN TRUEX &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
In the 1970s, multipurpose domed stadiums were the rage. Houston's
Astrodome, the so-called Eighth Wonder of the World, had its
imitators: the Superdome in New Orleans, the Metrodome of
Minneapolis and the 59,166-seat Kingdome of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome, which opened in 1976, may be more blunder than
wonder. Sparky Anderson, former manager of the Detroit Tigers,
said: ``I walk in there and I'm not sure what I'm in. It's just a
big ball of cement. No color. It seems like a big factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some hitters will miss it when it closes in July, to be
succeeded by Safeco Field. Braves coach Don Baylor said of the
Kingdome: ``When you walk to the plate, you're in scoring
position.''
</P>
<P>
   The stadium's bias for hitting is a mystery. It's darker than
the Astrodome, and it has a 23-foot-high barrier in right field
that's nicknamed Walla Walla.
</P>
<P>
   But for reasons no physicist has revealed, a baseball travels
better in the Kingdome than in the Astrodome. Sometimes it carries
into speaker boxes attached to the Kingdome roof. Dave Kingman once
launched a would-be 500-foot home run that bounced off a speaker
and was caught in deep left field.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, a similar missile from Willie Horton struck a speaker
and dropped for a single. That same year, a pop fly by Ruppert
Jones lodged in a speaker in foul territory. That feat was
duplicated four years later by Milwaukee's Ricky Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   The weird ricochets are an embarrassing trademark of the
Kingdome. But the building's main drawback is that the roof can't
be drawn back on days when Seattle's fickle weather favors outdoor
activity.
</P>
<P>
   When attendance lagged in the 1980s and early '90s, demand arose
for a retractable roof to keep the Mariners from drifting away as
the Seattle Pilots had done nearly 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome became the place not to be. One Mariners fan,
Joshua Normand, recalled sardonically, ``What I liked most about it
is that you could buy a ticket at 6:45 and sit anywhere you want.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the canyon-like emptiness, echoes reverberated; the
public address system could be difficult to understand.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 the Kingdome suffered its worst crisis: Ceiling tiles
broke loose the afternoon before a game, crashing into seats.
</P>
<P>
   Repairing the damage forced the Mariners on a 22-day, 20-game
road trip in midsummer. The acoustics were improved, but at a
tragic cost _ two workers were killed during the renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome's best days came in 1995 when the Mariners advanced
to the American League Championship Series. Fans responded, jamming
the concrete bubble to create a deafening roar.
</P>
<P>
   There were doubts the enthusiasm would last, but in 1996 the
Washington state legislature authorized $320 million for a
baseball-only stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Following approval of the new ballpark, fans continued flocking
to the old one. The Mariners ranked third in AL attendance in 1997,
with 3.19 million. Even with a losing team, they drew 2.6 million
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Kingdome is not as drab as its reputation promises.
No stadium with Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez in it can fairly
be called boring. The scoreboard is technologically advanced, and
the concession stands offer Starbucks coffee and well-crafted beers
from local microbreweries.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many sports arenas, the Kingdome has an attractive
location, near the entertainment center of Pioneer Square.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Field, which will seat 46,600, is farther from downtown,
in the aesthetically challenged Duwamish Industrial District. But
it will bring back real grass and sky. And it may have enough
luxury suites to bring sky-high revenues.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Kingdome, it will be demolished next year to make
room for a new football field for the Seattle Seahawks. Such is the
fate of multipurpose stadiums as the new millennium approaches. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
