<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-MESA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESA HOPES TO CHANGE MARINERS' DISMAL BULLPEN HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As Jose Mesa trots in from the bullpen, reaches for
the ball from manager Lou Piniella and attempts to restore his
once-invincible reputation, a piece of advice for Senor Smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Head for the nearest exit.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mariners bring in a closer, that's usually where the
fans go, cursing another unwanted giveaway night.
</P>
<P>
   For some unknown reason, stoppers come to Seattle to die. Or get
lit up. No position has been so unreliable for the Mariners. So
agonizing. So Bobby Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I can change that,'' Mesa said.
</P>
<P>
   Brave man.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander from the Dominican Republic not only is being
asked to register baseball's three most difficult outs, but also
wipe away two decades of game-ending ineptitude. Talk about going
extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   Every big-league team except recent expansionists Florida and
Tampa Bay had more saves than the Mariners (31) last year.
</P>
<P>
   Every team except 1990s expansionists Tampa Bay, Colorado and
Arizona has an individual save record better than Seattle (33).
</P>
<P>
   In 11 seasons that blown saves have been tracked, the Mariners
have rung up 20 or more on seven occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most teams have 13 to 17 a year,'' said Adam Loss, Rolaids
Relief Man researcher, which oversees those stats. ``Over 20 is
pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the year the franchise was saved with a playoff run,
the Mariners still blew 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, with another team headed for the postseason, they
blew 27.
</P>
<P>
   The big-league record is 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can do about it,'' center fielder Ken
Griffey Jr. said. ``I'm not a closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he should be. Everybody else has.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-nine different pitchers have registered Mariner saves,
which is part of the problem. The alumni list includes Randy
Johnson, Mike Hampton, Brian Holman, Dave Burba, Chris Bosio, Mike
Moore, Mike Morgan, Jim Beattie and Matt Young. Starters normally.
</P>
<P>
   The club relied on Bill Wilkinson in 1987. Nothing against the
lefty, but he was 22 and a rookie. Six years later, the club gave
the ball to Ted Power for half a season, after Norm Charlton was
injured. Power was 38, in his last year of baseball. The Mariners'
original closer was Enrique Romo, a Mexican League refugee. He
apparently wasn't too busy to start the second game in franchise
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just from being around the league, it's always been a bullpen
by committee in Seattle,'' said Billy Swift, who closed for the
1991 Mariners. ``I hate to say that. But you need one guy doing it
day in and day out. It hasn't been like that here.''
</P>
<P>
   In 22 seasons, the Mariners have had just two high-quality
closers _ guys who stuck around for more than one season and were
ranked among the league leaders. Bill Caudill and Mike Schooler.
Between them, they were responsible for 150 of the first 401
Mariner saves.
</P>
<P>
   The club eventually traded Caudill to the Oakland A's to avoid
paying him a huge salary. Schooler blew a shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Caudill, who saved 52 games for Seattle in 1982 and '83, lives
on the Eastside and coaches baseball on Mercer Island. Now 42, he
has watched recent Mariner closers with bemusement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see pitchers trying to be too careful rather than too
aggressive on the mound, and it's not one person,'' he said. ``What
I see coming out of the bullpen more and more is people trying to
nitpick.''
</P>
<P>
   When the man known as ``the Inspector'' played, the Mariners had
a closer and seemingly nothing else. Lately, the opposite has been
true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been interesting to me that they haven't gone out and
tried to sign someone to solidify that position,'' he said.
``They're running the organization and know better than I do, but
it's always difficult to get to the last game of the World Series
and win it without an effective closer.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Mariner response?
</P>
<P>
   ``Go around baseball and you will find more clubs have turnover
in the closer role than any other position,'' said Woody Woodward,
M's vice president of baseball operations. ``Guys like Dennis
Eckersley are exceptions to that rule.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the past five seasons, the Mariners kept coming back
to Ayala, possibly the club's least popular player ever. He was
booed at the Kingdome. He was booed at spring training. He was
probably booed whenever he went to the grocery store. Failure
ostracized him.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala had a nasty split-finger fastball, but an even nastier
habit of leaving the door open. He blew 30 Mariner games, more than
enough to obscure the 56 saves he collected.
</P>
<P>
   The second coming of Charlton couldn't fix things. Nor did
trades for Mike Timlin and Heathcliff Slocumb.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Mesa's turn to operate out of this little shop of
horrors.
</P>
<P>
   He comes to the Mariners with a high pedigree, yet baggage. For
Cleveland, he registered 46 saves in 1995, 39 in '96 and 16 after a
late start in '97. Then he blew the seventh game of the World
Series, against Florida, was traded to San Francisco and hasn't
closed since. It's been 17 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it happens, it's a tough job,'' he said. ``They put
you in for a couple years, you fail a little bit and they find
another guy. I think it was unfair. That really makes me mad, but I
keep pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Mesa not be up to the task, the Mariners can turn to
another Jose, Paniagua, who became a closer merely by chance late
last season and registered one save. Or newly acquired Mark Leiter,
who last year led Philadelphia with 23 saves but also topped the
National League with 12 blown saves.
</P>
<P>
   If desperate enough, the Mariners could even turn to another
offseason addition, Butch Henry. He saved seven games for Boston in
1997, after Slocumb was traded by the Red Sox to Seattle. He
enjoyed himself, as long as he knew the assignment was temporary.
He has a clause in his contract that he can ask for his release if
he is not a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a rush, or you're an adrenaline junkie, that's
what you shoot for,'' the lefty said. ``You could get hooked on it.
But I don't have the stuff to be a closer.''
</P>
<P>
   The stuff is usually a mid-90s fastball, an attitude, a Fu
Manchu mustache, a cheek bulging with chew, a stiff-legged walk and
a rigid routine.
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley, recently retired, would never speak or be spoken to
when he reached the bullpen in the seventh inning. Lee Smith, also
out of baseball now, used to sleep in the clubhouse for the first
five innings. They got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would come into the dugout yawning,'' said Mariner starter
Jamie Moyer, who teamed with Smith in Boston and Chicago. ``That
was his way of doing it. Nobody ever confronted him as far as his
habits.''
</P>
<P>
   Closers are like football placekickers. They can have more
influence on the outcome of games than any other individual on the
field, but usually turn up in their jobs by accident or default.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are doing something about this. Last summer, they
drafted a closer from the college ranks with their top pick. Matt
Thornton of Grand Valley (Mich.) State is being groomed as the
Seattle stopper of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly a basketball player, Thornton threw just 21 innings as a
collegian. No matter, say the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me I have the body and mindset for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping Thornton wasn't a history major.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
