<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERSITY FUELS WORLD SERIES CHAMPS ON HEELS OF RECORD YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Just what the rest of major league baseball needed, a
newly-motivated New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   As if it wasn't burden enough to try to back up a
record-breaking 125-win 1998 season. As if there wasn't desire
enough to go for a third World Series championship since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Yankees can prove themselves a team able to overcome
great adversity _ if you can truly call adversity an organization
with an $87 million payroll that boasts last year's batting champ,
Bernie Williams, and just acquired baseball's only five-time Cy
Young Award winner, Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   From high profile trades to serious health problems, this New
York club has endured enough distraction and hardship during the
past two months to make its players wonder at times if they have
become the damned Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   And yet New York remains the odds-on favorite to win another
World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   The best team in baseball has gotten better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to live up to our reputation as a professional
team,'' said starting pitcher David Cone. ``And good teams get
through bad times.''
</P>
<P>
   Spring training began last month with a blockbuster trade that
sent left-handed starter David Wells, lefty reliever Graeme Lloyd
and promising second baseman Homer Bush to the Toronto Blue Jays
for Clemens, who despite all his great personal triumph, has never
won a World Series ring.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily this kind of a deal alone would have dominated
headlines and spurred enough side stories to fuel a month of
papers. But a week into spring training Yankee great Joe DiMaggio
died and a crazy turn of Yankee fortune has followed:
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   -- Darryl Strawberry returned to play March 10 for the first
time since undergoing colon cancer surgery last October and was
hobbled by, of all things, a sore knee. On the same day fans
welcomed Strawberry to the lineup again, Yankees manager Joe Torre
told the team he had been diagnosed with prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's cancer is contained and doctors expect him to return to
his managerial post in 10 weeks. Strawberry, the Yanks' big-bat and
preferred left fielder, will start the year in Class AAA Columbus,
Ohio after finishing chemotherapy treatment.
</P>
<P>
   -- Two weeks after Torre's announcement, Yankees minor league
catcher Jaime Torres was diagnosed with thyroid cancer.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don Zimmer, who will manage the club in Torre's absence, was
examined by doctors for a bleeding ulcer on March 24, less than two
weeks into his new position.
</P>
<P>
   -- Andy Pettitte, now the only left-hander in the starting
rotation, strained a muscle in his throwing elbow early in spring
and will start the season on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   -- Of course it wouldn't be a Yankees spring training without
controversy. Yankees boss George Steinbrenner and former player
Reggie Jackson made up this week after a short-lived feud.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time preseason was coming to an end, New York
newspapers had relegated themselves to full-length feature articles
about pitcher Hideki Irabu failing to cover first base in the
fourth inning of an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   A normal team might be distracted or overwhelmed by such an
eventful spring. But these are the New York Yankees. And they
remain every baseball pundit's pick to repeat as world champions.
</P>
<P>
   There is no weak link in a familiar lineup that is as deep as it
is talented. It's so stacked, World Series MVP third baseman Scott
Brosius will bat at the bottom of the order.
</P>
<P>
   It's a card that features Williams, shortstop Derek Jeter and
second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who each scored more than 100 runs
in '98. Jeter and Knoblauch stole 30 and 31 bases, respectively.
First baseman Tino Martinez and right fielder Paul O'Neill each had
more than 100 RBIs. Martinez drove in a team-best 123 runs and hit
a team-high 28 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   With Clemens on board, baseball's most daunting pitching staff
has actually managed to improve. Clemens, last year's American
League Cy Young winner; Cone, a 20-game winner in '98; Cuban
sensation Orlando `El Duque' Hernandez; Irabu and Pettitte are
expected to anchor the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Mariano Rivera had 36 saves, a 3-0 record and a 1.91 ERA
in 54 appearances last year and relievers Jeff Nelson and Mike
Stanton will again provide solid bullpen support. Ramiro Mendoza
was 10-2 with a 3.25 ERA as a spot starter and has also been
effective in relief. He could move into a starting role early this
season should Irabu continue his spring struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can look to your right and see the same guy and look
to the left and see the same guy you saw last year and do that at
every position, it's outstanding,'' said Knoblauch, a former AL
Rookie of the Year acquired by the Yankees just before last season.
It just adds to the uniqueness of this team and this
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   In this era of inflated egos, the Yankees' pitching ace and team
leader, Cone, actually welcomed the Clemens deal _ even at the
expense of his No. 1 spot in the rotation. The team's young, flashy
All-Star shortstop, Jeter, sports a pair of World Series rings, but
he still refuses to address his manager as anything other than Mr.
Torre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we have the same resolve on a day-to-day basis that
we had last year and not get caught up in our celebrity of last
year,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get to the World Series; it is a need. I don't
think it's a need just because we won 125 games last year. We need
to get to the World Series because of who we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
