<SLUG> BC-YAHOO01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yahoo! expected to acquire Broadcast.com
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yahoo!, the Internet's No. 1 portal service, is
expected to announce plans today to buy Broadcast.com, a
Dallas-based provider of multimedia video and audio sports, news
and music events, for about $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation for some time a deal was pending. The
acquisition would further expand Yahoo!'s considerable range of
goods and services, which now include free e-mail, news and stock
information, magazines, and even credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara, Calif.-based Yahoo! and other major Internet
companies are trying to make their Web sites more attractive by
adding products such as live audio and video. The idea is to lure
users and keep existing users sticking around their sites longer.
</P>
<P>
   The length of a visit is one way Web measurement firms determine
a site's popularity. Web companies can then sell more advertising
at higher prices and rent spots on their sites to sell goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com's technology could be used to attract more users
and small businesses to Yahoo! using streaming media, or combined
audio and video broadcasts on the Internet. The acquisition of a
company like Broadcast.com, which specializes in audio, video and
live Webcasts, could also signal Yahoo's desire to acquire content
for the world of high-speed broadband access. In today's dial-up
Web environment, Broadcast.com's offerings are difficult to view
even on high-speed T1 workplace connections. However, as users move
to faster cable modems and high-speed telephone connections such as
DSL, the experience will become better.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com stock has surged about 40 percent since Business
Week reported Yahoo! might be interested in buying the provider of
live event Webcasts. The Wall Street Journal followed with a story
that Yahoo! would buy Broadcast.com for $110 to $120 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! will reportedly pay about $130 a share for each share of
Broadcast.com. Calls to Yahoo! and Broadcast.com weren't
immediately returned, though both companies declined to comment
previously.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! shares fell $3.93 3/4 to $168.37 1/2 on Wednesday and
Broadcast.com rose $4.81 1/4 to $118.18 3/4. Trading of both stocks
was later halted. Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
