<HEADER>
A1458 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATISSE-PICASSo-EXHIB     03-31 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATISSE-PICASSo-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MATISSE AND PICASSO' ENCHANTS DESPITE ITS FLAWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Yve-Alain Bois received his doctorate years
ago. But ``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle Rivalry,'' his most recent
curatorial project, still manages to read like a thesis exhibition
_ one predominantly brilliant but boneheaded in spots.
</P>
<P>
   You have until May 2 to see ``Matisse and Picasso,'' which
opened Jan. 31 at the Kimbell Art Museum in Fort Worth, its
exclusive venue. It features more than 100 paintings, sculptures
and works on paper _ slightly more by Picasso than by Matisse _ and
is the first major museum exhibition devoted to the artistic
``chess match,'' as Bois calls it, between the two giants of
20th-century modern art.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Bois' first stroke of brilliance: that he
thought to translate this well-known interaction into a show.
Surely it has been obvious over the years: If nothing else,
Francoise Gilot's 1990 book ``Matisse and Picasso: A Friendship in
Art'' spells out the mutual influence. Yet it took Bois to pursue
the obvious and the Kimbell to produce it.
</P>
<P>
   But here, too, is Bois' greatest blunder: his failure to
translate the obvious into a coherent visual experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle Rivalry'' features stellar works
by both artists and is an overwhelming pleasure to view. But it's
organized as a linear chronology that generally doesn't allow for
side-by-side comparison of key works. And that makes it difficult,
although not impossible, to learn by looking.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Bois' bottom-line idea is so strong that it knits
the show together in spite of the way it's installed. The
interaction he addresses is so real, so profound and so
encompassing that it allows us to form our own ideas about what's
going on between artworks. And we can always simply savor the
individual works, most of which are truly magical.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bois might have helped viewers out by placing small
reproductions or related works on the wall labels accompanying
certain pictures in question. This ploy would have been
particularly helpful early in the exhibition, because this part is
dominated by Picasso works.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Picasso's extraordinary ``Figure and Profile''
(1928) was painted in response to Matisse's ``The Piano Lesson''
(1916). ``The Piano Lesson'' is owned by the Museum of Modern Art
and probably wouldn't have been let go for this show, because MoMA
is co-organizing its own exhibition on Matisse and Picasso,
scheduled for 2002. But surely MoMA would have permitted a modest
reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too _ intentionally or not _ Bois' exhibition presents
Matisse as the greater artist, even though there are more works by
Picasso on view and even though both artists are represented by a
number of inferior pictures that Bois chose to illustrate some of
his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the installation, Picasso is transformed from
the intensely focused aggressor, an artist in top form, to a
follower casting about for a new sense of direction. If he starts
off in a proactive mode, creating one picture after another that
make teasing references to Matissean themes, Picasso ends up
reacting to Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   For when Matisse died in 1954, he went out like a lion. By then,
he was at the height of his powers, having developed his audacious
paper cutouts and successfully executing his commission for the
Chapel of the Rosary at Vence.
</P>
<P>
   Again, however, Bois' exhibition is stunning despite its flaws.
Walking through it is like attempting to wade through a heavy surf:
If you're not dragged bodily out to sea, you're at least knocked
off your feet by the art that has been assembled in the Kimbell's
galleries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle Rivalry'' is at its best in the
sculpture section, which presents several bronzes by both artists
in telling juxtapositions.
</P>
<P>
   Matisse, a master of modeling in clay, created pieces that hold
together as if by gravitational pull. Their integrity is innate.
Picasso, in turn, constructs his sculptures from individually
formed pieces of clay _ not unlike the assemblages and collages he
created from found materials _ that never quite relinquish their
separate identities. Even when they are masterfully incorporated
into works like ``Head of a Woman'' (1931), these components work
against the sculpture's integrity in an exciting way.
</P>
<P>
   As a bonus, both ``Head of a Woman'' and Matisse's ``Jeanette
V'' (1913) incorporate evidence of the processes of their making in
ways that enhance both finished pieces. Both were cast in bronze
from clay models. In his piece, Picasso additionally cast the
wooden armature that underpins that modeled clay. Matisse, on the
other hand, finished off his bust with a traditional pedestal, but
he permitted the seams from the sections of the plaster mold to
become part of the work, underscoring its cubistic qualities.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
