r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     03-31 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPPING UP THE SEARCH FOR MINORITY ADOPTIVE PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Gracie Bonds Staples 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Ken and Heather Smith sit in a conference
room of the Edna Gladney Center with nothing more than hope. But
even that is more than they had a year ago, when doctors told
Heather she could not bear children because lupus had begun
attacking her kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if I'd lost a child to know I'd never be able to
experience childbirth,'' said Heather Smith, 35. ``I was really
taken aback.''
</P>
<P>
   But under a relatively new Gladney program designed to increase
the number of African-American adoptions, the couple can become
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The center launched its African-American and Biracial Children
program a year ago but recently stepped up efforts because more
birth mothers want minority parents to adopt their babies, said
Paige McCoy Smith, a spokeswoman for the center. Requests have
jumped from about 20 a year to double that number in the past two
years, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gladney began public-service announcements starring TV
personality Nell Carter and established an advisory council of
minority community representatives and staff members to devise ways
to help raise awareness about their efforts. Revised brochures and
a Web site further emphasize the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout our history, Gladney has been placing children of
all races,'' McCoy Smith said. ``But we have found there is a
shortage of African-Americans, for whatever reason, who want to
adopt.''
</P>
<P>
   By increasing the number of black couples willing to adopt,
Smith said, the center can better accommodate birth mothers by
giving them more families to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 babies are adopted each year through the Gladney
Center, McCoy Smith said. Only 10 percent of those are placed with
African-American or biracial couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge problem. A huge need,'' said Retter Williams,
president of the Minority Adoption Council of Tarrant County, a
nonprofit support group. ``More children are coming into the system
than are going out.''
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the shortage, she said, are varied. Foremost is a
lack of African-American families able or willing to adopt; they
are either unaware of the need or cannot adopt because minority
children often come with a sibling.
</P>
<P>
   Gladney's ABC program is one of several efforts launched across
the country in recent years to publicize the need for more minority
families to adopt and to encourage them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   A group of African-American clergy members, for instance, began
a local affiliate of One Church, One Child four years ago. The
national organization matches homeless and parentless minority
children with caring families.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1993, Rose Jones, who for seven years helped recruit
adoptive families for Child Protective Services, started her own
agency, the Children and Family Institute in Fort Worth. The
institute finds permanent homes for children, including those with
special needs, and provides counseling and other services to birth
parents who want to keep their children.
</P>
<P>
   According to Raquel McFadden, an adoption caseworker and
coordinator of the Gladney Center's ABC program, the wait for a
child is generally six months to a year. But because of the
shortage of minority couples, their wait is less than half that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the demand, we need more African-American
families,'' McFadden said. ``We need more Kens and Heathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Smith, a 40-year-old financial analyst, and Heather Smith, a
product market manager, learned about Gladney and the program
through friends. After much prayer, they began the adoption process
in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really wanted was to have a family and raise a child
with my husband,'' Heather Smith said. ``I could do that with any
child.''
</P>
<P>
   At any given time, an estimated 100 African-American children in
Tarrant County are awaiting adoption, said Williams, who has eight
adopted children. In comparison, about 70 white children are
awaiting families at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, about 110,000 children are awaiting adoption, said
Joe Kroll, executive director of the North American Council on
Adoptable Children, a nonprofit agency that advocates for foster
children. Of those, about 59 percent are African-American, compared
with 10 percent Hispanic and 29 percent Anglo.
</P>
<P>
   Because costs are the biggest barrier to infant adoption, Kroll
and others said, Gladney's efforts are commendable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any effort by a private agency to be willing to put programs
in the minority community to recruit families we applaud,''Kroll
said. ``That's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Families pay as much as $9,000 to adopt a child through Gladney.
The fee covers a home study and a series of services to the birth
mother, such as medical care, legal services and counseling.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths said that they were attracted to the Gladney Center
because the program is comprehensive, well-organized and
internationally known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did they give us a lot of information,'' Heather Smih
said, ``they gave us a chance to interact with pregnant moms and
people who had already adopted from the agency.''
</P>
<P>
   The dusty exercise equipment that once sat unused in the Smiths'
third bedroom has been removed, making room for a crib, a rocker
and perhaps a dressing table.
</P>
<P>
   Someday _ soon, they hope _ their newborn will fill this space
and their hearts with the wonder of childhood.
</P>
<P>
   So now, they wait like expectant parents in a hospital delivery
room. Boy or girl. African-American or biracial. They don't care.
They just want a healthy baby.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
