<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1462 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-GRIFFEY-     03-31 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-GRIFFEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TALK TURNS TO AARON RECORD, GRIFFEY HAS A HAMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Enough already with this Y2K talk.
</P>
<P>
   There's potentially a far more disruptive element at work out
there. A threat to the daily balance that people across Seattle can
barely imagine. Paralyzing stuff.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of a contemporary label, let's call it KGJ756.
</P>
<P>
   Eight to 10 years from now, when people finally have sorted
through all the computer wreckage and recovered from that pesky
millennium bug, imagine a middle-aged Ken Griffey Jr., bald and
goateed like Jay Buhner and round around the edges like Tony Gwynn,
in the chase of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the 25th anniversary year of Henry Aaron becoming the
greatest home-run hitter of all-time, a possible successor has been
identified. To the next generation, the long-ball torch officially
has been passed.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can surpass Hammerin' Hank and his mammoth total of
755 big-league homers, the people's choice is Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   The stat geeks agree on this. So do current and former Mariner
teammates. Even Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   They believe that Griffey, with all that radiant youth and
burgeoning talent on his side, stands the best chance of one day
sitting alone atop baseball's homer mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Junior stays consistent, sure, the record's in jeopardy,''
Buhner says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe it,'' Aaron said. ``If he stays on track and
keeps his eyes on the prize, he could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   KGJ756.
</P>
<P>
   It stands for baseball record-breaker, not computer
circuit-breaker. It looks like an overseas flight number.
Ultimately it could be Griffey's personalized license plate number.
</P>
<P>
   Entering his 11th season in the majors, the Mariners' slugging
center fielder has accumulated 350 homers, ranking him 52nd on the
game's all-time list. He hit No. 300 last year in Cleveland and
easily could pick up his 400th somewhere this season.
</P>
<P>
   More compelling, the 29-year-old Griffey has collected 52 homers
more than Aaron and 112 more than Babe Ruth at a comparable age.
Aaron and Seattle's wunderkind won't be even again any time soon,
unless Griffey socks just eight over the entire 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Bill James, baseball's ultimate stat wizard, is so impressed by
this feverish pace he gives Griffey the best chance _ 45 percent _
of surpassing Aaron's 755 total. To reach this conclusion, James
uses a homemade formula comparing the player's age and long-ball
momentum. In this case, it's a career expected to last at least
another seven seasons and 56 homers per season over the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers come up Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a realistic chance he can hit quite a few more than
755,'' says James, a former Kansas school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   He gives Mark McGwire only a 34-percent chance of breaking
Aaron's record. The St. Louis Cardinal strong man captivated the
sports world last year by hitting 70 homers in a season to undo
Roger Maris' longstanding single-season mark. Big Mac's heroics
appear more suited for the short term. Age _ 35 _ is his downfall
here.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, of course, has to be not only good but lucky to touch
3,024 bases with his home-run trot. He has to avoid injury, hope
that Safeco Field is four-bagger friendly and lobby against any
league rule changes geared to alter a game turned power hungry.
</P>
<P>
   James prefers to see Griffey making contact on the sweet spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to imagine him not doing it,'' the stat man said.
``It's easier to imagine him doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   David Vincent, who tracks home runs for the Society of American
Baseball Research, has done his own detailed numbers crunch. He
estimates that Griffey will have rung up 485 homers by the time the
Mariner celebrates his 31st birthday, 605 at 34 and 725 at 38.
Aaron and Ruth didn't surpass 700 homers until they were 39.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Griffey decides he wants to play, and he stops running into
the center-field wall, he can do it,'' the Virginia-based Vincent
said. ``I have no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey dives out of the way when he hears all this.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing bat exploits never has been one of the Mariner's
favorite pastimes. To him, any acknowledgment that he has a yen for
socking balls halfway to the moon is braggadocio.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard Aaron single him out as the most likely successor
to obtain homer immortality, and appreciates the kind words from a
legend. But Griffey says he is not buying any of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be realistic,'' he said. ``I've got 405 to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey takes a few more cuts. On this subject, he swings from
the toes with scarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season must be getting close, because it's time to write
goofy things about Griffey _ Junior closing in on Hank Aaron's
record,'' he intones. ``It's not like it's 25; it's 405. It means
if I averaged 40 for the next 10 years, I'd still be five short.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates don't question his ability to pull this off. Just his
interest level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about hypotheticals,'' Buhner said. ``That's a lot of
years. Who's to say in four or five years he doesn't want to do
something else? Say, if he wins two or three World Series?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mariner newcomer Butch Huskey, ``For Griffey to play past
14 or 15 years, it will be because he wants to break the record. It
won't be for financial reasons. It will be a heckuva lot of wear
and tear. He'll have to play first base or somewhere else down the
line. I hope I'm still playing to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Griffey came along, Alvin Davis was the Mariners' top
home-run hitter. He had 160 in eight seasons. Davis can already
picture himself trailing his former teammate by about 600 homers
when all the hitting is said and done.
</P>
<P>
   In comparing Griffey and Aaron long-ball totals, health will be
the determining factor, Davis says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about it that he can do it, but some things
have to happen for Junior,'' he said. ``You have to be consistent.
You have to play every day. Look at Hank's career: He was a very
healthy player.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron told the Post-Intelligencer two years ago that Griffey was
the likeliest candidate to replace himself as baseball's homer
king. Aaron reiterated that thought at an Atlanta luncheon two
months ago. He repeated it again to the P-I last week.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday, when he is an opening-night visitor at the
Kingdome, Aaron likely will say it one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I talk with him, I'll tell him to keep doing what he's been
doing,'' the former Atlanta Braves slugger said of his impending
Seattle stop. ``Don't let anything change him. Records are made to
be broken. He's carried himself in such a way, everybody's going to
be pulling for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron, however, had a tremendous finishing kick at a late age to
catch Ruth's 714 total. He, too, wonders if Griffey will want to
stick around long enough to do wondrous things in the 21st Century.
Aaron wonders if he would have.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the catch, you can't do it in 15 or 16 seasons,'' Aaron
said. ``I hit a lot of home runs when ballplayers are usually
heading in the wrong direction. These guys are so filthy rich now
at such a young age, it's hard to stay focused. Today, I'd probably
be the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward, Mariner vice president of baseball operations,
won't argue with Aaron. Or Davis. If Griffey plays long enough, all
kinds of records will be shattered, the exec says.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward won't project numbers. But he says Griffey is capable
of getting the homer record. Keeping it, however, might be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have another guy who's going to be very similar in this _
Alex,'' he said, referring to Rodriguez, the Mariners' 23-year-old
shortstop. ``He just hit 40 homers and he's so young.''
</P>
<P>
   AR757, anyone?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
