</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:FACES:CHERYL-CROW-art-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHERYL CROW IN TOP FORM AS SINGER-SONGWRITER 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Includes one color slide of singer-songwriter Cheryl Crow. (Credit:
Courtesy of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHERYL CROW
</P>
<P>
   Age: 37.
</P>
<P>
   Home base: Born in Missouri, moved to Los Angeles in 1986,
currently living on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Claim to fame: Way popular _ and way attractive _ singer with a
slew of singles, hit albums and Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   History lesson: If Sheryl Crow weren't a pop star, chances are
she'd still be playing music. She has, after all, been tinkering
with music since she was 6 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by her musically inclined parents, Crow was writing
songs at 13 and playing in bands throughout high school. In 1984,
she graduated from the University of Missouri, majoring in music
composition.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, she moved to Los Angeles, where she waited
tables and recorded commercial jingles. Through the recording
studio where she worked, Crow heard that Michael Jackson was
looking for backup singers. She auditioned. She got the gig. That
started everything.
</P>
<P>
   She started writing songs for artists such as Eric Clapton and
Celine Dion; soon, she wrote her own album, her debut ``Tuesday
Night Music Club.'' Featuring the single, ``All I Wanna Do,'' the
record sold 7.2 million copies and won her a trio of Grammys.
</P>
<P>
   Between tours, she made the follow-up album, ``Sheryl Crow,''
which has sold 4.8 million copies since it came out in '96. It won
Grammys for Best Female Rock Vocal and Best Rock Album.
</P>
<P>
   Her third disc, last year's ``The Globe Sessions,'' has also
sold well and garnered her a Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike her first two discs, ``The Globe Sessions'' was recorded
in New York, in a sorta seedy meatpacking district. Crow says she
dug the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved working there,'' she told The New York Times. ``It
just was a cool, cool vibe. If you ever got really hung up in the
frustration of trying to get something accomplished in the studio,
you could walk out and just be amongst some bizarre energy. It
clears your head and gives you some perspective when you walk out
in such a strange, frenetic, unpredictable atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 1955EST &QL; 
