<HEADER>
A1477 &Cx1f; tab-z
w l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS:TEENSTALK-CLASSA     03-31 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:TEENSTALK-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE ABOUT ATHLETE FAVORITISM; PROMISCUOUS FLIRTING 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I'm in high school, and I know a lot of
athletes. And I know teachers do not discipline them like other
students. I have one teacher who helps the athletes with special
tutoring, and his papers always seem to be graded differently from
the papers of the rest of us. I think they want to make sure with
the no-pass-no play rule that the athletes still maintain their
grades high enough to play.
</P>
<P>
   If I were to act like they do, I would fail or be punished. I
don't know what to do. The teacher will get mad at me if I say
anything. I really don't know who to tell. I think this is unfair
to students. No pass, no play.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR No pass, no play: You make a good point. No preferential
treatment is appropriate for the school or home setting. A double
standard applied to athletes is not fair to you and other students.
Try to talk to the teacher or vice principal or someone at the
school you can trust. Discuss what you have seen and explain why
you think athletes receive less discipline and exceptions on
grades.
</P>
<P>
   You can discuss this with your parents and have them talk with
school administration. Even if certain teachers are handing out
grades to athletes, eventually another teacher will not, and the
student will fail.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: My friend is very promiscuous. She goes around
asking guys if they want to get lucky. She leads them on. She will
flirt with every guy. She will also make dates with several guys,
go out with one and then not bother canceling the dates with the
others. The guys get real mad. I think if she keeps this up, she's
going to get hurt. Worried.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Worried: Your friend is headed for major trouble. You can
talk with her and let her know that she should treat guys in the
same way she wants to be treated. No one wants to be led on, then
dropped. The guys will spread the news, and she won't be able to
find a good guy who will treat her with respect. Let her know that
you think highly of her and that she should respect herself enough
to change her ways. Let your friend know that she, like everyone
else, deserves that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a problem or concern that needs an answer? The Class
Acts Teenstalk panel _ headed by Kathy Pope, a counselor at a Texas
junior college _ is comprised of teenage students who care about
other students. Write to: Teenstalk, c/o Class Acts, The New York
Times Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
