A1489 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOURING-SYNTHESIZER-T     03-31 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURING-SYNTHESIZER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WELL-ORCHESTRATED RISE OF THE TOURING SYNTHESIZER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If you are lucky enough to get tickets to
``Rent,'' the largely sold-out touring production playing Bass
Performance Hall this week, you'll probably see something the New
York audience didn't get: an extra musician.
</P>
<P>
   The production of ``Rent'' seen in Fort Worth uses a
rock-inspired orchestra of six, an unusually small ensemble for a
Broadway show, but one more than the original show used. An extra
part was written to provide work for the additional musician, who
was added to the tour to cover spots in case of illness.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to touring shows, ``Rent'' is an anomaly: When
you attend a touring Broadway production in Fort Worth, you're
often hearing only a fraction of the orchestra that played in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's production of ``Phantom of the Opera'' at Bass
Performance Hall was far more typical. An orchestra of 30 to 35
members played the show on Broadway; 20 played Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly over the past three decades, almost as unnoticeably as
the paint on the wall that fades imperceptibly day by day, the
orchestra for touring Broadway shows has turned, in many cases,
into a half-orchestra plus electronic synthesizer. Listeners with
sensitive ears who attended ``Phantom'' at Bass Hall might well
have been perplexed by the long stretches of obviously synthesized,
electronically produced sound in places where they heard a
traditional acoustic string sound on the cast recording or on
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Critics lament the decline of the musical on Broadway, where
presenting a flashy spectacle, or reviving old shows from earlier
days, has eclipsed the traditional process of creating and
presenting shows carried by drama and music.
</P>
<P>
   But the audience just keeps pouring in. ``The Lion King'' _ a
knock-off of an animated movie _ and ``Phantom of the Opera'' _ a
feeble frame for special effects from a composer whose best work
was behind him in his early 20s _ have become tourist attractions
in New York, right along with the Statue of Liberty and the Empire
State Building.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike those venerable structures, the hit Broadway show
can become a traveling tourist attraction. You'll pay up to $75 for
a good ticket on Broadway; you'll pay just as much in places such
as Fort Worth to see the touring company. But you won't hear as
many live performers.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the synthesizer, a modest, almost unnoticeable
little keyboard down in the pit where the strings used to sit. When
originally introduced to the Broadway pit in the early 1970s, the
synthesizer helped to create the new gospel and rock sounds _ as in
``Jesus Christ Superstar'' _ that revitalized the Broadway scene in
those days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can write for the synthesizer, and you can write for it
well,'' says Joseph Stecko, music director and conductor for Fort
Worth's Casa Manana theater.
</P>
<P>
   But the synthesizer also introduced two degrading elements.
Instead of finding that perfect instrumental effect, today's
arranger may succumb to the temptation to hit close enough with the
synthesizer, and never apply the discipline that creates truly
memorable music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, I'd play real keyboard sounds on the
keyboard,'' says composer-musician Robert Stecko, Joseph Stecko's
New York-based son, who has played numerous Broadway and touring
shows. ``Nowadays, you play strings, oboes, cymbals, violins and
harps on the keyboard.'' (In a current production at Dallas
Children's Theater, the synthesizer also convincingly replicates
gastronomical distress, to much audience laughter.)
</P>
<P>
   For Broadway touring companies, and in smaller theaters around
America, the synthesizer has become a substitute for live players:
one musician seated at the electronic keyboard can fill in for a
whole section of string players.
</P>
<P>
   Although this has occurred since the early 1970s, it just
doesn't sound as good: The reliably perfect intonation doesn't
begin to make up for the loss of a group of human beings making
music.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Church, music director for ``The Lion King,'' contends that
the substitution of a synthesizer for a few live musicians doesn't
make that much difference. In New York, 24 musicians play in the
pit for ``The Lion King;'' on the road, the orchestra is reduced to
17.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just an artistic issue. It's a labor issue as well.
Local musicians in Fort Worth picketed when a touring production of
``Fiddler on the Roof'' at Will Rogers Auditorium performed with
only eight live musicians, none of them local. In the original
score, 26 were called for.
</P>
<P>
   Local musicians' union President Ray Hair vehemently supports
the idea of using local musicians to make up a full Broadway
orchestra for touring shows. Although the pit at Casa Manana holds
only 18 musicians, and thus requires that Broadway orchestra parts
often be reduced, the larger pit at Bass Performance Hall can
easily hold a full Broadway contingent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we have the opportunity to present Broadway shows with
original orchestrations,'' Hair says.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, major professional productions of Broadway
musicals come before the audience in three ways.
</P>
<P>
   Some Broadway touring shows, such as the recent presentations of
``Les Miserables'' and ``Fiddler on the Roof,'' are presented,
usually at Will Rogers Auditorium, by a New York-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth-based theater company Casa Manana presents major
touring productions, such as last summer's ``Phantom of the Opera''
and the upcoming ``Rent'' at Bass Hall. Casa Manana also creates
its own productions, sometimes at Bass Hall (as was the case with
the recent ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum)'' and
sometimes at its own famous domed theater-in-the-round (as with the
upcoming production of ``Annie).''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Casa played it safe, with an orchestra of 14 for ``A
Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum'' in Bass Hall _ even
though the pit in the new facility easily would have accommodated
the original full orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still finding out what it costs to put on a show in Bass
Hall,'' says Casa Manana executive producer Denton Yockey. ``If I
had known how successful `Forum' was going to be, we might have
used a larger orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Summer Musicals, meanwhile, proves that it can be done.
That company presents mostly Broadway touring companies at Fair
Park Music Hall and at the Majestic Theatre. But it also annually
produces one or two shows locally, and it has a policy of matching
the original Broadway score _ part of a greater philosophy of
reproducing in Dallas what audiences see on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to duplicate the original as closely as possible,''
says Dallas Summer Musicals president and managing director Michael
Jenkins. ``And we try to use as many local musicians as possible.
It's not always cost-effective, but we're more interested in
presenting a quality product than in profit.''
</P>
<P>
   However, with an annual budget of $19 million, Dallas Summer
Musicals earns more than it spends every year. And although we
can't make Broadway orchestrators and arrangers entirely abandon
the synthesizer, we have the opportunity to insist that the
orchestra for Broadway shows in Bass Performance Hall can be as
good and as large as those on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay covers classical music for the Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
