   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AID (Washington) _ France announces it will send 10
airplanes to the borders of Kosovo to protect refugee convoys from
Serbian forces, and Italy plans to send police officers to Albania
to bring order to refugee camps. By Elizabeth Becker. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ Serbian forces are now
shelling villages, towns and cities across a wide swath of Kosovo,
refugees arriving here say. The shelling drives more than 10,000
ethnic Albanians from their homes, according to a count by the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe. By John
Kifner. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ On the choices facing the White
House. By John M. Broder. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   HEMP-FARMERS (Bismarck, N.D.) _ Battered by sinking commodity
prices and rising costs, wheat farmers are looking across the
Canadian border at a crop they say could help save them _ if only
it were legal. That crop is hemp, a non-intoxicating look-alike
cousin of marijuana grown around the world for its fiber, seed and
oil. But long identified with marijuana both by law enforcement and
the counterculture, it is banned in the United States as part of
the war on drugs. As farmers from Hawaii to North Dakota to Vermont
lobby state legislatures to study hemp's potential and make it
legal, they are opposed by federal officials unwilling to relax
drug laws even symbolically, whether by endorsing marijuana's
medical use, or by approving a once-common crop, hemp. By
Christopher S. Wren. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
