<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALLIED-TROOPS (Washington) _ The United States and its
European allies launch emergency efforts to alleviate the deepening
refugee crisis along the borders of Kosovo in a move that raised
the possibility of British, French and Italian ground forces
entering Kosovo to create safe havens backed by U.S. warplanes. By
STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ NATO, opening the second week of air
raid against Yugoslavia, vows to leave President Slobodan Milosevic
no safe place from which to plan or execute his campaign against
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. By CRAGG HINES. (Will update.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOSNIA (Sarajevo, Bosnia) _ Some 7,000 Muslim refugees
from another part of Serbia, the Sandzak region, flee to the
Bosnian capital of Sarajevo, bringing accounts of beatings and
murders by Serbians and tanks massing outside their villages. By
LAURA PETERSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GROUND (Washington) _ Republican hawks, including former
Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci and former U.N. Ambassador Jeane
Kirkpatrick, call for the use of ground forces in Yugoslavia. By
BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EMBASSY (Washington) _ The State Department closes the
Yugoslav Embassy in Washington, with diplomats rousted out of their
building by federal agents. By JENNIFER DAY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-STATES-RIGHTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court struggles
with state sovereignty vs. federal power in a case involving an
overtime-pay dispute from Maine. The key issue is whether state
employees may legally sue the state in its own courts to make it
follow federal rules regarding such pay. By MARK HELM.
(1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
