<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SENDS SHIP TO MONITOR KOSOVO; U.S. OBJECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-VUKOVAR,
KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES,
KOSOVO-SOLANA, KOSOVO-HACKERS, KOSOVO-AID, KOSOVO-CLINTON,
KOSOVO-SERBS-NY, KOSOVO-UPDATE, KOSOVO-VATICAN) 
(nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia announced Wednesday that it is sending a
military reconnaissance ship to the Mediterranean to monitor the
conflict in Yugoslavia, a move criticized by the State Department
as unhelpful as NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia intensifies.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Defense Minister Igor D.
Sergeyev confirmed that Russia had notified Turkey of plans to
dispatch seven vessels from its Black Sea Fleet through the
Bosporus in two flotillas. But just now, he said, Moscow has
decided to send one electronic intelligence-gathering vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must insure the security of Russia,'' he said, ``and for
this reason we must have more concrete information about the
situation in the area. We must analyze such information and draw
the necessary conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   The six other ships are being prepared, he said, and a decision
on their deployment will be made ``when the defense ministry
decides that this is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian decision to send ships to the Mediterranean drew a
rebuke from the State Department, where a spokesman said that such
a deployment would not be a ``helpful gesture'' because it could
give the wrong impression to Yugoslavia about Russia's intentions
and because the ships' presence would only ``complicate an already
complicated situation'' off the Yugoslav coast.
</P>
<P>
   Top Russian officials, including President Boris Yeltsin, have
repeatedly said Russia will stay clear of the military conflict in
Yugoslavia, even as it continues to condemn the NATO bombings as an
act of unwarranted aggression. At the news conference Wednesday,
Foreign Minister Igor S. Ivanov reiterated this policy, but added
that the naval deployment was ``politically fully justified.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians announced their decision on the day Prime Minister
Yevgeny M. Primakov returned to Moscow empty handed from a
diplomatic mission that included stops in Belgrade and Bonn. Ivanov
said Wednesday that Russia would continue its attempts to broker a
political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed Primakov's failure to get a discussion going between
Yugoslavia and the allies on NATO intransigence, in particular on
its insistence that the bombing will not stop until Yugoslavia
first agrees to a withdrawal of its troops from Kosovo. President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia told Primakov that he would not
curb his forces' activities in Kosovo until the air strikes halt, a
stand that the allies rejected out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would this mean in practice?'' Ivanov asked of NATO. ``In
practice this would mean that Yugoslavia would have to renounce its
sovereignty over that region, hand it over to the so-called Kosovo
Liberation Army, which gets all the necessary support form the
United States and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fulfilled the task that we set ourselves: to get from the
Yugoslav leadership a clear signal in favor of a political
settlement,'' he said, noting that Belgrade had promised to start
withdrawing troop from Kosovo and to guarantee the rights of
Albanians if the bombing stopped.
</P>
<P>
   According to Western diplomats, the Russian delegation was
informed before it left for Belgrade what NATO's conditions for a
cease-fire would be. It is still unclear whether Primakov left on
his mission with the hope that Milosevic would agree to those
conditions, or whether he knew that it would fail, thus casting
NATO in the role of an unrelenting warmonger.
</P>
<P>
   Using the harsh Cold War oratory that has characterized all his
statements in recent days, Ivanov again accused NATO of unleashing
a ``humanitarian catastrophe'' in Kosovo, and of using the news
media to ``brainwash'' the public by blaming the mounting refugee
crisis on the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his assertions that the refugees fleeing Kosovo were
scared away from their homes by NATO bombs, despite eyewitness
accounts that the Serbian police and paramilitary have driven
Kosovo Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Constant bombing raids are being made against Kosovo,'' he
said. ``Even the center of Pristina is being struck. Populated
areas are being hit. A war is going on. In any war there are
refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees arriving Wednesday in Macedonia and Albania from
Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, reported an intense effort by
Serbian and Yugoslav forces to drive the Albanian residents out of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev also repeated earlier claims that the allied bombing
raids had caused more than 1,000 civilian casualties, with 28
Yugoslav service personnel killed and 90 wounded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
