<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-US-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP CALLS FOR NATO TROOPS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time since NATO began attacking
Yugoslavia by air, support for the option of sending ground troops
into Kosovo is gaining momentum here _ just as US and allied
officials hint it may be ``too late'' to consider such action.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, an influential group of former diplomats and
top-level government officials publicly called for the ``urgent
planning for deployment of NATO ground troops to Kosovo.'' And US
Senator Chuck Hagel, a Nebraska Republican, echoed the sentiment in
an column in The Washington Post entitled, ``Victory: The Only Exit
Strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcements came as dismay, frustration, and even
pessimism mounted in the capital over the allies' ability to bring
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic back to the negotiating table,
or to halt the campaign to uproot ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a war, and we need to recognize it's a war and allow
our military to do what is necessary to prevail in that conflict,''
said Frank Carlucci, former defense secretary and national security
adviser to President Ronald Reagan. ``If it means troops on the
ground, then so be it, even recognizing that this is an
extraordinarily difficult place to fight a land war and that it
would take time to get troops in.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlucci spoke a National Press Club briefing, as a member of
the Balkan Action Council, a nonpartisan group of influential
former policy makers, writers and others pushing for a peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Morton Abramowitz, a former US ambassador and assistant
secretary of Defense under President Carter, said the flaw with the
NATO strategy is that it has failed to protect the people of
Kosovo. Without a change in direction, he said, as many as a
million Kosovar Albanians could end up refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Abramowitz also said it was ``unacceptable'' to allow Kosovo to
be ethnically cleansed. Ethnic Albanians are ``going to have to go
home, and to go home may very well require the use of armed forces
on the ground.'' So it is crucial, said council members, for
President Clinton to prepare the American public for the
possibility that allied ground forces will be needed, at the very
least to ensure a safe return for the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Hagel said in his column that the allies must not
settle for half-measures. ``We must be prepared to do what is
necessary to achieve our objectives and ensure victory, including
the option of ground troops,'' Hagel wrote. ``The most likely path
to peace is in convincing Milosevic of our intention to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO has made much of maintaining the ``credible threat'' of
force. But for a military action to be credible, council members
said, it must include a well-planned alternative that goes beyond
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   This is a point made repeatedly by Senator John McCain, an
Arizona Republican and presidential hopeful who, while falling
short of advocating ground intervention, has been the lead critic
of the administration's decision to avoid such force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
