<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO LIBERATION ARMY NEARLY FINISHED, LEADER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Beaten back and running short of weapons, the
rebel Kosovo Liberation Army that spearheaded the armed effort for
Kosovo independence is on the verge of collapse, a guerrilla leader
says.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the guerrilla group is resupplied, or is helped by NATO
ground troops, Serb forces will drive them off, said Azem Syla, one
of the KLA's founders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA is not properly equipped with arms,'' and its supply
lines have virtually been cut off, said Syla, sitting in a barren
Albanian Army barracks near the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The logical consequence, if we don't have arms, is that we
will be defeated by Serbs and killed by Serbs,'' said Syla, who
goes by the nickname ``Daja'' and who was part of the rebel
delegation at the failed peace talks in France.
</P>
<P>
   He called on the Western alliance either to rearm the rebel
forces or send in ground troops, while at the same time conducting
its NATO air assault ``more seriously.'' Syla said that there had
been a convoy of 50 Serb tanks in western Kosovo earlier this week,
but that NATO had not bombed it. His claim could not be
independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Syla said the rebel force is running out of money for guns and
is finding it difficult to get whatever weapons it can procure over
the mined and heavily guarded border.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the rebel group, which held off Serb forces for
more than a year, had begged for a NATO air assault. But since the
airstrikes began last Wednesday, the situation for the KLA and the
ethnic Albanian populace it backs has become more desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Kosovo refugees have crossed into Albania
at the border near Kukes in the past four days alone. Many
thousands more have flooded across the Montenegro border, while
others have made the trek to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The battered rebel forces have withdrawn to six centers, and are
in a ``more threatened'' position in the two centers near the
Albanian border, Syla said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the KLA has completely pulled out of Pristina, Kosovo's
capital. In that city, Albanian sources say two neighborhoods,
including the hillside area where the US Information Agency and
other international organizations had their offices, have been
largely demolished by Serb shelling.
</P>
<P>
   In Albanian border towns, men in uniforms decorated with the
black, red, and yellow ``UCK'' emblem _ the Albanian acronym for
the rebel army _ wander the streets or sit idly in coffee bars. A
few troops were ferrying truckloads of ethnic Albanian refugees _
the human evidence that the rebels have failed to stop Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic's campaign against them.
</P>
<P>
   One rebel official in Kukes asked young men to sign up for duty
back in Kosovo, but none of the weary refugees was showing
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Even if NATO eventually forces the Serbs to stand down, the
rebel army's future is in doubt. A peace proposal developed by the
Contact Group of six nations requires its disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   But Syla said the rebel army would never completely disband.
``They can defeat the KLA, but they cannot demolish it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
