<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT JUSTICES SEEM READY TO TILT MORE TOWARD STATES IN
FEDERALISM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With its deep divisions over federal authority
versus state sovereignty on full view Wednesday, the Supreme Court
appeared on the verge of tilting even further in the direction of
the states than it had gone in a series of recent 5-4 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The court heard arguments on whether state employees can go to
state court to sue for federally guaranteed overtime pay, a
seemingly narrow question whose deep implications for basic
federal-state arrangements never appeared far from the justices'
minds. This was the first of four arguments in important federalism
cases that the court had agreed to hear in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The case Wednesday was an outgrowth of a 1996 Supreme Court
decision that closed federal courts to private suits of this type
against state governments. The Supreme Judicial Court of Maine
interpreted that and other recent decisions as announcing a broad
principle of state sovereignty that closed the state courthouse
doors as well, although Congress explicitly authorized suits under
the Fair Labor Standards Act to be brought in state court.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine court's decision was incompatible with the
Constitution's supremacy clause, which makes the Constitution and
federal law the supreme law of the land, Solicitor General Seth P.
Waxman told the court Wednesday. Otherwise, he said, the
legislative authority the Constitution conferred on Congress might
as well have been ``written in disappearing ink.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, Waxman, who brought the government into the case on the
side of 65 Maine parole officers and juvenile-justice caseworkers,
said the Maine court had misapplied the concept of sovereign
immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``With respect to federal claims, the sovereign is not the
state, it is the nation,'' he told the justices.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most telling comment of the intense and spirited
hour came from Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who was clearly
unpersuaded by either Waxman's argument or by the argument of the
state workers' lawyer, Laurence S. Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't conceive of the Constitution being ratified,'' Kennedy
said, ``if it were perceived that states could be sued in their own
courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The remark was significant because of the five justices who have
taken the states' side in the recent federalism decisions, Kennedy
has been widely seen, on the basis of his record, as the one most
likely to take a different approach in the current round of cases.
</P>
<P>
   But neither he nor the other four _ Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and
Clarence Thomas _ gave any sign of having concluded that the court
might have gone far enough.
</P>
<P>
   When Gold, representing the state employees, said that an
elevation of state over federal sovereignty in the application of
federal law would be a ``wholly extraordinary notion,'' Scalia
said: ``You say it's an extraordinary notion, but the whole system
of dual sovereignty and dual citizenship was an extraordinary
system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extraordinary,'' Scalia added emphatically. The exchange
was a reminder of Scalia's emphasis on state sovereignty in his
majority opinion two years ago, when by a 5-to-4 vote the court
struck down a provision of the Brady gun control law as an
unconstitutional incursion on the states.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      03-31 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the states. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter J. Brann, Maine's state solicitor, referred to that
decision Wednesday in his argument in support of the state's
immunity. The court had made clear that the federal government was
one of ``limited and enumerated powers,'' Brann said, adding, ``One
of those powers is not to abrogate a state's immunity in its own
courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Brann offered a sweeping argument, asserting that state immunity
barred not only private plaintiffs, but also the federal
government, from suing a state in state court. In answer to the
justices' questions, he also said states could not be sued for
violating someone's patent or copyright. The patent question is at
issue in a case the justices will hear next month.
</P>
<P>
   The state lawyer also made frequent reference to what he
described as the states' terms for agreeing to enter the union,
telling the justices, ``We can't violate the original bargain.''
Brann described the bargain as an acceptance of federal lawmaking
authority within a framework of state sovereign immunity from suit.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter, a vigorous dissenter from the court's
recent federalism decisions, sparred extensively with Brann. ``You
did give up the right to control the law that would be enforced in
your own courts,'' Souter said. He told Brann that Maine's position
lacked coherence and ignored the principle of federal supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   The argument in this case, Alden vs. Maine, No. 98-436,
proceeded on several levels simultaneously. On the surface, it was
about how to interpret the court's most directly relevant recent
precedent, Seminole Tribe vs. Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That 1996 decision held that the federal courts lacked
jurisdiction to hear suits against state governments by private
plaintiffs asserting rights under laws that Congress had passed
under its authority to regulate interstate commerce. The question
now is what that decision meant for the states' immunity in their
own courts.
</P>
<P>
   On a deeper level, the argument was a continuation of the
court's ongoing struggle over an even more basic issue, the federal
government's substantive authority over the states. Between 1968
and 1985, the court reversed itself twice on the question of
whether Congress had the constitutional power to bind the states to
pay their own employees according to federal wages and hour
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The final ruling in that series, in 1985, was a 5-to-4 decision
that the Fair Labor Standards Act did apply to the states. While
there is little doubt that most of the current justices are unhappy
with that decision, the court has turned down opportunities to
reconsider it; a third reversal in barely 30 years may strike some
members of the court as institutionally unseemly. Widening the
boundaries of state immunity from suit under the law, however,
offers a more oblique route to the same end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2021EST &QL; 
