<HEADLINE>
CHINESE PRIME MINISTER PLANS MIT ADDRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongji will give what is
being billed as a major address at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology on April 14 as part of his widely anticipated US visit,
MIT said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While his other stops on the tour will be watched for what he
says about human rights, trade issues, and US allegations that
Chinese spies stole military secrets, MIT officials said Zhu's
speech at the nation's premier institute of science and technology
will outline his vision of how his country's creations in those
fields will move it toward a freer, more market-based economy.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's speech in Kresge Auditorium will be
broadcast around the world by CNN and in China by official
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Americans, we tend to think everything of importance tends
to be invented in the United States, and China looks like just a
big market to us,'' said Suzanne Berger, head of the MIT
International Science and Technology Initiative. ``We don't
understand that knowledge today is being created in many different
centers in the world, and China will be a major center. The Chinese
will be our colleagues, and they will also be a center of knowledge
creation. We're going to see big things coming out of China.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of Zhu's US visit in mid-March came amid
tensions over a Chinese spy who the US government said stole
nuclear secrets from the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New
Mexico to create miniature warheads for the Chinese. In a public
address before his country's legislature, Zhu said he anticipated
facing an ``anti-China wave'' in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   His speech at MIT came out of a visit by MIT president Charles
M. Vest to China in 1995, when Zhu was deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him to be extremely interesting as an economist, full
of ideas of moving the Chinese toward a more open, more
market-based economy,'' Vest said. ``We know China will have an
increasingly important world role in the creation of new
scientific, technological, and industrial activities. What we
understand he intends to address is science technology and
education in a global society, which would obviously be a very good
fit for the venue.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, through the program Berger directs, MIT has several
projects working with China on the development of technology,
particularly in education and the environment. For the past several
years, it has sent 30 students to China for the summer to connect
Chinese high schools to the World Wide Web, and other students to
work in Chinese labs.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a blunt-speaking technocrat, Zhu is trained as an
electrical engineer, and has also been president of the Chinese
central bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
