<HEADER>
A1511 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-TAX-BOS &LR;      03-31 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HAMPSHIRE MISSES SCHOOL TAX DEADLINE SET BY COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N. H. _ After 15 months of divisive debate over how to
fund public schools, New Hampshire's citizen legislature failed to
agree on a solution in time to meet Thursday's state supreme court
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   In a December 1997, the court ruled that the state's system of
funding education through local property taxes was
unconstitutional, and that, come April 1, it would be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, lawmakers and Democratic Gov. Jeanne Shaheen have
been searching frantically for a solution, only to see plan after
plan collide with a stark reality: this is a state where taxes have
always been considered political poison. Just this week, the House
defeated a plan it had already approved in an earlier form that
would have included the state's first personal income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Granite State's attention has turned to the Democratic
Senate, where legislative leaders Wednesday were trying to build a
consensus around Shaheen's latest bill, a mix of a property tax, an
entertainment tax, and an expansion of gambling. But that bill
still faced hurdles within the Senate, which is set to vote
Thursday, as well as in the Republican-controlled House, where
opposition to gambling runs strong.
</P>
<P>
   And, everywhere, the grinding deadlock has left nerves frayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the constitutional rights of our kids and our
taxpayers are being trounced by spineless politicians in Concord,''
declared Thomas Connair, the lawyer and one-time school board
member in the mill town of Claremont who launched the winning case
that brought the court's sweeping decision. Since education is a
state responsibility, the constitution requires all property owners
to be taxed at the same rate to pay for it, the court found.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with bond rating services threatening to lower New
Hampshire's credit rating, every day of delay adds to the woes
facing the state and its schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``As each day passes the realization that you are getting closer
to the brink is happening,'' said John Cepaitis, an assistant
superintendent of Nashua's schools.
</P>
<P>
   Blame for the impass lies in part with the state's unique
political culture, and the ``pledge'' that lies at it's core. Since
1973, when then Gov. Meldrim Thomson Jr. and conservative Union
Leader newspaper publisher William Loeb crafted the vow to veto any
broad base tax, no governor has been elected without taking it.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Shaheen took that pledge in both her campaigns. She has
since bent her vows and indicated that she will countenance a
statewide property or sales tax but has vowed to veto any income
tax. An income tax bill passed the House and then the Senate but
failed on its return to the House this week because of Shaheen's
veto threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must have scattered Billie Loeb's ashes in Concord,''
said one dejected legislator after a House vote that doomed the
income tax.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no lack of ideas for how to raise money.
Proposals have ranged from increased taxes on liquor and
cigarettes, a capital gains tax and a tax on services like those
provided by lawyers or hairdressers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the Senate takes up a new version of Shaheen's own
solution, one that calls for raising $825 million largely through
the legalization of video gambling at the state's racetracks and
grand hotels, increased business taxes, a statewide property tax
and a new 8 percent tax on tickets sold by theaters, ski resorts,
racetracks and other for-profit entertainment businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Should that plan pass it will go to the House. But Rep. Neal
Kurk, chairman of the House Finance Comittee issued a warning
Wednesday: ``Any Senate proposal with gambling in it will be in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Without added gambling revenues, though, the state would face
three unpalatable options: increases in business taxes on the order
of $200 million to make up for gambling; a hefty statewide property
tax of at least $9 per thousand valuation, a first ever tax on
sales and services.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is over not only how to raise the money but also how
much to raise. If the total is not high enough, it may not appease
the coalition of property poor towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think $825 million does not do it,'' Connair said of the
Shaheen plan.
</P>
<P>
   Some found cause for celebration. Activists gathered Wednesday
in Portsmouth to celebrate the end of an era.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were throwing tea in the harbor and we are throwing local
school property tax bills into the harbor'' said Gordon Allen, a
former legislator and member of Citizens for Fair Education
Taxation.
</P>
<P>
   But the rules of the new era remain almost as murky as they were
when the deadline was first imposed almost a year and a half ago.
Indeed, said Allen, those who wouuld like to ignore the court's
ruling entirely have been emboldened because April 1 will come and
go with the school buses still rolling. A group of more than two
dozen conservative House members are backing a law telling the
court to stay out of the schools. It is an effort supported in
principle by House Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are among those who would like to see it said that the
court is wrong...that the court ought not to insert itself into the
center of the issue,'' said Rep. Warren Henderson, the House
Majority Whip.
</P>
<P>
   It will take not a law but a constitutional amendment to get the
courts out of the schools, however, Henderson said. The first
opportunity for voters to enact one comes in November, 2000. By
then the schools will have closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
