<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-INTERNET01-C     03-31 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-INTERNET01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web gives candidates' fund raising interactive edge
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In addition to a big win on election day, the
Georgia campaign of Gov. Roy Barnes engineered a lesser-known feat
in 1998: It produced a really cool Web site.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye-catching design and host of interactive features,
the site attracted loads of praise from the Internet political
junkies who actually study such things.
</P>
<P>
   The Barnes site was also cutting edge for another reason.
Barnes' campaign was one of only about 20 nationwide that allowed
visitors to make online contributions with their credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   But while the rest of the site may have been a winner, the
fund-raising aspect was largely a bust _ netting the campaign only
about $5,000 of some $11.7 million raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped us look modern and allowed us to make a few digs at
our opponents,'' said campaign manager Bobby Kahn. ``But for fund
raising, it was not that big a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Elizabeth Dole, who boasts $50,000 in online
pledges the first two weeks after her Web site debuted on March 10.
Or George W. Bush, whose Web site is already wired for online
contributions. Or Lamar Alexander, one of the first politicians to
begin experimenting with online donations back in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   With fund raising a top priority in the crowded 2000
presidential campaign, most major candidates for president are
urging potential donors to contribute online to their campaigns.
Only Bush offers credit card contributions, the most direct method
of online giving.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the pack is poised to join in when the Federal
Election Commission rules on whether credit card donations are
eligible for federal matching funds of up to $250 per contribution.
The FEC is considering changing the long-standing prohibition at
the request of former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, a Democratic
contender, and Internet giant America Online.
</P>
<P>
   An official at a leading manufacturer of online contribution
software, Phil Noble of PoliticsOnLine, predicts that 15 percent to
20 percent of all campaigns in 2000 will be raising money
electronically. He says presidential nominees have the potential to
raise several million dollars each online.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion in e-commerce is fueling some of the rush to
online fund raising. Politicians and their handlers are
trend-watchers, and few have failed to take note of the billions
transacted on the Internet during the last holiday season alone.
</P>
<P>
   Competition, the name of the game in politics, is another
reason. No candidate wants to be perceived as behind the curve, or
at a disadvantage to his or her opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the frenzy is also due to the fact that the Internet is,
well, the Internet _ the hot new frontier of the electronic age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's de rigueur in this cycle,'' says Eric Loeb, technology
chief with Net.Capitol, a political Internet consulting group.
``You need to get your tin cup out there early.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the new political fund-raising tool point to the
phenomenal success of Amazon.com and other online merchants who
have lured buyers to their sites to make purchases big and small.
</P>
<P>
   But buying a book online is different from sending money to a
political candidate, and that may help explain why expectations
about Internet fund raising haven't matched results.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a person buys something online, you get the purchase a
few days later,'' says Brian Jones, the Web site coordinator for
Alexander, the former U.S. education secretary who is seeking the
GOP presidential nomination. ``When you contribute to a politician
online, what do you actually get? That's part of the mystery . . .
How do you make people feel like they are getting something for
their money?''
</P>
<P>
   Another limiting factor, inherent to all e-commerce, is that
many people do not feel comfortable sending out credit card
information over the Internet, even though most such transactions
are performed over encrypted, secure transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns themselves have also been less than aggressive in
marketing their Web sites, says Don Goff of the University of
Maryland, who studied Internet fund-raising in the 1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can find the sites even if they are interested,'' says
Goff.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the presidential contenders this year appear to have
gotten that message and are aggressively promoting their sites as a
way to round up both volunteers and money. Forbes actually
announced his candidacy online, and Dole allowed the public to
catch an online simulcast of her announcement that an exploratory
group was being formed.
</P>
<P>
   But online contributing is also not without risks to the
candidate. Just ask Harlan Barnes, the Georgia governor's eldest
son and the Webmaster responsible for the governor's site.
</P>
<P>
   Harlan Barnes says that every credit card contribution was
followed up with a telephone call before the transaction was
processed, to make sure the people contributing were who they said
they were.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes says he lived in fear that the campaign would get some
bogus contributions that would then somehow make their way into a
30-second attack ad against his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be the one to bring my dad down,'' Barnes
says.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the inevitable technological snafus. For the
first several days that Alexander's Web site was up and running
this year, Web surfers who typed in the campaign's address,
lamaralexander.org, were instead connected to a nautical supplies
dealer in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Still, online contributing holds the potential to lure small
donors back into the political process, which continues to put a
premium on those donors who give the maximum allowable
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really encourages the right kind of contributions,'' says
Larry Makinson, director of the non-partisan Center for Responsive
Politics. ``You post your positions on your site. People evaluate
you and you send along a check. That should be the American way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
