<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1513 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS01-COX     03-31 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Census expected to miss 5 million people as debate over tally
method continues
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Census Bureau begins its mammoth task of
counting the population a year from today, the best Americans can
expect from a nose-by-nose tally is not very good at all.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau expects to miss 5.1 million people of an estimated
population of 270 million. To put that number in perspective, it is
roughly equal to the population of Maryland and it is worse than
the results of the 1990 census, widely viewed as flawed.
</P>
<P>
   And, like the 1990 count, the 2000 census will miss a higher
proportion of Hispanics, African-Americans and other minorities
than whites.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau has a proposal for finding most of those people, but
it is at the root of a years-long political controversy that is
threatening to derail, or at least delay, an undertaking that has
been compared in its complexity to putting a man on the Moon or
waging war.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this ongoing fight, Democrats are billing the census
as the next big test of civil rights. They argue that Republicans
prefer that minority groups remain disproportionately undercounted
because those groups tend to support Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real and great civil rights issue,'' said Commerce
Undersecretary Robert J. Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   In an atmosphere of mutual distrust, Republicans say they want
to count everyone just as much as the Democrats do.
</P>
<P>
   But they are leery of the Census Bureau's plan to make an
estimate of the population, no matter how scientific the method,
because they suspect the White House will attempt to manipulate
census numbers to benefit Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody believes they won't use it for political gain,'' said
Rich Galen, executive director of the Republican political
organization GOPAC.
</P>
<P>
   Census information is used to allocate the 435 seats in the
House of Representatives among the states, draw congressional and
other electoral districts within states and determine each state's
share of more than $180 billion in annual federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   The bickering between Democrats and Republicans is so bad that
Chief Justice William Rehnquist has issued a rare appeal to
Congress to keep funding for the federal judiciary out of the
dispute over the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judicial branch should not, and does not, have any role in
this debate, as the resolution of this issue very properly rests
with the political branches of government,'' Rehnquist wrote senior
members of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have complained bitterly about the Clinton
administration's failure to present a budget for the census over
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau had estimated that the census would cost $5
billion, but that was before a Jan. 25 Supreme Court ruling that
barred the bureau from using statistical sampling, a method of
scientific estimation, for purposes of apportioning congressional
seats.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is adamant about using sampling for
redistricting and other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   But that means the Census Bureau actually will produce two
population numbers for every state _ one for divvying up
congressional seats, due Dec. 31, 2000, and another for everything
else, due April 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make the 1990 census look like a Sunday school
picnic,'' said Rep. Harold Rogers (R-Ky.), chairman of the
Appropriations subcommittee that controls funding for the census.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt told Rogers that the
later number will likely be more accurate, particularly with
respect to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are headed for a showdown, probably around the
middle of June, when funding runs out for the Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the parties resolve the dispute over money, the
squabbling is certain to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Another wave of lawsuits awaits this controversial undertaking,
with the Atlanta-based Southeastern Legal Foundation first in line.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Glavin, president of the public interest law firm, is
confident that the courts will find that sampling may not be used
for redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court decision came in a lawsuit filed by Glavin's
firm. The court specifically addressed only apportionment, a point
the administration has cited in going forward with plans for
sampling for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   But Glavin said that earlier court decisions have used
apportionment and redistricting interchangably. Constitutional
requirements that the votes of American citizens count equally also
will lead courts to outlaw the use of estimates for redistricting,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he fears that if his firm files suit before Congress
provides funding for the census, a judge would rule the suit
premature.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Glavin's position is ultimatley endorsed by the courts,
Shapiro, the Commerce official, sees no end in sight to the legal
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be litigating this for the next 10 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
