<HEADLINE>
MEXICO: SHIPPING _ PORT OF CRAWL
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By BARBARA BELEJACK 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's first major port privatization took place
in Veracruz, on the Gulf Coast. Mexico's construction giant ICA,
with no port experience, teamed up with the Philippine-based
stevedoring company International Container Services, to win a
50-year concession in 1995. The port vastly improved productivity
and service.
 &HT;    But a booming business is now causing chaos. Cargo volume _
growing an average of 20 percent per yearis beginning to outpace
the improvements, catching Veracruz port officials by surprise.
Rail privatization may make things even more hectic. This year, a
second privatized railroad begins offering service from Veracruz to
Mexico City via Puebla, where Volkswagen has its North American
manufacturing plant.
 &HT;    If port problems in Veracruz seem troubling, most of the rest of
Mexico's major ports are in far worse shape, mainly because only
six of the nation's 76 ports have been privatized.
 &HT;    Although it's hardly reached a state of crisis, blame for the
port problems rest with the Mexican government. Last year,
officials at Mexico's Secretariat of Communications and Transport
(SCT) promised that five concessions would be granted by the end of
the year. It never happened. More recently, Pedro Pablo Zepeda
Bermudez, who heads the SCT's Ports and Merchant Marine division,
said publicly that the agency was considering packaging 12 ports
for privatization, similar to the way Mexico's airports are slated
for privatization. Translation: more delays.
 &HT;    Ironically, with cargo volume rising, how new concessions are
granted may not be anywhere near as important as when the process
gets up and running. Consider: Between 1994 and 1997, cargo volume
grew an average of 8.4 percent per year. In 1998, an estimated 230
million tons of cargo were handled by the ports, says the SCT.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, even the few privatized ports struggle to handle the
boost in demand. On the Pacific Coast, Manzanillo is expecting a
big boost in cargo now that a new private railroad operator has
widened the tracks to accommodate ``double-stack trains'' on the
185-mile route to Guadalajara. Transportacion Maritima Mexicana
(TMM) and its partner Stevedoring Services of America, which won
the concession to operate the port, are busy ordering new cranes to
double capacity. While slumping Asian markets have eased pressure
on the port, construction in and around the port has already
started to fuel complaints about congestion.
 &HT;    Traffic may get worse. The Saskatchewan Wheat Pool (SWP), a
Canadian agribusiness giant with more than US$4 billion in annual
sales, is building a $27-million grain terminal with Mexican
partner, Conquistadora La Junta, in Manzanillo. Saskatchewan's CEO
Don Loewen is hoping that the new facility captures cargo traffic
from the ``golden triangle'' of business between Guadalajara,
Mexico City and Monterrey.
 &HT;    Even with the fears that perhaps things are getting a bit too
crazy, Peter Brink, the general manager of Operadora Portuaria de
Manzanillo, which operates the private container terminal joint
venture between TMM and Stevedoring, prefers to look at the bright
side. ``I think it's great for the port of Manzanillo,'' he says.
 &HT;    Back on the Gulf Coast, the concession for Altamira, built less
than 20 years ago as an industrial port to compensate for the aging
Tampico, went to Remaconst, a Mexican company. In January 1998,
Stevedore Cooper/T. Smith from Mobile, Alabama, began operation of
a new facility as the port expanded storage capacity to 100,000
cubic meters. But, in this case, lack of a rail link has hurt the
port's ability to service key chemical companies. With a new
railroad slated to arrive soon, port authorities hope to solve the
situation.
 &HT;    There is hope that the current situation could push Mexican
officials to get the concession process rolling again. Further
developments may remain mired amongst concerns about unsteady
global markets, Mexico's austerity plan and the prolonged
legislative battle over the budget.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
