<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION STRIKER SAVARESE HAS FOOT X-RAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Revolution lost another key player, at least
temporarily, Wednesday. Striker Giovanni Savarese was taken to
Newton-Wellesley Hospital for X-rays on his right ankle after being
taken down by a sliding, two-footed tackle in a practice game
against the New Hampshire Phantoms.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese was felled in the third minute, and the match at Babson
College, in Wellesley, was suspended by Revolution coach Walter
Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid he will miss Saturday's game in Kansas City, but I
hope not,'' Zenga said. ``I want to have a friendly game every
week, but losing one player is enough for me to say a match is
finished. I hope this will not be repeated in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution seemed most displeased with the Phantoms'
comportment after the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese and Johnny Torres were approaching the New Hampshire
goal when Phantom defender Willie Schweitzer took down Savarese on
the edge of the penalty area. Savarese screamed as he fell and
Revolution trainer Mike Fritz arrived for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell it was going to get out of hand,'' Revolution
forward Joe-Max Moore said. ``It was a two-footed tackle over the
ball and there is no need for that. You can end someone's career
doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may think a game like this is an opportunity to show what
they can do. I'm sure some of their players would love an
opportunity to play in the MLS, and they might try to catch
Walter's eye. But there is no need to overdo it. When Gio was on
the ground, they were saying, `Tell your trainer to get him off the
field,' so they could keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams are scheduled to be rematched next Wednesday. The
Revolution faced the Rhode Island Stingrays last week, and
assistant general manager Joe Cummings said the midweek matches
will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this is the last bad thing that happens to us,'' Zenga
said. ``Gio is important for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution lost Imad Baba (groin surgery) during preseason
training in Italy and John Harkes (right knee ligament) while
preparing for the opening match against Miami. Edwin Gorter
(suspension) is scheduled to return for the April 10 home opener
against D.C. United. And Kris Kelderman suffered a slight knee
injury and practiced only briefly Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Savarese recovers, the Revolution might retain the
defensive strategy that nearly produced a victory at Miami. They
led from the 22-second mark, when Savarese set a Major League
Soccer record for fastest goal after the opening kickoff, until
Tyrone Marshall tied the score in the 88th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Though the team needs to develop the capacity to impose its
defensive will on the opposition, there will be a need for more
midfield possession and more offensive production. The Revolution
have been constructed to emphasize substance over style, but they
simply are not equipped for a perpetual battle of attrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second game should be better,'' Moore said. ``We need to
string some things together better.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore appeared in his first opener after injuries prevented him
from starting the season in 1997 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our defense was excellent and that was nice to
see,'' Moore said. ``It was better than giving up five or six
goals, like Walter said. But when we get our full team healthy we
are going to be a good team, and that will happen at some point in
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long season and there is time for everything to click.
After the next game we should have a better idea of what to
expect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
