<SLUG> BC-SLOBODAN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Positive opinions of Milosevic take drastic turn
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ To some of the people who came in contact with
him in 1995, Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic deserved some
credit for coming to Dayton and negotiating the Dayton Peace Accord
that ended the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But the Serb attack on the ethnic Albanian population in Kosovo
has caused opinions about Milosevic to undergo an abrupt change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure have changed my mind,'' said Dieter Krug, who hosted
Milosevic and the rest of the negotiators at a dinner in 1995 at
his restaurant, l'Auberge, in Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   ``His actions speak for themselves,'' said Krug. ``This shooting
and killing of innocent women and children is very bad. I hope they
come to their senses.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was more visible around Dayton during the talks than
either Croatian President Franjo Tudjman or Bosnian President Alija
Izetbegovic. The Serbian leader dined in local restaurants, hung
out at Packy's Sports Bar at the Hope Hotel at Wright Patterson Air
Force Base and shopped for shoes at the Fairfield Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Waszczak did not actually meet Milosevic but observed him
from close range.
</P>
<P>
   Then a student at Greenon High School, Waszczak, with John Kim,
won an essay contest and a trip to Paris for the signing of the
accord in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was a peacemaker then,'' said Waszczak, from
Pennsylvania where she is now in college. ``Now from what I see on
television he seems very stubborn, very hard-headed. It seems like
he wanted a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago Elinor Sluzas owned the Amber Rose, which
delivered Eastern European food to Wright- Pat during the talks.
Sluzas is of Lithuanian ancestry and talks to many people with
Eastern European backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening to others talk, I've seen opinions change
dramatically,'' Sluzas said. ``They see a man overwhelmed by power.
When any country is fighting a holy war, nobody wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
