<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FINDING WHAT WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The conflict between police and large segments of the
community in New York City is worsening, not easing. Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir have made the
unsettling and potentially very divisive suggestion that a recent
slight increase in homicides may somehow be linked to the protests
against police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, hundreds of angry cops, nearly all of them white,
chanted ``no justice, no police'' as they marched in the Bronx in
support of the four officers who shot Amadou Diallo. The marchers
contended that the killing of Diallo was a tragedy but not a crime.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, protesters carrying signs that said ``Arrest
Giuliani'' marched outside the courthouse in the Bronx where the
officers who killed Diallo were arraigned on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   And in Brooklyn this week the trial of the officers accused of
brutalizing Abner Louima got under way in federal District Court.
</P>
<P>
   The din of dangerously escalating hostilities has nearly drowned
out some very sensible comments and suggestions being made by U.S.
Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who describes himself as a ``friend
of law enforcement and of the minority community.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech he delivered on the Senate floor last week, Schumer
said it was wrong to judge all cops by the bad behavior of a few
and that ``there are men, women and children, black and white,
alive today because of the work of the New York City Police
Department.''
</P>
<P>
   He then added, ``But what we all must realize is that the
momentous drop in crime and the model behavior of many officers
does not undo the plain truth that black men and women in New York
City who have never broken the law and who should have absolutely
no reason to fear law enforcement are all too often hassled and
made to feel like lawbreakers.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week the senator said he wanted to come up
with some ``doable things'' that would prevent catastrophes like
the attack on Louima and the killing of Diallo, while contributing
to the successful fight against crime and insuring that law-abiding
New Yorkers are treated with respect by police.
</P>
<P>
   He had several suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   He said police officers who are a clear threat to the public
should be quickly weeded out. ``It was well known among the police
that Justin Volpe (one of the officers accused of attacking Louima)
was a bad, bad seed with multiple complaints against him,'' Schumer
said. But nothing was done about Volpe until his encounter with
Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said another ``obvious'' step that should be taken is
the recruitment of many more police officers from ethnic minority
groups. ``When mostly white cops patrol high-density, minority
neighborhoods, resentment is bound to follow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator noted that he and the Rev. Johnny Ray Youngblood of
the East Brooklyn Congregations have established a program to
recruit and train police officer candidates who will agree to serve
in precincts in their local neighborhoods for at least five years.
Similar efforts should be undertaken, he said, including an
expansion of the city's police cadet corps, which has been
neglected by the Giuliani administration.
</P>
<P>
   The senator also recommended that New York take a close look at
a program that has had great success in Boston. The crime rate in
Boston has plunged as dramatically as it has in New York, but
because of a cooperative program worked out between the Police
Department and a group of activist ministers, tensions between
police and the city's ethnic minorities have not escalated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston model will work in New York,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Another program worth looking at, he said, is the one developed
by the military to deal with the racial hostilities that erupted in
the ranks during the Vietnam era. A number of police departments,
working with the military, have adopted variations of that very
successful program, Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Constructive steps need to be taken now to end the divisiveness
that is threatening to inflict long-term harm on New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can bring these communities together,'' Schumer said. ``I
want to find what works and then get people to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
