<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-WEB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON E-MAIL QUEST RAISES ONLINE SECURITY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. has broadened its probe of on-line messages by
employees over the World Wide Web, creating an early test of how
far Internet service providers will go to protect the anonymity of
their users.
</P>
<P>
   A Massachusetts judge recently granted motions requested by
Raytheon demanding information from America Online, Microsoft
Corp., Earthlink Network Inc., and several other service companies
about customers Raytheon suspects posted private company
information on a Web site operated by Yahoo Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon alleges the employees' actions caused more than $25,000
in damages and has vowed to take steps to discipline the workers _
if it can identify them. However, the posts were made mostly under
pseudonyms such as ``Raytheonveteran'' and ``Jimbo255.''
</P>
<P>
   Unaware of their real names, the Lexington, Mass. defense
contractor has sued 21 users it calls ``John Does'' in a case now
pending in Middlesex (Mass.) Superior Court while the company
attempts to discover their true identity.
</P>
<P>
   But while Yahoo has complied with Raytheon's demand for
discovery, according to people familiar with the matter, other
service providers have different policies designed to give stronger
protections to people who chat on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, for example, notified customers who were subject to
Raytheon's demand for information and gave them up to 14 days to
seek to block the motion. ``It's only fair,'' said Rich D'Amato, a
spokesman for the Dulles, Va., company. A spokesman for Earthlink,
based in Southern California, also said the company wouldn't
automatically comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has to be looked at on a case-by-case basis,'' said
the spokesman. ``People have certain rights that have to be
respected and balanced'' against Raytheon's claims.
</P>
<P>
   Such comments show how Raytheon's actions have led it into an
uncharted area of on-line law, Internet specialists say. While the
company says it is only trying to staunch leaks, lawyers say that
its actions conflict with public expectations that companies will
respect their anonymity on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``People consistently expect to enjoy more anoymity than in fact
they do when the rubber meets the road,'' said Jonathan Zittrain, a
Harvard Law School Internet specialist. ``Those Raytheon employees
are probably thinking now they might shop around'' for service that
provides more anonymity than Yahoo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time they went into the Yahoo chat board, it probably
wasn't on their mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel this sense of invincibility because they're
posting anonymously, and they shouldn't,'' said Charles L.
Solomont, a partner at the Boston law firm of Bingham Dana who is
pursuing a simliar case involving anonymous chat about a Canadian
videoconferencing company.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's case centers on postings to a financial message board
maintained by Yahoo Inc., the California-based company best known
for its search engine used to locate sites on the Web. The message
board, billed as a discussion forum about Raytheon's stock, has
also become a center of much heated discussion about management
issues and the policies of the company's various employee unions.
</P>
<P>
   In its suit, Raytheon alleges that various employees posted
messages disclosing private company matters such as manpower,
profits, and bid proposals, in violation of company policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of these breaches of duty and other violations of
law by the defendants, Raytheon has suffered injury, including harm
to its business reputation,'' Raytheon's complaint states.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one person identified on the chat board only as
``Rtn RIF'' wrote on Oct. 21, 1998, that investors should ``NOT
look for RTN to hit 4Q estimates of $1.08,'' becuase of certain
accounting adjustments. In another posting, on Sept 3, 1998, a
person identified as ``Snobawl98'' wrote that ``Our stock is in for
a further slide to 35!! Due to info I have privy to about some our
booking problems I sold at 57! Thank goodness!''
</P>
<P>
   But other messages cited by Raytheon seem more innocuous. ``We
sure aren't doing that great with the current FAA contracts,'' one
poster wrote, referring to the Federal Aviation Administration.
Raytheon's new chief executive ``is going to drive the stock under
50.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing such messages, many critics both within Raytheon and
outside the company say the company's intent in taking legal action
was to silence dissent on its message boards. James George, a
private investigator in Haverhill, Mass. who often monitors Yahoo's
financial chat groups on behalf of law firms, said he suspects the
lack of protections by Internet service providers make it easy for
Raytheon to silence its employees without having to prove their
words actually caused damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They obviously have a lot of (angry) people, and they don't
see any downside if they can just keep them quiet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report in Wednesday's Boston Herald, a Raytheon
vice president has resigned after Raytheon identified him as the
source of some of the postings. The executive and his lawyer didn't
return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon declined to discuss the matter or how it identified the
executive. Diane Hunt, a spokeswoman for Yahoo Inc., denied the
Herald's report that Yahoo said it would comply with Raytheon's
demand for information.
</P>
<P>
   However, people familiar with the matter indicated that Yahoo
did provide data to Raytheon. Participants on Yahoo chat boards are
required to create an on-screen identity, and to provide Yahoo with
limited personal information _ just an e-mail address will do.
Since that e-mail address is not always included on public postings
on the chat boards, Raytheon sought and obtained those addresses
from Yahoo, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The demands for further information were filed by Raytheon's
attorneys on March 5, about a month after Raytheon's initial case,
and were granted by a judge shortly thereafter. In an affidavit,
Raytheon lawyer Jeffrey C. Morgan of the law firm of Hale and Dorr
described ``discovery taken against Yahoo'' as the basis of the
need for further information from other service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt declined to discuss Raytheon's demands to Yahoo or the
company's reponse. She said she wasn't familiar with Yahoo's
policies as to whether the company would notify users when it
received such demands, or whether it would give them a chance to
block the disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   On the company's Web site, Yahoo states that it does not make
personal information ``available to third parties without your
permission.''
</P>
<P>
   However, at a different point in the document, Yahoo mentions
that it might turn over such information in response to what it
terms ``special cases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
