<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-INDICT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR OFFICERS ARRAIGNED IN SHOOTING DEATH OF AFRICAN IMMIGRANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:45 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo of protest is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Four New York City police officers were arraigned on
charges of second-degree murder and suspended from the police force
Wednesday in the shooting death of Amadou Diallo, marking a new
stage in a case that has riveted, and riven, the city for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With security so heavy that the Bronx County building was shut
down, and with hundreds of demonstrators on both sides of the case
massing and chanting outside, the officers uttered their first
public statements about Diallo's death. Asked how they pled,
Officers Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Richard Murphy and Kenneth
Boss each emphatically replied, ``Not guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   The arraignment judge, John P. Collins of State Supreme Court,
rejected a request by the Bronx district attorney to remand the
officers, and set bail at $100,000 each. After the officers posted
it, they emerged from the courthouse and were greeted with cries of
``Murderers'' from demonstrators and chants of ``We Support You''
from fellow officers.
</P>
<P>
   Each officer faces two counts of second-degree murder. They
fired a total of 41 bullets at Diallo, hitting him with 19 of the
shots, as he stood in the vestibule of his apartment building at
1157 Wheeler Ave. in the Soundview section of the Bronx early on
the morning of Feb. 4. One count charges that the officers intended
to kill Diallo, while the other charges that they exhibited a
depraved indifference to human life. Each count is punishable by a
maximum of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The officers also face one charge of reckless endangerment in
the first degree, based on the charge that the large number of
shots endangered people inside Diallo's building. That charge is
punishable by a maximum of six years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx district attorney, Robert Johnson, broke an eight-week
silence on the case, first handling the arraignment himself, then
conducting a news conference. It was only the second time in his 10
years as district attorney that he had appeared personally at an
arraignment, the other case being the arson fire at the Happy Land
Social Club, which killed 87 people in 1990.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
