<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HACKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKERS CAUSE OUTAGES OF NATO WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-VUKOVAR,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-WARCRIMES, KOSOVO-SOLANA, KOSOVO-AID, KOSOVO-CLINTON,
KOSOVO-ARMS, KOSOVO-SERBS-NY, KOSOVO-VATICAN) 
(rk) 
 By   AMY HARMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an electronic assault on NATO's presence in cyberspace,
computer users in Serbia managed to temporarily disable the
alliance's site on the World Wide Web last weekend and cause
intermittent outages over the last few days, NATO officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Magis, NATO's web master, said computer hackers bombarded
the site in what is known as a ``ping attack,'' which twists a
protocol that Internet computers use to query one another into a
weapon that overloads a server with more queries than it can handle
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, anyone trying to retrieve information from the NATO
site was blocked from doing so all day Saturday, and parts of
Monday and Tuesday. To guard against such attacks, NATO officials
said they have added an additional server and a filter to block out
all ``ping'' queries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ping attack, the site has been flooded with
thousands of e-mail messages a day, some of which were designed to
overload the alliance's computer, and some of which contained files
with viruses. But the attachments containing viruses were not
opened and did not enter the computer system, Magis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've had a crisis like this,'' he
said. He emphasized, however, that the attackers did not manage to
break into the system and damage anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer security experts said the attack, which was relatively
unsophisticated, is one form of ``information warfare'' which will
be increasingly common as governments and the public rely on
computer networks for news and communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``This episode highlights the ease of entry for this kind of
warfare,'' said John Arquilla, a professor of information warfare
at the U.S. Naval Postgraduate School. ``You just need a modem.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One advantage of such attacks is that it is difficult to trace
their point of origin. NATO officials said their investigation led
to a server in Serbia, but they did not know whether it was being
used by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO site, which includes press releases and transcripts of
speeches by NATO officials in several languages, serves as a public
relations tool for the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In the week since NATO began air assaults on Yugoslavia, the
number of pages requested by Internet users has jumped to 90,000 a
day from an average of 30,000 previously, Magis said. The most
popular items are the video footage of NATO airstrikes taken from
the fighter planes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
