<HEADER>
A1558 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHWESTERN-UNIV-PRE     03-31 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHWESTERN-UNIV-PRES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Architect of Southwestern's success to step down in 2000
 &HT;    By Pamela LeBlanc
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Texas _ On the surface, it's easy to see the
sweeping change Roy B. Shilling Jr. has brought to Southwestern
University in the 18 years since he took the helm of the
liberal-arts college.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 38 major buildings on campus today, 23 were built or
renovated during Shilling's presidency. Trees have been planted.
Facilities updated. Sidewalks moved.
</P>
<P>
   But the deeper changes brought by Shilling, who has announced
that he will step down as president as of June 2000, may be more
lasting _ the school's transformation from a small local college to
one recognized nationally for leadership and academic achievement.
The school has increased the size of its permanent endowment
tenfold, tripled the number of student applicants and been named
among the best regional liberal-arts colleges in the nation _ all
during Shilling's tenure. ``I used to sit and think, 'Roy, you're
doing too much,''' said Isabel Brown Wilson, a trustee of the Brown
Foundation in Houston, which has contributed about a third of the
college's $337 million endowment in the past two decades. ``He was
the kind of man who never stopped working. He energized everyone
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shilling told the university board Friday of his decision, which
was made public Wednesday. By then, Shilling was more eager to talk
about the celebrities he saw in the stands at the Final Four
basketball tournament last weekend than his accomplishments. No, it
wasn't a difficult decision to retire: It's time to pass the baton
to the next leader. And even in retirement, Shilling, 67, plans to
share his expertise as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Shilling first came to Southwestern, the state's oldest
chartered institution of higher learning, in 1968. He served
briefly as executive vice president before taking the job as
president of Hendrix College in Conway, Ark. He returned to
Southwestern as president in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that this university had the greatest potential of any
institution in the country,'' Shilling said. ``I thought by working
with trustees and faculty we might be able to achieve that
potential. I hope we have exercised our stewardship well. We've
come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Shilling set into motion the school's master planning process,
which has guided growth and development decade by decade, purposely
limiting enrollment to about 1,200 students and focusing on the
quality of education.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after he joined Southwestern, U.S. News and World
Report named the university among the best regional liberal-arts
colleges in the nation. In 1994, it was reclassified into the
national liberal-arts category, a more selective group. That same
year, Southwestern landed a $6.7 million building grant from the
F.W. Olin Foundation, awarded on the basis of academic excellence
and national emergence.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Die, president of Hendrix College and chairman of the
Associated Colleges of the South, a group of 15 liberal arts
colleges that includes Southwestern, called Shilling ``a president
of presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a visionary, a strategist and an implementer,'' Die said.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Shilling lowered the student-professor ratio to
less than 12 to one and still raised faculty salaries. He forged a
partnership with the local school district to promote literacy and
combat dropout rates. And last fall, 55 percent of entering
students ranked in the top 10 percent of their high school class.
``He's really turned the school _ which was a good regional school
_ into a national powerhouse,'' said Southwestern spokesman Eric
Van Danen.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Shilling has kept his finger on the pulse of the
campus, paying attention to everything from staffing to curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years ago, he recruited biology professor Vicente D.
Villa from New Mexico State University. Villa had interviewed at
Southwestern, but turned down a job offer. Shilling called him
back, told him not to rush into a decision and ultimately flew to
El Paso to visit with him at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is that type of person,'' said Villa, named the 1993 U.S.
Professor of the Year. ``I was really impressed by his words of
encouragement. He's an outstanding person who deals with detail but
at the same time has the larger picture in focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Shilling, who earned more than $221,000 in salary and benefits
in 1996-97, will devote his time next fall to fund raising and
institutional visibility. He will take a sabbatical for the spring
2000 semester. ``I want to continue to be the number one friend and
supporter of Southwestern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Board Chairman Red McCombs of San Antonio, owner of
the Minnesota Vikings football team and a multimillion-dollar
contributor to Southwestern, will miss Shilling's leadership. ``As
hard as it is to recognize that Roy is moving on, I'm reminded of
the old saying `There's never a horse that couldn't be rode and
never a cowboy that couldn't be throwed.' We will, I think, be able
to get a very farsighted successor to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William B. Jones will serve as executive vice president of
Southwestern, working as the university's chief operating officer
during the 1999-2000 academic year. Jones, who joined Southwestern
in 1965 as a history professor, has served 11 years as provost and
administrative vice president. ``He received a school which had a
great deal of potential,'' Jones said of Shilling. ``What he did
was realize that potential ... He put us on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Trustee Jim Walzel will lead the search for a replacement, whom
officials hope to name by July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
