<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-CLEMENCY01-COX     03-31 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-CLEMENCY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas extends clemency deadline to 21 days
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas parole board Wednesday gave itself
more time to consider condemned prisoners' requests for mercy, but
defense lawyers warned that the move could backfire by denying some
convicts a hearing at all.
</P>
<P>
   The board's action stemmed from complaints about how it conducts
most of its business in private and rarely grants clemency to
condemned prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-hour public hearing, the Board of Pardons and Paroles'
policy committee voted unanimously to require death-row prisoners
to file their clemency petitions no later than 21 days before their
scheduled execution. The deadline had been five days.
</P>
<P>
   Parole Board Chairman Victor Rodriguez said the additional time
is needed for the board to properly review and vote upon requests
for clemency, which includes reprieves and commutations of death
sentences to life in prison. ``We have been pressed and pressed and
pressed. We are trying to give the board additional time to
consider these important matters,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   At a Feb. 5 meeting, the policy board had proposed a deadline 25
days before execution. Opponents of that had proposed 10- or 14-day
deadlines. The board settled on 21, however, after listening to
public comments on Wednesday that 25 days was too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give us more time, and I think it will give
(convicts) enough time to file what they need to file,'' said Board
Member Rissie Owens, who proposed the 21-day compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, several attorneys who represent death-row convicts
warned that extending the deadline could cause problems. In some
cases, they said, executions are set only 30 days in advance and
the clemency deadline will have passed before they or their
attorneys learn of the execution date.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Radostitz, an Austin defense lawyer, said courts that set
execution dates ``sometimes will notify the trial lawyer who hasn't
been involved in 15 years,'' instead of a convict's appeals lawyer
who will file the clemency petition. Austin defense lawyer Maurie
Levin said she has had clients read about their execution date in
the newspaper before they got official notice in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Other opponents said the new deadline poses a problem because
court appeals likely will still be pending at 21 days, making it
impossible for the parole board to tell whether due process has
been afforded _ one of the key elements board members have said
they use in reviewing clemency requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense bar is now faced with fighting two battles at one
time,'' Levin said. ``It will make the process more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the parole board makes only a recommendation to the
governor on clemency, its suggestion can mean life or death to a
condemned convict. Under Texas law, the governor can grant clemency
only if the board recommends it. A governor can grant a single
30-day reprieve, however, without the board's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said Wednesday's decision will take effect May 11,
meaning the first convicts who will have to comply with the 21-day
filing deadline will be three scheduled for execution in June _
including Joseph Stanley Faulder, a Canadian whose court challenge
of Texas' clemency system late last year helped prompt the change
in rules.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, the board has come under fire for the
way it decides clemency issues behind closed doors and for the
refusal by its members to give reasons publicly for their
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
