<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1560 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MISSING-BOS &LR;      03-31 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MISSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE US SOLDIERS NEAR YUGOSLAVIAN BORDER MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Kosovo-Identity)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ Three American soldiers on a ground mission
near here Wednesday reported gunfire, then disappeared, sparking a
massive search by NATO forces and local police near the Yugoslav
border, defense officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The news came at the end of a day when thousands of refugees
streaming across the border from Kosovo Wednesday said they had
been stripped of all identification by Serb police, confirming NATO
reports of a campaign of ``identity elimination,'' described as
part of a broader plan to erase all evidence that ethnic Albanians
ever inhabited the province.
</P>
<P>
   The US soldiers here were driving a military vehicle on a
routine reconnaissance mission in the Kumanovo area of Macedonia,
approximately two miles from Yugoslavia. They were driving on a
civilian road at the time, NATO Lieutenant Colonel Michael Kimmerer
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they were surrounded. Then no more was heard from
the patrol,'' another US defense official said.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearances came amid a newly-intensified NATO air
campaign, which appeared to hit at least one key target in
Belgrade. However, Yugoslav troops were reportedly continuing their
efforts in Kosovo with zeal, blowing up entire city and town halls
to incinerate piles of paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, leaders of the Kosovar Liberation Army, the
rebel separatist group seeking independence, said the group is on
the verge of collapse. A founding member, Azem Syla, said KLA
troops are in desperate need of either weapons or NATO ground troop
support.
</P>
<P>
   Abroad, Russian leaders also prompted new concerns, announcing
plans to dispatch a warship to the Mediterranean. White House
officials, unhappy with the decision, said they would nonetheless
trust Russian President Boris Yeltsin's promise to stay out of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he did not, however, trust Milosevic
enough to grant a cease-fire on Easter Sunday, despite pleas from
Pope John Paul II to do so. Clinton also explained his opposition
to sending in US ground troops in a CBS interview, saying what
bothered him was ``the prospect of never being able to get them
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was news of the ``identity elimination'' inside Kosovo
that eclipsed most other developments of the day, as refugees told
repeated tales of having their paperwork taken away by Serb
officers who then taunted them and told them they would never be
allowed to come home. Connecticut Senator Chris Dodd, who met with
top NATO officials in Brussels Wednesday, called it ``Orwellian in
scope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on a massive scale,'' Dodd said in a telephone call.
``Community after community, they are destroying these records,
taking documents from people.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the campaign was
proof Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic intended to ``rewrite
history'' by erasing the ethnic Albanians, who once made up 90
percent of the region's original population of 1.9 million. An
estimated 570,000 refugees have been forced out of their homes
during the current conflict, in which both Milosevic and Kosovar
leaders have claimed the province as their own.
</P>
<P>
   In Skopje, the Macedonian capital, Major Jan Joosten, a NATO
spokesman, said the Serbian strategy appeared aimed at rendering
the refugees ``nationless,'' so they could not re-enter Kosovo even
if there were a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Another purpose of the campaign is believed to be to drive waves
of refugees into Macedonia to destabilize the tiny nation, which
left the Yugoslav Federation in 1991 and in doing so infuriated
Milosevic, Joosten said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, refugees waited in packs at the Macedonian border
some 15 miles north of Skopje, wearily standing in lines that
stretched back several miles. Many said Serb police and troops had
looted their cars, snatching pieces of identification such as
passports and birth certificates as they tormented the refugees
with warnings they could never return.
</P>
<P>
   Standing near the border checkpoint, Jo Hegenauer, chief of the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees in Kosovo, also
confirmed that field workers were being told of the eradication
campaign by many refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking the IDs from men, especially,'' Hegenauer said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart denounced the atrocities once
again, echoing President Bill Clinton's suggestion a day earlier
that if the killings continued, Milosevic might be confronted with
international support for Kosovo independence. Lockhart said the
province ``would become so radicalized that that might prove
impossible to keep as is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community's support for keeping Kosovo as
part of Serbia would be eroded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also responded to the latest news of Russia. According
to the State Department, Russian officials informed officials in
Turkey that they would soon move seven units of the Russian
military's Black Sea Fleet into the Mediterranean in response to
the NATO airstrikes. That action was unwelcome to the White House,
where it was seen as sending ``some mixed messages'' about the
``purpose of this and the intent on the depolyment,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, referring to a speech by Yeltsin the night
before: ``We take seriously the Russian government's statement that
they have no intention of getting involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav military also presented a new challenge, as
Milosevic ousted General Radosav Martinovic, the head of the Second
Yugoslav Army, and replaced him with a close Serb ally. The Second
Yugoslav Army is stationed in the neighboring province of
Montenegro, which is still part of the Yugoslav federation but has
in recent days distanced itself from Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the conflict might spread, US and NATO officials have
kept close watch on Montenegro, and Wednesday offered to avoid
bombing targets there if Montenegran officials continued not to
side with the Serb leader.
</P>
<P>
   NATO military officials also sent a positive message about their
own campaign. After Tuesday night's airstrikes, officials said
early reports indicated a number of key targets had been hit,
including the headquarters for Yugoslav special forces in Belgrade
_ a command station for a paramilitary group accused of widespread
massacres in Kosovo. Some Serb tanks appeared also to have been
hit, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving almost daily to a broader set of targets,'' he
said. ``We will as rapidly as we can choke them off.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet questions remained about whether NATO strikes, which so far
seem only to have strengthened Serbian resolve, could make an
impact before the ethnic Albanian population disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   What had become of men of fighting age was especially unclear.
</P>
<P>
   According to one account, made by KLA leader Hashim Thaci on
German television, Serb forces had rounded up young ethnic Albanian
men inside a soccer stadium in the capital, Pristina, effectively
transforming it into a concentration camp. According to another
account, Kosovo rebels were stopping ethnic Albanian men ages 18 to
50 as they tried to flee Serb troops, sending them back into the
countryside to fight alongside the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   Neither report could be independently confirmed, and some
refugees from Pristina crossing into Macedonia Wednesday denied the
story of the soccer stadium, saying it was just a rumor.
</P>
<P>
   An independent radio report in Belgrade saying that eight people
were killed in the airstrikes also could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   But two Kosovo Albanian leaders reported to have been summarily
executed by Serbs over the weekend are alive, US diplomatic and
Kosovo Albanian sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fehmi Agani, a veteran politician who played a key role in the
Rambouillet peace talks, and Baton Haxhiu, the Koha Ditore
newspaper editor-in-chief who voiced the aspirations of his people,
had not been executed as reported by NATO Monday, the sources told
Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. We believe they are alive,'' a U.S. source said.
</P>
<P>
   A western diplomat in Skopje also said he had no evidence of
Serb concentration camps. If they were set up, the diplomat said,
American satellites and spy planes could detect them.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Senator Dodd, after a private meeting Wednesday with
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, put the atrocities in the
category of the worst crimes against humanity in history. He said
that ``any question about whether Slobodan Milosevic is engaged in
genocidal behavior has now been answered completely.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Cullen filed from Macedonia, Kornblut from Washington.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
