<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1562 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JAZZ-HNS &LR;      03-31 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SALT LAKE CITY _ The Utah Jazz has added a new word to its
basketball vocabulary.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Right alongside such staple terminology as pick-and-roll, blind
screens and Stockton to Malone, the Jazz has added another word:
slump.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the much-anticipated clash between the Rockets and Jazz,
a rematch of last year's Western Conference playoff opener, has
been dulled somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the collision course everyone had been expecting, the
teams, who meet for the first time this season tonight at the Delta
Center, are now like two ships passing in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets are the Starship Enterprise, having streaked to wins
in nine straight games and 12 of 13. Utah? Images of the Titanic
come to mind, since the Jazz has dropped four of its last six
games, including an embarrassing 26-point loss to the Los Angeles
Clippers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through some tough times right now,'' said Utah
forward Karl Malone. ``But we're a team that has always bounced
back and worked through the tough times. We have them every year,
and this is tough times now for everybody because it's no fun
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially in Utah, where the Jazz has won 60-plus
regular-season games and advanced to the NBA Finals the past two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers figured this season would include Utah's third
straight trip to the Finals, and the Jazz did nothing to ease those
expectations when it won 19 of its first 23 games.
</P>
<P>
   But
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say the Jazz has hit hard times the same way the
you-know-what hit that iceberg. And it has had the same effect.
Things are so bad that in ESPN.com's weekly NBA power rankings,
Utah is ranked 30th, even though there are only 29 teams in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   The guys at ESPN.com slipped in NCAA champ Connecticut at No.
21, a good-natured jab at the Jazz and its struggles of late.
</P>
<P>
   These are strange days indeed here in Utah. Of the Jazz's four
recent losses, three have come in overtime, including Tuesday's
104-101 setback at Sacramento. And its two wins in that span have
been difficult, to say the least. The Jazz had to rally to beat
Vancouver 85-80 and needed a last-second 3-pointer from Bryon
Russell to bounce Miami 84-81 at home March 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to turn it around,'' said point guard John Stockton.
``We need to play great basketball from here on out.''
</P>
<P>
   But things may not shake out that way for the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to most teams _ like the Rockets, for example _ the
Jazz has had a fairly cushy schedule to this point. But April kicks
off a brutal stretch for Utah, which will face the Rockets three
times and the Lakers twice and will play 16 games in 23 days,
including two sets of three games in three nights.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, Utah is mere percentage points ahead of the
Rockets in the Midwest Division standings, an amazing turnaround
from early March. Back then, the Rockets were a disappointing 10-8
after suffering a humiliating 40-point loss at Portland. At the
same time, the Jazz was 14-4 and had just started a six-game
winning streak that would put it at a league-best 19-4 on March 18.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the Jazz has hit the wall. And the wall
seems to be hitting back.
</P>
<P>
   The team that had been leading the league in field-goal shooting
suddenly can't find the basket. In the five games prior to
Tuesday's loss at Sacramento, the Jazz shot just 39.7 percent
(142-of-375).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's execution,'' Stockton said. ``It's the type of shots
we're having to settle for because we're not doing the little
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was that poor shooting more evident than in the line
next to Malone's name. Before hitting eight of 12 shots against the
Kings, Malone had made just 43 of his previous 123 shots, or 34.9
percent. This from a guy who is a career 53 percent shooter. The
streak was punctuated by his pitiful 1-for-7, seven-point effort
against the Clippers, during which the Mailman was ejected for
delivering elbows, not field goals, ending his streak of
double-figure scoring at 575 games.
</P>
<P>
   But Jazz coach Jerry Sloan refused to single out Malone for his
poor shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's struggling,'' Sloan said. ``We're trying to work
our way through it. Every team goes through stretches like this. I
just hope we can get it worked out and have a strong finish. If we
can do that, we'll be fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any practice, there isn't much of a chance to work on
our shooting _ at least the kind of shooting we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Jazz managed to break out of its shooting slump,
it found another way to lose. Utah connected on 51 percent of its
shots against the Kings but wound up committing a season-high 26
turnovers, including three by Stockton down the stretch in
regulation and in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been turning the ball over more than we ever have,''
said Sloan, noting the Jazz has averaged 22 turnovers in its last
four losses. ``(Tuesday) night we shot the ball better, but we
didn't get rid of those turnovers. We couldn't make a pass into the
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Kings) fronted us inside, and we threw the ball all
over the place. We hit the backboard with it; we hit the rim with
it, everywhere. If we had made a few of those passes, we would have
had layups.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the Jazz struggle with such fundamental aspects of the
game is odd and remains inexplicable to the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things aren't going well, you don't get the breaks,''
said guard Jeff Hornacek with a shrug. ``Things just seem to go
wrong, and that's the way it's going for us now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's called a slump.
</P>
<P>
   But as bad as things are going for the Jazz, Stockton said there
is no way his team is going to add yet another word to its
vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   He swears the Jazz is not about to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the worst thing you can do,'' Stockton said. ``There
have been other times we haven't played well. We have lost to teams
with horrible records before, and it's not good. It needs to be
addressed. But panicking would only make it worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
