<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-ENQUIRER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tabloids drop suits over lurid Gifford story
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The rivalry between the Globe and the
National Enquirer will be relegated to the supermarket checkout
lines once again.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe agreed last week to drop its federal lawsuit against
the Enquirer over a story about Frank Gifford's tryst with a Palm
Beach woman named Suzen Johnson. The Boca Raton-based tabloid also
dropped its suit against Johnson, who lured the sportscaster to a
New York hotel room where the Globe was waiting with audio
equipment and cameras to record the story.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe said it had the exclusive rights to Johnson's story
after the 1997 affair. But earlier this year, Johnson told the
Enquirer, a tabloid in Lantana, that she was paid $250,000 by the
Globe to ``help set up'' Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe, which denied setting up Gifford and said it paid
Johnson only $125,000 for her story, sued in response.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Johnson nor the Enquirer paid anything in exchange for
dismissal of the suit, though the agreement says Johnson is once
again bound by the confidentiality deal that started the dispute in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a ludicrous, unwarranted action and that's basically
what discovery proved,'' said David Perel, executive editor of the
Enquirer. ``We're not looking at them with any animosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 48, has also agreed to drop her countersuit against the
Globe, in which she said she was badgered into signing the contract
giving the weekly the exclusive rights to her story indefinitely.
She could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a sworn statement filed in federal court, Johnson said Globe
reporters smuggled her to hideaways in Florida and Mexico in the
weeks after her affair with Gifford. She said she was not allowed
to consult her husband or her own lawyer about the contract, and a
Globe reporter even slept in her bed to keep an eye on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to cry and told the Globe's lawyer and the reporter
I wanted to go home and I did not want to sign the contract,'' she
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Other details about Johnson's dealing with the tabloids have
emerged since the lawsuit was filed in January.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, nearly two months before her encounter with
Gifford, Johnson signed a ``source agreement'' with the Globe for
$50,000 in exchange for the story of her relationship with the
sportscaster. But $25,000 of that was contingent upon Johnson being
photographed with Gifford ``in a romantic encounter,'' court
records show.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Globe could not be reached for comment
Wednesday, but they have insisted in the past that they did not pay
Johnson to have sex with Gifford. They also said Johnson misled
them about the nature of her relationship with Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe also dropped its claims against Johnson's agent, David
Hans Schmidt, who was said to be negotiating a book and video deal
for Johnson _ projects that apparently would be barred under the
dismissal agreement. Schmidt, who no longer represents Johnson,
declined to comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
