<HEADER>
A1564 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      03-31 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BLAST SPRAGUE TAKEDOWN OF FRYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ Sensitive to the condition of Jeff Frye's
surgically repaired knees, the Red Sox, from manager Jimy Williams
to pitcher Pedro Martinez to Frye himself &UR;  &LR; -- &UR;  &LR; were unanimous in
condemning a takedown slide by Ed Sprague of the Pirates, who later
protested his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Frye had just taken a flip from shortstop Donnie Sadler on a
second-inning groundball by Al Martin when Sprague, on base after
Martinez hit him in the back with a pitch, slid through the bag and
beyond, knocking Frye off his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Frye was not hurt on the play, but Williams rushed from the
dugout to register his protest while Sprague exchanged words with
Martinez, who 11 days earlier had hit Martin, causing both benches
to empty briefly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't slide before the bag, at least not on my replay,''
Williams said. ``I don't mind guys playing hard. I don't like guys
playing dirty. They can hurt somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like that, period. I don't want our players doing it.
If our guys did it, it would be the wrong way to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Martinez was hit by a pitch by Pirates
starter Francisco Cordova, but he went straight to first base and
said afterward that he didn't believe the pitch was intentional. He
was less forgiving of Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't think as a human being,'' Martinez said. ``That was
really dirty. That was not nice. That wasn't professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye, who missed last season after undergoing knee surgery and
is four days away from playing in his first regular-season game
since September, 1997, sat in the visitors' clubhouse here and
ripped Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked he'd stoop to that level,'' said Frye, claiming
that it should have been obvious to Sprague that he had stepped off
the bag and had no intention of attempting to turn a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's going to be a tough guy and respond to a pitcher
hitting him with a pitch, he should go after the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had two knees operated on. If he's going to slide into me
when I'm not looking and say that's hardball, that's chicken
(expletive). That's just BS, that's all you can say. There's a
difference between playing hard and playing dirty, and guys who
play dirty will get theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye said he had stepped away from the base, toward left field,
after receiving Sadler's throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I tear up my knee again my career is over,'' said Frye, who
has had surgery on both knees. ``I'm sure he doesn't (care) about
that. I firmly agree with going in hard and sliding in hard to
break up two. That's the way I do it. But there's a certain line
that you don't cross. . . . I just lost respect for somebody,
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague, who played all nine innings and took some extra hitting
afterward, reacted strongly when told the Sox were offended by the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they were so upset about the slide,'' Sprague
said. ``It was a legitimate slide. I slid right through the bag. I
understand Jeff is coming off a knee operation, that's probably why
he's so upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't go out of my way to get him, and I didn't go
after him because Pedro hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague said he was in no position to assume that Frye wouldn't
attempt to turn the double play. ``I was already into my slide by
then,'' he said. ``Go talk to Wendell Kim.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague, the Pirates' third baseman, talked to Sox third-base
coach Kim after the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to tell Jeff that I wasn't trying to hurt him,''
Sprague said. ``If you try to ease up, that's the way you get hurt.
I always try to go hard, no matter what. That's the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the fourth meeting this spring between the Sox and
Pirates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
