<SLUG> BC-YAHOO01-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: 1ST UPDATE; Changes throughout.
 &HT;    Yahoo! expected to acquire Broadcast.com
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yahoo!, the Internet's No. 1 portal service, is
expected to announce plans today to buy Broadcast.com, a
Dallas-based provider of multimedia video and audio sports, news
and music events, for about $5.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   There had been speculation of a deal. The acquisition would
further expand Yahoo!'s considerable range, which includes free
e-mail, news and stock information, magazines, and even credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! said only that it has an 8:30 a.m. conference call with
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The deal means that Yahoo will pay about $130 a share for
Broadcast.com's 44 million shares outstanding, Dow Jones News
Service said.
</P>
<P>
   The price is more than the $120 a share that Yahoo had initially
offered, indicating its desire to avoid rival bids from other
interested companies such as America Online Inc. and others,
unidentified sources told Dow Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara, Calif.-based Yahoo! and other major Internet
companies are trying to make their Web sites more attractive by
adding products such as live audio and video.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to lure users and keep existing users sticking
around their sites longer.
</P>
<P>
   The length of a visit is one way Web measurement firms determine
a site's popularity. Web companies can then sell more advertising
at higher prices and rent spots on their sites to sell goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com's technology could be used to attract more users
and small businesses to Yahoo! using streaming media, or combined
audio and video broadcasts. The acquisition could also signal
Yahoo's desire to acquire content for the world of high-speed
broadband access. Broadcast.com's offerings are difficult to view
even on high-speed T1 workplace connections. That will improve as
users move to faster cable modems and high-speed telephone
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com stock has surged about 40 percent since Business
Week reported Yahoo! might be interested in buying Broadcast.com.
Yahoo! shares fell $3.93 3/4 to $168.37 1/2 on Wednesday and
Broadcast.com rose $4.81 1/4 to $118.18 3/4. Trading of both stocks
was later halted. Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
