A1586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRS-CHURCH-NYT &LR;      03-31 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-CHURCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT UPHOLDS IRS PENALTY FOR CHURCH'S ANTI-CLINTON AD IN 1992 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal court has upheld a decision by the Internal Revenue
Service to revoke an upstate New York church's tax-exempt status
for taking out newspaper advertisements before the 1992
presidential election that strongly suggested Christians not vote
for Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, handed down on Tuesday in U.S. District Court in
Washington, D.C., affirmed an IRS decision in 1995 to revoke the
tax exemption of the Church at Pierce Creek in Conklin, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS concluded that the nondenominational church violated a
federal ban on partisan political activity by tax-exempt
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling reinforces a boundary restricting what
religious organizations may do during political campaigns. The case
had been closely watched by some religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruling seems unlikely to discourage public activity by
religious groups around issues like opposition to abortion or war,
because the case was highly unusual, with a church having publicly
opposed a specific candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was first reported Wednesday in The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The full-page ads the church purchased appeared in USA Today and
The Washington Times on Oct. 30, 1992, four days before the
election, with boldface type stating, ``Christian Beware.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads accused Clinton, as Governor of Arkansas, of having
supported ``abortion on demand,'' the ``homosexual life style'' and
the distribution of condoms to teenagers by public schools.
</P>
<P>
   After the ads appeared, Americans United for the Separation of
Church and State, based in Washington, complained to the IRS. The
group's executive director, the Rev. Barry W. Lynn, said Wednesday
that the ruling clarified a distinction for churches. ``There had
not been a clear statement from the federal courts about the bright
line separating moral statements from direct political advocacy,''
Lynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn said his organization has also filed complaints with the
IRS in 16 other cases in which it believed a church-state boundary
had been breached, among them Vice President Al Gore's appearance
at a political fund-raising event at a Buddhist temple in Los
Angeles in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sekulow, chief counsel for the American Center for Law and
Justice, a conservative religious legal organization, which had
sued the IRS on the church's behalf, said he would appeal the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Sekulow said the ruling drew an ``artificial distinction''
between a minister's remarks from the pulpit and a church's
statements in a publication. ``Those are both forms of protected
speech,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An IRS spokesman declined to comment. In 1996, the IRS said that
under the federal tax code, charities, educational institutions and
religious organizations were ``prohibited by the terms of their
exemption from participating or intervening, directly or
indirectly, in any political campaign on behalf of, or in
opposition to, any candidate for public office.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, written by Judge Paul L. Friedman, rejected
arguments by the church that the IRS had revoked the tax exemption
because of the church's religious views and had inhibited its right
to free exercise of religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the circumstances presented here _ where a tax-exempt
church bought an advertisement that stated its opposition to a
particular candidate for public office, attributed the
advertisement to the church and solicited tax-deductible
contributions for the advertisement _ the IRS was justified in
revoking the tax-exempt status,'' the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Daniel Little, who was pastor of the church when the
ads were purchased, said he was disappointed by the ruling.
Although the church remains in existence as a legal entity, Little
and his congregation, which numbers about 400, have moved to a
building in Binghamton and are now known as the Landmark Church.
</P>
<P>
   Among its members is Randall Terry, the abortion opponent who
founded Operation Rescue, which conducted anti-abortion street
protests in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Little said he saw little distinction between a church losing
its tax-exempt status for having addressed ``moral issues in
writing'' and IRS agents slipping into church pews to take notes on
a sermon, ``and going home and saying, `He said non-tax-exempt
words.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom of the press and freedom of speech, they're more than
cousins, they're brother and sister,'' Little said.
</P>
<P>
   But Randy Tate, executive director of the Christian Coalition, a
conservative organization, said the ruling would not have a wider
impact on churches that have been involved politically.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
