<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1588 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMEDY01-COX     03-31 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMEDY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV's comedy headhunters are following their noses to Texas
 &HT;    By Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Pop quiz: What city hosts the third-largest
comedy festival in North America?
</P>
<P>
   If you answered Austin, you're better informed than most locals
regarding the Big Stinkin' International Improv and Sketch Comedy
Festival, which, in its fourth year, is living up to its hyperbolic
name.
</P>
<P>
   For reputation, the Big Stink does not compete with the closely
watched Montreal and Aspen comedy festivals, but it is gaining
respect, especially among television executives, who hunt on the
humor circuit for future stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this festival is an absolute must-go,'' said Cory
Stern, executive producer for Fox Family Channel. ``I get access to
completely unknown talent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It jumped to our attention this year,'' said Daysun Perkins,
coordinator of casting for the ABC Network. ``Improv is really
picking up around the country. Here I will be looking for anyone
who stands out.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to the fest, which showcases 60 improvisation and sketch
troupes, is the television talent pipeline. Comedy Central and Time
Warner Cable are heavily involved as sponsors, but Fox, NBC, ABC,
MTV, HBO and Walt Disney Company also are sending representatives.
Honchos from Def Comedy Jam, U.S. Comedy Arts Festival and
``Saturday Night Live'' will cast their nets widely among the many
showcase performances. Industry watchers in attendance include
Entertainment Tonight, Variety, Access Hollywood, Hollywood
Reporter and In Style.
</P>
<P>
   The big switch this year is the juried invitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We invited fewer groups this year to improve the quality,''
said Big Stink managing director Fiona Cherbok, who reviewed scores
of videotapes. ``I mean, you have to be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not always the case in the past, when barely qualified
troupes _ that seemed to have formed hours before the festival _
were showcased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been disappointed in the quality of the acts, since it
was nonadjudicated up until this point,'' said Gary Mann, producer
of HBO's U.S. Comedy Arts Festival. Mann, nevertheless, is
returning this year and is a big fan of the Austin sketch troupes
Monk's Night Out and Only 90 Percent Effective. ``It takes a while
for a festival to gear up. There was a certain amount of dreck
early on because it was essentially an open call.''
</P>
<P>
   The fest began with 20 participants in 1996, through the
pioneering efforts of Monk's Night Out, Austin's second most
successful sketch comedy troupe (after Esther's Follies). It
quickly grew under the ownership of Ed Carter, a former Monk who
saw the potential of a larger format.
</P>
<P>
   While talent scouts attend the Montreal festival during
television's development season and Aspen during the casting
season, smaller fandangos in New York, San Antonio and elsewhere
primarily provide off-season platforms for stand-up comics. The
Austin fest (and a new event in Chicago) concentrate on comedians
performing in groups for sketch comedy (scripted short programs)
and improv (formatted scenes that are improvised on the run).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the new kid on the block,'' said Mike August, television
agent for the William Morris Agency. ``But it has a niche to fill.
It's the only festival dedicated to the art of sketch comedy. And
it is very grass roots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As the talent in Austin improves, so will the buzz,'' said
Mann, who discovered several comics for his Aspen fest here.
</P>
<P>
   Some producers will come to the Austin fest with a laser-like
focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I am looking for a young, hip woman (16-23) to host
a block of afterschool programs,'' said Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many of the troupes are extensions of student or
``garage'' efforts, the Big Stink sounds a lot like the first years
of South by Southwest Music Festival. Groups with sassy names like
Houseful of Honkeys, Hits Like a Girl, Oui Be Negroes and Well Hung
Jury will participate in workshops and seminars, but also will
perform in several hundred performance slots Tuesday through
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   For many locals, the draw will be the minor celebrities, such as
Rick Najera (``In Living Color''), Dean Haglund (``The X Files'')
and Beth Littleford (``The Daily Show''). Practically the entire
casts of Fox's ``Mad TV'' and ABC's wildfire improv show, ``Whose
Line Is It Anyway,'' will be on hand for the galas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a lot to convince people to come to Austin,''
Cherbok said. ``Having a festival here is just like throwing one
big barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
