<SLUG> BC-Y2K-REPORT-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
92 PERCENT OF FEDERAL COMPUTERS READY FOR 2000, WHITE HOUSE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Calif.)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House said Wednesday that 92 percent of
the federal government's essential computer systems were now free
of year 2000 problems, but predicted that Americans would have
difficulty reaching some foreign countries by telephone or
airplane, because some computers overseas would not be fixed by
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the administration's self-imposed deadline for
finishing the renovation and repair of federal computers so they
will operate properly next year.
</P>
<P>
   John Koskinen, the White House official supervising computer
preparations for 2000, said that 13 major federal departments and
agencies had met the deadline. But, he said, 11 agencies, including
the Defense Department and the Department of Health and Human
Services, which supervises Medicare and Medicaid, missed President
Clinton's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Special
Committee on the Year 2000 Technology Problem, cited these examples
of systems that were supposed to be fixed by Wednesday, but were
not yet ready:
</P>
<P>
   _ Computers used to plan missions for the F-117A Stealth fighter
and the F-15E fighter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Command and control networks for the Ballistic Missile Early
Warning System, a critical part of the United States' air defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   _ A computer system that pays out $165 billion a year in federal
grants for the school lunch program, highway construction and
health care. This ``payment management system'' disburses money for
10 federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen, the chairman of the President's Council on Year 2000
Conversion, said the government had been making steady progress in
renovating its computers. Only 40 percent of the computer systems
were deemed ready last May.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 problem arises from the fact that many early
computer programmers used a two-digit format to express the year.
In such programs, 2000 could be interpreted as 1900 or not
recognized as a valid date. If the problem is not corrected,
experts say, computers could produce inaccurate data or shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said federal agencies had redefined the problem by
shortening the list of computer systems critical to their
operations. The number of such systems is now 6,123, down from
7,300 a year ago. In effect, the government revised its priorities
and decided that some computers were not so critical after all.
</P>
<P>
   By the administration's account, 12 percent of the 2,038
critical computer systems at the Defense Department have not yet
been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in Congress and at its independent watchdog agency, the
General Accounting Office, say the administration has sometimes
overstated its progress on year 2000 problems. But Koskinen said
the federal government was far ahead of state and local
governments, private industry and foreign countries in preparing
for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are clearly going to be countries that will have basic
infrastructure failings and problems,'' Koskinen said. ``There are
going to be some countries that you may not be able to reach by
phone. There are going to be some countries that are at risk that
their power grids are not going to hold, and they're going to be
without power for some time. There are going to be some countries
that you will not be able to fly to.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans should probably buy refundable tickets for airline
flights to developing nations, because some flights may be canceled
early next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said the executive office of the president, which
includes the White House, the National Security Council and the
U.S. trade representative, was lagging far behind most federal
agencies in fixing its computers, in part because it did not get
all the money it sought from Congress last year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   White House agencies have 65 to 70 critical computer systems,
Koskinen said, but only 25 percent met Wednesday's deadline to be
ready for 2000. The White House hopes to have 50 percent of its
computers ready by June and 75 percent by August, with the
remainder fixed by October, Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steve Horn, R-Calif., who held the first congressional
hearing on year 2000 problems in 1996, said he was distressed that
even a few federal agencies had missed the president's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among the federal systems not yet ready for 2000 are those
that operate the air traffic control system and pay medical bills
for the nation's elderly and poor,'' Horn said. ``It's a
significant concern that these agencies are still fixing computer
systems when they need to conduct extensive testing to insure that
the government's core business functions work from beginning to
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Rayner, the chief information officer of New Jersey, has
said that ``testing is 60 to 70 percent of the job of getting ready
for the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare relies on private insurance companies and other
contractors to review and pay Medicare claims. Kevin Thurm, deputy
secretary of health and human services, said the essential
computers run by his department and by Medicare contractors would
be fixed by this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said many big businesses had made good progress in
upgrading or replacing computers. But, he said, many small
businesses, local hospitals and smaller cities and counties have
deferred action. In many cases, Koskinen said, their announced
position is: ``We don't think it's a big problem. We'll just wait
and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department has one-third of the federal government's
essential computer systems. Koskinen said Pentagon officials had
assured him that their computers would be fixed by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those smart weapons in our arsenal have to be tested'' to
see if the computers and the computer chips will work properly
after Jan. 1, Koskinen said. ``You have to go through every
airplane, every missile, every weapon system to determine what is
at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said the Social Security Administration completed its
computer repairs five months ago and was testing the machines. In
private industry, he said, ``banking is clearly in the best shape
of any industry in the country,'' in part because federal
regulators have required even small banks to fix their computers.
</P>
</TEXT>
