 Column: NetZero Looks Like the Real Deal
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I recently heard about a company called NetZero that
gives free Internet access. I looked at what they're offering, and
on the surface, it looks good. They have numerous local telephone
numbers, unlimited access, etc. The claim is that they do not need
to charge because they make money strictly through advertisers. I'd
appreciate any information you can provide.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  NetZero looks like the real deal to me, too. Based in
Southern California, it has quickly grown to be one of the top 10
Internet service providers in the country, with more than 600,000
users. Its popularity isn't surprising when you consider that it
gives away a service for which most ISPs charge about $20 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The only catch is that you must put up with a constant barrage
of ads, which NetZero displays in a 1-by-3-inch window on your
desktop the entire time you're online. And that's in addition to
the regular banner ads on Web pages that you visit. NetZero's
advertisers, which include Disney, eBay, Macy's and Nissan, are
able to target their ads by using personal information you provide
when you sign up for the service, and through your dial-in number,
which tells them where you live.
</P>
<P>
   To use NetZero, you must use its software, which delivers the
ads. For browsing and e-mail, you can use either Netscape
Communicator or Microsoft Internet Explorer. You can download the
software, find out if there's a local dial-in number near you and
get connected by going to  &LR; www.netzero.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Prying Eyes
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have just started a new job and would like to use my lunch
hour to write some personal e-mail to people outside the company.
I'm hesitant, however, because the company's policy is that e-mail
is not private. They say they are monitoring e-mail, but I don't
know what that means, and I don't feel comfortable enough to ask
them. Does my boss have the ability to read my mail?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Your boss probably can read your mail if he or she wants
to. Assuming you're using a conventional system like Outlook or
Exchange, all your messages are stored on a server computer until
they're deleted. (Some companies get rid of e-mail every week;
others keep it for months.) As long as messages are in the system,
they're fair game for anyone with the authority to access them.
</P>
<P>
   If I were you, I'd ask my supervisor whether it's OK to use the
e-mail system for personal messages. If it is, just follow a few
simple rules and you'll never have to worry:
</P>
<P>
   _Don't write anything in an e-mail message that you couldn't say
out loud in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't discuss company business, especially competitive
strategies. E-mail like that can land you on the witness stand.
Just ask Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   _Never, in writing of any kind, refer to your boss as a horse's
rear end.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck Zipper
</P>
<P>
   Q: Often, when I download something off the Internet, it is in a
zip file configuration. Windows will ask which program I want to
use to view the file. I don't know even know if my computer has
such a program. Please tell me what I have to do to use zip files.
</P>
<P>
   A: You need a zipping-unzipping program, something that doesn't
come with Windows. The best one, IMNSHO (that's Internet for ``in
my not so humble opinion'') is WinZip, a $29 shareware program that
you can download from any shareware site including
 &LR; www.hotfiles.com  &LR; and  &LR; www.shareware.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A program such as WinZip is designed to manage files that are
compressed so that they take up less space (and can be downloaded
faster). Some compressed files end in .zip _ hence the zip
designation. Zip files can be a single file or many files zipped
together, as is often the case with programs that you download.
</P>
<P>
   Pentium Power
</P>
<P>
   Q: My good friend Jerry saved up for two years to get a computer
and got an HP 366-MHz Celeron system. He only has an eighth-grade
education and is very visually impaired, but he loves his computer.
He likes to play video games, but a lot of the games he wants say
the minimum system requirement is a Pentium II, and he figures that
because he doesn't have a Pentium II, he wouldn't be able to use
the games. Is that right?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've got good news for Jerry. The Celeron  &LR; is  &LR; a Pentium II,
just a little slower version of it. The 366-MHz chip in his machine
should be plenty fast enough to play any video game out there.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; The attack of the Melissa virus this week really brought home the
dangers that can lurk in e-mail attachments. ``Don't ever open an
unsolicited attachment'' is the '90s version of the old adage about
not accepting rides from strangers. To protect your PC, consider
getting software such as Norton's AntiVirus or McAfee's VirusScan.
These programs, which you can get for under $30 with rebates, can
sniff out and eliminate most viruses. And the makers quickly post
online updates to handle new viruses that appear on the scene, like
Melissa. Free trial versions are available at  &LR; www.norton.com  &LR; and
 &LR; www.mcafee.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
