<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Visa Says Use Of Its Products Rose 16% in '98
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Visa USA said yesterday that customer use of its card products
jumped 16 percent last year as consumers and businesses
increasingly reached for plastic instead of cash or checks.
</P>
<P>
   Led by fast-growing use of debit cards and corporate cards,
total spending in the United States under the Visa brand reached
$610.3 billion in 1998. Visa, based in Foster City, predicted that
it will cross the $1 trillion threshold by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Visa said it accounted for 10.5 percent of total consumer
payments last year, compared with 6.2 percent in 1994 and 9.6
percent in 1997. The association measures its market share in terms
of all consumer payments for goods and services, not just credit
and debit card payments.
</P>
<P>
   That growth came by grabbing a higher share of payments
traditionally made with cash or checks, such as those for national
parks fees, utility bills and fast-food restaurant meals, Visa USA
chief executive Carl Pascarella said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cash and checks are the real competitors,'' Pascarella
stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Visa handily dominates the credit and debit card market. It said
it upped its share 0.6 percentage point to 52.8 percent in 1998,
about twice that of No.2 MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of Visa credit and debit cards in circulation
in this country rose 7.9 percent to 322.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Visa's gains came despite a brewing crisis that surfaced as an
increasingly powerful group of big banks that dominate the
organization demanded sweeping changes. The association is owned by
member banks that actually issue Visa cards.
</P>
<P>
   Members such as BankAmerica are pressuring Visa to scale back
its massive marketing program, which they think interferes with
their efforts to promote their own brand names. Visa has been
forced to make concessions, such as considering a plan to let
issuers move the Visa logo from the front to the back of credit and
debit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from Citigroup, the nation's largest bank, recently
quit Visa's board because of disagreements over the association's
marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Visa's growth ``is particularly impressive in light of the
internal and external challenges they are facing,'' said Jim
Greene, a credit card specialist with Andersen Consulting in San
Francisco. Visa is an Andersen client.
</P>
<P>
   Visa's business cards grew quickly last year, an area
traditionally dominated by American Express. Transactions on those
cards rose 41.7 percent to $31.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Those gains reflect a series of product introductions, such as
business-to-business purchasing cards, and an advertising campaign
that targeted small business, Pascarella said.
</P>
<P>
   Transactions using Visa's debit cards, which make payments by
withdrawing funds from the cardholder's checking account, rose 43
percent last year. Banks have been pushing their use because they
are cheaper to process than checks.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional credit card volume grew 8 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Visa didn't release separate figures for online transactions,
but they have been an important area of growth. The association
calculates that it controlled more than half of the estimated $3
billion to $5 billion in Internet payments during the last three
months of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
