<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1595 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      03-31 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Long before the Astros arrived in Florida this
year, manager Larry Dierker warned everyone not to expect a repeat
of 1998, when his team won a franchise-record 102 games.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quite frankly, the odds are against it. In 1998, the Astros
coasted through the season without significant injuries to key
players, and several players produced career years. What are the
chances of that happening again?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not very good.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou, who some believe was the Astros' most valuable
player in 1998, never made it to spring training, thanks to a freak
accident on a treadmill. The addition of Ken Caminiti was supposed
to help pick up some of the slack caused by Alou's potentially
season-ending knee injury, but illnesses put Caminiti behind
schedule this spring, and he might start the season on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, it's safe to assume the Astros' offense, which
produced a club-record 874 runs last season, might lose some of its
potency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the pitching. The Astros were a good team
before they acquired Randy Johnson at the trading deadline last
season, but they became a great team after that. Johnson won 10 of
his 11 starts down the stretch but bolted for Arizona as a free
agent during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement in the rotation, Chris Holt, has just eight
career victories and hasn't pitched in a regular-season big-league
game since the end of the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their apparent drop-off, the Astros still appear to
be the best team in the National League Central, and they will
enter the season favored to win the division for the third
consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question will be asked: Is the team that will take
the field against the Cubs on opening day as good as the team that
ended the 1998 season with a Division Series loss to the Padres?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``Who knows what's
going to happen this year, but we knew we had a great team last
season. You don't win 102 games without being a great team. That
was the best team I've ever played on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm wrong. Maybe this year's team will turn out to be
that good, too. But I think we'll have to play into the season
before that can be determined. We're missing some guys, but we're
still a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious difference between the 1999 Astros and last
year's version is depth. Because the Astros were so stacked in
1998, Carl Everett, Richard Hidalgo and Tony Eusebio couldn't get
regular playing time. This year, they'll each be in the opening-day
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The scaled-down bench leaves the Astros more vulnerable to
injury. For instance, if another outfielder goes down, the
major-league replacements are Glen Barker and Alex Diaz. Both serve
a valuable role on the team, but neither is considered an every-day
player. Does the name Lance Berkman ring a bell?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any doubt that our overall talent is
lesser,'' reliever Doug Henry said. ``I'm not saying we're bad or
anything like that. But when you take away a Randy Johnson or a
Moises Alou, it's almost impossible to replace those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is the depth. We had good players to fill
those gaps, but because of that, our depth is nowhere near where it
was. That just means that guys, myself included, are going to have
step up. Because of what we did last year, there are going to be
more expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker realizes those expectations might exist from the
outside, but when he gathered his team together at the beginning of
the spring, he reminded them that the competition was this year's
schedule, not last year's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year is not the standard as far as I'm concerned,''
Dierker said. ``That was a special season. But our goal isn't to
win 100 games. It's to get to the playoffs one way or another. A
lot of things have to go right in order to have the kind of season
we had.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not typical to avoid injuries the way we did and to hit,
pitch and field like that. We're probably not as good as we were
last year, but we're pretty close. I believe teams that are
destined to win championships get better as the season goes on, and
that's what we're hoping to do.''
</P>
<P>
   If they can do that, how they looked at the end of spring
training will hardly matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
