<HEADLINE>
FOUNDER OF ZAMBIA DECLARED STATELESS IN HIGH COURT RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Kenneth D. Kaunda, the father of
modern Zambia and the country's president for 27 years, was
declared a stateless person by the country's High Court Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on a case brought by high-ranking members of the present
governing party, the court ruled that Kaunda is not a Zambian
citizen under the Constitution because his parents were from the
former British Nyasaland, now called Malawi.
</P>
<P>
   Kaunda renounced his Malawian citizenship years ago, when he was
president, so he is now effectively stateless.
</P>
<P>
   Under Zambian law, that renders him liable to arrest and the
seizure of his passport while he seeks a country that will offer
him refuge. Malawi has already refused him entry, according to a
legal expert in the Zambian capital, Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
   Kaunda has been feuding for years with the current president,
Frederick J.T. Chiluba, who replaced him after elections in 1991.
Kaunda has criticized Chiluba's government as inept and corrupt and
has announced plans to run for the presidency next year. Chiluba
has repeatedly had Kaunda and top members of his party arrested,
usually on treason charges that were later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, each man's party started trying to prove the
other was not a citizen. Questions about Chiluba's paternity and
the possibility that he had assumed the identity of a schoolmate
were raised.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, a court declared him a Zambian citizen
because he had lived in the country for 10 years, and Kaunda's
party is demanding to know why the same ruling was not extended to
him, Kaunda's son, Wezi, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Kaunda said the ruling was ``all part and parcel''
of the ruling party's campaign to get rid of his father. ``We're
going to fight it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
