<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AID-NYT &LR;      03-31 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN NATIONS PLEDGE MONEY AND SUPPORT FOR ALBANIAN REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-VUKOVAR,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-WARCRIMES, KOSOVO-SOLANA, KOSOVO-HACKERS, KOSOVO-CLINTON,
KOSOVO-ARMS, KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-SERBS-NY, KOSOVO-UPDATE,
KOSOVO-VATICAN) 
(nk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ France announced Wednesday that it would send 10
airplanes to the borders of Kosovo to protect refugee convoys from
Serbian forces, and Italy plans to send police officers to Albania
to bring order to refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   The French aerial cover could protect refugees from attacks like
the one described Wednesday by a NATO officer in Brussels, who said
refugees were fired on by Serbian artillery and tanks in the
Paragusa Valley, a stronghold of the separatist Kosovo Liberation
Army. According to the separatist guerrillas, 50,000 Albanians in
the valley are under attack by Serbian and Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight 40,000 new refugees were forced across Kosovo's
borders into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro, according to the
U.N. High Commission for Refugees, bringing the total of people
displaced in the last 10 days to 140,000. Insisting they not be
quoted by name, officials in the Clinton administration and relief
organizations now fear that the total could reach one million
before the air war is over. Before the Serbian push against the
Kosovar Albanians, they accounted for about 1.8 million of the
province's population of 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The administration Wednesday pledged $50 million to aid the
refugees, including $25 million from the Defense Department to
provide a mobile air traffic control operation, to repair or build
roads, airstrips and ports and to supply food and tents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Defense Department stands ready to provide whatever
assistance we can,'' said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon, who
said that the refugees ``are fleeing a murder machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the NATO countries also offered millions of dollars in
aid Wednesday for food, shelter and medical supplies and
governments sent assessment teams to Macedonia and Albania. Germany
and Britain began an airlift to the region Wednesday, with four
German military planes carrying medical supplies and a British
military transport plane filled with blankets and tents arriving in
Skopje, Macedonia, and Tirana, Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up makeshift camps for huge numbers of refugees along
the Kosovo border raises serious political and military questions
as well as humanitarian problems.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro (a republic in the Yugoslav
federation with Serbia) are politically and economically fragile
and ill equipped to care for these newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Already Albania has accused Yugoslavia of shelling across its
borders, which could force the refugees further inland. Kosovar
Albanian leaders hope to keep the refugees grouped near the border
so they can return to their homes once the war is over, a goal of
the Europeans as well. Moreover, if the shells hit Italian police
officers, that could spark demands for retaliation by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian effort was outlined by Alessandro Di Franco,
counselor for press information at the Italian Embassy. ``We are
preparing a major massive humanitarian effort,'' he said. ``The
Albanian government has asked us for tents, food, shelters and for
our police forces to bring order to the camps.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcements from Italy and France, and pledges of
$40 million of aid from Germany, were measures of the fear in all
of Europe that the refugee crisis is becoming a nightmare, and that
a failure to keep open the possibility of the return of the
refugees to Kosovo could force Europe to absorb them as new
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Although the relief organizations, along with the United States
and other NATO nations, had put aside food stocks several weeks
ago, they were not prepared for this vast flight, according to
administration officials, foreign diplomats and aid officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already reached our worst case scenario projection of
150,000,'' said Karen Abuzayd, Washington director for the U.N.
High Commission for Refugees. ``Our projections now are for over
half a million refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Di Franco described the Italian effort in detail. The program,
valued at $10 million, was approved Wednesday by the Italian
Cabinet. After consultations with the United States, Italy agreed
to provide security for the refugee camps immediately, using the 80
Italian officers already aiding the Albanian government; this group
is to be supplemented by a larger contingent from Italy, though the
size was not announced. At Durres, an Albanian port city, the
Italians will build a camp for 25,000 refugees and use the Italian
soldiers and sailors already stationed in Albania for security.
</P>
<P>
   If Albania asks for troop support in the camps along the Kosovo
border, Italy is prepared to ask NATO for approval, according to Di
Franco.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Serbs have apparently speeded up their
forced expulsion of Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just exploded today, and refugees have just been pouring
over the borders,'' Ms. Abuzayd said. ``The Serbs are running
trains from Pristina carrying 3,000 Albanians on a 12-car train.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate we had food in our warehouses in anticipation
of a refugee crisis,'' she said. ``Now it is a question of
organizing the offers and getting the supplies quickly where they
are needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other help offered Wednesday, France and Britain each
pledged $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   All of the relief agencies have been thrown out of Kosovo and
most have left Belgrade, where they had stored three-fourths of
their supplies. No international agencies remain to provide help or
protection to the 260,000 Albanians displaced from their homes
during the war, according to the U.N. agency. The buildings of most
foreign agencies in Kosovo were looted and some were burned down by
the Serbs as soon as the relief workers fled, Ms. Abuzayd said.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States and the NATO allies have pledged that
the refugees can return to Kosovo when the shooting stops, some
critics of the administration wonder if that will be possible
without sending in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the long term, we have to decide whether we really are
going to bring them back to Kosovo,'' said Morton Abramowitz, the
former ambassador to Turkey who oversaw the 1991 return of Kurdish
refugees to northern Iraq under the protection of the American
military. ``And that's not going to happen unless we're prepared to
put in force. If we haven't committed troops so far, I don't think
it will be possible when it's time to bring the refugees home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
