u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YAHOO-BROADCAST-COM-5     03-31 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-BROADCAST-COM-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YAHOO SET TO BUY BROADCAST.COM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yahoo is expected to announce Thursday that it has agreed to buy
Broadcast.com in a stock swap valued at $5.6 billion, executives
close to the talks said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The boards of both companies met Wednesday and approved the
deal, which had been rumored for some time, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com shareholders are expected to receive 0.77 share of
Yahoo for each of their shares, which values the deal at about $130
a share, analysts said. On Wednesday, shares of Broadcast.com rose
$4.8125, to $118.1875. In after-hours trading, the company's shares
rose an additional $6.8125, to $125.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for both companies did not return calls for
comment Wednesday. But an analysts' meeting to discuss the
acquisition is scheduled for Thursday morning. Mark Cuban, the
chairman and president of Broadcast.com, and Todd R. Wagner, the
chief executive, are expected to remain at the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Broadcast.com, which sends audio and video over the
Internet, jumped by $31 two weeks ago after Business Week reported
that it was in talks with Yahoo. Shares of Yahoo fell $3.9375
Wednesday, to $168.375.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is another move by Yahoo to take advantage of its $34
billion stock market value by using its shares to pay for
acquisitions. In January, Yahoo agreed to exchange stock, now worth
$3.7 billion, for Geocities, a service on which three million
people publish Internet home pages.
</P>
<P>
   While $5.6 billion is an astounding price for a company as small
as Broadcast.com, analysts said that Yahoo was almost compelled to
make such expensive purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo won't be able to sustain its extraordinary valuation
unless they make acquisitions like Geocities and Broadcast.com that
help them capture more of their users' time,'' said Keith Benjamin,
an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens. ``If they don't buy,
their market value will lose $5 billion over time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com runs a vast site with all sorts of audio and video
programming that can be seen or heard over the Internet. But with
the current level of technology, the sound has much more static
than a radio station and the pictures are small and flicker like a
dim candle.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the company's revenue come from corporations,
which hire it to operate conference calls and investor meetings
over the Internet. The remainder of its revenue, and the vast bulk
of its traffic, comes from advertising and product sales on
programs that range from foreign news broadcasts to high school
sports. The company lost $16.4 million last year on sales of $22.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's acquisitions have been meant to broaden its audience so
that it could maintain its position as the second most popular
collection of services in cyberspace after America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, once simply a directory of other Web sites, has
refashioned itself as a broad portal, or gateway, to a wide range
of services from stock quotes to electronic mail and now to
television and radio programming.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com was visited by 8.9 million Internet users in
February, according to Media Metrix, an audience measurement firm.
Yahoo and Geocities reached 36.9 million users. But nearly all of
the Broadcast.com users already visit Yahoo's sites, so the
combination only gives Yahoo one million new users, not enough to
overtake America Online, which recently bought Netscape
Communications Corp.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to sheer reach, the deal has the potential to help
Yahoo move from the current state of the Internet _ which mainly
involves sending static pages of information over relatively slow
modems _ to the expected world of broadband services, in which
audio and video programming can be delivered over cable television
systems or much faster modems that use telephone wires.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the shift to broadband services, Excite, one
of Yahoo's chief rivals, agreed to be bought by the At Home Corp.,
the leading provider of broadband programming through cable
systems. Similarly Lycos, another Internet portal, is combining
with the Home Shopping network and other assets owned by USA
Networks in a complex deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense for the most heavily trafficked site on the Web
to acquire the largest provider of streaming audio and video on the
Web'' said Paul Noglows, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. ``With
the advent of broadband, Internet sites will come to closely
resemble broadcast networks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All of this merger activity is being fueled by the unprecedented
rise in Internet stock prices. Investors are bidding up the stocks
of companies _ no matter how young, unprofitable or implausible _
to prices that defy even the most optimistic valuations.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on its second day of trading yesterday after its
initial offering, Priceline.com, an Internet service that sells
discount airline tickets, rose in value to $11.7 billion, more than
any airline in the world.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, Ziff Davis sold 14 percent of its online
subsidiary ZDNet. By the end of the day, ZDNet's stock market value
was $2.6 billion, more than the $2.2 billion value of the parent.
The only justification for this would be that Ziff Davis' print
publications _ including PC Magazine, one of the most profitable
publications in the world _ in fact have a negative value.
</P>
<P>
   With values like these, Internet companies simply cannot be
bought by established companies where stocks are valued on profits,
not promise.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Broadcast.com is out of reach for such logical buyers as
CBS or Disney. But it is an easy bite for Yahoo, which can simply
exchange its highly valued stock for that of Broadcast.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
