<SLUG> BC-HIGH-LIFE-COST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEX CHARTS RISING COST OF LUXURY ITEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- People with money to burn are spending more of
their cash on the finer things in life, according to the 15th
annual Moet &AMP; Chandon Luxury Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The price of a dozen items deemed essential for ``the ideal
lifestyle in New York'' -- items like a round-trip ticket from New
York to Paris on a Concorde jet, Petrossian Russian beluga caviar
and Dom Perignon champagne -- rose by 3.9 percent last year,
according to a survey.
</P>
<P>
   That means prices for the finer things rose faster than the
government's Consumer Price Index, which charts the cost of goods
that average folks buy. The CPI increased 1.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is the fourth or fifth year of continued,
very strong demand for luxury goods,'' said Stuart Foster, senior
brand manager in charge of U.S. marketing for French champagne
maker Moet &AMP; Chandon. ``If luxury goods can take these kind of
price increases and still (grow), it's very evident that the demand
is very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of an Air France Concorde trip to Paris saw the
sharpest increase -- 12.4 percent from $9,704 in 1997 to $10,912
last year.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end, the cost of a Jaeger-LeCoultre Men's
Reverso Duo 18-carat pink gold watch with bracelet fell 1 percent,
or $990, to $19,800, according to the index.
</P>
<P>
   Though the index is keyed to a New York lifestyle, the same
trend holds true for Beverly Hills and other upscale parts of the
country, Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Giss, a partner with the trade retail services group at
the accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP in Los Angeles, said
upscale retailers are doing better than mainline retailers in the
area because they're perceived as offering a better quality
product, and thus a good value.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, the discounters are also doing well because they
offer cheaper products.
</P>
<P>
   ``So people are defining value in terms of price and in terms of
quality,'' Giss said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
