<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE'S CANDIDATE LIST GROWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Former Pepperdine teammates Jim Harrick Jr. and
Marty Wilson both said Wednesday they have applied for the vacant
men's head basketball position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a family feud,'' Wilson quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, an assistant at UC Santa Barbara, played at Pepperdine
from 1984-89. Harrick, an assistant at Rhode Island under his
father, played from 1983-87. The two former Waves join
well-respected Pepperdine assistant Randy Bennett and UCLA
assistants Michael Holton and Jim Saia as confirmed applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there are eight or nine names in the hat and I hope
to be one of the four or five (to interview),'' Harrick said from
his office. ``I'm very familiar with the Pepperdine infrastructure
and its surrounding area.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick's father, Jim, was named the head coach at Georgia on
Wednesday, but that university's nepotism rules make it impossible
for Harrick to bring his son along.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Harrick, 34, has never been a head coach. In
addition to Rhode Island, he has been an assistant at San Diego
State, Valparaiso and Marshall. While at San Diego State, Harrick
was an assistant under Tony Fuller, a former head coach at
Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've kept it in the Jim Harrick family tree for so long,''
Harrick said, referring to the fact that former Harrick Sr.
assistants Tom Asbury and Lorenzo Romar have been head coaches in
Malibu. ``That tree has been pretty good to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who became the interim head coach at Pepperdine midway
through the 1995-96 season when Fuller resigned, also was an
assistant at the University of San Diego for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very interested,'' said Wilson, 32. ``I know quite a few
people (at Pepperdine).''
</P>
<P>
   UC Santa Barbara head coach Bob Williams, meanwhile, said he
isn't interested in leaving UCSB.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy (here),'' said Williams, who guided the Gauchos
to a 15-13 record last season, including 12-4 in the Big West,
after winning the Division II national championship at UC Davis.
``I love the young players and I love the recruits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2144EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
