</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WARCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITIA LEADER ARKAN IS INDICTED IN WAR CRIMES, AND YUGOSLAVS ARE
WARNED
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-VUKOVAR,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-SOLANA, KOSOVO-HACKERS, KOSOVO-AID, KOSOVO-CLINTON,
KOSOVO-ARMS, KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-SERBS-NY, KOSOVO-UPDATE,
KOSOVO-VATICAN) 
(nk) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The international war crimes tribunal disclosed
Wednesday that it had warned Yugoslav officials they would be held
accountable for violence against civilians in Kosovo and announced
that it had indicted the notorious Serbian militia leader known as
Arkan.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan, whose real name is Zeljko Raznjatovic, was secretly
indicted on Sept. 30, 1997, in connection with war crimes during
the fighting after the breakup of Yugoslavia. Officials at the
tribunal in the Hague said they had decided to publicize it now
because of reports that he and his men were terrorizing civilians
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A warrant for his arrest was sent to the Yugoslav government
Wednesday, but it is expected that it will be ignored because the
government does not accept the authority of the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   The government also rejected the letters sent to Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic and 12 senior officials, warning them
that they would be held accountable for their actions in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Louise Arbour, the tribunal's chief prosecutor, said the
letter had been faxed to the Yugoslav government on March 26, but
on Monday, the Yugoslav Embassy in the Hague refused to accept the
originals of the letters. Therefore, Arbour said she was forced to
publicize the letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my intention to investigate all serious violations of
international humanitarian law that merit prosecution in the
international forum, particularly those involving attacks on the
civilian population,'' Arbour wrote. Her letter also criticized the
Yugoslav government for refusing tribunal investigators access to
Kosovo. The investigators have been amassing evidence of atrocities
against civilians in Kosovo since last summer, but the team, which
has limited means, depends in part on intelligence provided by
Western governments.
</P>
<P>
   Tribunal officials who are usually discreet in public, have
expressed frustration in private that they are not getting enough
information.
</P>
<P>
   Arbour showed some of that frustration Wednesday, as she told
reporters: ``In recent days, the U.S., the U.K. and NATO have
indicated publicly that they have evidence of the commission of
crimes within our jurisdiction, including information about the
perpetrators, and that they will share this information with my
office. I expect to be provided with this information on a
continuous basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment of Arkan did not come altogether as a surprise.
He was known to be under investigation, but tribunal officials
hoped to make it easier to arrest him by keeping it secret. The
prosecutor's office Wednesday refused to reveal the charges against
Arkan or publish the indictment. ``Publishing the indictment and
the charges could compromise the witnesses,'' a tribunal official
said. ``A man like him, with his capacity for violence, might
eliminate witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The war record of Arkan is well-documented. A man wanted in
connection with bank robberies and other crimes in six European
countries before the war, he created a paramilitary group, known as
the Tigers, in late 1991. His armed gang worked closely with
Serbian secret police and military, at first in Croatia and later
in Bosnia. The group has been accused of some of the most vicious
and rapid ``ethnic cleansing'' of 1992 as they went into towns and
villages.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses have said the Tigers went on rampages of killing,
looting and raping until they had achieved what they wanted,
forcing non-Serbs to flee their homes. One of the most bloody
operations Arkan was accused of being involved in was in Bijeljina
in eastern Bosnia, where non-Serbs were violently forced out in
1992. It also has been alleged that Arkan and his Tigers killed
hundreds of Muslim men they had locked up in a sports center in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CNN on Wednesday, Arkan denied that he was
a war criminal and rejected accusations that he had killed innocent
people. He said the indictment was unsealed ``because of the
political situation.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, American and British officials have said that
Arkan had been seen in Kosovo and that he and paramilitary
followers were involved in the Serbian brutality against ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan said in the interview that his men were not involved in
Kosovo but that he would be willing to defend his country against
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan has appeared on television in Belgrade to deny that he had
recruited volunteers to act in Kosovo. But in an interview with
Reuters Television he warned of ``a new Vietnam in the heart of
Europe'' if NATO brought ground troops into its conflict with
Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
