<HEADER>
A1616 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     03-31 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR THE ENCORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What can baseball do for an encore?
</P>
<P>
   It has endured a nefarious World Series fix, unpopular strikes,
sanctioned bigotry, world wars, multi-million dollar free agents,
and innately myopic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an imperative part of the American culture before
football had a forward pass and basketball had even made it out of
the YMCAs.
</P>
<P>
   It has given us legendary names that have become a standard part
of the nation's vernacular like Ruth and Gehrig and Cobb and
DiMaggio and Robinson and Mantle and Mays and Koufax and Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, baseball, that quintessential American pastime, that gentle,
slow-moving endeavor that preoccupies our sporting thoughts from
March through October, that graceful skit that can so abruptly
erupt into a riveting drama that can leave you thrilled with
ecstasy or steeped in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   It is now set to commence its final season of the 20th century,
and one can't help but idly wonder what the sport can do for an
encore after its storied act last year when it ruled the summer
with unprecedented heroics dispensed by its array of noble
performers.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, considering what unfolded throughout that epic summer of
1998 when Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa were obliterating Babe Ruth
and Roger Maris, when the New York Yankees wound up the year with
125 victories, when the sport reached popularity levels and
established attendance records unrivaled in its history, you wonder
if our sacred national pastime is destined for a slightly less
glamorous odyssey on its way to the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   It is the intrinsic allure of baseball that one never knows for
sure what will happen on the ball fields even off them, for that
matter and the fickleness and unpredictability of the game itself
are what make it so difficult to handicap.
</P>
<P>
   If one, say, were to predict a year ago at this time that Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa would combine for 136 home runs and keep an
entire country transfixed throughout the season by their astounding
batting accomplishments, the person would have come under the same
severe ridicule had he been so outlandishly brash as to predict
that the Dodgers soon would be getting rid of their great hitting
catcher, Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Much to the shock of the citizenry that resides in Southern
California, the Dodgers did just that in the first major move
consummated by Rupert Murdoch's new Fox management team.
</P>
<P>
   The decision still inspires a sour taste among most Dodger
patrons the notoriously moody and brittle Gary Sheffield is all the
team now has to show for Piazza's departure but the Dodgers did in
the off-season take a far more aggressive posture than it had under
its previous caretaker, Peter O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike O'Malley, a timid soul who kept his general manager, Fred
Claire, under a tight financial leash, Murdoch gave his general
manager, Kevin Malone, a blank check to strengthen the team.
</P>
<P>
   Malone did just that when he handed that seven-year, $105
million contract over to one of baseball's most renowned pitchers,
Kevin Brown, in a stunning transaction that was roundly condemned
around baseball especially by the small-market teams as a classic
example of the inequity that now afflicts the game.
</P>
<P>
   What else is new?
</P>
<P>
   Throughout its existence this century, baseball, for the most
part, has been dominated by its wealthiest franchises, going back
to when the New York Yankees began their lengthy reign by being
able to purchase Babe Ruth from a financially-struggling Boston Red
Sox team.
</P>
<P>
   You think the Atlanta Braves have been perennial World Series
contenders throughout the 1990s they've appeared in the Fall
Classic four times because of the stellar genius of their manager,
Bobby Cox, who's actually a shameless bumbler, or the deep pockets
of their billionaire owner, Ted Turner?
</P>
<P>
   It's now quite apparent that Murdoch, a long-time bitter rival
of Turner on the international cable television scene, is obsessed
with overtaking Turner's Braves in the National League, giving
Kevin Malone the freedom to wheel and deal in high stakes signings
that the ousted Claire never was given by O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt with the presence of Brown and a new manager
with a proven record of success, Davey Johnson, that the Dodgers
will be a more formidable outfit.
</P>
<P>
   But whether they will be making their first World Series
appearance since 1988, as Malone so loudly predicts, is still quite
doubtful in light of the question marks surrounding the people who
will be at third base, shortstop and behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But who knows what will happen? After all, it's baseball, and Mo
Vaughn, scandalously overweight from an off-season of a lot of
important chowing down after the Anaheim Angels gifted him with
more than $80 million, might suddenly break out in a rash of home
runs after a spring in which his bat has remained ominously silent.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels still do not have enough quality pitchers to make the
Yankees, or even Cleveland Indians, wince, but they do have an
exceptional manager in Terry Collins and they do have just enough
hitters to compete seriously again with another stout-hitting,
erratic-pitching club, the Texas Rangers, for the A.L. West
Division title.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure baseball will have its usual gaggle of
surprises, and one of the biggest could be that the young St. Louis
Cardinal phenomenon, J.D. Drew, might turn out to be a better
hitter I didn't say slugger than Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt McGwire will threaten his home run record of 70 I'm not
sure anyone ever will and I doubt Sosa will approach the 66 he
deposited last season, or realize his dream of leading the Chicago
Cubs into the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   I also doubt the Yankees will again win 114 regular season
games, and I know the San Diego Padres, stripped of most of the
personnel that was vital to their National League pennant-winning
success last season, won't appear again in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling here is that, come next October, form, which seldom
prevails in baseball, will this time and a sequel to the 1996 World
Series between the Yankees and Braves will be staged.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Yankees begin the season with their manager, Joe
Torre, on the sidelines recovering from prostrate surgery and their
stellar left-handed pitcher, Andy Pettitte, on the disabled list,
but they have added the most overwhelming pitcher in baseball,
Roger Clemens, to a talented mix that includes Derek Jeter, Paul
O'Neill, Bernie Williams, David Cone, Chili Davis, Orlando
Hernandez, Tino Martinez, Mariano Rivera, Scott Brosius, Chuck
Knoblauch and many others.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Braves begin the season without Andres Galarraga, who
was diagnosed with cancer in February, but they have added an
exceptional second baseball, Bret Boone, and hard-hitting outfield,
Brian Jordan, to go with Chipper Jones, Javier Lopez, Andruw Jones
and Ryan Klesko. And no one not even the Yankees has a trio of
starting pitchers better than Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and John
Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the Braves still have Bobby Cox commanding their troops,
but the team still seems to have too many weapons for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But who knows?
</P>
<P>
   The only certainties in baseball are the uncertainties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
