u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-NY-NYT &LR;      03-31 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-NY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMONSTRATORS RALLY TO PROTEST U.S. POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-MISSING, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-VUKOVAR, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES, KOSOVO-SOLANA, KOSOVO-HACKERS,
KOSOVO-AID, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ARMS, KOSOVO-VATICAN) 
(js) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A band of demonstrators in New York on Wednesday
protested the bombing of Yugoslavia by NATO and U.S. forces, some
wrapping themselves in Serbian flags, some pinning a black target
to their chests as a symbol of solidarity with the people of
Belgrade, nearly all questioning the version of events reported in
the American news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is Serbia,'' they chanted, as they marched from Grand
Central Terminal to the office of The New York Times on 43rd Street
between Seventh and Eighth Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Some held signs that described NATO as the ``New Albanian
Terroristic Organization.'' Others urged the United States to
devote its resources to schools, not bombs. Teen-age boys and
girls, in red and white Serbian soccer jerseys, pumped their fists
and chanted, ``Serbia!'' as though cheering for a favorite team.
One woman held up a sign that read, ``Kosovo Albanians Seek
Independence in Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   If their anger was directed at NATO and U.S. officials, it was
also vented against The New York Times, which has published
editorials in support of the NATO offensive against the forces of
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Times has become an organ for the bombing,'' said Brian
Becker, co-director of the International Action Center, which
organized the demonstration. ``The editorial position has been
pro-war, and the news coverage has been unbalanced, in keeping with
those who support the KLA and the NATO bombings.''
</P>
<P>
   The KLA is the Kosovo Liberation Army, a separatist Albanian
guerrilla group in Kosovo, the southern province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking what they called the American news media
``anti-Serbian rhetoric,'' the protesters argued that atrocities
against Serbs had received scant attention over the years. Becker
described the guerrillas as a mercenary group financed by
foreigners, akin to the contras in Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   The police estimated the numbers of protesters at 1,000. The
organizers said there was five times that figure.
</P>
<P>
   Among the demonstrators were Serbian immigrants like Milica
Savic, 27, of Queens, who questioned news reports that Serbian
forces had burned the houses of Kosovo Albanians after having
forced them out in droves. ``That is not true,'' she insisted.
``Who burned those homes? Did you see some Serbians burn those
homes?''
</P>
<P>
   Behind her stood a retired Greek immigrant from Astoria, a black
wool military cap on his head and a sea-blue Greek flag in his
hands. He is not much of a protester, he said, but he demonstrated
Wednesday because he recalled his countrymen's shared history with
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe what they believe,'' said the man, Emilios Dimitris,
65. ``We have fought the Ottomans together. We have fought the
Nazis together. How do I feel if the Turks take part of my country,
and the Americans support them?''
</P>
<P>
   Behind him stood a young woman with a fashion magazine in her
hand. ``My parents are in Belgrade,'' said the woman, Liliana
Novakovic, 28, suddenly in tears. ``They are very scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the bombings began, Ms. Novakovic said, she and many peers
in Belgrade _ college educated, English speaking and even
identifying with America _ had little respect for Milosevic, whom
she called despotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Clinton had left us alone, they would have overthrown
Milosevic,'' said Ms. Novakovic, who left Belgrade eight years ago
for Jersey City. ``This sort of united them. It's sort of like
fighting with your parents. If there is a great danger, you kind of
unite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
