<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FUNDRAISING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RAISES $6 MILLION PLUS IN LESS THAN A MONTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In less than 30 days and without holding a
single organized fund-raiser, Gov. George W. Bush has pulled in
more than $6 million for his likely presidential campaign,
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The eye-popping figure puts Bush well ahead of other GOP
hopefuls and brings him in line with the $7 million haul that
Democratic Vice President Al Gore is reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has been outpacing Republican rivals and even Gore in
national polls, said he is honored by the contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make sure that behind the polls and the phone
calls, that there was some substance,'' Bush said. ``I think this
is the first indication that there is true support.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticized recently for vague statements on issues ranging from
abortion to Kosovo, Bush said his financial support indicates that
people are comfortable with his stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a lot of people would write a check like that
unless they knew where my heart is, what my intentions are,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The money has been rolling in even though Bush has not appeared
at any fund-raisers or, as he put it, gone ``dialing for dollars.''
He did say he made a few phone calls to thank supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Although raising more than $200,000 a day is impressive, it is
not clear whether Bush can reach the goal of forgoing federal
matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   That decision, to be made in the fall, would cost the campaign
about $15 million in federal funding but it would allow Bush to
ignore state-by-state spending limits and thus direct his resources
where they are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say Bush would have to raise about $50 million to give
up federal campaign funding. In 1996, President Clinton raised
about $30 million for his primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first-quarter money is the easy money,'' said University
of Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato. ``Am I impressed by
the $6 million? Sure. Show me the second quarter and I'll be more
impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter for Bush included 27 days. He formed his
exploratory committee March 4, and the time period for the
financial disclosure report ended Wednesday. The final total, which
aides say could rise, will be reported to the Federal Elections
Commission on April 15.
</P>
<P>
   But candidates typically let the news out before the deadline,
and Wednesday was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have raised at least $7 million in the first quarter,'' a
Gore 2000 spokesman said. The aide said that the funds have come
from more than 40,000 donors since Feb. 1, and that 77 percent of
the contributions have been from supporters who gave $200 or less.
Gore is planning a series of major fund-raisers this month.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican field, ex-Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander is
expected to report between $700,000 and $800,000, and former Vice
President Dan Quayle will report raising about $2 million, aides
said. Among other GOP hopefuls, Arizona Sen. John McCain, Ohio Rep.
John Kasich and conservative activist Gary Bauer are reporting
about $1 million each in donations.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, Bush's closest GOP competitor, declined to join
the numbers game immediately. ``We are not going to officially
release any figures today,'' a spokeswoman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter reports cover the period through June, and
Bush said he would be ``very pleased'' if he could raise the same
amount as this quarter, for a total of $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush announced his fund-raising figures on the same day he held
a ``Conference on Youth,'' which focused on strategies to combat
drug, alcohol and tobacco use, teen-age pregnancy and sexually
transmitted disease.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said abstinence is the best strategy to combat the last
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children must know that abstinence isn't just saying no to
sex, abstinence is saying yes to a happier and healthier life,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those speaking at the conference was former drug czar
William Bennett, author of the bestseller ``The Book of Virtues,''
who said Bush has ``caught the imagination of the American people
to an astounding degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before reporters with Bush later, Bennett addressed
the issue of Bush's ``young and irresponsible'' early years by
saying that mistakes people make when they are young do not taint
them in voters' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish say, you know, the merry-hearted boys make the best
of all men,'' Bennett said. ``Young and male, some of us in
college, some of us in high school, did things we weren't
particularly proud about later.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people understand fallibility,'' he added. ``They
understand weakness. They understand youth.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
