<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS MAY SEEK HIGHER DRAFT-PICK STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots made offers to the Oakland
Raiders and Chicago Bears a year ago to move up in the draft and
take either Charles Woodson or Curtis Enis. But when the price got
too steep the Patriots backed off and kept their two No. 1 picks.
</P>
<P>
   Sources indicate that the Patriots, who again have two No. 1
picks (20 and 28), will again make a bid to move up for a chance to
draft either Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams of Texas or
Miami's Edgerrin James, the top-rated running backs in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Patriots settled for Robert Edwards, the
third-rated back in the draft, but he wound up being the
second-best rookie back in the league (behind Jacksonville's Fred
Taylor).
</P>
<P>
   Enis was a holdout, then was injured, and his full potential was
never fully realized.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots certainly like Mississippi State running back James
Johnson and Louisiana State's Kevin Faulk, but Patriots personnel
realize that Williams would give their running game instant
credibility, even if it means expending so many draft picks (they
have five in the first three rounds) that they can't draft the
offensive lineman _ or two _ they were seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reports that Williams may be sliding in the draft or
that his hands are too small and will be fumble-prone, he is the
prize. New Orleans Saints coach Mike Ditka has recently backed off
of a report that he had offered his entire draft for Williams, but
if quarterbacks are drafted by the first three teams, Indianapolis
would be next in line.
</P>
<P>
   While the Colts have an All-Pro in Marshall Faulk, there have
been reports they would be willing to deal him to take Williams.
Faulk wants to renegotiate his contract to be in line with Curtis
Martin, but Williams would likely cost more.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing concern that Williams's agents, the Master P
group, might be asking for the moon. That may be the only reason
Williams would drop in the draft. The Colts, too, have more
pressing needs, mainly on defense.
</P>
<P>
   It appears the Patriots wouldn't have enough to move up to get
Williams, but they could be a player.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston College's Damien Woody, the top-rated center in the
draft, was a visitor at Foxboro Stadium Wednesday. He was given a
physical at Massachusetts General Hospital and then visited with
the Patriots' brass. Woody seems to be moving up the first-round
charts, and there's no guarantee he'll be around when the Patriots
pick. If he is, he may be the choice . . . Scott Zolak hasn't
signed with the Miami Dolphins, but he was in Boca Raton, Fla.,
looking for houses Wednesday. Zolak's agent, Ralph Cindrich, said
he has not spoken recently with the Dolphins . . . Vincent Brisby
will join the team's workout program next week. Troy Brown remains
in West Virginia working on his own. Brown, a loyal participant in
the past, hasn't been pleased with his contract negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1624 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TOBACCO-BOS &LR;      03-31 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TOBACCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS STRONGLY BACK ANTISMOKING USE FOR TOBACCO FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- By a more than two to one margin, Massachusetts voters
want at least 25 percent of the $7.6 billion in its tobacco
settlement funds to go toward expanding the state's antismoking
campaign _ a policy Governor Paul Cellucci has rejected.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide poll taken for the American Cancer Society reveals
that 66 percent support a plan for using 25 percent of the funds
for tobacco control, while 30 percent agree with Cellucci's plan to
apply the funds to nonsmoking public health projects.
</P>
<P>
   A cancer society official said Wednesday the poll, taken of 401
voters in early March, proves Cellucci is going against a public
sentiment that strongly supports the state's public health efforts
to curb smoking and wants the programs expanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters have a keen understanding of the fact that one of the
state's primary reasons for suing the tobacco industry in the first
place was to reduce smoking among kids,'' said Dr. David Rosenthal,
past president of the American Cancer Society. The poll was taken
by Kiley &AMP; Associates of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer society, which led the coalition that engineered a
voterapproved cigarette tax hike in 1992 to create the state's
tobacco control program, has called for at least 25 percent of the
national settlement money to be used to expand the project.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci in January proposed creating a special health-care
trust fund that would provide money for children, senior citizens,
and AIDS victims, but offered no money for tobacco control.
</P>
<P>
   With former Attorney General Scott Harshbarger taking the lead,
the attorneys general reached a $206 billion national settlement
with the tobacco industry in November. The agreement, which
distributes the funds over 25 years, specifically calls for using
some of the funds for tobacco control.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's announcement in January sparked a sharp reaction from
antismoking activists, who have lauded the Massachusetts Department
of Public Health's $30 million a year tobacco control efforts as a
national model. Another $30 million or so is used by the Department
of Education for antismoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's proposal to spend $500,000 of the settlement money to
evaluate the tobacco control program particularly added to their
concerns. The activists say millions of dollars have been spent to
evaluate the program, and they say those studies have found it
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other state wants to replicate the success of our
tobacco control program,'' said Lori Fresina, director of
government affairs for the American Cancer Society. ``It has become
one of our most popular domestic exports in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, the governor brushed aside the poll results,
saying his plan responds to the majority of voters' sentiment
because the national settlement also provides a mechanism for
additional funding for antismoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand there's about $28 billion dollars that is part of
the national settlement that is for antitobacco efforts and that
that money will also come back to the states,'' Cellucci said
Wednesday when asked about the poll. ``I think that will provide a
significant increase in our tobacco control efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor also said that if those funds are not available, he
will consider revising his plan to add settlement money to the
tobacco control program.
</P>
<P>
   But tobacco control lawyers who have analyzed the national
settlement said Wednesday that Cellucci's decision to use none of
the money for antismoking projects flies in the face of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The document makes it abundantly clear that the money is to do
two things _ to improve public health and to implement
tobacco-related public health measures,'' said Graham Kelder, an
attorney with Northeastern University School of Law's Tobacco
Control Resources Center. ``The AGs clearly intended that part of
the money is to go to tobacco control.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelder said the agreement does create a foundation to which the
industry would contribute $25 million a year for 10 years. The
foundation would provide funding to the 50 states for antismoking
advertising and educational programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
