<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-SEANEZ01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stability's a relief for Seanez
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It has been a surreal spring training for Braves
reliever Rudy Seanez.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the second time in a 14-year career, including
stops with eight organizations, that Seanez can feel secure and
work on something other than proving himself.
</P>
<P>
   The only other time Seanez felt that way was in 1995, when he
started the season with the Dodgers. At every other stop, Seanez
started the season wondering where he would end up and if he would
play. Often, it has been the minors or disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   But he has found sweet security in the Braves bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a good feeling, especially with my wife and two
girls,'' said Seanez, who took some time off this winter after
playing winter ball six of the previous seven years. ``It makes it
so much easier on them.''
</P>
<P>
   After being called up from AAA Richmond on May 30, Seanez became
a fixture in the bullpen. He stayed healthy and proved to be a
valuable setup man.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez had a career-high 50 strikeouts in 36 innings pitched and
was 4-1 with a 2.75 ERA. He went on the disabled list in September
with a muscle tear in his forearm, but was able to return in time
for the postseason, where he pitched a scoreless inning in the
Division Series against Houston and appeared in four games in the
NLCS, allowing two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to remember things I was doing last year and
enjoying myself at the same time, not dwelling on things too much,
not getting too obsessive about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up five earned runs in one outing against the Indians
this spring, but has been dominant in all other appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The key for Seanez is staying off the disabled list, where he
has been six times in his career with arm, back and groin injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd call timeout and signal for the trainer,'' Seanez said.
``I'm sure managers were like, `What now? Let's see what happened
this time to this guy.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said he's learned not to play if he feels a groin twinge in
the bullpen, and he's learned how to take better care of himself.
He doesn't expect to throw the 100 mph fastball, the one that kept
teams interested despite all his health problems, but his fastball
was clocked at 98 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could be back in the major leagues if I could stay
healthy,'' Seanez said. ``That was pretty much it. Just knowing my
arm is still good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are the third team Seanez has signed with as a
six-year free agent. He's also been traded three times, the last of
which came as a player-to-be-named from the Mets to the Royals in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't make me feel too good,'' Seanez said. ``But it
seems like things turned out good. Some guys get here with a lot of
talent; other guys do the little things. Me? I guess I'm kind of in
between.''
</P>
<P>
   Seanez, 30, offers his support to the younger players in the
Braves clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let them know they're not the only ones who've been through
it,'' Seanez said. ``I understand completely how they feel. Usually
stuff works out for guys. It just does.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
