<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-HARRICK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glory turned to ignominy with UCLA
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His resume fairly runs the game's gamut. Head coaching
stops at Pepperdine, UCLA and Rhode Island? Been there and there
and there. Won a national championship, fired amid scandal 18
months later and resurrected after a year's exile? Done that and
that and that. And now Jim Harrick has come south, if not quite
full circle.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years after loading up the car in his native West
Virginia and driving cross-country to chase his basketball dreams
in California, Harrick has found a new home in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from the glory, and then ignominy, of UCLA to a
fresh start at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That which does not destroy you makes you stronger,'' Harrick
said. For all the success he's enjoyed _ 404 wins, 14 NCAA
Tournaments in 19 seasons, a near-miracle at Rhode Island and his
crowning glory, the 1995 NCAA title _ Georgia's new basketball
coach is also known for his controversial firing in November 1996.
It came 20 months after Harrick accomplished what none of John
Wooden's first five successors at UCLA could: He won the national
championship, with a stunning 89-78 upset of defending champ
Arkansas that was orchestrated largely by an Atlanta guard named
Cameron Dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Wooden era is over,'' Dollar declared then. ``The Harrick
era has just begun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harrick era ended abruptly, shockingly, two weeks before the
1996-97 season began. The coach admitted to lying to UCLA
officials, who were investigating a recruiting dinner, to protect
two Bruins _ Dollar and Charles O'Bannon _ who were at the dinner.
To read the school's internal report, and especially to hear UCLA
athletics director Peter Dalis, you'd have thought Harrick was the
lizard of Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   There were three recruits but five UCLA players at the dinner at
Monty's, a Westwood restaurant. According to NCAA rules, there can
be only as many players as recruits at such dinners, each player in
effect serving as one recruit's host. The school's internal report
said Harrick had lied to school officials eight times during their
investigation, that he'd falsified an expense report and that
Dollar and O'Bannon weren't entitled to a free meal.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick was ``shocked'' when, after eight consecutive 20-win
seasons and the '95 NCAA title, he was fired by Dalis and UCLA
chancellor Charles Young. He refused to resign and said the penalty
``far outweighed the crime, by mountains and miles.'' Harrick said
UCLA could have suspended him for a game or fined him or put him on
probation. Instead, he was gone and out of coaching for a year,
during which he was briefly hospitalized because of stress. UCLA
was placed on minor probation by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``I'm the better for it,'' Harrick said Wednesday. ``I've
grown from that. I'm a better coach for being there, a better
person, a better human being. As you look around the country, those
things happen at a lot of places. I hate to say it, but I guess
it's probably part of the business right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like UCLA. It's a great school, a great institution. Maybe
some of the people in it aren't so great, but the school is a very
fine place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While he had phenomenal success at UCLA, he also had some
difficult times,'' said Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley,
who hired Harrick. ``I did do due diligence on that. I did visit
with the NCAA. There were some mistakes made. There'd be some
question whether those mistakes were justifiable enough to take as
strong an action as was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've discussed (those mistakes) with coach Harrick. He knows
that compliance is A-No. 1 here and that we're going to go the
extra mile to make sure that we're operating within the rules and
regulations of the NCAA. After being assured that's what his
intentions are and that his experience, though hurtful, was a
growing and healing experience, I was convinced he is serious and
felt very good about recommending that Coach Harrick be our
basketball coach.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dooley knows this: ``We have the best qualified man for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
