<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-NEWCOACH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia hires proven winner
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley summarized
in one brief statement why he hired Jim Harrick as the Bulldogs'
new basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Been there, done that, wants to do it again,'' Dooley said
Wednesday. ``That's what I liked about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia hired the 60-year-old Harrick, who won a national
championship at UCLA in 1995 but was fired the next year for his
involvement in an illegal recruiting dinner, as its 19th head
coach, succeeding Ron Jirsa, who was fired March 11 after just two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said from the beginning our commitment was to hire a proven
head coach,'' Dooley said. ``I think it's obvious we far surpassed
our expectations in that regard. ... It's not often a school has a
chance to hire a coach who has won a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick has led three Division I-A programs to 14 NCAA
Tournament appearances in 19 years as a head coach. He comes to
Georgia after leading Rhode Island to the NCAA Tournament in both
of his seasons with the Rams. Including stints at UCLA (191-63) and
Pepperdine (167-97), Harrick is 403-182 (.688).
</P>
<P>
   Harrick, who was making about $350,000 a year at Rhode Island,
agreed in principle to a four-year contract that will pay him
$550,000 a year, plus a $100,000-a-year annuity that will mature in
four years. Dooley said he hopes to have the deal completed in
three or four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've followed Georgia basketball for many, many years,'' said
Harrick, who was in Athens for the first time. ``I'm very close
friends with (former Bulldogs coaches) Hugh Durham and Tubby Smith,
and I've seen what can be done here and the potential it has. I'm
here because of the great conference we play in and the high-level
basketball that is achieved in this league. ... To me it was almost
a no-brainer to come down here.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Harrick originally balked at Georgia's overtures
because of the state's anti-nepotism policy. He said Dooley and UGA
President Michael Adams told him from the beginning that Harrick's
son, Jim Harrick Jr., an assistant on his staff at Rhode Island,
would not be permitted to join him on his Georgia staff. At the
time, Harrick said, ``That would be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it was Harrick's son who cleared the way for his
father to come to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to my son and he said, `Dad, you can't not take that
job,''' Harrick said. ``That hurt more than anything, leaving him
behind, and that's the reason we delayed it that long, making my
mind up.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick said Dooley offered him the job Sunday night in St.
Petersburg, Fla., where they were attending the Final Four. Harrick
did not give Dooley the final word until ``about 11 o'clock''
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts differ about whether Harrick was the Bulldogs' first
choice. Delaware coach Mike Brey said Tuesday night that Dooley had
offered him the Georgia job Sunday and he turned it down that day.
Dooley refused to confirm or deny that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hired the best-qualified guy for the position, period,''
Dooley snapped after repeatedly fielding the question.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley also bristled at reports that Harrick's hiring was the
handiwork of Adams, who has known Harrick since the two were at
Pepperdine in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to say that our president was involved in the
process from the last interviews on,'' Dooley said. ``I'm also
pleased to say that he let me, as I expected he would, make the
decision to hire a basketball coach. All the recommendations I made
to Dr. Adams, he endorsed 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his goals at Georgia, Harrick spoke with the same
confidence Smith did when he accepted the job almost exactly four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly have the goal of winning another national
championship,'' he said. ``I don't think there's any doubt it can
be done here. That's one of the reasons I came.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
