<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players looking forward to Harrick's arrival, but Jones absent
from scene
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Among the horde of media, players and fans at
Wednesday's news conference announcing Jim Harrick as Georgia's new
basketball coach was one very noticeable absentee _ Bulldogs star
forward Jumaine Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a 6-foot-7 sophomore, announced in February that he plans
to enter the NBA Draft in June. While his teammates seemed to
welcome Harrick, the former Rhode Island and UCLA coach, Jones was
nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of Harrick's first duties as Georgia's coach was
sending two student managers scurrying to find Jones, who wasn't in
his McWhorter Hall dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jumaine is a great person, but he is going to make his own
decision on (whether or not to return),'' freshman guard D.A. Layne
said. ``I haven't talked to him about that, but we'd like to have
him back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rufus McDuffie, who coached Jones at Mitchell-Baker High, said
Wednesday that his former player is eager to meet Harrick, but
McDuffie added that Jones still is seriously considering the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBA people have told me that he'd be one of the first guys
taken,'' McDuffie said, ``but I've never told him to enter the
draft. He needs to make his own decision. The ideal situation would
be for him to go back to Georgia and for them to compete for an SEC
title. But with the players they've got, I don't think that's
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick was expected to meet Georgia's returning players
Wednesday afternoon, and he said he would telephone the incoming
freshmen signed last fall. Harrick also said that he would compile
a list of four or five recruits to visit before April 7, the start
of the spring signing period.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick, 60, led teams at UCLA and Rhode Island to the NCAA
Tournament 10 years in a row, and the Bruins won the national title
under him in 1995. That is welcome news to Georgia's players, who
missed the tournament the last two seasons under departed coach Ron
Jirsa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing is he is a winner, and he can take us to the
next level,'' Layne said. ``He won at UCLA. . . . I am confident he
will be here for a long time. We need to get to the Sweet 16 and
eventually a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' center Robb Dryden said. ``Everybody
knows coach Harrick. When I heard the news, I was like, `He's
coming here?' That should do volumes for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior guard Adrian Jones, who missed last season after breaking
his foot, said he is looking forward to the change. He did not
learn of Harrick's hiring until Georgia officials telephoned him at
9 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things he can teach us,'' Jones said. ``I mean,
we'll be playing for a coach who has won a national championship,
and not many players ever get a chance to say that. I'm glad this
is over with, and I'm happy he's here. He will bring us back to a
level we all expect.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
