A1629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-EXPECTATIO     03-31 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-EXPECTATIONS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech's defense gets new look
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Georgia Tech, which finished 10-2 a year ago and
shared the ACC title with Florida State, is going to contend for
loftier honors this season, the main concern will be shoring up its
defense as the Yellow Jackets open spring drills this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in as many seasons, Tech will have new a
defensive coordinator. Ted Roof, a former All-ACC linebacker for
the Jackets, was promoted from linebackers coach after Randy Edsall
left after just one season to become head coach at Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Roof also will have an entirely new staff of assistants in Dave
Sollazzo, interior line; Paul Ferraro, secondary; and Danny
Crossman, ends and special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Their task is daunting. The Yellow Jackets must replace five
starters _ including leading tackler DeLaunta Cameron at linebacker
and big-play defensive backs Jason Bostic and Jerry Caldwell _ from
a unit that allowed 22 points and almost 400 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very comfortable with Ted Roof as coordinator,'' coach
George O'Leary said. ``I think we've brought in a fantastic staff
from an experience standpoint on defense. There are guys on that
staff that have coordinated (at other schools).''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, who coordinated top-ranked defenses at Tech 1988-91,
said Roof, 35, brings a wealth of ACC knowledge to his new post, as
well as the proper attack-oriented mindset.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to continue to be a pressure team, `` O'Leary said,
``continue to basically mix up man and zone (pass coverages) and
always looking for better ways to get things done, which I was
looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good teacher ... good with new coaches ... gets the
most potential out of his players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure definitely is on the defense,'' says Travares
Tillman, an All-America candidate at free safety. ``We're going to
have to show more aggressiveness, everybody hustling to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, junior defensive end Felipe Claybrooks
recorded 10 sacks last season, and linebacker Chris Edwards had 53
tackles over the final four games. Junior linebacker Matt Miller
will miss spring practice with an injured knee but is expected to
be fully recovered by the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Here are other areas of emphasis:
</P>
<P>
   Offense: All-ACC quarterback Joe Hamilton (2,166 yards passing,
17 TDs) and split end Dez White (46 receptions, 973 yards, 9 TDs)
return. Gone, however, are versatile running back Charlie Rogers
and All-America center Craig Page.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to run the ball more aggressively,'' O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Burns is back at tailback after a splendid freshman year in
which he led the team in rushing with 474 yards, averaging 4.8
yards per carry. Senior Noah King, who started five games at guard
last season, will move to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to leave this spring with a second quarterback,''
O'Leary said, adding that sophomore George Godsey has the early
edge over redshirt freshman Jermaine Crenshaw and Brian Camp, the
Ohio prep player of the year who graduated from high school last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking game: During the spring, the kickers will be
inexperienced. Kai Cornwell made his only attempt as a backup last
season, and punters Hal Higgins and Dan Dyke are walk-ons. However,
Tech signed two kickers, Luke Manget and Phillip Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Depth: O'Leary will look to solidify the Jackets' overall depth,
while also paying close attention to the team's competitive
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all,'' O'Leary said, ``is to leave the spring with a
two-deep that is pretty sound, and if not, know where our freshmen
can help us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second is basically, have we grown offensively and
defensively? We want to run the ball more aggressively; we want to
stop the run on defense. So, we're going to get a pretty good
measure of where we are. The key is that everybody stays healthy.
That's a great spring.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
