<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Shark' feeling green around the gills
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Greg Norman withdrew Wednesday morning from the
BellSouth Classic, which begins play todayat the TPC at Sugarloaf.
</P>
<P>
   Norman's wife, Laura, called PGA Tour official George Boutell
and said her husband could not play because of a virus. She said
Norman, who designed Sugarloaf in Duluth, was at home in Hobe
Sound, Fla., with a fever and did not feel he could shake the
illness in a day. Chris Smith replaces Norman in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, who finished fifth in 1997, the tournament's inaugural
year at Sugarloaf, missed the cut last week at The Players
Championship. He missed the 1998 BellSouth while recuperating from
shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Kaplan, the tournament's executive director, said an annual
appearance by Norman at the BellSouth was not part of the contract,
when Sugarloaf was chosen to replace Atlanta Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no reason to believe that it's not a legitimate
reason,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman's Great White Shark Enterprises had a party planned for
clients for tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
