</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SUGARLOAF-FINISH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough Sugarloaf ends with whimper, pros say
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the original blueprints, the 18th at Sugarloaf was
supposed to go left of the lake as a long par 4.
</P>
<P>
   But after some changes to Greg Norman's original Sugarloaf
Country Club plans by the PGA Tour's Tournament Players Club
division, the hole was fashioned into what ideally would be a
dynamic, risk-reward, go-for-it, two-shot par 5.
</P>
<P>
   But that was on paper. More often than not, the 576-yard, par-5
finishing hole at the site of today's BellSouth Classic is an
uneventful layup, three-shot finishing hole. Or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible hole,'' said Mark Calcavecchia, who won the
BellSouth in 1995 when it was held at Atlanta Country Club. ``With
the tees back, it's basically a wedge or 9-iron par 3. The first
two shots don't even count, because everybody's going to just plop
it in the fairway and just plop it down there and have 130 (yards)
in, anyway. It's basically just a one-shot hole.''
</P>
<P>
   That's in stark contrast to its predecessor, the 18th at Atlanta
Country Club, one of the finest, risk-reward par 5s in golf. There
is no way to compare the two. The 18th at ACC was slightly uphill,
then flattened out gracefully and turned left and was bordered by a
lake. A carefully hooked drive up the right side of the fairway
could scoot far enough to leave a long- or middle-iron shot to the
green.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic moments were common. In 1994, John Daly hit a massive
drive, an 8-iron to the left bunker and got up and down for a
winning birdie. Brian Henninger had applied the pressure moments
earlier with an eagle to climb within a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that to last year at Sugarloaf, when Jay Don Blake,
trailing Tiger Woods by one shot, decided to lay up because of
concerns about swirling winds.
</P>
<P>
   In its third year of scrutiny at the BellSouth Classic, the 18th
at Sugarloaf continues to be more panned than praised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible,'' 1996 winner Paul Stankowski said. ``It's
pathetic as a last hole. ... I think they should start over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the best hole on the course,'' Smyrna's Stewart Cink
said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the kinder assessments comes from Nick Price, one of
Norman's best friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a bad hole,'' Price said. ``But it doesn't fit the
rest of the course. It seems to me that you've got so many famous
holes on that golf course, and then all of a sudden you've got that
one, and it doesn't fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Norman, who reworked the hole to fit what the PGA Tour
wanted _ a grandstand, theater-type finish after the original,
par-4 18th was scrapped _ isn't completely happy with it. Unless
the tees are moved up, allowing something less than a fairway wood
or 2-iron from the highly elevated fairway to the water-guarded
green, Norman admits, the hole doesn't quite do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The layup is too easy,'' Norman said. ``That's the only thing
I don't like about it. You just bump it down there with a 7-iron or
8-iron. I'd like to see it where the tee is moved up, and it
becomes a hole where everybody's got a chance of getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman knows the pros don't like the hole, but he acknowledges
that some things are out of his control. There are no plans to
rework No. 18, but tournament officials are expected to use the
shorter tees during this year's event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to be a long par 4, and we were going to come
back to that green as the 19th hole,'' Norman said, referring to
the type of unofficial ``betting'' hole found on European courses.
``Then, all of a sudden, the TPC (took over), and the value of
those residential lots went through the roof, and we had to
eliminate that one hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Logistics aside, the 18th is gorgeous. The tee shot is hit
between the trees at the top of a hill, then the fairway bends
sharply downhill, narrowly turning past the water to the green.
Bleacher seats are on the left side of the fairway, in position to
see shots soaring overhead. At the green, the stands are uniquely
positioned in the water. But then come hundreds of 110-yard wedge
shots that don't provide the glamour of the risk-taking long shot
over water.
</P>
<P>
   Some think the 18th green would be better with a backboard-type
shaping, to encourage second-shot gambles. As it is, the only
bailout is the back bunker, which still leaves a fairly dicey third
shot. On the second shot, many players think that the distance and
orientation are difficult from the high elevation, creating a weird
feeling of open space. Downhill lies are common and not conducive
to launching a screaming 2-iron or 4-wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The short hitters can't get down that slope,'' Stankowski
said. ``I don't have a problem with the longer hitters having an
advantage _ that's that the way the game is _ but if you flatten
(the landing area) a little more, you'd make it available. The hole
is only hard if you're going for the green. ... Why not have a
3-iron or a 3-wood into that green instead of a lob wedge?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the first year the BellSouth used Sugarloaf, the tee at
the 18th remained back for all four rounds, allowing only about 10
percent of the field to go for the green. Tim Herron was one of the
few players to go for the green in two on all four days. The course
was baked in 1997 and played hard and fast, allowing drives at the
18th to scoot down the slope for extra yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the course played wet and slow because of heavy
spring rains, the tee was moved ahead about 40 yards for two rounds
to allow players to take a gamble. From the back tee, it was
impossible except for a handful of players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost forced you to lay up, because it was wet,'' Billy
Andrade said. ``It's a hole where you want to be able to get there,
but it's a dicey second shot. That back bunker's no bargain,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I go for it if I can, but not very often do I get a chance to
go for it,'' said Cink, who practices frequently at Sugarloaf.
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia said he prefers the hole when the tees are down.
But if he has the shot ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If I've got a 2-iron to the green, I'm going to hit it,'' he
said. ``I ain't layin' up with 210 to the front and 230 to the
hole. I don't care where I am.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
