<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH IS QUARTERLY LEADER IN SECURITIES UNDERWRITING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With MARKET-QTR. See also ECON-REPORT) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. underwrote more securities than
any other Wall Street firm in the first quarter of 1999, while
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. was the leader in mergers and acquisitions,
according to rankings announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter took first place in stock
transactions, bolstered in part by arranging three big stock
offerings by Delphi, Equant and Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly rankings of securities firms, known as league
tables, are closely watched within the industry as an indicator of
which banks and brokerages houses are strongest, information that
is seen as swaying the decisions of companies that use Wall Street
investment banking services.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the tables did not contain many surprises in the two
dozen areas of the businesses they track, including municipal
bonds, initial public stock offerings and merger-and-acquisition
deals. Merrill Lynch, Morgan, Goldman, Citigroup's Salomon Smith
Barney, Lehman Brothers and Credit Suisse First Boston generally
rank at the top, as they did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some Wall Street firms earn a big chunk of their overall profits
advising companies on mergers and acquisitions, and that business
is one of the most heavily contested.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Goldman holds a commanding lead over its main
rivals in advising on deals completed, with a 43 percent market
share worldwide by value of the deals. First Boston placed second
with 28 percent market share and Merrill Lynch ranked a close
third.
</P>
<P>
   In total underwriting of both debt and equity, Merrill is the
perennial leader of all Wall Street firms, and the first quarter of
this year was no different. Salomon Smith Barney placed second, and
Morgan Stanley was third. The one exception was Goldman, which
ranked second in the category a year ago but slipped to sixth for
the period this year.
</P>
<P>
   Another measure of prowess is underwriting fees earned, which do
not always correlate to the volume of deals completed. Merrill
battled Morgan for the honors, with Merrill earning $345 million in
fees and Morgan reporting $326 million. Credit Suisse First Boston
beat out Salomon Smith Barney for third place, earning $236
million, just $2 million more than Salomon. Goldman fell to fifth
with $197 million in fees.
</P>
<P>
   Total fees actually slipped from the first quarter of last year,
to $2.46 billion from $3.14 billion, a 20 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Issuers are shopping their deals around for the best prices,
which puts pressure on fees,'' said Richard Peterson of Securities
Data. ``Some of the firms cut prices to bring in more business.''
</P>
<P>
   In the debt business, Merrill maintained its long-standing
position as America's biggest bond underwriter, increasing its
market share from 14 percent a year ago to almost 16 percent so far
this year. Salomon, as usual, was second in the category. First
Boston jumped a few spots to No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley took first place in equity and equity-related
volume this quarter, followed by Merrill and Goldman. In 1998,
Merrill held the top slot, followed by Morgan and Equitable's
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. In the lucrative business of
underwriting first-time stock offerings, however, Merrill snatched
first place from Morgan, with Goldman placing third.
</P>
<P>
   The initial public offering market, which is often an indicator
of the overall health of the U.S. stock market because it shows
investors' appetite for risk, was surprisingly weak given the
continued strong performance of market indicators, industry experts
said. There were fewer than 100 offerings in the period, the lowest
number for a quarter since the stock market slump of 1991. The
exceptions to that rule: Internet stocks and big-name companies,
like Delphi, that offered stock for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is really about a few big deals and Internet and
technology issues, and that's about it,'' said Richard Kauffman,
head of global equity capital markets at Morgan Stanley. ``People
presume that because the market indicators are so strong,
everything is strong. But in many areas this is a tough market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
