<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-REPORT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Federal report assails Everglades restoration effort
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Gridlock and cost overruns threaten to
undermine the federal government's $1.2 billion Everglades
restoration effort, congressional investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   The draft report by the U.S. General Accounting Office could
come at an awkward moment _ in three months, federal engineers plan
to hand Congress a new Everglades proposal costing $7.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators say the government lacks a clearly organized
Everglades strategy, making it hard to predict costs or gauge
whether the efforts are working. They also say that somebody needs
the power to solve disputes among federal and state agencies, which
have stalled parts of the restoration for as long as 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The unreleased draft _ which The Palm Beach Post obtained
Wednesday _ echoes some critics' complaints that projects in the
southern Everglades have become mired in disagreements between the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the U.S. Interior Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're paralyzed by process,'' said Terry Rice, a Miccosukee
Indian tribe consultant.
</P>
<P>
   But others said the report fell short of a blistering attack and
shouldn't sour Congress on Everglades spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a smoking gun here,'' said Charles Lee of the
Florida Audubon Society.
</P>
<P>
   One restoration leader acknowledged that disagreements sometimes
drag on, but he said the system is working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with real things, things that matter to people,
things that in previous times would have been left unresolved,''
said Terrence ``Rock'' Salt, executive director of the federally
created South Florida Ecosystem Restoration Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   The task force lets federal, state, local and tribal leaders
work together on Everglades policy, but it lacks the power to order
solutions. Salt said he doubts that the panel could ever wield that
kind of authority, especially over the state.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional budget leaders ordered the study last fall after
becoming irked at the Florida Legislature, which was trying to
increase payments to landowners in Everglades condemnation cases.
</P>
<P>
   The report says the federal government has spent more than $1.2
billion on the Everglades since 1993, with three-quarters coming
from the corps and the Interior Department. The investigators said
some agencies couldn't completely account for their Everglades
spending, which includes money from many sources that not everyone
tracks the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
