<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MISSING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE U.S. SOLDIERS MISSING ON KOSOVO BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three American infantrymen patrolling Macedonia's
border with the Yugoslav province of Kosovo were missing Wednesday
after reporting by radio that they had been surrounded and were
under fire, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers might have been captured, presumably by Serbian
forces or paramilitary units, officials said, but they cautioned
that they had no direct evidence to support their suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers are part of the United States 1st Infantry
Division, which has had about 350 members in Macedonia for years, a
remnant of a United Nations force that is being withdrawn now that
thousands of NATO troops are guarding the border with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman, said last night that the
three soldiers, whose names were not released, came under fire
about 2:30 p.m. (7:30 a.m. ET). They had split off in their Humvee
from the rest of the patrol along a road near Kumanovo, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came under small-arms fire,'' Bacon said. ``They reported
over the radio that they were surrounded. No more was heard from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that American and other NATO forces, along with
Macedonian police, immediately launched a search on the ground and
deployed a helicopter and a plane equipped with infrared
heat-detecting sensors, but the team could not be located. The
search was still continuing twelve hours after the incident, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon refused to say whether the search parties would cross the
border into Serbian territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk about the search, because I just don't know,'' he
said. ``I assume we are searching aggressively, but remember,
Kosovo is part of Yugoslavia, and it is heavily armed along the
border right now.''
</P>
<P>
   While it was not the first time that there has been scattered
shooting along the tense border since the NATO bombing of Serbia
began, this was the most serious incident to date, threatening to
spill the crisis into one of Yugoslavia's neighboring states and
tempting Allied forces to drive across the border.
</P>
<P>
   When the pilot of an F-117 Stealth fighter plane went down in
Serbian controlled territory last weekend, NATO sent in rescue
helicopters. But that pilot's location was far from where his plane
landed, unknown to the enemy, and disclosed to his rescuers by a
special electronic beacon. Infantrymen do not routinely carry such
devices, especially when they are not expecting to be engaged in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon spokesman said that the three soldiers, all
enlisted men, were on a patrol in a Humvee, which are heavily
armored and often well-armed all-purpose infantry vehicles. They
were traveling in a group with a small number of other vehicles, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   They were in uniform and were not wearing the blue helmets of
U.N. peacekeepers but their standard military gear, a military
official said.
</P>
<P>
   During the patrol, the vehicles separated from one another as
part of a training exercise, he said. It was then that the
occupants of one vehicle reported to the others that they were
under fire.
</P>
<P>
   While the three tried to get away, the other vehicles raced back
to find them, but could not, Bacon said. He did not know whether
the soldiers ever returned fire.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said that the soldiers reported to a U.S. task force known
as Able Sentry, which is part of the U.N. force in Macedonia, and
the task force launched a Blackhawk helicopter to search.
Meanwhile, NATO units that are part of the Allied Rapid Reaction
Corps, a 7,500-man group run by the British in preparation for an
eventual peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, put their own helicopters
into the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty to 90 American ground troops deployed to the area from
Task Force Able Sentry, joined by a number of allied ground troops
and several helicopters,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   The weather in the area was ``lousy,'' he said, restricting
visibility for the search parties.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces have ``substantial armored forces along the
border,'' he said..
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has maintained a small peacekeeping force in
Macedonia since the former Yugoslav republic declared its
independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, amid growing fears that fighting in the Balkans would
spread, the U.N. Security Council renewed the force's mission and
increased the troop strength to more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has contributed about 350 soldiers since the
peacekeeping mission, and American officials have said they have no
plans to send more. Bacon said the American unit was scheduled to
leave the country soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
