</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-IRAQ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS SEEK IRAQI HELP FOR DEFENSE, BRITAIN SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-VUKOVAR,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-WARCRIMES, KOSOVO-SOLANA, KOSOVO-HACKERS, KOSOVO-AID,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-ARMS, KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-SERBS-NY,
KOSOVO-UPDATE, KOSOVO-VATICAN) 
(nk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The British government said Wednesday that
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia had formed a ``close
relationship'' with President Saddam Hussein of Iraq and that they
had stepped up their military cooperation in the face of a common
threat from American air strikes. American officials, however, were
skeptical about the degree of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Sir Charles Guthrie, chief of the British defense staff,
said at news conference in London that the Milosevic government
``is now a key military ally for Iraq'' and that a Yugoslav
delegation toured Iraqi air defense sites last month _ ``no doubt
to learn tactics on how to down allied aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen some of the tactics put into practice already
over Serbia,'' he told reporters. ``We are aware from a variety of
sources that over the last six months this relationship has grown
in depth and breadth, as both Milosevic and Saddam have come under
increasing pressure from the West.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there had recently been a ``continuous two-way flow of
military and defense industry delegations'' between Yugoslavia and
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials confirmed news reports this
week that a delegation of Yugoslav defense specialists visited Iraq
in February, presumably to discuss air-defense tactics against
American warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   And they said that Yugoslav forces may have adopted tactics
recommended by the Iraqis in dealing with the threat of American
air strikes, including the movement of anti-aircraft weapons into
populated areas less likely to be attacked by NATO planes.
</P>
<P>
   But they said Wednesday that American intelligence agencies had
little evidence to suggest that the cooperation between the
Yugoslav and Iraqi armed forces was as sweeping as the British
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reports of contact between the Serbs and the Iraqis on air
defense are true,'' said an intelligence official, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``But I would not take from that the
implication that there is an active and ongoing advisory or
resupply effort. I just don't think we can substantiate that at
this point.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Iraq would be condemned by other Muslim nations in
the Arab world if it assisted Yugoslavia in the persecution of the
ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo, which is mostly Muslim. The
Iraqi government Wednesday condemned the assault on Yugoslavia as
``cowardly NATO aggression that is a flagrant violation of the
United Nations charter and of international law,'' Iraq's official
news agency, INA, reported.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Pentagon has said publicly that recent military
contacts between Yugoslavia and Iraq were no surprise, given that
Milosevic and Hussein find themselves confronted by a common
adversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two countries, both subject to attack by forces
within NATO,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said earlier this
week. ``They both have primarily Soviet-built or purchased
air-defense systems, and they are both subject to international
embargoes. So they obviously might look for ways to work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that the Yugoslavs believe that the Iraqis have
learned a thing or two over the last seven years in dealing with
Western aircraft,'' he continued. ``What they've learned is that
they haven't been able to deal with them very successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia and Iraq have a history of military cooperation that
predates the Kosovo crisis by many years. In the 1980s, Yugoslavia
sold Soviet-made air-defense equipment to Iraq and helped Baghdad
in the construction of airfields, underground command centers and
other infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
   American and British officials said that Iraq, which has been
the target of an international arms embargo since the 1991 Gulf
War, would be eager to obtain spare parts from Yugoslavia,
especially for its air-defense network, while Yugoslavia would seek
detailed information from Iraq about its knowledge of American
combat tactics.
</P>
<P>
   British Defense Minister George Robertson said Wednesday that
``what links these two countries together appears to be a
determination in the face of domestic and economic difficulty to
continue to build a war machine and, secondly, a callous disregard
for human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching for equally tough language, Guthrie, the British
defense chief, said that ``all of this adds up to a close
relationship between Saddam and Milosevic or, as somebody said to
me, a marriage of convenience based on the suffering of their
peoples.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
