<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS01-COX     03-31 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush boasts $6 million in funds for pending campaign
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a demonstration of political muscle-flexing
and fiscal fitness, Gov. George W. Bush on Wednesday said he
collected more than $6 million for his budding presidential
campaign in less than a month.
</P>
<P>
   The figure was $3 million higher than one that hit the grapevine
last weekend. It is $2 million more than one incorrectly reported
Wednesday by the New York Times and carried by the Austin
American-Statesman. And it is about $4 million more than the amount
raised by any of his GOP rivals, including some who have been
working toward the 2000 campaign for several years. Only Democratic
Vice President Al Gore raised more _ $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said there is more cash in the pipeline _ ``our accountants
are still counting'' _ and he hopes to double the bottom line by
the end of June. By comparison, Bob Dole, the 1996 GOP nominee,
raised $13.5 million in the first six months of 1995. Bush is
trying to approach that figure in four months.
</P>
<P>
   After months in which polls and pundits provided the only
measure of the presidential field, Wednesday's announcements
provided another yardstick for the candidates' viability and
relative strength heading into caucuses and primaries that won't
begin for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm blessed with a lot of friends in life who seem to want to
encourage me to take the next step,'' said Bush, who officially is
still exploring a presidential bid. Asked if the fund-raising
success ``inches'' him toward running, Bush said, ``It more than
inches. It feets and yards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted to make sure that behind the polls and the phone
calls that there was some substance,'' he said. ``And I think this
is the first indication that there is true support.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush resisted talk that donors, who by federal law are limited
to giving $1,000, were signing on with a candidate who is still
developing positions on major issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they would write a check like that unless they
knew where my heart is, what my intentions are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The money announced Wednesday came at the end of a three-month
reporting period that will be the subject of disclosure filings
with the Federal Election Commission by April 15. Bush, whose fund
raising began in March, released no list of donors or
state-by-state totals on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Bush friend Donald Evans, national finance chairman for
the presidential campaign, said the money poured in in response to
a fund-raising letter and a web of ``friend-to-friend'' efforts
based on the massive Bush family political network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is people across the country responding to the
governor's positive vision for America going into the 21st
century,'' Evans said. ``We did it one by one, lots of phone calls,
lots of friends calling friends.''
</P>
<P>
   While speculation about fund-raising totals had been rumbling
for days, the Bush total was a closely held secret. Eager to make a
big splash Wednesday, Bush aides declined to talk numbers before
then, even privately. ``You're going to be surprised,'' one aide
said Tuesday. The Bush campaign said Evans was misquoted as saying
Tuesday the total was more than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he made two brief fund-raising calls to Michigan and
Florida. He plans to hit the fund-raising trail after the
legislative session ends May 31.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's goal is to raise enough money _ in excess of $45
million _ to be able to pass on federal matching funds that come
with spending limits that can hamper a campaign. Steve Forbes, who
largely funds his campaigns out of his own deep pockets, is the
only major contender who has announced he will not take the federal
money. Spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss said Forbes has not raised
a significant amount of money since formally announcing his
candidacy this month.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Schmidt, campaign manager for former Tennessee Gov. Lamar
Alexander, was impressed, but not discouraged, by the Bush numbers.
Schmidt referred to two other Texas Republicans who were early
fund-raising stalwarts: Phil Gramm and John Connally.
</P>
<P>
   The current Texas senator and the late Texas governor have
become poster boys for presidential campaign sizzle and fizzle.
Both raised big money early, then cratered _ Connally in 1980 and
Gramm in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, fund-raising prowess does not
necessarily translate to victories in a presidential primary
process,'' said Schmidt, whose boss raised between $700,000 and
$800,000 in the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Gramm was the candidate making early
fund-raising headlines. In February 1995, at a Dallas Convention
Center dinner, Gramm set a one-meal record by collecting $4.1
million for his presidential race. He wound up spending $28 million
on a campaign that crashed with a fifth-place finish in the Iowa
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could be an interesting lesson to try to avoid what
happened to Phil,'' Bush said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush, Gramm came armed with a political Rolodex to die for.
Gramm had a computerized database of names, jobs, interests of
164,454 people he had met in the preceding four years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Connally, the top fund-raiser in 1979, spent $12
million and earned one delegate at the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to announcing the fund-raising total, Bush on
Wednesday again road-tested a stump speech sure to become part of
his White House campaign. He brought his ``responsibility era''
message to the conference of the Governor's Conference on Right
Choices for Youth, telling the audience that the greatest risk for
young people is ``their moral and spiritual lives will not
improve'' in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was introduced by William Bennett, former education
secretary in the Reagan administration and national drug czar in
the Bush administration. Bennett, who has yet to endorse a
presidential candidate, said Bush ``has now caught the imagination
of the American people to an astounding degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bennett, who dedicates himself to moral and values
issues, was asked if Bush's self-titled ``young and irresponsible''
years could be a stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish say the merry-hearted boys make the best of all men.
Even I, believe it or not, was a merry-hearted boy at one time.
Young and male, some of us in college, some of us in high school,
did things that we weren't proud of later. Speaking for myself, I
don't think that's what's of concern to the American people. I
think the concern of the American people is whether they have
somebody who has integrity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
