<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, APRIL 1
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-FORD-NYT (moved on Thursday, Mar. 11)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Harry Ford moved by the New York Times News
Service on Thursday, Mar. 11, described the formation of Atheneum
Publishers incompletely. Atheneum, where Mr. Ford worked for 28
years, was created in 1959 by Alfred Knopf Jr., Simon Michael
Bessie and Hiram Haydn, not by Mr. Knopf alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1659 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-INDICT-ART-     03-31 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-INDICT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: in 1990. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the sometimes contentious arraignment, and in comments
afterwards, the lawyers accused Johnson of playing to the political
winds. Worth called his client a ``political prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson implicitly criticized the officers for failing to
present their version of events during a three-week inquiry by a
Bronx grand jury, calling it ``one of the oddities'' of the case.
Because the officers had not offered any justification for the
shooting, he said, the court should treat them ``like any other
individuals who rolled up to a building and fired 41 shots'' at
someone.
</P>
<P>
   That assertion prompted outrage from the officers' lawyers.
``Certainly police offciers, being proposed defendants, have the
same rights as anybody else and do not have to testify to the grand
jury,'' Carroll's attorney, Marvyn M. Kornberg, said.
</P>
<P>
   With the indictments unsealed, more details about the case began
to emerge Wednesday. Worth said that the officers continued
shooting because Diallo continued to stand upright as the 19
bullets ripped into his body. `` Diallo did not fall at any point
during the incident and that's why the number of shots that were
fired were fired,'' Worth said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Diallo family's lawyers attacked that assertion as
``absurd,'' saying that it was contradicted by an autopsy done by
their own pathologist, Dr. Cyril H. Wecht, the coroner for
Allegheny County in Pennsylvania. That report suggests that Diallo
was knocked down and likely paralyzed by some of the earliest
bullets that hit him, said one of the lawyers, Peter Neufeld. Two
of the first shots fired perforated Diallo's spine, and ``he was
brought down to the ground immediately,'' Neufeld said.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Examiner's office has refused to discuss its
official autopsy, although it has released copies of the report to
several involved parties. People who have reviewed the report said
it states that one of the bullets struck Diallo squarely in the
chest, rupturing his aorta and perforating his spine. A second
bullet also perforated and partially severed his spine.
</P>
<P>
   The report does not give a sequence for the shots fired, draw
conclusions about what position Diallo was in when the shots were
fired, or express any opinion about whether the shots paralyzed
him, according to the people who have seen it. But, they said, the
report does note that great volumes of blood were found in Diallo's
chest cavity, ostensibly from the chest wounds. Experts said that
can be evidence that the shots that struck his torso were fired
early in the sequence when the body's blood pressure was still
high.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers, who have not seen either of the autopsy
reports, strongly disputed the conclusions of the Diallo family
lawyers. ``How does anyone tell it's one of the earlier shots?''
Worth asked. ``When I was a prosecutor I never heard of a Medical
Examiner who could say with any certainty the sequence of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   At the officer's arraingment Wednesday, the courtroom was
bifurcated by race and allegiance. On one side sat the Diallos,
their relatives and their supporters, including the Rev. Al
Sharpton, all of whom were black or Hispanic. On the other sat
representatives of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association and
friends and relatives of the officers. With a few exceptions, all
of them were white. Among those present to register their support
for the defendants was Inspector Bruce H. Smolka, the commanding
officer of the Street Crime Unit, the elite police squad where the
four officers were assigned and that critics say has unfairly
targeted members of minority groups in its mission to search
suspects for guns.
</P>
<P>
   After the officers entered their pleas, Justice Collins oversaw
the selection of the judge who will handle the case through its
conclusion, and, if the officers waive their right to a jury trial,
decide their fate. Patricia Anne Williams, an acting Supreme Court
justice, was chosen when her name was picked at random from a wheel
containing the names of 12 judges.
</P>
<P>
   The arraignment and the subsequent comments by the officers'
lawyers offered a glimpse of the defense they will provide, and of
possible conflicts between the scenarios that the prosecution and
defense will present. All of the lawyers referred to their clients'
``reasonable belief'' that they were in imminent danger. Under the
penal code provision for justifiable homicide, the officers will
have to prove not only that they thought they or their fellow
officers were in imminent danger, but that it was ``reasonable'' to
believe so. Stephen Brounstein, the lawyer for Boss, who fired five
shots, and James Culleton, the lawyer for Murphy, who fired four,
both said that their clients heard gunfire and saw McMellon on the
ground, leading them to assume that Officer McMellon had been shot.
``He had a sick feeling inside his being that he would be shot and
he reacted,'' Culleton said of Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   A clearly agitated Johnson leapt to his feet at the end, saying
that Murphy ``did not see Amadou Diallo fire a weapon, he did not
see Amadou Diallo have a weapon, because Amadou Diallo did not have
a weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers for McMellon and Carroll did not deal with the facts
during the arraignment, but afterwards, Kornberg said that McMellon
had fallen after firing about three shots. Kornberg said his
client, Carroll, that he had seen a ``black object'' _ which later
turned out to be Diallo's wallet _ coming out of the victim's back
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client saw him reaching into his back pocket, saw this
black object come out and my client yelled `Gun!''' Kornberg said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After the court proceedings, the officers briefly thanked their
supporters, and proclaimed their innocence. Eyes welling, brows
knitted, Murphy said, ``I did nothing wrong and this trial will
show that I did nothing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   James Savage, the president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent
Association, said, ``This is a dark day for the New York City
Police Department when four young, eager aggressive police officers
who have done nothing but serve their city well are indicted for
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Diallos, who met with Johnson for half an hour before
the arraignment, and their supporters expressed satisfaction with
the indictments, and said they hoped that justice would be done. At
the arraignment's end, Mrs. Diallo's eyes were full of tears.
</P>
</TEXT>
