<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUDGE IN MICROSOFT TRIAL SETS A LONG TIMETABLE
</P>
<P>
   The presiding judge in the Microsoft antitrust trial, Thomas
Penfield Jackson, tentatively set a May 10 date for the trial to
resume and laid out a timetable that virtually insures that what
was to have been a speedy trial will not end much before 2000. The
long trial means that the government will not achieve its main goal
of stopping the bundling of a Web browser with Microsoft's Windows
98 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIP MORRIS LEADS STOCKS LOWER
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell as investors sold shares of Philip Morris after a
jury found the company liable for $81 million in damages for the
death of a smoker and hopes faded for a quick settlement of
Microsoft's antitrust trial. The Dow Jones industrials fell 127.10
points, to 9,786.16, and the Nasdaq composite index lost 18.53
points, to 2,461.76. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell
14.38 points, to 1,300.75.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds prices fell, finishing their worst quarter in three years
on fears of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow industrials rose 6.6 percent for the quarter, compared
with 4.6 percent for the S&AMP;P 500, as investors intensified their
preference for big companies' shares.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL LYNCH TOPS UNDERWRITERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch underwrote more securities than any other Wall
Street firm in the first quarter of 1999, while Goldman, Sachs led
in mergers and acquisitions. Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   IBM STRESSES WEB-SITE PRIVACY
</P>
<P>
   IBM, the second-biggest advertiser on the Internet, said that it
would pull its advertisements from Web sites that lacked clear
privacy policies.
</P>
<P>
   CBS IN EXCLUSIVE CLINTON INTERVIEW
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton gave his first exclusive interview in nearly
15 months to Dan Rather of CBS News, answering questions about
Yugoslavia and the impeachment scandal.
</P>
<P>
   CONDE NAST NAMES GQ PUBLISHER
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Florio, the publisher of Conde Nast Traveler, was named
publisher of the Conde Nast men's title GQ. Jack Laschever is
resigning for medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   A DEADLOCK OVER A NEW TRADE CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   After a yearlong search for a new head of the World Trade
Organization, the European Union and the United States appear to be
deadlocked between Suphachai Panichpakdi, the Thai Commerce
Minister, and Michael Moore, left, a former Prime Minister of New
Zealand. The term of Renato Ruggiero of Italy expires April 30.
</P>
<P>
   AN ANGRY DENIAL BY DAIMLERCHRYSLER
</P>
<P>
   The co-chairmen of DaimlerChrysler responded angrily to recent
reports of managerial troubles, insisting that the defection of a
half-dozen former Chrysler executives, some to Ford and G.M., did
not pose a problem.
</P>
<P>
   BMW SHARES FALL ON ROVER WORRIES
</P>
<P>
   BMW shares tumbled more than 4 percent after the company's top
executives gave analysts a vague and unconvincing description of
their strategy for repairing Rover, the troubled British
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI WILL CUT 14,500 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Electric, the big Japanese electronics company,
announced a broad overhaul that will reduce its global work force
by 14,500, or 10 percent, over three years. More than half the job
cuts will be in Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
