<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IBM-SFCHRON &LR;      03-31 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 IBM Gets Tough About Web Site Privacy
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In a move that could both burnish IBM's image and help stave off
government regulation of the Internet, International Business
Machines yesterday said it will stop running ads on Web sites that
fail to post privacy guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the action was designed simply to build consumer
confidence in Web commerce by supporting sites that let surfers
know how their personal information will be used, and particularly
whether it will be sold to other businesses. Surveys show that
privacy concerns are the top reason consumers hesitate to make
purchases over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   As the world's largest computer-maker and also the biggest
e-commerce consulting firm, IBM has a tremendous interest in
promoting the Web as a sales medium. As the country's
second-largest Web advertiser (after Microsoft), the company wields
heavy digital clout. IBM will spend $600 million on advertising
this year _ about one-10th of it on the Web _ with a large chunk of
the money earmarked to boost its image as a leader in
``e-business.''
</P>
<P>
   But IBM, of Armonk, N.Y., has other reasons for the hard-nosed
new stance, which it outlined in electronic letters sent yesterday
to the 350 U.S. and Canadian sites that carry IBM ads.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, members of the U.S. Congress submitted some 84 bills
to regulate how Web sites treat personal information about
visitors. Online publishers have been put on notice that the
Federal Trade Commission will step in if industry self-policing on
user privacy proves inadequate; the FTC is currently auditing sites
and will report on its findings later this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been an advocate and continue to be for self-regulation
of the Net,'' said IBM spokesman John Bukovinsky. ``We decided late
last year that an appropriate approach might be to try to leverage
the size of our advertising investment in a positive way and
require sites to have a privacy policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy was developed jointly by IBM's government affairs
office in Washington and its advertising team, Bukovinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The move was generally hailed as positive by others in the
industry who want consumers to consider the Web a safe place to
conduct transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think what IBM has done shows some important leadership in
an area that's absolutely essential for the industry,'' said Rich
LeFurgy, chairman of the Internet Advertising Bureau, a coalition
of advertisers that supports industry self-regulation and counts
IBM among its members.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey last year, the FTC found that only 14 percent of
commercial sites informed surfers of their policies on collecting
and selling online data.
</P>
<P>
   FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky said yesterday that the FTC doesn't
have a specific goal for how many sites should have such a posted
policy this year.
</P>
<P>
   But he called IBM's move ``a very fine thing. I hope others will
recognize that IBM is taking a step in the right direction and ...
do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Congress has been quick to act on Internet concerns in the
past. Within a matter of months last year, a bill on marketing to
children over the Web was recommended by the FTC, passed by
Congress and signed into law, Pitofsky noted.
</P>
<P>
   LeFurgy said his organization is pushing for 80 percent
compliance with Online Privacy Association guidelines in six
months. The guidelines, which are about individually identifiable
data, state that sites should have a privacy policy that is easy to
understand and available before any personal data is collected, and
that surfers should be able to opt out of any use for the data,
particularly if it is being sold to a third party. He declined to
disclose current levels of compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the political ramifications of IBM's new policy, the
company also stands to gain from a public relations aspect. IBM
hopes the ad stance will bolster its reputation as a trusted
industry leader. ``It's a conscious effort to reinforce what we
believe already is a leadership position in e-business,'' said
Bukovinsky.
</P>
<P>
   So what will happen on June 1 when IBM's new policy goes into
effect? Bukovinsky said he expects that IBM won't need to withdraw
ads from many sites because most sites will comply. Currently,
about 30 percent of the sites in the United States and Canada are
in compliance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   IBM advertises on another 430 sites outside of the United States
and Canada and will gradually begin imposing the new policy there,
Bukovinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have altruistic motives and clear business motives as well,
and we're in a position to leverage our advertising weight,'' said
Bukovinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton McCandlish of the Electronic Frontier Foundation, a Web
privacy advocate, said consumers can get into the act by refusing
to buy from sites that don't post their privacy policies _ and
letting the sites know with a quick e-mail message that they've
lost a sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way sites will have a real market reason to (adopt) a
privacy policy that lets consumers make an informed choice. If they
don't do it, Congress will legislate it,'' said McCandlish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORAN-NYT &LR;      03-31 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH HORNETS IN A JAM, STERN SUMMONS JORDAN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael. The mere mention of the name conjures up a kaleidoscope
of images and a lifetime of memories. Having conquered the
basketball universe, where does the next challenge lie for the
world's most prominent athlete?
</P>
<P>
   The back nine? Corporate America? Owner of a National Basketball
Association franchise? Or will Michael Jordan come out of
retirement at age 36?
</P>
<P>
   While returning to the NBA may not be a priority for Jordan _
the league prohibits owners from being players _ the possibility of
obtaining a controlling interest of a franchise is on Jordan's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has had preliminary discussions with Commissioner David
Stern and the Charlotte Hornets owner George Shinn about buying 50
percent of the team. Apparently realizing Jordan cannot save the
league on the floor anymore, Stern has enlisted Jordan to help
resuscitate a troubled franchise in his home state of North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Stern and Shinn, according to league and team officials, are the
driving forces behind Jordan's involvement. The commissioner would
not only delight in becoming the first commissioner to help award a
former player a significant portion of a franchise, but Stern could
also reduce the impact of Shinn's tarnished reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The owner has been named in a civil suit by a woman alleging
sexual misconduct. The district attorney in York County, S.C.,
where the alleged misconduct took place, did not file criminal
charges based on the original evidence. But based on new evidence,
there is interest in reopening the case.
</P>
<P>
   Only two former recent players have been part owners of teams,
Earvin (Magic) Johnson, a vice president with the Los Angeles
Lakers, and Isiah Thomas, the former general manager of the Toronto
Raptors and a current NBC analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like with Magic, Bird or myself, I think Jordan should
always have a connection to the NBA,'' Thomas said Wednesday. ``It
just makes sense, business-wise, and in other ways. For Jordan to
have no connection to the league would be a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said that Stern and the deputy commissioner, Russ Granik,
``are both genuinely interested in seeing minorities own or be a
part of franchise, whether it's Jordan or J.R. Reid. I don't think
that's a league mandate, but that's how I think they think as
individuals. I don't think all of the 29 owners think that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck Williams, the former president of the players association
and a 17-year veteran, has expressed interest in ownership with
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Michael talking about 50 percent, that's pretty much a
monumental position,'' Williams said. ``What Michael could do is
grow the team and grow the revenues. He could be the driving force
behind a new arena. He can use his status to encourage and help the
growth of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who grew up in Wilmington, N.C., and starred at the
University of North Carolina, said staying involved in the NBA
would be a ``fulfilling personal and business challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Jordan pronounced himself ``99.9 percent''
retired. Jordan issued a statement Monday confirming his interest
in owning half the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage,'' Jordan said, ``the discussions are very
preliminary.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is on vacation in the Bahamas, but is expected to renew
talks when he returns, a team official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've publicly criticized the NBA for their lack of minority
owners,'' Williams said. ``Most minority owners own maybe 1 percent
and 2 percent. It's much needed in a predominantly black league.
Whether it be me, Michael or Dr. J. I don't understand why they
can't have an ownership stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson bought 5 percent of the team from the Lakers' owner,
Jerry Buss, after his retirement in 1991. He sold the shares back
to Buss after ill-fated comeback attempts and eventually reacquired
the 5 percent, which he still holds.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas owned as much 9 percent of the Raptors and sat on the
team's board of directors until two years ago. But disagreements
with the former majority owner, Allan Slaight, over financial
matters relating to the building of a new arena forced him to
resign and have the team buy out his portion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great fit in many ways, but I would caution Jordan to
be careful who you're partners with,'' Thomas said, referring to
Shinn.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a report by Fox Sports that Jordan would return to
the NBA with the Hornets, David Falk, Jordan's agent, said
Wednesday, ``There's absolutely no truth to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
