<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB FORCES APPARENTLY CAPTURE THREE U.S. SOLDIERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Story has been updated) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three U.S. Army soldiers apparently were abducted
Wednesday by Serb forces in Macedonia as they patrolled near the
Yugoslav border, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO ground and helicopter search was under way amid the rough
terrain, according to alliance and Department of Defense spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   The incident came as the second week of NATO airstrikes began
against Yugoslavia with an allied vow to leave no safe place for
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to plan or execute his
campaign against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still determined to push forward on our sustained air
campaign, and the operation will continue,'' David Leavy, spokesman
for the National Security Council, said after the three soldiers
were reported missing.
</P>
<P>
   National security adviser Samuel Berger informed President
Clinton of the apparent abduction, the most harrowing incident of
the Balkan engagement to be made public since a U.S. F-117A stealth
fighter went down Saturday in Yugoslavia. The pilot ejected, was
rescued and then taken back to a NATO base in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The loss came as NATO and the Clinton administration was coming
under pressure to consider using ground forces to counter
Milosevic's violent campaign against Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton expanded Wednesday on his reluctance to take the step.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers me about introducing ground troops into
a hostile situation, into the Balkans and Kosovo, is the prospect
of never being able to get them out,'' Clinton said in a CBS
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent abduction occurred in the Kumanova district of
northwestern Macedonia, immediately south of the international
border with Yugoslavia, which is the line between Macedonia and the
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers, from the 1st Infantry Division, were part of a
peacekeeping mission that the United Nations dispatched to
Macedonia at the time of the ethnic fighting in Bosnia and which
had become part of a residual NATO force numbering 1,200, with
about 350 from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The missing soldiers were on a reconnaissance mission Wednesday,
a Pentagon spokesman said. They were traveling in a Hum-Vee vehicle
when they reported being surrounded while taking small-arms fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more was heard from the patrol,'' said a NATO statement
issued at alliance headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe they have possibly been abducted,'' said Col.
Richard Bridges, a Pentagon spokesman. ``There's a
search-and-rescue effort on.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon source said that the incident took place about 2:30
p.m. (6:30 a.m. CST). It was reported by NATO and the Pentagon
about 11 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Before the soldiers were reported missing, Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth Bacon said the lengthening list of bombing targets was
intended to tighten ``NATO's noose on Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh night of the aerial bombardment NATO missiles
slammed into the headquarters of a Serbian special forces unit in
Belgrade _ apparently the closest strike to the capital's center so
far, Bacon said. Coming days could see direct air assault on such
key installations as the Yugoslav Interior Ministry, home of
Milosevic's police force, allied sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Improving weather over the Balkans offered NATO the hope of more
sustained bombing by day and night.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, supreme allied commander in Europe,
confirmed that NATO political leaders had given him ``expanded
authority'' and said he would be looking at ``a larger array of
possible targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark refused to detail which sites had been newly opened to
NATO military planners, but said, ``We're going to take every
action that's available within our means and capabilities to bring
home the tragedy of his policy to President Milosevic and his
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing that almost no target in Yugoslavia is off limits,
alliance spokesman Jamie Shea said: ``It's clear that no facility,
no unit, which is currently being used to plan, conceive, direct or
carry out the Yugoslav campaign against the Kosovars, is going to
be a sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going away,'' British Defense Secretary George
Robertson told the House of Commons late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart said the mission will
not be defined by the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no firm timetable for this,'' Lockhart said. ``This is
going to move forward and either President Milosevic is going to
change his calculation or we are going to continually and
systematically hit his military and deprive him of the ability to
impose his will,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance air commander David Wilby said that the alliance's
``week of hard work'' had taken its toll on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that he is running short of fuel,'' Wilby said at NATO
headquarters. ``We are now starting to hit him very hard on the
ground. We've hit him in his command and control facilities. You
will start to see the resolve starting to crack very quickly. I
believe we've accomplished one hell of a lot in this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilby also said Milosevic's air power ``is almost nonexistent
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees continued to flood out of Kosovo, although Shea said
the flow ``slowed somewhat'' because Yugoslav border guards
sporadically closed the border.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton authorized $50 million from an emergency
account and the Department of Defense to aid Kosovar refugees who
have moved into Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said half of the money would be given to the
U.N. High Commission for Refugees and the remainder would finance
direct food and shelter assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Agency for International Development sent a
seven-member disaster assistance team to Albania, which has been
flooded with refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin said most refugees
leaving Kosovo are women and children, ``and we are gravely
concerned by the whereabouts and fate of the missing men.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least two Kosovar Albanian leaders reported to have been
executed by Serbs are alive, U.S. diplomats said. NATO had reported
the killing of Fehmi Agani, a delegate to recent peace talks in
France, and Baton Haxhiu, a newspaper editor.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said ethnic Albanians still in Kosovo ``are in a truly
precarious position.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Bacon said there was no feasible way to
attempt to aid ethnic Albanians still in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to do it would be through airdrops and I think it
is not a very hospitable area through which to fly airdrops at this
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said reports were increasing about Kosovars being stripped
of records, what the spokesman has called ``identity elimination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yugoslav forces, so we are learning, are destroying the
archives of the Kosovar people,'' Shea said. ``Property deeds,
marriage licenses, birth certificates, financial and other records,
public records are being systematically destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after a Russian mission to Belgrade failed to produce a
breakthrough in the international standoff, NATO leaders were faced
with a Kremlin plan to send a group of ships in the Mediterranean
Sea soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are obviously concerned by the signal such a large
deployment might send to Belgrade and other countries in the
region,`` State Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that although the Russian foreign ministry ``has made
it quite clear that Russia does not intend to become entangled in
the conflict in the Balkans ... the deployments of these ships we
don't see as a particularly helpful gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the Clinton administration ``is concerned the
development will encourage Milosevic to hold out. And that concern
has been communicated to the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
