<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Cnet Reporter Wins First Amendment Victory in
Microsoft  Dispute 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Cnet reporter Dan Goodin earned some respect for the online press
last week, winning a First Amendment victory in a dispute with
Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft wanted Goodin to name his sources after he broke a
story last fall about Sun Microsystems' lawsuit against the
software giant.
</P>
<P>
   But now a federal magistrate has quashed Microsoft's subpoena,
and the company doesn't seem likely to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Goodin, 34, who previously worked at the San Francisco legal
newspaper the Recorder, had somehow gotten his hands on Microsoft
memos that had been placed under seal in the case. The suit accused
Microsoft of trying to pollute and co-opt Sun's Java programming
language.
</P>
<P>
   His story, ``Microsoft's Holy War Against Java,'' ran on Cnet's
 &LR; www.news.com &LR;  on September 23. It quoted an internal Microsoft
e-mail in which Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates said Sun's Java
``scares the hell out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   On October 6, ``at 7:30 a.m., as I was eating my Raisin Bran,
there was a knock at my door,'' Goodin recalls. ``It was a process
server and he handed me a subpoena.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft wanted its documents back, and it wanted to find out
who violated the court order sealing the documents. In other words:
It wanted Goodin's sources.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sort of request that usually sends journalists
packing for a stint behind bars as they defend their sources' right
to remain anonymous. And while no one relishes any time in the
clink, it is the sort of principled stand that can earn a
relatively young news organization like Cnet a mountain of free
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   While Goodin said his lawyers told him a stay behind bars was
highly unlikely, Goodin noted that ``the unique marketing
opportunities that Microsoft afforded us by subpoenaing me has not
been lost on me or my editors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goodin was spared from doing time in the slammer last week
when U.S. District Court Magistrate Patricia Trumbull of San Jose
ruled that Goodin could have obtained the documents from any number
of sources without necessarily violating the court's seal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The documents at issue were distributed to numerous
individuals within Microsoft,'' Trumbull wrote. She noted that some
of the same documents were provided to the U.S. Department of
Justice for its antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, she said, she couldn't force Goodin to squeal on his
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet spokeswoman Karen Wood said Cnet's victory boosts the
fledgling online news industry. ``Online news organizations are to
be taken seriously,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Tom Pilla said the company was not singling
out Cnet but merely saw it as a ``clear case that the seal was
broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Smillie, director of the News Research Group, a New York
organization that studies media and the Internet, said ``most
likely, Microsoft was sending a message'' to employees and business
partners that if they leak its confidential documents, they will be
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft hasn't decided whether it will appeal the decision,
but Pilla said, ``We obviously respect the court's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   And there wouldn't be much point if Microsoft did appeal: The
documents in question are now unsealed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW MEDIA MOGULS: &LR;  Two titans of technology, the gray-bearded
eminence George Lucas and the pink-cheeked entrepreneur Halsey
Minor, are competing for leases on a prime chunk of Presidio
property.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the former Letterman Hospital site, 23 acres of
grassy bay views in the country's largest urban national park.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, &UR;  &LR; 54, the pioneering filmmaker, wants to move 1,500 of his
employees scattered throughout Marin County into a new campus that
would serve as a center for digital filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Minor, 34, the impresario who founded Cnet only five years ago,
wants to consolidate his offices _ now clustered in various
buildings below Telegraph Hill _ as part of the Shorenstein Group's
broader commercial proposal for the Presidio site.
</P>
<P>
   Two other groups are finalists for the land, but Cnet and
Lucasfilm hope the glamour of the digital future will give them an
edge.
</P>
<P>
   The two competitors put together vastly different videotapes to
impress the Presidio Trust members.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lucasfilm video, violins played as aerial shots lingered
lovingly on the buildings, vineyards and streams at Lucas's
splendid Skywalker Ranch, in bucolic West Marin. Film clips showed
scenes from ``Star Wars'' and glimpses of Oscar statuettes.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet's video, on the other hand, reflected the fast-pace of the
Internet, with quick cuts, pulsing music and short sound bites from
Cnet employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Presidio Trust Board of Directors will pick a finalist in
May _ right around the time the new ``Star Wars'' movie comes out.
Good luck, Halsey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WELL, WELL, WELL:  &LR; A pair of geezers in their respected fields,
the 111-year-old Press Club of San Francisco and the WELL, which at
14 years is about the same age as the Press Club in Internet years,
combined forces last week to discuss a question with
up-to-the-minute relevance: ``How is the Internet changing
journalism?''
</P>
<P>
   Panelist Elizabeth Weise, a technology writer for USA Today,
noted that the Web has created a need for ``a tremendous number of
reporters, and not all are from as rigorous a background as I'm
used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Rosenberg, senior editor of the online magazine Salon,
noted that readers keep Web journalists honest by catching their
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg, who used to work at the Examiner, said online readers
are far more likely than readers of print publications to dash off
an e-mail ridiculing a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd better get it right,'' he said, ``because people are
going to know.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE THERE'S WILL: &LR;  A company doesn't usually bring members of
its board of directors on dog-and-pony shows to demonstrate its
product.
</P>
<P>
   But since Replay Networks added William R. Hearst III to its
board last week, the company knew it had a marquee name that might
appeal to journalists jaded by the same old product pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, 49, the former publisher of the San Francisco Examiner,
is now a partner at the Silicon Valley venture capital firm of
Kleiner Perkins Caulfield and Byers.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst accompanied Replay marketeers on a press tour last week,
demonstrating the company's device _ a newfangled video cassette
recorder _ and touting Kleiner Perkins' new $8 million investment
in Replay.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst sits on several other boards, including Internet firms
Preview Travel, AtHome Corp. and SpringStreet.
</P>
<P>
   Do these high-tech endeavors mean Hearst has forsaken his
print-media roots?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a believer that one technology pushes another out of
business,'' he said. ``If that's true, the invention of television
should have pushed radio out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The San Francisco Chronicle.
Send buzz, dirt, tips and comments to fostd(AT SIGN)sfgate.com,
call (415) 777-6004 or fax (415) 543-2482. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
