<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHILDREN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSTEPS OF YOUTH WON'T HAUNT BUSH CANDIDACY, BENNETT SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Former U.S. Education Secretary and drug czar
William Bennett said Wednesday that missteps Gov. George W. Bush
may have made during his ``irresponsible youth'' should not haunt
Bush as he seeks the Republican presidential nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish have a saying: The merry-hearted boys make the best
men,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young and male, some of us in college, some of us in high
school, did things we're not particularly happy about or proud of
later, including myself,'' Bennett said. ``That doesn't concern the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said that in the aftermath of the White House scandals,
voters want a mature president ``whose words and actions they can
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and Bush were the key speakers to a conference of 700
people on how to teach young people family values, clean living,
moral ethics and abstinence from sex until marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the conference that he wants to ``teach young people
(that) the rewards of abstinence far outweigh the risks of sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said teen pregnancy and sexually transmitted diseases make
this an important lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children must know that abstinence is not just saying no
to sex, but saying yes to a happier and healthier life,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said he first met Bush in 1989, shortly after Bush's
father had become president and named Bennett the head of the
Office of Drug Control Policy. Bennett said George W. Bush
introduced himself and noted Bennett's drug-fighting role.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Kick butt.' I think that was the first public
articulation of what has become known as compassionate
conservatism,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett told the conference that President Clinton has set a bad
moral example for the nation's youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got children here. Somebody said earlier in the first
presentation, children don't think oral sex is sex. Duh. Who's
telling them that?'' Bennett asked. ``There have got to be some
lines you just cannot cross.''
</P>
<P>
   The Governor's Conference on Right Choices for Youth, which drew
professionals who work with young people, cost $75,000 to $80,000,
said Dr. Joe S. McIlhaney of Austin, president of The Medical
Institute for Sexual Health, a private organization based in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   McIlhaney, a well-known leader in the movement for abstinence
until marriage, helped the governor's office, the Texas Education
Agency and the Department of Health in organizing the event.
</P>
<P>
   The program was financed by five foundations, Texas Instruments
Inc., Houston physician John P. McGovern and the Governor's
Business Council, which is a private organization of business
leaders across the state.
</P>
<P>
   An oft-repeated theme was that children stray into early sex,
alcohol, tobacco and drug use, gangs and violence when their
parents and other adults send conflicting signals to them about
such behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
