<HEADER>
A1677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     03-31 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A MATURE EWING STILL IS A MIRAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is an impression _ and we all know how
deceiving impressions can be _ but there is a thought that Patrick
Ewing grew up Tuesday night. Some reporters used just that kind of
language in commenting on it.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't mean that Ewing grew physically. For he stands seven
feet tall. Nor did they mean chronologically, in terms of the
physical as well as the basketball. Patrick Ewing is 36, after all,
and is in his 14th season as a professional basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to his growing up had to do with his perceived
ability to place the good of the team above the purely
self-engrossed. And the best that can be said of this is that Ewing
will be in the lineup Thursday night when the Knicks play yet
another tough team, the Cleveland Cavaliers, who, like Indiana on
Tuesday, are trying not to do the Knicks any favors.
</P>
<P>
   But to me, Ewing was on the verge of seeing the Cleveland game
from elsewhere. Against the Pacers in Madison Square Garden, he
went for a rebound and knocked Jalen Rose of Indiana to the floor.
This is fairly routine in the NBA and it is also fairly routine
that Rose might retaliate in some way.
</P>
<P>
   So he did. As Ewing trotted over and past him, Rose tripped him.
Ewing stumbled; Rose rose, and Ewing got to his feet and went after
Rose, as though to throttle him.
</P>
<P>
   For the thousands watching in the stands and even more viewing
on television, this was old hat. It was obvious that Ewing was
going to fight Rose and then they'd both be thrown out of the game
and be suspended for one or more games. So the fans were screaming,
to their neighbors in the stands or their neighbors on the third
floor, ``Patrick, don't! Patrick, don't.''
</P>
<P>
   He has done this numerous times, the most hurtful being when a
brawl broke out on the court during a Miami playoff and he left the
bench even though he was reminded at that moment by a teammate that
the rules state he would be suspended if he did so.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are struggling to secure a playoff spot. They can ill
afford to lose any of their valuable players _ Ewing being among
the most valuable _ for one game or more, or even for a part of a
game.
</P>
<P>
   As Ewing came closer to Rose, obviously looking for trouble,
Rose backpedaled with hands and arms in a kind of rope-a-dope
posture, looking for an opening to the bigger Ewing, or an exit.
</P>
<P>
   And then the referee, Dick Bavetta, jumped between them and
received an accidental whack on the nose from the defensive Rose.
And now here came Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, about a foot shorter
than the pugilists on the court, grabbing and yanking at Ewing's
jersey as if it had just been stolen from his shop.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing still apparently wanted a piece of Rose and struggled to
get free, but soon the whole thing was over. Rose was ejected and
Ewing, miraculously, was allowed to continue play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to smack him,'' said Ewing after the game, ``but.
...'' Some have interpreted this as Ewing growing up, that he
backed off. To me, he lost his professional cool and simply
couldn't reach Rose.
</P>
<P>
   If Ewing had truly grown up, he would have shaken the trip off
and then beaten the other team's brains out on the court.
</P>
<P>
   He did return to play superbly in the Knicks' one-point triumph.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ewing had truly grown up, he would follow the way Reggie
Miller and _ this is difficult to write _ Dennis Rodman react to
physical play. They laugh it off and walk away. And then try to
beat the other team's brains out in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Self-absorbed behavior has done in the Knicks on too many
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears it won't end, not with Ewing and not with Latrell
Sprewell, in his own fashion.
</P>
<P>
   While Sprewell has been an exciting and increasingly effective
player with the Knicks, it is obvious that he is not looking to be
team-oriented. After his suspension from basketball for choking his
previous coach, and before the team signed him, the Knicks, with
Van Gundy, had long conversations with Sprewell last summer about
fitting in with the team.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd do whatever it takes to win. Now he is grousing
about being a sixth man. The coach says that NBA players often
complain, but, wisely, he says he won't change what he feels is
best for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Championship teams invariably have one player who leads on the
court. Ewing is the leader on the court. Sprewell is developing in
that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, however, has demonstrated the selfless vision to earn
the coveted rings. Knick fans, sadly, may just be waiting in vain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
