<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CBS-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      03-31 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATHER INTERVIEWS CLINTON ON `60 MINUTES II'
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON-IMPEACH) 
(rk) 
 By   LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a coup for CBS' &UR;  &LR; fledgling news magazine program ``60 Minutes
II,'' President Clinton gave his first exclusive interview in
nearly 15 months Wednesday to Dan Rather of CBS News, the new
program's senior correspondent, as well as the anchor of the ``CBS
Evening News.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton answered questions about the war in Yugoslavia and about
the impeachment scandal, which was just getting under way the last
time he gave a one-on-one interview, to Jim Lehrer of ``The
NewsHour'' on PBS, on Jan. 21, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rather's interview was part of a new policy of openness toward
the press by the administration, a White House press aide said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rather interviewed Clinton for an hour at the White House
Wednesday afternoon, then prepared reports for the ``CBS Evening
News,'' at 6:30 p.m., and two segments for the hourlong,
three-segment program ``60 Minutes II,'' which was broadcast at 9
p.m. last night.
</P>
<P>
   By creating two segments, the program's producers could separate
questions about the war in Yugoslavia and questions about the
Monica Lewinsky matter, a topic that might seem trivial in
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very strong stating his case'' about the war, Rather
said by telephone Wednesday after the interview, and ``very
forthcoming'' in answering questions about the impeachment crisis
of the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was opposed to sending American ground troops to
Kosovo because of ``the prospect of never being able to get them
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the impeachment crisis, he said: ``I do not regard
this impeachment vote as some great badge of shame. I do not.
Because, I do not believe it was warranted, and I don't think it
was right.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he did not think of resigning: ``I wouldn't do
that to the Constitution,'' Clinton said. ``I wouldn't do that to
the presidency. I wouldn't do that to the history of this country.
I would never have legitimized what I believe is horribly wrong
with what has occurred here over the last four or five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather is one of four regular correspondents for ``60 Minutes
II,'' which was added to the network's prime-time schedule in
mid-January in the hope that it would attract large audiences, as
the original ``60 Minutes'' does on Sunday evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night was the program's 10th appearance, and it has
posted solid ratings, averaging a 9.6 (each rating point equaling
994,000 homes) and a 15 share (the percentage of sets in use tuned
to that program).
</P>
<P>
   Although some producers from rival networks downplayed the
exclusive, saying that the president was unlikely to make
revelations about either the war or the impeachment process, others
gave CBS News credit.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Bettag, the executive producer of ABC News' ``Nightline''
program, said: ``We're all competitors and can pooh-pooh it, but
when someone gets the first one-on-one interview with the president
after a very long time, that's a great `get,' and the rest of us
would have loved to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswomen for ABC News and NBC News said that their news
divisions had submitted requests for interviews with Clinton in
recent months. Wednesday, NBC News' Washington bureau was told by a
White House spokesman that it was ``CBS' turn in the rotation,'' an
NBC spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS had pressed hard for the interview as a way to help its new
program, ``60 Minutes II.'' Clinton has done similar interviews in
the past, appearing with NBC's Tom Brokaw for the July 1996,
kickoff of MSNBC, the cable channel started by Microsoft and NBC
News, and with NBC's Tim Russert of ``Meet the Press,'' in honor of
that program's 50th anniversary in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS had little time to turn the interview to promotional
advantage. Rather learned only the night before that he had the
interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
