<SLUG> BC-MITSUBISHI-CUTBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITSUBISHI ELECTRIC TO CUT GLOBAL WORK FORCE BY 10 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Mitsubishi Electric Corp., one of Japan's big,
diversified electronics makers, announced a broad overhaul
Wednesday that will reduce its global work force by 14,500, or 10
percent, over the next three years to help increase profit. More
than half the job cuts will be in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was one more hint that the economic recovery
the Japanese government has promised in the fiscal year that begins
Thursday may not come as early as officials hope. There is some
fear that an unprecedented wave of corporate restructuring, which
is increasing unemployment and causing financial insecurity among
consumers, could delay a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate, which hit a postwar high in February, is
not going to reverse as long as companies such as Mitsubishi
Electric keep making efforts to pare their labor forces.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Electric was only the latest company to announce
cutbacks. Besides its plan to reduce the work force of 146,000
people, it intends to reduce capital investment by 20 percent. The
company's own heavy industrial machinery business has suffered
mightily as other Japanese companies have cut their own spending.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, all of the pain these corporations
are currently willing to suffer could be expected to lead to
productivity gains and better profitability, creating jobs and
high-return investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan is also grappling with deflation, which means that as
fast as corporations are cutting jobs, expenses and investment,
their revenue growth is falling. Corporate revenue fell 7.1 percent
in the fourth quarter of 1998, according to the Finance Ministry; 4
to 5 points of that can be accounted for by a slump in wholesale
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, restructuring is gaining pace, and it sounds
impressive _ until you look at deflation,'' said Andrew Shipley, an
economist with Schroders Japan Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Shipley said companies would have to reduce compensation by 6
percent to 8 percent to make up for the revenue erosion that
deflation is causing. Thus far, however, wages have declined 2
percent year on year, and 1 percent of the work force has lost
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The moves that corporations are making to revamp their
businesses are considered aggressive by Japanese standards.
Mitsubishi Electric, which is expected to report a loss of roughly
90 billion yen, or about $750 million, in the fiscal year that
ended Wednesday, said that by March 2002 it will have eliminated
8,400 jobs in Japan and 6,100 abroad. More than 2,000 of these have
already been cut, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi already has reduced its American operations, closing
a semiconductor factory, abandoning sales of analog television sets
and subcontracting the production of cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   It has stopped producing computers and TV sets in Britain and
eliminated its semiconductor assembly and testing in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Electric also said it would reduce the number of its
consolidated subsidiaries to 140 from 180 by March 2001. The
winnowing process is aimed at unprofitable lines of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have asked the company to jettison its consumer
electronics business, and some would like to see it leave auto
parts manufacturing. The company's money-losing semiconductor
manufacturing business is known for quality technology but cannot
compete with larger rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Electric said Wednesday that it planned to restore
profitability to its semiconductor operations in two years by
focusing on producing more customized chips.
</P>
<P>
   The company projected annual sales of 4 trillion yen by March
2002, compared with 3.7 trillion yen in the fiscal year that is
ending.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi, which is also a big maker of military electronics,
said it hoped to become the world's largest producer of satellites
and satellite equipment, as well as a leading seller of
communications infrastructure technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
