<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-ELECT-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND EUROPE AT IMPASSE ON NEW WORLD TRADE CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A month before the head of the World Trade Organization
is to leave his post, the search for a successor reached a
stalemate Wednesday over the inability of the 134 members to decide
between the two finalists.
</P>
<P>
   After a yearlong search, the European Union and the United
States appeared to be deadlocked over the choice between Suphachai
Panichpakdi, the Thai commerce minister, and Michael Moore, a
former prime minister of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Mchumo, the Tanzanian representative, who leads the search
committee, said the difficulties faced by the two candidates ``are
so serious that neither of them can enjoy consensus from the
membership to enable them to be elected as the next director
general.'' He made the statement to a gathering of trade
negotiators Wednesday night, the deadline the organization had
imposed for itself to choose a new director.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the trade organization runs its day-to-day affairs
and helps settle contentious disputes among members. It is unclear
what the group will do if it has not selected a director general by
April 30, when the term of Renato Ruggiero of Italy, the current
chief, expires.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock comes as the United States and the European Union
are fighting over a number of contentious trade disputes,
concerning, most notably, banana imports and resulting American
sanctions, hormone-treated beef and aircraft noise.
</P>
<P>
   Mchumo, describing the trade group's failure to meet its
deadline as ``unfortunate and disappointing,'' also alluded to
complaints that certain nations, including the United States, were
impeding the selection process. ``It is clearly very unhealthy for
this process to drag on because such delay breeds rumors,
suspicions and even puts personal friendships at stake,'' he told
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's caretaker trade commissioner, Sir Leon
Brittan, expressed his grievances in a letter to Mchumo, which was
later faxed to journalists, accusing ``unnamed countries'' of
threatening to veto a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anonymous vetoes are plainly inconsistent with the kind of
transparency within the WTO that we have been seeking,'' Brittan
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Under its rules, the trade organization chooses a director
general by consensus, which has generally been accepted to mean
there is no vote and no veto allowed. The idea is that every
nation, regardless of size, gets an equal say and the trading
giants cannot tip the balance.
</P>
<P>
   However, the only time the process has been used before _ in
selecting Ruggiero four years ago _ it took nine months and was
plagued with delays, accusations and recriminations. The United
States was accused of delaying the selection of Ruggiero, a former
Italian trade minister, because of concerns that his background and
approach were too bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   European officials have asserted that once again, the Americans
are holding up the selection and have been working behind the
scenes to insure that Moore wins. The United States has never
publicly stated a preference.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the European Union's 15 countries back Suphachai.
However, several countries, including France, appear to have
shifted allegiances back and forth between the two candidates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rita Hayes, the U.S. delegate to the trade organization, called
Brittan's letter ``very difficult,'' but refused to comment further
on its contents.
</P>
<P>
   Although Moore insisted in a radio interview earlier this week
that the contest for the post did not reflect a split between
industrial and developing nations, interviews with trade diplomats
say that is an element. The United States and other industrial
nations support labor standards that require developing countries
to insure minimum levels for wages and working conditions.
Developing countries generally oppose such standards, arguing that
they would raise the cost of their exports and make them less
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Some trade envoys say the United States does not think its best
interests would be served by Suphachai, 52, who is an economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an academic, he's intellectual,'' said a European trade
official, who insisted on anonymity, adding that the Americans
``don't see having a cozy relationship with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, this official said, ``talks the language labor likes to
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans say he can also talk to Congress, which is
suspicious of the WTO,'' the official noted.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's envoy, Munir Akram, said Moore, 50, a former union
activist, ``is more likely to push for labor standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has led an effort by developing countries to insure
that one of their leaders becomes the next director general.
</P>
<P>
   Both Moore and Suphachai visited the trade organization's
headquarters here for last-minute lobbying. Thai officials have won
support not only from Asian and many European nations, but from
Latin American and Caribbean countries as well.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates are to meet again next week to try to choose between
the two men. Countries backing Suphachai, envoys said, have
threatened to block Moore if Suphachai's candidacy is derailed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
