<SLUG> BC-POTTER-BESTELLER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG WIZARD IS BEST SELLER AND COPYRIGHT CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a junior wizard, 11-year-old Harry Potter has stirred up
quite a steaming caldron of magic _ one that has brought him fame,
glory and a tiff over international copyright laws.
</P>
<P>
   As if on a loopy ride on his Nimbus 2000 broom, Potter has
soared into the popular imagination, with the first volume of his
adventures even outselling adult titles by the likes of Tom Wolfe
in the United States. Written by a first-time author, J.K. Rowling,
and originally published in Britain, ``Harry Potter and the
Sorcerer's Stone'' has reached a level of best-sellerdom never
before achieved by a children's novel in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The unrequited desire for stories about the young wizard is so
keen that the books have become the literary equivalent of Furby
stuffed animals. Demand is so high, in fact, that knobby-kneed
Harry Potter and his fellow students from the Hogwarts School of
Witchcraft and Wizardry are presenting an Internet challenge to
traditional copyrights regulating trade in the works of the mind.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rowling's much-awaited sequel, ``Harry Potter and the
Chamber of Secrets,'' has not yet been published in the United
States. But devoted fans are buying British versions that are
available through online bookstores like Amazon.com's British
subsidiary _ a development that is alarming Scholastic Press, the
American publisher that paid for the right to publish the book here
in September.
</P>
<P>
   Longstanding concepts of territorial publishing rights are
increasingly challenged in the expanding world of electronic
commerce in literature. Computer users can ignore global borders as
easily as Harry Potter and his friends use the magical compound
floo powder to transport themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When a book published in London is purchased from a computer
attached to a desk in New York, is the sale taking place in Britain
or the United States? The answers are evolving.
</P>
<P>
   `` I think it could very well lead to a test case,'' said
Christopher Little, Ms. Rowling's literary agent in London, who
protested to Amazon.com- after discovering that copies of the
British version of her second book were steadily leaking to the
United States. Little said his complaints so far had been futile,
and he accused Amazon of ``blatantly disregarding territorial
rights and therefore acting illegally.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the sequel in the United States, where it is still
months away from publication, is such that more than 80 readers
posted effusive reviews on Amazon's U.S. Web site, offering simple
instructions for ordering the foreign version from the company's
British site at a cost of less than 14 pounds, or about $23.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Murdoch, the managing director of Amazon's British
subsidiary in England, said that usually the situation was
reversed: British publishers must contend with American books
seeping into their market through online sales. In such cases, he
said, if a British publisher provides documentation about a British
version, the American version is removed from the database.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch said he did not know whether a similar policy existed
for American publishers and referred questions to Amazon's top
executives in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Amazon's founder and chief executive, Jeff Bezos,
referred questions to Murdoch. Bezos did say though that he
considered purchases of the British version ``no different than if
you go to London on a vacation and pick up a book and take it home
in your suitcase.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do anything that challenges the establishment, you're
going to annoy some people,'' Bezos added.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this messy global debate about territorial
rights is the author, Joanne Rowling, a 33-year-old former French
teacher who has been described so often as a Cinderella who went
from the dole to the best-seller list that she jokes that the words
``penniless and divorced single mother'' should be tattooed on her
forehead.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of Harry Potter came to her while she was on a train
to London in 1990. ``It was the most incredible feeling,'' said Ms.
Rowling, who plans to write a total of seven volumes about the
world of Harry Potter. ``I was halfway through a novel for adults
at the time, and out of nowhere, it just fell from above. Harry
came fully formed. Really, it was weird. Basically, the idea was
for a boy to make weird stuff happen all his life and never know
why.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she wrote much of the first manuscript in an Edinburgh
cafe called Nicholson's, which allowed her to scribble away at a
table for the price of a cup of coffee while her infant daughter
napped beside her. Ms. Rowling, who is divorced, said she spent
nearly nine months on public assistance in 1993 before finding a
job as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter's fantasy world ``seemed like my private internal
world in which I could escape, and it remained quite inviolate,''
Ms. Rowling recalled. In that imaginary realm, Harry has his share
of struggles too. An orphaned son of Hogwart wizards, he sleeps in
a cupboard in the home of odious relatives (of the nonwizard Muggle
persuasion) until he enrolls at the Hogwarts School.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There, equipped with a holly-and-phoenix-feather wand, he
studies potion mixing and herbology and trains on his broomstick to
play quidditch, a sky-high form of basketball with six hoops and
balls.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's world has struck a chord with both children and adults:
the first book in the series has lingered in the upper reaches of
the New York Times best-seller list for 14 weeks and ranked No. 9
in the hardcover fiction category on Sunday. The closest any other
children's novel has come to that long a stay was the three weeks
E.B. White's ``Charlotte's Web'' spent on the list in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the word `miracle' mean anything to you?'' said Nancy
Pines, a publisher of children's books at Simon &AMP; Schuster's Pocket
Books. ``What we're talking about here is a foreign import with no
television show, no movie and no celebrity. It's a noisy world, and
it's hard to get attention for a children's book.''
</P>
<P>
   To entice adults in Britain, the book's British publisher,
Bloomsbury, printed a second edition with a more sophisticated
cover so grown-ups could read it in public without embarrassment.
But many adults here are not shy about expressing enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   At the Morton household in Elk Grove Village, Ill., a suburb of
Chicago, both Connie Morton, 43, and her 12-year-old daughter,
Jessica, so loved the characters that they ordered the second
volume directly from Bloomsbury. ``Since then we found out that
Amazon has a United Kingdom Web site, and next time we'll order
from them,'' said Mrs. Morton, a homemaker, adding that her
daughter had read both books a total of 17 times.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lord, a 44-year-old lawyer from Boise, Idaho, purchased
the second book from Amazon's British site. ``Harry Potter carries
a sense of innocence in a hostile world,'' said Lord, who posted a
positive review of the book on Amazon and received about a dozen
e-mail messages seeking to know how he got the copy. ``Harry is a
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   This steady stream of orders to Britain worries executives at
Scholastic Press in New York, who know that it's possible to order
a British copy and receive delivery in less than eight days.
</P>
<P>
   But the Amazon view is that publishing executives have to face
certain facts. ``The Internet is changing the way the world shops
and the way the world works,'' said Bill Curry, a spokesman for
Amazon. ``And it's shaking up the old order and raising concerns
and issues as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic is now trying to respond to increasing demand by
moving up the publication of the second Harry Potter volume to June
and the third book to October. In the meantime they say that they
are working to resolve the situation with Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now feel it's substantial numbers,'' said Michael Jacobs,
Scholastic's senior vice president for trade, who noted that he had
received calls from American booksellers complaining about lost
sales. ``This is the little book that could. And now some
booksellers are starting to feel that if they can't satisfy
customers they're going to lose customers, who will get used to
going to Amazon.''
</P>
<P>
   So far Scholastic has been diplomatic in its dispute with
Amazon. But it is hashing out the issue with its lawyers, and the
Association of American Publishers also met with its lawyers last
week and concluded that it might have to take action by seeking new
copyright legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Current U.S. copyright law does not provide firm answers
addressing Internet sales that cross borders. The law bars
importing a copyrighted book without permission but allows an
individual to buy one copy if it is for private use and not for
distribution. But what happens if more than one book is ordered, or
a bookseller buys copies to resell here? How can the law be
enforced? The answers are evolving.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Scholastic intended to sue, Jacobs said he could not
comment. He vowed, though, that the company would protect its
territorial rights. He could not explain precisely how that could
be done short of a lawsuit. Or dragon-blood potions. Or the Draught
of Living Death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to give up,'' he said, then brightened for a
brief moment. ``We could turn them into Muggles?''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
