<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1693 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-1stLD-     03-31 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THREE U.S. SOLDIERS MISSING IN MACEDONIA AFTER REPORTED CLASH
 &HT;    EDS: New details on missing soldiers; adds 4th and 5th grafs for
context
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. combat troops on the ground and in Blackhawk
helicopters were conducting a massive search Wednesday night after
three American soldiers came under fire and went missing along
Macedonia's mountainous border with Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by British and other NATO search and rescue teams, more
than 80 American troops were combing the area late Wednesday,
Pentagon officials said, hours after the missing soldiers' last
radio contact with U.S. forces in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Details were sketchy, but fears that the three might have been
abducted by Serb forces raised tensions over a NATO Balkans mission
that is escalating by the day.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark has asked to add 75
carrier-based warplanes to the U.S. and allied forces attacking
Serbs across Yugoslavia, the Pentagon said Wednesday, as U.S.
officials sharply rebuked Russia for its plan to send spy ships to
the region.
</P>
<P>
   While those two developments were not specifically linked, they
pointed to the rising stakes in a NATO mission that drew fire on
the ground on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said three Army troops traveling in a Humvee
military vehicle were ambushed, shot at and surrounded by gunmen
shortly after 2:30 p.m. local time (7:30 a.m. EST).
</P>
<P>
   The attack came shortly after the troops split off from two
other Humvees conducting what the Pentagon called ``a routine
reconnaissance patrol'' near the town of Kumanovo. The town
straddles a major road leading from the Macedonian capital of
Skopje into the embattled Serb province of Kosovo, site of
extensive Serb military and paramilitary operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans radioed to a nearby unit that they had come under
fire and were surrounded, the Pentagon said, and then the group
lost radio contact.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon would not release the names of the troops as of
late Wednesday. But officials said the families of the missing
soldiers had been contacted.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was notified early Wednesday afternoon, but
made no public comment.
</P>
<P>
   Joining in the search were British troops and helicopters, other
NATO forces, and Macedonian police, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. troops are attached to the First Infantry Division
based in Wurzburg, Germany. The soldiers have been stationed in
Macedonia supporting a NATO mission there that would make up the
vanguard of a proposed peacekeeping force for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has stepped up its patrols along the Macedonia-Kosovo
border since the alliance launched air strikes March 24 against
Serb forces attacking ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. NATO officials
have also taken steps to strengthen the security of patrols near
the border, out of concern that Serb commandos might cross over in
the rugged terrain and try to engage NATO forces in retaliation
against the allied air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   An eighth day of NATO attacks struck more deeply than ever into
Yugoslavia and across the province of Kosovo on Wednesday, as
NATO's political arm formally agreed to target military and
government facilities in downtown Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   NATO struck Serb special forces headquarters near the capital
and hit tanks and troops inside Kosovo. At the same time, Serb
forces continued to shell civilians, burn villages and terrorize
entire communities, extending a rampage aimed at expelling ethnic
Albanians from the tiny Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   With supersonic B-1 heavy bombers set to join in the raids on
Thursday, NATO officials insisted that the air strikes were
beginning to bite into the bone of Serb offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Harried from the skies for three straight days, at least one
Serb battle group had been forced to withdraw from attacks in
Kosovo, NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving, I'd say almost daily, to a broader set of
targets,'' said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon. ``We'll attack
all the facilities needed to support, fuel and feed the forces, and
we will, as rapidly as possible, choke them off.''
</P>
<P>
   As Serbs continued to force thousands of ethnic Albanians out of
Kosovo, President Clinton ordered $50 million in emergency aid as
part of a broader NATO effort to get desperately needed tents, food
and medicine to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to give a speech on the Kosovo crisis on
Thursday at the Norfolk Naval Station in Virginia, adjacent to the
home port of the USS Theodore Roosevelt aircraft carrier. He's
expected to speak while standing alongside an F-14 Tomcat and F/A18
Hornet, the Navy's top warplanes which are the tip of the spear of
the Roosevelt's firepower.
</P>
<P>
   The Roosevelt is steaming across the Atlantic and due to arrive
in the Mediterranean Sea by this weekend en route to a scheduled
deployment in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, the supreme commander of allied forces in Europe, has
asked the Pentagon to add the carrier and its 75 Tomcats, Hornets
and other warplanes to the NATO mission, Bacon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said no decision had been made on that
request, or on Clark's earlier request for Apache combat
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   The Roosevelt would add extensive firepower to the NATO mission.
It travels with a protective carrier battle group made up of four
warships and an attack submarine, all capable of firing long-range
cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots from the ship have flown combat air patrols over the
Balkans before, in support of peacekeeping operations in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   In echoes of the Cold War, Russia announced plans to dispatch a
group of seven Navy ships, including a high-tech spy vessel, to the
waters off the Balkan coast in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   In a sharp rebuke, the Clinton administration voiced concern
that the move might lend relief to Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic,
president of Yugoslavia. He warned Moscow to hold to its public vow
not to inject the ships into the NATO conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deployments of these ships, we don't see as a particularly
helpful gesture,'' said State Department spokesman James Rubin.
``We are obviously concerned by the signal such a large deployment
might send to Belgrade and other countries in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the Navy's long Cold War experience of having carrier
battle groups tailed by Russian spy ships had taught U.S. sailors
and airmen how to protect their communications and operations from
eavesdropping by the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, the most powerful ally of its Slavic brethren in Serbia,
has opposed the NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The allied military campaign continued apace on Wednesday, with
NATO reporting that the city of Orahovac, in southwestern Kosovo,
was being emptied of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Still unaccounted for as of Wednesday were thousands of ethnic
Albanians reportedly forced by Serbs to march into concentrated
areas near the provincial capital of Pristina and several
surrounding towns.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Serbs were following up forced expulsions by
wiping out public records of the lives of ethnic Albanians driven
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Property deeds, marriage licenses, birth certificates,
financial and other records, public records, are being
systematically destroyed,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told
reporters at alliance headquarters in Brussels. ``This is a kind of
Orwellian scenario of attempting to deprive a people and a culture
of the sense of past and the sense of community on which it
depends.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-03-31-99 2148E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
