WVA-RESORT-CASINO-3, 3-31 -- The entrance to the Greenbriar in
White Sulphur Springs. The owners of the resort, which has long
been a symbol of elegance, want to convert a once-secret bomb
shelter built under the hotel for the use of Congress in the event
of a nuclear war into West Virginia's first casino, for the
exclusive use of the Greenbrier's guests. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) LEWISBERG, W.Va. -- March 31, 1999 --
WVA-RESORT-CASINO-2, 3-31 -- The town of Lewisberg is likely to
benefit if a proposed casino at the nearby Greenbriar is approved.
For the second time this century, the resort is planning to expand.
Almost 90 years ago, Greenbriar's owners built a golf course that
helped turn the stately hotel into one of the nation's best-known
resorts, a favorite of the rich and the famous. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) RUPERT, W.Va. -- March 31, 1999 -- WVA-RESORT-CASINO-1,
3-31 -- Harold Hinkle, a barber in Rupert, says he believes a
proposed casino at the Greenbriar would put more people to work.
``I'm all for it,'' he says. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WINCHESTER, Ky. -- March 31, 1999 -- HEMP-FARMING-2,
3-31 -- Hemp is a look-alike, non-intoxicating cousin of marijuana.
As farmers from Hawaii to North Dakota to Vermont lobby state
legislatures to study hemp's potential and make it legal, they are
opposed by federal officials unwilling to relax drug laws even
symbolically, whether by endorsing marijuana's medical use, or
approving a once-common crop, hemp. (Mark Lyons/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BETHEL, Ky. -- March 31, 1999 -- HEMP-FARMING-1, 3-31 --
Tribby Vice, a tobacco and dairy farmer in Fleming County, sees
hemp as a crop that could save his financially ailing business.
``The equipment we have for tobacco we can take and use for hemp,''
he says. ``We don't have to go out and buy new equipment.'' (Mark
Lyons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SHFAYIM, Israel -- March 31, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS,
3-31 -- Gideon Ezra, center, an aide on Arab affairs to Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, receives an angry welcome and police
protection in Shfayim on Sunday by local Arab residents. The roar
of the crowd's shouting, ``Bibi go home!'' was barely audible in
the tightly guarded City Hall, where Netanyahu was whisked to speak
to a handpicked audience from this Israeli Arab town. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LONDON -- March 31, 1999 -- BP-ARCO, 3-31 -- With the
acquisition of Amoco, Sir John Browne, chief executive of BP Amoco,
cut tens of thousands of jobs and left an organization where there
is almost no layer of middle management and constant pressure to do
better. Now he is poised to do the same with ARCO. (Robin
Laurance/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MORINI BORDER CROSSING, Albania -- March 31, 1999 --
KOSOVO-ALBANIA-4, 3-31 -- Weary ethnic Albanian refugees from Hass
sit in their trailer at the Morini Border Crossing on Wednesday.
Serbian forces are now shelling villages, towns and cities across a
wide swath of Kosovo, driving more than 10,000 more ethnic
Albanians from their homes. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MORINI BORDER CROSSING, Albania -- March 31, 1999 --
KOSOVO-ALBANIA-3, 3-31 -- Distraught ethnic Albanian refugees from
Prizren at the Morini Border Crossing on Wednesday. Serbian forces
are now shelling villages, towns and cities across a wide swath of
Kosovo, driving more than 10,000 more ethnic Albanians from their
homes. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BLACE, Macedonia -- March 31, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA-2,
3-31 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo cross the Albanian
border on foot along railroad tracks Wednesday after getting off a
train from Urusevac. This group of more than 500 refugees - walking
on the tracks because the fields to either side were mined -
reported that many of the men had their identity documents
confiscated by Serb authorities. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BLACE, Macedonia -- March 31, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA-1,
3-31 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo cross the Albanian
border on foot along railroad tracks Wednesday after getting off a
train from Urusevac. This group of more than 500 refugees - walking
on the tracks because the fields to either side were mined -
reported that many of the men had their identity documents
confiscated by Serb authorities. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BANTEAY CHHMAR, Cambodia -- March 31, 1999 --
CAMBODIA-TEMPLE-THEFT-2, 3-31 -- A section of temple wall at the
ruins in Banteay Chhmar shows where a bas relief was drilled off.
Officials say a robbery of the temple, carried out last year, was
organized by military officers using power tools and heavy
equipment. (Seth Mydans/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BANTEAY CHHMAR, Cambodia -- March 31, 1999 --
CAMBODIA-TEMPLE-THEFT-1, 3-31 -- A young Cambodian soldier sitting
in the ruins of the looted temple at Banteay Chhmar. Officials say
the robbery, carried out last year, was organized by military
officers using power tools and heavy equipment. (Seth Mydans/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- March 31, 1999 -- MCPHERSON-PROFILE-2, 3-31
-- Michelle Fairley, Jim Norton and Brendan Coyle, right, in ``The
Weir.'' Conor McPherson's play has already been a hit in Dublin and
London (where it won an Olivier award as best new play). (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- March 31, 1999 -- MCPHERSON-PROFILE-1, 3-31
-- Conor McPherson's play ``The Weir'' opens Thursday night on
Broadway. The play has already been a hit in Dublin and London
(where it won an Olivier award as best new play). (James Estrin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 31, 1999 -- JENKINS-DANCE-REVIEW, 3-31
-- Ellie Klopp on the ground and, from left, Gerald Hiken, Sue
Roginski, Margaret Jenkins and Rebecca Rossen in ``Breathe
Normally'' at The Joyce Theater in Manhattan. At its best, the
production makes for compelling theater, allowing a specific event
to resonate into a more universal meditation on life and death and
on memory's coloring of the past. (Ruby Washington/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 31, 1999 -- GIOVANNI-OPERA-REVIEW, 3-31
-- Stefan Szkafarowsky, left, and Victor Benedetti in New York City
Opera's production of ``Don Giovanni.'' Rolf Langenfass' grim sets
and unattractive costumes undermine the impact of the direction.
The stage is framed by spindly, gray-green leaves and tree
branches, even in the indoor scenes. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 31, 1999 -- BLUES-THEATER-REVIEW, 3-31
-- Gretha Boston and Ron Taylor in ``It Ain't Nothin' but the
Blues'' at the New Victory Theater in the new Times Square. This
rich, evocative, rousing show, with some 50 musical numbers ranging
from African chants and spirituals to Delta and Chicago blues, with
plenty of stops along the dusty roads, river banks, broken country
hearts and juke joints in between, is more than a musical feast.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NORTH CHATHAM, N.Y. -- March 31, 1999 --
CIR-COMPUTER-DOUBTS, 3-31 -- Langdon Winner, a political scientist
at the Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, is also trained as a
social and political theorist. ``As I looked at all kinds of
technological systems, it seemed to me that the stuff of politics
is almost always built into them,'' says Winner, who is known for
his view that technological advances have political implications.
(Alan E. Solomon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LAS VEGAS -- March 31, 1999 -- CIR-MEMORY, 3-31 -- The
IBM Microdrive being demonstrated with a digital camera at a recent
computer electronics show in Las Vegas. The microdrive is garnering
attention from computer industry consultants because of its
engineering and potential uses. Announced last fall, the device is
a mechanical, magnetic hard drive the size of a matchbook and can
hold up to 340 megabytes of data. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- March 31, 1999 -- CIR-GOVERNMENT-EMAIL, 3-31 --
The Boston City Council is trying to block a request from a local
weekly to see all the council's E-mail. James Kelly, the council
president, says he will fight any decision on the part of the State
Attorney General's Office to make him turn over the files. ``I
think I would be committing a major violation of the confidence
that's placed in me if I were to make that available to the
press,'' he says. (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. -- March 31, 1999 -- CIR-NEWBORNS,
3-31 -- A nurse scans the data chips worn by Jacquelyn Carr and her
newborn son, Jaylen. To keep infants from going home with the wrong
parents, more and more hospitals are using technology commonly
associated with department stores. Like a pair of jeans, babies are
scanned when their parents check out, and they are protected from
abduction by sensors they wear that can set off alarms. (Marissa
Roth/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- March 31, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 3-31
-- Vents rely on natural temperature differences within the attic
to move the air. They use no electricity, so they are economical.
In most cases, a few well-positioned vents may be all you need to
keep the air recycling in your attic. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WILMINGTON, Del. -- March 31, 1999 -- DUPONT-DAUGHTER,
3-31 -- Ruth Ellen Lord on the neo-classical stairs of Winterthur,
her childhood home. Winterthur, a 2,400-acre estate in the
Brandywine Valley outside Wilmington, was one of four family homes.
But by her account, Henry du Pont, who died in 1969, might have
been as surprised as the tourists visiting his house to discover
that there were small children who grew up in it. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) EILAT, Israel -- March 31, 1999 -- UNDERWATER-RESTAURANT,
3-31 -- At the Red Sea Star in Israel, dinner is served 20 feet
below as fish eye you from portholes. ``I wanted to create an
interior space that would merge with the sea, where the light and
color and language of shapes would play together in a kind of
Ping-Pong,'' says Ayala Serfaty, the restaurant's designer. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
