<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-NYPD-1STLD-     03-31 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-NYPD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BULLETS OF BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to correct to Wednesday sted Tuesday in lede)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a nation that the Supreme Court believes has achieved
color-blindness, the murder indictments issued Wednesday against
four white police officers in New York tell a very different story.
</P>
<P>
   Race bias has been treated as a theoretical issue by the
justices, but it is a daily, street-level torment for millions of
Americans. At its worst, it is perpetrated not only by neighbors
but by government agents, especially those trained and armed to
protect the citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   The bare facts of the New York case are well known. On Feb. 4,
four plainclothes officers in search of a rapist encountered Amadou
Diallo, 22, in front of his Bronx home. Sensing, they said later,
that Diallo might be reaching for a weapon, the cops blew him away.
Forty-one shots were fired; 19 hit their target. Diallo, a West
African immigrant, had no gun.
</P>
<P>
   Gross police overreaction is certainly involved here, and some
may see no need to stress the racial element. Such a killing would
warrant a murder indictment even if no prejudice were involved.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to imagine that this slaughter would have taken
place if Diallo had been white or the police had been of different
races. And it is impossible to imagine that the response of Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir would have
been so callous and slow. Belatedly, Safir is talking about
assigning more minority officers to the Street Crime Unit.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of continuing race bias in America are evident in
stacks of statistics relating to education, income, health, and
nearly every aspect of life.
</P>
<P>
   But the most dramatic and worrisome examples are those in which
racist actions are carried out by law enforcement personnel _ the
very people designated to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   The Diallo case is extreme, but it is not alone. Anyone who
thinks it is is truly blind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
