</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NORTH CHATHAM, N.Y. -- March 31, 1999 --
CIR-COMPUTER-DOUBTS, 3-31 -- Langdon Winner, a political scientist
at the Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, is also trained as a
social and political theorist. ``As I looked at all kinds of
technological systems, it seemed to me that the stuff of politics
is almost always built into them,'' says Winner, who is known for
his view that technological advances have political implications.
(Alan E. Solomon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LAS VEGAS -- March 31, 1999 -- CIR-MEMORY, 3-31 -- The
IBM Microdrive being demonstrated with a digital camera at a recent
computer electronics show in Las Vegas. The microdrive is garnering
attention from computer industry consultants because of its
engineering and potential uses. Announced last fall, the device is
a mechanical, magnetic hard drive the size of a matchbook and can
hold up to 340 megabytes of data. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- March 31, 1999 -- CIR-GOVERNMENT-EMAIL, 3-31 --
The Boston City Council is trying to block a request from a local
weekly to see all the council's E-mail. James Kelly, the council
president, says he will fight any decision on the part of the State
Attorney General's Office to make him turn over the files. ``I
think I would be committing a major violation of the confidence
that's placed in me if I were to make that available to the
press,'' he says. (Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. -- March 31, 1999 -- CIR-NEWBORNS,
3-31 -- A nurse scans the data chips worn by Jacquelyn Carr and her
newborn son, Jaylen. To keep infants from going home with the wrong
parents, more and more hospitals are using technology commonly
associated with department stores. Like a pair of jeans, babies are
scanned when their parents check out, and they are protected from
abduction by sensors they wear that can set off alarms. (Marissa
Roth/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- March 31, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 3-31
-- Vents rely on natural temperature differences within the attic
to move the air. They use no electricity, so they are economical.
In most cases, a few well-positioned vents may be all you need to
keep the air recycling in your attic. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WILMINGTON, Del. -- March 31, 1999 -- DUPONT-DAUGHTER,
3-31 -- Ruth Ellen Lord on the neo-classical stairs of Winterthur,
her childhood home. Winterthur, a 2,400-acre estate in the
Brandywine Valley outside Wilmington, was one of four family homes.
But by her account, Henry du Pont, who died in 1969, might have
been as surprised as the tourists visiting his house to discover
that there were small children who grew up in it. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
