r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     03-31 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELSON IS GIVING MAVS FANS A GAGGING FEELING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, we know how Latrell Sprewell felt.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we know why Sprewell wanted to take his coach by the throat
and strangle him.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes _ and today's one of those times _ don't you just want
to grab Don Nelson by his big old thick neck and shake him a bit?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing serious, you understand. Just throttle the Mavs'
coach/general manager until his face turns blue and his tongue
sticks out. Nothing a little heavy-duty CPR can't reverse, but
enough to get his attention.
</P>
<P>
   I'd do it, too, I swear, except that Nellie's 6-6 and built like
a bull elk. I wouldn't get physical with him if you paid me Kevin
Brown money.
</P>
<P>
   We love you, Big Don baby, but it's getting harder and harder to
believe that you know what the hell you're doing any more.
</P>
<P>
   Our patience has grown as thin as your sorry, depleted bench.
</P>
<P>
   Now, comes word that Nellie has decided that, by golly, it's
time to bag the season and play for that lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   What lottery pick, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   You mean the one Nelson failed to get protection for when he
traded the Mavs' 1999 No. 1 choice for point guard Steve Nash?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that lottery pick, the one that belongs to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   You do remember Nash, of course. Most of you showered him with
boos a couple of home games ago. Should have saved that for the GM
who told us the Suns' No. 3 point guard was exactly what the Mavs
needed, then signed him to a six-year, $33 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when Nelson made that deal and said if the Mavs didn't
make the playoffs this year, ``it's a terrible trade?''
</P>
<P>
   So, whom do we hold accountable? Don't ask Ross Jr. He ain't
talkin'. He knows the first critical word he says about Nelson, Big
Don's back in his swim trunks, basking on the beach in Maui,
sipping mai tais and counting his millions.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad idea, at that.
</P>
<P>
   But the resume, you say. Oh yes, we know it by heart. It's why
so many of us applauded when Junior hired Nelson in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   We know that Nellie and Pat Riley are the only three-time
winners as NBA coach of the year; that Big Don was named one of the
top 10 coaches in NBA history by a panel of former coaches, players
and media; that when he was coach/GM at Golden State in the late
'80s and early '90s, he turned that franchise from a 20-62 loser
into a 55-27 club in four years.
</P>
<P>
   We know he has drafted or developed such eventual NBA stars as
Marques Johnson, Sidney Moncrief, Mitch Richmond, Tim Hardaway,
Tyrone Hill, Chris Gatling and Chris Webber, and that he once had a
knack for finding nuggets, like Sprewell, late in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   But that was 10 years ago. Let's check the facts now.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took over the Mavs, he has coached 98 games. His record
is a dismal 26-72. The coach he fired, Jim Cleamons, also coached
98 games. He was 28-70, two games better than Nelson over the same
span.
</P>
<P>
   This, after Nelson turned this team over not once, but twice to
get ``his players'' in place.
</P>
<P>
   The only move he has made this year that has turned out even
half decent was signing Gary Trent. And that was more accident than
design, because it would never have happened if Kurt Thomas hadn't
suddenly bailed out to take the Knicks' offer.
</P>
<P>
   By signing Trent, Nelson was telling Cedric Ceballos ``we don't
need you.'' Then Ceballos came crawling back, got hurt and now he's
Nelson's No. 1 alibi for why another season has gone into the tank.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the season was doomed even before the lockout and
before the 10-22 start, when Nelson made the deals for Dirk
Nowitzki and Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the weary and overmatched Mavs players have gotten a peek
at the finish line and they've quit on Nelson, who had promised
that this team would be competitive and fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Play the kids? Sure. Should have been doing that from the start.
Why A.C. Green or Hot Rod Williams ever got any minutes is the
question.
</P>
<P>
   We should have already been seeing Chris Anstey, ``best running
big man in the NBA,'' according to Nelson. We should have been
seeing Samaki Walker instead of Williams and certainly Nowitzki,
even if it means sitting Michael Finley. We know what Finley can
do.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, Nelson must develop the young players he has because
they're all he has. What you see now is what you're going to get
next year, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes all this so hard to take and why fans are
gagging at what they see. It's not just that the Mavs are bad
again. Lord knows, we've endured that. It's that the future has
already been mortgaged, too.
</P>
<P>
   That tightening you feel around your throat? That's the hope
being choked out of you one more time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
