<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BANK-INVESTIGATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN CENTRAL BANK PLANS A CURRENCY INSIDER INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ The nation's central bank said Wednesday
that it is conducting an investigation into accusations that
several domestic and foreign financial institutions used inside
information in January about an impending shift in exchange-rate
policy to profit from the devaluation of the currency.
</P>
<P>
   The assertions _ first made public in February by Aloizio
Mercadante, a member of Congress from the opposition Workers Party
_ include charges that nine banks used access to government
officials in the days leading up to the Jan. 13 policy shift to
make trading decisions resulting in a combined profit of roughly $1
billion. The list of banks includes Citigroup, J.P. Morgan and
BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Many banks in recent weeks have reported preliminary results to
the central bank showing they made substantial profits after the
devaluation of the currency, the real, largely through a
combination of successful bets in futures markets and purchases of
dollar-linked government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous size of these profits comes as the economy is
struggling with recession, and has resulted in calls by several
members of Congress to look into the legality of such financial
results.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Sen. Antonio Carlos Magalhaes, the president of the
Senate and a man widely considered Brazil's most powerful
legislator, said he would support a congressional inquiry into the
accusations that some banks used inside information to profit from
the devaluation. That move is separate from the central bank's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Georges Lamaziere, a spokesman for President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, said on Tuesday that the government sees no problem with
the congressional inquiry going forward. The central bank's
investigation should be finished by next week and the results will
be announced then, a spokeswoman said in Brasilia, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the banks have said they broke no laws by accumulating
profits in the aftermath of the devaluation, which pushed the real
down by 40 percent against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   There had been widespread expectations for months that Brazil
might have to abandon its artificial support for the currency and
let market forces of supply and demand determine its value.
Currency traders at banks and other financial institutions who had
bet on that possibility, based on publicly available information,
did nothing illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a devaluation, you tend to make money,'' said
Richard Howe, a spokesman for Citigroup in New York. JP Morgan and
BankBoston also denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the devaluation, the central bank was led by an
interim president, Francisco Lopes, who has since resigned. It is
now headed by Arminio Fraga, a former fund manager, who ordered the
insider-trading investigation last week.
</P>
<P>
   He has also ordered an inquiry into accusations that the central
bank may have acted illegally in helping two small Rio de Janeiro
investment banks, Banco Marka and Banco Fonte Cindam, after the
devaluation. The banks lost millions of dollars after betting
against the likelihood of a devaluation. Marka has since been taken
over by the central bank, while Fonte Cindam has been sold to
Banque Nationale de Paris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2332EST &QL; 
