<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0512 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLVENCY-ECONSCENE-NY     03-31 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLVENCY-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: NO COMFORT IN NEW SOLVENCY FIGURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The administration boisterously pointed this week to new actuary
studies showing that Medicare and Social Security will remain
solvent for a few more years than previously estimated. Social
Security would not go bankrupt until 2034, rather than 2032, and
the Medicare trust fund would last until 2015 rather than 2008.
</P>
<P>
   But the revised estimates should bring little comfort to anyone
who looks seriously at the numbers. Solvency is an accounting
measure that can be achieved merely by shifting costs from the
trust funds to general taxpayers. The fundamental problem posed by
government retiree programs has not gone away.
</P>
<P>
   Longer life expectancies, rising medical costs and falling birth
rates combine to drive up the working Americans' burden of
supporting the elderly. Add up the cost of Social Security,
Medicare and the part of Medicaid that pays for nursing homes for
the elderly. These three retiree programs alone will account for
more than a third of federal spending next year.
</P>
<P>
   By 2030, retirement benefits will account for more than
two-thirds of the budget. That means the fraction of the federal
spending devoted to other parts of government, from law enforcement
to housing subsidies, will shrivel unless Congress substantially
cuts the growth rate of retiree benefits or raises taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Steuerle of the Urban Institute points out that the
baby-boom generation can look forward to generous retiree benefits
even as birth rates fall, leaving fewer workers to support a
growing number of the elderly. By locking in layers of retiree
benefits for rich and poor alike, Steuerle observes, the baby
boomers are leaving themselves a government ``almost the sole
purpose of which will be to care for their consumption needs in
retirement, a government by, of and only for the baby boomers.''
</P>
<P>
   The footprints of Steuerle's stern warning lie all over the
White House and congressional budgets. Sam Elkin of the Center on
Budget and Policy Priorities tracks domestic discretionary
spending, which encompasses nearly all the programs except military
and entitlement programs like Social Security and welfare. Elkin
points out that under the recently passed Republican budget, such
spending will fall by 18 percent by 2002 and almost 30 percent by
2009, after taking account of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   That would take domestic discretionary spending from almost 3.5
percent of the national economic output today _ which is as low as
this figure has been since the early 1960s _ to about 2 percent by
2009. As Medicare and Social Security costs rise thereafter, this
figure would fall further still. By comparison, domestic
discretionary programs accounted for more than 5 percent of the
economy in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed evisceration of discretionary spending comes as no
surprise from the party that has all but declared war on big
government, but the fact is that President Clinton's budget would
not restore the proposed cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In his winning presidential campaign in 1992, Clinton pledged to
raise government spending by $50 billion a year on public programs,
for example high-speed trains and improved training for the work
force. His current plan would use about 10 percent of the expected
surpluses over the next 15 years to preserve some discretionary
spending. That would avoid more than half of the Republicans'
proposed cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But the added money would not come close to honoring his 1992
pledge, even though the current and projected economies are flush
compared with the economy that Clinton inherited from President
Bush. Indeed, Elkin said that after taking account of inflation,
Clinton's latest budget would probably cut domestic discretionary
spending by 7 percent by 2002 and 13 percent by 2009. There goes
part of the president's investment bridge to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   To do more, Clinton would have had to propose trimming retiree
benefits, perhaps by proposing to raise the eligibility age for
Medicare. Or Clinton would have had to propose cutting Social
Security and Medicare benefits for upper-income families, measures
neither he nor the Republicans would touch.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he proposed to use most of the expected surpluses to
give Medicare and Social Security first call on general tax
revenues in the future when the trust funds run dry. Therein lies
the fate of future discretionary programs.
</P>
<P>
   There are important differences between the Clinton and
Republican plans. His plan buys back far more of the government's
$3.7 trillion debt from the public, a sound economic step that
would pump trillions of dollars into private capital markets for
use by companies to invest in plants and equipment. The Republicans
would return about $800 billion of the future surplus to taxpayers
in the form of a tax cut over 10 years. They would not use the
surplus to bolster domestic discretionary spending, unlike the
president.
</P>
<P>
   But the similarities overwhelm the differences. Both budgets
call for a future wherein the government takes in tax dollars from
a diminishing number of workers in order to support the consumption
of an increasing number of elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Few take seriously the prospect that Congress, even if it stays
in Republican hands, will gut discretionary spending anytime soon.
It would seem ludicrous to believe a Congress that needed decades
to summon the political courage to strip wartime subsidies from the
producers of mohair would immediately whack nearly a third out of
the budget for border patrols, medical research and highway
construction.
</P>
<P>
   But budget logic will eventually have to overcome cowardice.
Over time, Congress will have only grim choices: Trim retiree
benefits, eviscerate discretionary spending or raise taxes. ``Never
before,'' says Steuerle of entitlement spending for the elderly,
``have so many commitments and so much growth been scheduled in our
laws _ literally for an eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   Many economists make the point that in about 30 years a third of
the adult population will be retired and that these people will
spend about a third of their lives in retirement. Congress can
promote private savings in a number of ways. It can generate
federal surpluses far into the future.
</P>
<P>
   But, Steuerle points out, there is no way that Congress can spur
savings enough ``to support close to one-third of the entire adult
population on Social Security for one-third of their adult lives,''
adding, ``Doesn't the blessing of longer life involve some
obligation to share in its cost?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
