<HEADLINE>
GQ NAMES A PUBLISHER, SIGNALING POWER SHIFT AT CONDE NAST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a transition that re-establishes him as one of the
company's central players, Thomas A. Florio, the publisher of Conde
Nast Traveler and the former publisher of The New Yorker, was named
publisher of Conde Nast men's title GQ on Wednesday. He replaces
Jack Laschever, 38, who is resigning for medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Steven T. Florio, the president and chief executive officer of
Conde Nast Publications and Florio's older brother, made the
announcement from his home on Long Island, where he is recuperating
from surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom is going to a magazine that is really central to the
success of the company,'' the elder Florio said. ``It's a very
profitable title for the company, and it's a very meaningful move
for Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Cooper, the editor in chief of GQ _ which generated more
than $88 million in advertising revenue for Conde Nast last year _
said that it would be the first time that he and Florio, both
15-year veterans of Conde Nast, would work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough guy, and I like tough guys,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Florio, 42, was moved out of his position as publisher of
The New Yorker by his older brother last May; his forced departure
from The New Yorker for Conde Nast Traveler was seen as a clear
sign of the competitive spirit between the two brothers.
</P>
<P>
   And during the last 10 months while Tom Florio was publisher of
Conde Nast Traveler, he did not report to his brother, reporting
instead to Cathy Viscardi Johnson, the executive vice president of
sales and marketing at Conde Nast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did that for personal reasons more than anything,'' the
elder Florio said. ``Like all brothers, we have our moments.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the younger Florio making something of a comeback as
the publisher of a strong Conde Nast title, but the appointment has
set off a chain of movement within Conde Nast, which is a unit of
Advance Publications.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher of House &AMP; Garden, Lisa Henriques Hughes, resigned
her position to become the publisher of Conde Nast Traveler, a
magazine she supervised as publisher from 1995 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Hughes was publisher of House &AMP; Garden, she raised the
magazine's rate base _ the circulation guaranteed to advertisers _
by 18.2 percent, to 650,000, in February of this year. The current
circulation, as of December 1998, is 722,195, according to the
Audit Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   The associate publisher of The New Yorker, Brenda Saget _ who
has worked in publishing roles at Elle Decor and Architectural
Digest _ has been named publisher of House &AMP; Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Laschever was not available for comment. A veteran of American
Express Publishing, he was named publisher of GQ in July of last
year, and published GQ's largest issue in a decade, with 317 ad
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The Conde Nast announcements came on the same day that Maxim
magazine, a powerful competitor in the men's magazine marketplace
that is published by Dennis Publishing Ltd., named its new editor,
Mike Soutar, the editor of the English men's magazine FHM.
</P>
<P>
   Competition in the men's marketplace is fierce; GQ's circulation
is 708,743, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations, while
Maxim's has surpassed that with 733,744 and is guaranteeing a rate
base of 950,000 for the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Maxim's previous editor, Mark Golin, left the magazine last
Friday. He has been named editor in chief of Conde Nast men's title
Details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
