<SLUG> BC-BOEING-ROCKET-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING NEEDS SUCCESSFUL SEA LAUNCH MONDAY TO WIN NEW CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Fresh off the successful firing last week of its first
Sea Launch rocket from a platform in the Pacific Ocean, The Boeing
Co. is hoping for similar results Monday night when it attempts for
the second time to launch its new Delta 3 rocket from Cape
Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   The first Delta 3 exploded in a spectacular nighttime fireball
over the Atlantic on its maiden flight in August, and the
Seattle-based aerospace giant can ill afford another catastrophic
failure this time, industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Though no customers have canceled their orders for Delta 3,
Boeing has not booked any new orders since the highly publicized
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious that we need to demonstrate success for more
satellites to get on the vehicle,'' said Jay Witzling, vice
president of the Delta 2 and Delta 3 programs for Boeing's
Expendable Launch Systems in Huntington Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing engineers say the problem that caused the first Delta 3
to veer out of control has been corrected by a software fix. To
further improve the rocket's reliability, modifications were made
to Delta 3 hardware not involved in the failure, said Dan Collins,
Boeing's Delta 3 program manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought in some very tough outside consultants, who have
looked at everything we have done,'' Collins said. ``They are as
convinced as I am that we have done everything we can do and that
this rocket is ready to go fly, and fly successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure of Delta 3 on its first flight resulted in the loss
of a multimillion-dollar Galaxy X communications satellite built by
Hughes Space and Communications in Los Angeles for PanAmSat Corp.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Delta 3 will carry a 4.5-ton Orion 3 satellite built
by Hughes for Loral Orion in Rockville, Md. Once in a
geosynchronous orbit about 22,300 miles in space, the satellite
will provide broadcast and communications services to the
Asia-Pacific region, including Korea, China, Japan, Australia,
India, Southeast Asia and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Orion 3 will be Loral's first satellite to serve the
Asia-Pacific region, Loral spokeswoman Jeanette Clonan said.
</P>
<P>
   She would not say how much the satellite cost. It typically
costs about $250 million to build, insure and launch a
communications satellite the size of Orion 3.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has said it would charge customers about $85 million to
launch their satellites on Delta III, though some industry analysts
believe the actual figure is closer to $55 million for competitive
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong launch window for the Orion 3 mission opens at 6:14
p.m. Monday, Seattle time. The launch can be watched live on the
Internet at www.Boeing.com.
</P>
<P>
   Delta 3's future may well ride on the success of the Orion 3
mission, said Marco Caceres, a rocket and space analyst with the
Teal Group, a marketing analysis firm in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing can't afford to have a completely disastrous launch
failure a second time,'' he said. ``If there is a slight
malfunction, that might not be so bad for the program _ just as as
long as it doesn't blow up and you have TV footage of pieces of the
rocket and satellite raining down over the Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   The 128-foot Delta 3 is the first large launch vehicle ever
built entirely with corporate rather than government money. Boeing
has not said how much the three-year Delta 3 development project
cost, but it was at least $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much Hughes agreed to pay McDonnell Douglas in 1995
to launch a block of 10 satellites, with options to launch 10 more
_ the first of which was the Galaxy 10. Boeing inherited the Delta
program when it acquired McDonnell Douglas in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Communication satellites are getting bigger and heavier, and it
takes more powerful rockets to launch them. Delta 3 was designed to
launch payloads twice as heavy as the very successful Delta 2.
</P>
<P>
   Using the $1.5 billion commitment from Hughes, Boeing raised
other private capital to build its more powerful rocket. So far,
Hughes has signed nine customers for Delta 3, including the
upcoming Orion 3 mission and the failed Galaxy launch last year,
Hughes spokeswoman Fran Slimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes is not worried about the rocket, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We followed the failure review very closely and have
participated in some of the engineering reviews,'' she said.
``Boeing has been very cooperative, and we are satisfied they have
determined the cause of the failure and taken steps to ensure a
successful launch.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing put together an accident investigation team that included
representatives from NASA, the Air Force and the Aerospace Corp., a
federally funded research and development center that provides
technical oversight of U.S. military space programs.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators determined that the Delta 3 control system was not
programmed to anticipate a roll motion of the booster that
gradually increased after liftoff. The control system consists of
the rocket's main engine, two vernier engines and three
solid-rocket engines that have thrust-vectoring nozzles.
</P>
<P>
   Those three solid-rocket engines tried so hard to steer the
wavering vehicle during its final seconds of flight that they ran
out of hydraulic fluid. The rocket then pitched over more than 30
degrees about 70 seconds into flight and was ripped apart by
aerodynamic forces and its self-destruct system.
</P>
<P>
   The real improvement in horsepower that allows Delta 3 to hurl
much heavier satellites into orbit comes not from the nine bigger
strap-on rockets on the first stage, but from the development of a
cryogenic upper stage _ another first for the Delta program.
</P>
<P>
   The engine _ whose fuel is stored at super-low temperatures to
increase the amount of fuel that can be carried _ is built by Pratt
&AMP; Whitney and is used on Lockheed Martin's heavy-lift Titan and
Atlas rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Delta 2 will likely be around for many years to come
because of the need to launch smaller satellites into low Earth
orbits, Delta 3 probably has a fairly short life. That's because
Boeing is already developing an even more powerful rocket, called
the Delta 4, under an Air Force contract.
</P>
<P>
   The first flight of Delta 4 is scheduled for 2001. Delta 3 and
Delta 4 will have several overlapping systems, including the new
cryogenic upper stage on Delta 3. ``Clearly, Delta 3 is very
critical to that evolution'' from Delta 2 to Delta 4, Boeing's
Witzling said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins called Delta 3 the ``key to both the present and the
future'' as Boeing pushes toward its goal of becoming the world's
leading provider of launch vehicle services.
</P>
<P>
   That assessment was echoed by Caceres, the industry analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta 3 may make some money for Boeing,'' he said, ``but it
will not make them rich. What's going to make Boeing rich is Delta
4. That is really going to be the rocket that will take Boeing into
the next generation of launch vehicles for heavy satellites.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing needs Delta 3 to work before it can take that next
step.
</P>
<P>
   If its new rocket does work the second time around, Boeing plans
for two more Delta 3 launches this year and six or seven next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
