<HEADLINE>
KILBORN: AN   ECHO OF `DAILY SHOW' ON `LATE LATE'
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York area; check local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The names are impossible to keep straight (``Late Night,''
``Late Show,'' ``Late Late Show''), which is why real people think
of the shows as ``Conan,'' ``Dave'' and ``Craig Kilborn, that guy
from Comedy Central.'' His version of ``Late Late Show'' began
Tuesday night, following David Letterman and going head-to-head
with Conan O'Brien. More important, Kilborn replaces Tom Snyder in
that slot and instantly zaps CBS into the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Kilborn got to take along his ``intellectual
property,'' as comedy routines have come to be known in the
late-night wars. Though the first show was extremely smooth and
amiable, the host seemed to breathe most easily when settling into
routines familiar from his time as host of Comedy Central's
sardonic news parody, ``The Daily Show.'' On Tuesday he played the
popular ``Five Questions'' with his first guest, Bill Murray,
asking bogus questions like, ``How do you make a perfect Rob Roy?''
Murray walked to a concealed liquor cabinet, mixed a stiff drink
and lovingly whispered the word ``vermouth'' over the glass as only
he could.
</P>
<P>
   Murray had also been the first guest on the Letterman show, and
his droll approach makes him the perfect match for both.
(Letterman's production company is behind the new show, as it was
Snyder's.) Letterman, of course, pioneered and mastered the ironic
approach to talk shows that made the Kilborn and O'Brien shows
possible. On Tuesday, Letterman had the best running joke of the
three, with his straight-faced claim that his is ``the only late
night talk show ever to receive a standing ovation at Sundance.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilborn's show is not reconfiguring that late-night model. He
begins with a monologue and even has the standard set, with fake
windows and a skyline behind him. Though there is no sidekick or
band (there will be musical guests), even these tweaks in the
format make the new show more like his old ``Daily Show'' (which is
doing well with Jon Stewart, a more cerebral wit, as host).
</P>
<P>
   Smaller differences can be telling, too. There is sports
equipment piled in a corner, the green-topped desk resembles a pool
table and the big leather guest chair screams ``retro macho.'' The
set might as well have ``looking for young male viewers'' written
all over it. Kilborn joked about that demographic hope by referring
to an audience member as a ``nice guy, about 18 to 34.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're not in that category, your fear might have been that
the Jekyll-Hyde Kilborn might have been at his smarmiest. He plays
the unthinking sexist so well that it's easy to believe he is,
beneath the layers of winking irony, a throwback to the swinging
Playboy era. But on Tuesday he wore his good-Craig face, and irony
won out. He changed into a blue silk smoking jacket to interview
the model Heidi Klum, making fun of his image even while indulging
it. That sardonic approach is his most enticing quality.
</P>
<P>
   What matters ultimately, of course, is how a late-night show
plays over time. Each cultivates a rhythm that is easy to feel and
hard to duplicate. The Conan O'Brien show is sailing along now,
with an impeccable balance of comedy and guests. The Kilborn show
can't match that, but it has done the best it could have hoped for:
If you're flipping around channels, it's already a place to stop.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE LATE SHOW WITH CRAIG KILBORN'
</P>
<P>
   12:30 a.m. ET weeknights on CBS (Channel 2 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Billy Kimball, executive producer; Brian McAloon, director;
Cathy Hoeven, line producer; Ted Jessip, consulting producer; Ross
Abrash, Joe Forristal, Jon Hotchkiss, Steve Lookner, Alec Sulkin
and Wellesley Wild, writers; Joanna Jordan, talent executive, and
Zoe Friedman, senior talent coordinator; Craig Kilborn, host.
</P>
</TEXT>
