u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-SENATE-POLL-NYT &LR;      03-31 0256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-POLL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL FINDS WHITMAN IN LEAD FOR SENATE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ A survey of New Jersey voters showed Gov.
Christie Whitman leading by 16 percentage points over former Gov.
Jim Florio in a matchup for the U.S. Senate seat to be vacated by
Frank Lautenberg next year.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Whitman nor Florio have formally declared their
intentions in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, who narrowly lost a race for re-election to Whitman in
1993, has formed an exploratory committee to consider seeking the
Democratic nomination. Whitman is expected to announce next week
whether she will enter the race.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Quinnipiac College poll, Whitman was favored by
51 percent and Florio by 35 percent in the poll that asked 984 New
Jersey residents their preference if the governor and former
governor were paired in the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty percent said they believed Whitman has been a better
governor than Florio; 18 percent said they preferred Florio. The
poll has a margin of error of 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said that other recent polls, conducted by Democratic
Party officials, suggest that he would beat Whitman. ``I don't
think that there is anybody in the state who does not believe, if
it comes to pass, that this will be a competitive race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pete McDonough, a spokesman for Whitman, said that ``walking
into a race that you have not even entered with a 50 percent base
is a very strong place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, a Democrat, is not seeking a fourth term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
