<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING A SPACE FOR A RUDY SITE 
BEARS ON BROADWAY 
DRINKS FOR 70
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yes, there is a Rudyno.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   No, it is not registered to Hillary Rodham Clinton. Nor has it
been assigned to Republicans hoping to head off a cyberspace attack
on Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the undeclared Republican candidate for
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the mayor's fund-raising committee opened the site
www.Hillaryno.com. When Dr. Amos Grunebaum, a gynecologist and
practiced Internet surfer, saw a story about it on television on
Monday evening, his first thought was whether anyone had claimed
www.Rudyno.com.
</P>
<P>
   He went to his computer and discovered that no one had. So he
registered www.Rudyno.com himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you attack, you need to cover your back,'' he said.
Referring to the mayor, he added, ``He asked for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunebaum, who maintains a site for women who are pregnant or
want to be (www.babydata.com) and is the co-author, with Dr. Ruth
Westheimer, of a just-published book, ``Dr. Ruth's Pregnancy Guide
for Couples,'' said that he set up the Rudyno.com site ``purely for
the fun of i.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any political agenda,'' he said, refusing to say
whether he would vote for Mrs. Clinton if she ran, or for Giuliani
if he ran.
</P>
<P>
   He did say that he did not mind paying the $70 registration fee
for the Rudyno.com site. ``For $70 I got more fun out of it than a
nice dinner,'' he said. For now, anyway, visitors to the site see a
message that says, in 11 languages, that the site is ``under
construction.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuffed Audience
</P>
<P>
   Between numbers from musicals that the late Gower Champion
directed or choreographed, from ``Hello, Dolly'' to ``Bye Bye
Birdie,'' the singer Barbara Cook told a story about ``42nd
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Cook said the producer, David Merrick, canceled the
previews of ``42nd Street'' to prevent anyone _ curious critics or
eagle-eyed editors, for example _ from finding out what was going
on at the Winter Garden Theater before opening night in 1980. At
the time, it was said that Merrick spent about $400,000 on salaries
of the cast and crew during a month of ``rehearsals'' for a show
that had already run for five weeks in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   After a few days of playing to an empty house, Miss Cook said,
someone in the cast brought in some stuffed animals and put them in
orchestra seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara?'' a voice interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Gurewitsch, a freelance writer, held up two stuffed
bears. They came from the clan of 50 or so that Gurewitsch and his
wife, Susan, own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara had told me the story'' before her opening on Tuesday
night at the Carlyle Hotel, he said. ``I said I was going to bring
some in case no one showed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Pre-Party Party
</P>
<P>
   T-minus 35 days, and counting.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit for Lenox Hill Neighborhood House, an East Side
social services agency, is not until May 6. But the pre-party
parties have already begun. On Wednesday, Audrey Gruss _ the wife
of Martin Gruss, the financier _ had the 70 designers who will do
the dinner tables at the benefit over to her Park Avenue apartment
for drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gruss said it was the only time she had ever invited people
over who were not personal friends. And this was not exactly a safe
crowd: All those designers were casting practiced eyes on the
walls, the windows, the furniture, the floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Hampton did it nine years ago,'' Mrs. Gruss said,
referring to the designer who died last year, and Albert Hadley
told Mrs. Gruss not to change a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to call Duane and tell her how wonderful it is,''
Hadley said. (Duane Hampton is Hampton's widow.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the tables at the benefit, the designers will base them
on paintings from the International Fine Art Fair. The benefit will
serve as its preview party. One designer, Kitty Hawks, had a memory
lapse when asked which painting she had chosen. ``Oh, God, I can't
remember the name of the painter,'' she said. ``But I'd love to own
the picture.'' (It is by Arthur Carles Jr.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
