<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBWAY SHOULD REMAIN CLOSED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's baseball quiz: What's more arrogant and detestable than
a Yankee fan talking about a World Series? Answer: Yankee and
</P>
<P>
   Met fans talking about a Subway World Series.
</P>
<P>
   This bilious chatter began in late February when spring training
began, and it is now being trumpeted in the New York tabs and some
national magazines. The latest edition of Sport Magazine has Derek
Jeter and Mike Piazza on the cover wearing burn-your-soul, whup-ass
stares.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your acid reflux.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't going to happen, of course. The Yankees will not
repeat last year's fantastic season because Roger Clemens and
interim manager Don Zimmer are carriers of the Red Sox curse, and
the Mets will implode because Piazza is a sullen millionaire and
manager Bobby Valentine a smarmy, disingenuous manager who could
only win a popularity contest if Tommy Lasorda were the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that could make that better is the thought of the
Angels and Dodgers breaking New York hearts and riding the backs of
Kevin Brown and Mo Vaughn into a Freeway World Series. But only the
incurably optimistic would believe that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are better today than they were last September, but
that is no guarantee. Both still have more questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Can Davey Johnson shake up a stagnant Dodger locker
room? (end bold) Absolutely. Lasorda was bombastic and Bill Russell
quiet. Either way, players tuned them out. No one tunes out
Johnson. He's considered a player's manager because he treats them
like men while demanding an honest day's effort.
</P>
<P>
   But in the feckless '90s, merely shaking up a locker room will
not automatically produce wins. In any 25-man locker room, there
will always be five players who are too sensitive or too rich to
give a damn.
</P>
<P>
   What happens the first time Gary Sheffield gets his feelings
hurt? Or the first time Johnson sits Todd Hundley because he can't
get the job done? Or the first time Johnson asks Ismael Valdes to
complete a game (two in 90 starts the last three seasons)?
</P>
<P>
   The Foxified Dodgers want to win now, and they are not reluctant
to make a move. But embracing that attitude is easier than making
it work.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Is Todd Hundley capable of replacing Mike Piazza?
(end bold)
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely, in the sense that he's weak defensively. And that
was before surgery on his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers overlooked Piazza's defense because of his offense.
Plus, after throwing out an embarrassing 18 percent of all thieves
in 1996 (34 of 189), Piazza did improve his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley is the son of a former catcher, Randy Hundley, which
makes his comparable stats all the more specious. Of all catchers
with 100 or more starts in 1997, Hundley ranked last in throwing
out runners. He was among the trailers in 1996 and 1995, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will trade that for some left-handed power. But over
a nine-year career, Hundley's two good seasons 41 home runs, 112
RBI in 1996; 39 and 86 in 1997 look like aberrations. His career
average is just .240, too, a mere 93 points lower than Piazza
(.333), and he has managed 400 plate appearances in a season in
just three of nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Is this team too new, too old and too rich? (end
bold) Yes, yes and yes. The Dodgers will start only two players who
were Dodgers in 1997. All of the major imports are in their 30s
Kevin Brown (34), Hundley (30 in May), Devon White (36), Alan Mills
(32), Mel Rojas (32) and Jeff Shaw (32).
</P>
<P>
   Rather than question whether Kevin Brown is overpaid, one should
wonder what inspired Kevin Malone to invest almost $50 million in
contracts for White, Shaw, Hundley, Mills and Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Is Mo Vaughn the answer to the Angels' problems each
September? (end bold) Only if he can pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting has never been a problem for this franchise, not in 1961
when five different Angels hit 20-plus home runs, not when Jim
Fregosi and Alex Johnson were its stars, not when Don Baylor,
Reggie Jackson, Fred Lynn, Rod Carew and Bobby Grich wore halos,
and not now, pre and post-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels go into the season with one new pitcher, Tim Belcher,
who is 37 and has a career A.L. ERA of 4.62; an ace, Chuck Finley,
who is 36; and with two other starters who are longshots to match
their modest career-best seasons in 1998, Omar Olivares (9-9, 4.02)
and Steve Sparks (9-4, 4.34).
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Will Mo produce the way he has the last three seasons
(averages of .316, 40 home runs, 118 RBI)? (end bold) He's
certainly capable. But Edison Field may neutralize some of his
power.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels hit 129 home runs last year, but only 48 of them came
at The Big E. The right-field alley is listed at 365 feet, but that
doesn't account for an 18-foot fence and wind which blows to left
when it blows at all. The Angels' 1998 home run index at Edison was
92, eight percent lower than the league average. In 1996-97, the
home run index was 127, or 27 percent higher than the average.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Edmonds averaged almost 16 home runs a season in Anaheim
from 1995 to 1997. Last year he hit nine. The flip side is that
Edison produces higher averages for left-handed hitters, and Vaughn
hits for average and is used to playing in a difficult home run
park (Fenway) for lefties.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Will the Angels miss Gary DiSarcina? (end bold) Does
a baby miss its mommy? The Angels were 16-27 without him in
August-September of 1996 and upchucked their big lead over Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina's freak arm injury, plus the loss of Jason Dickson and
Matt Walbeck, reinforces the franchises's jinx complex. Adding a
key player from a team with its own curse sort of makes Anaheim
Ground Zero for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Is Terry Collins nearing the same precipice he fell
from in Houston? (end bold) It looks like it. Collins won 66, 76
and 82 games in his three years in Houston, but he was fired in
spite of that improvement. His high-strung personality grated on
the players.
</P>
<P>
   He's won 84 and 85 in Anaheim despite beleaguered pitching. But
a summertime rip last year at players for checking out early before
the All-Star break lingered into the fall. Vaughn is a huge
clubhouse presence; how well he and Collins get along will be a key
theme for '99.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Is there any reason to believe the two locals will
make the playoffs? (end bold) One can dream of the first I-5 World
Series. But the real novelty would simply be a postseason victory.
It's been 11 (Dodgers) and 13 (Angels) years since either team
claimed one. Maybe we're due.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
