<HEADLINE>
HAROLD STEINBERG, 77, PUBLISHER AND WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.H.)  (mk) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Harold Steinberg, a former co-owner and executive of
Chelsea House publishing company, died last Friday at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center in Manhattan. He was 77 and had
moved to the Kateri Residence nursing home in Manhattan from East
Hampton, N.Y., three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea House Publishers was founded in 1964 and named for the
Chelsea Hotel, on West 23rd St. Steinberg was living there at the
time and had been working in public relations.
</P>
<P>
   By 1986 Chelsea House was based in Greenwich Village and
publishing reference works, mainly in the field of American
studies, and series like ``American Presidential Elections'' and
``World Leaders.'' Its project editors included the historian
Arthur Schlesinger Jr., the literary critic Harold Bloom and Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. For years the company's main owners
were Steinberg and Andrew Norman. The business was sold in 1983 to
Main Line Book Co. of Pennsylvania, and Steinberg stayed on for
some years as Chelsea House's chairman and publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg's own writings ranged from early novelty books like
``The Psychiatric Coloring Book'' and ``Animals in Love'' to
pseudonymous fiction and two plays. But the work he liked best
seemed to be publishing books. ``Having the privilege of making
them,'' he said in a 1986 interview, ``is a very satisfying
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Manhattan and raised in Brooklyn and used to say
that he studied at five colleges without staying long enough at any
one of them to receive a degree. He served in the Army Air Corps in
World War II and held various jobs before going into public
relations.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to Rebecca Vyorst ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Mary McCarthy Steinberg of Staten
Island, N.Y.; a daughter, Katharine Steinberg Golick of Brooklyn,
N.Y.; a son, Anthony Burgess Steinberg of Los Angeles; two
brothers, Bernard of Los Angeles and Herbert of Manchester, N.H.; a
sister, Joy Schwartz of Staten Island, and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-31-99 2352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990331.0523 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-31 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1874 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-REBUILD     03-31 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-REBUILDING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SEASON IN TATTERS, MAVERICKS TURN TO YOUNGSTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Expect to see a lot less A.C. Green, Shawn Bradley and
John ``Hot Rod'' Williams this season for the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be a pleasant sight for fans who paid to see them,
but the Mavericks will be playing more of their younger players,
such as Chris Anstey, Dirk Nowitzki, Steve Nash, Samaki Walker and
Erick Strickland, to get more experience for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Gary Trent, another young player, was surprised the
Mavericks didn't put forth maximum effort against the Minnesota
Timberwolves, in Tuesday's 98-78 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you really don't realize until the lead starts
building and you start going down two, six, 12 and 20,'' Trent
said. ``That's when you realize it's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks' defense has been lacking lately, especially on
the inside, as teams often attack the basket for easy layups or
dunks. The Mavericks have allowed an average of 102 points per game
over the past three games after allowing 89.2 points during the
previous six games.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Nelson, who is slated to take over as the Mavericks coach
when the new American Airlines Center is completed in time for the
beginning of the 2000-2001 season, believes the Mavericks' ship
will be righted one day soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take \Rlosing\S personal and hard,'' Nelson said. ``It's
very frustrating. We don't get much sleep after games like \Rthe
loss to Minnesota\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we do like the guys in that locker room. If
you're going to be in a trench, we feel very comfortable being in
the trenches with that kind of group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a go-to guy to emerge for us. We have, right now, a
team of very, very good support players. We have no superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Nash, who was handed the starting point guard spot and a
six-year, $33 million contract extension before the season started,
agrees with Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really have, per se, a superstar,'' Nash said. ``We
don't have a guy who commands a $70 million or $80 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RMinnesota forward\S Kevin Garnett makes everyone on his team
better by leaps and bounds. We don't really have that type of
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Nash said the Mavericks have to use other means
just to scratch out a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have a premium on rebounding and outhustling the
other team, and we're not doing a good enough job of that,'' he
said. ``We've hit the wall, so to speak. But we have to try to
solve this riddle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks will try to solve the riddle by turning to their
younger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to play our younger guys, but I don't want to
jeopardize losing a game that I feel we should win,'' Mavericks
coach/general manager Don Nelson said. ``It's a fine line between
trying to get our youth some experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope to get the best of both worlds, and that we win
and they get experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing the Mavericks are experienced at is losing
ballgames. They are the NBA's worst franchise this decade, with a
dreadful 190-498 record (.276).
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks haven't been to the playoffs since the 1989-90
season _ the longest drought in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson was supposed to change all of that. But he's 26-72
since he took over as Mavericks coach on Dec. 4, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's frustration with the team's failure boiled over Tuesday
against the Timberwolves. That's when he received two technical
fouls and was ejected from a game for the first time this season
for protesting a noncall on a collision that sent guard Erick
Strickland to the showers with back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got frustrated, and a lot of times when you don't have a
good record refs might take the night off or not give you the
respect you deserve,'' Nelson said. ``And that's happened a few
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Strickland is OK, and practiced with the team yesterday. He will
be in uniform tonight when the Mavericks (10-22) play the 3-26 Los
Angeles Clippers at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clippers own the worst record in the NBA, Nelson is
proceeding with caution. He knows the Clippers just beat up Utah,
103-77, and also recently won at Minnesota, 100-85.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson also knows his team's psyche has been affected by losing
eight of its past 10 games. That includes the loss Tuesday to the
Timberwolves, a 109-101 loss to Seattle in a Monday game that the
Mavericks trailed by 21 points in the fourth quarter, and last
Saturday's 99-77 loss to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a very dangerous team for us,'' Nelson said of the
Clippers. ``We are vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team that comes in here thinks they can beat us. So,
it's up to us and it's important that no one comes into our home
and gets away with an easy win.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
