<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-RELAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UT WOMEN SET FOR TEXAS RELAYS TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ After years of battling to climb the mountain, Bev
Kearney has finally reached the top. And, curiously, she has found
that the view from up there looks amazingly like that from down
below.
</P>
<P>
   After spending 10 years as a perennial runner-up in women's
track and field, Kearney and her Longhorns won the prize last June,
breaking Louisiana State's domination of the NCAA Outdoor
Championships with a stirring victory in the meet's final event.
</P>
<P>
   But as she prepared her team for the first major meet of the
1999 outdoor season _ the Texas Relays, which begin today at
brand-new Mike A. Myers Stadium in Austin _ Kearney said she has
seen no difference between opening the season as the champion,
rather than one of the pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized in my heart years ago that as long as we were in
the top three or so, we were a championship-caliber team,'' said
Kearney, whose teams at Texas and Florida earned four second-place
outdoor finishes before last year's title. ``The last couple of
years before we won, we were second in the nation. Every team but
LSU would have loved to switch places with us.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, this year is the same as last year. The goal is to win the
national championship. That we did it last year doesn't make it any
different than what we've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a little extra incentive this week. Despite
their victories in the '98 outdoor meet and the '99 national indoor
championships last month, the Longhorns opened the outdoor season
ranked a shocking fifth by Trackwire, the sport's most respected
college rating service.
</P>
<P>
   With No. 1 LSU, No. 2 UCLA and No. 4 SMU all expected to make an
appearance in Austin, the stage is set for the Longhorns to send an
early season message that they haven't gone anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to trade teams with anyone,'' Kearney said.
``All of our ladies feel they are capable of carrying the team, and
we want all of them to feel responsible for the success or failure
of this team. We feel we've got the athletes who can handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the heart of last year's championship squad is back in a
senior class that has powered Texas from the day it arrived on
campus. Among them, Suziann Reid, Nanceen Perry, LaKeisha Backus,
Kim McGruder and Aminah Haddad have won 15 national titles in the
sprints and relays and have carried the Longhorns since their
freshman season in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can imagine people thinking we've been in college forever,''
laughed Reid, whose eight NCAA championships include the '98
outdoor and '99 indoor 400-meter titles. ``To us, it's gone by
fast, but to them ... We started to clean up in our first year, and
we've cleaned up big-time since then. It's only natural to wonder
how much longer we're going to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   For all those wondering, this will be the last time around for
Texas' version of the Fab Five, and their drive to win is as strong
as it was when LSU ruled the women's track world.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really drives you is competition,'' Reid said. ``When you
look at our team, just about everyone there is in the top five in
the country in her events. We are the best, so in practice we're
running with the best. We use each other to push ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
