<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-HEALTHY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND, PALMEIRO EXPECTED FOR OPENING DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Closer John Wetteland and first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro will start the Rangers' final Florida exhibition
game today, manager Johnny Oates said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Rangers are convinced the two will be available
Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, neither one of them will go on the disabled list,''
said Oates, who witnessed Wetteland and Palmeiro play in a
minor-league camp game yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Oates plans for Wetteland to start and pitch one inning and for
Palmeiro to be the designated hitter and bat fifth in today's game
against Cincinnati at Charlotte County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Oates also revealed his probable Opening Day lineup, which will
be unveiled for today's game. Left fielder Rusty Greer will not be
displaced by Palmeiro as the Rangers' No. 3 hitter in a decision
the manager described as a ``no-brainer.'' Palmeiro will bat fifth
behind right fielder Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Rusty is more suited to hit third,'' Oates said.
``Raffy can hit in either one of 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who like Greer would prefer to bat third, accepted the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with that lineup,'' Palmeiro said. ``I'm
fine with that. I just want to be in there. I just had two knee
surgeries in one month. I don't care where I hit. He could hit me
first or ninth. I just want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who underwent arthroscopic surgery March 7 to remove
torn cartilage from his right knee, went 0-for-6 during yesterday's
minor-league camp game. Perhaps the most important numbers, though,
were 4.9 and 4.8. That's how many seconds it took Palmeiro to run
from the batter's box to first base, Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the ball pretty well,'' Palmeiro said. ``I'm not worried
about hitting. I'm just concerned about running and getting out of
the box. I did that pretty decently today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be full-strength Opening Day, but I'm confident I'll
be able to play. I'm still a few weeks away from being
full-strength, but I'm confident I can go out there and do a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland (soft-tissue injury, right ankle) threw 25 pitches in
his one-inning appearance, but Boston's Triple-A Pawtucket ballclub
scored twice on two wind-aided home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I talked to said it was encouraging, but it never
feels good to give up home runs, whether they're wind-blown or
not,'' Wetteland said. ``However, the stuff was definitely there.
Obviously, I wasn't as sharp as I'd like to be. I just want to
continue to see improvement _ improvement on the bite of the
slider, improvement on throwing the changeup for strikes and
consistency on the velocity of my fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good part is that stuff will come swiftly, provided you're
healthy and strong. The reason pitchers need three weeks to get
ready is they're fighting soreness all the time. For me, that part
is over and done with. My arm strength was great coming into
camp.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wetteland and Palmeiro available for Opening Day, reliever
Jeff Zimmerman likely would begin the season at Triple-A Oklahoma
and only two roster berths would be needed for bench players.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers likely would carry another utility infielder (Scott
Sheldon, Jon Shave or Rafael Bournigal) and a fifth
outfielder/pinch runner (Milt Cuyler or Scarborough Green).
</P>
<P>
   ``Every roster decision you make,'' Oates said, ``impacts
somebody.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
