<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-REVAMPED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES SAY THERE'S NO FIRE SALE, NO SMOKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ If it's true that where there's smoke there's
fire, shouldn't the same be true of a fire sale?
</P>
<P>
   So, the intrepid detective searches the San Diego Padres'
spring-training camp for a telltale puff or two.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, none in the clubhouse. Or in the front office. Or on the
practice fields.
</P>
<P>
   There, in the main stadium. Isn't that smoke?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. But it's coming from a Trevor Hoffman fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Hoffman? What's he doing here? Surely the best closer in
baseball, in the final year of his contract, would fetch a high
price in young prospects. Isn't that what you do when you're
conducting a fire sale?
</P>
<P>
   But Hoffman is not only here, he's also the proud possessor of a
four-year, $32 million contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the defending National League champions aren't
conducting a Florida Marlins-style fire sale after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not even accurate,'' Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn said.
``I don't agree with that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins held the mother of all fire sales after winning the
World Series in 1997. The Padres stand accused of doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins spent liberally on free agents in an attempt to
build a contender and attract fans. They succeeded at the former,
but failed miserably at the later.
</P>
<P>
   So, after winning the Series, they began dumping players. Owner
H. Wayne Huizenga wanted to sell the team, and to make it more
attractive to potential buyers the payroll went from $52.5 million
to $19.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Marlins, the Padres went to the Series, although they
lost to the New York Yankees in 1998. Like the Marlins, there was
an element of attracting fan interest. The postseason push
contributed to San Diego voters' approval of a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And like the Marlins, the Padres no longer have a lot of their
star players. Gone are pitchers Kevin Brown and Joey Hamilton,
third baseman Ken Caminiti and outfielders Steve Finley and Greg
Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it looks suspiciously like a fire sale.
</P>
<P>
   However, a look at some other numbers shows that might not be
the case. The Padres' payroll was $44 million last season. It's $48
million this season.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, Caminiti and Finley are gone because they became free
agents, and the small-market Padres were outbid for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried,'' first baseman Wally Joyner said. ``They tried to
re-sign everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was traded to the Toronto Blue Jays for pitchers Woody
Williams and Carlos Almanzar. Vaughn was dealt to the Cincinnati
Reds in the only true cost-cutting deal the club made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still a small market trying to survive until they get
the new ballpark built,'' Gwynn said. ``You're losing money every
year already. Now, you're going to throw an extra $20 million on
there because you went to the World Series? Sooner or later, teams
have to make responsible decisions. Sometimes they're not popular,
but they're the right ones to make. I think in our case, they've
made really good decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were a true fire sale, Joyner wouldn't be around. He
also was a free agent, but was re-signed. The Padres also signed
Sterling Hitchcock, Dan Micili, Williams, Chris Gomez, Carlos
Hernandez and John Vander Wal to long-term deals.
</P>
<P>
   And they gave Hoffman the contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing that he's going to be here for a while now, that's
huge,'' pitcher Andy Ashby said. ``It's good to show the fans that,
hey, we're still trying to win. Some things had to change, but some
things they are keeping the same.''
</P>
<P>
   A true fire sale shows up in the record. The Marlins went from
World Series winners to 108-game losers.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expects the Padres to contend this year. But they
shouldn't fall that far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a young team, but I think we have one that can be very
competitive,'' Gwynn said. ``If things fall into place, if our
young guys play well, we can be right there again.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
