<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS LIMPING DURING BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ So much for the luxury and benefits of a three-day
break.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had looked forward to this unusually long gap between
games _ first to rest, then to practice hard and get new parts like
Glen Rice further acclimated. But when they returned from their day
off Wednesday, the Lakers got dealt their usual bad hand.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, out with the flu. Robert Horry, sidelined with a
strained left hip. Bumps and bruises all around. (And don't be
surprised if they all come down with writer's cramp after players
took turns signing 300 official NBA basketballs.)
</P>
<P>
   A fresher team after taking Tuesday off? Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, aside from Robert being hurt, Glen not being here, Shaq
(O'Neal's) stomach problem, (Derek Fisher's) foot, Rick (Fox's)
foot, Fish's face, (Derek) Harper being 37 years old, Dennis
(Rodman) being (38) . . . what else?'' coach Kurt Rambis said.
``Aside from about half the team being hurt, I guess we looked as
fresh as we could be.''
</P>
<P>
   His sarcasm was understandable. The Lakers haven't been at full
strength all season, and even when healthy, they've been busy
incorporating new players or changing the starting lineup or
dealing with some other unplanned change.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, Fox and O'Neal all practiced Wednesday despite
season-long ailments.
</P>
<P>
   But without Rice, the Lakers were denied a precious opportunity
to get the ace shooter and his teammates more adjusted to one
another. Rambis has been tweaking the offense to give Rice more
shooting opportunities off of screens and movement, rather than set
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got done what I could get done with the players that we
have,'' Rambis said. ``But even some of the players that are here
are injured, so we couldn't get done everything that I wanted to
get done. . . . It does get frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Worm on MJ: Dennis Rodman was incredulous over reports that
former Bulls teammate Michael Jordan was considering playing for
the Charlotte Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you nuts? There's no way,'' Rodman said of the prospect of
Jordan playing again. Rodman figures Jordan floated the rumor
himself. ``He's just doing it because he wants his name in the
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling fined: O'Neal, fined $3,500 for tossing the Knicks'
Chris Dudley into photographers along the baseline Sunday, was
unrepentant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who got fined, me? How much I get fined?'' he said. ``That's
cool, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal later made fun of the entire issue while talking about
the Lakers' new offense with Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Kurt he doesn't have to call plays for me. I'm gonna do
what I get paid to do, and that's push people into cameras,
dominate and get fined,'' O'Neal said, laughing.
</P>
</TEXT>
